<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7706 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FERTILITY-AZR &LR;      07-13 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERTILITY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINIC SEARCHES FOR EMBRYO DONORS BEFORE DESTRUCTION DATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ After 16 years of working miracles in the eyes of
infertile Arizonans, Dr. Robert Tamis is retiring and closing his
Phoenix clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know where your children are?
</P>
<P>
   The embryos of about 50 donors are stored in 35-liter metal
containers in a stark white room at the clinic near 24th Street and
Thomas Road. Unless their donors are located by July 31, they will
be destroyed, along with unclaimed vials of frozen sperm from as
many 70 donors.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers started to search in early May for donors whose records
are out-of-date, scanning telephone books and sending out certified
letters to last known addresses.
</P>
<P>
   They ran a classified ad in ``The Arizona Republic'' on June 27,
asking, ``If you feel you have embryos or sperms stored with
Arizona Institute of Reproductive Medicine, please contact us
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an awkward task _ in part because of patient privacy issues
and in part because of the ethics of destroying the embryos and
sperm.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, people who work in the field of assisted
reproduction have worried about just this situation, said Robert
McGaughey, an Arizona State University professor and an expert on
the ethics of human reproduction. He also works with the Arizona
Center for Fertility Studies, having frozen and implanted more than
3,400 embryos.
</P>
<P>
   Embryos are created by fertilizing an egg with sperm in a
laboratory and letting it divide into eight cells before being
frozen and stored. When a woman wants to try to conceive, some of
the embryos are thawed and implanted in her uterus.
</P>
<P>
   The Society for Assisted Reproductive Technologies, a branch of
the American Society for Reproductive Medicine, has clear _ and
regularly updated _ guidelines on cryopreservation, the freezing
and storage of embryos and sperm.
</P>
<P>
   It strongly recommends that patient and clinic sign an agreement
about how long specimens will be stored and whether they can be
donated to other couples. The group's ethics panel decided that
clinics could destroy embryos unclaimed after five years.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that is a mandate.
</P>
<P>
   And the decision is clear for Tamis' staff. Come month's end, if
the donors do not claim the embryos, Fink said, they will be
allowed to thaw and will be discarded as medical waste.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic, she says, has no choice. The embryos cannot be
donated to other couples without the permission of both egg and
sperm donors. Nor would any other facility take responsibility for
abandoned embryos.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they have found about half of the embryo owners, and all
but 15 of the men who store sperm there, said Kathy Fink, patient
coordinator for the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very difficult,'' she said, ``because what kind of
message do you leave on an answering machine? Talk about opening a
can of worms.''
</P>
<P>
   The donors can either have the specimens transferred to another
facility or destroyed. The possibility of the latter choice
outrages abortion opponents and even makes doctors and ethicists
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, that's destroying lives,'' said Tom Takash, a
member of Children of the Rosary, an anti-abortion group that
routinely holds prayer vigils outside another clinic where Tamis
works in east Phoenix. ``There's life there. It's been created,
it's growing and put in a state of suspended animation.''
</P>
<P>
   John Jakubczyk, president of Arizona Right to Life and a lawyer,
says the abandoned embryos raise endless questions: Who decides
when they will be destroyed? Why can't they be given to other
couples for adoption? Could they be declared wards of the state?
</P>
<P>
   Tamis started having patients sign agreements that spelled out
what would be done with any abandoned embryos several years ago,
but some of the specimens date back to the `80s and early `90s,
when record keeping was done by hand and there were no such
contracts. In such cases, the embryos are so old that they likely
would not survive inside a womb.
</P>
<P>
   But the ethical questions are so disturbing that Fink is even
looking for those who signed agreements just to double check.
</P>
<P>
   Tamis, 68, who produced Arizona's first test tube baby in 1984,
among other innovations in assisted reproduction, is retiring this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Tamis, who is considered one of the Valley's leading fertility
specialists, was the first to fertilize an egg by injecting it with
a single sperm in 1987. In 1986, he helped a woman without ovaries
conceive and deliver a baby. And, in 1996, he helped a woman
conceive a baby with testicular sperm.
</P>
<P>
   Tamis is on vacation this week, so Fink spent most of Monday
talking with media across the country and in England.
</P>
<P>
   Fink said the clinic placed the newspaper ad to show that it had
made all efforts to reach the donors and and to stem off any
potential legal problems if someone surfaces after the specimens
have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (the clinic) have made and are making the efforts to
contact the people, that's about all you can expect,'' said Steven
Hoffman, an ASU microbiology professor and expert on biomedical
ethics.
</P>
<P>
   He said the onus to keep in touch with the clinic should rest
with the donors, the would-be parents of any resulting offspring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you considered it that important to yourself, you would
have maintained contact, left a change of address or something,''
Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 50 patients had as many as 16 frozen embryos at the
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Some donors moved and left no forwarding address. Other embryos
belong to people who may have stored eight embryos and conceived
four children and may have simply forgotten the rest were there.
Some may have given up their quest to have a child.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the men who banked sperm at Tamis' clinic did so either
because they were getting vasectomies or had testicular cancer and
would be undergoing treatments that could damage their fertility.
</P>
<P>
   In a certified letter sent to donors, Tamis told donors to
contact the office and make plans for their specimens, or they
would be destroyed by July 15. That deadline has since been pushed
back to July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Fink contacted some by telephone after receiving confirmation
that they had received the letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were surprised to hear from me. They said, `Well, you
said in the letter that you would just destroy them,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of these people don't contact us because then
they don't have to make the decision. They want us to make that
decision and discard it for them.'' &QL; 
Karina Bland can be reached at 444-8614 or via the Internet at
karina.bland(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
