<HEADER>
A7710 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HACKER-SENTENCED-LADN     07-13 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-SENTENCED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER HACKERS SENTENCING DELAYED IN DISPUTE OVER RESTITUTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Mitnick, possibly the world's most notorious
computer hacker, should pay $1.5 &UR;  &LR; million in restitution because of
his enormous earning potential from book and movie deals,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mitnick's attorney told a U.S. Federal Court judge Monday in
Los Angeles the hacker shouldn't pay any restitution because he is
penniless, has no college degree and will be barred from using
computers, his most marketable skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``No amount of restitution should be ordered due to my client's
indigency,'' said attorney Donald C. Randolph. ``The only thing he
knows is computers, and he will not be able to use them under his
plea agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Christopher Painter said $1.5 &UR;  &LR; million
is ``a conservative estimate'' of what companies lost when Mitnick
stole telecommunication services and they had to make repairs and
investigate the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could make money selling his story,'' Painter said, adding
he could also become a computer journalist. He pointed out that
convicted computer hacker Kevin Poulson, who was in the courtroom
covering the hearing, now works as an Internet journalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are possibilities for him,'' Painter said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the former Monroe High School student's agreement
with prosecutors, he will turn over any money he makes from movie
or book deals to the companies he victimized.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Mariana R. Pfaelzer told Mitnick he would
have to stay away from computers _ and from working in the computer
industry _ for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Pfaelzer had expected to sentence Mitnick on Monday, but granted
a two-week delay so his attorney has time to file a motion
challenging the prosecution's restitution request.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt the amount of victim loss is gigantic, but
the question is, Does Mitnick have the ability to pay?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To allow him no restitution would allow him to escape
responsibility,'' Painter said. ``He caused a substantial amount of
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick's computer hacking exploits fueled Web sites, books and
a coming movie. The 36-year-old became a hero to that hacking
underground while he was on the run, and by the time he was
captured in February 1995 he was the first hacker to make the FBI's
Most Wanted list.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick pleaded guilty in March to computer and wire fraud
charges. If Pfaelzer approves, the deal with prosecutors means he
could be free by December because of time already served in jail.
</P>
<P>
   State computer fraud charges filed in Van Nuys Superior Court
are pending against him.
</P>
<P>
   Pfaelzer delayed sentencing until July 26 because Randolph
complained he did not have time to respond to prosecutors' request
for $1.5 &UR;  &LR; million in restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick's exploits drew a small fan club to court Monday in
support of their cyberspace hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in jail more than four-and-a-half years. How much
restitution do they want him to pay?'' said supporter Josh Cohen.
``Some of the victims are multibillion-dollar corporations. What is
$1.5 &UR;  &LR; million going to do?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
