<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA SWELTERS IN DAMP HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sweating out near-record temperatures and high
humidity, Southern California residents suffered through another
wacky weather day with thunderstorms, lightning, a flood watch and
a statewide power alert.
</P>
<P>
   Woodland Hills in the San Fernando Valley was the hottest spot
in Los Angeles on Monday, with a 107-degree high and a ``misery
index'' of 130 _ meaning the humidity was so high it felt like 130
degrees, compared with a normal index in the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   And it's expected to be just as bad today: More hot and humid
air with a chance of showers and thunderstorms in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In an area where the humidity usually runs about 20 &UR;  &LR; percent,
readings of 45 &UR;  &LR; percent Sunday and Monday in the Valley and as high
as 65 &UR;  &LR; percent downtown left everyone cranky and looking to escape
the heat.
</P>
<P>
   So Sandy Fink's physical education classes at Mark Keppel
Elementary School in Glendale, Calif., can expect to spend its
exercise periods today in the auditorium playing paddle ball and
other games. Fink moved her classes at the year-round school off
the hot asphalt schoolyard by 9:30 a.m. Monday to beat the
stifling, sapping heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just blazing,'' Fink said. ``The kids went out for
their morning recesses and that was it and then we were in for the
rest of the day. The playground doesn't get a chance to cool down
overnight so once the sun hits it, it's horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The hot, dry weather that makes brush fires far more likely than
rain storms in summer has been mugged by monsoonal moisture.
</P>
<P>
   The humid air moved in over the weekend from the four-corners
states to the east, where the monsoon season is a summer staple. A
strong high pressure system on the California-Oregon border helped
draw the air flow into Southern California, said David Sweet, a
National Weather Service meteorologist in Oxnard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's getting it right now,'' Sweet said. ``It's a bit of
an extreme case of a situation that does affect us at least once
every summer. Normally it's a little bit later in the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Add a dose of hot air driving daytime temperatures 10-15 degrees
above normal on the coast and in the valleys and you have a recipe
for both dangerous rain and heat.
</P>
<P>
   The Weather Service posted flash-flood watches for the mountains
of Ventura and Los Angeles counties.
</P>
<P>
   Search dogs prowled mud and debris for more bodies Monday after
flash-flood waters 25 feet high swept homes, boulders and cars
through the mountain hamlet of Forest Falls. Bulldozers snaked a
path through the vacation community of 3,500 awash in debris that
included giant pine trees, wreckage of automobiles and propane
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Most at risk from the extreme heat are infants and children up
to age 4, the elderly, overweight adults, and people with health
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``People sometimes forget they can't keep up their usual
routines when they are exposed to the brunt of summer heat,'' said
Jonathan Fielding, the Los Angeles County director of public
health.
</P>
<P>
   ``When temperatures climb, you should take simple preventive
measures,'' he said. ``Obviously you don't want to exert yourself
too much outside. One of the most important things is often you
don't feel as thirsty as you are, so drinking fluids is very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Coastal beaches offered some relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the heat over in the Valley, they're coming. It's picking
up. Everybody's down here,'' said Lorry Haddock, a Los Angeles
County senior lifeguard based at Zuma Beach in Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he said the cooler coastal temperatures only eased the
effect of the sticky air. ``It's pretty sticky. We're getting the
high clouds pushing all the way over here. We don't usually get
that down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Air conditioning wasn't an option for animals at the Los Angeles
Zoo, but a 2-year-old misting system offered cooling comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every animal that we have here has a shaded environment
and, depending on the animals, they have either a misting system or
if it gets hot, as they do in the wild, they will lie down and go
to sleep,'' said Michael Dee, the zoo's general curator.
</P>
<P>
   The misting systems were turned on in recent days to keep a fine
spray of water flowing from midmorning to early evening. The water
will cool environments 10 degrees or more, Dee said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking particular advantage of the cooling, constant water spray
were the ostriches. They soak in the water and then ruffle feathers
before taking in more.
</P>
<P>
   The chimpanzees resort to splashing each other with water from a
recirculating creek in their exhibit. Keepers drenched elephants
with cooling water from hoses.
</P>
<P>
   Air conditioning surged with the beginning of the workweek,
triggering a Stage One Emergency in response to the hot and humid
weather. Both the Los Angeles Department of Water and Power and
Southern California Edison reported the greatest single-day
electricity usage of the year. The increases were as much as
20 &UR;  &LR; percent compared with a normal summer day.
</P>
<P>
   One factor is people turning up systems in the middle of the day
when temperatures and homes are hottest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes that long for the homes to get really uncomfortable
to the point where people really crank up the air,'' said Darlene
Battle, DWP spokeswoman. ``We're asking people to try to set the
air conditioner at 78 degrees, keep draperies drawn and windows
closed and limit appliances that use a lot of electricity during
the peak part of the day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
