r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-FUTURE-COMMENTARY     07-13 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FUTURE-COMMENTARY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE OF WOMEN'S PRO SOCCER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ OK, we've had a good two days to lower
ourselves from the pedestal created by the Women's World Cup in the
past three weeks. Perhaps that's not enough time to begin thinking
realistically again, but we'll give it a shot anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, this commentary isn't going to be one of those
women-bashing, soccer-bashing soliloquies we've come to expect in
this country on the downside of such a huge event.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was thrilling to be a small part of history in
watching the American team live up to the hype that surrounded its
World Cup victory over China.
</P>
<P>
   The images and emotions will last a lifetime, much the same way
those from the 1994 men's World Cup did when it was played in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   We're being told a women's professional soccer league is coming.
I plan to be there watching with my daughter when it happens, but I
also know I'm in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   Before our emotions get the best of us, let's take a step back
and realize what we witnessed Saturday at the Rose Bowl isn't
likely to be duplicated in our lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   We also must realize another professional sports league only
means another fragmentation of an already jaded sporting public
with diverse interests.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there is room for another league, and for that matter,
there is just cause to finally open opportunities for women never
before seen in athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the landscape of the American sporting scene may change in
the next century, but let's keep the expectations realistic.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men's soccer team surely captivated our nation when it
advanced to the second round of the '94 tournament. After beating
world power Colombia, enthusiasm was at a fever pitch, inspiring
such headlines as ``Miracle on grass.''
</P>
<P>
   Soccer never had been bigger or of greater interest in this
country. Television ratings went through the roof. Surely, this
would mean the sport was here to stay, right?
</P>
<P>
   Even then, however, the sport struggled to gain popularity at
the pro level in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it isn't here to stay, mind you. Major League Soccer
likely will persevere, but just not at the same level of a World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   MLS, which began two years after the '94 Cup, continues to
struggle at the gate and in television ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, these were many of the same American men who had inspired
this nation like no other soccer players had before, playing there
in MLS. Cobi Jones, Alexi Lalas, Tony Meola, John Harkes, Eric
Wynalda, Paul Caligiuri. Remember them?
</P>
<P>
   Why hasn't that league taken off? It likely never will, but that
doesn't mean it needs to be eradicated. We simply should remember
to keep it in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   And this has nothing to do with the fact the best men's soccer
in the world is played elsewhere. That argument fails when we
consider the plight of track and field in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, during every Olympic Games, Americans can't seem to get
enough track and field. We wave our flags, we tear up at every
gold-medal moment and we want it all to go on and on.
</P>
<P>
   But take Carl Lewis or Michael Johnson or Jackie Joyner-Kersee
or any other world-class American athlete who has given us
goosebumps during an Olympiad and put them in a ``regular'' meet.
For some reason, as a public, we really don't care.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Track and Field Championships were held last month in
Oregon. But did we care? Not really. There were no sellout crowds,
no TV ratings bonanzas.
</P>
<P>
   Why is that, you ask? It's because Americans support events, but
for whatever reason have a hard time doing the same when it comes
to the doldrums and the ordinary existence of a season's worth of
games.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the NFL, no other professional sports league has the
power to consistently captivate crowds outside its own individual
markets.
</P>
<P>
   That won't change with a women's professional soccer league. But
as long as those in the know realize, it doesn't mean a league
can't be successful on a number of levels.
</P>
<P>
   Determining what ``success'' means is open to interpretation.
And surely there will be those naysayers who will be standing by
with their ``I told you so's'' when the numbers begin to trickle in
for a women's league.
</P>
<P>
   ``What defines the success of a league will be different for
different people,'' U.S. assistant coach Lauren Gregg said. ``In
our opinion, it doesn't need to be TV ratings and attendance.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement may be nothing more than an attempt to provide
cushion down the road to what surely figures to be a drastic fall
from the moment's glory.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fact we're sitting here in the summer of '99 debating
the merits and prospects of a women's professional soccer league
should be looked upon as a victory in itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
