<SLUG> BC-HEARD-SHOOTING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS EXPRESS CONCERNS ABOUT SLAYING OF NEIGHBOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSAWATOMIE, Kan. _ Five months have passed since police fatally
shot Willie Heard during a drug raid at his house in this Miami
County city, but many people who attended a community forum Monday
night were still worried that the same thing could happen to them.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, the U.S. attorney's office, the U.S.
Department of Justice's Community Relations Service, the American
Civil Liberties Union and the Osawatomie police advisory board
answered questions from about 65 persons at the forum. City and
police officials were invited, but the city's insurance company
advised them not to attend because Heard's family is pursuing a
civil lawsuit in his death, said City Manager Ted Hayden.
</P>
<P>
   Heard, 46, was shot about 1:25 a.m. Feb. 13 when police and
Miami County sheriff's deputies rushed into his house with a
warrant, searching for crack cocaine that they thought was being
sold there. His daughter said she screamed for Heard when she woke
to the shouts of strange men around her. Officers found Heard with
a rifle in his bedroom and shot him. Police found a small amount of
what they believe was marijuana, but no cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute meeting Monday at Osawatomie's municipal
auditorium was scheduled to discuss police policies and citizens'
rights, but the discussion often focused on the situation from five
months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothers me the most about what happened to
Willie Heard is it was 11 seconds from entry to death, and I think
a lot of us are concerned about, `What if it happens to me?' &UR; ''
said Henry Gueary III, president of the NAACP's Olathe branch. His
group organized the forum.
</P>
<P>
   People need to talk about the problems in their communities and
they have to work closely with police, participants said. They also
need to register and vote for officials who share their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   There are no absolute solutions, but people must work to reduce
the chance that such a death will occur again, said Joe Rodriguez
of the Community Relations Service.
</P>
<P>
   Many questions dealt with processes by which police obtain
search warrants and what the rules for arrest are, but a common
thread was a discussion of ways to build better relations between
police and the rest of the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tragedy that it took a death to bring our community
together,'' said Gloria Anderson of Osawatomie, a friend of
Heard's. ``But now that we are together, we need to work to keep
this from happening again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
