r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEED-TRACK-2Takes-KA     07-13 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEED-TRACK-2Takes-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH TRACK SUCCESS HINTS AT ECONOMIC BOON AHEAD FOR KANSAS
CITY, KAN. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ If there's a Johnny Appleseed out there for
economic development projects it might be a state-of-the-art motor
speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Pat Svacina, a spokesman for City Hall in Fort Worth,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has been beyond our expectations,'' he said of the
spin-off businesses sprouting up around the 200,000-capacity Texas
Motor Speedway that opened two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Like what? Restaurants? Hotels and motels? Retail shops and
office buildings? More entertainment venues?
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the above,'' Svacina said.
</P>
<P>
   That's just what Kansas City, Kan., wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Florida-based International Speedway Corp., is building a $224
million Kansas Speedway in Kansas City, Kan., north of Interstate
70 just west of the Interstate 435 interchange. The track is
expected to open in early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If Fort Worth's experience is any guide, the metropolitan area's
most economically depressed community could enjoy a breathtaking
revival in the first decade of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't happen overnight,'' warned Eddie Gossage, general
manager of the Texas track.
</P>
<P>
   But stacked up against the past few decades of economic history
in Kansas City, Kan., another two- or three-year wait before an
economic boomlet would be just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an enormous opportunity for our community,'' said
Wyandotte County Unified Government Administrator Dennis Hays.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure the opportunity is not missed or muffed, the Unified
Government within weeks will begin a formal search for a master
developer to plan and oversee economic growth on 400 or so prime
acres of land around the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a temptation to grab the first deals that come
along,'' Hays said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to be selective and pick projects that
ensure a long-term quality and benefit to the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Would-be developers already are lining up at City Hall with
plans and proposals tucked under their arms, Hays said.
</P>
<P>
   A New York-based water theme park developer was the first to go
public with its blueprints for a family recreation center in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Hays confirmed that several national hotel and restaurant chains
are looking hard, as are local investors.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth traveled the same road about four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing wasn't really big around here'' before the track,
Svacina said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unknown factor for us was whether there was a (local fan)
market and whether people would drive here from other parts of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth officials had their answer even before the first race
weekend when the city's hotels were booked to capacity and overflow
crowds were forced to find lodging in Dallas, Arlington and other
cities in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, he added, ``folks spend a lot of bucks'' during
their weekend racing jaunts.
</P>
<P>
   That fact certainly wasn't lost on the local and national
developers and entrepreneurs who are financing Fort Worth's
spin-off building boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tourism dollars are the best dollars you can get,'' Gossage
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 40 percent of the people who come to auto races are
local,'' he said. ``The rest require accommodations, restaurants,
night clubs ... they forgot their toothbrush and they have to shop
at the local store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they go back home and leave all that tax money behind,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway Motor Sports Inc. built the Texas racetrack and a
nine-story office, condo and private club and restaurant next door
that is helping to keep the track and the surrounding area hopping
with traffic and other events about 300 days a year, Gossage said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Speedway will have about half the seating of Texas _
75,000 plus thousands more temporary seats _ at least for the time
being.
</P>
<P>
   Local track president Grant Lynch announced last week that plans
are already under way to increase the number of luxury suites. And,
he noted, the track is designed for the easy addition of up to
75,000 more grandstand seats. And most likely they will be built,
Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   The maxim in professional motor sports racing the past few years
has been: Build it and the crowds will come.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels, restaurants, condominiums and office parks have been
bursting out of the Texas soil around the track for two years,
Svacina said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a major announcement of a luxury hotel resort
being built in conjunction with a business park and golf course,''
Svacina said. ``The developers cited the racetrack as one of the
major reasons they came here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Cooper is general manager of a 102-room Hampton Inn &AMP;
Suites that opened in February at the nearby Alliance Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we would have chosen this spot if it wasn't for
the Texas Speedway,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is wonderful. We're full,'' she said, even when the
company bumps up its room rates about 30 percent on big race
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   And Cooper said her company recently broke ground next door for
a 140-room Hawthorne Suites operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all kinds of standing reservations,'' Cooper said.
``Mostly it's for the racing teams and our regular customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only book 50 weeks out. But we know as soon as we're able
to book them, they'll be in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said a new shopping center is expected to be announced
soon for a site across the highway from the track. It will probably
include a grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Texas track employee Linda Snelson said on race days one Fort
Worth grocery chain loads up an 18-wheel tractor-trailer rig and
sets up shop outside the track selling everything from cold cuts to
toilet paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people really appreciate that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On race weekends, Svacina said Fort Worth sales tax and hotel
room tax collections jump about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``To our amazement the (racing fans) market didn't have to
grow,'' Svacina said.
</P>
<P>
   It arrived full-grown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
