<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEED-TRACK-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH TRACK SUCCESS HINTS AT ECONOMIC BOON AHEAD FOR KANSAS
CITY, KAN. 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Kan., has heard this siren song of economic boom times
before.
</P>
<P>
   When The Woodlands pari-mutuel dog and horse racing tracks
opened in 1989, city leaders heralded the event as the springboard
for an economic development explosion along the same I-435 corridor
at the city's western fringe.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, of course, is the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   While auto racing has leaped to major spectator-sport status
nationwide in recent years, The Woodlands opened in the late '80s
as the U.S. pari-mutuel racing industry lay wheezing on its
deathbed.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, riverboat and tribal gambling swept the
Midwest. A succession of casinos opened and they are still thriving
in Iowa, Kansas, Missouri and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday early years, The Woodlands hastened the demise of
the struggling Ak-Sar-Ben track in Nebraska by grabbing Kansas
City's racing market for itself.
</P>
<P>
   By 1994, however, The Woodlands was in steep decline and then
was staggered by Kansas City's glitzy riverboat competition. The
track filed for bankruptcy in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Unified Government's Hays said experts who have studied the
motor sports marketplace do not expect the Kansas Speedway to
reprise The Woodlands' financial disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The racing industry is in a major growth mode,'' Hays said.
``And we will virtually be the major track in a 500-mile market
radius.''
</P>
<P>
   Hays said the tax-incentive table is being set now for
developers by virtue of last month's Unified Government approval of
a master land-use plan for western Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   Using state tax-incentive laws, the Unified Government
essentially will allow new retail developers within a specially
designated track ``tourism district'' to keep every penny of the
6.9 percent state and local sales taxes they collect to help pay
off their construction debts.
</P>
<P>
   According to state law, Hays said, those sales tax rebates will
be the only tax dollars those new developers will receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be on the property tax rolls,'' Hays said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally watched race days aren't the only moneymakers for
speedway neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the top-of-the-line NASCAR races, other major
sanctioning bodies use speedways _ among them the Sports Car Club
of America, the American Motorcyclist Association, North American
Sport Bike as well as truck and go-kart racing groups.
</P>
<P>
   The big Sunday NASCAR races _ usually two or three dates a year
for established tracks _ attract crowds to town as early as
Thursday for qualifying heats and practice runs, Fort Worth's
Svacina said.
</P>
<P>
   Racing isn't all that tracks offer.
</P>
<P>
   Svacina said the Texas track is being used more and more for
concerts and other large-crowd gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first music festival out here, the night of the concert,
you couldn't get a hotel room within 100 miles of this place,''
track employee Snelson said.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes there can be too much of a good thing. Gossage
said the track's first and last rock 'n' roll festival drew more
than 400,000 people over a weekend, overwhelming local facilities.
``We haven't done that again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said the track's Speedway Club has become a popular
venue for meetings, weddings and other gatherings. One couple got
married on the track surface, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said his Texas track is used about 200 days a year for
``racing school,'' a sort of fantasy camp for race fans who pay to
get behind the wheel of a race car.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get going about 150 miles an hour,'' Gossage said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Speedway's Lynch said similar race schools and other
non-racing uses for the track are being looked at here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to use the track all we can,'' Lynch said. ``We
promised to bring the people in.''
</P>
<P>
   After the track opens, Lynch said, local civic groups can look
to it for fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be looking at civic groups to come in and man the
concession stands for us'' just as the Kansas City Royals and other
entertainment venues have done here.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said the track will employ about 60 people year-round _
but will need as many 3,000 workers on race weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, who also is president of both the Talladega Superspeedway
in Alabama and the Talladega, Ala., Economic Development Authority,
is sensitive to what a community needs and wants from its tourism
industry.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is confident a track-fueled tourism industry will
grow up quickly in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city already has the infrastructure in place,'' he said,
unlike many new racing venues that are built at the undeveloped and
underpopulated fringes of major metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   Hays said he is typical of many people in the metropolitan area
who know little about pro motor racing, and he is learning as the
project proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   This spring he attended his first big-time race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole different culture than going to a Chiefs game,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
