<SLUG> BC-SUPERINTENDENT-SCHOOLS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL BOARD MEMBERS BOUND FOR OKLAHOMA TO CHECK OUT DEMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Three Kansas City Board of Education members
will travel to Oklahoma City Wednesday to look into the background
of Benjamin Demps Jr., a candidate to be the next superintendent of
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to talk to people who have interacted with him,'' said
board President John Rios. ``We want to find out about his
management style, about his credibility. We're hoping to find out
what other people feel about him.''
</P>
<P>
   The board will meet Wednesday night to determine whether to
offer the job to Demps and to begin contract negotiations. Demps,
65, is a retired Federal Aviation Administration official who also
headed the Oklahoma Department of Human Services in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Board members said attorneys for the district would try to
schedule interviews with Demps' former associates at the FAA and
the state agency, as well as civic leaders and minority groups such
as the Oklahoma City Urban League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to talk to some grass-roots groups,'' said board member
Helen Ragsdale, who will travel to Oklahoma for the day with board
members Connie Clark and Sandy Mayer. ``I want to meet with some of
the people who casually know him.''
</P>
<P>
   No interviews had been scheduled by Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Dean Whipple last week gave the school board
until July 19 to hire a superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Demps is the only one of four finalists identified by a
screening committee who did not later withdraw as a candidate. Even
so, several board members on Monday said he was not a shoo-in for
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether a board majority would support Demps, board member
Lee Barnes said: ``It's real close.''
</P>
<P>
   Members said they had not formulated a plan in case they do not
reach agreement with Demps. That discussion will take place
Wednesday if necessary, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We better have something to give the court on Monday
morning,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The court-appointed Desegregation Monitoring Committee has said
it may recommend that it appoint an interim superintendent if the
board can't meet the court's deadline. The interim superintendent
would report to the DMC, not the school board. The board could then
continue its search for a permanent superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Board members on Monday also agreed to have district
representatives contact another finalist, retired Air Force Maj.
Gen. Jay T. Edwards, to tell him he is not being considered for
superintendent at this time. Edwards withdrew last month and then
later said he was still interested in the post. He contacted
several board members in recent days expressing his interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an option right now,'' Mayer said. ``We're focusing
on Demps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
