A7732 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROTEST-HIGHWAY-KAN &LR;      07-13 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
PROTEST OVER MINORITY HIRING CLOSES INTERSTATE 70 IN ST. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- PROTEST-HIGHWAY-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Janette Hill figured what she and several hundred
others did Monday morning was justified _ even if it meant blocking
busy Interstate 70 during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all else fails you have to try this,'' the former Kansas
City resident said as demonstrators gathered early Monday about
five miles west of downtown St. Louis. ``If political leaders can't
take control, people have to take control.''
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by chants of ``Shut It Down,'' the protesters did just
that. They shut down I-70 for nearly an hour because they said
there were too few minorities working on state highway projects in
the St. Louis area.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested 125 demonstrators and charged them with impeding
traffic and disobeying a police officer, a St. Louis police
spokesman said. Those arrested were released by noon. They face
August court appearances on the city charges.
</P>
<P>
   The list of persons arrested included the Rev. Al Sharpton, a
New York civil rights leader who headed the protest, and three
Missouri lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of protesters streamed across the highway about 6:30
a.m., halting six lanes of eastbound and westbound traffic.
Supporters on a nearby overpass cheered them on.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said there were about 900 people at
the march. Organizers earlier said they hoped to attract 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop James C. Christmas of St. Louis said he brought several
hundred dollars in his pocket and was prepared to go to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate America wants black folks to take a small piece of
the pie,'' Christmas said. ``I don't think we want a slice. We want
the pie.''
</P>
<P>
   But the morning rush hour tieup also triggered complaints from
some of those caught in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to get...out of my way so I can go to work,'' said
Gabrielle Dyer of O'Fallon, who works for TWA in St. Louis and was
one of the motorists who had to grind to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is the way to go about it,'' Dyer said of
the protest.
</P>
<P>
   Many commuters used alternate routes because threats of a
protest had been publicized for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Hindmon, who heads a group that represents minority
contractors, said protesters want minority firms to account for 25
percent of state highway projects in the city of St. Louis and for
minorities to represent 35 percent of the work force.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Taegel of the Missouri Department of Transportation said
the statewide goal is to have 10 percent representation by
minority- and female-owned firms on state highway projects. Exact
figures vary depending on location and types of projects, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A $19 million highway and bridge project in St. Louis that drew
most of the protesters' ire has about 14 percent minority
representation, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Sifford, chief of staff for Gov. Mel Carnahan, defended
the state's highway practices and said Monday that contractors have
voluntarily agreed to boost minority participation on the St. Louis
project.
</P>
<P>
   The requirement for minority participation depends on location
of the project and what type of work is being done, Taegel said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Lewis &AMP; Clark Viaduct stretch of I-70 in
downtown Kansas City requires that 10 percent of the project's work
be awarded to disadvantaged business enterprises _ those owned by
minorities and women.
</P>
<P>
   Some parts of the Bruce R. Watkins Drive project require 15
percent; many rural projects have no minority requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Several contractors in 1995 unsuccessfully sued the state
Highway and Transportation Commission. They said several firms on
the Watkins project were not legitimately allocating work to
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Malone, a board member of the Minority Contractors
Association of Greater Kansas City, said Missouri's highway
department has a ``very good program'' to include minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for people to feel like their community is
part of the process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's protest followed a weekend of talks between state
officials and organizers of the rally. The talks were aimed at
reaching an agreement that could have prevented the blockade.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters started gathering around 5 a.m. for Monday's rally.
Organizers hawked $5 ``Shut Them Down'' T-shirts. Sharpton and
others led protesters in a variety of chants while several
television helicopters swirled overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a moment we are going to move to the highway,'' said
attorney Eric Vickers, one of the leaders. ``We're going to shut it
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later a group of marchers bolted down an on-ramp to I-70
and waved travelers to a halt. Dozens more protesters, many
shouting and waving their fists in the air, followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sending a message to the administration of the state,''
said state Sen. Jet Banks, a St. Louis Democrat and one of three
lawmakers arrested on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not getting our fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   The other lawmakers arrested were state Reps. Charles Quincy
Troupe and Paula Carter, both St. Louis Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Ten or 15 minutes after protesters took over the highway, St.
Louis Police Department Col. Everett Page approached the
demonstrators, many of whom were sitting on the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't move yourself from the highway you will be
arrested,'' Page said.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later Sharpton was the first to be led to a nearby St.
Louis law enforcement van as supporters cheered.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests were anything but a 1960s-style showdown between
police and marchers. Both sides were cordial. Some police officers
chatted easily with those they took into custody. Some callers to
St. Louis radio stations complained that police accorded protesters
kid-glove treatment.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Police Chief Ron Henderson defended his department's
handling of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some inconvenience to motorists, protesters made their
statement and no one was hurt, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
