r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KCSI-SPINOFF-KAN &LR;      07-13 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KCSI-SPINOFF-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC SOUTHERN INDUSTRIES GETS TAX-FREE STATUS FOR PLANNED SPINOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City Southern Industries Inc. on
Monday finally got official tax-free status for its planned spinoff
of its Janus and Berger mutual fund families into a separate public
company.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Southern also revealed that the new fund company
would be called Stilwell Financial Inc. Spokesman Bill Galagan said
the name honored the Kansas City financier who founded Kansas City
Southern Railway more than a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur E. Stilwell, a New York state native, moved to Kansas
City in 1888 and formed plans for the railroad. He even traveled to
Holland during an economic depression in the United States to raise
money to stretch the railroad to the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The approval Monday came from the Internal Revenue Service.
Kansas City Southern had sought IRS assurances that the spinoff
would not trigger taxes for its shareholders. Kansas City Southern
had been seeking the approval for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The spinoff plan calls for shareholders of Kansas City Southern
to receive shares of Stilwell Financial in the fourth quarter. A
date has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   Galagan said the distribution of shares couldn't proceed until
after Oct. 22. The plan approved by the IRS requires Kansas City
Southern to have owned Berger Associates Inc. for at least five
years. Kansas City Southern acquired majority ownership of Berger
in October 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The new company's shares are expected to trade on the New York
Stock Exchange under the ticker symbol SV. Kansas City Southern
would continue to trade on the New York exchange under the ticker
symbol KSU.
</P>
<P>
   Stilwell Financial will own Janus Capital Corp., the $160
billion Denver-based mutual fund giant; Berger Associates, its $4
billion neighbor; Nelson Money Managers PLC in England; and 32
percent of the shares of DST Systems Inc. in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Southern will continue to operate its railway
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS approval came the same day an article in Barron's
reported pleas from the Janus fund group to be spun off into a
separate company.
</P>
<P>
   Galagan said officials from Janus and Kansas City Southern spoke
about alternative plans for the spinoff at recent meetings in New
York. But he said the plan the IRS approved would be the plan the
company would use.
</P>
<P>
   ``This IRS ruling is worth between $2.5 (billion) and $5.5
billion to our shareholders'' because of its tax-free structure,
Galagan said. ``If someone could come up with another plan with
that kind of value to our shareholders ... we would do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
