<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7735 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARTINEZ-HNS &LR;      07-13 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARTINEZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BOSTON _ For years, he was known as Ramon Martinez's little brother
_ the skinny kid who former Los Angeles Dodgers manager Tommy
Lasorda thought was too little to be an effective starting pitcher
in the big leagues.
<TEXT>
<P>
   His frame was so slight, pitching coaches used to discourage him
from running between starts because they felt it would take too
much of a toll on his diminutive body.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez never got much bigger in physical stature. But
despite a 5-11, 170-pound frame, he's living quite large these
days. Ask anyone in Boston, and they'll tell you he's the biggest
star among the star-studded group gathered for tonight's 70th
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, Martinez will be the American League's starting
pitcher at Fenway Park, where he is absolutely revered.
Philadelphia's Curt Schilling is the National League's starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a big deal for the fans,'' Martinez said.
``They're going to be very loud. I know my fans. They're probably
going to be banging on the walls and rooting my name. It's going to
be fun. I'm pretty sure we're going to see some crazy things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to pitch the way I always pitch, and I'm not going
to try to do anything special. It's a fun game, and that's the way
I'm going to approach it. With this being the last (All-Star) game
of the millennium and it being at Fenway, that makes it even more
special. It's a historic game, and I'm glad to take part in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of history, Martinez is chasing a piece of it this
season. He cruised to the All-Star break with a 15-3 record and has
a chance to become the major leagues' first 30-game winner since
Denny McLain won 31 games for Detroit in 1968. Dizzy Dean (1934)
was the last man to accomplish the feat before McLain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never won 20 games,'' said Martinez, who established a
career high with 19 victories in 1998. ``So I'm not even focusing
on 30. With all we've seen from Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa, Juan
Gonzalez, Manny Ramirez and a lot of the offensive guys, I think it
would be great to have something like that from the standpoint of a
pitcher's contribution to the game. Of course, 30 wins means
something to me. But it's not going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, things never have been easy for Martinez, who had
plenty of doubters when he was a minor-league pitcher in the
Dodgers organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people doubting me my whole life, people who didn't
know anything about the game,'' said Martinez, whom the Dodgers
traded to Montreal, which shipped him to Boston in a salary-dump
trade after he won the National League's Cy Young Award in 1997.
``But those people who doubted me have to be banging their heads
right now. To understand what I went through to get here, you would
have had to live it. That's the only way I can explain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even doubted myself sometimes. I looked at myself in the
mirror and thought, `Maybe you're not good enough. Maybe you won't
make it.' But I remember going to Los Angeles in 1990 to visit my
brother, and I saw a lot of guys who didn't throw as hard as me.
Then I said to myself, `Why can't I do it?' I think all of that has
made me appreciate all of this more.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 2.10 ERA and 184 strikeouts in 132 innings this season,
Martinez is nowadays being compared to the likes of Nolan Ryan and
Sandy Koufax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a good start to the season,'' Martinez said. ``It's
been all roses for me so far, and I hope I can keep it up. I take a
lot of pride in being considered with guys like that. It's a great
compliment. But I don't think I belong in the same category with
those guys, because I haven't done what they've done yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez won't be able to say that if he wins 30 games. And
while it would be difficult to imagine the 27-year-old righthander
duplicating his win total in the second half of the season, it's
not out of the question. Even Martinez, whose humility is perhaps
his most charming quality, believes he has an outside chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things have to go right,'' he said. ``If you get 35
starts in a season, it could happen. Why not? I don't know who's
going to get it, but I hope it's me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get close to 30 _ like 25 _ I'll be asking to pitch every
day. Realistically, if I have a shot at it, I could probably make
three starts in nine days. But I'm not going to be stupid about it
and risk an injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan already has concerns about
Martinez's workload over the first half of the season. Martinez is
averaging an American League-high 112.59 pitches per game this
season, and he averaged 114.12 pitches last year, second only to
Roger Clemens in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   To buy Martinez a little time, Kerrigan plans to put him at the
end of the Red Sox's rotation after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get a little vacation there, a little break,'' Kerrigan
said. ``I think he needs it body-wise. We want to make sure he
comes out strong in the second half. We feel by giving him the
little vacation break, we'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has proved to be a slightly more productive pitcher in
the first half of the season throughout his career. Excluding 1999,
he is 46-20 with a 2.87 ERA before the All-Star break and 38-26
with a 3.11 ERA afterward. He's 7-11 with a 3.27 ERA in September,
including a 1-3 record with a 4.15 ERA last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws a lot of pitches, has a lot of strikeouts, and he
may wear down more than the average guy,'' Kerrigan said. ``That's
why you really track his number of pitches and the number of days
he has between starts. I think he'll be OK in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he falls short of 30 wins, Martinez is in the process of
putting together one of the best seasons for a pitcher in the last
half of this century, which isn't bad for a short, skinny kid who
some thought wouldn't last in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I could pitch in the big leagues, but I never
thought I'd be at the point I am now,'' Martinez said. ``I never
thought I'd be given a chance. But looking back, no one gave it to
me. I earned it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
