<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7736 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALL-STARS-     07-13 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALL-STARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BOSTON _ So this is what being an All-Star is all about.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Billy Wagner was introduced to a Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton shared an elevator with baseball's hottest pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   And Jose Lima was, well, Jose Lima.
</P>
<P>
   All of the attention might take some getting used to, but the
Astros' contingent of first-time All-Stars did their best Monday to
get acquainted with the new surroundings. They mingled with fellow
players, spoke with hordes of media, signed plenty of autographs
and stood in awe as they looked out at historic Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The experience, they say, will be hard to forget.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner walked through a crowd of people at a downtown hotel,
holding his 11-month-old son, Will, in his arms. He entered a
hospitality room, where he was introduced to Hall of Famer Frank
Robinson. The Astros closer turned to his infant son and whispered,
``You'll never know whom you met.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlton Fisk, whom Wagner watched play growing up, passed by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too scared to say anything,'' Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton casually walked around the hotel lobby before entering
an elevator. Standing beside him was none other than Boston Red Sox
ace Pedro Martinez, tonight's American League starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just like everybody else,'' Hampton said of his encounter
with Martinez. ``He's easy to talk to. He doesn't let the stardom
go to his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima spent the morning entertaining crowds of reporters who
gathered around the table where he sat. He spoke of his 13
first-half wins, of the Astros' chances in the final three months,
even about the state of the game.
</P>
<P>
   And that was only the tip of the iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after his arrival at Fenway Park, Lima was in the
outfield, cap turned backward, dancing to the beat of merengue
music blaring from the public address system.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Martinez, a fellow Dominican, approached Lima and
playfully bowed in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the attention,'' Lima said. ``I'm so excited. I don't
know what to say. It's going to hit me when I see everybody hitting
bombs out of the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought of taking center stage in one of baseball's biggest
events slowly began to sink in for the Astros' representatives on
the plane ride from Kansas City to Boston late Sunday night. They
celebrated with a bottle of champagne as Jeff Bagwell shared
memories of his three previous All-Star appearances.
</P>
<P>
   As the group headed to baggage claim, autograph seekers spotted
Bagwell. Wagner just kept walking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baggy was stuck back there,'' Wagner said. ``That's the price
of fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday was a particularly special day for Wagner, 27, who spent
the morning walking around Boston with his wife, Sarah, and family
members. Wagner has been in the majors full-time only three years,
but his wait to be an All-Star goes back further.
</P>
<P>
   As he approached his locker and saw his All-Star jersey hanging
up, Wagner had a tough time convincing himself he belonged. After
all, he never was an All-Star even in Little League.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was the coach, and he told me flat-out I was
terrible,'' Wagner said. ``I pitched, and that didn't work out.
Then he put me in right field; that's where you put all the shoddy
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little different when your dad is the coach. He didn't
want all the other parents getting mad if he takes his son and not
the other guy's son. This is a little better than the ninth-grade
All-Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner watched his first major-league game at Fenway Park in
1992 _ Red Sox vs. Milwaukee Brewers _ while playing in the Cape
Cod League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember walking up the runway and seeing the Green Monster
and being in awe of the whole thing,'' Wagner said. ``Now that I'm
pitching here, it's not a big deal. If a guy hits a home run off
me, that ball is way out of there anyway. It doesn't matter how
high that fence is.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting players from the American League was the highlight
Monday for Wagner, Hampton and Lima. Tonight, they hope to enter
the game and help the National League to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to throw a strike and not embarrass myself,''
Wagner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
