<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7737 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-SPI &LR;      07-13 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-SPI </SLUG>
  
 Midsummer Classic a dream for first-time All-Stars  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Five years ago, Jeff Zimmerman was living off baguettes
and cheap red wine, playing before 40 people a night in a country
that doesn't understand why it is poor etiquette to steal bases
when a team is down 15 runs.
</P>
<P>
   When you've played for the Montpellier Barracudas of France's
National Baseball League _ not to mention the Winnipeg Goldeyes of
the Northern League _ you appreciate a day like Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a little bit intimidated,'' said Zimmerman, a Texas
Rangers reliever and an American League All-Star. ``I was going
down the elevator with Cal Ripken, and I wanted to introduce myself
to him, but I didn't. It was pretty full, and he was talking to
other people. I didn't want to interrupt his conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   All-Stars aren't supposed to be sheepish. But Zimmerman is. So
is Kent Bottenfield. And Paul Byrd. And Jeromy Burnitz. And a host
of other first-time All-Stars who have come a long way in a short
time.
</P>
<P>
   Burnitz, a Milwaukee Brewers outfielder, will be the National
League's starting left fielder Tuesday night at Fenway Park in
baseball's 70th All-Star Game. As he looked around a hotel ballroom
Monday, he saw a lot of stories that read something like his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we've got 15 or 16 first-time guys,'' said Burnitz,
who has been traded twice. ``I don't know _ is that normal?''
</P>
<P>
   It's not, and it's even more dramatic than Burnitz estimated.
Twenty-four All-Stars have never participated in a midsummer
classic, including 17 on the National League roster. (The record
for first-time Stars is 30, in 1988.) Albert Belle, Barry Bonds,
Kevin Brown, Roger Clemens, Juan Gonzalez, Greg Maddux, Alex
Rodriguez, Frank Thomas and Mo Vaughn will have the same seat as
you _ at home, on the couch.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Brad Ausmus was last year, and every year before
that. The Detroit Tigers catcher is a veteran of five organizations
and has been asking Tigers coaches and veterans what to expect at
his first All-Star Game. This much he knows: ``It gives me a better
seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Twins third baseman Ron Coomer didn't believe it when
a club official told him he'd made the team. Coomer spent nine
years in the minor leagues and is with his fourth organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many miles I've logged on buses, but that's
the way it goes,'' Coomer said. ``Everyone's road to the big
leagues is a little different, and mine was just a little longer.
It makes you realize and appreciate how fun it is to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ausmus and Coomer are having solid seasons, but they probably
owe their spots to the requirement that each club be represented.
Ausmus acknowledged as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why players get upset,'' he said. ``But if you
step back and look at the whole picture, that controversy brings
more attention to the All-Star Game.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of other unknown All-Stars who were not their
club's only selection. Burnitz has company in teammate Dave
Nilsson, an Australian catcher who is a first-timer in his 13th pro
season. Bottenfield, a pitcher with the St. Louis Cardinals, is a
teammate of Mark McGwire. Zimmerman has three other Rangers on the
roster; Byrd two other Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, fans are not the only star-gazers in Boston this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be professional about it,'' said Bottenfield, who
brought a video camera. ``But at the same time, it's like being a
kid. It's a dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield, whose career record was 18-27 before this season,
leads the National League with 14 wins. He was released once,
signed a minor league contract three times and often considered
quitting. Since making the All-Star team, he said, he's been
congratulated by general managers who once gave up on him. ``I
guess I made a mistake,'' one told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an ordinary person; playing baseball is the only
difference between me and somebody else,'' Bottenfield said. ``I
know it can go as quickly as it came. I know how fast it can leave.
The talent is too good inside and outside this room. Guys could
beat you into the ground and you could never come back up.''
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, Bottenfield was teammates with Jose Lima, the
Houston Astros right-hander who went 8-16 with a 6.24 earned run
average in parts of three seasons with the Tigers. Pitchers like
himself and Lima, Bottenfield said, were taught to throw hard and
didn't have success until they learned to back off, change speeds
and locate their pitches better.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who is 13-4, enjoyed four bottles of champagne (the small
kind, he said) with his fellow Astros All-Stars on the flight to
Boston Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left Detroit, I never thought I was going to be at this
point, being an All-Star,'' Lima said. ``I've come a long way.
That's the biggest (story) in Detroit right now: I can't believe
they traded Lima.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans in Atlanta must have the same trouble believing their club
let Byrd get away on waivers. The Phillies became his fourth
organization when they claimed him last August, and the
right-hander has gone 16-7.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame, Byrd said, that players often get labels they
can't shake. His success, and that of fellow first-time/long-road
All-Stars, makes him wonder how many more potential All-Stars are
never discovered.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also evidence of just how unpredictable things can be
in baseball. Because if the Bottenfields and Byrds can dress next
to the Griffeys and Ripkens, just about anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows that as long as you have a uniform,'' Byrd said,
``you always have a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 0147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7738 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-13 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BOSTON _ On good knees, Mike Hampton Sr. might have won.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the father of Astros All-Star pitcher Mike
Hampton has bad knees _ quite the contrary, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always used to challenge my dad, but I never beat him in a
race until I was 16,'' said Mike Jr., whose football coaches at
Crystal River High in Florida clocked him at a sizzling 4.45 in the
40-yard dash. ``My dad can run. He's a great athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Mike Sr.'s youngest son, Cody, continued the long
family tradition by challenging his father to a footrace as they
were sightseeing near Fenway Park on Sunday night, Mike Sr.'s knees
still were wobbly from the first commercial flight of his life
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to cheat at the start, but I'm 46, and I could have
gone my whole life without that airplane ride,'' said Mike Sr., who
previously has gotten in his car and driven up to 37 hours to watch
Mike Jr. play ball. ``I couldn't eat; I couldn't do anything on
that flight. I hated every minute of it scared to death. When they
told us it was going to last two hours and 40 minutes, I was
counting the minutes off one by one.''
</P>
<P>
   But a promise is a promise. Especially the ones you make to your
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told everyone that if Mike ever made it to the All-Star
Game, I'd fly to wherever it was,'' Mike Sr. said. ``They almost
had to drag me onto that plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton indeed has made it. But it hasn't been with much
fanfare or noise.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Monday when the world's media gathered to visit
with the National League All-Stars, there were more than 30
reporters watching an empty chair _ jockeying for position in front
of the seat that belonged to St. Louis Cardinals slugger Mark
McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the adjacent seat, Hampton sat looking wide-eyed
and in awe of it all, with never more than four or five reporters
talking to him. Most often, it was just one or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried I'd be sitting here by myself,'' Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   He joked about how when he and Astros closer Billy Wagner walked
through a hotel lobby Monday morning with Arizona ace Randy
Johnson, the fans thought Johnson had brought his kids with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like, `Daddy, can we get some candy?''' Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   For Hampton, this All-Star experience isn't about pounding his
chest, signing autographs or acting too good for it all, like Big
Mac did, for example, never showing for Monday's mixer with the
media.
</P>
<P>
   It's about hearing the screams on the other end of the telephone
line when he called home and told his mother and father he had made
the All-Star team. It's about all those days when he was the one
challenging his father to a footrace, going to the park to play
catch, sharing a dream with his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got bruised and bloody a lot trying to keep up with my
dad,'' Hampton said. ``And then when I got home, my mom would clean
me up.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about seeing the looks on his parents' faces when he walked
into their hotel Monday and was an NL All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have a real close-knit family,'' Hampton said. ``We
support each other, and it's always been that way. My dad has
always been the one that could do anything. I used to ask him,
`Hey, let's play tennis.' And when you go out there, he plays
great. It's the same in basketball, anything. He's just got a lot
of ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many dads, Mike Sr. often dreamed about his son making it
to a stage such as this one. But who knew Mike Jr. would be among
McGwire, Ken Griffey Jr. and Sammy Sosa?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a hillbilly from Tennessee,'' Mike Sr. said. ``We
never had a whole lot growing up. And when we moved to Florida, I
pretty much had to work to help out. I just can't believe all this
is happening for Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sr. married young and was just 19 when he and Joan Hampton
had Mike Jr. He coached his son in Little League and high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Mike and I grew up together,'' Mike Sr. said. ``We
were strict on him and always wanted Mike to be respectful of
people and do the right thing. But a lot of times we were just two
kids competing with each other. He'd come home from school and
always want to go out and play ball. I did, too. This is like a
dream seeing him here.''
</P>
<P>
   But whose dream is it? Mike Sr.'s or Mike Jr.'s?
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about this is they're here to watch me,''
Hampton said. ``It wouldn't be the same if they weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   The only bad part about it all comes Wednesday morning. Mike Sr.
has to get back on an airplane and fly home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't care much for looking at stuff getting smaller
under my feet,'' Mike Sr. said. ``And I wouldn't mind if I never
rode in an airplane again.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he won't have to _ for a while, anyway. Next year's
All-Star Game is in Atlanta, an easy drive from Orlando. But then
there's the 2001 game. In Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 0147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
