<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7739 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS &LR;      07-13 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Sometimes, it's self-serving when golfers
predict gloom and doom about how tough a course will play. When
they finish with a decent score, it makes them look all the more
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the British Open, which begins Thursday at
Carnoustie, forecasts of bogeymania are a case of the truth being
too obvious to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Carnoustie is so nasty that players are saying an aggregate
score of 300 probably will be competitive Sunday afternoon. That's
4-over-par 75 on each day. The last time 300 won the Open
Championship was 1925, when Jim Barnes shot that number at
Prestwick.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course is great,'' Steve Elkington said, ``as long as
it's a par-76.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, par will be 71, and nobody is expecting to beat it over 72
holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it blows hard, I don't know,'' Elkington said. ``They may
have ruined the course. It's a really great course. But you've got
fairways that are 19 yards wide. It's playing to 7,361 yards with
the potential to play a lot longer with the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``By Sunday, they can take all the red (under-par) numbers and
throw them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind, these comments came Monday, a day that was
picture-perfect for Houston and virtually unmatched by Scottish
standards. A light breeze, sunshine and temperatures in the 70s
made scoring as easy as it could be.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the tight fairways, knee-length rough and sloping greens all
had players wondering what things will look like by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two holes, I felt like it was such a claustrophobic
course,'' Lee Janzen, a two-time U.S. Open champion, said. ``The
fairways just aren't very wide. And if you're in the rough and try
to advance the ball, you can just get deeper and then you're
looking at a really big number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Par will be a great score. And I think higher than that will
win. And that's in good conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course really will beat up guys who are on the edge (of
playing mediocre). I think this is the first time you'll hear guys
saying the British Open is more unfair than the U.S. Open.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfair'' is a word used cautiously by golfers. Everybody plays
the same course. So nothing should be viewed as unfair, in some of
their minds. But several fairways at Carnoustie are less than 20
yards wide at the landing area. And they get even narrower for
longer hitters. With few of the fairways level, moguls can kick a
ball 10 or 15 yards in any direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got 470-yard par-4s where even a drive straight down
the middle doesn't end up in the fairway,'' Janzen said. ``That's
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   And the rough is severe. The club at Carnoustie installed an
upgraded sprinkler system last year, and the rough has been watered
and fertilized. Even though it's weeds and heather, it still has
sprouted up knee-high in many places. And even the shorter ``first
cut'' is deep enough to require a search crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw it in conditions that just don't exist,'' said U.S.
Open champion Payne Stewart. ``It was just a fabulous day for golf.
But the fairways are very narrow. And if you spend a lot of time in
the rough, you're not going to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Colin Montgomerie has grown up and honed his game in Scotland.
He loves windy, misty, cold conditions. But even he knows
Carnoustie might be over the borderline beyond a fair test of golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most difficult (course he could remember), by a
long, long way,'' said Montgomerie, who is fresh from a victory
last week at Loch Lomond. ``And that's on a glorious summer's day
with very, very light breeze. If it becomes a wind, you'll see
scores higher than we've ever, ever seen before in any British
Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it does blow at all, the 300 mark _ people talk about the
300 mark not being (realistic) _ but it might well be, because I
don't think 4 over par is a bad round here.''
</P>
<P>
   There are seven par-4s that are 459 yards or longer. Many will
play into the teeth of the wind. There are predictions that ``a big
blow,'' as Tom Watson called it, will be heading into the area
Thursday. And then, life will be miserable for the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I'll hit 3-iron, 3-wood and then hopefully I'll be
able to find it,'' Montgomerie said. ``Hopefully it'll be a brief
search.''
</P>
<P>
   But because of the harsh conditions, Elkington believes the
championship is up for grabs perhaps more than it ever has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tournament is going to be a lot closer event,'' he said.
``Everybody is in it. Somebody could be seven or eight shots back
on Sunday, shoot even-par and be right there at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big hitters have no advantage, because they'll be hitting
irons off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie agreed that accuracy will be more important than
length, even though the course is playing so long. Better to make
bogey from the fairway than double bogey from the deep rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has to be champion here on Sunday evening,''
Montgomerie said. ``I feel as confident as anybody. But it's a
matter of being very, very patient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
