A7740 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BB0-ALLSTAR-HOMERS-SP     07-13 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB0-ALLSTAR-HOMERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY WINS ALL-STAR HOMER CONTEST FOR THIRD TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For several days, usually without prompting, Ken
Griffey Jr. had dropped hints about the All-Star Home Run Derby. He
hadn't been invited, he said. He wanted to bring his own batting
practice pitcher, he joked. His sore left knee might keep him out.
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise, then, that when the contestants were first
announced Monday, Griffey's name was not among them.
</P>
<P>
   And it was no surprise that after testing the knee in batting
practice, the Mariners' center fielder took part anyway _ and won
it for the third time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe five minutes,'' he said, when asked how close he came to
not participating. ``It's still a little sore, so I've got to do
what's best for my team and the organization under the
circumstances. We've still got a chance in the second half to make
a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Griffey's team is the American League All-Stars,
and it's a group among whom he thrives. Even Griffey's opponent in
the final round, Jeromy Burnitz of the Milwaukee Brewers, knew he
was overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much knew I was going to lose,'' Burnitz said. ``He
got down to like one or two outs to stay in the round, and then hit
a bunch. You're talking about guys that can do it at will. And when
he had to, he did it. And he does that quite often.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey won last year's derby in Denver, silencing the boos he
got from the Coors Field crowd after first declining to take part.
He also captured the 1994 contest at Pittsburgh's Three Rivers
Stadium and became the first player to hit the warehouse at Oriole
Park at Camden Yards during the 1993 derby in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey was one out away from elimination in the first round
Monday. He had only one homer in his first 10 swings, but homered
twice to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, which also included Burnitz, Houston's Jeff
Bagwell and St. Louis' Mark McGwire, Griffey homered 10 times,
including his longest, a 460-foot blast to the wall behind the
center field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   Burnitz homered twice in the last round, and Griffey had no
homers after three swings. But he homered on his next three swings,
the last a 438-footer over the bullpen in right field, to win.
</P>
<P>
   He had 16 homers overall, tied with McGwire for the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just going out there and having a lot of fun, that's the
main thing,'' said Griffey, whose son Trey joined him on the field
during the contest. ``Going out there, putting on a show for the
fans, and watching Mark hit them 500 feet. You're getting them over
like 420, 430, and his balls are doing the postal service (thing),
just flying by you and dropping mail off at your house.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's homers averaged 420 feet. McGwire's averaged 438, and
he hit most of his to left field. At Fenway Park, that means over
the Green Monster and onto Landsdowne Street and its mosh pit of
fans. McGwire set a single-round record with 13 homers in the first
round, one of which hit the lights and the last of which traveled a
Derby-long 488 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter how many you hit,'' Griffey said. ``I think
the distance is the most important thing that the people
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire easily outshined his 1998 home run comrade, the Chicago
Cubs' Sammy Sosa. Sosa, who admitted, ``I'm not too good hitting
BP,'' had just one 371-foot homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was enjoying it just like everybody else was,'' McGwire said
of his heroics. ``I was having fun. I love doing these things.
Earlier in my career, when I didn't accept myself as a home run
hitter, I didn't like doing these things. But now I enjoy them. I
think sometimes it's better than the game.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire noted that last night's event was carried live, instead
of on tape delay as in the past. ``The home run,'' he said, ``has
really taken over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   A longtime American Leaguer, he also made a pitch to save Fenway
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's baseball, and it's going to be sad to think that they're
going to have to make a new one here,'' McGwire said. ``It's hard
to think that they can't just redo this in a way where they can
make it more comfortable, more stands here. I thought they should
shut down Landsdowne Street and put bleachers out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, McGwire's wish won't be granted; the Red Sox are hoping to
replace their 87-year-old home with a ``New Fenway'' by 2003. But
he gave Landsdowne Street an unforgettable farewell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
