<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 02:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7765 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALL-STAR_RAMIREZ-     07-13 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR_RAMIREZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERIOUS RAMIREZ ON VERGE OF GREATNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Cleveland Indians slugger Manny Ramirez was accused of
using a corked bat during a May series against the New York
Yankees. No way, several Yankees argued, could Ramirez flick his
bat at an ankle-high pitch and send it to the stands with such
ease.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had Ramirez's bat checked, but nothing illegal was
found.
</P>
<P>
   One joke, however, that quickly made the rounds suggested
Ramirez's head, not his bat, was filled with cork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people think that way of me, and there's nothing I
can do to change that,'' Ramirez said. ``I'm not someone who gets
involved in many serious things. I like to keep my life simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The laughable part of the bat incident is Ramirez's choice of
lumber changes from day to day and, sometimes, at-bat to at-bat.
Teammates have often had to persuade Ramirez to stop using their
bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever bat feels comfortable to him at that moment he
uses,'' Indians second baseman Roberto Alomar said. ``If it feels
good in his hands, it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez is one of the most mysterious players in the game,
someone whose burgeoning talent has him on the verge of being
mentioned as the greatest run-producer in the majors these days.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, whose 96 RBI at the All-Star break have him on pace to
reach 178 this season, could challenge Hack Wilson's single-season
record of 191.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the big reasons I don't like to do many interviews is
that I want to focus all my energies and concentrate fully on the
RBI record,'' Ramirez said. ``I want to give my all for that
record. I know I have a chance this year, and who knows, I may
never be in this position again.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 27, some wonder just how good Ramirez, who was born in
the Dominican Republic and moved to New York City at age 13, can
become. He has already hit 179 home runs and has 613 RBIs in his
barely 5-year-old career.
</P>
<P>
   Say one thing for Ramirez: He managed to concentrate on sports
while growing up in the Washington Heights section of New York, an
area where some youths head into a life of drugs and crime.
</P>
<P>
   It's also sometimes easy to forget how uncomfortable Ramirez is
with his English language skills. He's an introverted person who
seems to speak freely only in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manny is a special talent,'' said Cleveland Manager Mike
Hargrove. ``Early in his career a lot was made about his lack of
concentration. But we're beyond that. I don't know why anyone
should be surprised by anything Manny does with the bat. And he's
also worked hard to make himself into one of the better defensive
right fielders in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering his numbers seem to only be improving and his peak
seasons should arrive in the next six years or so, exactly where
Ramirez will wind up is mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not just incredible, he's amazing,'' said former star
reliever Dennis Eckersley. ``He can become a monster in this game
if he keeps it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hall of Famer Frank Robinson, ``He's just starting to
scratch the surface and come into his own. Who knows how good he
can become? He needs to continue what he's started over time.
That's what really separates the good ones from the great ones.''
</P>
<P>
   On the best hitting club in the majors, Ramirez stands out as
its biggest bopper. What remains unknown is where Ramirez fits in
among the Indians' best players.
</P>
<P>
   There are strong arguments, even within the Indians' clubhouse,
as to who Cleveland's MVP is in 1999. Some believe Kenny Lofton or
Alomar might be more vital to Cleveland's offensive dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always appreciated Manny's game and now that I see him
every day, I appreciate it more,'' Alomar said. ``He's an
unbelievable hitter and a real smart hitter. Maybe it doesn't come
across because he's a quiet guy. He's definitely the MVP of our
team and the entire league.''
</P>
<P>
   To back up that claim, consider that Ramirez missed nine games
in the first half because of either injury or suspension. The
Indians were 3-6 and averaged 4.6 runs per game in those games.
With Ramirez they are 53-25 and averaged 6.9 runs per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those numbers speak for themselves,'' said Baltimore pitcher
Mike Mussina. ``Mistake pitches to him mean nothing. He can hit
anything anywhere. You don't drive in that many runs waiting for
just center-cut fastballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1994, Ramirez came close to winding up with the Oakland
Athletics. The Indians and A's had agreed to a deal that would have
sent Ramirez to the A's in exchange for Eckersley. It was the A's
who vetoed the deal at the last minute, a prominent major league
source said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about that deal,'' Ramirez said. ``Who knows what
would have happened to me if I'd ended up in Oakland. Thankfully,
it didn't happen. To me, Cleveland is the best city to be playing
baseball in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, who often shuns reporters, was the only American League
All-Star not to appear at the mandatory mass interview session
Monday. None of which came as a great surprise to any of those who
know the right fielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saying he won't show,'' said Diamondbacks third baseman
Matt Williams, who played with Ramirez in 1997. ``He'll probably
show up (today), go 3 for 4 and win the MVP award and not even know
what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, who missed his flight from Cleveland to Boston Sunday
night and then missed a few more Monday morning before finally
showing up, did make it to the afternoon workout.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Ramirez was making himself a thorn in the
side of Indians' management. Over a one-week stretch, Ramirez, who
turned down a seven-year, $56 million extension because he wanted
more, took batting practice while wearing spikes with messages on
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free me,'' ``Justice will be served,'' and ``Can't we all just
get along,'' were some of the messages. But it wasn't Ramirez who
wrote them. With Ramirez's blessing, a Cleveland clubhouse manager
was responsible. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 0258EDT &QL; 
