<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7767 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALL-STAR_BICKLEY-     07-13 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR_BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE NOT ALWAYS FOR BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The elevator was filled with kids clutching autograph
books, and as the door opened, they sprinted into the lobby, hoping
to fill a few more pages.
</P>
<P>
   In the back of the elevator, Ozzie Smith smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guess they didn't know who I am,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing like baseball in Boston, and no better way to
close the century than an All-Star Game at Fenway Park. If you look
closely, there's a striking juxtaposition at work, a contrast
between old and new, then and now.
</P>
<P>
   There is still some doubt whether baseball has truly entered a
renaissance period, but as you glance at the names assembled for
tonight's game, you need both hands and a couple of feet to count
potential Hall of Fame candidates.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder whether the new breed of dynamic athletes can save
the sport from all its peripheral problems. Or whether it has
thrown the game completely off kilter.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt, the hitters are way ahead of the curve,'' Yankees
pitcher David Cone said. ``I just hope they raise the mound. It's
the least invasive change they can make to help the pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, Ozzie Smith was an All-Star just because of
his glove and Cal Ripken Jr. was in a class with Robin Yount and
Alan Trammell. Ripken is still here, but the bar has been raised.
Tonight, he will share a dugout with Derek Jeter and Nomar
Garciaparra. The talent level at shortstop has changed so
dramatically that Alex Rodriguez didn't even make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution exists at all positions except pitchers, and if
you think otherwise, please explain Jeromy Burnitz and his 38 home
runs in 1998. A plateau that Hank Aaron passed only nine times.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came along, the amount of opposite-field home
runs was very few, the home runs to center field were very few and
the outside part of the plate was a safe place for pitchers to
go,'' Ripken said. ``That has all changed, and it's a matter of
bigger, stronger and faster. And I think it exists in all sports.''
</P>
<P>
   But has the change enhanced baseball? It is a touchy subject for
the suits that run the sport because offense means interest,
because last year's home run derby sparked the resurgence, and
really, who doesn't want to see Sammy Sosa bat in front of Mark
McGwire?
</P>
<P>
   Still, such tipping of the scales doesn't agree with everybody,
especially the purists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look up at the scoreboard, and all the time, there are
five-run innings, seven-run innings, (scores like) 13-4, 12-11,''
Yankees Manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Once, the All-Star Game was a diversion, a showcase for hitters.
Once, the home run hitting contest was a nice quirk. Now, both are
reflective of a pervasive mentality, a game in transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came into the game, there weren't any weight rooms in
most of the ballparks,'' Cone said. ``George Brett never lifted a
weight. It was really frowned upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's hitters have learned to lift weights and retain their
flexibility. The strike zone and the ballparks are smaller. And the
average American League ERA is 5.00.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a five ERA when I came in, you were back down in
the minor leagues,'' Cone said. ``Now, you're an average pitcher.
And if you're in the mid-fours, you're doing pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   A hitter's game, from statistics to mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you even come close to hitting anybody, and guys are
stepping from the dugout, guys are wanting to fight,'' Tampa
reliever Roberto Hernandez said. ``Things have changed a lot in the
past few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, you will see Fenway Park in all its glory. You will see
the Green Monster and a pitching mound once used by Cy Young. You
will be flooded with memories and escorted to the past.
</P>
<P>
   A past quickly buckling under to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Once, John Kruk was smoking a cigarette outside Veterans Stadium
in Philadelphia. He was approached by a woman appalled at his vice,
given his status of professional athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ma'am, I'm not an athlete,'' Kruk said. ``I'm a baseball
player.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, times have changed. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
