A7771 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     07-13 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE VIEW FROM DIMAGGIO DECK  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Weird town.
</P>
<P>
   Whattaya mean, what do I mean? Look around.
</P>
<P>
   We try to honor Joe DiMaggio, and his lawyer bullies us. Tells
us we can't do anything without the lawyer's permission. And
whatever we name after DiMag had better be huge, like SFO or the
Bay Bridge or Willie Brown's ego.
</P>
<P>
   Look, Mr. Lawyer, if we name the airport after a famous local
Italian American sports hero named Joe who launched flying objects,
it might not be DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   I say we pick the DiMaggio tribute we deem appropriate and dare
Mr. Lawyer to take legal action. If a judge sentences everyone in
San Francisco to a month in jail for misdemeanor mis-honoring of a
local hero, Terence Hallinan will have us all back on the street
and into a diversion program by noon.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, we can't place a monument to DiMaggio at the airport
because the airport is lost, like Atlantis. I tried to find it
Monday, and all I could see was a huge cloud of construction grit.
Maybe we should name SFO after Dusty Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Or, because it's such a massive construction project, name it
Carol Doda International.
</P>
<P>
   In defiance of Mr. Lawyer, Lou Bristol named his rooftop the Joe
DiMaggio Memorial Sun Deck, and from that perch Lou has noted a
fashion epidemic in Joe's old 'hood. In the wake of Saturday's USA
soccer win, the Brandi Chastain shirtless look, jog bra only, is
sweeping the Marina.
</P>
<P>
   THE CITY continues to march to its own drummer.
</P>
<P>
   Our most famous works of art, on my current list, are: a
rejected foot, a fiberglass doggie head now as protected as the
statue of David and an erased drawing that got defaced with a cat.
</P>
<P>
   The cat project reinforces this feeling: I don't understand art,
but I  &UR; really  &LR; don't understand artists.
</P>
<P>
   Circa 1953, artist Robert Rauschenberg asked artist Willem De
Kooning for a piece of De Koonig's art, to be erased. De Kooning
sent a drawing, which Rauschenberg erased, creating a smudged piece
of paper titled ``Erased De Kooning,'' which now hangs in SFMOMA,
inspiring blank stares.
</P>
<P>
   Many art fans were livid at Rauschenberg's erasing of a great
artist's art, but most of us worked through our grief and anger
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not local ``plop'' artist Richard List, who has plopped bicycles
and toilets in public spaces around the Bay. Last week, List and an
accomplice sneaked a cat doll into MOMA and Velcroed it to the wall
just above ``Erased De Kooning,'' then ran like hell.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for MOMA told me she was unaware of the prank.
Thus, SFMOMA has erased all memory of List's art work (``Defaced
Erased De Kooning''?), which means that the work is now a double
negative and twice as valuable.
</P>
<P>
   In other local bizarre artsy news: Del Close was co-founder here
(with Alan Marsten) of the Committee, legendary '60s improv group.
He later moved to Chicago, and he died last March. Close willed his
skull to Chicago's Goodman Theater, where it will play the role of
Yorick in productions of ``Hamlet.'' Or, says a friend of Close,
the skull will ``just lie around in some desert scene. He wasn't
fussy.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing Close didn't leave his skull to San Francisco. It
would be kicked around art committees and Board of Supervisors
debates until it gathered moss and lost face.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, who needs a skull? Tony Bennett left us his heart, and
Tony's lawyer isn't trying to tell us how to display it.
</P>
<P>
   AT LEAST we're hip. Antonio Lara saw a panhandler at Market and
Van Ness with a sign: ``WWW.SPARECHANGE.COM.''
</P>
<P>
   And this is one city that does not discriminate against blind
drivers. R. McLeod notices that the drive-up window at the
Serramonte Mall's Wells Fargo has instructions in braille.
</P>
<P>
   NO OPINION goes unchallenged here. Manuel Gutierrez of Southern
California contests my claim that San Francisco lags behind L.A. in
cutting-edge-obnoxious/ostentatious cell-phone use.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez recently landed at Montana-Baker-Doda-Doda Airport and
ducked into a rest room. In the next stall, a man on cell was
loudly berating his limo service for not picking him up.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gutierrez dropped in at a North Beach flower shop, where
the young clerk chatted on her cell in lieu of acknowledging
Manuel's presence or offering her assistance, except to take his
money.
</P>
<P>
   Then at Roma on Columbus, Manuel sat near a man who was
operating, simultaneously, the morning newspaper, a cup of coffee,
a lap-top computer and, of course, a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Eat your heart out, Vishnu, you four-handed underachiever.
</P>
<P>
   The Roma man was demonstrating the new standard for
coordination, which in simpler times was defined as the ability to
walk and chew gum at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez quickly fled back to the bosom of normalcy in Los
Angeles. (Legal disclaimer follows.) Which is not to imply that
bosoms in L.A. are normal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 0312EDT &QL; 
