<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 03:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7774 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYNAGOGUE-BURNINGS-SF     07-13 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYNAGOGUE-BURNINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WHITE SUPREMACIST SUSPECT FOLLOWED PATH TO EXTREMISM  &HT;     By JAXON VAN DERBEKEN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For years, Benjamin Matthew Williams drifted,
trying to find his place in the world.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Navy and was stationed in Washington, then left a
fiancee and their young daughter to go to Idaho, where he attended
college and soon joined what he later called a religious cult.
</P>
<P>
   He left the cult devastated, only to develop a fascination with
the white supremacy movement, eventually going so far as to mail
bizarre, hate-filled reading materials to friends for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Williams and his younger brother, James, are being held
in Shasta County Jail, suspected of slaying a gay couple near
Redding, Calif., and torching three synagogues in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The Shasta County Sheriff's Department is expected to file a
homicide case against the brothers with the district attorney's
office as early as Wednesday, at which time prosecutors will decide
whether they have enough evidence to prosecute the pair on two
counts of murder.
</P>
<P>
   As a task force of federal and local authorities continues to
investigate the Sacramento arson fires, friends and former
acquaintances described the older Williams brother's gradual
descent from religious seeker to right-wing zealot under
investigation in hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he felt lost, really. We all felt lost,'' said former
fellow cult member Michael Godbold.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 31, was deeply religious, strictly adhered to a
vegetarian diet and regularly attempted to purify his body and
soul, Godbold said. Godbold described him as both charismatic and
gullible and said he dominated his younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   Godbold said he helped recruit the older Williams into the
Living Faith Fellowship in Moscow, Idaho, where Williams studied
engineering and biology at the University of Idaho from 1993 to
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The fellowship was described as a cult by former members, who
said that the leader, Dr. Karl Barden, preached a fundamentalist
Christian gospel. The group had as many as 500 members who attended
twice-weekly services and gave 231/3 percent of their income,
Godbold said.
</P>
<P>
   Barden also allegedly kept files of embarrassing facts on
members, cut them off from family members and forced them to endure
arranged marriages.
</P>
<P>
   It was as part of a recruiting questionnaire, which Godbold
claimed was used against members who later broke with the group,
that Williams revealed that he had briefly served in the Navy and
had a daughter who lived in another state.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams heard allegations that the leader of the sect was
keeping files on members of the group, he quit almost overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Barden and other members of the group did not return calls
seeking comment but have insisted in earlier published accounts
that their group demands devotion from its members.
</P>
<P>
   In an article published in a local newspaper a month after he
left the group, Williams described how he was taken in: ``You are
young, your mind isn't fully formed, you are a long ways from
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Godbold, who left the group before Williams, helped his friend
get out. Afterward, Williams was devastated, Godbold said. He cried
for hours and talked about bombing the church and assassinating
Barden.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was completely lost,'' said Jeff Monroe, another friend
from Pullman, Wash., just across the state line from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Friends tried to soothe Williams, but it was not long before
Williams found the King James Only movement on the Internet,
Godbold recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The King James Only movement is an independent Baptist church
that shares fundamentalist Christian values and believes that the
King James Bible is the definitive version.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a true believer,'' said Monroe. ``Whatever he (Williams)
is involved in, he is involved in absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Monroe said that in the summer of 1995, not long after leaving
the fellowship, Williams also threw himself into a one-man tax
crusade, explaining how people could avoid paying taxes based on
loopholes in the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   From taxes came politics during what Monroe called a ``six-month
developmental period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He just became very insistent that we all join his little tax
revolution,'' Monroe said. ``He became extremely intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax thing was a stepping stone to the very
ultra-conservative. ... He was so far out there. He became very
interested in militia-type information.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Williams was struggling financially, Monroe
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just had a long, long series of bad luck,'' he said. ``It
got so bad, Matthew just started selling off some of his stuff. He
sold his computer, stereo, near everything he had. The tax thing
became all-consuming.''
</P>
<P>
   For a brief period, James Williams visited his older brother,
apparently wanting to get away from their parents. But James
Williams soon confided to Monroe that he wanted to get away from
his domineering brother, and he returned to California.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Benjamin Williams left Idaho, telling Godbold that he
wanted a better climate to grow his edible plants, with which he
had become fascinated. Godbold figured he was just homesick.
</P>
<P>
   Not long before he left, there were signs that Williams'
fascination with the white supremacy movement had become far more
serious, Godbold said. Williams would go on ``verbal fishing''
expeditions, making negative references about interracial couples.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe said Williams initially encountered the racist philosophy
while searching the Internet for health miracles ranging from
fungus teas to eye exercises that were supposed to improve vision.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Williams called Godbold to ask about a mutual
friend. When Godbold told Williams the friend was gay, Williams
became extremely upset.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Christmas package full of hate literature that
Williams sent from his home address in Palo Cedro, Calif., outside
Redding, to mutual friends. His friends showed Godbold the letter,
which began with a ``Merry Christmas'' greeting, then explained
that he was including reading materials about the ``TRUTH.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspected that was where Matthew was heading, to be honest
with you,'' said Monroe. ``I hoped I was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Monroe said he feared Williams was heading on an apparently
self-destructive, racist mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, there was no authority I could call _ he hadn't
done anything,'' Monroe said. ``But,'' he said, ``I figured the
next time I'd hear about Matthew, he'd end up in the media having
killed somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we heard, it was like, `Oh my God, I hoped that would
never happen.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writers Kevin Fagan and Stacy Finz contributed
to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
