 ART ADV.: Photos with ALLST-GRIFFEY, ALLST-RYAN-COL and ALLST-DREAM
are being transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For IMMEDIATE Release   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following 1999 All-Star Game
feature stories Tuesday for use by NYTimes News Service clients.
All stories will bear the BOS designator and move under the Sports
(s) category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions, contact the NYTimes News Service desk at The
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-DREAM (Boston) _ Pedro Martinez' first pitch, to Barry
Larkin of the Cincinnati Reds, will be thrown to the backdrop of
thousands of flashbulbs popping. By Gordon Edes. 1245 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-GLUTS (Boston) _ Nomar? Derek? ARod? Omar? No easy
choices exist at AL shortstop, either for fans or a poor manager
trying to fill out his team. By Bob Ryan. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-MARTINEZ (Boston) _ Connect all the dots, and you have
Pedro Martinez by the numbers. His pitch for history is there for
all to see. By Gordon Edes. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-GRIFFEY (Seattle) _ Ken Griffey Jr. has emerged as not
only the top vote getter for the 70th All-Star Game, but also as
pro sports' most marketable athlete. By Larry Whiteside. 900 words.
PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-SOSA (Boston) _ Being the Nation League's top vote
getter humbled slugger Sammy Sosa, because, as he said, ``For me
it's the first time.'' By Michael Vega. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-RYAN-COL (Boston) _ The All-Star player quickly learns
that it is the totality of the entire experience that really
matters. By Bob Ryan. 1125 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-PALMIERO (Boston) _ A perennial member of the All-Star
snub club has been Texas Rangers first baseman Rafael Palmeiro. By
Larry Whiteside. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-SCHILLING (Boston) _ It's taken a long time for Curt
Schilling to gain a measure of revenge against the Red Sox. Now he
has a chance to toss the first stone and make it count. By Michael
Smith. 615 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-TV-SPORTS-COL (Boston) _ Broadcaster Kurt Gowdy
remembers how difficult it was to call the sixteen All-Star games
he worked before retiring. By Howard Manly. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-FENWAY (Boston) _ In other cities, baseball calls on
the lure of the amusement park to draw fans. But Boston is Boston
and here baseball is enough. By Michael Madden. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-GWYNN (Boston) _ Tony Gwynn, unable to play because of
an injury, came anyway, serving as an interpreter for the young
players. By Steve Fainaru. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
