<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7920 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLST-GLUTS-BOS &LR;      07-13 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLST-GLUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ROOM FOR ALL THESE STARS TO ROAM AT ONCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Nomar? Derek? ARod? Omar? No easy choices exist at
shortstop in the American League, either for fans voting or a poor
manager trying to fill out his All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Messrs. Garciaparra, Jeter, Rodriguez, and Vizquel are all great
players, and the first three appear to be heading to Cooperstown in
20 years (sorry, Omar, but you started your march a bit late). They
are all star shortstops, but four into three doesn't go. But before
any of them start wallowing in self-pity, they should hear about
Hank Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1935. When the AL assembled its team for the third
All-Star Game, Greenberg, the Tigers' first baseman, was leading
the league in home runs, RBIs, hits, and doubles. He was second in
runs scored. His RBI total was 103.
</P>
<P>
   So where was Hank Greenberg during the All-Star Game? Home. Lou
Gehrig was the starting first baseman. Jimmie Foxx, the third base
starter, would serve as a potential backup at first.
</P>
<P>
   There was a surprising lack of outcry, although the Associated
Press did observe that Greenberg was ``strangely missing from the
All-Star ranks at a time when a couple of his long-range blows
would be most welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The AL really did not need him. Gehrig was 0 for 3 with a run
scored. Foxx had a three-run homer. The AL won, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Now move up 20 years. As good as our aforementioned shortstops
might be, they don't represent the best glut of talent at any one
position. Consider what took place in the National League from 1954
through 1971, when true giants (including one Giant) roamed the
outfield for the Senior Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Mays, Hank Aaron, Roberto Clemente, and Frank Robinson
all either solidified themselves as major leaguers or entered the
league in a three-year period from 1954 through 1956. These men
would combine for 12,997 hits, 2,241 home runs, 7,317 RBIs, and
7,481 runs scored over their careers, each breezing into the Hall
of Fame. But when the All-Star Games came, someone had to sit.
Occasionally, someone even had to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's competition.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was the first of the four to start an All-Star Game. He
was the starting left fielder as a rookie in 1956. Mays couldn't
beat out Cincinnati center fielder Gus Bell. Aaron and Clemente had
to yield to Stan Musial in right.
</P>
<P>
   Mays received the first of his 18 All-Star starts (covering 15
seasons) in 1957. Aaron got his first start the same year. Clemente
didn't start until 1961 because, well, because he was a right
fielder and so was Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years there was a great deal of juggling. Clemente
replaced Aaron in a game. Aaron replaced Clemente. Robinson
replaced Clemente. Aaron replaced Mays. Clemente replaced Mays.
Robinson bounced around, playing left, right, and even first base,
entering the second game in 1959 as a replacement for Musial at
first.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1961, the right field starting spot became a
battleground. It went like this: 1961 _ Clemente. 1962 _ Clemente.
1963 _ Aaron. 1964 _ Clemente. 1965 _ Aaron. 1966 _ Clemente. 1967
_ Clemente. 1968 _ Aaron. That was the start of a major Aaron run
that reduced an exasperated Clemente to a substitute through 1971,
his final season.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a starter in 1957, became the odd man out. He didn't
start another All-Star Game until 1966, by then an American
Leaguer, having been traded to Baltimore in one of the worst front
office blunders in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   One fact emerges from all this: Willie Mays was The Man of his
time. Aaron played both right and center as an All-Star, as did
Clemente. Once ensconced (he played a little right field in 1956),
Mays played one position and one position only for the next 16
years as an All-Star. He owned center field.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar, Derek, and ARod are very good. But take another look at
those Aaron-Clemente-Mays-Robinson numbers. These young lads have
much to accomplish before they become fully anointed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
