<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLST-SCHILLNG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIES' ACE SCHILLING HOPES HE CAN CASH IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It's taken a long time for Curt Schilling to gain a
measure of revenge against the Red Sox. Now he has a chance to toss
the first stone and make it count.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Schilling, the ace of the Philadelphia Phillies,
will lead the charge by the National League against the American
League in the 70th midsummer classic at Fenway Park. Schilling was
the choice over Arizona's Randy Johnson, the NL strikeout leader
(211), and it would make the former Red Sox farmhand happy to pitch
two or three scoreless innings against Boston's Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited, he said Monday. ``I'm ecstatic. I'm nervous as
hell. There is only one All-Star Game a year. . . . There is only
one major league game on earth. And I'm starting for one side. It's
pretty awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling doesn't talk about revenge against the Red Sox. On the
contrary, he looks back to the 1988 trade that sent him and Brady
Anderson to Baltimore for Mike Boddicker as one of the turning
points in his career. Success did not come overnight. But after a
one-year stint in Houston (1991), he has hit his stride in
Philadelphia, where he has become one of baseball's most powerful
and durable pitchers. And he has the numbers to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   His 13-4 record and a 3.13 earned run average got him the
starting nod over Johnson. But then it's hard to pass over a power
pitcher who has recorded back-to-back 300 strikeout seasons for a
team that never seemed to get him enough runs. He was 15-14 last
year with 15 complete games. This year he has seven complete games
and is having a great time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The park hasn't been too good to me the last year or two,''
said Schilling. ``But I don't dwell on the Red Sox. I'm going to
try to have as much fun as I possibly can. I thanked Bruce Bochy,
our manager, for the selection and the start. He did his
homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling said he would not have felt slighted if Johnson had
been chosen ahead of him. He respects the Big Unit and what he has
accomplished. The admiration is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``He usually goes out and finishes what he starts,'' says
Johnson. ``That makes him one of a dying breed of power pitchers.
Over a period of time I don't have as many complete games as him.
My teammates are out there for nine innings, why shouldn't I?''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling will be appearing in his third All-Star Game and the
first without the specter of a trade hovering. As far as he knows,
he is off the market and a Phillie for two more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mute point,'' he said. ``I'm not going anywhere. I
think (general manager) Eddie Wade has made that pretty clear to me
and a lot of people. I'm a Phillie. I think we've got a legitimate
shot to contend for a postseason spot. The key right now is we're
playing better when I pitch. We score runs and have played
consistenty solid defense the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling has mixed emotions facing Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a totally respectful way I'm looking forward to facing all
of them,'' he said. ``But I really don't want to face any of them,
especially not in the same game. I'm going to take the generic
approach. Throw a lot of fastballs and try to get outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro is somebody I've always watched with admiration. He is
the rare guy who is not only a power pitcher but he also has a
strikeout changeup. Watching him this year is like being a Triple A
player watching the major leagues. It's been enjoyable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
