<HEADER>
A7939 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN14-COX     07-13 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's nothing like a fair-weather Web friend
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ My good friend Gail _ the one who moved to
the Oregon coast a few years back with little more than a basket of
books and a featherbed _ has had a bit of bad luck. Seems she lost
her most recent beau to an Internet seductress.
</P>
<P>
   Gail has been single for many years, ever since her husband
discovered his secretary was younger and thinner than his wife. The
experience left her a little touchy where men are concerned. In
fact, she has worked out her own philosophy in a terse six words:
They're ruled by their anxieties. Sometimes, if she's feeling
particularly modern, she'll substitute an expletive for
``anxieties.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Gail a handsome woman of 56, a retired judge and lawyer,
blessed with intellect and charm ... (SET ITAL)and(END ITAL) ... a
little sports car, seldom dates. The men who do ask her out, she
explains, are either married or senile. Frequently, both.
</P>
<P>
   But a few weeks ago, a likely candidate (we'll call him Albert
because that's his name and we're not trying to protect him from
anything) walked into the art gallery where she works weekends, and
struck up a conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Albert, 73, had been recently widowed and wanted to talk. It was
a slow afternoon and Gail is an expert listener. Two hours later,
she'd agreed to meet him for dinner at a nearby fish house.
``Meet'' is the key word here because that's what cautious single
ladies do on a first date, which assures them of two things:
transportation, and no awkward moments at the front door.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Gail and Albert had a marvelous time and decided to
spend the next day together visiting galleries and walking the
beach. Albert talked. Gail listened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she confided that evening in one of our marathon phone
calls that keeps AT&AMP;T stockholders fat, ``I've made the big move.
I've invited him to dinner.'' Albert had proved to be good company
as well as an honorable man. ``He's polite, intelligent, and
realizes it's too soon to become seriously involved, so we're just
friends,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gail and I talked daily. She filled me in on Albert's remarkable
attributes. ``He doesn't smoke, he'll drink a glass of wine with
dinner, and he enjoys reading as much as I do,'' which is no mean
task since Gail digests six to eight books a week. She says it's
what she does instead of housework.
</P>
<P>
   Albert and Gail drove up and down the Oregon coast searching out
used bookshops. On rainy afternoons, they sat together in her
oversized easy chair in front of the big window looking onto the
bay, counting eagles and sharing confidences. ``His dreams for the
future are the same as mine. I think I may have found the right
one. We're giving it a lot of time, just to be sure,'' she told me.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days later, she called to share some news. ``You
know how I hate computers?'' I knew. She refuses to have one in the
house, along with television. ``Well, Albert bought one today and
he's at home right now setting it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The next evening, she said Albert wasn't there because he had
been on the phone with IBM for four hours. ``Can you believe he's
spent the entire afternoon trying to figure out where to plug in
the toaster.'' I mentioned that in my modest experience with
computers, I'd never run across one that made toast. She guessed
she'd heard him wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Albert was still a no-show. ``He has learned
how to get on the Internet and spends all of his time surfing. He
said I could come over if I'd bring sandwiches. I took him pastrami
with sprouts, but he didn't have time to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, all of Albert's conversation was in print. He'd discovered
chat rooms. Gail decided to wait it out, until the novelty wore
off. She went back to her books.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days later, Gail called Albert to be sure he hadn't
slumped over his keyboard from exhaustion. He was alive, well, and
sincerely apologetic. ``I can't see you any more,'' he said,
``because I'm getting married to a lady I met on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail was incredulous. ``She's a 71-year-old woman he picked up
in a chat room on Wednesday night. Thursday she drove 400 miles to
his house, and they're getting married on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's hear it for progress.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
