r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN14-COX     07-13 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Questions aside, does Bush's money make election irrelevant?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The best _ most ominous? _ indicator of what's
happening in the race for the White House is the sudden interest in
a stretch of Texas dirt along Prairie Chapel Road.
</P>
<P>
   Reports say Gov. George W. Bush is interested in that property
seven miles from Crawford, Texas. With those reports the
population-631 berg became Insta-Cam City. And of course there was
insta-talk about land speculation. Where to house the Secret
Service agents for the next president of the United States? Who
will sell them their Big Gulps in a Texas August?
</P>
<P>
   Readers who missed the news that Bush had already won the
presidency can be excused for being disoriented. This time, rather
than use the traditional means of electing a president, we've gone
to the auction-barn method. And bids apparently have closed. Sold,
to G.W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever raised this much money this early _ $36 million
in the first half of 1999. Bush's figure doubles the $18 million
raised by Al Gore and leaves the entirety of the GOP field looking
like fleas on Bush's socks.
</P>
<P>
   Though in fact it is way too early to hand him the GOP
nomination, the war chest alone wins him the equivalent of a
half-dozen primaries simply by raising to nose-bleed heights the
implausibility of several GOP candidacies.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is going to take some hits in the primaries from whoever
manages to survive the money-raising season. Billionaire Steven
Forbes, for one, is guaranteed survival, and is going to take away
much of his right flank. Sen. John McCain and Elizabeth Dole are
going to contend for moderates. And in cranky New Hampshire,
Patrick Buchanan can still make George's day miserable, as he did
once for George's father.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's money edge _ more than an edge, this is the
continental shelf _ is already winnowing the GOP field. Hard-right
candidate Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire has announced he's
bolting the party to run as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   These chain reactions are happening, this train of invincibility
chugging, though most Americans have no clue about this man.
</P>
<P>
   They shouldn't feel left out. The Washington Post's David
Broder, one of the nation's most astute political observers, admits
not having a clue either.
</P>
<P>
   ``His five-year record in office largely is unexamined,'' Broder
writes. ``His views on most issues are unknown. And yet, on the
basis of public opinion polls and even more his bank account, the
New York Times said his third week as an announced candidate _
devoted largely to fund raising _ 'has the feel of covering a
general election nominee.'''
</P>
<P>
   Broder wonders about the ``lack of public indignation'' that a
distinguished GOP field would be rendered inconsequential by a
question-mark mysterian and his money.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls? How could anyone outside of Texas have any
opinion about George Bush? Granted, the name sounds very familiar.
Didn't he used to be president?
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance watchdog Common Cause attributes Bush's
remarkable success to a group of money-raisers tagged the Pioneers
_ ``insider money men who each have committed to raising $100,000
for the campaign . . . the new class of political power brokers
whose status and access are determined by the big money they
bring.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts observe that Bush is in a position to turn down federal
matching funds. This sounds altruistic. Rather, it is conniving. It
would mean Bush wouldn't be subject to many post-Watergate campaign
spending limits which come with public financing. Reportedly, Gore
is considering the same. Yahoo. No holds barred _ the equivalent of
campaign-finance nuclear war. It will be televised.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
