<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONEYTALK: Personal finance books to read ... and avoid
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Readers often ask what books would help them get smart about
investing in general and the stock market in particular.
</P>
<P>
   That's no surprise. A lot more people have investments these
days because they have 401(k) retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   Others have gotten interested because they keep hearing about
the booming stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers know this hunger exists. That's why there are so many
investment advice books in the stores and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those books are very good.
</P>
<P>
   But some are them are awful, as Charles A. Jaffe notes below.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for investment books at a public library, go
for the ones numbered 332. Many will be grouped in the subsection
332.6.
</P>
<P>
   If you're wading through the offerings at a bookstore, here's a
rule of thumb: Avoid any book that promises to make you rich in the
next 30 days or that claims to have a secret investment strategy.
You can't do the first, and nobody knows the second.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some good places to start:
</P>
<P>
   For novices
</P>
<P>
   _ ``If You're Clueless About the Stock Market and Want to Know
More,'' by Seth Godin. Makes investing easy to understand, even on
some of the more-complicated topics. Includes a clear explanation
of how to read corporate financial reports, discussions of common
investment strategies and an extensive list of further resources.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Green Magazine Guide to Personal Finance: A No B.S. Book
for Your Twenties and Thirties,'' by Ken Kurson. $12.95. Strong on
explaining the basics in an informal way; oriented toward young
people.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Investing for the Financially Challenged,'' by Walter
Updegrave of Money magazine. A basic personal finance book for
anyone who might otherwise have bought a Dummies or Idiot's book _
a nomination from Charles A. Jaffe.
</P>
<P>
   If you're past square one
</P>
<P>
   _ ``One Up on Wall Street'' and ``Beating the Street,'' by Peter
Lynch. Very popular books by the retired manager of the huge
Magellan Fund. He explains how everyday experiences can help
beginners make investment choices.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Zebra Among the Lions,'' by Ralph Wanger. The witty and
widely respected chief of the Acorn mutual funds describes his
``growth at a reasonable price'' investing style.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Stocks for the Long Run,'' by Jeremy Siegel. Practical
advice on how the market works and how to buy stocks.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Intelligent Investor,'' by Benjamin Graham. One of the
basic books on analyzing stocks. Warren Buffett called it ``by far
the best book on investing ever written.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Making the Most of Your Money,'' by Jane Bryant Quinn;
``Marshall Loeb's Lifetime Financial Strategies,'' by Marshall
Loeb; or ``The Wall Street Journal Lifetime Guide to Money,''
edited by C. Frederic Wiegold. Big-picture books that deal with
investments and many other personal finance topics.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of Crowds,''
by Charles Mackay. Read this if you need an inoculation against
fads.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The New Commonsense Guide to Mutual Funds,'' by Mary
Rowland. Explanations of the basics, brief but penetrating essays
on the ``do's and don'ts'' and a first-rate test for deciding how
much risk you can bear.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``But Which Mutual Fund? How to Pick the Right Ones to Achieve
Your Financial Dream,'' by Steven T. Goldberg. Describes investment
strategies and pitfalls to watch out for.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Handbook for No-Load Fund Investors,'' by Sheldon
Jacobs. Much commentary and down-to-earth advice.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Bogle on Mutual Funds,'' by John C. Bogle. The founder of
the Vanguard Index 500 fund explains how to build a successful
portfolio using mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
