r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLATE-CHANGES14-COX     07-13 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLATE-CHANGES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slate.com aims to reach into readers' palms
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Another new day has dawned at Slate.com, the online
journal of politics and opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Slate has always been notorious for keeping its light under a
bushel and in the shadow of that other popular online magazine,
Salon. But now it seems that Slate may have finally found a
combination of editorial, commerce and alternative revenue streams
to push the Microsoft-owned site into mainstream acceptance after
three years of failed attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, in the Web site's daily e-mail ``morning delivery,''
there was a note from famed editor Michael Kinsley talking up
Slate's latest efforts aimed at reaching a broader audience and
tapping into current Web trends.
</P>
<P>
   The new and improved Slate _ it seems like Slate is always
reinventing itself as new and improved _ has taken a huge leap into
the next century with versions now available for PalmPilot and
Windows CE users.
</P>
<P>
   Slate's attempt to score with the hand-held crowd is a growing
strategy being adopted by CNN, the Weather Channel and a host of
other news-and-information Web sites that want to reach out to the
Web surfer who doesn't always surf from the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Slate Publisher Scott Moore says the extension of Slate from the
PC to hand-held devices is an ideal move from both an industry and
product perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``These devices are proliferating right now, and for us, it's a
natural way to extend our brand because it's a very low-cost
distribution channel,'' he says. ``It's also exposure to an
attractive audience that really uses these products. We view part
of our mission as being a laboratory for these newly developing
products. This type of thing works for Slate because our audience
tends to be very sophisticated and a lot of readers are `early
adopters' and the people who are using these devices.''
</P>
<P>
   Slate is also taking a leap into the world of downloadable
digital audio files via a deal with Audible.com. Slate will provide
all of its content to Audible.com for users who want to listen to
Slate, as Kinsley put it, ``on the treadmill or in the car.''
Actors will be reading the content, and users will be able to
purchase a digital player to download the files. The product is
available from Audible.com for about $80.
</P>
<P>
   These new developments put Slate on the bleeding edge of
Internet technology, and Moore thinks the timing is perfect as
Slate begins its coverage of the 2000 presidential campaign. While
many like to compare Slate with Salon, Moore says there are some
very distinguishable differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I would say Salon is a direct competitor,''
he says. ``Editorially, we are slightly different. We have more
coverage of politics and current events.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead toward Campaign 2000, Moore says Slate is poised
on the front lines of what could be a watershed year for politics
and the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think back to the Kennedy-Nixon debates,'' he says. ``Kennedy
was the first politician to realize how to use television. Nobody
has started spending advertising dollars online. We've talked to
all the campaigns, and we know they are all thinking hard about how
to use the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore says Slate has a long way to go before it reaches the
profitability it's struggling so hard to achieve, but taking away
the subscription barrier, adding the shopping resources of the
Microsoft Network to the site and being promoted on most of the MSN
sites have resulted in a big boost for advertisers and readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we are on the path to profitability and we do take a
long-term view of success,'' says Moore. ``We've only been at this
for three years. Most magazines take about five or six years to
become profitable. But Kinsley always says Slate will really have
made it when you can take it into the bathroom and read it.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
