r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GUILLAUME14-COX     07-13 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GUILLAUME14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stroke won't stop actor's return to `Sports Night'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Robert Guillaume, Emmy-winning star of TV's ``Benson''
and ``Soap'' and currently co-star of ``Sports Night,'' walks
slowly and gingerly, leaning on a cane. The effects of the stroke
he suffered in January are obvious.
</P>
<P>
   But then he sits down, flashes a wide smile and starts to talk,
and it's clear he hasn't been slowed at all in the ways that
matter. Guillaume, 71, was in Atlanta last week to receive a Legacy
Award for show business achievement from Jomandi Productions.
Sitting in the lobby of the Four Seasons Hotel, he talked about his
stroke and his future as irascible boss Isaac Jaffe on ``Sports
Night'' (9:30 Tuesday's on ABC), which starts shooting season two
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Normally when people say ``How are you?'' they don't really
want to know. But in your case people do want to know: How are you?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm recovering. I'm doing my speech therapy, physical
therapy, occupational therapy (relearning skills such as bathing
and brushing his teeth). I've been doing that since January. It's
like one step at a time. Good today, weak tomorrow, stronger the
next day. My wife (Donna) is my biggest booster. She won't be
satisfied until I'm running alongside the car, pushing a
wheelbarrow.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The original news reports called it a mild stroke. Did it
feel mild to you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Of course not. It sort of makes life a random universe. Your
foot may act right or not act right. It ends your life as you knew
it. For me, it was like mild depression, constantly thinking if you
want to do something: How much time is it going to take, and is it
worth it?
</P>
<P>
   It could be very depressing. When you're older there's a certain
vanity involved, so that you don't want to be seen stumbling about,
hobbling about. But all my limbs work to a more or less degree. And
I didn't lose my speech and I didn't lose any cognitive powers _
whatever I had before. (He laughs). In that sense, it was a mild
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were you concerned Isaac might not return to ``Sports
Night''?
</P>
<P>
   A: There was always that concern that I wouldn't come back
sufficiently to warrant being written back in again. (Executive
producer) Aaron (Sorkin) came to see me in the hospital, and I
think he was relieved. We talked about the logistics of getting
around the set, whether I'd have to use a wheelchair. But it was
agreed I could come back, and they'd write it into the character.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you talked about how Isaac will be in season two?
</P>
<P>
   A: I suspect it will have something to do with the brass
upstairs and how they feel about whether Isaac can perform his job:
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't think you can cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes you think I can't cut it? I'm doing exactly the
same thing I was before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't like the way you look.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be some sort of ongoing battle like that. It could be a
new chapter, one we haven't seen before in sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
