<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7952 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOL-BANDANA14-COX     07-13 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOL-BANDANA14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Cool' bandanna helps take edge off heat
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Determined to mow the grass and work in the
garden this week? Here's another product designed to help you play
it cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to say you tie one on and chill out,'' says Teresa
Doenges of Lima Medical Supplies, who sells a scarf called the
Miracool Bandanna.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been carrying these for the past four years and sell a
lot on our retail floor and also to our industrial accounts,'' she
explains. ``I sell thousands each year to factories that aren't
air-conditioned. It's a safety issue when you're working in a
factory and you want to make sure people are alert.''
</P>
<P>
   The special scarf is filled with polymer crystals that absorb
water. Soak it in cool water for a half-hour and watch it plump up
slowly. It isn't necessary to freeze the scarf. Then just drape it
around your neck. The scarf stays cool for a full day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works by evaporation, just like when you come out of a pool
or the shower,'' explains Laura Vermeire, executive vice president
of marketing for OccuNomix, the New York company that manufactures
the product. ``Evaporation creates a cooling effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Her company also uses the cooling crystals to make headbands,
visors, baseball caps and hard-hat inserts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have them for dogs and horses, too,'' Vermeire adds.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Crisp, a safety engineer at DTR Industries, says she buys
the scarves ``100 at a time'' for employees who then purchase them
at cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plant isn't air-conditioned, and we do a lot of curing
processes, which are very hot,'' she explains. ``When someone is
suffering from heat stress, you want to cool off the back of their
neck. Employees put the scarves around their necks, and it helps
them to keep cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The scarves, which retail for about $4.99, come in more than 40
colors and patterns ranging from American flag prints to Balinese
batiks. They can be rinsed and reused.
</P>
<P>
   Available at:
</P>
<P>
   THE LIMA MEDICAL SUPPLY STORE: (419) 228-2455.
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRIAL SAFETY CO.: (419) 227-6030.
</P>
<P>
   CROUCH FIRE &AMP; SAFETY (937) 223-8801
</P>
<P>
   BILL'S SUPPLY CO. (937) 228-3201.
</P>
<P>
   OCCUNOMIX: (800) 466-0071.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
