r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MCCOY-COLUMN14-CO     07-13 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCCOY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let the Indians win something first
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The assignment is difficult _ the old compare
apples to oranges cliche, except in this case it is comparing
giants, like watermelons to cantaloupes.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Are the 1999 Cleveland Indians comparable to the 1976
Cincinnati Reds, The Big Red Machine?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Gulp.
</P>
<P>
   It is an assignment designed to make people angry, but also to
get people talking and, no, the results won't be biased. Yes, the
writer covered the 1976 Reds, saw nearly every game, covered the
sweep of the Philadelphia Phillies in the National League
championship series and covered the sweep of the New York Yankees
in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the writer grew up in the shadow of old
Cleveland Municipal Stadium, the dark and dank Mistake on the Lake,
and rooted shamelessly for the Tribe through the best of times,
through the worst of times . . . and the worst of times far
overshadowed the best of times.
</P>
<P>
   So, on with The Show:
</P>
<P>
   CATCHER: Johnny Bench or Sandy Alomar? As Reds manager Sparky
Anderson said, when asked if Yankee catcher Thurman Munson was as
good as Bench: ``Don't ever embarrass any catcher by comparing him
to Johnny Bench.'' Alomar is good, very good, but Bench may not
have invented the position, but he personifies it.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER, Bench.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST BASE : Tony Perez or Jim Thome? Amazingly, both Perez and
Thome were converted from third base to first base. This time we
spin back in time to Reds manager Dave Bristol, who had Perez in
the early stages of The Big Dog's career. ``If there is a way to
win a baseball game, Tony Perez will find a way to win it,''
Bristol said. Thome is very good, a clutch hitter, but Perez is
acknowledged as one of the best clutch hitters ever.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER, Perez.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND BASE: Joe Morgan or Roberto Alomar? Alomar may be the
final piece the Tribe needed to push its way over the top, just
like Morgan was the final piece added to the Big Red Machine in a
dynamic trade with Houston. Morgan won back-to-back MVPs and Alomar
has won . . . well, none. Little Joe was a big, big man.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER, Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   SHORTSTOP: Dave Concepcion or Omar Vizquel? Both Concepcion and
Vizquel couldn't hit a bull in the butt with a bass fiddle early in
their careers, but Concepcion became a solid hitter later in his
career, just as Vizquel is. Concepcion had few peers in his day
while Vizquel plays in the shadow of offensive-minded shortstops
like Derek Jeter, Nomar Garciaparra and Alex Rodriguez. Vizquel,
though, continues to make plays that can't be made by flesh and
blood.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER, Vizquel.
</P>
<P>
   THIRD BASE: Pete Rose or Travis Fryman? The temptation is to
say, ``Next category, please. No discussion needed.'' Fryman is a
solid player. Rose was Mr. Baseball throughout his playing days.
Throw aside his personal off-the-field problems that landed him on
the outside looking in on the baseball scene, Rose was the ignition
switch on the Big Red Machine and for every team on which he
played.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER, Rose.
</P>
<P>
   LEFT FIELD: George Foster or David Justice (or whomever)? Foster
was the most underrated and least talked about player of his era.
For seven years, he averaged 32 home runs and 107 RBIs with his
Black Beauty Bat (few players used black bats then) and in a time
when home runs weren't cheaper by the dozen. Justice does as much
DHing as he does playing in the field and is an excellent run
producer, but he nor anyone else the Tribe sticks in left field,
can match Foster.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER, Foster.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER FIELD: Cesar Geronimo or Kenny Lofton? Geronimo was one
of those guys who made a living with his glove and his arm, a
good-field, no-hit guy who Anderson could stick in the No. 8 hole
and forget about, a luxury The Big Red Machine could afford. He did
hit .300 one year with a series of bloops and seeing-eye grounders
and the team called his bat, ``The Magic Wand.'' Lofton, though, is
The Complete Player . He plays defense, he runs the bases, hit hits
for average and some pop. He is far superior to Geronimo, who, with
his name, should have played with the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER, Lofton.
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT FIELD: Ken Griffey Sr. or Manny Ramirez? Griffey was good,
very good. He was better defensively than Ramirez and, by far, a
better base-runner _ a master of the infield hit. He had 37 infield
hits one year. Ramirez, though, is a run-producer . . . a lot like
Perez, a guy who can hoist a team upon his shoulders and carry it.
And sometimes, the way Ramirez runs the bases, it looks as if he is
carrying something heavy on his shoulders. But he is The Big Man on
the Tribe and Griffey was merely an integral part of The Big Red
Machine.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER, Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   STARTING PITCHERS: Are you kidding? Neither team has produced a
Cy Young winner, or even come close. Neither team needed much
starting pitching because they used the hammer-them-to-death
method. No lead by the opposing team was or is safe. The Reds had a
legitimate No. 1 in Don Gullett, while Jack Billingham and Freddie
Norman were adequate. The Tribe has Dave Burba and Charles Nagy and
Bartolo Colon and Jaret Wright . . . all very serviceable, all very
average. It was Billingham who made up a very bad poem about his
team scoring runs for him: ``Seven (runs) is heaven, eight we
skate, nine is divine, ten we win.'' As a poet, he matched his
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER, Nobody . . . a draw.
</P>
<P>
   RELIEF PITCHERS: Are you kidding again? The Big Red Machine had
a couple of excellent guys to finish games (they weren't called
closers then) in left-hander Will McEnaney and right-hander Rawlins
Jackson Eastwick III. And there was Pedro Borbon, the rubber-armed
guy of many goofy deeds. The Tribe has a true closer in Mike
Jackson and a bunch of other ever-changing parts. Neither team
needed or needs much of a bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER, Nobody . . . a draw.
</P>
<P>
   MANAGERS: Sparky Anderson or Mike Hargrove? As Bench once told
Anderson, ``Just stay out of our way and we'll win you some
championships.'' And for the most part, he did. He put the same
eight guys in the lineup every day, then earned his nickname,
``Captain Hook,'' by manipulating his pitching regularly and often.
Hargrove has had to manage around an abundance of injuries and done
a masterful job of bandaging and patching. With the DH, he doesn't
have to use much strategy. Anderson is headed for the Hall of Fame
and Hargrove is still trying to head for his first World Series
ring.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER, Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMING UP: Even by giving the 1999 Cleveland Indians the
advantage at DH because there was no such animal in 1976, The Big
Red Machine wins, 6-4-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribe is very, very good, but what has it won? Nothing, yet.
In fact, it still has to prove it is better than the New York
Yankees this year. The Big Red Machine was far and away the best
team in 1975 and 1976, winning the World Series both years.
</P>
<P>
   When the Indians win a World Series, don't come back. Win two in
a row first.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
