<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7960 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN14-     07-13 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quite a load when big back gets big bucks
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jamal Anderson will get the money he wants, or most of
it. He'll get his new contract soon enough, probably after training
camp begins but before the second exhibition game. And he'll be
happy, and he'll have another big season, and probably the Atlanta
Falcons will, too. Question is, what happens when this extended
contract hits Year 4, Year 5, Year 6?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is the Falcons' best and most marketable player, the
most compelling reason to buy a ticket to go watch this
increasingly compelling team. Today, he's almost worth the $10
million signing bonus he wants for agreeing to remain with the
Falcons beyond the millennium. The only guarantee that tomorrow can
offer is that Anderson won't be as good in 2001 as he is today.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson turns 27 the last day of September. Emmitt Smith and
Barry Sanders, the best backs of this decade, are both 30 and have
begun the inevitable descent toward retirement. Neither Smith nor
Sanders absorbs the full-on blows that Anderson does. Neither Smith
nor Sanders has carried 410 times in the course of a regular
season, as Anderson did last season. Nobody else ever has, either.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks and offensive tackles can get better with age.
Running backs cannot. It's not humanly possible to be hit in the
knees and ankles so many times and keep your speed. A little
running back can stretch his career by becoming a Dave Meggett, a
third-down specialist who runs away from people. A big running back
doesn't have that option. As he ages, a big running back will get
only disproportionately worse.
</P>
<P>
   There are antecedents aplenty _ Christian Okoye, Pete Johnson,
James Wilder, even the great Gerald Riggs of the Falcons _ but the
most apt is Earl Campbell. Equipped with Anderson-like thighs and
an Anderson-like will, Campbell had five 1,000-yard seasons in his
first six NFL years, the powerful string broken only by the 1982
strike. Came the seventh season, Campbell was just another
beaten-up back. This will be Anderson's sixth NFL season.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are differences. Anderson did little his first two
years, rushing only 41 times; Campbell had 670 carries in his first
two seasons. But Anderson has rushed 700 times these past two
seasons, and the workload doesn't stand to ease much when he
returns. The Falcons won the NFC largely because of Anderson's
pounding, and their use of a second-round pick to draft Reggie
Kelly, a blocking tight end, points to an even greater emphasis on
power, if that's possible.
</P>
<P>
   Figure Anderson will get between $25 million and $30 million
over five or six years. Not all of that will be guaranteed, but
most will. That's money well-spent in the short run _ after three
decades of muddling, could the Falcons not re-sign their MVP now
that they have something to defend? _ but it stands to buy little
toward the contract's end. By 2001, the Falcons will be seeking a
new Anderson, even as the old one remains on the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like a weird bit of business, it's really just
the way of this front-loaded world. To get Jamal Anderson into
camp, the Falcons will have to promise to keep paying him later.
But they won't need him later. They need him now.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
