<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7961 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-TRIPLEJUMP14-COX     07-13 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRIPLEJUMP14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Desmond Hunt: World-class jumper...and getting a doctorate, too
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Many athletes are looking forward to 2000, the
year of the Summer Olympics in Sydney. But for triple jumper
Desmond Hunt, next year will be doubly significant. That's also
when he's scheduled to complete his doctoral work in kinesiology at
the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a guy do what he's doing,'' said Dan Pfaff,
assistant track coach at the University of Texas. ``He's in the top
10 in his event and he's getting a doctorate in a top 10 program.''
</P>
<P>
   A typical day for Hunt begins at 7:30 a.m. in the lab, where he
works until 3 p.m. Training sessions start right after that and run
almost three hours. After a dinner break, Hunt goes back to the
classroom, where he teaches until 9:30 p.m. Then, it's back to the
apartment to say hi to the dog, catch up on some reading and get
ready to start the routine all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten to the point where I'm uncomfortable not being
busy,'' said Hunt, who would like to teach at a university or do
research after he receives his doctorate. Hunt is in his fifth year
here of working on post-graduate degrees.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent U.S. outdoor track and field championships in
Eugene, Ore., Hunt, who graduated from Iowa State in 1994, finished
second in the triple jump. Provided Hunt meets qualifying
standards, he will qualify for the world championships in August.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of July, Hunt left the United States for Europe
to compete in some meets, but also to get some much-needed rest and
relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   Dual careers in academia and track and field seemed unlikely
paths when Hunt was growing up in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Illinois, basketball is life. It's like football is in
Texas,'' Hunt said. At Zion-Benton High School, Hunt was a lanky
basketball shooting guard. He didn't start start triple jumping
until late in his high school career but did manage to finish third
in the state in his senior season of 1989. That was good enough to
get the long-striding jumper some nibbles in college track offers,
including one from Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, however, acknowledges that he did little more than get by
in the high school classroom and wasn't really prepared for
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some tremendous difficulty getting grades,'' he said.
''It's not that I couldn't learn the material. I didn't know how to
study. I didn't go to some classes, and if I did go, I'd just sit
there.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hunt came back home for Christmas break during his freshman
year, his mother, Shirley, picked him up at the airport and gave
him an earful during the ride home. She told him that if he wasn't
going to work in the classroom he might as well quit school and get
a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a 3.5 after that,'' Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Success in track also followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to work your way up there if you didn't run distances
(races),'' Hunt said. While the foreign-born distance runners were
often the stars, Hunt was usually in the background as a solid
performer in an often overlooked event.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people who don't even know what the triple jump is,''
Hunt said. ``They've never seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his senior year, he finished second in the Big Eight and 14th
in the NCAA meet. His career best was still shorter than 54 feet
and it looked like his jumping days were over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We throw people out on the street after undergrad,'' Pfaff
said. ``Other countries find a way to take care of their people.
Here, you can't get into meets. We let them in all-comers meets,
but there might be only three guys in that. You can't get very
excited about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Track athletes who want to continue their careers after college
usually buck a triple whammy. In addition to the lack of
competition, there can be a lack of training facilities and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In track there's maybe 10 or 15 guys who are making a
living,'' Pfaff said. ``If you look at golf, the 125th guy is
making good money. If you look at the 125th athlete in track and
field, you'd cry. They're not driving sports cars, they're hoping
to keep the rent guy away.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt kept jumping because he found a conducive atmosphere at UT
and a coach/friend in Pfaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan said that track and field used to be an art, but now it's
a science,'' Hunt said. ``He knows what's going on and he's open to
new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   While in Austin, Hunt's triple jump has increased by about two
feet. But he has no endorsements. He doesn't even get free shoes.
In the outdoor championships, he ran in a borrowed uniform from a
sprinter. Last year, because of his academic workload, he didn't
even compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the ability to be a top 10 performer in the world,''
Pfaff said. ``He needs more competition and fewer financial worries
and time constraints. But, his intelligence and maturity are a
plus. It's an event of wisdom; it takes a lot of years to figure it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt will get some much-needed competition in Europe, but unlike
his previous trips there, he won't be focusing solely on the meets.
He'll be staying with a friend in Madrid and plans to do some
sightseeing and take pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take the opportunity to enjoy the cultures and
the history,'' Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   After that it will be back on the dual treadmill that will only
accelerate as 2000 approaches.
</P>
<P>
   John Maher writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
