<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7962 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLAN-COLUMN14-COX     07-13 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLAN-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jack-of-ALL-trades
 &HT;    By Leigh Allan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you're a klutz around the house and yard,
Chuck and Jay say thanks. And keep up the bad work.
</P>
<P>
   I opened the mail at home. A note from our bug people, AAbel.
Nothing interesting there.
</P>
<P>
   Then, out fell the fliers:
</P>
<P>
   AAbel Lawn Care
</P>
<P>
   AAbel Paver Systems
</P>
<P>
   AAbel Landscaping
</P>
<P>
   AAbel Appliance Service
</P>
<P>
   AAbel Home Assessment
</P>
<P>
   AAbel Home Improvement
</P>
<P>
   AAbel Carpet Cleaning
</P>
<P>
   AAbel Duct Cleaning
</P>
<P>
   AAbel Heating and Air Conditioning
</P>
<P>
   AAbel Airline and Nuclear Power Plant Construction, all at the
same Kettering, Ohio address.
</P>
<P>
   Okay, the last two weren't really there, but only because Chuck
Norman and Jay Moran haven't had a crack at them yet. In a few
years, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   The AAbel EEmpire seemed unusual. There's a connection between
lawn care and landscaping, but exterminating and appliance service?
Other than they both try to get the bugs out?
</P>
<P>
   At least the assemblage seemed odd until Norman, 51, a CPA, and
Moran, 41, a management major, explained it. Then I saw what was
really unique was their business philosophy, one based on an
observation many have made but not acted upon.
</P>
<P>
   The observation is simple _ there are lots of tradesmen who are
very good at their crafts, but abysmal at business. And because
they lack financial and management skills, they fail or just scrape
by.
</P>
<P>
   Norman and Moran's actions are simple, too _ they find a company
that provides good service but is shaky on the business side, buy
it, and leave the skilled person in charge with an ownership cut
while they handle the books and marketing and personnel and so
forth.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a common-sense idea you'd think it would be common
practice, but Norman and Moran say they know of no one else going
their way. Companies often expand within one service line by buying
up similar outfits, but not across services.
</P>
<P>
   The duo got the entrepreneurial urge while both worked with Jet
Express trucking in the '80s. They and a Jet owner wandered into a
chance to buy a Miamisburg, Ohio company making auto sub-carpet
matting. Five years later, they sold to a bigger firm.
</P>
<P>
   Norman and Moran went on their own in 1990, when a man told them
his aunt and uncle wanted to sell AAbel Exterminators, which had
ambled along since 1937 as a mom-and-popper with a good reputation.
They saw a big opening in the insect-slaying game between tiny
operations that would have trouble coping with new regulations on
toxic chemicals and national firms with no personal touch, and
bought the first AAbel before they knew anything about
exterminating.
</P>
<P>
   They learned and grew.
</P>
<P>
   The same thought process added the other businesses. The idea is
to become an all-in-one home service center. The coming
opportunity? Home spa maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon homeowners will be unable to do anything for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe that should be UUn AAble.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh Allan writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
