   THE LAYOUT'S DONE FOR YOU: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are
available for purchase in paginated form:
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMOTIVE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 0713 _ The 10th anniversary special edition of the
MX-5 Miata clearly isn't for everyone who wants a two-seater
because of its inflated price. But it does stand out in a niche
market segment catering to traditional sports car enthusiasts.
(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 3-column color
photo of car's exterior and an 6-pica color photo of car's
interior.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 1999 Miata 10th
anniversary edition.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP DRIVING _ Whether you are making an out-of-state car trip
or just a short ride to a nearby lake or mountain retreat, don't
spoil your summer vacation by letting the heat and the boil of
traffic get the best of you. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
Includes 1-column color photograph of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ A review of the new Saturn midsize L-Series.
(Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-IMPALA _ A test drive of the 2000 Chevrolet Impala
(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL FINANCE
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Readers often ask what books would help them get
smart about investing in general and the stock market in
particular. That's no surprise. A lot more people have investments
these days because they have 401(k) retirement plans. Others have
gotten interested because they keep hearing about the booming stock
market. Publishers know this hunger exists. That's why there are so
many investment advice books in the stores and libraries. Some of
those books are very good. But some are them are awful. We list
some good places to start. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TVSERIES-MINORITIES _ When the NAACP took on the networks Monday
at its annual convention, blasting them for failing to include
minority actors in prominent roles in new series set to debut on in
the fall, they were partly right. And partly wrong. A comment from
the AJC TV critic. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   TV-GUILLAUME _ A talk with actor Robert Guillaume about his
resurgent career as one of the stars in ``Sports Night'' and his
real-life stroke and recovery that also played a big role in the
season ender of the ABC show. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   DOGGY-CAMP _ HUTTO, Texas _ You drop them off for the week,
choose what they'll eat from a laminated menu, and set up a
personalized schedule that includes swimming, nature walks and
romping after a flying disc. No, this isn't day care for the kids.
It's summer camp with a decidedly doggy flair, and if you want your
pooch to participate, you'd better book early. It's just one of the
offerings at the Triple Crown Dog Academy, where canine aficionados
are heading from across the country to board, train and show their
animals. (LeBlanc, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEOGAMES-VIOLENCE _ The killings at Columbine High School
prompted lawsuits against the makers of Doom, the granddaddy of
violent video games, but Doom looks like child's play compared to
the games that are out now, including Kingpin, just released last
week, which allows you to form your own mafia (not the trenchcoat
kind) shoot your victim in 15 different body parts. A look at
violoent video games, and those who play them. Photo tba. art from
boxes of games, frame grabs available. (Emerson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 60. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VIDEOGAMES-WHO _ Who plays video games, how much, etc... by the
numbers. (Emerson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   COOL-BANDANA _ The Miracool Bandana is designed to beat the
heat. Just soak it in water, wear it around your neck, and stay
cool. (Moss, Dayton Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   HEARTATTACK-COUGH _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Coughing will not prevent a
heart attack, in case anyone was wondering. The question came up
after a recent e-mail message circulated with the virulence of a
chain letter. It says that anyone who feels heart attack symptoms
while alone should cough ``repeatedly and very vigorously,''
repeating a breath ``about every two seconds. . . until help
arrives, or until (a normal heartbeat returns).''
</P>
<P>
   The advice even cites some impressive sources. But it is wrong
on so many levels, say both the American Heart Association and Dr.
Gary Fishbein, a cardiologist with the Dayton Heart Center. ``It's
right up there with voodoo as far as I'm concerned,'' Fishbein
says. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   VETS-HIGHTECH _ With depressurized rooms, high-tech air filters
and waste water steam cleaners, the new Animal Health Research
Center at the University of Georgia's College of Veterinary
Medicine will allow scientists to safely study organisms heretofore
deemed too deadly. On the drawing board since the late 1970s, the
ARHC will have cost about $20 million_which has been split by the
federal government and the state of Georgia_once it opens in a few
weeks. Administrators believe the unique facility, which is
designed to accomodate animal species of all types, will be used by
researchers from cross the country. The Australian government has
already contacted the Vet School about doing some research for it
on Exotic Newcastle Disease, which has infected poultry in that
country and necessitated the slaughter of 2 million chickens. We
tour the facility and write about it and what it will mean.
(McCarthy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
