<P>
   SCIENCE/HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   HEARTATTACK-COUGH _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Coughing will not prevent a
heart attack, in case anyone was wondering. The question came up
after a recent e-mail message circulated with the virulence of a
chain letter. It says that anyone who feels heart attack symptoms
while alone should cough ``repeatedly and very vigorously,''
repeating a breath ``about every two seconds. . . until help
arrives, or until (a normal heartbeat returns).''
</P>
<P>
   The advice even cites some impressive sources. But it is wrong
on so many levels, say both the American Heart Association and Dr.
Gary Fishbein, a cardiologist with the Dayton Heart Center. ``It's
right up there with voodoo as far as I'm concerned,'' Fishbein
says. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   VETS-HIGHTECH _ With depressurized rooms, high-tech air filters
and waste water steam cleaners, the new Animal Health Research
Center at the University of Georgia's College of Veterinary
Medicine will allow scientists to safely study organisms heretofore
deemed too deadly. On the drawing board since the late 1970s, the
ARHC will have cost about $20 million_which has been split by the
federal government and the state of Georgia_once it opens in a few
weeks. Administrators believe the unique facility, which is
designed to accomodate animal species of all types, will be used by
researchers from cross the country. The Australian government has
already contacted the Vet School about doing some research for it
on Exotic Newcastle Disease, which has infected poultry in that
country and necessitated the slaughter of 2 million chickens. We
tour the facility and write about it and what it will mean.
(McCarthy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
