<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ John Lynch was one of ours, one
of Sonoma's and one of a kind. One day last week, at the age of 46,
John died. He was found at home, fully dressed for the morning
shift at The Examiner. We all have searched for explanations for
his death, and found nothing but reasons for him to live. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ In his Newsweek cover story,
``The Whine of '99: Everyone's Getting Rich But Me,'' Adam Bryant
wrote about the explosion of U.S. millionaires and billionaires and
how it makes other Americans feel envious, resentful and desperate
to gain entrance to the club. ``The strange thing,'' wrote Bryant,
``is that nobody's really countering the money hype.'' By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Somehow, I've developed an
allergic reaction to wasp or bee venom. About 4 per cent of the
population has this vulnerability. The nasty little assassins
manage to kill about 50 Americans every year. For some reason, and
nobody knows why, bees and wasps actually seem attracted to people
allergic to their venom. I'm told that they treat this thing with
two years or so of weekly shots to build up your tolerance for
insect venom. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (San Francisco) _ Mexico, more than ever, needs
to boot out the corrupt and authoritarian Partido Revolucionario
Institucional (PRI) _ the massive political machine that has
simultaneously ruled over that country for 70 years and been the
main cause of its massive poverty. By ELIAS CASTILLO.
</P>
