<SLUG> BC-JAN-DEBONT-DIRECTS-THE-HAUNTING-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GHOST STORY: JAN DE BONT DIRECTS `THE HAUNTING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jan De Bont directing a scene from ``The
Haunting.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Jan De Bont's latest film, a sentimental, low-budget drama about
four old ladies swapping sad stories over tea in the English
countryside, is about to ...
 &HT;    Yeah, right.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes I think about doing smaller films, but right now I
have a lot of energy and I need to be on big films,'' says De Bont,
the high-powered, Dutch-born director of ``Speed'' (1994),
``Twister'' (1996) and ``Speed 2'' (1998). ``I might get a little
bored, though I think directors who do smaller films are really
great.
 &HT;    ``Directors should do the things they're better at,'' he says.
``Making my kind of movie is very hard and not always a lot of fun,
because there's a lot more pressure from the studio, a lot more
press, and it's nerve-wracking to get them done.
 &HT;    ``That's the kind of pressure I could sometimes really do
without,'' he says with a chuckle, ``and I don't think you have as
much of it on a small drama. But I'm happy doing what I do.''
 &HT;    In other words, staging emotional roller-coaster rides for his
audiences _ and De Bont is back doing that thing he does with ``The
Haunting,'' a $75 million horror film based on Shirley Jackson's
1959 novel, ``The Haunting of Hill House.'' Her chilling tome also
served as the source material for Robert Wise's 1963 film classic
of the same name.
 &HT;    The new film unfolds in contemporary times, and stars Liam
Neeson as a psychologist whose work takes him, Catherine
Zeta-Jones, Lili Taylor and Owen Wilson into an ominous New England
manor dominated by a tentacled bed, helix-shaped staircases, marble
griffins, a 14-foot chandelier and a massive stone fireplace.
 &HT;    All hell breaks loose as the house comes to life to scare the
bejabbers out of the group and, hopefully, the audience.
 &HT;    A thriller in the psychological-horror tradition of ``The
Innocents'' (1961), ``Rosemary's Baby'' (1968), ``The Exorcist''
(1973) and ``The Shining'' (1980) _ all of which De Bont says
served as inspirations _ ``The Haunting'' opens nationwide on July
23.
 &HT;    In his version of the story, Wise created a palpable sense of
menace without ever letting his poltergeists appear on screen. De
Bont promises plenty of goose bumps, too, but he chose to employ
state-of-the-art special effects to show his evildoers in action.
 &HT;    ``The movie will not bombard you with effects,'' he says in his
tombstone-thick accent during a telephone call from a sound-editing
room at Skywalker Ranch, George Lucas' production facility just
north of San Francisco. ``We have 110 or so effects shots, which is
nothing compared to most summer movies.
 &HT;    ``There was a lot more written in the book than Robert Wise was
able to put on the screen,'' he adds. ``That doesn't mean that all
of a sudden we're going to show you everything _ there's still a
lot you have to imagine.''
 &HT;    Besides, De Bont says, in the age of ``Scream'' (1996) and
``Hannibal'' (1999), even the most gruesome special effects don't
have the impact they once had. With ``The Haunting,'' he's
returning to the idea that less is more.
 &HT;    ``It's not only what you can't see, but what you can hear and
can't see that can scare you,'' he says. ``It's quite often the
smallest sound that starts the imagination going. You can have a
big, dark room, but it doesn't mean much until something _ that
little sound _ sets off the imagination.''
 &HT;    So crucial was the aural element, the director adds, that he
recorded sounds prior to filming. On the set, he had this library
of digital sound effects available at the touch of a button _
helpfully marked ``Moaning,'' ``Loud Creak'' and so on.
 &HT;    This emphasis on sound is new for a director who began his
career as a cinematographer, providing visuals for such films as
``Die Hard'' (1988), ``Flatliners'' (1990), ``Basic Instinct''
(1992) and ``Lethal Weapon 3'' (1992). But for this project, he
felt, he had no other choice.
 &HT;    ``Each time before when I'd done a movie, either as a director
or a director of photography, the actors had problems reacting to
things that were not there,'' he says. ``It was hard for them to
imagine what would be where.
 &HT;    ``In this case, the house is such a major character that it had
to be reacting. There had to be something for the actors to react
to, something to stimulate their fears,'' De Bont says. ``By having
the sound effects there, I could instantly deliver a sound, in
between lines even, so that the actors could always react to
exactly the right thing at the right time and in the right
direction.
 &HT;    ``There wasn't any guesswork, and that helped the actors
tremendously.''
 &HT;    Such concern for his actors might surprise longtime De Bont
observers. After all, he's widely known as a driven, demanding and
sometimes impossible-to-work-with director, to the point of
inspiring a reported crew mutiny during the filming of ``Twister.''
 &HT;    ``It's partially true,'' De Bont admits. ``On `Twister,' all I
did was explain to the actors and the crew about things that
weren't there. That leaves you so little time to spend on the other
things that are needed for the rest of a scene.
 &HT;    ``On `The Haunting,' I had time to sit with the actors and
rehearse, before we started the movie and on the set,'' he says,
``On my other films we'd always been victims of the effects,
because they were kind of catapulting the story. On `The Haunting,'
it's the actors who propel the story.
 &HT;    ``That's a huge change, such an interesting and exciting
change.''
 &HT;    While finishing editing ``The Haunting,'' De Bont has his eye on
several percolating projects. In the coming year he'll serve as
executive producer on Steven Spielberg's sci-fi epic ``Minority
Report,'' to star Tom Cruise, and will also produce ``The
Paperboy,'' popular Spanish director Pedro Almodovar's
English-language debut.
 &HT;    Despite the flurry of activity, however, De Bont will be closely
watching the reaction to ``The Haunting.'' So will the Hollywood
studios, he knows: The director stumbled mightily with the
disastrous ``Speed 2,'' and a second consecutive misfire won't be
so easily forgotten or forgiven.
 &HT;    ``I think the stakes are high for any director on any new
movie,'' says De Bont, who lives with his wife and children in Los
Angeles.
 &HT;    ```Speed 2' was a little bit of a victim of not having a
finished script before we started to shoot,'' he admits. ``There
were many times, even in pre-production, that I said, `We shouldn't
make this movie. It's not ready yet.'
 &HT;    ``The studio wanted the movie, and once there's no turning
around you just try to make the best of what you have,'' he adds.
``You cannot make these big movies, with effects _ with water,
which is the most horrible thing to do _ and write it on the set as
you go.''
 &HT;    De Bont pauses.
 &HT;    ``Listen, you're only as good as your last movie,'' he says
without anger. ``It doesn't matter who you are, what you are or
what the stakes are.
 &HT;    ``Also, if you do something that's good again, people really
embrace you,'' De Bont says. ``I've learned from working with a lot
of directors that nobody makes hit after hit after hit. It just
doesn't exist.
 &HT;    ``You can't guess what will happen. Audiences' tastes change
constantly, even by the month.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
