<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8027 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-BACKSTREET-BOYS-O     07-13 1504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-BACKSTREET-BOYS-ON-TOP-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BACKSTREET BOYS ON EASY STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of the Backstreet Boys performing live on
stage.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's Saturday afternoon in New York, and the Backstreet Boys _
except for Howie Dorough, who's across town rehearsing for a skit
on ``Saturday Night Live'' _ are trying on clothes.
 &HT;    These aren't just any duds, mind you _ these are the Tour
Costumes, the threads that for most of the rest of the year will
have to hold up under screaming loud enough and shrill enough to
pop stitching and summon dogs from every corner of the planet to
wherever the Backstreet Boys happen to be playing that night.
 &HT;    Yes, the Boys are back, complete with their new album, the
mightily hyped ``Millennium'' (Jive Records, 1999). It's the
eagerly awaited followup to ``Backstreet Boys'' (1997), which in
the process of selling 27 million copies worldwide launched a batch
of hits such as ``Quit Playing Games (With My Heart),'' ``As Long
As You Love Me'' and ``Everybody (Backstreet's Back),'' and made
the world safe again for Tiger Beat subscribers and the sugary pop
of boy bands.
 &HT;    But theirs is a notoriously fickle audience, one that's prone to
capricious changes of loyalty. So all concerned seemed relieved
when ``Millennium'' _ which set a sales record with more than 1.1
million first-week copies blowing out of stores _ shook out as the
biggest pop-culture happening this side of ``The Phantom Menace.''
 &HT;    Meanwhile, radio stations have jumped all over ``Millennium's''
first single, ``I Want It That Way,'' making it the most added song
of the year so far. And the media blitz accompanying the album's
release has taken the Boys everywhere, from ``Saturday Night Live''
to Nickelodeon and the Disney Channel, from ``Rosie'' to the World
Music Awards, not to mention into a tongue-in-cheek he-man ad
campaign.
 &HT;    ``It's kind of like, `Whew, that's a weight lifted off our
shoulders. They're still responding,''' says Kevin Richardson, at
27 the oldest member of the band.
 &HT;    ``It was great to be overseas a few weeks ago to promote the
single and do TV shows and stuff,'' he adds. ``We did `Top of the
Pops' in London with a live studio audience, and the first time we
went through the song, even though they had never heard it before,
they were singing it with us. That was a great sign.''
 &HT;    Richardson and his mates _ Dorough, Nick Carter, Brian Littrell
and A.J. McLean _ were well aware of the high expectations that
confronted ``Millennium.'' Coming on the heels of the Spice Girls'
success, the Orlando, Fla.-based quintet had created a phenomenon
that opened the pop-market doors for a slew of similar ``boy
groups,'' including 'N Sync, 98 Degrees and C-Note.
 &HT;    But the Backstreet Boys are the first of those bands to test its
audience's loyalty with a true followup to its breakthrough album.
Some of the others have exploited their success through the release
of quick-hit fodder such as holiday albums, but not through an
actual followup record. The pop trio Hanson, for instance, cashed
in with a live album and a collection of archival recordings, but
still hasn't released its next ``proper'' album.
 &HT;    But the Boys _ who deny persistent rumors of intense rivalries
with any of the other ``boy groups'' _ passed up such gap-fillers
in favor of concentrating on an album of all-new material. With the
success of ``Millennium,'' the gamble seems to have paid off.
 &HT;    ``We put the pressure on ourselves just to make better music,''
Richardson says. ``We're not really looking at the sales _ if you
make good music and keep trying to outdo your last album as far as
quality of music, the sales will come.
 &HT;    ``Something I came to realize in the past year _ which initially
bothered me but now I've accepted it _ is the fact that you just
can't please everybody,'' he says. ``Everybody is not going to like
our music, or us.
 &HT;    ``But we just want people to know that everything they hear on
the album is real, it's us. It's our voices singing. It's us coming
up with the treatments for our videos and the ideas for our stage
show.
 &HT;    ``We're not just the guys that are told what to do, where to be,
what to sing, how to look,'' Richardson says. ``We just want people
to know that this is us, not somebody else's idea of us.''
 &HT;    If Richardson sounds sensitive on that point, it's no wonder _
it's been an issue since last year, when the Backstreet Boys parted
ways with Lou Pearlman, the Orlando-based entrepreneur who brought
them together. Inspired by the success of the early-1990s group New
Kids on the Block, he recruited the Boys, beginning with
Richardson, from aspiring performers working at theme parks and
other venues around the Orlando area.
 &HT;    The group's 1995 debut made only a marginal splash in the
modern-rock-infatuated United States, though it was a big hit in
Europe. Two years later, however, ``Backstreet Boys'' cracked the
American market and made the Boys pinups around the world.
 &HT;    But a disagreement over finances led to a lawsuit against
Pearlman, who had built a stable of other pop acts, including 'N
Sync. Eventually the case was settled out of court.
 &HT;    The lawsuit, along with several family deaths and open-heart
surgery for Littrell, made what should have been a celebratory 1998
into what Richardson calls ``the hardest of my 27 years on the
planet.''
 &HT;    ``Millennium'' represents a new approach, he adds. Crucial
players from the last album remain, notably songwriter/producer Max
Martin _ who also scored recently with Britney Spears _ but
Richardson says the five singers themselves took a greater role in
creating and overseeing the music this time around. He co-wrote
``Back to Your Heart,'' while Littrell co-wrote three, including
the album-closing ``The Perfect Fan,'' a tribute to his mother
featuring his high-school choir.
 &HT;    ``We want to get involved and write more,'' says Richardson,
adding that the other members wrote songs that were not chosen for
the album. ``But, at the same time, we realize it's a growing
process _ we don't want to just jump into it and say `OK, we're
going to write this whole album ourselves.' They still have to be
of a certain caliber, no matter who wrote them.
 &HT;    ``We feel like we've grown on this album,'' he concludes. ``The
album's deeper, lyrically, but it's not over our young fans'
heads.''
 &HT;    Richardson says the group is acutely aware of the delicate
balance between delivering on fans' expectations and stagnating.
 &HT;    The heavy radio play for ``I Want It That Way'' was, he says,
``kind of like a weight being lifted off our shoulders. They're
still responding.'' Edgier dance tracks such as ``Don't Want You
Back'' followed, giving their fans a chance to digest the album a
bit first.
 &HT;    ``We're just trying to evolve with the times in order to stay in
the pop-music scene,'' Richardson says, ``just like Madonna's done,
just like Janet and Michael, so we have a long career.''
 &HT;    And the Boys _ who are touring Europe throughout the summer
before bringing their in-the-round stage production to North
America _ don't expect much help from the critics, who as a rule
don't give much respect to this kind of aim-to-please pop.
 &HT;    ``Critics are critics,'' Richardson says. ``We're not trying to
be the Joni Mitchell of our time or the Jimi Hendrix of our time.
We're just trying to make good music and make people happy and
forget about their problems. We're not trying to send a message.''
 &HT;    The criticism is frustrating, he admits.
 &HT;    ``But what can you do?'' he says with a shrug. ``We're happy
with what we're putting out, and so are millions of other people.
We're happy about that, too.''
 c.1999 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on the Backstreet Boys, consult
their official Website at www.backstreetboys.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
