<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUPERT-EVERETT-IN-INSPECTOR-GADGET-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD GUYS HAVE ALL THE FUN: RUPERT EVERETT SINKS HIS CLAW INTO
`INSPECTOR GADGET' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Rupert Everett with Michael G. Hagerty
in a scene from ``Inspector Gadget.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Rupert Everett doesn't much care if people think it's possible
for an openly gay man to be a major Hollywood star.
 &HT;    But if he can't, maybe it isn't possible, because in every other
respect Everett is the ideal big-screen leading man. He's drop-dead
gorgeous in the old-fashioned, movie-star way, with rugged, dark
looks, a sculptured body, a full head of dark, wavy hair and a
voice that's smooth as silk.
 &HT;    All of the above were on ample display in his breakthrough
performance as Julia Roberts' gay editor in ``My Best Friend's
Wedding'' (1997). Despite her starpower, Everett stole the picture
with his deadpan wit, his subtle smile and his killer rendition of
``I Say a Little Prayer For You.''
 &HT;    Despite the fears of closeted stars, past and present, Everett
says that his open homosexuality hasn't hurt his career in the
least.
 &HT;    ``Coming out is one of the best things I've ever done,'' Everett
says. ``Let's face it, I'm just a sex machine to both genders. And,
frankly, it's very exhausting _ I need a lot of sleep.''
 &HT;    He looks like it early one morning as he enters a suite at Los
Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel, visibly hung over, to talk about his
new film, ``Inspector Gadget,'' which will open July 23. In a
switch from his typically elegant image, Everett plays the vampy
villain Claw in the children's movie, opposite title hero Matthew
Broderick.
 &HT;    At 40, Everett has the charm of a young Cary Grant, even before
his order of aspirin arrives. Cutting a handsome figure in black
pants and a sweater, he has a voice that rumbles low and sexy until
one recurring question lends an edge of serious anger.
 &HT;    Over and over again for days, journalists have asked him if an
openly gay man can become a sex symbol in Hollywood, and he's
frankly tired of the question.
 &HT;    ``I don't mean to sound defensive, but sexuality is not an
issue,'' he says tightly. ``A gay person can play a straight role
and a straight person can play a gay role. It's just acting, isn't
it?''
 &HT;    Everett ought to know about acting. His two most recent films
have offered plum roles from the pens of William Shakespeare, as
Oberon in ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' (1999), and Oscar Wilde, as
the witty womanizer Lord Goring in the current ``An Ideal
Husband.''
 &HT;    After such high-toned fare, he says, he jumped at the chance to
play a Disney bad guy.
 &HT;    ``I always wanted to make a movie for children where I could
play the nasty,'' he says. ``Children enjoy these characters so
much.''
 &HT;    His own childhood was largely free of such pleasures, he says.
Growing up in a strict British military family, he wasn't
encouraged to indulge his natural instinct toward performing.
 &HT;    ``I was expected to go into the armed forces or into the stock
exchange,'' he recalls, ``but I was too much of a celebrity seeker
for those professions. I was always dreaming of being famous _ I
even prayed for fame and celebrity.''
 &HT;    He dropped out of boarding school at 15 to study acting in
London, but at 17 was kicked out of acting school for
insubordination. Broke and on the streets, Everett didn't know
where to turn.
 &HT;    ``I fell into prostitution,'' he admits. ``I was a struggling
actor who got propositioned one day outside a subway station. The
guy offered me a massive amount of money.''
 &HT;    That period in his life lasted only briefly, he adds. Some early
acting opportunities and modeling work helped him straighten out
his life.
 &HT;    By this time he had come to terms with his sexual orientation.
 &HT;    ``I think I always knew I was gay,'' he says. ``For a while I
thought I might also be heterosexual, because I enjoyed being with
women. The problem was, a girlfriend was never enough for me and I
wasn't enough for them. Things had to change.''
 &HT;    From a career point of view, it really wasn't a big deal, he
adds.
 &HT;    ``I never thought I'd be working in America,'' he says, ``so it
really didn't matter. In Europe, people are not hung up on
sexuality, especially when it comes to entertainers. They judge
them on merit and talent.''
 &HT;    His early film career featured strong performances in ``Another
Country'' (1984), ``Dance With a Stranger'' (1985) and ``Duet for
One'' (1986), but it wasn't until ``My Best Friend's Wedding'' that
he broke through to the fame he'd always longed for.
 &HT;    Predictably, it wasn't everything he'd hoped.
 &HT;    ``The horrible thing about fame is that it fluctuates all the
time,'' Everett says. ``You get used to everyone loving you, and
then it hurts when they stop. Then it's very weird when they start
loving you again.
 &HT;    ``It's also like being on this treadmill,'' he adds. ``I know
there's always someone else who is going to get the job I want.
There's always someone coming up _ someone in front of you, someone
behind you, someone who does it better.
 &HT;    ``Of course, you can take all this with a pinch of salt,'' he
says, ``but I don't like salt!''
 &HT;    In the meantime, though, Everett is having a ball, especially
making ``The Next Best Thing'' _ about a woman who has a son with
her gay best friend, and the ensuing complications _ with his
friend Madonna.
 &HT;    ``She's a pro at handling fame,'' the actor says. ``But the
problem is that Madonna has energy like no one else _ she just
drives through every obstacle.''
 &HT;    Of course, he adds, he himself is much the same way.
 &HT;    ``One of my best friends is an English guy,'' he says, ``and he
never wants to see me _ he says I have too much energy and I make
him feel depressed.''
 &HT;    Currently in the works is Everett's first stab at screenwriting,
a script that would reunite him with Roberts in a story that is
bound to be controversial _ if only behind certain closed doors in
Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``Julia and I will play the most famous stars in America,'' he
says eagerly. ``I'm a big action hero, she's Miss American Pie.
We're been married for 15 years. We're People magazine's No. 1
couple every year. We're Bill and Hillary's best friends.''
 &HT;    The twist: It's all a sham, a marriage of convenience _ one of
them is gay.
 &HT;    Asked if this is based on any specific Hollywood actor, actress
or marriage, Everett laughs wickedly. Then ignores the question
entirely.
 &HT;    Actually, he says later, there are days when he's sorry the
public knows he's gay.
 &HT;    ``When you're an actor, I think it's better when the public
knows nothing about you,'' Everett says. ``I think the public
should be able to make you into what they want you to be.
 &HT;    ``In the old days in Hollywood, an actor's persona was made up
by the studio,'' he adds. ``These public images had nothing to do
with the reality of these actors as human beings. In a way it kept
careers going, because the public wasn't interested in the actor _
they were interested in their films.''
 &HT;    One thing's for sure, he says: He has no interest in being a
spokesman or poster child for out actors.
 &HT;    ``From my point of view,'' he says, ``if I had to wear a banner
across my chest and write something on it, I wouldn't write `gay.'
I'd write `actor.'''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Inspector Gadget,'' consult
