<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8030 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-DOGS-OF-PRIME-TIM     07-13 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-DOGS-OF-PRIME-TIME-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DOGS OF PRIME TIME: BEHIND THE SCENES WITH TV'S LEAST TALKATIVE
STARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Eddie in a scene from ``Frasier.'') 
 By CATHERINE DAWSON and BRIAN HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not every television star is a hot-air generator who dreams of
directing between on-the-set temper tantrums and off-season demands
for more money.
</P>
<P>
   Some don't even have a bad word to say about anyone they've ever
worked with.
</P>
<P>
   Check out our exclusive look behind the scenes with four
frequently underappreciated but always valuable prime-time pooches.
 &UR; EDDIE OF `FRASIER' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who can tell what's really going on in Eddie's mind during those
unnerving long stares at Frasier Crane (Kelsey Grammer)?
</P>
<P>
   Well, trainer Mathilde deCagny has a fair idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a connection between us,'' she says. ``It's kind of
interesting to watch his thoughts going on ... sometimes I can see
him think, `What's next, what's next?'''
</P>
<P>
   The trainer and Moose _ Eddie's real name, inspired by his hefty
25 pounds and 14-inch stature, both large for his breed _ live with
six other acting dogs in Venice, Calif. According to her, the
longer the show runs, the harder it gets to keep Moose interested
in his ``Frasier'' scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moose is an old pro, he's been in the business too long,
almost,'' deCagny says. ``It's at the point where to work him is
really challenging. He wants to outsmart everybody _ and he can, he
knows the routine. If I rehearse him too much, then he'll know too
much. I have to keep him guessing a little bit. It's a very fine
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Moose's 4-year-old son Enzo has come aboard as his stand-in
during rehearsals, and also has taken over the more athletic
stunts. At 9, deCagny says, Moose still has a lot of energy, but
using Enzo as an understudy helps keep the Jack Russell terrier
from getting bored.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very obnoxious little dog, annoying,'' she adds of
Moose. ``The character he plays on `Frasier' is pretty much what
he's like in real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the average dog that is loving,'' deCagny says.
``Moose is independent and has a selfish side _ yet he's very
lovable, extremely attractive and smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of Moose's early years will be revealed in a book to be
released next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Moose's life story from his point of view,'' deCagny
says. ``Before and after `Frasier,' the celebrities he's met. It's
not just about work, but his home and dog life too.'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; HAPPY OF `7TH HEAVEN' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``7th Heaven's'' Happy wasn't too jolly the day trainer Shawna
Hamann tried to slip her paws into rubber boots.
</P>
<P>
   But what could Hamann do? The script called for the Camden
family dog to walk onto the set in rain boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had velcro closures,'' Hamann recalls, ``and she'd lift
up her feet real weird. Happy finally learned to walk in them, but
she didn't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old, terrier-mix mutt dresses up often on the show
and, Hamann says, it's never easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's had to learn to wear a lot of stuff,'' the trainer
recalls. ``She had to wear a tutu in one show, bow ties and feather
boas around her neck. That's the hardest thing, getting them used
to stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy has to handle every trick because she's a crossbreed, and
Hamann can't find a matching stand-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between her ears, her hair coat and her hair color, we've had
a really hard time finding another dog,'' she says. ``And we go
looking at pounds all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy is herself a rescued stray, so named because ``she was so
enthusiastic when we found her,'' Hamann recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``7th Heaven'' is Happy's first crack at acting, and Hamann says
her skittish nature sometimes makes training harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she was probably abused before we got her,'' the
trainer says, ``because she's a bit wary of some men. If somebody
is there that she doesn't know, she gets a bit shy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she learns stuff really fast, and she's really smart.'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; MURRAY OF `MAD ABOUT YOU' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maui isn't as dumb as Murray, the sitcom character he portrayed
for seven seasons on the recently concluded ``Mad About You.''
</P>
<P>
   On the series, when Murray wasn't inexplicably creating piles
out of Paul's socks he was ramming headfirst into walls. But in
real life, the 11-year-old border-collie mix has a reputation as a
consummate professional.
</P>
<P>
   The son of two actors, Maui get his start in the business when
he began doubling for his mother on the set of the 1991 movie
``Bingo!'' Soon after he auditioned for ``Mad About You'' and won
the job, replacing the dog initially cast in the pilot, who the
producers thought was too enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his extensive trick repertoire, Maui's best work came
when there was little for him to do. In the real world, most dogs
aren't constantly upstaging their owners. Instead, they can be
found lounging on the couch or hanging around the supper table.
</P>
<P>
   Maui was perfect in that role, serving as the silent comic foil
to Paul and Jamie's zaniness. Evidently, producers saw fit to
reward the floppy-eared canine. During the run of ``Mad About
You,'' Maui basked in his celebrity status with limo rides, an
air-conditioned trailer and even his own stand-in.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike many Hollywood stars, Maui is as likable offscreen
as on. When he wasn't working, he spent his spare time in support
of worthy causes, including cancer- and AIDS-research events and
Humane Society benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Now that ``Mad About You'' has ended, Maui is enjoying
semi-retirement at Boone's Animals for Hollywood in Castaic,
Calif. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; WISHBONE OF `WISHBONE' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soccer is one in a million _ or at least one in a hundred.
That's how many other dogs the 11-year-old Jack Russell terrier had
to beat out to win the coveted role of Wishbone, PBS's
history-hopping pooch.
</P>
<P>
   The role is a dream job for an actor, canine or otherwise.
``Wishbone'' is a children's series that takes an innovative
approach to works of classic literature, casting Soccer in such
diverse roles as Pip from ``Great Expectations,'' Dr. Frankenstein,
Hercules, King Midas and even the notorious Dr. Jekyll.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Wishbone'' isn't the Connecticut-born terrier's only
acting experience. He's appeared in a number of dog-food
commercials for Mighty Dog and Chuck Wagon, and in print ads for
Nike. Soccer also recently completed his first feature-length film,
``Wishbone's Dog Days of the West,'' which is currently available
on home video.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Soccer is often upstaged by his ``Wishbone''
wardrobe, for which designer Stephen M. Chudej won an Emmy Award.
On the show, Wishbone is seen as everyone from Quasimodo to Robin
Hood, providing impressive challenges to the dog's ability to
maneuver in the elaborate getups _ challenges to which, so far, he
has always proven equal.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer, who earned his name because of his predilection for the
black-and-white ball, has completed 40 episodes of the
award-winning ``Wishbone'' since 1995 _ but not without some
professional help.
</P>
<P>
   Like many human actors, Soccer has an entourage to help get him
through the day. No fewer than four stand-ins provide relief when
the work becomes too much, while comedian/voiceover artist Larry
Brantley supplies Wishbone's vocals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Catherine Dawson and Brian Hartigan are staff writers for TV
Guide Canada, based in North York, Ont.) &LR; 
