<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8056 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-ECONOMY14-COX     07-13 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ECONOMY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIGH-TECH CITIES HAVE AN ECONOMIC ADVANTAGE, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    With TECH-LIST.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cities that have transformed themselves into
high-tech hot spots will have a head start as their economies head
into the new century, according to a study released Tuesday by the
nonprofit Milken Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the Santa Monica, Calif., research group found that
a strong technology component helps a region's economy in two ways:
first by boosting wages and tax revenues directly, and then
filtering wealth down to traditional workers as tech employees
purchase local goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1990-91 recession, growth in the high-tech sector has
been four times as large as in the aggregate economy.
</P>
<P>
   In that period companies that invent or improve technologies
have not fanned out evenly across the landscape, preferring to
cluster in certain communities, the Milken study found.
</P>
<P>
   The list of pumped-up places is topped by the San Jose, Calif.,
area, the 500-ton gorilla of the high-tech world. No other region
comes close to the Silicon Valley in terms of technology-driven
jobs and output. The study found that with 279,000 tech workers,
San Jose's weight in the information economy is more than triple
that of the next closest competitor, Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many other regions are flourishing in the post-industrial
world, giving the Top Ten list some surprising winners, such as
Chicago and Atlanta, cities known more for their airports than
their Internet portals.
</P>
<P>
   The Milken study created a weighted index to rank metropolitan
areas based on the concentration of high-tech industries and their
economic output. Its ``high-tech'' universe encompasses 14
industries, from computer makers to telecommunications firms to
drug manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas came up with the No. 2 ranking because of its diversified
technolgy base. The metro area is home to seven high-tech
industries, giving it both large pools of workers and a rich mix of
company headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The next three cities were the Los Angeles-Long Beach area,
Boston, and the Seattle-Bellevue-Everett region, all well-known
tech centers.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the next five cities were more surprising:
Washington, Albuquerque, N.M., Chicago, New York and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is usually associated with lawyers, lobbyists and
bureaucrats, but its suburb of Fairfax County, Va., is home to
America Online, UUNET and PSINet. The study found that more than
half the nation's Internet traffic passes through firms in
Washington's suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, which grew up on meat packing and transportation, has
become an important center of communications equipment
manufacturing, thanks largely to the presence of Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   And Atlanta, which started as a center for freight
transportation, has become a center of information transportation,
with jobs growing rapidly in telecommunications services, computers
and data processing services.
</P>
<P>
   What can cities do to attract or create more technology jobs,
given their importance to a regional economy?
</P>
<P>
   The study found that many firms still look for traditional
location factors, such as tax rates, energy costs and rents.
</P>
<P>
   But other factors were even more important. They include: access
to a trained and educated work force; close proximity to excellent
educational facilities and research institutions; an existing
network of suppliers; availability of venture capital; climate, and
other quality-of-life factors.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Wong, an economist who worked on the study, said the 1999
list of high-tech winners won't necessarily dictate which cities
will flourish in the next century. Tech companies can hop cities
easily because they are ``about content and ideas, not physical
inputs' such as iron ore or timber, he said. ``High-tech companies
are a lot more easily moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Wong said metro areas that want to attract and keep high-tech
companies should concentrate on improving infrastructure, such as
roads and sewers, to keep pace with the increase in demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-tech brings high growth and a lot of new people,'' he
said. ``If (city officials) commit themselves to higher growth,
they have to face the risk that the local economy will be
transformed beyond recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, San Jose was a relatively sleepy town a generation
ago. Today, its streets are clogged and even the smallest homes
sell for more than $300,000, forcing many young families to have to
leave the area where they grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Rapid growth ``can be a blessing, but you really have to plan it
out better'' than most cities have been doing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
