<HEADER>
A8092 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     07-13 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV01-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., AUG. 1, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have to hang a very heavy, framed mirror on my living room
wall, so I was advised to mount it with screws or hooks that go
into the studs, rather than merely depending on hollow drywall
anchors of any kind. However, the spot where I want the mirror to
hang does not work out for properly spaced studs _ even though the
mirror is considerably wider than the space between the studs.
Fastening to one of the studs would mean the mirror could not hang
level. Is there a method that will enable me to fasten to the
studs, yet insure that the mirror will hang level?
</P>
<P>
   A: Use a stud finder to locate the studs, then screw a length of
1x6 lumber several inches shorter than the width of the mirror to
two or three of these studs so it bridges them and will be centered
over the area you want the mirror to hang (as shown in the
drawing). You can then fasten two hooks, properly located to hang
the mirror level, by screwing them to this board.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our wall-to-wall carpet was installed five years ago and has
rippled up slightly so that it now has small ``waves'' in the
carpeting. How can we level this out, and how can we prevent this
happening again?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your carpet has apparently stretched so that it is no longer
tight against the flooring. This is usually due to improper
installation when the carpet was first put down _ it was not
stretched as tightly as it should have been. The solution now is to
pull it up around the edges where it is held by the tackless strips
along one side of the room, then re-stretch the carpet properly
before tacking it back down again. Since this requires some special
tools, and techniques most homeowners are not familiar with, it is
usually best to call in a professional to do this job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a concrete driveway that has an uneven or wavy finish
with numerous depressions in the surface. As a result water puddles
and does not run off completely when it rains. Is there any way of
leveling this off so that it will slope properly and cause water to
drain off completely when it rains?
</P>
<P>
   A: A concrete driveway that does not slope properly usually has
to be torn up and replaced. However, in some cases it can be
resurfaced with a special cement that can be applied in thin
layers, after first roughing up the original surface. However, this
will raise the level of the driveway anywhere from one-half to one
full inch, depending on the depth of the depressions. This is a
sizable project that requires familiarity with concrete work, so
for most people I would recommend calling in a masonry contractor
for this.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My kitchen floor has a parquet wood floor which I plan to
have sanded and refinished in the near future. I have spoken to two
carpenters about this and one advised using a rotary sander, while
the other said that a drum sander should be used. What do you
think?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rather than a carpenter I would suggest calling in a floor
finishing contractor who also will do the sanding. Traditionally,
most use a drum sander on wood floors, but if your floor is not a
solid wood parquet and is merely laminated wood ``tiles'' with a
thin veneer of plywood on top, then it may be that a rotary sander
would be safer. An experienced floor finishing contractor could
determine this.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``HANGING A HEAVY MIRROR'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Board screwed to studs will provide a solid surface for
hanging a heavy mirror.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
