<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, July 14. If you have any questions, please call The
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   PCHICK: Last year, greater prairie chickens were added to
Missouri's endangered species list. They number less than 1,000,
and those birds are scattered in dangerously small flocks on
prairie remnants. If population trends continue, they will vanish
in the next decade. Yet the deeper trouble is that all grassland
birds are declining in the Midwest. Kansas, a prairie stronghold,
has seen prairie chicken numbers drop in the southeast and the
southwest. Now, an unprecedented effort between public and private
agencies is under way to save the lowly prairie chicken. Bill
Graham. 50. Photos and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TREE: Kamsas City's curb and sidewalk replacement program has a
number of neighborhood groups up in arms. That's because the city
is cuttingdown hundreds of mature trees because, public works
officials say, the roots are in the way of the new curbs and
sidewalks. Many residents say too many trees are being sacrificed
needlessly. Winston Ross. 35. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH: A Missouri group will circulate petitions to do away with
the death penalty in the state. The Secretary of State's office has
approved the petition drive, which, if successful, would put the
issue on the November 2000 ballot. Oscar Avila. 12.
</P>
<P>
   PONZI: Independence, Mo., man sentenced to three years in prison
for bilking 68 people out of $5 million in a ponzi scheme. Mark
Morris. 15.
</P>
<P>
   BUS. The National Transportation Safety Board last week
recommended stricter rules on the types of vehicles used to
transport children involved in school, Head Start and other
programs; the recommendations, if adopted, would phase out vans
often used by day-care centers and others, replacing them with
sturdier and safer school buses; some area school district already
have made the change. Robert A. Cronkleton.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A tribal casino in Miami County, Kan., takes another
step closer to reality. Rick Alm.
</P>
<P>
   JCINDI _ Although President Clinton and Jesse Jackson are just
now discovering the American Indian housing crisis, a Johnson
County, Kan., company is at the front of a trend in lending _
mortgages for First Americans. Eric Palmer. Photo
</P>
<P>
   JCBOOT _ Olathe Boot, which claims to have invented the cowboy
boot, has closed temporarily while looking for a buyer. Writer TBA.
</P>
<P>
   JCLONG _ Folo on Supreme Court ruling that a Sprint subsidiary
in Kansas that resells long distance is in fact a utility. Ted
Sickinger.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   ALLSTARS. All-Star Game. AL vs. NL, 7:30 p.m. Photos. Dick
Kaegel.
</P>
<P>
   POZNANSKI. Column on British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ALLSIDE. All-Star sidebar. Steve Rock. 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA. Midseason overview.
</P>
