<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8115 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-LONGWOOD-2N     07-13 1632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-LONGWOOD-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... in 1963.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That was the seed of the pro revival leading to open tennis in
1968 and the riches in the game today. This weekend's Davis Cuppers
ought to know that their momentary playground, Longwood, kept their
profession breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer dug up 12 guys to play the US Pro, and the bank put up a
sum that seemed a fortune, a $10,000 purse. Laver beat Gonzalez on
grass in a rainstorm and felt like the Aga Khan when he saw the
champion's check for $2,200. Julie Hickey, now a Boston attorney,
felt like Helen of Troy, having launched an historic conflict.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, after losing to Rosewall, the volatile Gonzalez
tried to knock out a steel locker in the dressing room with a
roundhouse right hand. The locker won the decision. But Pancho had
a point, bellowing, ``Why are we still playing on this goddamn
grass? They should pave over the whole place!''
</P>
<P>
   His sentiments, though shared, weren't expressed so vociferously
by colleagues. Nevertheless, Longwood, a fairly progressive outpost
(despite the passe name) in a very conservative sport, began a
court evolution for its professional guests. In the interest of
truer bounces, stadium grass was uprooted, replaced by a plastic
carpet in 1969, presently by clay in 1974, and _ overdue _ hard
courts in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The US Pro had led the way away from grass for the country's
prime tournaments. Installation of clay was copied by the US Open
in 1975 along with floodlit night tennis that Longwood had
pioneered in 1969, and acceptance of the then radical tie-breaker
at the US Pro of 1970. But the resistance to hard courts _ ``No
parking lot tennis in our club,'' huffed one reactionary board
member _ was costly after the US Open embraced asphalt at Flushing
Meadow in 1978, and the US, except Boston, followed. The quality of
talent declined. Those shining days and nights that made Boston
second only to the Open in New York _ the titles of Laver,
Rosewall, Roche, Jimmy Connors, Bjorn Borg _ were but a lilting
memory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A return to prominence
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years late, the US Pro got around to hardening up, but
further mismanagement sent the tournament into further decline.
Instead of remaining with the newly reorganized ATP Tour in 1990,
Longwood presented a series of charades, exhibition tourneys
through 1995, turning off its public. In 1996 the house went
regrettably dark. But the efforts of president Tom Ford paid off in
1997 _ ``this is a big-league city that deserves big-league
tennis,'' he proclaimed _ as Longwood climbed back onto the
recognized circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the way back,'' says president Steve Roiter, having
hired Woolf Associates to lead a 21st-century revival and obtained
Jim Courier to head the August cast, playing for considerably more
than the 10 grand of 1964: $350,000 with perhaps $200,000 more for
unannounced appearance fees, unimaginable sums to a hopeful band of
cricketers of 1877 who paid $40 annual rent to the estate of David
Sears for a patch of turf on his intown estate called Longwood. A
$200 shanty was erected as clubhouse with a shallow tub posing as
plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Groundsman Charlie Chambers recalled the place in his old age:
``That tub was like a bird bath with members flicking water on
themselves as a sort of shower. They didn't believe much in
laundries. At the end of the season they made a bonfire out of the
cricket and tennis clothes they'd worn practically non-stop.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Longwood I, the original, at the corner of Brookline
and Longwood Avenues, present-day site of the Winsor School, across
from Beth Israel Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three years after the founding a young member studying at
Harvard, Dwight Davis, ordered a sterling Cup from Shreve's, and
the Davis Cup came into being. It spread from just Britain and the
winning US in 1900 to 129 countries this year. This was 12 years
before Fenway Park rose a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   The property became too valuable for tennis, and Longwood II was
conceived in 1911, a move way out into what appeared to be the
wilderness at the time, a lot divided between Newton and Brookline,
halved like Berlin not so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   By 1922 the new courts, reclaimed from a swamp, and the spare,
twin-towered stucco clubhouse, purchased and moved from the defunct
Chestnut Hill Club, were ready for use. Big Bill Tilden beat club
member Dick Williams (the Titanic and Harvard alumnus) for the
Longwood Bowl. Molla Mallory took the female version over Helen
Wills Moody. Tilden came back with Richards for the US Doubles
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Longwood set up shop, a Harvard-trained physician,
Dr. James Dwight, who wisely never let medicine interfere with his
tennis, became a member as did his protege, Dick Sears, grandson of
the property owner. Dwight was probably the first American to play,
in 1874, with Fred Sears on a front lawn in Nahant. He surely won
the first tournament, a sociable round-robin, in 1876 at Nahant.
And the groomed young Sears, a 19-year-old Harvardian, to win the
inaugural US Championship at Newport in 1881.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight, rightly considered the Big Daddy of American tennis, was
a leading light in forming the US Tennis Association, putting
together the Davis Cup competition and playing championship doubles
with Sears. The club has spawned several other USTA presidents
(one, Walter Elcock, was also president of the International Tennis
Federation, 1975-76), champs, innovators, Hall of Famers, and a few
genuine heroes.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was Al Stitt in 1958. On his way to play a US
Doubles match, he heard a cry of distress from the swimming pool. A
tot had fallen in, unnoticed by the guards. Quickly Al dived to the
rescue. Then he resumed walking squishily to the assigned court
where his partner berated him for his sodden, bedraggled
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Another was the club president Jack Steverman, the electrician
who had installed the floodlights. Prowling the empty grounds to
check up on everything about 2 a.m., after play had ended, the
crowd departed, he, too, heard a mournful cry for help. Turned out
a porta-john had been turned over by pranksters while occupied. The
door was blocked, the poor guy trapped. Steverman liberated him.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody liberated Napoleon the second time he was exiled, to the
small, distant isle of St. Helena off the West African coast. The
manor house where he died was called Longwood, the name chosen by
Napoleon buff David Sears for his estate. A few tennis conquerors
experienced Waterloos at this Longwood.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody has replaced Hazel Wightman as the American Lady of
Tennis. She died at 87 in 1974 after grabbing cartloads of titles.
Winning was the least of it, although she was an all-timer who
racked up extraordinary US triples (the US singles, doubles, and
mixed titles) three straight years, 1909-11, had a Wimbledon title
and two Olympic gold medals in doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Like Dwight Davis, Mrs. Wightie, as everyone called her,
believed in international team play, feeling the women should have
a Davis Cup-style tournament of their own. She also donated a
trophy, the Wightman Cup, for that purpose. Lifting off in 1923, it
was a hit for years, the US vs. Britain, and inspired the later
Federation Cup. If anybody wanted tennis lessons, this tiny, jovial
old ivory-haired lady gave them gratis in her garage a block from
the club to countless kids and adults, demonstrating her trademark
volley in the limited space. She was a giver and an encourager.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A championship venue
</P>
<P>
   Following Dick Sears, US champs flowed from the club in the
early days when the Northeast was dominant. Mike Leach, triumphant
in the NCAA singles in 1982, was the most recent, and accompanied
his old man, Dr. Robert Leach, to the Father and Son title in
1990-91. Sarah Palfrey in 1941 and 1945 was the last Longwoodian to
take the big one, the US Singles, then at Forest Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Making a singular Longwood-Forest Hills leap in 1968, Lt. Arthur
Ashe was a breakthrough man while serving in the US Army. With
searing serves and volleys Arthur captured and captivated Boston
that year to win the US Amateur over Bob Lutz, his first important
title and national TV debut, courtesy WGBH-PBS. Few gave him a shot
at the US Open, but he blitzed the pros, too, beating Tom Okker in
the final. No amateur will ever take both titles again.
</P>
<P>
   At Longwood a reporter asked Ashe how it felt to play and win at
a restricted club where he wouldn't be accepted as a member. He
replied, ``I don't like it, but I have to go where the tournaments
are played. And I believe that will change.'' Happily it did, some
time ago.
</P>
<P>
   But little has changed in the club's outward appearance. Well,
the cow belonging to the mother of Senator Leverett Saltonstall no
longer grazes in the area of the terrace courts. Chambers
remembered that cow as an obstacle when he was laying out the new
courts just after World War I.
</P>
<P>
   ``The club had just about all the land it wanted, except that
parcel owned by Mrs. Saltonstall,'' he said. ``She said she
wouldn't sell until the cow died. I'm sure a few members thought
about poisoning it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only cow now is the cash cow, the US Pro, and Longwood is
one of a determined handful of clubs hanging in the professional
tournament game. Mike Humphrey, the groundsman for a
quarter-century, is pleased that he doesn't have to care for such
an animal tramping on his bluegrass and creeping bent, and that the
Japanese beetles haven't been in touch for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't even many crickets, although I saw one the other
day,'' he says. ``We do have a few little weevils, about a
quarter-inch.'' But it isn't likely the name will be changed to
Longwood Weevil Club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
