<HEADER>
A8116 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     07-13 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGELLAN CONTINUES TO PERFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember when everyone said Fidelity's Magellan Fund was too
big?
</P>
<P>
   That was the prevailing sentiment in September 1997 when the
mutual fund giant closed the fund to new investors. The argument
was pretty basic. At $60 billion, the fund was considered something
of an elephant, too big and too slow to make the nimble moves
necessary to generate good returns.
</P>
<P>
   Among those making that case were the authors of this column,
who, in applauding the decision to close the fund wrote, ``Magellan
has become too big to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   So what do you expect for your 50 cents a day _ perfection?
</P>
<P>
   The Magellan fund is set to become the first mutual fund to
cross the $100 billion mark _ it reached $99.3 billion Monday _ and
contrary to predictions, its performance has been awfully good. As
of last Friday, Magellan had returned 16.2 percent for the year,
slightly ahead of the 14.9 percent turned in by Vanguard's Standard
&AMP; Poors 500 Index. Last year Magellan topped the index by five
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Since Robert Stansky took over the helm of Magellan in June
1996, the fund has outperformed 77 percent of all growth funds,
according to Lipper Inc.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging Stansky's skill, some in the industry insist
he has also benefited from good luck. ``This has been a good time
to be big,'' says Russel Kinnel, mutual fund editor for
Morningstar.com, a firm that tracks the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Stansky's hot stretch has coincided with a period of excellent
performance by large-cap stocks, especially technology stocks. The
large-cap renaissance has allowed Stansky to buy the big stocks he
must buy, without paying any penalty. Should the market hit an
extended period where small- and mid-cap stocks do better, he will
be hard-pressed to keep pace, say the defenders of the ``big is
bad'' philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Those same people are also correct when they point out that the
Magellan fund is unlikely ever to beat the index by the huge
margins it did when it was younger and leaner. In 1991 and 1993,
the fund topped the index by 11 and 14 percentage points
respectively. The fund's current size guarantees that it must own a
big chunk of the index.
</P>
<P>
   But a look at Stansky's record suggests something else: that the
fears about the fund's size were overblown in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, Magellan's growth has been more than matched by
the stock market in general. Put another way, the fund's value
represents a smaller percentage of the total value of the stock
market than it did back in 1995. At $100 billion, Magellan can
still move in and out of stocks without causing big disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Second and most important, Stansky has proven he can be quite
nimble. If his fund is an elephant, it's an elephant that knows how
to tap dance.
</P>
<P>
   Stansky's method of operation is to make good-size bets on
different sectors of the market _ technology, retailing, energy
etc. Over time, those bets can change quite a bit. Consider: At the
end of 1997, Magellan had 12.9 percent of its money in technology
stocks. By the end of 1998 technology represented 25.8 percent of
the fund; by the end of the first quarter of 1999 technology was
down to 20.9 percent of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, Stansky's bets have paid dividends. Last
summer, after the Russian financial crisis took the air out of
technology stocks, Magellan moved aggressively into the sector,
says David O'Leary, a Fidelity watcher at Alpha Equity Research in
New Hampshire. According to O'Leary, Stansky's purchase of five big
stocks _ Microsoft, Dell, Cisco, American Online, and MCI Worldcom
_ allowed him to beat the market handily for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Stansky has also profited by investing heavily in retail stocks
and lightening up on financial stocks and health care stocks,
sectors that have not done well of late. He has consistently had
very little money in companies like Coke and Gillette, consumer
product firms that have been hurt by weak overseas economies.
</P>
<P>
   The 5.4 million shareholders in the Magellan fund have voted
their approval of Stansky's performance by sending him more of
their cash flow. The fund attracted about $2.1 billion in new money
in the first five months of the year, according to O'Leary. While
Magellan is officially closed to new investors, it is still
available to enrollees in retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   If we goofed when we questioned Stansky's prospects for beating
the market, we had plenty of company. ``I was one of those who said
it was too big,'' says William Dougherty, president of Kanon Bloch
Carre, a mutual fund consulting firm. ``I recommended that they
break the fund into pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does Dougherty think of his advice now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wrong,'' he says flatly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
