<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8123 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-13 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH, DECENCY IS TAYLOR LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'll forgive the shell shock in this newsroom, the sense that
we've lost too much of our own control. For the first time in 126
years, the Taylor family is not guiding the newspaper, and an
uncertain future has dawned on the tradition-laden pages of The
Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   It was swift, this decision to remove Ben Taylor as publisher
Monday _ and surprising. He was, literally, born to the job, but
nevertheless worked his way through the newsroom as a reporter and
editor, learning the intricacies of daily journalism from the
street on up.
</P>
<P>
   There was something reassuring about him, though never anything
glib. The Taylors, Ben included, might have stumbled here and
there, but you always knew they were trying to get things right.
Decency was, and is, the family trademark.
</P>
<P>
   So is excellent journalism. I've had the good fortune to travel
near and far on the Taylor nickel over much of my 10-year career
here. One of the things I've learned living out of hotel rooms in
distant cities is this: The Globe is inarguably one of the
half-dozen best newspapers in America, a fact that even we in this
newsroom _ natural complainers, all _ too often tend to forget.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Ben Taylor and the family members who came before him.
While other newspapers were cutting budgets _ and with it, news
holes and reporters _ the Taylors demanded a quality product every
day of the week, and were willing to pay for it in slimmer profit
margins. For them, journalism was more than a means to make a
dollar. It was a way to make their mark in the community they have
always loved and lived in.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone seemed to flourish from their efforts. Fifteen
Pulitzer Prizes have been won by members of the Globe staff over
the years _ one of so many reasons this has become a marquee
newspaper. At the same time, a $1,000 investment in Globe stock in
1973 was worth $120,000 only 20 years later. There are pressroom
workers who drive Cadillacs and Lincolns to their Cape Cod vacation
houses every Friday afternoon because of their well-placed faith in
the Brahmin Taylors.
</P>
<P>
   When the family sold the Globe to The New York Times Co. in 1993
for more than $1 billion, Ben Taylor could have probably bought a
small cruise ship with his profits and spent his remaining days
sailing the Mediterranean in the hands of an obsequious crew.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Taylors, led by then-publisher Bill Taylor, Ben's
second-cousin, struck a deal to keep one of their own in charge for
at least the next five years. It wasn't out of a need for money,
but from a sense of mission. The Taylors have always devoted
themselves to public service in the form of the best possible
newspaper they could produce, and the sale and its resulting
windfall would do little to change their goals.
</P>
<P>
   Has Ben Taylor taken his knocks in his two-plus years as
publisher? Of course, most prominently in the paper's
well-chronicled handling of the two well-known writers who once
occupied this space, Mike Barnicle and Patricia Smith. Criticize
his indecisive handling, but be gin clear on this fact: Any of his
mistakes were born of nothing more sinister than humanity _ an
attempt to be fair to the paper, to its public, and to all the
people involved. He'll live with that just fine.
</P>
<P>
   With Monday's announcement, it became apparent that change was
inevitable, though dignity was not. The New York Times didn't buy
this company to leave it in someone else's hands. Ben Taylor could
as easily have gone home after he got the news, taken solace in his
banking statements, and avoided the public eye. Instead, he stood
before the gathered editorial staff to welcome his replacement,
Richard Gilman, a Times executive, and spoke only of his hope for
the Globe's future. He'll remain as chairman of the Globe's board
of directors. It was the class act that we had come to expect of a
classy man.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman, in turn, spoke soothingly about the paper's future and
appreciatively of the Taylors' guiding hand. Even in this time of
tumult, we'd be foolish to overlook the fact that The New York
Times knows a thing or two about publishing a great newspaper. The
Taylors could have sold out to a lesser chain, but didn't.
Ironically, any upside in Monday's transition was largely the
Taylors' doing.
</P>
<P>
   What we lost in the sale six years ago was local ownership of a
uniquely local institution. Monday we lost the stewardship of a
family that always tried to do the right thing. The Taylors have
made a great city better through the paper that covers it. Their
mark will linger for as long as we have a Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
