<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8128 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-GARBAGE-BOS &LR;      07-13 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-GARBAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA GARBAGE PROBLEM MOUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ China's richest and most Westernized city is
confronting an unpleasant underside of being a modern,
consumer-oriented metropolis: garbage. Tons of it.
</P>
<P>
   Once a thrifty populace, Chinese consumers are now buying more
products wrapped in elaborate packaging and throwing them away
sooner. Cities such as Shanghai are spending money and energy to
move and treat ever greater amounts of trash, and losing precious
land to dumps and landfills.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Mingyang, 70, a farmer from Anhui province, is one of
thousands who have migrated to Shanghai to make a living collecting
garbage. Ten hours a day, he drags a rickshaw behind him and loads
it with waste cardboard, which he exchanges for cash at one of
hundreds of primitive downtown recycling lots, a vast expanse of
glass heaps, bottlecaps, plastic piles, and paper mountains that
has become a virtual city unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cardboard is useless now, but we can produce new things
with it, like your notebook,'' Sun said. He makes the equivalent of
$2.50 a day, four times his earnings as a farmer. He also
recognizes the social import of his arduous work. ``We create a lot
more waste than before. . . . What I do is good. I clean the
place.''
</P>
<P>
   This commercial capital of more than 13 million people produces
26.4 million pounds of waste daily, and it is piling up faster than
the city's garbagemen can collect it. Two pounds of garbage per
person per day is low by Western standards _ the average American
creates 4.4 pounds a day.
</P>
<P>
   But that is changing. The vast majority of Chinese have incomes
far below those of consumers in developed nations, but China is
projected to have the world's largest economy by 2020. The
resulting waste problem will have implications for air, land, and
water quality, and for energy use and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Per capita garbage production is rising 10 percent a year in a
nation with nearly five times the population of the United States,
making the environmental problems accompanying China's breakneck
economic growth a threat to the global, as well as local,
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Shanghai doesn't want its trash to become a cause celebre like
New York's notorious ``garbage barge,'' which in 1987 was turned
away from five states and three countries. Shanghai already has
2,000 trash heaps; nationwide, dumps cover 193 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   But Chinese cities are running out of places to dump their
trash. Some have turned to incineration, but burning is
controversial because it releases toxic gases.
</P>
<P>
   So Shanghai, which prides itself on being China's trendsetter,
is trying to promote recycling. Next month, officials say they will
launch a program in one of the city's 15 districts to test the
public's willingness to separate garbage _ and the government's
ability to process it.
</P>
<P>
   Both Beijing and Shanghai have tried pilot programs before,
without success. Collectors stored the trash and then eventually
just re-mixed the items that residents had separated because the
government had nowhere to recycle them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a country is first developing, people say, `We want
money; we don't care about quality of life,' '' said Feng Suwei,
director of Shanghai's Environmental Sanitation Administrative
Bureau. The city, he said, is in the second stage of development,
when a government with rising revenues can start to think about
minimizing the environmental impact of growth.
</P>
<P>
   But ``to protect the environment is a very high investment. Not
every city can afford it. . . . China is developing later, so we
are doing this later.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, China began recycling in the 1950s, but not in the way
we think of it today. Living standards were low, and reusing every
shred of almost everything was a state-sponsored ``mass activity''
and an economic necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Some old-fashioned, direct-use recycling still takes place. Like
hundreds of other pig farmers, Sheng Jingrong, 34, bicycles three
hours each way into the city to dig in restaurant trash bins for
discarded food for his 80 pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Shanghai once had 500 state-run recycling stations where people
sold everything from chicken feathers and hair to scrap metal and
old books. In the past two decades of a more market-driven economy,
all but 50 of those operations went out of business because they
were unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
   Small-time entrepreneurs have filled the void, buying and
selling scrap at a small profit to factories in neighboring Jiangsu
and Zhejiang provinces to make new bottles and cans.
</P>
<P>
   Huang Weiguo, 31, runs a plastics recycling lot piled high with
bottles separated into piles of red, yellow, blue, and orange. He
pays collectors 12 cents for every 2.2 pounds of plastic they bring
in, and he resells it to factories for a penny profit per pound. He
clears $185 a month, 2 1/2 times his pension as a laid-off state
factory worker.
</P>
<P>
   Sanitation officials say it's great to combine reemployment with
recycling, and they don't mind collectors making money off
Shanghai's garbage. But Feng complains that many factories in
Zhejiang and Jiangsu that use Shanghai's recycled trash are
polluting the air and water. ``We don't like the idea that
Shanghai's garbage is producing more environmental problems in
other places,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Feng says Shanghai could recycle its waste cleanly and
efficiently, and turn waste treatment into ``the main industry of
Shanghai in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   In the upcoming pilot project, the city will ask residents to
separate trash into toxic, wet, and dry piles. Feng estimates 28
percent can be reused, but that it will take at least five years to
get the whole city to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Song Qinghua, of the environmenal advocacy group Global Village
of Beijing, says that's a good idea, but says China needs stronger
regulations to deter pollution and enforce recycling. She says that
the government should create a market for recycled goods by, for
example, requiring that state-owned enterprises buy at least half
their paper from recycling mills.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when her group tried to print a report on recycled
paper, it couldn't find a single factory making the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that unlike those in Western countries
city governments here get no tax revenue or federal funds to
finance garbage collection.
</P>
<P>
   Feng says Shanghai is considering a waste tax on manufacturers,
similar to ones in developed countries, to fund environmental
efforts. The city also will push for national legislation to
enforce recycling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is going to work,'' he said, ``we need the support of
business, nongovernmental organizations, citizens, every sector of
society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
