<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT BACK ON TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have to give Bob Baffert credit. The popular trainer
suffered the first dip in his career recently when he orchestrated
a disasterous Triple Crown campaign. Some thought the ``genius''
label was wearing a little thin. But Baffert has rebounded so
quickly, helped by two big stakes victories over the weekend, that
his problems now appear to have been but a blip on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who rose to the top in 1997 and '98 when Silver Charm
and Real Quiet both won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness before
losing exciting Triple Crown bids in the Belmont Stakes, sent out
an entry of General Challenge and the filly Excellent Meeting in
this year's Derby. The pair were well-prepared and deserved their
billing as favorites, but they both had rough trips and finished
off the board. Excellent Meeting was pushed back to 18th before
rallying to finish fifth, and General Challenge was knocked
sideways out of the gate, then shut off on the first turn, and
wound up 11th.
</P>
<P>
   After the Derby ordeal, General Challenge was sent home to
California, but Baffert made a curious decision to bring Excellent
Meeting back for the Preakness, a difficult assignment for a filly.
Excellent Meeting informed Baffert that he had made an error by
pulling herself up on the far turn. Baffert then sent out his other
top filly, Silverbulletday, in the Belmont, even though he may have
been the only one in racing who thought she could run a mile and a
half against males. Predictably, she took the lead but faded to
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, long a media darling, was stung by a barrage of
criticism and was on the verge of becoming yesterday's news.
However, General Challenge, Excellent Meeting, and Silverbulletday,
who won the $250,000 Monmouth Oaks Saturday, all came back to
capture their next starts. That means, despite his obvious
miscalculations, that Baffert didn't ruin any of them. And, to top
it off, Baffert turned Foresty, another 3-year-old, loose to
capture the $150,000 Dwyer Stakes at Belmont, marking the first
victory in 10 tries for Baffert in New York. It now looks as if
Forestry could be his most powerful sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday, a daughter of Silver Deputy, has now won six of
seven races this year and 12 of 14 in her career. The only race she
lost other than the Belmont was to Excellent Meeting. The one
comment on starting Silverbulletday in the Belmont that made any
sense came from owner Mike Pegram, who said that he and Baffert
were out to stop Charismatic, who had won the Derby and Preakness,
from becoming Horse of the Year by being the first to win the
Triple Crown since Affirmed in 1978. They want Silvebulletday to be
Horse of the Year, but that's a hard assignment for a young female.
</P>
<P>
   In the Monmouth Oaks, which drew only four starters,
Silverbulletday and Jerry Bailey stalked pacesetter Bag Lady Jane
from the outset, took over when ready, and drew off to a 5-length
tally at minimum odds of 1-20 ($2.10 to win), covering a mile and
one-16th in 1:43. ``I could tell that she was ready, her energy
level was high,'' said Baffert. ``She's so much fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Forestry, a son of Storm Cat, cost a whopping $1.5 million as a
yearling, but he was a late developer for owners Aaron and Marie
Jones. Silverbulletday was 2-year-old filly champion, but Forestry
did not race at age 2. He debuted on Jan. 2 at Santa Anita and ran
second. He broke his maiden in his next start, then ran third in an
allowance race won by the precocious Apremont, with Charismatic
second. Forestry has taken five straight races since and now sports
a record of 8-6-1-1, with over $300,000 in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dwyer, Forestry and Bailey broke first in the field of
five. The speedy Doneraile Court, a $1 million yearling trained by
Nick Zito and ridden by Jorge Chavez, rushed up and took over,
sizzling through a half in :44 4/5 and 6 furlongs in 1:08 2/5.
Forestry tracked the leader, then ran past him turning for home and
coasted to the wire to score by better than two lengths. Off at
even money ($4), Forestry covered the mile and one-16th, run around
one turn at Belmont, in 1:41.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I picked the right day to get my first win in New
York,'' said Baffert. ``Forestry is getting better and learning how
to run. When we bought him, he was medium-sized, and he got big
quick. That's why I didn't want to push him too early.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Silverbulletday and Forestry will return to Churchill
Downs, where they are based, and Baffert will mull when to start
them next. Silverbulletday grabbed a quarter (cut her front foot
with her back) in the Monmouth Oaks, and Baffert wants to keep his
eye on her. But he might run both Silverbulletday and Forestry in
the $1 million Haskell Invitational at Monmouth Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The Haskell is raced at a mile and one-eighth, a more suitable
distance for Silverbulletday than the marathon 12 furlongs of the
Belmont, and Baffert and Pegram, who also owns Real Quiet, know
that Silverbulletday needs to beat colts at least once this year to
be considered for Horse of the Year. But would Forestry blast her
in the Haskell?
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping Baffert makes the right decisions for the Haskell,
since he made enough wrong ones during the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Thief' tuning up
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief, third in the Derby, seventh in the Preakness, and
sixth against older horses in the Met Mile May 28, is training for
the Swaps Stakes for 3-year-olds at Hollywood Park Sunday, in which
he will be ridden by Pat Day. Last Sunday, Cat Thief, also a son of
Storm Cat, worked seven furlongs in 1:25 1/5 at Santa Anita. ``Cat
Thief just isn't a very good work horse, and he probably never will
be,'' said Randy Bradshaw, assistant trainer for D. Wayne Lukas.
``But, for him, this was a very good workout. We gave him some
company, and it seemed to wake him up a little bit.'' . . . Valhol,
who won the Arkansas Derby April 10 as a maiden but was
disqualified from the purse money when his jockey, Billy Patin, was
found to have carried an electrical device, broke his maiden
officially June 29. Valhol won an allowance race at Lone Star that
day and will race next in the Ohio Derby at Thistledown July 24 . .
. The National Thoroughbred Racing Association announced that the
Eclipse Award Dinner will be held Jan. 17 at the Beverly Hills
Hilton.
</P>
<P>
