<HEADLINE>
RONALDO REBIRTH CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago Monday, Brazil was succumbing to one of its most
baffling and humiliating defeats in the World Cup championship.
France deservedly won the game, 3-0, at Stade de France in
Saint-Denis, igniting the biggest celebrations on the Champs Elysee
since the end of World War II. But the mystery surrounding the
(literal) collapse of the Brazilian's star striker, Ronaldo, took
on an equally enduring life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has recovered, though, under Wanderly Luxemburgo, who
replaced Mario Zagallo as coach. And Ronaldo seems to be
rejuvenated. He scored the game-winner in a 2-1 victory over
Argentina Sunday as the Brazilians qualified for a Copa America
semifinal date with Mexico Wednesday in Ciudad del Este, Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo has already probably received more publicity than any
other 22-year-old athlete, a double-edged sword which brought him
riches but created unimagineable pressures. He seldom had a break
from publicity tours, international duty, and Serie A obligations
with Inter, the club which was supposed to be his first
professional obligation. Ronaldo's personal life was strained, his
engagement with Susana Werner has ended, and he has been
romantically linked with several other young women.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, Ronaldo has been paired with Amoroso, who was
recently transfered from Udinese to Parma. With the powerful
Rivaldo in support, along with three physical midfielders, Flavio
Conceicao, Emerson, and Ze Roberto, the Brazilian attack has been
formidable. Amoroso was Serie A's leading scorer with 22 goals last
season and might be an even better striking partner for Ronaldo
than Christian Vieri, who will join him at Inter next season.
</P>
<P>
   At France '98, the Brazilians were supported by thousands of
countrymen. But they are feeling more comfortable now, with a home
base on the Brazil border at Foz de Iguazu.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has performed well in the tournament, overcoming the
suspension of Cuauthemoc Blanco and the accusation of doping of
Paulo Cesar Chavez and Raul Rodrigo Lara. Luis (El Pajaro)
Hernandez scored twice as Mexico eliminated Peru in penalty kicks
after playing to a 3-3 tie. Hernandez has now scored nine goals in
Copa America.
</P>
<P>
   The Copa America, initiated with an unofficial tournament in
1910, is the oldest continental competition and the last of the
century is reaching a dramatic climax. Chile and Uruguay meet in
the other semifinal. The final will be in Asuncion Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FIFA-Asia agree
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FIFA reached a compromise with the Asian Football Confederation,
awarding the Asians a playoff against Europe for a place in the
2002 World Cup finals. Asia will have four teams _ two qualifiers,
plus co-hosts Japan and South Korea _ and a fifth team will meet
Europe's No. 15 team for a place. The Europeans will have 14
automatic qualifiers, including defending champion France. The rest
of the 32-team field includes Africa ( five teams), CONCACAF
(three), South America ( four, plus a fifth team involved in a
playoff with Oceania).
</P>
<P>
   The final match will be July 26, 2002 at Yokohama's 70,336-seat
stadium. FIFA rejected a proposal by the World Cup Organizing
Committee to change the format to extend group play into the second
round, which would have increased the number of games from 64 to
76. Organizers are attempting to maximize opportunities for
spectators, since this will be Asia's first-ever World Cup, and
expanding the tournament would allow them to rival attendances for
the US '94 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   US officials are jockeying for position for a return of the
World Cup in 2010. The success of the Women's World Cup reminded
FIFA officials how lucrative the event can be in the US, even if
both the '94 and '99 championship matches ended in boiling
temperatures, decided in penalty kicks by someone with a ponytail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chivas is regal
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The MLS All-Star Game is scheduled in San Diego this week with
attendance estimates ranging from 25,000 to more than 50,000. The
attraction is not only some of the best players in the MLS, but the
exhibition involving CD Guadalajara Chivas and Universidad
Cattolica of Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Chivas is probably the most popular team in any sport in North
America, with the ability to draw huge crowds on a regular basis in
most major cities in Mexico and the US. Organizers are hoping to
attract fans from Tijuana and south. If the MLS decides to place an
expansion team in San Diego, it would be wise to set up a formal
partnership with Chivas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   United they stand
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United has officially forsaken its defense of the FA
Cup since it will be involved in the World Team Championship club
competition Jan. 5-14 in Brazil. But AXA, the insurance group which
sponsors the FA Cup, has not surrendered. It has proposed providing
costs and transportation for United's FA Cup opponents and their
fans if the game could be staged in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Another deal has been proposed in which United would withdraw
from the Worthington Cup, formerly the League Cup, instead of the
FA Cup. United coach Alex Ferguson said the team simply does not
have time to accomodate all competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, United is about to begin a tour of Australia and
China without Ferguson and midfielder David Beckham.
London-educated South African midfielder Quinton Fortune, who has
been playing with Atletico Madrid, is on the verge of joining
United. Fortune's former Cape Town club recently signed an
agreement with United, and three other players are slated for
tryouts later this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
