<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-LONGWOOD-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRASS COURTS OF LONGWOOD HAVE GROWN LUSH FOR 122 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Once in his musings, the picaresque boxing promoter
Sam Silverman wondered about Longwood Cricket Club: ``How come they
got a club for bugs?''
</P>
<P>
   Jess Cain, probably the greatest of Boston's radio voices when
he babbled on WHDH, didn't take it as seriously as Silverman.
During the August week of the long-since-fled US Doubles
Championships Jess would intone, ``The bugs are playing tennis
again out at Longwood.''
</P>
<P>
   If any current Longwood member even understands cricket, the
game, that would be a bigger upset than an 18-year-old Australian
named Lleyton Hewitt batting apart both Pete Sampras and Jim
Courier on the club's lone green hard-rock tennis court over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Cricket, a pastime known and revered by the Aussies infiltrating
Chestnut Hill for the Davis Cup bash against the United States, and
other peoples descended from the British Empire, was certainly the
reason the club was founded 122 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But a new fad, tennis, barely 4 years old, started to take over
almost immediately, in 1878. Cricket would go down in 1911, a year
before the Titanic _ an accident, incidentally, from which a
Longwood member, Dick Williams, swam away to become a Davis Cupper
himself and US champ in 1914 and 1916.
</P>
<P>
   So, Longwood Cricket Club? Even today? This, perhaps, is a
tribute to our town's devotion to changing nothing. So what's new,
really? That aged crock, the Davis Cup, is right back where it was
launched in 1900, the Cricket Club, the home base of numerous
members whose influence has long been felt in tennis. Never in
cricket.
</P>
<P>
   But Longwoodians have a sense of humor about it as illustrated
by the insect in question adorning the club flag and the polo
shirts on sale at Buddy Schultz's pro shop. Entomologists may well
identify it as the sire of Jiminy Cricket.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, crickets and grass do go together, and it is their 25
rare grass courts, fastidiously attended by groundsman Mike
Humphrey and crew, that the 900 members cherish, a kind, yet
tricky, footing enjoyed by few other clubs. They seem spectres,
clad in white, gamboling on an Elysian Field.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sod for all seasons
</P>
<P>
   On God's own sod the game began in England after it was patented
in 1874 in London by Major Walter Wingfield. If grass was good
enough for God and Wimbledon, barely-changing Longwood gladly stuck
with it, despite expensive upkeep and vulnerability to weather. A
grass court is alive and breathing, never quite the same from one
day to the next, which is part of its charm, but a maddening
feature for someone who prefers uniformity of court and bounce.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, other surfaces would appear on the 9.2-acre plot at
the corner of Route 9 and Hammond and Dunster Streets. The 13 clay
courts are popular, and the paving within the stadium appeals to
nomadic professionals. That means green slab, the Aussie-US
battleground, will also serve for the annual Longwood production,
the US Pro (Aug. 23-29), a stopover on the world-wide ATP Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Although the seats in the Longwood arena have been sold out for
months, spectators at the US-Aussie engagement will note numerous
sideshows of varying ability on adjacent lawns: members going at
it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it's nice to see the pros, the best,'' says long-time
member Z. Paul Callahan. ``But your own game is a lot more
important to you than theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, international events _ Davis Cup, Wightman Cup,
Federation Cup, national championship tournaments _ have made
Longwood's reputation across the globe, and marked it as the
fountainhead of the American game, the country's oldest tennis club
of prominence. As early as 1890 the leading Americans were checking
in for the Eastern Doubles Championships, and the following year
the Longwood Bowl tourney was established, attracting the best from
everywhere. Until 1942 the Bowl was a fixture on the Eastern
grass-court circuit when that summertime route was the most
important segment of the US season.
</P>
<P>
   Grass and amateurism ruled until 1968, the dawn of open tennis,
the integration of amateurs and pros, as prize money materialized.
Even though the Longwood Bowl faded away during World War II, the
greats continued to show up for another Longwood specialty, the US
Doubles, that ran from 1917 through 1967 with only a couple of
brief interruptions. The season climaxed with the split US
Championships, the Doubles at Longwood followed by the Singles at
Forest Hills.
</P>
<P>
   It was a better arrangement than today's because all the
foremost men and women played doubles in Boston, then turned their
attention to singles in New York. However, since the US Open
gathered everything under one umbrella in 1968, doubles, often the
more entertaining, has been practically forgotten, partaken in
largely by no-names.
</P>
<P>
   Players like Aussies Rod Laver, Roy Emerson, and John Newcombe
remember the carnival that was the US Doubles spread across the
Longwood greensward to determine titles in men's and women's
doubles, mixed doubles plus Father and Son and senior doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great show,'' says Newcombe, the Aussie Davis Cup
captain, who won in 1967 with his current lieutenant, Tony Roche.
``Unique. The only tournament in the world devoted to top-class
doubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Laver ``enjoyed watching the Father and Son and the seniors. We
didn't have anything like that in Australia then.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Van Ryn, at 93 the senior among US Davis Cuppers, says,
``Wilmer Allison and I loved going to Boston for doubles. We were
in finals six times (between 1930 and 1936) and won in 1931 and
1935. Bostonians knew their doubles teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, pairs such as Jack Kramer-Ted Schroeder, Bill
Talbert-Gardnar Mulloy, Chuck McKinley-Dennis Ralston, Stan
Smith-Bob Lutz, Roy Emerson-Fred Stolle became favorites. Titanic
survivor Dick Williams, the last of several Longwood members to win
a US male title, took it with Vinnie Richards in 1925-26. Richards
was 15 when he won with legendary Big Bill Tilden in 1918, and they
repeated in 1922-23.
</P>
<P>
   Longwoodian Sarah Palfrey won here seven times between 1935 and
1941, four of them with Alice Marble. Louise Brough and Margaret
duPont were perenn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
