<HEADLINE>
GOOD TIMES AT FRANKLIN'S CABARET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've heard of Benjamin Franklin the statesman and diplomat.
And Franklin the author and philosopher. And Franklin the inventor.
But Benjamin Franklin the cabaret star?
</P>
<P>
   Why not? In America anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   The year is 1789. The nation is new but Franklin is old, 83 to
be exact. The place is 1 Milk St., Boston, the site of his birth
and now the home of Ben Franklin's Colonial Cabaret, a joyous
evening of singing, snacking, and, especially, schmoozing with Dr.
Franklin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Franklin, portrayed accurately and lovingly by Emmy winner Bill
Meikle, is the central character in a two-act play, but the rest of
the cast is you, the audience. What Franklin says (and he always
speaks his mind) depends on what you do _ question, talk with,
laugh with, cajole, or argue with the good doctor. Thus, no two
performances are the same. Although his favorite subjects are death
and politics, topics the other night ranged from Franklin's pride
in being a printer to his misgivings about the Declaration of
Independence (``It was a declaration of war, not independence'') to
the woman who rejected his marriage proposal to why he feels the
turkey, not the eagle, should have been the nation's symbol. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meikle has been ``Frankling,'' as he puts it, for almost two
decades. During that time, we've seen his show in its various
incarnations several times and always have been entertained and
often surprised by his comments. Here are a few from the other
night: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --``There's no accounting for Rhode Island.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --``Behind every successful son-in-law, there stands an
astonished father-in-law.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --``I prayed in church _ I was praying I'd stay awake!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --While he enjoyed his years in the French court (``I was adored
. . . they called me mon cher papa''), the people there ``stank to
the high heaven. If they bathed at all, it was in perfume.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cabaret/tavern aspect of the show is not yet where Meikle
and his producer and wife, Barbara Meikle, want it to be, because
they're still seeking a licensed caterer to serve historically
accurate ``comestibles and potables.'' But there are lanterns and
checkered tablecloths and, during intermission, George Washington's
Cake (a spice cake) and Benjamin Franklin's Torte (a chocolate
concoction with raspberries _ no wonder the man had gout) for $3
each and coffee, tea, and lemonade for $1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And there is music. Some nights feature Whistling Jack Barton
(Kevin Skorupa) and Robert Stewart (Larry Young), intinerant
minstrels who perform as Poor Richard's Penny. On other nights,
Elizabeth Blanchard (Janet Ashton) sings traditional Scotch-Irish
songs and gets the audience to join in. Sometimes Franklin sings
along, too. And the other night he sang a solo: ``To Anacreon in
Heaven,'' a tune devoted to the god of wine, women, and song. You
may not recognize the words to this rowdy number but the melody
should sound familiar: This old drinking song evolved into ``The
Star Spangled Banner.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Through Sept. 4, the cabaret takes place Fridays and Saturdays
at 8 p.m. in the Great Room of the International Institute of
Boston, 1 Milk St. Tickets are $20. Call 781-648-0628 for
reservations, and ask also about colonial Boston walks and lunch
with Dr. Franklin or Abigail Adams.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Tidbits: China contains how much of the world's population:
11, 21, or 31 percent? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: There is a bakery in Salisbury, England, called Upper
Crusts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Most of my treasured memories of travel are
recollections of sitting.'' _ Robert Thomas Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Today's loopy law: Ottumwa, Iowa, forbids ``any male person . .
. to wink at any female person with whom he is unacquainted.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's contest time: Prove that you're as busy as you claim and you
just might win a trip to a Pacific paradise. 7-Eleven, the
convenience store retailer, has announced a search for the person
with the most hectic schedule in America. The winner will receive a
free trip for two to Bora Bora and will stay in the Bora Lagoon
Resort _ a perfect destination for anyone who needs to relax as
much as you do. Entrants must turn in a page from their daytimer
(showing a typical busy day) and write a brief summary explaining
why they are the busiest person in America. And if the busiest
person is too pressed for time to enter, a spouse, assistant, or
business associate can submit the entry for them. The deadline for
entries is Sept. 1, and the winner will be announced on Oct. 1. You
can find an entry form at www.7-eleven.com or send the entry to
7-Eleven ``Summer Stress Escape'' Contest, 2200 Ross Ave., Suite
4600E, Dallas, TX 75201. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of contests: Embassy Suites has announced the winners
of its third annual ``Well Traveled Luggage'' contest. Tina Winkler
of McKenzie, Tenn., won in the luggage category for her tale of a
camelskin bag bought in Saudi Arabia and carried with her for
nearly 30 years, from India to Lebanon to the United States. The
suitcase, in fact, was such a faithful friend that she gave it a
name: Haboob. Meanwhile, Christie Leal of Lawton, Okla., won in the
briefcase category for her story of an attache case that was
purchased by her father at the Fort Walters Army base exchange in
Mineral Wells, Texas, and ended up traveling the world, carrying
the secrets of a nation, because he worked in the military with
classified documents. Both winners receive a host of prizes that
include stays at Embassy Suites hotels, natch. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of luggage: We learn from the Savvy Traveler
newsletter than the Unclaimed Baggage Center of Scotsboro, Ala., is
now on line. By clicking on www.unclaimedbagge.com, you might be
able to get a good buy in someone's unclaimed cameras, designer
clothes, electronics, and goodness knows what else. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking some more of luggage: Some 99.5 percent of checked
airline luggage gets to the correct destination on time. Of the
200,000 pieces a month that don't, 8 of 10 are reunited with their
owners within 24 hours. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? 21 percent, which means that more than 1 in 5
humans lives in China. (With thanks to info(at)daytrips.com, via
faithful contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
