<HEADLINE>
STAYING IN STYLE IN EGYPT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASWAN, Egypt _ What's good enough for Agatha Christie or King
Farouk is good enough for me. So on a recent jaunt to Egypt, I put
up at the hotels where they stayed, palatial 19th-century piles.
They make an enticing alternative to the cruise down the Nile that
is most visitors' favorite way to explore Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   I stayed at three of them: the Old Cataract in Aswan; The Winter
Palace in Luxor; and the Mena House in Giza, just outside Cairo.
All fostered fantasies about turn-of-the-century Egypt, and on my
next visit to these cities that offer endless possibilities for
exploration of thousands of years of Egyptian history, I'd stay in
them all again.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Cataract, which celebrates its centennial this year, is
best-known as a setting for Agatha Christie's ``Death on the
Nile.'' This was my favorite of the three hotels, in part because
Aswan is a sleepier place than either Luxor or Giza. Not that it
lacks for attractions. Abu Simbel, the great rock temples that were
dismantled and relocated to allow the building of the Aswan Dam, is
a short plane ride away. The High Dam itself and the Philae Temple,
also rescued from drowning and moved to the island of Agilkia, are
closer; still nearer is Elephantine Island, so named because it was
a center for ivory trading in antiquity. The island lies in the
middle of the Nile, just across from the hotel. Instead of reaching
it via tourist ferry, I took a grimy public felucca _ a small
sailboat _ in the company of women clad head to toe in black. When
we reached the island, they automatically deferred to the men on
board, letting them disembark first. My blood pressure soared. It's
tough to be a feminist visiting Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the felucca-luxury scale is the one you take
from the hotel's own launch. Decked out in Arabian Nights style,
with one printed fabric over another and plump pillows to lean back
on, it is available for high tea cruises and moonlight sails.
</P>
<P>
   Diagonally across the street from the Old Cataract is the
year-old Nubia Museum, the most up-to-date in Egypt. A lavish stone
complex, it pays tribute to a people whose villages were
deliberately submerged, again to build the dam. The museum includes
both art and ethnographic exhibits, and all the wall texts and
labels are in both Arabic and English.
</P>
<P>
   As for the hotel itself, its exterior is a soft brick red,
trimmed in slate gray and white, and the building itself is low,
sprawling, and graceful. You're greeted by a male staff member
dressed in puffy pants and bright embroidered vest, looking like an
extra from ``Scheherazade,'' proffering a glass of fresh strawberry
juice. If your shoes have become dusty on the journey, there's a
free shoe-shine service, for which you sit on a throne-like affair
of dark wood inlaid with mother-of-pearl. Lining the hallways are
prints of the watercolors of David Roberts, an intrepid
19th-century visitor to Egypt, who recorded a Nile yet to be
disturbed by motorboats and half-buried temples yet to be
excavated.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Cataract's lobby is done up in Oriental style, with
scalloped arches striped in purply red and white, a plush red
banquette, and lighting fixtures with perforated metal shades that
cast lacy shadows and lend exotic glamour to a room that acts as
dark, cool sanctuary from the white heat outside. Aswan, Egypt's
southernmost city, is generally the warmest place in the country _
which makes the Old Cataract's spectacularly lovely pool all the
more welcome.
</P>
<P>
   A quartet of local musicians dressed in long embroidered
galabeias play native string and percussion instruments on the
terrace at tea time and in the restaurant for dinner. The
restaurant was inaugurated on Dec.10, 1902, the day the cornerstone
was laid for the first Aswan dam, an event attended by heads of
state from all over Europe. Designed as a Moorish hall, the room is
topped by a dome that soars 75 feet. It still enchants, as does the
cuisine, a French-Middle Eastern fusion. (The local bolty fish is
particularly recommended.)
</P>
<P>
   As for guest rooms, try for one with a balcony facing the Nile,
the perfect place for a room service breakfast. The rooms are all
different, and suites come with parquet floors, sitting rooms,
antiques, and lavish silver bibelots. As satisfying as the decor
is, the service is even better, delivered by a smiling staff eager
to make you happy. You'd have to be curmudgeonly indeed not to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the Winter Palace, you sleep across the Nile from the Valley
of the Kings, where Egyptian rulers sleep forever. The classier
guests of yore would moor their yachts right across the street,
crossing the river at their leisure to visit the astonishing array
of tombs on the West Bank, each individually carved and/ or
painted, each a mini-museum. Should you remain on the hotel side of
the river, you could spend days exploring the great temples of
Luxor and Karnak, connected by an avenue lined with sphinxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Winter Palace is a relic of colonial days, and looks it.
Spreading outward from the grand, horizontal, sand-colored facade
is a horseshoe-shaped staircase that is both welcoming and
forbidding. Inside the door is an airport-style metal detector,
reminder of tragic violence in Luxor's recent past. But pass
through the detector and you're in another world, where a cranberry
glass chandelier dips down from a ceiling with gilded beams, and a
wrought-iron balustrade lines a winding staircase. Ceramic camel
statues on that staircase remind you you're in Egypt. Under the
glass of a low coffee table in the lobby is a display of Egyptian
faience bead necklaces in turquoise and gold, an incentive to step
outside again and go shopping: Luxor is crammed with jewelry stores
of both souvenir and serious levels, and they're open until at
least 10 at night, long after the tombs and temples have closed.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's hallways are as wide as a good-sized drawing room is
long, an extravagant use of space. Along them, in addition to the
guest rooms, are a bridge room and billiard room, and a Victorian
lounge with European paintings of the mysterious East, scenes of
maidens reclining on cushions, being ogled by pashas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
