<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-GLOBE-TAYLORS &LR;      07-13 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-GLOBE-TAYLORS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TAYLOR WAY: THE COMMUNITY CAME FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It began with Charles H. Taylor, a Civil War veteran
who in 1873 agreed to help out ``for a few weeks'' as business
manager of a failing, year-old newspaper called The Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 126 years, a Taylor was at the helm of the Globe,
as the family filled the publisher's office with men linked not
just by name but by devotion to fairness, accuracy, and profits,
and by an unwavering commitment to the community.
</P>
<P>
   The line ended Monday with the announcement that Richard H.
Gilman, senior vice president of operations at The New York Times,
would become publisher of the newspaper, effective immediately. He
replaced Benjamin B. Taylor, publisher since April 1997. The move
came nearly six years after The New York Times Co. purchased the
Globe from trusts controlled by the Taylor family and the
descendants of Eben D. Jordan, who co-founded the newspaper and the
Jordan Marsh department store.
</P>
<P>
   During the family's reign, five Taylors served as publisher,
helped by other family members in numerous capacities at the
newspaper. With the staffs they built, they guided the Globe
through more than 45,000 days of wars and assassinations; the
presidencies of 24 men; women's suffrage; the Great Depression;
famous crimes and civil rights movements; moon landings and
blizzards; sporting triumphs and, this being Boston, frustrating
failures.
</P>
<P>
   While other Boston papers folded or went through cycles of birth
and death, the Taylors used a combination of journalistic quality
and business acumen to build the Globe into New England's largest
newspaper and the winner of 15 Pulitzer Prizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were a single word with which their scores of friends
would describe the Taylors, the word would be decency,'' said
Thomas Winship, the Globe's editor from 1965 to 1984. ``They care
intensely about their native city, especially its traditions of
philanthropy, politics, and sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Winship, whose father, Laurence L. Winship, was editor of the
Globe before him, recalled how the Taylors were unflagging in
support of the paper's coverage of the most vexing issues of the
day, from political corruption to civil rights to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then came the grimmest time of all for the Globe, when the
Boston school integration battle came to our front door,'' because
of the paper's support for busing, Winship said. ``Bullets were
fired into the building, a truck was overturned in Boston Harbor,
and there were reader boycotts galore. And there was never a word
of discouragement from the Taylors, never a word from the front
office to slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Taylor family, all of them, loved and encouraged action on
behalf of a more vital town _ and did they ever give all of us fun
who worked for them,'' Winship said.
</P>
<P>
   It was anything but fun in the early years, though, as Charles
Taylor worked 16-hour days to reverse the fortunes of a a newspaper
that was losing $60,000 a year and had 10 competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who had become a respected journalist after serving in
the Civil War, had a deceptively simple philosophy for his
newspaper: ``My aim has been to make the Globe a cheerful,
attractive and useful newspaper that would enter the homes as a
kindly, helpful friend of the family. . . . My ideal for the Globe
has always been that it should help men, women and children to get
some of the sunshine of life, to be better and happier because of
the Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   One non-journalism legacy of Charles Taylor was Fenway Park. He
bought the team, then known as the Boston Pilgrims, in 1904, then
built Fenway in 1912. The family sold the team to concentrate on
covering the city's institutions instead of owning them.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Taylor's three sons, Charles H. Jr., William O., and
John I., all joined the newspaper, with William becoming publisher
upon his father's death. It was a job he held from 1921 to 1955.
</P>
<P>
   William O. Taylor oversaw a difficult period in the Globe's
history, keeping the paper afloat through the Great Depression and
despite intense competition from numerous other Boston newspapers.
On the news side, he is remembered for his choice of Laurence
Winship as managing editor, a move that set the stage for the
newspaper's future success.
</P>
<P>
   William O. Taylor's death in 1955 led to the appointment of his
son William Davis Taylor as publisher. Known as Davis, he brought a
first cousin, John I. Taylor, into the publisher's office, as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they guided the newspaper into one of the most vibrant
periods of the Globe's history. In 1966 _ with Thomas Winship as
editor _ the newspaper won its first Pulitzer Prize, for exposing
the poor qualifications of a candidate for a federal judgeship
nominated by the Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Taylor took particular pride in the newspaper's _ and his
family's _ hard-won reputation for supporting fair treatment of
ethnic and racial minorities. ``I remember my grandfather telling
me when I was a kid, how back in the days when signs and classified
ads read `No Irish Need Apply,' the Globe was the only paper in
Boston to crusade against them and in favor of allowing Catholic
priests to enter the WASP-run hospitals,'' he once said.
</P>
<P>
   With Winship's prodding, the Taylor-led Globe of the late 1960s
and early 1970s was one of the first newspapers to editorialize for
the unilateral withdrawal of US troops from Vietnam, and in 1971 it
published portions of the Pentagon Papers, the Defense Department's
classified history of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Taylor retired in 1977, and his son William O. Taylor II
(known as Bill) took over as publisher. During the next 20 years,
Bill Taylor was credited with greatly enhancing the Globe's
strength as a business while offering strong and steady support for
journalistic excellence.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, he engineered the Globe's $1.04 billion sale to The New
York Times Co. in advance of the impending dissolution of the
Taylor and Jordan family trusts. Then, in April 1997, he passed the
mantle to his second cousin, Benjamin B. Taylor, the son of John I.
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Taylor, who, like his great-grandfather, Charles H.
Taylor, came to the job with strong credentials as a newsman, was
credited Monday with putting a premium on quality and integrity at
the Globe, and for his support of excellence in all areas of the
newspaper. He will remain as chairman of the Globe Newspaper
Company's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   The Taylor family legacy was memorably articulated by Louis
Lyons, author of ``Newspaper Story: One Hundred Years of The Boston
Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Their family traits have been built into the newspaper.
Unconnected with the Establishment or with established churches,
they worked and learned and lived by their own standards, which
proved a sound foundation for an enduring institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, community and business leaders marked the passing of an
era and praised the family for its contributions on many fronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Taylors stand for integrity, competence, and journalism
that was honest and to the point,'' said Mayor Thomas M. Menino.
``They had class, and they built the paper of record. You might not
agree with the Globe all the time, but you always said it had
class. That was the Taylors.''
</P>
<P>
   Menino praised the two most recent Globe publishers for their
involvement in local causes. ``You saw them out in the community,
whether it was the United Way, or the Boys and Girls Club, or
advocating for the schools, the Globe was visible and the Taylors
were visible.''
</P>
<P>
   His sentiments were echoed by Charles K. Gifford, chief
executive of BankBoston: ``From the Boston Public Library
Foundation to Big Brothers, to Globe Santa, and free jazz concerts,
the Taylor family has been an important part of this community and
has served it extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The town is better for the Taylor family having been owners of
the newspaper,'' said advertising executive Jack Connors. ``Any
number of people have taken money out of the community, but there
is a much smaller number of people who have put a lot back in as
well, and the Taylors as a family are numbered on that very short
list.''
</P>
<P>
   Said former Massachusetts governor Michael S. Dukakis: ``In the
'60s, '70s, and '80s, the Globe became an extraordinarily effective
newspaper. It was tough, it was crusading, and it didn't let up. .
. . The Taylors and Winships transformed the Globe into one of the
best newspapers in the country, a newspaper that had a huge
influence on this state and this city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're embedded in Boston history,'' said Bill Fowler,
director of the Massachusetts Historical Society. ``They aren't one
of the founding families, but they're a family that has taken on an
enormous responsibility for the community, not just with the
newspaper but also by supporting a number of charities in the
town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporations will never be families,'' Fowler said, ``and the
Taylors are a family whose legacy is integrity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
