<HEADLINE>
SETH'S `AN EQUAL MUSIC' DOESN'T RING TRUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
AN EQUAL MUSIC 
By Vikram Seth 
Broadway Books, $25, 381 pp. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vikram Seth is one of the world's best storytellers. A few years
ago, more than a million readers of ``A Suitable Boy'' put their
real lives on hold in order to surrender to Seth's characters as
they moved through the events that brought India into the modern
world without surrendering their individual values, idiosyncrasies,
and cultural traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Seth painted ``A Suitable Boy'' on a huge canvas; it has been
described as the longest novel in English since Samuel Richardson's
``Clarissa'' back in the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Seth was clearly under some pressure to write something more
practical this time. (One reader of ``A Suitable Boy'' tore her
paperback into four sections to make it portable.) What he has come
up with is a novel of merely 400 pages, ``An Equal Music.'' To his
task he has brought skill, attention to detail, and finesse of
feeling _ everything except the breath of life that animates every
page of ``A Suitable Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The milieu of the new novel is the world of classical music; in
an afterword Seth confesses, ``Music to me is dearer than speech.''
Music of various kinds plays a major role in ``A Suitable Boy,''
and Seth himself is an enthusiastic amateur Lieder singer who has
performed the major song-cycles of Schubert.
</P>
<P>
   Most novels about musicians are full of ridiculous errors of
sense and sensibility; there are a few honorable exceptions, like
Romain Rolland's ``Jean Christophe,'' Henry Handel Richardson's
``Maurice Guest,'' Rebecca West's ``The Fountain Overflows,'' or,
more recently, Nina Beberova's ``The Accompanist.'' Seth has gone
to a lot of trouble to keep his facts straight, and he doesn't make
mistakes. Some of the banter is mildly amusing _ a prissy music
critic points out a nearby composer: ``That's him over there. He's
just written a marvelous piece for baritone and vacuum cleaner.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the conversation, however, doesn't sound like the way
musicians talk; it doesn't even sound much like human speech. Seth
has always had an impeccable ear, even when compressing California
speech into the intricate stanzas of his novel in verse, ``The
Golden.'' Now he seems to be going tone-deaf. ``That lemony-jasmine
fragrance that's so dizzying comes from these little white blossoms
here,'' observes the heroine. ``You'd hardly think it, would you?''
``Oh, I thought it was you,'' responds her besotted lover.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Equal Music'' tells a love story _ basically a soap opera.
Michael Holme, second violinist of the Maggiore String Quartet,
pines for Julia McNicholl, a pianist he had loved during his
student days in Vienna and then abandoned during a crisis of
self-confidence and an orgy of self-pity. Now, years later, they
meet again and Michael is desperate to rekindle Julia's old
passion. But Julia is now married to a rich American we are
supposed to like, and they have a precocious cute-kid son who loves
the family dog. Julia has a dreadful secret, revealed early in the
novel: She's a great musician who is going deaf. She soldiers on,
performs Schubert's ``Trout'' Quintet with members of the Maggiore
in Vienna, then flees to Venice for a tumultuous, bittersweet
interlude of romance.
</P>
<P>
   This plot is on the level of Lloyd C. Douglas's ``Magnificent
Obsession,'' which reduced susceptible readers to sobs back in
1929, except that Seth's heroine is going deaf rather than blind;
the dilemma Julia faces is the one Celia Johnson quivered over in
the famous British movie weepie of the same era, ``Brief
Encounter.'' Will Julia choose love or duty?
</P>
<P>
   Seth is nothing if not industrious. He gives Michael a
working-class background, a patroness, a hobby (swimming in the
murky water's of London's Serpentine), a violin he loves as much as
Julia and that he may lose too.
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the Maggiore Quartet have monochromatic
identities and contribute subsidiary complications _ Piers, the
first violinist, is gay; his sister, Helen, the violist, has taken
up with someone from the field of early music. ``He's part of an
outfit called something Antiqua,'' Piers observes, ``he plays a
baroque fiddle and wears sandals and sports a beard: you get the
idea.'' There's a pushy manager, a dying violin teacher, a violin
maker and repairer, an eccentric record company executive named
Ysobel to fill in the background. There is considerable information
about deafness, and longtime record collectors will cherish the
glimpse of the dusty shelves and helpful service of Harold Moore's
shop, off Oxford Street.
</P>
<P>
   Vienna and Venice fulfill their roles admirably, and so does
London. But the people and their dilemmas sound manufactured, not
real; they are constructions, pieces of a puzzle, and incapable of
surprising us, the way the characters of ``A Suitable Boy''
repeatedly do. Michael, the first-person narrator, is truly
insufferable in his humorless, snivelling self-absorbtion; he is
not a person any reader will want to spend 400 pages in the company
of, and the irresponsible Julia isn't much more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Michael, on the verge of collapse again, daring to enter
Schubert's mind. ``But it was the year I walked to Haydn's grave,
it was the year I died; and the earth took my syphillis-riddled
flesh, my typhoid-ravaged guts, my vainly loving heart many times
around the sun before my quintet for strings was heard by human
ears.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with ``An Equal Music'' is that Seth has applied
sensitivity and intellect to the material of popular fiction that
doesn't require them, the kind of fiction that intellect interferes
with. Seth has worked too hard to write the kind of predictable
bestseller that can be produced by instinct alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
