<HEADLINE>
HELLO, NEW BRUNSWICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Brunswick has to be one of the hidden treasures of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   So close, yet so unknown by most Americans. For many, myself
included, it was the drive-through province on the way to Prince
Edward Island or Nova Scotia. And yet, its scenery and attractions
are the equal, and in some cases more dramatic, than those of the
other Atlantic provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe now that New Brunswick has prepared a colorful and easy to
follow ``Fundy Coastal Scenic Drive Guide,'' travelers will
discover all that this province, a seven-hour drive from Boston,
has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Along the route, visitors can witness the world's highest and
wildest tides, see reversing falls, explore sea caves, or see the
famed Hopewell Rocks, towering free-standing sea stacks that rise
off the ocean floor. Visitors can wander about them at low tide.
</P>
<P>
   The drives include opportunities to hike, visit Campobello,
where President Franklin D. Roosevelt summered, see whales, visit
beautiful gardens, take one-day adventures, explore covered
bridges, go birding, and more _ all at low cost, espcially now that
the American dollar buys almost 40 percent more just across the
border.
</P>
<P>
   New Brunswick is worth the drive. For more information, call
888-364-4444.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Upcoming
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did you ever hear of Bell Buckle, Tenn.? If you were a veteran
of World War II, you just might have visited this town. Bell Buckle
was where troops training at Camp Forest conducted maneuvers. Now,
the folks of Bell Buckle want you back for their Veterans Reunion &AMP;
Celebration July 17-18. Jeeps and tanks will again rumble through
the town, and there will be reenactments of battles, USO shows with
music of the times, and a lot more. Proceeds will benefit the
restoration of the First Baptist Church, which is listed on the
National Register of Historic Places. For details, call
931-389-6020.
</P>
<P>
   Barbados is celebrating its annual Crop Over Festival through
Aug. 2. Dating to the 18th century, Crop Over marked the final
reaping of the season's sugar cane harvest. The festival now
celebrates the cultural traditions of the island with parades, food
festivals, crafts, and parties. Barbados also is offering a Super
Saver program with special prices during the festival. For
information, call the Barbados Tourism Authority at 888-BARBADOS or
visit www.barbados.org.
</P>
<P>
   The official 30th anniversary of the Apollo 11 Mission,
America's first moon landing, will be celebrated at the Kennedy
Space Center Visitor Complex in Florida July 16-17. Among
highlights will be former astronauts giving briefings, and a 1960s'
pops concert. For information, call 407-452-2121 or visit
www.KennedySpaceCenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Anguilla will celebrate its 25th Summer Festival July 30-Aug. 8.
The festival festures dancing, pageants, parades, contests, and
foods. It all coincides with Anguilla's National Boat Racing Week.
For information, call 800-553-4939.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Handy outings
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sister Clymena's chicken pie and Sister Mary's zesty carrots are
just two of the treats awaiting diners at the Hancock Shaker
Village candlelight dinners Saturday evenings July 17 though Oct.
16. The program begins at 5 p.m. and includes a tour of the
village, along with a brief introduction to Shaker history and
beliefs, and 170 years of life at Hancock. For reservations or
information, call 413-443-0188.
</P>
<P>
   Route 1 in Rhode Island connects eight remarkable private
gardens for the South County leg of Gardens Open for Blithewold, a
series of garden tours benefiting Blithewold Mansion, Gardens, and
Arboretum. The July 24 tour is $30 a person. For information, call
401-253-2707.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know a forgery when you see one? At the Springfield
(Mass.) Museum of Fine Arts now through Aug. 22, a special
exhibition, ``Treaures of Deceit: Archaeology and the Forger's
Craft'' will show you how it's done. Visitors are encouraged to
participate through interactive labeling, ultraviolet light
displays, X-ray photos, and magnifying glasses. For information,
call 413-263-6800.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont Quilt Festival July 16-18 at Norwich University in
Northfield, Vt. will feature antique quilts, and special exhibits
on 20th century quilts and ``Quilts from the Heart.'' For
information, call 802-485-7092.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Weekending
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Charles Hotel in Cambridge, Mass. is featuring special
weekends this summer based around the John Singer Sargent exhibit
at the Boston Museum of Fine Arts, and a weekend based on Boston's
new Literary Trail, which highlights the literary culture of
Boston, Cambridge, and Concord. For details, call 800-882-1818.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems to be holding a film festival featuring top
flimmakers, but in Phoenix, N.Y. (just outside Syracuse), they're
planning the first B-Movie Film Festival Aug. 28-29. B-films are
low-budget ones that ``rival or surpass big-budget mainstream
pictures,'' according to the promoters. For details, call
315-454-5608 or visit www.b-movie.com/hof/fest.html.
</P>
<P>
   Learn how to be a chef via the Epicurean Escape package at the
Colonnade Hotel in Boston. The weekend package offers two tickets
for a Williams-Sonoma chef demonstrations at Copley Place, just a
short walk from the Colonnade. The package features cooking
sessions on July 25 and Aug. 15. The $199 price includes
accommodations, breakfasts, taxes, and gratuities. For information,
call 800-962-3030.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lights of LIberty
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lights of Libery, a sound and light show, is giving visitors to
Philadelphia a high-tech way to immerse themselves in the drama of
the American Revolution as it happened and where it happened. The
60-minute show begins and ends at the PECO Energy Liberty Center.
Participants are then taken along past some of America's most
important buildings on which five-story images are projected. The
show runs nightly at dusk with groups leaving every 10 minutes.
Tickets are $18 for adults, less for seniors, students, and
children. For reservations, call 215-LIBERTY or visit
www.lightsofliberty.org. The show goes through October.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Flu warning
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported
nearly 400 people became ill from the flu in Alaska and Canada's
Yukon Territory. There have been no deaths, the Reuters report
said, but last summer almost 5,000 people on land and sea tours
became ill from the flu. Researcher said the influenza may become
more widespread because of increased volume of tourist travel
between May and September. The CDC said people ages 65 or older
should be aware of the risk and symptoms of the flu and should ask
their doctors about carrying antiviral medication to prevent or
treat influenza.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Canoe adventure
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The legends of Lewis and Clark will come alive on canoe voyages
of discovery on Montana's Upper Missouri River. Participants travel
on modern, 34-foot voyageur canoes, which replicate those used by
early fur traders. Prices begin at $850. For information, call
River Odysseys West at 800-451-6034.
</P>
