<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8148 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIAMSBURG-SLAVERY-     07-13 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMSBURG-SLAVERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLONIAL WILLIAMSBURG SKITS CAST NEW LIGHT ON PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSBURG, Va. _ Rain cascaded outside his quarters as a
young slave, with bloody gashes on his back, lay whimpering on a
straw bed. Through the misty glow of candlelight, onlookers
swallowed hard. Some turned to wipe away tears.
</P>
<P>
   This is the new Colonial Williamsburg, the popular
Revolutionary-era tourist attraction, far different from the one
that used to tell a cozy tale of America's courageous fight for
independence from the British.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enslaving Virginia,'' a program that opened in March, uncovers
the ugly story of human suffering beneath the glossy tale of heroic
patriots. The frank reenactment of slavery during the Colonial
period unveils the shameful dark side of Patrick Henry, George
Washington and other slave owners.
</P>
<P>
   In these realistic, first-person portrayals of slavery, where
costumed actors play slaves and slave owners, visitors _
particularly children _ often find themselves unexpectedly drawn
into the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a skit where a slave patrol violently breaks up a
group of slaves, one boy shrieked, ``Let him go!'' while other
tourists murmured, ``Oh my God.'' In past performances, some
visitors have attacked the actors portraying slave owners.
</P>
<P>
   Younger visitors, some outfitted in tri-cornered hats, keep a
close lookout for the slave patrol who circle the park in search of
runaway slaves. The youngsters break free from their parents to
warn the slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter, Peter,'' cried 10-year-old J.D. Touchton, as he
scurried to one of the key slave characters in the unfolding skit.
``Be careful, be careful. The slave patrol is coming. They're
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The Enslaving Virginia program is the first time such in-depth
and personal narratives of slaves have been used in Colonial
Williamsburg's 79-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole program is full of contradictions,'' said Christy
Matthews, the director of interpretive planning. ``People
constantly have to reevaluate the role of slavery within a war that
was about freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The new focus has evoked strong emotions from both blacks and
whites visiting the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little, white old ladies have come up to me and apologized for
being white and for the things their ancestors have done to the
slaves,'' said Karen Sutton, an actress who portrays a slave.
``Black folks have said that a lot of this still hits home to them.
They cry, and sometimes I cry along with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously, slavery was portrayed in small snippets at Carter's
Grove, a reconstructed plantation six miles east of the main
grounds. The park decided to develop a focus on race after a 1994
reenactment of a slave auction drew criticism as a degradation of
African-American history.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial Williamsburg has actively recruited black actors to
portray the slaves, and they now comprise about 10 percent of the
nearly 600 actors.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Broken Spirit,'' a new play that opened last weekend, a
young slave, Kofi, is whipped for trying to run away. The audience
stood in the pouring rain on opening night Saturday listening to
the chilling sounds of a whip cracking on Kofi's back.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of plot twists, the play bares the realities of
masters who kept young female slaves as mistresses, and slaves who
turned against each other to win the favor of their owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slaves made up a de facto family, but they were clearly not
homogenous,'' said Matthews, who wrote and directed the play that
sold out on its first night. ``I wanted to show the complexity in
the lives of slaves, the struggles they went through, and what they
did so their spirits would not be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   While many whites who watched the performance said they were
shocked by the brutality that slaves endured, many blacks said they
were familiar with such incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are stories that have been passed down to me. I know it
well,'' said Opeline Davis, 72, a Williamsburg resident, who
brought her 14-year-old granddaughter to the play. ``Lots of white
people don't know these stories. The details aren't taught in
schools. You can't read it in a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Such realistic portrayals have resonated strongly within some
black visitors. According to park officials, some have walked away
from the more graphic scenes in the skits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, it's too real for people. Slavery's so hard to talk
about. And then to see it play out in front of you when you know
it's happened to your great-grandmother,'' Davis said, shaking her
head.
</P>
<P>
   In the sweltering heat last week, onlookers wiped tears from
beneath their sunglasses as Sarah Southall, a young slave, told how
her family was torn apart when her master sold her 4-year-old
daughter to another slave owner.
</P>
<P>
   The day is Nov. 17, 1775. The royal governor, Lord Dunmore, has
issued a proclamation that offers slaves the possibility of
freedom: Fight for the British crown and be released from slavery.
Behind Raleigh's Tavern, Southall, who is pregnant again, argues
with her husband, Peter, about running away to fight for British.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can think about is how my ancestors must have stood out
here in this heat picking cotton or tobacco on this same land 200
years ago,'' said Valetrius Garmon, 9, of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   When the slave patrol harassed the actor portraying Peter
Southall by forcing him to remove his shoes and empty his bag,
Nahim Shakoor, 58, of Atlanta whispered, ``Compare this field to a
ghetto today. The same thing still goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   While many blacks, like Shakoor, draw present-day comparisons,
many whites are learning a new chapter of history. ``I never
realized how difficult the lives of slaves were,'' said Terry
Blevins, 41, from Hudsonville, Mich. ``I knew slaves must have
endured terrible hardships, but I never knew to what extent.''
</P>
<P>
   Park officials estimate that African-Americans comprise about 4
percent of the 1 million annual visitors. But at the several
performances last week, nearly half of the audience was black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my children to honor slaves, the way Jewish people
honor the people of the Holocaust,'' said Mikalah Holt, 34, from
Atlanta, who brought her children, ages 9 and 5. ``We still see the
legacy that slavery left us. We still have white people names. My
children need to honor their past, so they can understand how
they've come to where they are, and so they can know how to go
about in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
