<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8156 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FEMALE-FIREFIGHTER     07-13 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FEMALE-FIREFIGHTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN FIREFIGHTER CLIMBS LADDER IN NYC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rochelle ``Rocky'' Jones never thought of becoming a
firefighter when she was growing up in Brooklyn. Her father was a
fireman, but it was a pointless dream to follow in his footsteps.
Women were not allowed in the Fire Department of New York City. Nor
were they as late as 1978, when Jones was 20 and, on a friend's
dare, took the entrance exam and passed.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones, now a 17-year veteran on the force, has been promoted
to captain, the first female to achieve that rank in the city's
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a proud day,'' she said at her promotion ceremony
recently. To her fellow firewomen, she proclaimed, ``It shows . . .
we are here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in large numbers, though.
</P>
<P>
   There are over 11,000 firefighters in New York City, of whom
only 36, 3/10 of 1 percent, are women.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, 2 percent of professional firefighters nationwide
are women: about 5,000 out of 250,000. The share reaches as high as
8 percent in San Francisco, 15 percent in Madison, Wis., and
one-third of the recruits coming into the department in Dade
County, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   (Even Boston's fire department, very rigid by most standards,
has 12 women in a force of 1,585, or, in percentage terms, three
times as many as New York's.)
</P>
<P>
   A spattering of cities, most prominently New Orleans, still have
no female firefighters, noted Terese Floren, director of Women in
the Fire Service, a Madison-based organization that tallies these
statistics. But of those cities that have some, she said, ``None
has as low a percentage as New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones felt the burden from the moment she entered her first
engine house as one of the first 40 women ever to join the force,
in 1982. ``Oh, they did not want me,'' she said with a laugh,
sitting in a room at department headquarters, between sessions of
her captain's-training courses.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever physically harassed her, even during night duty,
when she slept in the same bunkroom as all the men. ``But,'' she
said, ``they cursed me, they called me names.''
</P>
<P>
   More painful still, she recalled, was ``the isolation _ just
trying to be accepted by the guys, having to prove yourself day in,
day out, for a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   She hauled hoses and ran into burning buildings with the rest of
them, but she always felt as though she was being tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you were asked to do something,'' she said, ``there
were lots of people standing around to see if you could do it _ and
hoping you couldn't. If somebody asked you, `How many lengths of
hose will we need?,' everybody went silent to hear your answer and
hoped you got it wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones knew she had stepped onto this turf in a less than
friendly fashion, through the force of a federal court order. In
1978, the year she took the entrance exam after a group of her male
friends told her they were taking it and dared her to come along,
the Fire Department had just decided to let women try out. However,
it also revised the physical part of the exam to make it virtually
impossible for women to get in.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put in things like a standing broad-jump and a one-arm
bent-elbow hang,'' Jones recalled, chuckling. ``You know, what does
this have to do with anything? It was all tests of upper-body
strength, which women have less of.''
</P>
<P>
   So, 41 women who passed the written exam filed a class-action
suit, claiming the new physical discriminated against them. A
federal judge agreed and, in consultation with a physical
therapist, ordered the adoption of a new test.
</P>
<P>
   Jones did not even tell her retired firefighter-father, Lester,
that she applied for the job until the suit was filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty surprised,'' he recalled, sitting in the home in
Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn, where Jones grew up with her three
sisters, all of whom were given boys' nicknames: Rocky for
Rochelle, Danni for Danielle, Mike for Michelle, and, briefly, Gus
for Giselle.
</P>
<P>
   Her father retired, after 21 years, when Rochelle was 11. ``I
never discussed my job much,'' he said. ``It's nothing you talk
about with your family, all the danger.''
</P>
<P>
   But after she told him what she had done _ and after he looked
at the revised physical and satisfied himself that it was a fair
test of what a firefighter needed to do _ he encouraged her to
stick with it. Still, her father understood why so many firemen
resisted her appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a stranger coming into your home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Cannon, professor of history at St. Peter's College in
Jersey City and the author of scholarly books on the New York Fire
Department, elaborated on this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a deep-seated sense of cultural continuity,'' he said
of the department. ``It's a culture of male domesticity. For a
woman to come in there _ sure, lots of guys are going to feel that
as an intrusion, a violation.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Fire Department was professionalized just as the
big wave of Irish immigration hit the Northeastern shores. In
several cities, including Boston and New York, Irishmen filled the
new slots of firemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They set the tone, the style of the trade for decades to
come,'' Cannon said. Even now, probably the majority of
firefighters in the city are Irish Catholics with conservative
views on cultural change.
</P>
<P>
   Floren called New York's fire department ``one of the more
traditional organizations in the country,'' adding, ``This goes not
just for women. It was one of the last departments to adopt
advances in protective gear. Not 20 years ago, they wouldn't wear
respirators _ it wasn't `manly' to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this feeds into a mystique about firefighters _ prevalent
in nearly every city but perhaps most of all in New York, which has
so many firefighters and, because of the age and height of its
buildings, so many fires.
</P>
<P>
   Last year alone, according to official figures, New York City
firefighters put out 381,537 fires, more than 1,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   When a firefighter dies, the daily tabloids give him a full-page
hero's spread, the funeral is immense, and every politician in town
comes to pay honor.
</P>
<P>
   The nickname for New York's police department, ``New York's
Finest,'' is often pronounced these days with a grain of irony, but
the Fire Department's moniker, ``New York's Bravest,'' is uttered
with universal sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I like to explain it,'' said Jones, ``is when we show
up, we make things better. That's all we do _ or that's all we're
seen doing. We're not like the police in that way. You know,'' she
added with a laugh, ``we don't stop kids and frisk them for
matches.''
</P>
<P>
   Cannon elaborated: ``A firefighter's workspace is hidden from
the public. Nobody knows what goes on in a firehouse. It adds to
the mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   It also explains, in part, how the profession could remain cut
off from the waves that shook the rest of American society.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's life as a firefighter improved in 1984, when she was
transferred from an engine company in Brooklyn to a ladder company
in Staten Island, the most suburban of the city's boroughs _ more
laid-back, less intense, fewer fires. That year, she met the man
who became her husband, a rescue firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman joined her company in 1988, the first time she had
not been the only one in the house. She advanced to lieutenant in
1994, the first woman in the city to do so.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, she believes, she was treated no differently
than any other officer. ``People who never spoke to me in the old
days see me now and say, `Hey, Rock!'''
</P>
<P>
   She paused and laughed: ``I pretend like I don't remember.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
