<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8158 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     07-13 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER-LONG CELEBRATION TO FOCUS ON INDIAN-FIGHTING BUFFALO
SOLDIERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Friday, just as the workweek came to an end and hundreds of
Abilene children and their parents went to the public library for a
weekend supply of reading material, they witnessed the unlikely
sight of Buffalo Soldiers sauntering across the concrete roadways
into town.
</P>
<P>
   OK, they weren't exactly sauntering and it wasn't an entire
regiment of the black riders or anything like that. It wasn't even
a good sized squad. But Ken Pollard cut a striking figure decked
out in his blue and gold uniform. He came armed not only with the
weaponry of the fierce Indian fighters he represented, but also
with the knowledge of how important the Buffalo Soldiers were to
Texas and the rest of the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   He knows how the Buffalo Soldiers were overlooked in much of
history, and as a supervisor for the Texas Parks and Wildlife
Department's community service program, he has taken it upon
himself to right that serious wrong.
</P>
<P>
   With a little help from the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   July has been designated as Texas Buffalo Soldier Heritage
Month. It is part of a summer-long celebration of educational
programs and events. The Heritage Trail, as the total program is
being called, is designed to promote the history of the Buffalo
Soldiers, vaqueros, African-American cowboys, American Indians and
frontier women of Texas during the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Parks and Wildlife Department says this is the first
time in history that the Texas Legislature has passed legislation
for a cultural group. An African-American support group called The
Soldiers in Blue Committee initiated the resolution that proclaims
July as Texas Buffalo Soldiers Month and July 28 as Capitol Salute
Day, when youth from across Texas will travel to Austin to recount
the Buffalo Soldier history. Texas is the only state to honor the
Buffalo Soldier with a monthlong celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Soldiers we hear most about were in the 9th and 10th
U.S. Cavalry, established in the summer of 1866. Originally, there
also were six infantry regiments, but they were later consolidated
into two units _ the 24th and 25th U.S. Infantry.
</P>
<P>
   They were, by what accounts we've been able to see, a fiercely
independent and dedicated group of soldiers. They got some of the
toughest, most isolated duties in campaigns against the Comanche,
Apache, Cheyenne, Kiowa, Sioux and Arapaho. It was the Plains
Indians who gave them the name Buffalo Soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   They fought in the Spanish-American War, World War II and in the
beginning stages of Korea. The last unit was deactivated in 1951.
They always fought a battlefield enemy, and the enemy of prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   The New Handbook of Texas says popular interest in the Buffalo
Soldiers began to grow during the 1960s with John Ford's film
``Sergeant Rutledge,'' but if there was a surge in interest, it
soon dried up. A greater influence was the work of Fort Worth
artist Burl Washington, whose detailed watercolors show a strong,
lasting western character.
</P>
<P>
   Books such as Elmer Kelton's ``The Wolf and the Buffalo'' also
deepened interest in the Buffalo Soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   With the efforts of people like Pollard, that interest is not
likely to go away. By the time he left Abilene, a street had been
named for the Buffalo Soldiers, and hundreds of kids were
scrambling for books and literature on the American heroes.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
