<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLST-WOMEN-ART-B     07-13 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLST-WOMEN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN BECOMING BIG-LEAGUE PLAYERS IN SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It seems like everyone carrying a microphone or a
camera in town this week wants a piece of Leslie Sullivan's time.
</P>
<P>
   As vice president of broadcasting and new media development for
Major League Baseball, Sullivan presides over the telecasts of the
All-Star Game, the Home Run Derby and other related events. And,
among other things, ESPN and Fox ask her where they can set up
their cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Francis is not having much down time, either. As vice
president of marketing for Major League Baseball, she is in charge
of more than a half-dozen events related to the All-Star Game _ all
of which are intended to help baseball address the crucial issue of
competing successfully for America's leisure time.
</P>
<P>
   And as vice president of special events for Major League
Baseball, Marla Miller is absolutely up to her eyeballs in work.
Miller is in charge of the whole affair, making sure that this
annual, gala festival, so crucial to burnishing the brand of Major
League Baseball, delivers all that the hoopla portends.
</P>
<P>
   On the field and in the dugouts at Fenway Park it will be all
men in uniform, the stars of the game. But anyone spending any time
behind the scenes around Boston this week knows that the All-Star
Game clearly is not just another ``guy thing.'' Women are playing
key roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent years, as sports have become more professional and
more corporate _ and less reliant on just the old boys' networks _
they reflect more and more the increasing diversity of the
corporate world,'' said Mary Jo Kane, director of the Tucker Center
for Research on Girls and Women Sports, at the University of
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old boys' network has not entirely disappeared, certainly.
But what you are seeing at the All-Star Game is how many women are
very much in place, and in some positions of real power, in the
business of major sports in this country,'' Kane said.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not just the front office of Major League Baseball.
The list of women playing key roles this All-Star Game week seems
as long as one of Mark McGwire's home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Both executives in charge of public relations for the two
leagues are women: Katy Feeney for the National League and Phyllis
Merhige in the American League. In addition to helping mete out
punishment for on-field disciplinary problems during the rest of
the year, Feeney and Merhige played key roles in helping All-Star
team managers gather information on which players to select.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Collet, a marketing communications consultant for the John
Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., has played a major role in the
coordination of the FanFest, which 80,000 people are likely to
visit by closing time.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Stein is under contract with Major League Baseball as
one of the key producers of FanFest.
</P>
<P>
   Colette A.M. Phillips, president and chief executive of Colette
Phillips Communication, is the official public relations firm for
the Boston Red Sox and FanFest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feedback we're getting is that the event has gotten a lot
of exposure,'' said Phillips, who started her company 13 years ago.
``We've got a good track record, but this will really expand our
sports marketing and event operations.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the women have different stories about how they arrived
at high-profile positions in the traditionally testosterone-laden
world of sports. Some have worked in the sports business for 25
years, starting when there truly were no other women around. Others
are more recent arrivals, grateful to the pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women in general feel that when they are interested in
something they can pursue it, whether that's sports or not,''
Miller said last week, while juggling in-coming phone calls.
``There's a lot more women around than I saw when I started out 10
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller pursued a career in sports management, about 15 years
ago, after her journalism degree at New York University led to a
job at a magazine group that did not live up to expectations.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 years ago, Mehrige's one-time boss, Lee MacPhail, the
former American League president, realized her value as a secretary
and kept giving her more responsibilities and, eventually, jobs and
titles commensurate with her contribution. She worked with Bob
Fishel, a premier public relations official with the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Bob was so well thought of, because he had such an
enormous reputation in the game, there was a sense that if Bob
liked me, I must be okay,'' Mehrige said.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan began her career at CBS Sports in New York with the
executive producer Eddie Einhorn. When Einhorn and Jerry Reinsdorf
bought the Chicago White Sox in 1981, Sullivan moved to Chicago as
manager of broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   She helped start up SportsVision, one of the early, regional
sports networks, that eventually became Sports Channel, Chicago.
From there, it was a short jump to running broadcast and new media
at Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   When Francis realized she was a shot or two short of being a
tennis professional, and that being a human resources administrator
for an insurance company was not her love, she said she returned to
school for a master's degree in marketing with a dream of working
in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told by some of my counselors that, `You probably want
to take that job with that consumer packaged goods company because
women don't really work in sports and if you do it will probably be
some low-level coordinator or secretary,' '' Francis said.
``Luckily, I didn't listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the women of baseball and observers agree that the glass
ceiling for women in sports is at the operations level, where few
women are involved in personnel decisions affecting the athletes or
the performances of the teams.
</P>
<P>
   There are but a few women scouts in Major League Baseball, and
only Marge Schott, of the Cincinnati Reds, and Wendy Selig-Prieb,
of the Milwaukee Brewers, own teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the arguments I keep hearing is that, `Well, women
didn't play the sport,' '' said Lisa Masteralexis, head of the
sports management program at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I can tell you there are a lot of men running the
operations who didn't play the sport either.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the lessons of the Women's World Cup Soccer
phenomenon is is that women can play the games,'' Kane said, ``and
they can bring that knowledge to the operations side of things.''
Kane said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
