<HEADER>
A8175 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSIE-KIDS-TEX     07-13 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSIE-KIDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE A TOUGH-TALKING COMIC, SHE NOW USES HER STAR POWER TO CRUSADE
FOR KIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A kid walks onto a talk-show set.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Jarrett Mynear clambers into the chair next to host
Rosie O'Donnell, who asks him to tell the audience what he does.
</P>
<P>
   He has a business. He delivers toys to patients at his local
children's hospital in Kentucky. Every other Tuesday. Three carts'
worth.
</P>
<P>
   He first saw the idea in a Seattle hospital, he says, when he
was getting treatment for one of the four cancers that he's had.
``That had always helped me to look forward to something, and I
wasn't quite as scared,'' Jarrett says, ``and I thought maybe it
would help some of the other kids who are really scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett says the donated toys are stacked up in his family room.
His aunts are working on getting some storage bins for the
basement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody can, we need somebody to donate a warehouse,'' he
says, raising both arms in the air and smiling, making the audience
giggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, guess what, Jarrett,'' Rosie says. ``I got news for you.
We're gonna get you the warehouse _ and Toys R Us is going to stock
it with as many toys as you need!''
</P>
<P>
   It's just another day in Studio 8G at Rockefeller Center, where
dreams come true and kids, increasingly, come first. As the
syndicated ``Rosie O'Donnell Show'' began its third season last
fall, promoters noted that the focus would expand beyond celebrity
adoration. Viewers could expect ``inspirational tales,'' kids
speaking out on topics, and parenting advice.
</P>
<P>
   The new family focus mirrored a shift in Rosie's priorities. In
1995, the former smart-mouthed, too-tough, stand-up comedian
adopted a little boy named Parker and suddenly began showing the
world her softer side.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what almost everyone in the world knows about Rosie
O'Donnell: Her show won the 1999 daytime Emmy for Outstanding Talk
Show, and she won the award for Outstanding Host. She makes, at
last report, $4 million a season. She's been in the movies,
including ``Harriet the Spy,'' ``A League of Their Own'' and ``The
Flintstones.'' She founded a Chub Club for people who want to lose
weight, but she's the self-professed ``biggest failure.'' Her mom
died when she was 10, and she was 14 or 15 before she heard an
adult tell her that he or she loved her. She's not a very good
singer.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to Rosie than that. As Rosie's rising
professional star has shot out of sight in the past few years,
she's become an expert at using her celebrity power for good _ and
her efforts are almost always directed at children.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 not-so-well-known reasons to love Rosie.
</P>
<P>
   1. In Rosie's world, being your own flawed self is a good thing.
Take what she has to say about her role as Terk in Disney's
``Tarzan'': ``When they told me I was going to be a gorilla, I
spent three weeks living in the zoo. No, I didn't do anything.
Because I feel I have innate gorilla tendencies. When they showed
me the drawings, it looked like me. Honestly. It's got a pot belly,
it's got a little double chin, it's got big hair. And you know,
it's round. I thought, `OK, I'll just be myself.' ''
</P>
<P>
   2. Rosie doesn't leave the house without a Sharpie. Paula
Kaplan, vice president of talent for the Nickelodeon network who
has worked with Rosie for years, says the Sharpie is a priority
because kids come right up to Rosie wherever she is, and they want
her autograph. She doesn't want to let them down.
</P>
<P>
   3. Rosie is a children's crusader. In February 1997, Rosie
founded the For All Kids Foundation, which serves as a
clearinghouse, granting awards to nonprofit organizations dedicated
to helping children through child care, education, health care and
other special programs. In the first fiscal year, the foundation
gave more than $1.5 million to charities. Seed money came largely
through Rosie's personal efforts: Proceeds from her ``Kids Are
Punny'' book brought in more than $1.7 million. Last December in
New York, her first benefit for the foundation raised $3.2 million.
This spring, Rosie also launched some auctions on eBay, selling,
among other items, ``Star Wars'' collectibles signed by George
Lucas. The site raised $686,439 to benefit For All Kids.
</P>
<P>
   4. She has a $20,000 playroom for her children next to her
office. But when she talks about life with her kids _ Parker, now
4, and Chelsea Belle, almost 2 _ she sounds like Everymom. The
other day, she was telling Parker that she was tired of him not
answering back when she talks to him. ``You know what, Mom,'' he
said. ``You're insane.'' In this month's ``Marie Claire'' magazine,
Rosie says that one time recently, Parker walked in while she was
taking a shower, and she said, ``Am I ever going to get any
privacy?'' To which he replied, ``Apparently not.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Her agent won't cough up a complete list of Rosie's
fund-raising efforts _ which are tremendous _ because ``Rosie's not
like that.'' Among other accomplishments, this year Rosie has:
sponsored a Chub Club 5K run in Central Park with proceeds going to
the Aubrey Fund for pediatric cancer research; co-hosted
Nickelodeon's Big Help-a-thon; agreed to host a fund-raiser gala
for Carnival Cruise Line with proceeds going to a children's
charity; teamed with Martha Stewart to decorate a Habitat for
Humanity home; autographed innumerable items, including her Rosie
O'Donnell doll, for charity auctions; and given away literally
warehouses full of food and toys and other goods on her show _ ``A
lot of times the money comes from (Rosie's) own pocket,'' says
Rosie's spokeswoman, Jennifer Glaisek. Rosie is popular as a host
for benefits, says Glaisek, who has been with her at auctions,
because ``she is able to force people into giving money.''
</P>
<P>
   6. Rosie is not afraid of Slime or Gak. Rosie has been slimed at
least twice. First time: Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards in 1997,
in her first year as solo host. Most recently: April 28 on a Rosie
show devoted to the Nickelodeon awards. She also introduced Bill
Cosby to Gak on that show. It was about time.
</P>
<P>
   7. She's not afraid of what people might say about her. On a
Nickelodeon special about teens and body images, ``The Body Trap''
(1996), Rosie said that whenever anyone says anything that hurts
her feelings, she thinks of what Glinda, the good witch, said in
``The Wizard of Oz:'' ``You have no power here. Off before someone
drops a house on you, too.''
</P>
<P>
   8. Like all seasoned moms, she can quickly become a mother bear.
When 17-year-old Britney Spears came on Rosie's show to promote her
new CD, ``Baby One More Time,'' Rosie gave the singer less than 15
seconds before letting her have it for wearing an inappropriately
revealing shirt for her performance at the Kids' Choice Awards a
couple of weeks before. ``I don't want to see you in that shirt
again unless you're wearing a vest,'' Rosie said. ``I'm so glad
you're bringing this up!'' Spears said. ``I was humiliated!'' She
mumbles something about how it was colder than she expected.
``Yeah,'' Rosie said. ``It was cold. Things happen. The point is,
promise me next time you wear the white shirt, you put a cute
little vest over it ... I'll ground you. Don't make me ground you,
because you're a sweetheart of a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   9. Rosie insists she's not a hero or a role model for single
mothers. ``I'm very, very rich,'' is what Rosie says, according to
Glaisek. ``The real heroes are the mothers that got themselves off
welfare.'' Rosie's hero? Marian Wright Edelman, founder and
president of the Children's Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   10. Despite what she says, Rosie is a role model for mothers and
kids _ one of the precious few on whom parents and children can
agree.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
