<P>
   SUMMER-MELONS (Undated) _ Melons are the aristocrats of summer
fruit, their cool elegance and exotic lushness perfuming dishes
with the essence of a flower garden on a perfect afternoon. The
charming palette of summer colors spans the spectrum from the
creamy white flesh of the honeydew to the brassy firecracker red of
the watermelon. In sorbets and chilled soups, in cocktails and
salads, or simply eaten out of hand, melons are wonderful
restoratives for this long hot summer; with recipes. By Marian
Burros.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN-EQUIPMENT (Undated) _ Melon ballers, and the many things
they can be used for. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ More than a few American winemakers are
obsessed with the riesling grape. With good reason: it is arguably
the finest white grape variety in the world. In this country, which
mostly means California, riesling produces wines that are
attractive, friendly, uncomplicated and easy to like. These are
good qualities in an Airedale, not necessarily in white wine. By
Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-CHEESE (Undated) _ The rule of red wine with cheese is as
revered as the one dictating no wine with cereal. But in a season
when chilled white wine seems so appealing, one of those rules
demands to be broken, and not just as a sign of surrender to the
weather. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
