<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S OPPOSITION PARTIES NEED TO COOPERATE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIAS CASTILLO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDWOOD CITY, Calif. _ Mexico more than ever, needs to boot out
the corrupt and authoritarian Institutional Revolutionary Party, or
PRI, the massive political machine that has simultaneously ruled
over that country for 70 years and been the main cause of its
massive poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent gubernatorial elections in the states of Mexico
and Nayarit clearly show that the task of ousting the PRI will be a
Herculean one.
</P>
<P>
   In the state of Mexico, which skirts the massive megalopolis of
Mexico City, the PRI edged out the two opposition parties, the
National Action Party (PAN) and the Party of Democratic Revolution
(PRD). However, in Nayarit, a small state, the opposition parties
swallowed hard, joined each other to support a single candidate and
forced out the PRI _ which had governed the state since the ruling
party was formed 70 years ago. The message was clear: Either the
opposition parties combine their efforts behind a single candidate
in next year's critical presidential elections or they remain
apart, split the opposition vote and lose the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is doubtful that either of the leading opposition
party candidates, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the PRD mayor of Mexico
City, or Vicente Fox, the PAN governor of Guanajuato, would bow out
to allow the other to win the presidency. Preventing that are the
major political differences between them: Fox is an avowed
free-market advocate, while Cardenas leans toward a socialist
state.
</P>
<P>
   Yet both candidates know that during the PRI's long regime, the
ruling party has miserably failed to allow Mexico to develop
economically.
</P>
<P>
   The string of Mexican presidents since the 1930s stifled free
enterprise by declaring Mexico a closed-market economy. That
allowed a handful of Mexican industrialists to enrich themselves
fabulously. It gave them a captive market in which Mexicans were
forced into buying shoddily produced merchandise. Deals were forged
between the government and the industrialists to keep workers wages
tragically low _ $3 to $5 a day. Health services and the nation's
schools and universities were given scant resources.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mexico's drug cartels amassed billions of dollars in
drug money, establishing themselves as a powerful force.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's middle class and some of its poor now realize they were
literally duped into poverty by the PRI. These groups could pool
their votes to oust the PRI from the presidency in the fall of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   However, with neither Cardenas nor Fox likely to abdicate, it
seems unlikely that the PRD or PAN will win that critical election.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, both parties should concentrate on winning control of
the Mexican Congress by combining candidates, where possible, just
as they did in Nayarit. Five years ago, opposition parties gained
control of the lower house of Mexico's Congress. Since then, the
opposition has weakened the PRI leadership by exposing its
involvement in bribes and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The majority PRD and PAN representatives in the lower house also
have attempted to force passage of major reform legislation, but
their efforts have been blocked by the Senate, which is controlled
by the PRI. By winning control of both houses, the PRD and PAN
could bulldoze the PRI aside and pass the measures badly needed to
bring Mexico back to its feet economically, socially and
politically.
</P>
<P>
   There is a possibility that the PRI could be so weakened by
election time in July 2000 that either Fox or Cardenas could pull
an upset and win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But a takeover of Congress could also erode the PRI's power
gradually. That's a safer alternative than ousting it suddenly from
the presidency _ which could evoke a violent and deadly reaction
from fanatical PRI members in the lower echelons of the party.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting chaos could make a shambles of Mexico's
government, threatening an already strained economy and society
that is just beginning to recover from the crippling 1995 peso
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   So, an alliance between the PAN and the PRD to win full control
of Mexico's Congress may be the surest winner in next year's
elections and the surest way toward the achieving the full
democratization process that can begin lifting the country out of
the quagmire created by the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Elias Castillo, a free-lance writer, journalism teacher and
consultant, lives in Redwood City, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
