<HEADER>
A8192 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-13 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUCHED BY ANGELS OR STUNG BY THE DEVIL? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Nellie Murphy Reed, my mother's mother, had a
decidedly un-Irish outlook on life.
</P>
<P>
   Always remember, my grandmother told her six grandchildren,
every cloud has a silver lining. Nothing bad ever happens unless
God has good reason for it.
</P>
<P>
   To which my mother's response generally was to roll her eyes
heavenward. From childhood, she'd subscribed to the more
traditional Irish belief that happiness is only a fleeting
interlude between longer periods of unpleasant normalcy. Faced with
a choice of lighting a candle or cursing the darkness, my mother's
habitual inclination was to mumble, ``Damn you, Darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, during my vacation, I found myself once again trying
to decide which perspective makes more sense. That was after I'd
found myself a member of a group I'd never wanted to join.
</P>
<P>
   It was 90-plus degrees at my rugged summer property in New
York's Finger Lakes region. I was alone on the beach, at the bottom
of a steep cliff, repairing a sailboat and sweating like a galley
slave. Luckily, I had a beer or two handy for nourishment. I was
taking a break when a red-hot poker suddenly touched the right side
of my chest.
</P>
<P>
   I knew it was a bee or a wasp. I've been stung dozens of times
over the years. But I'd never felt anything quite like this. I
jumped into the lake for relief, but the thing still hurt like
hell. So, I started up the 53 wooden stairs I'd built two years ago
on the face of this cliff. When I reached the first landing, the
world suddenly turned black and white, and I thumped down on the
boards like a falling tree.
</P>
<P>
   That's when I said to myself: Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   I found myself impossibly weak. It took me another 20 minutes
and another sagging collapse before I reached the top of those
steep stairs. Then I needed 10 minutes to sit, gasping, before I
could make my way to our little cottage high on the mountainside
and have my wife drive me to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   I scratched furiously at my skin throughout that nine-mile
jaunt. My throat closed. I could see colors again, but my vision
wasn't right. My lips were swollen. I was splotchy all over.
</P>
<P>
   In the emergency room, I was pumped full of fluids and
medication while they watched my heart with an EKG and took my
blood pressure every few minutes. The heart was fine throughout,
but the blood pressure started out dangerously low.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, they sent me home with instructions to see a
doctor. Somehow, I'd developed an allergic reaction to wasp or bee
venom, possibly aggravated by dehydration. About 4 percent of the
population has this vulnerability. The nasty little assassins
manage to kill about 50 Americans every year.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, and nobody knows why, bees and wasps actually
seem attracted to people allergic to their venom.
</P>
<P>
   So this week, I'll be at my doctor's office. I'm told that they
treat this thing with two years or so of weekly shots to build up
your tolerance for insect venom. For the next 24 months, I suppose,
I'll be treated to the equivalent of a weekly bee sting. And I'll
probably also get to carry around with me everywhere an emergency
needle full of medication _ just in case some other bee or wasp
read a column that bent him out of shape.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder, though: Who was right _ my mother or her mother? As I
ponder it, I'm inclined to go along with my grandmother's point of
view. Yeah, sure, I almost died, and my newly discovered allergy
clearly will be a huge annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   But, after all, I did get a column out of it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
