A8193 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-13 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEVEN DEADLY SINS, MINUS ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In his Newsweek cover story, ``The Whine of '99:
Everyone's Getting Rich But Me,'' Adam Bryant wrote about the
explosion of U.S. millionaires and billionaires and how it makes
other Americans feel envious, resentful and desperate to gain
entrance to the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strange thing,'' Bryant writes, ``is that nobody's really
countering the money hype. In previous boom times in the 1800s and
earlier this century, there was always influential criticism of
such behavior coming from pulpits, schools and colleges. Now it
seems as if the list of seven deadly sins has been shortened to
six.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone is looking for sermon fodder _ anyone who still
believes that greed belongs on the list with idleness, gluttony,
lust, pride, envy and anger _ she or he need look no further than
two brilliant-but-chilling radio ads for Forbes.com, the on-line
edition of Forbes magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Especially the one about ``Jimmy.''
</P>
<P>
   A gentle, treacly guitar provides the background music as a
sincere sounding, soft-voiced man begins: ``Meet Jimmy.'' In
sing-song earnestness, the man says that Jimmy is a ``lot like his
other friends. He loves rap, he devours pizza and he always wants
to stay out past curfew.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the man's voice takes on a more serious tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except, there's something different about Jimmy, something
that makes him ... special.''
</P>
<P>
   Because we have heard dozens of commercials like this _ to
solicit donations for the Special Olympics or kids or adults with
some disability _ we prepare for the characteristic that makes
Jimmy ``special.''
</P>
<P>
   The man delivers: ``You see, Jimmy is a capitalist pig.''
</P>
<P>
   The smug way the man says ``capitalist pig'' makes it clear that
it's a great, butt-kickin' thing to be. He then explains that Jimmy
created an Internet Web site with a computer he got for Christmas
and ``some big company bought it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, ``while his friends are thinking about college, Jimmy is
thinking about his next Web site's IPO.''
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of Jimmys, the man says, and touts Forbes.com's
ability to help them: ``So, if you think you may end up
disgustingly wealthy, or if you find the prospect hard to resist,
please, click onto Forbes.com. ... Remember, we're here to help.
Forbes.com. It's a new game.''
</P>
<P>
   The companion ad is about ``Sandy,'' who's ``like a lot of women
today _ alone, raising kids.'' The twist: Sandy is ``filthy,
stinking rich'' from designing Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Before the spot is over, the man uses the terms ``ridiculously
wealthy'' and ``making bundles of dough.'' Again, despite the
parodic please-help tone, it's clear that being filthy, stinking
rich is what anybody who's not a chump wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   In Bryant's piece, such commercials are dismissed by ad industry
reps as ``jokes, exaggerations, intended to grab eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. Like much of Hollywood and cable television, Madison
Avenue appears to be in the grasp of clever but sophomoric young
men who never met a person, product or issue they couldn't turn
into a joke _ preferably one with a babe in it.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is nothing sacred or deserving of dignity, anything
that once was held as such _ say, a sense that excess, greed-driven
wealth is obscene _ is Public Enemy No. 1, begging for a put-down.
</P>
<P>
   But lightweight intentions do not always produce inconsequential
results. Advertising is ubiquitous today because it works. Added to
the not-so-subtle cultural message that conspicuous consumption and
the widening wealth gap already send to all Americans, is it such a
far reach to expect hip and clever ads to intensify the attitude?
</P>
<P>
   The Web site of a magazine that has grown famous by publishing
an annual list of the wealthiest individuals in the world now says
it is truly cool to be a filthy, stinking rich, ridiculously
wealthy capitalist pig.
</P>
<P>
   Like the man says, it's a new game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
