<SLUG> BC-TV-PREVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SEASON IS OVER BEFORE IT BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's look back at some of those can't-miss, sure-fire,
no-brainer fall hits that the networks rolled out for review at
this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Costello.'' ``DiResta.'' ``Wind on Water.'' ``The Army Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, we are just warming up. You just can't forget ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Conrad Bloom.'' ``Mercy Point.'' ``Brimstone.'' ``Living in
Captivity.'' Mid-July means the summer Television Critics
Association Press Tour. The annual fest is where critics are called
together from around the country to a Pasadena, Calif., hotel to
review the upcoming fall shows.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the broadcast and cable networks bring in all their
stars for preview sessions, interviews, schmoozing and parties
whose opulence would leave Donald Trump shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's a job.
</P>
<P>
   Still, everybody involved in this pre-fab event knows the same
thing, although it sometimes goes unsaid: Many, if not most, of
these new shows will be goners by the time the season is out, often
much sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of a Kind.'' ``Holding the Baby.'' ``Secret Diary of
Desmond Pfeiffer.'' ``L.A. Doctors.'' There. That feels better.
</P>
<P>
   No, don't get the idea that the networks are outright lying to
us. Some of these shows had to look good on paper, or in
pre-pre-pre (pre-) production. Then again, some new shows get the
green light only because nothing better is in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vengeance Unlimited.'' ``Guys Like Us.'' ``The Brian Benben
Show.'' ``Encore! Encore!'' ``Hyperion Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, the networks announced their planned lineups for the
coming fall. Based on some preview tapes (they have not yet been
formally released for review), some of the shows look pretty good,
some OK, some lame, some awful.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, no one knows what shows will appear to be horrible
to critics, then go on to be hits. Call it the ``Providence''
scenario. On the flip side, some new programs will seem perfectly
palatable _ even good _ only to be disasters in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cupid.'' ``Buddy Faro.'' ``Fantasy Island.'' ``Trinity.''
</P>
<P>
   I only have a year on the beat, so don't take it like I have
grown hopelessly cynical already. Anyone who gripes about watching
television, even bad television, for a living needs to get off the
Barcalounger and run for a quick fix of perspective.
</P>
<P>
   So what will the networks tell us this year, besides that
they've each had ``the best development seasons in years''? Well,
in short, it will probably go something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ABC: ``Drew Carey will star in two shows, a made-for-TV movie,
work the cash register at the commissary and fluff your pillow
before bed.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC: ``There is life after `Seinfeld' and George Clooney. It's
just not as good.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS: ``We can do women lawyer shows, too. Lots of 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox: ``We can make funny comedies with real, live, undrawn
people. Honest.''
</P>
<P>
   WB: ``In continuing our pursuit for a younger audience, we are
shooting to lock up the in-utero demographic.''
</P>
<P>
   UPN: ``We're still here. And `Desmond Pfeiffer' is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Pax: ``We are too a network, gosh darn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Why wouldn't you believe everything they say?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret Lives of Men.'' ``Maggie Winters.'' ``To Have and
to Hold.'' ``Legacy.'' Oh. Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
