<HEADLINE>
OUTLOOK FOR CHIP BUSINESS IS ROSIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBY McGILL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The semiconductor industry is in an upbeat mood
after a dismal 1998 for the manufacturers of the high-speed brains
on which computers rely.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a difference a year makes,'' said Stan Meyers, president
of Semiconductor Equipment and Materials International, the
2,300-member trade group that is sponsoring the 29th Semicon West
trade show. ``There is a decidedly more upbeat, though cautious
optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers said 1998 was the ``worst single year in the history of
the industry'' because of a steep market decline.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide sales of semiconductors sank to $125.6 billion, the
lowest level since 1994, according to San Jose-based Pathfinder
Research. The decline represented an 8.5 percent drop from the
previous year, and a 13 percent drop from the $144.4 billion in
sales generated in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers blamed a variety of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our industry is coming out of a three-year down cycle fueled
by a convergence of factors, including overcapacity and the Asian
financial crisis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those ills, the industry has staged a comeback and the
rebound is expected to continue. Pathfinder estimates worldwide
sales will rise to $143.1 billion in 1999 and continue to grow in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, major changes are afoot. The future of the personal
computer market is crucial. Giants like Santa Clara-based Intel
have ridden the PC boom to riches. Analysts fear the PC market is
saturated, creating less demand.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up the slack from the computer market will be
manufacturers of products such as household appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're PC-related, you're not so happy; if you are not
PC-related, you are fairly happy right now,'' said Dan Niles, a San
Francisco-based analyst for BancBoston Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual applications, such as your toaster and your washing
machine, are going to have intelligence imbedded into them now,''
Niles said. ``There are a lot more areas that semiconductors are
going into compared to five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Mitchell, president of Air Products Electronic Chemicals in
Allentown, Pa., takes a guarded approach when looking into the
future of the semiconductor industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The function of economic forecasting is to make astrology look
respectable,'' Mitchell said. ``It is certainly very difficult to
predict where we're going, but all of the indicators are certainly
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Semicon West show, being held in San Francisco, features
1,940 exhibitors, up from 1,750 last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1424EDT &QL; 
