<SLUG> BC-DENIM-STYLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENIM IS HIP IN BACK-TO-SCHOOL FASHION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As teen-agers start their initial forays into the department and
specialty stores for back-to-school clothes, they will be treated
to an unusually large array of denimwear.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the prototypical American fabric is back with a vengeance.
The stores are full of it (fall clothes arrived early this year).
</P>
<P>
   Lately, classic American jeans _ Levis 501s, Wranglers, Lees and
their designer spinoffs _ have taken a back seat to khakis,
particularly the body-obscuring hip-hop look typified by designer
Tommy Hilfiger: khaki pants worn four sizes too big over Joe Boxer
briefs, topped by an oversized athletic team jacket and expensive
athletic shoes, laces undone.
</P>
<P>
   Now fashion's romance with the human body has re-emerged _ as
have form-fitting clothes to flaunt it. Add to that the hip Western
wear shown off in ``Wild Wild West,'' starring rap artist/actor
Will Smith, and jeanswear is back, big time.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, look for more variety in texture, weight and
hue. In other words, buying denim for school wear is not the
slam-dunk it used to be. It was very simple when all you wanted was
a pair of boot-cut Levis to go over your Frye's. These days, denim
comes in many hues, from the palest of the smooth, worn washed-out
blue to the deepest indigo.
</P>
<P>
   Do you want stretch? Heavy-weight? Rumply? Do you want them
pre-broken-in or would you have the patience to watch a stiff pair
of Diesel's deep blue jeans earn their ``patina?''
</P>
<P>
   When I was a kid, we bought our Levis jeans in boys sizes.
</P>
<P>
   And we'd dump them in the washing machine with super hot water
treated with bleach. We'd wash them, not once, not twice, but three
times _ until the bleach broke down the fabric enough for the jeans
to fit like second skin.
</P>
<P>
   Blue jeans are an American tradition that started with German
emigre Levi Strauss, who, in 1853, sailed around the Horn to San
Francisco to begin a dry-goods business. What Strauss did, however,
was to sell long-wearing, durable work pants out of a fabric called
serge d'nimes (Nimes being the city in France where the material
was woven) to the gold miners of the Placer lodes.
</P>
<P>
   The miners complained that with all their rough use, the denim
pants didn't hold up. The pockets ripped when they stuffed their
tools into them.
</P>
<P>
   When a Reno, Nev., man named Jacob Davis, a Latvian-born tailor,
put metal rivets at the points of stress on the pants _ at the
pocket corners, at the base of the button fly _ to strengthen them,
he didn't have the $68 it would cost to patent his invention. He
contacted Levi Strauss, and together the two received Patent No.
139,121 from the U.S. Patent Office. The classic Levis jean was
born.
</P>
<P>
   Denimwear has come a long way since then, but the identification
of denim as the all-American fabric has solidified over the years.
``Denim really is the American fabric, the teen-aged `club'
totem,'' says Old Navy's Joe Enos. ``It's the anchor in the
wardrobe. Whether it's in the form of a denim skirt, a pair of
coveralls, a jean jacket, denim is a fabric that everybody can
wear. Right now, the softer washes are really comfortable. Denim is
a staple in the back-to- school wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Brad Kelly of The Denim Group U.S.A., an outfit out of
Wichita, Kan., that finds and consigns high-end vintage clothing
for the Asian market as well as for the East and West Coast,
``Denim is so comfortable. The new fabrics are light, they're easy
to maintain. It's ease of operation. And it's status with (high
schoolers).''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What retailers such as Diesel, American Eagle and Old Navy have
begun stocking in denim, in addition to trendy styles (such as
cargo pants, carpenter jeans and draw-strings), are traditional
boot-cut jeans _ now dubbed ``flares'' _ to go over platform tennis
shoes, platform slides and chunky-heeled half-boots. Says jeans
dealer Kelly, ``I'm seeing trends back to clothes that fit. It's
probably a good sign.'' He even goes so far as to suggest that the
more contoured jeans style is a move away from the popularity of
hip-hop clothing, a statement that ``I don't want to be associated
with gang-style clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeans are easy to accessorize. This year's go-with is the plaid
shirt, layered with a sweater, a hooded jacket or a fleece or down
vest. It's neat, it's clean and it's totally American. ``Everybody
can wear a pair of jeans,'' Enos says. ``They're very democratic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
