r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUN-DAMAGE-HNS &LR;      07-13 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-DAMAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNTAIN OF YOUTH MAY BE FOUND IN THE SHADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Think of the part of your body with the
smoothest, softest, baby-like skin.
</P>
<P>
   If you're an adult, it's probably not your face, your arms or
your belly. Chances are it's your buttocks, and the reasons are
clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty to 90 percent of the damage you normally associate with
aging is sun damage,'' said Dr. Mark Mitchnick, a Long Island
pediatrician and medical director of SunSmart Inc., a private
research and development company specializing in sunscreens.
</P>
<P>
   These days, most people are trying to protect themselves with
sunscreens. But knowing how to decode the numbers can be confusing,
and not all sunscreens are alike.
</P>
<P>
   Many products say they offer a sun protection factor or SPF of
15, 30 or 45 times ``your natural sunburn protection.'' Others
promise all day protection that's waterproof or water-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   Calling such claims misleading and confusing, the Food and Drug
Administration recently has issued new labeling guidelines to make
it easier for consumers to know what they're buying. The rules are
the first to cover the testing and labeling of sunscreens since the
FDA issued tentative standards in 1978 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   As of May 2001, words such as ``waterproof'' ``sunblock'' and
``all-day protection'' will be banished because such claims ``could
provide the wrong message and a false sense of security,'' the FDA
says.
</P>
<P>
   Also disappearing from the shelf will be any products labeled
with an SPF higher than 30, in favor of one label: ``30 Plus.'' As
the FDA explains it, the benefits of products above 30 are tiny and
difficult to accurately measure.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mitchell Singer, a Schenectady dermatologist, agrees. ``It's
become a numbers game,'' he said. ``You don't really get anywhere
once you get to a certain point.''
</P>
<P>
   So how high should you go with sunscreen? To answer that
question, you need to know how sunscreens are designed to work.
</P>
<P>
   A sunscreen with an SPF 15, for example, theoretically means
that someone who would burn in 15 minutes could stay burn-free for
3 hours and 45 minutes. Using an SPF 30 would lengthen the
protected period to 7.5 hours.
</P>
<P>
   But those laboratory calculations don't take into account
real-world conditions, such as sweating, swimming or skimping on
the amount of sunscreen used. You should also know that the higher
SPFs provide only slightly more protection.
</P>
<P>
   For example, SPF 30 filters nearly 97 percent of sunburning
rays, while SPF 45 filters only about 1 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   Because there's not a lot of difference in the higher SPFs,
Singer spends less time talking numbers with his patients than
trying to get them to use sunscreen daily, not just for the long
day on the boat or at the beach. ``If you use it on a daily basis
all else is equal,'' said Singer, who recommends an SPF 15.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchnick believes applying sunscreen should be as routine as
brushing your teeth, since every moment in the sun can add up to
problems later. ``Most of the sun you get in your life is daily, in
small incremental doses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a daily basis, Michelle DiPasquale, 24, gets more than her
fair share of sun as a summer lifeguard for the New York Department
of Parks and Recreation, which issues sunblock with the uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I get older, I'm worried about it on my face,'' DiPasquale
said. ``It does cause premature aging of the skin. You can tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Some easy ways to protect yourself include wearing a hat, and
using sunscreen with at least an SPF 15 daily.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchnick also counsels people to look for a sunscreen that
protects against both UVA and UVB rays. Not all sunscreens protect
against UVA, and you should read the fine print on the label to
find out.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Mitchnick is a big proponent of zinc oxide. But since
most people don't want to spread the white paste all over their
bodies, his company patented a transparent formula in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, many of the large cosmetic and sunscreen
companies, including Oil of Olay, Maybelline, Body Shop, Nu Skin,
Iguana and Basis, started using Z-Cote on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They work wonderfully,'' Singer said. ``It's like wearing long
pants and going outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, however, that no product offers total protection
against the sun, and you shouldn't use sunscreen as an excuse to
stay out longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of using common sense,'' Singer said. ``Just
because you're wearing a seatbelt doesn't mean you should drive 100
mph.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
