<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-TRADING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT WAVE OF INTERNET INVESTING: MUTUAL FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While hyper cyber-traders flip their stocks like
mad, brokerage firms and analysts are betting that more cautious
long-term investors will make on-line investing in mutual funds the
next big rage on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Recent surveys and business developments show that those more
conservative investors are diving quickly into the on-line world.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 600 fund investors, released Monday by the Charles
Schwab and Co., found that 72 percent plan to trade mutual fund
shares in the next half-year, with nearly all of those trades done
on line.
</P>
<P>
   They also love the ease of Internet trading, with only 2 percent
saying they feel uncomfortable trading on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who wants to be in the mutual fund industry in the
future has to get involved in the Internet,'' said Greg Gable, a
spokesman for the San Francisco-based brokerage. ``People are
embracing mutual fund investing on line. We've only scratched the
surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, on-line fund assets total $128 billion _ a tiny portion
of the $7 trillion in total assets held by the nation's 7,000-plus
funds. But on-line fund assets may grow to $1.2 trillion by 2003,
according to Forrester Research Inc., an Internet research and
consulting firm in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Forrester report predicted that three financial behemoths _
Schwab, Fidelity Investments and Vanguard Group _ will dominate the
Internet market and kill smaller Internet brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's customers have $160 billion in 1,600 mutual funds, and
more than one-third of their on-line transactions involve mutual
funds. Fidelity boasts 3 million on-line accounts, and more than 30
percent of Vanguard's customers invest through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``On-line investing is going mainstream,'' said James Punishill,
an analyst at Forrester. ``The mass market has arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial companies were slow to hit the Web with mutual fund
products. Techno-savvy cyber-traders _ typically white-collar
professionals in the financial and high-tech fields _ were the
first wave of on-line financial consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerages tailored their services to those investors, who
engage in rapid-fire trading of stocks hundreds of times a year.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, however, Jack White &AMP; Co., a discount brokerage
house in San Diego, broke the ice by selling mutual fund shares
over the Internet. Charles Schwab and others quickly joined the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Now the companies are targeting the next wave of investors:
financially conservative middle-class folks with billions of
dollars in retirement money in 401(k)s, individual retirement
accounts and other investment vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   After some early fear of the technology, consumers are warming
up to on-line finance. Their initial caution is similar to
consumers' distrust of automated teller machines two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest mutual fund product on line has been the so-called
mutual fund supermarkets, which offer consumers the choice of
thousands of mutual funds and money managers. Schwab's OneSource
supermarket is the most popular, with 1,100 no-load funds holding
$99 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   With more mutual funds coming to the Internet, fees should drop
as investors look for the cheapest deals, Punishill said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, consumers with 401(k)s will use more financial
planning software made available on their company Web sites and on
financial Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year or two, the financial sites also have become
much easier and more convenient to use.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab hopes to lure more customers into mutual fund investing
by providing fund research, share purchases and the monitoring of
portfolios at one easy, convenient site on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything will be at your fingertips with one click,'' Gable
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
