<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8224 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-PARTNERS-HNS &LR;      07-13 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-PARTNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES APPEAL UNMARRIED PARTNERS RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Continuing their flight from a landmark San
Francisco ordinance, United Airlines and other air carriers
appealed a court order that says they must give employees with
unmarried partners some of the same benefits they give to married
employees.
</P>
<P>
   United and the other carriers on Monday asked the 9th Circuit
Court of Appeals to overturn a federal court order requiring them
to comply with San Francisco's Equal Benefits Ordinance as early as
next month.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal was the latest in a flurry of court actions to buffet
the carriers, who have said they are seeking exemption from the
local law on business, not moral, grounds.
</P>
<P>
   If upheld, the San Francisco ordinance could affect benefits
offered by national carriers around the country, said lawyers on
both sides of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Aftergut, chief assistant city attorney, said United and
Federal Express currently violate the civil rights of employees
with unmarried partners by denying them equal pay. ``The airlines
are fighting to continue discriminating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Berg, a laywer for the Air Transport Association of
America, which represents major airlines, said, ``We're concerned
about the impact on the airlines if we're forced to comply with
this novel ordinance. We can't do business in the United States or
anywhere else if we have to comply with differing, or sometimes
conflicting, local ordinances.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco ordinance, the first of its kind in the
nation, says all companies contracting with the city must give the
same benefits to workers with registered domestic partners that
they do those who are married.
</P>
<P>
   The measure _ which covers unmarried heterosexuals as well as
homosexuals _ took effect in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But United, Federal Express and the Air Transport Association
joined in a lawsuit contending that, as national carriers, they
should be exempt from the measure and should only be regulated by
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the Airline Deregulation Act and other federal
laws bar local governments from regulating the benefits they offer
their workers, saying it would be unmanageable for them to operate
under standards set by numerous local communities where they
operate.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, U.S. District Judge Claudia Wilken of Oakland
agreed with the carriers that federal law alone governs their
pension and health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But in May, Wilken said they still must comply with other parts
of the city ordinance and give unmarried partners standard industry
perks, such as family and bereavement leave and flight discounts.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the carriers appealed that ruling to the federal
appeals court, where it will be decided within several months or
even years.
</P>
<P>
   On July 2, Wilken denied their request to stay her order so they
would not have to comply with it pending the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the carriers asked the appeals court to reverse that
decision and to impose a stay.
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance takes effect as contracts are signed for the first
time or are amended. United and Federal Express are the only
contractors at San Francisco International Airport affected so far,
but more than 20 other national carriers would ultimately be
covered by the ordinance, Aftergut said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1450EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
