<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8236 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BO     07-13 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 ART ADV.: Photos with ALLST-WOMEN and DAVIS-LONGWOOD are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-GARBAGE (Shanghai) _ China suddenly faces the problems of
developed countries. Shanghai, for example, has a huge
garbage-disposal problem and is preaching recycling. By Indira A.R.
Lakshmanan. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ALLSTAR-CARDS (Washington) _ Packs of ``All Star'' cards given
to members of Congress, bubble gum included, include 11 people
helped by US foreign assistance. A cover sheet, by Sammy Sosa, says
these people are the real ``All Stars.'' By John Donnelly. 700
words. (w, a and s coding)
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Washington) _ There's too much ado over Al
Gore's hiring of consultant Carter Eskew. By Thomas Oliphant. &UR;  &LR; (w
and k coding.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMSBURG-SLAVERY (Williamsburg, Va.) _ Colonial tourist
attraction tackles slavery vs. freedom, with the tourists becoming
major players along with the actors. By Eun Lee Koh. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-ANTIYUPPIE (San Francisco) _ An anti-yuppie harassment
campaign in the San Francisco Mission district underscores the
divide between haves and have-nots in a time of prosperity. By
Lynda Gorov. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FEMALE-FIREFIGHTER (Brooklyn, N.Y.) _ Rochelle ``Rocky''
Jones never thought of becoming a firefighter when she was growing
up in Brooklyn. Now Jones, a 17-year veteran, has become the first
female fire captain in New York history. By Fred Kaplan. 1380
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCGRORY-COLUMN (Undated) _ What the Boston Globe lost in the
sale six years ago was local ownership of a uniquely local
institution. Now we've lost the stewardship of a family who always
tried to do the right thing. By Brian McGrory.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Jan Freeman's language column is unavailable this week.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-GLOBE-TAYLORS (Boston) _ While other Boston papers folded
or went through cycles of birth and death, the Taylor family used a
combination of journalistic quality and business acumen to build
the Globe into New England's largest newspaper and the winner of 15
Pulitzer Prizes. By Mitchell Zuckoff. 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-EQUAL (Undated) _ In writing ``An Equal Music,'' Vikram
Seth has brought skill, attention to detail, and finesse of
feeling. By Richard Dyer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (t) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EGYPT (Aswan, Egypt) _ What's good enough for Agatha
Christie or King Farouk is good enough for you. Cruising the
palatial 19th-century hotels where they stayed. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN &UR;  &LR; (Undated) _ New Brunswick has to be one of the
hidden treasures of Canada. By Jerry Morris. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOTES (Undated) _ You've heard of Benjamin Franklin the
statesman, diplomat and inventor. But Benjamin Franklin the cabaret
star? By Richard Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-WOMEN (Boston) _ On the field and in the dugout, the
All-Star Game is dominated by men. But behind the scenes you'll see
women executives in Major League Baseball and at companies playing
a major role. By Gregg Krupa. 900 words. (f and s coding) &UR;  &LR; PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Fidelity's Magellan Fund, the
world's biggest mutual fund, nears $100 billion mark in assets. By
Steven Syre and Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   LEVINGSTON-COLUMN (Undated) -- Analyzing Philip Morris's dumping
of its advertising for ``The Family Guy.'' By Steven Levingston.
</P>
