<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8301 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KHRUSHCHEV-GRANDSON-T     07-13 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KHRUSHCHEV-GRANDSON-TRAITOR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I HAVE NOT AS YET BEEN EXECUTED' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By NIKITA KHRUSHCHEV  
 c.1999 Moscow News  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Forty years ago, for the first time in Soviet history, an
American exhibition opened at a fair in the Moscow park of
Sokolniki. There, my grandfather, Nikita S. Khrushchev, who was at
the time first secretary of the Communist Party's Central Committee
and chairman of the Soviet Council of Ministers, had a debate with
Richard Nixon, vice president of the United States and head of the
U.S. delegation.
</P>
<P>
   One of the exhibits on display was a ``typical American home for
a typical American family.'' The most heated part of the debate
took place in the model kitchen. So it went down in diplomatic
history as the ``kitchen'' debate.
</P>
<P>
   During the exchange, Khrushchev predicted that Nixon's
grandchildren would live in a socialist America, to which Nixon
retorted that, no, the grandchildren of the Soviet Union's No. 1
Communist would live in a capitalist Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Khrushchev, a staunch Communist, proved to be wrong. His
grandchildren indeed now live in Russia, but under a system that
can hardly be called socialist. Meanwhile, his son, my father,
Sergei N. Khrushchev, 63, after eight years of working in the
United States, became a U.S. citizen a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   This would seem a fitting postscript to that debate. I should be
putting a period here. Yet I can't. What I've come up against in
recent days shows that for many people in Russia, the Cold War has
never become a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   In my role as a researcher for Moscow News, I am often in
contact with agencies and bureaus for photographs, archival
information and so forth. Although Father lives in America, we are
frequently in touch. Just recently he asked me to contact a man he
knew who used to be prominent in the Soviet leadership _ at one
time, a member of the Central Committee. I phoned him and
introduced myself.
</P>
<P>
   And here is what I heard in response: ``Khrushchev's eldest son,
Leonid, surrendered to the Nazis; they used him to conduct
anti-Soviet agitation on the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   I tried to object: ``No, there are no documents to that effect
in any archives, Russian or German.''
</P>
<P>
   But not letting me cut in on his monologue, he continued to
enlighten me about my relatives. ``At the end of the war,'' he
said, ``Sudoplatov's (a Stalin-era spy chief) agents snatched
Leonid from Nazi captivity and put him on trial, and he was
sentenced to be shot for collaborating with the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Again my interlocutor would not listen.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it was time to learn about the former Soviet leader. It
seems that Grandfather was once summoned by Stalin, and crawled
before him on his knees, crying, but the ``father of the peoples''
was adamant in his criticism. This was apparently why Khrushchev
Sr. came to hate Stalin, and plot to take revenge for being so
humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the old hard-liner ended up talking about my father.
``I am not surprised,'' he told me, ``that yet another Khrushchev
degenerate has betrayed our Motherland and sold himself out to the
Americans.'' He added that I, personally, would have to answer for
this under the ``criminal code'' of the land.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment I didn't understand. Then it dawned on me: He was
actually referring to the notorious Article 58 of the Stalin-era
Criminal Code, all of whose paragraphs provided for capital
punishment. One of them referred to ``members of the family of a
traitor to Motherland.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, in the view of that staunch Leninist, I am now a member of
a traitor's family; however, as yet, I have not been executed and
continue to work. What I am quickly learning, though, is that this
man is not alone in his view of me. My father's new status has
irked other people besides him.
</P>
<P>
   Quite by surprise, I was told at a Russian design bureau, once a
highly classified project, where I chose to turn for assistance in
tracking down a picture of a big space rocket that was not destined
to be produced in quantity, that they ``did not maintain any
relations with foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   But I live in Moscow, I told them, and never changed my
citizenship, whereas, indeed, this very year they were visited by
delegations from the United States, France, Japan and other
countries. That cut no ice.
</P>
<P>
   I was told this: ``Should the FSB (Federal Security Service)
give a positive response IN WRITING to your application IN WRITING
to its director, then we might be able to help you. If not, you
will never get to see this photograph.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, I phoned an archive where I had had some
documents duplicated for my father. Its employees had never turned
down my requests before. But this time was different. They said:
``The head of the administrative department would like to talk to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of department, a relatively young man, told me in a
voice of steel: ``In view of the change in the status of your
father, the cost of this order will be 40 times as much. It is also
desirable that payment be made in hard currency.''
</P>
<P>
   This is of course no longer a Cold War. But neither is it peace
as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Nikita Khrushchev is head of the Moscow News Information
Service.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
