<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8318 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS &LR;      07-13 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN KNOWS LITTLE OF SUSPECTED KILLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICAHEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDDING, Calif. _ People acquainted with the two brothers who
are suspected of killing two gay men and burning three synagogues
were aware of their beliefs about white supremacy, but were shocked
that these two quiet and unfailingly polite young men were linked
to the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone we've spoken with finds it extremely hard to
believe,'' said Samantha Burke who, with her husband, Tom, hired
Benjamin Matthew Williams, 31, as their yard man. Williams'
brother, James Tyler Williams, 29, also worked at their house on
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers were arrested last week in Yuba City while using
the credit card of Gary Matson. Matson, 50, and Winfield Scott
Mowder, 40, a well-known and well-liked gay couple, were found shot
to death in their Happy Valley house July 1.
</P>
<P>
   During a subsequent search of Matthew Williams' Redding home and
a house in nearby Palo Cedro, where Tyler Williams lived with his
parents, investigators found evidence that they said linked the
pair to the arson fires of the synagogues in Sacramento on June 18.
(The brothers go by their middle names.)
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Ron Richardson of the Shasta County Sheriff's Department
said the Williamses would probably be charged in the deaths of
Matson and Mowder on Wednesday or Thursday. They are being held on
charges of possessing stolen property. Richardson said no other
arrests were anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI said Monday that it had new evidence that further linked
the two to the synagogue fires.
</P>
<P>
   A search Monday focused on the outskirts of the Northern
California town of Oroville, where the car belonging to Matson and
Mowder was found last week.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators hoped to discover whether any evidence in the
arson case had been tossed away near the site of the abandoned car,
possibly into nearby irrigation ditches.
</P>
<P>
   While some people in Redding are familiar with the Williams
family, those interviewed for this story said they did not know the
family well.
</P>
<P>
   Ben and Sally Williams, the parents of the brothers, live on a
three-acre plot in rural Palo Cedro, up against North Cow Creek.
Not only have they not come to know their neighbors in the three
years since they moved here from Gridley, in Butte County, but Ben
Williams demonstrated an unusual technique to insure that nobody
tried to socialize with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I understand you're a drug dealer,'' Williams said when he
first met his next-door neighbor, a medical technician, according
to the neighbor's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided then that I wouldn't be hosting any welcome coffees
for them,'' she said. ``I think it was his way of saying `stay
back.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Williamses' sons, who had been home-schooled and reportedly
did not socialize with their peers in Gridley, went into the
Redding community to work. Both were avid horticulturists, and sold
their organic produce at the local farmers market.
</P>
<P>
   It was there, according Richardson, that they became acquainted
with Mowder and Matson, who were also devoted to raising plants.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving in this area, Matthew Williams got a job at
Orchard Nutrition, a health-supply store.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little different,'' recalled Orchard employee Leona
McCall. ``He had his little weird way of thinking. He kept to
himself a lot. He was just an oddball.''
</P>
<P>
   She said he had once tried to distribute his own nutritional
literature in the store, but the owner told him to stop.
</P>
<P>
   He left Orchard about a year ago to launch his own landscaping
business. And, to some clients, he offered literature of a
different sort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to do with the supremacy of the white race,'' said
Samantha Burke. ``We were rather surprised and found it
distasteful.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband said they returned the racist information to
Williams and told him ``we were of a different persuasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, said the Burkes, they had no reason to dislike their
enthusiastic gardener and his younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very polite, very respectful and nice to have
around,'' Tom Burke said. ``We had no reason not to trust them, and
also they were good workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers' arrest ``really came as a shock'' to Cheri Cooke,
47, who cleaned houses for two families that also employed the
siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matthew was a really sweet person,'' she said. ``There wasn't
a subject you could broach with Matthew that he didn't know
something about.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding religion, she said, ``he was very much what you would
call a fundamentalist. His lifestyle, everything. He tended to be
by the book, and he was very inflexible, very rigid.''
</P>
<P>
   She said his dogmatic ways also applied to food: ``He wouldn't
eat anything with sugar, he wouldn't eat anything that was
processed, he wouldn't take any caffeine. He was fanatical about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooke said she had met Matthew Williams' parents once and
``found them gracious and warm and friendly and accepting.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Williams, on the other hand, did not relate well to
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell he did not like being around people,'' she
said. ``He was aloof and distant.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Williams left home in 1995 and briefly attended the
University of Idaho in Moscow. He attracted some attention there
when he became involved in a controversy surrounding the Living
Faith Fellowship, a Christian youth organization that some
defectors, including Williams, accused of being a cult. He told the
Moscow Daily News that he had been attracted to the group because
he was ``emotionally devastated'' after breaking up with his
fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   If true, it appears that Matthew Williams has been engaged to be
married on at least two occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rarely had girlfriends, and the reason is they had to think
like Matthew,'' Cooke said. ``They had to agree with his religious
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, she said he had recently become engaged to a woman
from the Redding area. ``It didn't work out,'' Cooke said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had been ``quite happy'' about being engaged, Samantha
Burke said. ``I know that he wanted to have big family; he wanted
to have a lot of children. I thought he would make a very fine
father.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1531EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8319 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-CHEESE-ART-NYT &LR;      07-13 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-CHEESE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY RED WINE AND CHEESE HAVE STOPPED GOING STEADY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The rule of red wine with cheese is as revered as the
one dictating no wine with breakfast. But in a season when chilled
white wine seems so appealing, one of those rules demands to be
broken, and not just as a sign of surrender to the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority of our customers drink red wine with the cheese,
but my personal preference is for white,'' said Roger Dagorn, the
accredited sommelier at Chanterelle. ``Red wine with cheese is an
old myth. White wine is livelier and has more acidity, which
balances the fattiness of cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   Many wine experts agree, although the message seems not to have
reached restaurant patrons or dinner party hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red wine with cheese? I'd like to debunk that,'' said Paul
Grieco, the beverage director at Gramercy Tavern, where his
selection of some 15 cheeses is routinely paired with red wine by
his customers. Though he is reluctant to go so far as to recommend
a dry white wine, he said he sometimes suggests a sweet one or an
oloroso sherry.
</P>
<P>
   At Picholine, which has the most elaborate cheese selection in
New York, Max McCalman, a former sommelier who supervises and
serves the cheese, lamented the bias toward red wines. He recalled
that the host at a large table of wine buffs not long ago selected
a magnum of Chateau Talbot 1989 to serve with cheese. ``There were
strong cheeses,'' McCalman said. ``It was a real clash.''
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Jean-Claude Vrinat, the owner of Taillevent, says he
generally prefers white wines with cheese but that most of his
customers continue with their red wine when the cheese is served.
``Red wines complement very few cheeses,'' he said. ``But our
customers usually don't ask our opinions when it comes to what to
drink with cheese, so we try to recommend the cheeses that don't
violate the taste of a red wine.'' Which defeats the pleasure of a
French cheese tray, of course.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner last year at Les Celebrites showcasing the red
burgundies of the Domaine de la Romanee-Conti, Aubert de -Villaine,
the co-owner of the estate, switched to Le Montrachet for the
cheese. ``With cheese, I only like white wine,'' he said to the
guests, some of whom had been nursing their red La Tache for the
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   He later said his preference had changed through tasting and
experience. ``I started drinking white wine with cheese because
every time we had a great red with the cheese, it was a
disappointment,'' he said. ``Cheese kills the nuances in red wine.
In Burgundy now, more and more people are drinking white wine with
cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion of red wine with cheese appears to be a vestige of
sexist, Victorian days. Gerald Asher, a wine writer, explained that
in 19th-century England, the consumption of red wine and cheese was
not considered ladylike. At the end of dinner, the women retired to
the parlor so that the men could get on with serious drinking:
claret and port. With Stilton, of course. Asher believes that in
France the habit evolved from a custom of saving the best (red)
wines for the end of the meal.
</P>
<P>
   The custom persists for practical reasons. ``Often, there's
enough red wine left from the main course, so people continue
drinking it with the cheese,'' Dagorn said. De Villaine conceded
that a white after a big red is not ideal, either. ``You need a
break,'' he said. Serve the salad.
</P>
<P>
   Even McCalman of Picholine said cheese would flatter a light,
simple red wine, but most people would not follow the big red wine
of the main course with a simple country red any more than they
would pop open a white. The one cheese that he believes demands a
robust red wine, like a Nebbiolo, is Parmigiano-Reggiano.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Hazan, an authority on Italian wines, whose next book is
to be called ``The Color of Wine Is Red,'' said that he no longer
advocates white wines at all but would not serve his best reds with
cheese. ``Cheese interferes with everything except a light,
sprightly red or a sweet wine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If you care only about the cheese, it might not matter what the
wine is, but to enjoy the wine and do it credit, give thoughtful
consideration to the pairing.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pocket Encyclopedia of Wine 1991 (Fireside), Hugh Johnson
gives a few easy rules, suggesting that in general, the harder the
cheese, the more tannins the accompanying wine can have, which
supports the marriage of Parmesan and Nebbiolo. He adds that the
creamier the cheese, the more acidity is needed in the wine.
</P>
<P>
   In general, cheeses taste of salt and fat. Many are also creamy
and pungent. These characteristics often deaden rich, tannic red
wines. But refreshing, fruity but dry whites can handle them. Some
sweet whites make for brilliant matches, like the classic
combination of Sauternes and Roquefort.
</P>
<P>
   Since many Americans like to fill their plates with a variety of
cheeses, the habit of red wine may be hard to shake. Others will
jump on the white bandwagon. But the best idea may be to ponder the
subtle nuances and make careful matches with the wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing many people I respect say the only wine to serve
with cheese is white now,'' said Steven Jenkins, the author of
``Cheese Primer'' (Workman, 1996). ``That's extreme. There are no
absolutes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
