<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8323 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KITCHEN-EQUIPMENT-NYT     07-13 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-EQUIPMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A USEFUL DEVICE, EXTREME SCOOPING ASIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the summer when I was growing up, my mother would cut
watermelon into a basket shape and diligently empty its flesh with
a melon baller, refilling the basket with perfectly round
watermelon and cantaloupe balls.
</P>
<P>
   It took forever, and it did look pretty, but I thought she was
crazy. Inevitably, after a few years, she gave up and put the melon
baller back in the drawer for good.
</P>
<P>
   The watermelon basket was just the kind of trendy 1970s dish
that gave the melon baller a bad name. In truth, it is an extremely
handy tool when used in reasonable ways.
</P>
<P>
   A large melon baller can be used to make tiny scoops of sorbet,
or balls of banana to layer on top of a tart. These kinds of
finishing touches do not take that much time and can make a big
difference in the visual appeal of what you're serving.
</P>
<P>
   It is just as useful as a corer. In restaurant kitchens, melon
ballers are used to remove seeds from cucumbers and to core apples
and pears. On a cucumber halved lengthwise, the melon baller
removes the seeds in a neat, rounded trough. With halved fruit it
scoops out the core in a clean, round half sphere _ impossible
using a paring knife.
</P>
<P>
   Melon ballers can also be used to create a cavity for stuffing.
Jacques Torres, the pastry chef at Le Cirque 2000, uses one to
empty the center of strawberries, then fills them with strawberry
sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   The tool's main drawback is that it creates a lot of waste. But
there are things to be done with that, too. With strawberries, for
instance, use what you core from the fruit to make a sauce. Scraps
from vegetables can be added to soups, or finely minced into a
garnish. Leftovers and excess juice from melons can be transformed
into sorbet or granita or strained and added to a cocktail for
flavoring.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear when exactly the melon baller was invented, but it
began appearing in cookbooks in the 19th century. At that time in
France, cooking was becoming a much more precise craft, and the
labor required of the diner was reduced to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Tools like the melon baller were created so that melon would not
need to be scooped at the table, said Burt Wolf, who is revising
``The Cooks' Catalog'' (Harper &AMP; Row, 1975), which he wrote with
James Beard, Barbara Kafka and Milton Glaser. Serving balled melon
was also a way to show off the wealth of the host and the depth of
his kitchen staff.
</P>
<P>
   Some classic uses for the melon baller are actually worthy of
revival. Pommes parisienne, for instance, is horrendously
time-consuming _ potatoes are carved into tiny balls, blanched and
browned in butter. But it's a delicious idea. Such painstaking
manipulation of so humble a food makes for a whimsical
presentation, and the small round shape offers a greater surface
area to be made crisp and buttery. The same can be done with
zucchini and carrots.
</P>
<P>
   The melon baller is one of the few tools that manufacturers seem
to have mastered. I tested 11, and the only significant differences
were in the prices, which ranged from $7 to $21. What is important
is for the edge of the baller to feel thin and sharp, for the tool
to seem sturdy and for the handle to feel comfortable in the palm.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of sizes and shapes are available. Some melon ballers make
spheres the size of peas, others as large as walnuts. There are
double-ended ballers, scalloped ones, even top-shaped ones.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of unusually shaped ballers depends on the
texture of the food. With cantaloupe, the shapes turn out distinct,
but they are completely lost with ice cream, which melts and blurs
the shape almost immediately. And potatoes are simply too hard:
shaped ballers get wedged in them and cannot be fully turned.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what shape or size the melon baller is, success
depends almost entirely on technique. If you want perfectly smooth
spheres or tops or ovals, you must press down firmly and make two
complete rotations with the tool. And when scooping ice cream, it
is a good idea to immerse the baller in hot water before plunging
it into the ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   If you work quickly enough, you can create, as Wolf does, the
world's smallest ice cream sundae.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
