<HEADER>
A8324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      07-13 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ALSACE, RIESLINGS RISE TO THE OCCASION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than a few American winemakers are obsessed with the
riesling grape. With good reason: it is arguably the finest white
grape variety in the world. In the United States, which mostly
means California, riesling produces wines that are attractive,
friendly, uncomplicated and easy to like. These are good qualities
in an Airedale, not necessarily in a white wine.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with yet another batch of California rieslings, I
sometimes feel like the reluctant _ and ultimately exasperating _
swain in one of Bernard Malamud's stories. ``This one!'' cries the
matchmaker. ``This one you will really like.'' But he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between that unhappy man and me is this: I know
where the good ones are. They are in Germany _ no surprise to
anyone _ in the Rheingau, along the Mosel and in the Pfalz, all
renowned Germany wine regions.
</P>
<P>
   But the best _ and I'm going out on a limb here _ the very best,
come from Alsace.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful, bloody, tragic Alsace, for centuries a pawn on the
chessboard of tyrants. Fought over by Romans, Franks and Teutonic
knights; utterly destroyed during the Thirty Years' War in the 15th
century; French for two centuries, German from 1871, then French
again after World War I; German during World War II and now French
once more.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Alsace embodies the best of both cultures. As someone
once said of Alsatian cooking, ``German ingredients and French
flair.'' So, too, for Alsatian wines. The riesling is the
quintessential German grape; the Alsatians invest it with French
flair.
</P>
<P>
   Gewuerztraminer is Alsace's signature grape. Even people who
never drink it and have trouble pronouncing it (it's
geh-VOORTZ-trah-meen-er) can pick out its unmistakable, almost
dizzying aroma of litchi nuts and roses. But eventually one tires
of gewuerztraminer; it's too much of a good thing. Moreover, the
richer and more powerful it gets, the harder it is to match with
food.
</P>
<P>
   Not so Alsatian riesling. Its cousin across the Rhine is a
better food wine than most people give it credit for, but German
riesling at its best has some sweetness, and efforts to ferment it
completely dry have had only modest success. In Alsace, riesling
has always been a dry wine and, consequently, a food wine.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, its qualities are only enhanced by age. On several
occasions in the 1980s, I had a chance to sample Alsatian rieslings
from the 1920s that had the fruit and liveliness of wines a tenth
their age. In 1989, when the Hugel family of Riquewihr celebrated
its 350th anniversary in the wine business at a dinner at the
three-star Auberge de l'Ill, it served _ among many, many wines _
rieslings from 1900, 1934 and 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Describing a fine riesling is no easier than describing any
other wine, but words like steeliness and flowery come to mind.
Suffice it to say that, at its best, riesling offers unmatched
elegance and depth. And, unlike any other white wine, it grows more
subtle and complex as it ages.
</P>
<P>
   During the long years of German control from 1871 to the end of
World War I, Alsace was treated as a source of cheap wine, much of
it made from the chasselas grape, which is grown on the floor of
the valley that separates the Vosges Mountains from the Rhine. With
Alsace back in French hands in the years before World War II,
riesling and other noble grapes were replanted. Once again, the
vineyards crept up the slopes of the Vosges behind the picture-book
medieval towns from Thann in the south to Marlenheim and Nordheim,
just west of Strasbourg, in the north. Riesling grows best in the
higher vineyards of the Department of the Haut-Rhin, in communes
like Ribeauville, Riquewihr, Wintzenheim and Rouffach.
</P>
<P>
   Hugel et Fils in Riquewihr and F.E. Trimbach in Ribeauville are
probably the best-known producers of Alsatian wines in the United
States, thanks to the tireless salesmanship of Jean (Johnny) Hugel,
now retired, and Hubert Trimbach, and, not incidentally, the fine
wines they sell. Hugel wines are perhaps softer and more accessible
to newcomers to Alsatian wines; Trimbach wines are more austere.
There are critics who maintain that Trimbach's Riesling Clos
Ste.-Hune, made from a three-acre vineyard in the town of Hunawihr,
is the finest of all Alsatian wines. A clos is a relatively small
vineyard, usually surrounded by a stone wall.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dozens of producers of great Alsatian rieslings,
several stand out. Zind-Humbrecht, in Wintzenheim, is a favorite
among connoisseurs of Alsatian wines because the Humbrechts strive
to make each of their various wines reflect the soil from which it
comes. Thus a riesling from the Herrenweg vineyard in Turckheim,
where the soil is largely granite, is a different wine from a
Gueberschwihr riesling, which springs from limestone soil. My
favorites are the Zind-Humbrecht rieslings from the Clos Windsbuhl
vineyard, which is also limestone.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for a producer like Zind-Humbrecht to make
wines from many vineyards. It may own or lease some of them
entirely, and own or lease parts of others. Thus, Zind-Humbrecht
owns the 13-acre Clos St.-Urbain and farms the 11-acre Clos
Windsbuhl. In some years, the Humbrechts may produce 30 or more
different wines, including a dozen rieslings from half a dozen or
more vineyards, each in a different style.
</P>
<P>
   It is now just 20 years since Theo Faller died, leaving the
Domaine Weinbach in Kaysersberg in the hands of his wife, Colette,
and their two daughters, Catherine and Laurence. Laurence is now
the winemaker and each year produces as many as six different
rieslings, including the Cuvee Theo and the Cuvee Ste.-Catherine
from the Schlossberg Vineyard. Some of the best Domaine Weinbach
wines come from the Fallers' 13-acre Clos des Capucins, one of the
finest vineyards in Alsace.
</P>
<P>
   Other prominent Alsatian rieslings come from Marcel Deiss, Marc
Kreydenweiss, Schlumberger, Leon Beyer and Dopff Au Moulin.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind the fact that with good riesling, the old ``red
with the meat'' rule becomes meaningless. It may be a white wine,
but a fine Alsatian riesling has the power and the complexity to
match almost any red. The Alsatians are hunters and they love to
pair their wines with game birds, venison and wild boar. They drink
their riesling with regional specialties like choucroute or ham in
parsleyed jelly, with their marvelous local charcuterie and, of
course, with fish.
</P>
<P>
   Most American wine drinkers are still not entirely comfortable
with Alsatian wines, which is a boon to those who are. It means
prices are still reasonable. The great single vineyard rieslings
are very expensive, costing $100 and more a bottle, but there are
very good ones, still, for $10 to $15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
