<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-APOLLO-EAGLE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EAGLE HAS LANDED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By HOWARD MEANS  
 FROM: Washingtonian  
 &HT;    Thirty years ago this month at 4:17 and 40 seconds p.m. Eastern
Daylight Time on the afternoon of July 20, 1969, the Apollo 11
lunar landing module Eagle touched down on the moon's bone-dry Sea
of Tranquility.
 &HT;    Seconds later, the Eagle's 38-year-old civilian commander, Neil
Armstrong, radioed back to Earth what was to become the second most
memorable broadcast from outer space:
 &HT;    ``Houston, Tranquility Base here. The Eagle has landed.''
 &HT;    ``Roger, Tranquility,'' came the reply from the NASA mission
headquarters in Texas, ``we copy you on the ground. You've got a
bunch of guys about to turn blue. We're breathing again. Thanks a
lot.''
 &HT;    Six and a half hours would pass before Armstrong and Air Force
Col. Edwin ``Buzz'' Aldrin became the first earthlings to walk on
the moon. As he did so, Armstrong topped his earlier broadcast with
the 11 most famous words ever beamed back from the heavens:
``That's one small step for man, one giant leap for mankind.''
 &HT;    Above them orbited the only hope that Armstrong and Aldrin had
of returning home: the command module Columbia, piloted by Air
Force Col. Michael Collins.
 &HT;    The production values of the lunar broadcast watched that day
and night by hundreds of millions of people were terrible: grainy
black-and-white images delivered by choppy transmission to TV sets
that still weren't all that high in resolution themselves. But for
sheer drama, it was a moment almost impossible to top.
 &HT;    In the Oval Office, Richard Nixon placed a phone call that
traveled through the White House switchboard to the Goddard Space
Flight Center in Greenbelt, and from there to the Space Center in
Houston and via the Goldstone antenna in California to the two
astronauts posed in front of the TV camera they had planted on the
moon:
 &HT;    ``Hello, Neil and Buzz,'' the president began. ``I'm talking to
you by telephone from the Oval Room at the White House, and this
certainly has to be the most historic telephone call ever made.''
 &HT;    NASA never tired in those days of reminding the public of all
the scientific advances already spun off from the space program:
filtering systems that could remove dust and airborne bacteria from
a command module or an operating room, sensors that were equally
adept at measuring meteorite hits on a spacecraft or muscle tremors
that might signal the early stages of Parkinson's disease. The list
went on and on.
 &HT;    As for future space conquests, the public's imagination didn't
need much stoking _ a lunar base, space labs, space wars, a landing
on Mars. Once you've gotten to the moon, what's to stop you from
going anywhere, doing anything?
 &HT;    What were more fascinating in many ways than the Apollo
program's future science or even its spinoffs were the actual
science and mechanics that went into the Apollo 11 flight. And it
was a triumphal moment for the engineers as well as for the
scientists.
 &HT;    But just in case there were any doubts, it seemed a good idea at
the time to invoke the aid of as many supernatural forces as one
could think of.
 &HT;    Then-Sen. Eugene McCarthy, who had contended for the Democratic
presidential nomination in 1968, recalls his son's telling him that
at his Catholic elementary school all the students had been praying
as the Eagle left the command module for the lunar surface, but
nearly all of them had also kept their fingers crossed under their
desks.
 &HT;    ``I think most of us felt that way,'' McCarthy recalls.
 &HT;    In various areas of Washington, D.C., the power went out between
the Eagle's landing on the moon and the historic walk. A summer
thunderstorm had ripped through the area, sending broken limbs
crashing down on power lines.
 &HT;    Susan and Neil Sheehan hurried from their house in suburban
Wesley Heights to Neil's office at the New York Times' Washington
bureau to find a working television: ``Saw Neil Armstrong take
first step on moon!'' Susan Sheehan wrote in her dairy. ``Watched
with Neil and Max Frankel for an hour or two.''
 &HT;    Others had to catch it all on the fly. Current NASA chief
administrator Daniel Goldin was working for the TRW Space and
Technology Group in 1969. He was on his way to Harvard University
when the Eagle touched down.
 &HT;    ``I was changing planes at LaGuardia and everything came to a
halt,'' Goldin says. ``I remember there were many young people at
the airport that day _ people in uniform and people just on their
way. We watched the historic event on a black-and-white television
in the center of the lounge. For those few moments it didn't matter
what else was going on in the world. It felt great to be an
American.''
 &HT;    If the Apollo 11 mission now can be seen as a simple and pure
moment of triumph, it also has to be seen in its own time, and the
end of the 1960s was anything but simple. When and how you saw the
moon landing, and what it meant to you, had a lot to do with which
of the many conflicting realities of the day you happened to
inhabit.
 &HT;    A quick journey through the almanac of 1969 is a tour through a
tortured history. In Nigeria, the Biafran conflict and subsequent
starvation crisis became the first of a decades-long string of
highly publicized famines to sweep Africa. By mid-January more than
half a dozen planes had been hijacked to Cuba, and Cuban air maps
had become standard issue for U.S. commercial pilots.
 &HT;    The Six-Day War was over _ Arab forces had been trounced _ but
terrorism in the Middle East showed no signs of easing. In
February, the Palestine Liberation Organization was formed, under
the leadership of Yasir Arafat; less than six months later, Israeli
jets were striking Egyptian positions.
 &HT;    On March 10, 1969, James Earl Ray was sentenced to 99 years in a
Tennessee prison after he pleaded guilty to the murder of Martin
Luther King Jr., but for blacks that hardly seemed recompense. A
hundred African-American students seized the student union at
Cornell University on April 19.
 &HT;    Three months later, with Command Module Columbia still circling
the moon, Ohio Gov. James Rhodes called out the National Guard to
quell rioting in Columbus after the fatal shooting of a black man
by a white store owner. And then there was the war in Vietnam, and
the war here against the war there.
 &HT;    Alma Powell watched the walk on the moon in an Atlanta hotel
room. Beside her in bed, her husband, Colin, the future chair of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, slept like a log, having just flown in
that day from a second tour of duty in Vietnam.
 &HT;    Retired NASA scientist Homer Hickam, whose book ``Rocket Boys''
led to the wonderful movie ``October Sky,'' was just back from
Vietnam too when the Eagle set down.
 &HT;    ``I watched the landing in a Fort Lewis, Washington, barracks
television room with Army troops headed for Vietnam the next day,''
Hickam says. ``It was an eerie sensation being there with them,
giving advice on how to survive in Vietnam while we were waiting
for Neil to come down the ladder. ... I felt the irony of being
part of the greatest tragedy of the 1960s while watching one of the
century's greatest triumphs.''
 &HT;    Two years before Apollo 11 lifted off from the Kennedy Space
Center on its way to the moon, Navy pilot John McCain had been shot
down over North Vietnam and interned in the prisoner-of-war camp
known as the Hanoi Hilton.
 &HT;    McCain says he was ``overjoyed'' to learn of the moon landing
``but I didn't find out until two years later.'' McCain's source: a
speech by George McGovern broadcast through the prison camp in
which the Democratic presidential candidate said, ``The U.S. can
land a man on the moon, but it can't end the war.''
 &HT;    ``There were two different American visions colliding,'' says
Jeremy Rifkin, who today heads the Foundation on Economic Trends
and who then was coordinating the antiwar Citizens Commission of
Inquiry to investigate ``war crimes'' in Southeast Asia. ``We were
reaching beyond ourselves into outer space at the same time we were
involved in an epic struggle between generations and between
different visions of what the social contract was. The whole planet
was up for grabs.''
 &HT;    Not surprisingly, the Soviet Union, which had begun the space
race a dozen years earlier with the launch of Sputnik I, couldn't
leave the moment alone. The unmanned Soviet probe Luna 15 was in
its 27th orbit around the moon when Armstrong, Aldrin and Collins
arrived for their first orbit. Eventually Luna 15 would crash into
the moon about 500 miles from Tranquility Base.
 &HT;    For the Kennedy family, the Apollo 11 mission would have been a
double-edged sword in any event. The 1960s had begun with President
John F. Kennedy's pledge to put a man on the moon before the end of
the decade _ an audacious promise that seemed to signal a new,
audacious era.
 &HT;    Now, with only five months to spare, NASA was delivering on that
vow. But Jack Kennedy was dead, murdered five and a half years
earlier. So was brother Bobby, murdered only a little more than a
year before.
 &HT;    The political mantle of the Kennedy clan had fallen to Teddy,
the junior senator from Massachusetts, and the Washington Sunday
Star headline of July 20 speaks volumes: SPACEMEN SET TO LAND ON
MOON, the top headline reads. Just below it in slightly smaller
type is this headline: WOMAN DROWNS, KENNEDY UNINJURED.
 &HT;    For some people, Chappaquiddick Island and Tranquility Base
would be forever linked. Apollo 11 was still two days away from
Earth on July 22 when Ted and Joan Kennedy attended the funeral
service for Mary Jo Kopechne in Larksville, Pa. Photos of the event
show the senator looking broken and impossibly young.
 &HT;    For NASA too, Apollo 11 was a double-edged moment. Nothing could
have gone more perfectly, and because nothing could have, maybe
there was no topping that first manned landing on the moon.
 &HT;    NASA kept sending astronauts back to the moon _ there would be
six more flights in the Apollo series and five more landings on the
moon. But the last landing took place in December 1972, and by then
Americans were less enraptured. The deed had been done, and the
moon, for all its power in literature and the imagination, was an
undramatic place once you got there.
 &HT;    ``Even Walter Cronkite was getting bored,'' McCarthy remembers.
``He had announced at the first landing that the moon was a dead
body, which people had pretty much known at any rate. The second
time, he said it was deader than we thought. The third time, he
said it was even deader still. I guess there was nothing left to
say unless they discovered life on it.''
 &HT;    NASA's audience got tougher too. Many of those who cheered
Apollo 11 had been raised on Buck Rogers, Jules Verne, Superman and
Captain Midnight. Just behind them was a generation differently
conditioned.
 &HT;    The novelist Charles McCarry says that he and his wife, Nancy,
were ``enthralled'' by the moon landing but that their four
children, all under age 10, could not have been less interested:
``Sometime during the night I awoke an realized why: They and the
rest of their generation were the first cyborgs,'' McCarry says.
 &HT;    ``Their minds had been twinned with technology, and what was a
wonder to us was a perfectly ordinary moment for them. Having
watched television from infancy onward, they were used to having
their consciousness projected onto `Gilligan's Island' and beyond
at the flick of a switch. A trip to the moon was no different. They
required no imagination; the electromagnetic spectrum was their
constant companion.''
 &HT;    Not that NASA hasn't had its triumphs in the years since. Probes
sent to the edge of our planetary system and beyond have sent back
striking photos. The space station is a model of science and
international cooperation. Space exploration continues to spin off
high technology with far-ranging applications for life on Earth.
 &HT;    But budget pressures have squeezed the agency, and bureaucracy
seems in danger of stifling the burning curiosity that drove it in
the old days, or so many say. Goldin generally gets high marks for
his leadership, but he's leading a mature agency in a different
age.
 &HT;    Hickam says the secret to reviving the space program lies in the
rocket engine: ``NASA needs to get out of the low-earth orbit
operational business and hand it over swiftly to commercial
interests, and get on with the true exploration of space. To do
that it needs to build big new rocket drives based on fission,
fusion or anti-matter physics.
 &HT;    ``These drives are not science fiction. We can build one or more
of them in 10 years with a dedicated budget and necessary
legislative direction. Such drives will allow NASA to go out to the
moon in hours, to Mars in days. We can conquer, settle and exploit
the solar system with these machines during the next quarter
century.''
 &HT;    Maybe most important, such propulsion systems _ or whatever
other ones scientists might come up with _ would give NASA
something it hasn't had since that evening of July 20, 1969:
something, as F. Scott Fitzgerald once wrote, ``commensurate to our
capacity for wonder.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Washingtonian  
