<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8387 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-E-PRIVACY14-COX     07-13 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-PRIVACY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WEB PRIVACY REGULATION NEEDED, CONGRESSMAN INSISTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., were grading the
companies that sell goods and services on the Internet, he'd give
them a ``a big fat F'' for failing to protect the privacy of
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Why are so many lawmakers and regulators willing to give credit
to Internet companies, Markey wondered, ``merely for taking the
course while they fail the subject matter?''
</P>
<P>
   At a House Commerce subcommittee hearing on consumer privacy
Tuesday, Markey disagreed sharply with Federal Trade Commission
Chairman Robert Pitofsky, who recommended Congress not regulate the
way companies collect and use information from Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky, appointed by President Clinton, argued that companies
operating on the World Wide Web are ``on the right track'' in terms
of protecting consumers. He said he'd give industry a letter grade
of C for existing privacy protections, and a B-plus for
``improvement'' over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky said passing laws now would be ``premature'' because
companies need time to develop policies for self-regulation. Those
policies would give lawmakers a better idea of what works best to
protect consumer data.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, some federal legislation may be needed to reinforce
those self-regulatory efforts, but Congress would be wise to hold
off because ``we want to get it right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Markey scoffed at that recommendation, saying that no matter how
quickly technology changes, lawmakers still have a responsibility
to set ``standards that are eternal.'' In terms of the Internet, he
believes those standards should include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Notice. Web sites should offer clear notice of what privacy
practices apply. For example, will the company sell your personal
information to other marketers?
</P>
<P>
   _ Choice. Consumers should be able to grant or deny consent to
the privacy practices of the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   _ Access. Consumers should be able to see the information
collected by the Web site so they could correct mistakes and find
out who has purchased their data.
</P>
<P>
   _ Security. Information collected, such as credit card numbers,
must be protected by reasonable safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contact information. Consumers ought to be able to contact the
Web site's manager with questions or complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Markey noted that the nation's stock exchanges largely regulate
themselves and use fast-changing technology. Still, the federal
Securities and Exchange Commission oversees the exchanges and is
able to set standards for fairness. The federal government should
regulate Internet commerce in a similar fashion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
