<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REYNOLDS-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SAFEWAY EXECUTIVE QUENTIN REYNOLDS DIES AT 93 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ILENE LELCHUK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Quentin Reynolds, retired chief executive
officer of Safeway Stores, died June 30 at his home in Walnut
Creek. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds had been suffering from emphysema.
</P>
<P>
   A company man for five decades, Reynolds began working as a
clerk for the giant grocery chain's predecessor, Skaggs Cash
Stores, during his high school years. He joined Safeway in Oakland
in 1926, and one year later he was managing his first Safeway store
in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, he is credited with opening the Marina Safeway
in the 1950s, once a model store for future Safeways and now a
commercial landmark. He also opened the Safeway on Market Street.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds climbed the corporate ranks and was promoted to vice
president in 1956 and president in 1966. He was named chief
executive officer in 1969 and board chairman two years later.
</P>
<P>
   During Reynolds' reign in the 1970s, Safeway sales surpassed
those of grocery giant A&AMP;P, making Safeway the largest grocery
chain in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Former store manager George Erb of Orinda remembers that
Reynolds was best known for compassionate people skills and
appreciation of store managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to visit stores in the early morning just to get
acquainted with the employees there,'' remembered another longtime
co- worker, Louis Bianco, 89, of Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds retired in 1974 after 51 years with the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the last grocery men to leave the company. The
ones that came after him were the MBAs, accountant types,'' said
his eldest son, Edward Reynolds, 67, of Healdsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Also active in the community, Reynolds sat on boards for the San
Francisco and California chambers of commerce, San Francisco Boys
Club and the San Francisco Zoological Society, among others.
Reynolds was vice president of the Alameda County Coliseum
Foundation Inc. and a member of the Board of Regents of Saint
Mary's College, which named him Alumnus of the Year in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Praised for his business acumen, Reynolds was named by former
President Lyndon Johnson to the 16-member Executive Board of the
National Alliance of Businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds was born May 16, 1906, in San Rafael, and his father
worked nearby as a San Quentin Prison guard. When his parents died
in 1926, Reynolds left school to work full-time in grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds is survived by sons Edward Reynolds of Healdsburg, Jon
Quentin of Piedmont and Peter Melone of Berkeley; stepchildren
Jeanette Dunckel of San Francisco, Parker Maddux of San Francisco
and Jacklyn Maddux of North Carolina; 12 grandchildren; and 11
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
