<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORTGAGES-SAVINGS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LAW OFFERS SAVINGS ON MORTGAGE INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SHERI GRAVES   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ A new law taking effect Aug. 1 will save
money for home buyers who purchase property with a down payment of
less than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Homeowners Protection Act of 1997, signed into law on July
29, 1998, will curtail a long-standing practice of overcharging
homeowners for Private Mortgage Insurance _ PMI _ coverage that no
longer is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with private mortgage insurance, and the reason for
the new law, is that ``once a PMI policy was in place, the premiums
continued virtually forever,'' said John Witty, an industry analyst
from New Jersey who is touring the country as a spokesman for the
Mortgage Insurance Companies of America.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, PMI allows a home buyer to substitute insurance
coverage for the down-payment cash. The insurance policy, however,
should be canceled when the borrower's home equity reaches the
point where it is equal to or more than the customary 20 percent
down payment the borrower would have made had there not been a PMI
policy in place.
</P>
<P>
   Lenders were supposed to notify borrowers when it was time to
cancel the policy, but many didn't. Insurers had no responsibility
to cancel the policies at the appropriate time. Only eight states
had laws requiring the insurance to be canceled as soon as the
lender's risk of default was outweighed by the borrower's equity in
the property.
</P>
<P>
   The Homeowners Protection Act requires automatic cancellation of
private mortgage insurance once equity has reached 22 percent. Over
the course of a typical 30-year mortgage, eliminating the monthly
PMI premium will result in considerable savings.
</P>
<P>
   According to Witty, the monthly PMI premium depends on the risk,
which is weighed by the amount of the down payment, the size of the
loan, and the credit characteristics of the borrower. For loans
from $100,000 to $250,000, premiums range from $30 to $100 per
month.
</P>
<P>
   About 98 percent of the time, the borrower pays the PMI premium.
So-called lender-paid mortgage insurance typically involves loans
with a higher interest rate, so the borrower pays more for the loan
and in effect is paying for the insurance anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision of the new law allows borrowers to request
termination of private mortgage insurance when they've reduced
their loan to 80 percent of its original amount, thereby
accumulating the 20 percent equity that otherwise would have been
represented by the down payment. The law, however, also allows
lenders to require the borrower to pay for an appraisal to prove
the property has not depreciated in value. Borrowers may wish to
forego the cost of the appraisal and wait until the automatic
cancellation at 22 percent equity.
</P>
<P>
   Fixed-rate borrowers will receive an amortization schedule
showing exactly when PMI can be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   In another twist, the new law allows lenders to refuse to cancel
the insurance if the borrower does not have a ``good payment''
record. Generally you're in good stead if you do not have one
payment 30 days late within one year of a cancellation request, or
one payment 60 days late within two years of seeking an end to PMI
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, lenders can continue PMI up to 15 years
for so-called ``high-risk'' loans, regardless of equity. FHA
financing is not covered under the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good law that got lost in last year's Monica
mess,'' said Witty. ``The disclosure provisions will be for
existing loans as well as new ones, but the 20 percent and 22
percent provisions will apply only to new loans. People need to
keep an eye on their loan balance and contact the lender when that
20 percent equity point is reached.''
</P>
<P>
   Private mortgage insurance has been controversial since its
inception during the depression. The Federal Housing Administration
started issuing mortgage insurance in 1934. Private industry picked
up the ball in late 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sheri Graves writes for the The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa,
Calif., which is a member of The N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper
Group. This article was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.
 &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
