s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV18-     07-13 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Airline Policies Aim to Improve Service &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the possibility of new federal regulations, the
airline industry last month announced a series of new policies to
improve customer service. But it may be up to six months before the
reforms take effect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congress began considering new regulations after increased
complaints about service and a snowstorm in Detroit in January that
caused a huge airport tie-up, leaving thousands of Northwest
Airlines passengers stranded on planes for hours, within sight of
terminals; they had little food, and on-board lavatories were soon
unusable.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 major American passenger lines that belong to the Air
Transport Association, which says its members handle 95 percent of
all domestic air travel, said new policies would include the
following:
</P>
<P>
   _ Telephone reservations agents will always quote the lowest
available fare, and customers will be guaranteed that fare for 24
hours so they can comparison shop. Airlines will either honor the
fare for 24 hours or give full refunds on cancellations within that
period, the association said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Lost bags will be delivered, if possible, within 24 hours; the
airlines have asked the Department of Transportation to raise the
liability limit for lost baggage, which has been $1,250 a passenger
since 1984, and the department has proposed making it $2,500. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Notification of flight delays will be improved and, when
passengers face long delays aboard aircraft on the ground, every
reasonable effort will be made to provide food, water, restroom
facilities and access to medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Policies on the disabled, unaccompanied minors and
frequent-flier programs will be published and made readily
available to customers, and refunds will be made within seven days
for refundable tickets bought with credit cards and within 20 days
for tickets bought with cash.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines also promised within six months to develop clear
policies on compensating passengers who are forced to make an
unscheduled overnight stop because of flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   David Cay Johnston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Near Paris, a Salute To Saint-Gaudens &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Augustus Saint-Gaudens (1848-1907) is often called the American
Michelangelo, but his father was French and he studied in Paris,
participated in important Parisian salons and eventually retired to
a New Hampshire farm named after his father's village in the
Pyrenees.
</P>
<P>
   This year marks the first major retrospective of his work in
France: Through Oct. 18, over 100 of Saint-Gaudens' monumental
sculptures, portraits and numismatic designs, gleaned from public
and private collections, will be displayed at the 17th-century
Chateau de Blerancourt northeast of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   His celebrated public commissions include Civil War memorials to
Lincoln, Admiral Farragut, General Sherman, Col. Robert Gould Shaw
(on Boston Common) and the exquisite double-eagle gold coins
created at the behest of Theodore Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   More intimate works are also presented in this exhibition _
informal portraits, delicate cameo jewelry, and a copy of the
sweetly elegant Diana, the sculptor's only female nude, which first
served as a weathervane atop the original Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Blerancourt Museum, founded in 1924 by Anne Morgan, is a
particularly appropriate showcase, as one of the most important
featured works, Amor Caritas, a sculpture of a winged angel, is
based on a funerary monument that Saint-Gaudens designed for the
J.P. Morgan family; Anne Morgan was J.P. Morgan's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The Musee National de la Cooperation Franco-Americaine, (33-3)
23.39.60.16, is about 70 miles northeast of Paris, by taking the A1
to Exit 9, and then heading toward Soissons. It is open daily
except Tuesday. Tickets cost $3.80 (at 6.35 francs to $1), under 18
free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corinne LaBalme &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suites and Nothing But At 2 Vancouver Hotels &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Vancouver have two new luxury all-suite hotels to
choose from. The Sheraton Suites Le Soleil, which opened in March
at 567 Hornby Street, sits about two blocks from the cruise
terminals and is in the heart of the business district.
</P>
<P>
   The 122 suites are furnished in crimson and gold, with silk
brocade coverlets, down duvets and Biedermeier-style furniture.
Each has two-line speaker phones with data ports and high-speed
Internet access. The hotel's restaurant, Oritalia, features Asian
and Mediterranean-style preparations. Doubles are $284 (at $1.48
Canadian to the American dollar); (604) 632-3000 or (877)
632-3030. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 207-room Westin Grand Vancouver, which opened in April at
433 Robson Street in the entertainment district, is built in the
shape of a grand piano. The decor is minimalist, with a largely
neutral color scheme. Each suite is equipped with a kitchenette, a
data port and two phone lines. Rates range from $148 to $236; (604)
602-1999.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa A. Trainer &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denmark Sheds Some Light on Dark Ages &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denmark has proclaimed 1999 its Medieval Year, highlighting the
many archeological digs, burial mounds, churches and museums that
offer information on the period from about 1000, when the Danes
turned from paganism to Christianity, to 1536, the year of the
Reformation. More than 400 events, including lectures and
workshops, have been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bright Ages,'' an exhibition at the National Museum in
Copenhagen, includes artifacts and reconstructed scenes designed to
demonstrate that the period was more colorful than the term Dark
Ages would suggest. It runs through Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   At the Moesgaard Museum near Aarhus in Jutland, medieval
manuscripts collected from research libraries throughout Europe,
including the Vatican Library, are on display, many of them never
before on public view. Some were written on parchment in
monasteries; some manuscripts are illustrated with pictures of
daily life and religious observances.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will be given a chance to try their hands at writing
with a quill pen. On Sept. 15 the exhibition will move to the Royal
Library in Copenhagen until Jan. 1, where it will occupy a new wing
called the Black Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   In Odense on July 27 and 28, the Medieval Days festival, on the
site of a 15th century military camp, will feature tournaments,
mock battles, archery contests and handicrafts.
</P>
<P>
   Through Oct. 24 on the island of Funen, Nyborg Castle, once the
royal palace, will display toys and other artifacts relating to
children's lives in the Middle Ages. The castle's halls are notable
for their thick walls, heavy oak ceilings and worn floor tiles.
</P>
<P>
   At the European Medieval Festival on Aug. 27 and 28 in Horsens
in Jutland, knights in armor will do battle. Musicians and street
entertainers will perform in the city center, and medieval food
will be sold at inns. After sunset flaming torches will replace
street lights.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Danish Tourist Board, (212) 885-9700 or
www.middelalder.dk.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
