<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A WOMAN IS STILL HER OWN BEST DETECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat (Santa Rosa, Calif.)   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One night Betsy Hall was watching a TV movie of the week about a
woman who gets cancer and then her husband leaves her. It was a
pretty bad movie, she said, and she told herself to either turn off
the TV or lie down on the bed and do a breast exam.
</P>
<P>
   She did the exam, suddenly felt the thing you never want to
feel, called her husband to verify ``It's a lump, isn't it?'' and
the next day was at the doctor's office. It was breast cancer and
she had a mastectomy. Now, five years later, she believes that you
can't get too many reminders to pay attention. In her case, she
says it was, ``Bad movie; good choice.''
</P>
<P>
   For a subject so long denied by scared women and a squeamish
media, breast cancer is now a common theme for novels, movie plots,
magazine articles, health studies and endless speculation by women
who are still scared but are definitely more on watch.
</P>
<P>
   A friend who lives in the Midwest thinks of breast cancer as a
tornado _ impossible to predict or tell whether it will hit your
house or your friend's across town. But it's coming and it's close.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend recently confided, ``I've had a shift in my
thinking. I used to think breast cancer would never happen to me.
Now I think it will.''
</P>
<P>
   I told Betsy Hall of my friend's cold certainty, hoping that she
would reassure her and the rest of us worried well people that we
don't have to be THAT accepting. Betsy wondered if my friend had
become obsessed by it and I said no, that she's decided to be more
diligent so she can catch it at the earliest stage.
</P>
<P>
   Smart woman, said Betsy. Better to feel it's inevitable than to
feel you're invincible.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy's a psychotherapist in Santa Rosa, Calif., who leads
support groups for women with cancer. Last year she started one
specifically for women who are newly diagnosed and has since added
one for women whose cancer has advanced. Betsy knows a lot about
the tornado.
</P>
<P>
   But she doesn't know anymore than the rest of us about
preventing it or curing it. In spite of all the talk about breast
cancer there's still more theory and speculation than solid,
reassuring breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Every study seems to bring a counter study. We swear off a
certain food and then suddenly it's acceptable. Then comes a new
drug that one research group says shows ``welcome encouragement,''
and another says should be ``viewed with caution.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember when we weren't supposed to eat fat? Then this spring
came the Nurses Health Study saying that a low-fat diet was good in
many ways but it didn't seem to make much of a difference with
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Hormone replacement pills were almost a certain danger until
Chicago researchers last month said maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, we're advised to avoid breast cancer by
eating more broccoli and cauliflower, load up on the soy, drink
bottled water, don't delay having children and breast feed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some women with all the risk factors never get breast cancer
and some who take the best of care, like the very organic Betsy
Hall, do.
</P>
<P>
   Still, every suspicious food or even flawed study is beneficial
to know about because they keep women on their guard, says Betsy,
who leans across the lunch table and asks, ``Do you self examine?''
</P>
<P>
   While I was writing this I got a call telling me that a woman
I've long admired, Woody Schwartz, had died. Woody spent her life
working for justice in every dark corner of the world. Everyone
knew she had breast cancer and that in the last few years it had
spread to her bones.
</P>
<P>
   Woody's husband Arnie said, ``Here's something women should
know'' and told me that 15 years ago no doctor or mammogram
detected Woody's breast cancer. Woody looked in her mirror and
noticed a strange dimpling in one breast. Ten years later she saw
something suspicious in the other breast. That cancer had spread to
her lymph nodes. ``Don't trust the experts,'' he said. ``Trust
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif., a member of The N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Swartz's e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
