worsening trade tensions with Europe over genetically engineered
foods, the Clinton administration said Tuesday for the first time
that it would conduct long-term studies on the safety of altered
farm products. But it insisted it would use all its legal remedies
to compel Europe to accept American farm products like soybeans and
corn even if that means placing tariffs on European-made goods this
summer. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
