<HEADLINE>
SOSA GOES TO BAT FOR WORLD `ALL-STARS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w, a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ You think the all-stars are all at Fenway Park
today?
</P>
<P>
   Only some of them, says Chicago Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa. In his
eyes, there also are ``all-stars of the world,'' people such as Li
Jun Cai of China, Loti Sareyo of Tanzania, and the Hyseni family
from Kosovo, who found a new home in Milton but are still far
afield from Fenway's spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Not one plays professional baseball, but the nonprofit
Interaction organization, capitalizing on the All-Star Game in
Boston and Sosa's fame, is presenting them and eight others as
hidden stars _ people who thrived in far corners of the world after
receiving US foreign assistance.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill today, enough private charity workers to fill
two baseball teams will distribute to members of Congress packs of
baseball cards with the pictures of these beneficiaries and their
life stories on the back. And yes, the packs come with bubblegum.
</P>
<P>
   There also will be a centerfold of Sosa slugging a baseball.
Next to his picture is a quote from him: ``With the support of
Interaction's members and the resources of the United States,
millions of the world's poor improve their situation. Please take a
moment to read about some of these `All-Stars,' the MVPs of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be the public relations equivalent of throwing a fat
pitch down the middle, but Interaction, a large coalition of
private aid groups, believes the cards get out the message that US
foreign aid can reap big benefits.
</P>
<P>
   A US House Appropriations subcommittee will take up the fiscal
2000 foreign aid bill Wednesday The Clinton administration has
requested $14.6 billion for foreign operations next year, but a
Senate bill whittled that down to $12.7 billion. US foreign
assistance has declined steadily over the last decade despite a
robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   Ian M. Houston, Interaction's legislative director, dreamed up
the baseball card pitch on a plane ride from Washington to Salt
Lake City six months ago. Sosa, he believed, would be a natural
spokesman because ``he grew up in poverty in the Dominican
Republic, he himself is a great success story, and he helped others
after Hurricane Mitch last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa couldn't be reached for comment, but he isn't expected to
make a pitch for the unsung ``All-Stars'' during the Boston
festivities, Houston said.
</P>
<P>
   That will be done by the Washington advocates, who will use the
cards to tell their story.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign news too often is about disasters and conflict, Houston
said, adding, ``But there are success stories out there. These
images are not the typical ones that Americans see.''
</P>
<P>
   There's ``All-Star'' Li Jun Cai, 8, shown sitting happily among
100 ducklings. The boy's family received assistance from the Heifer
Project, based in Little Rock, Ark., which has helped thousands of
Chinese farmers raise low-cost livestock such as ducks, geese and
rabbits.
</P>
<P>
   There's Loti Sareyo of Tanzania, who learned from the Heifer
Project how to build ridges and drainage ditches across the steep
slope of his garden. Gaining profits from soil-conservation
techniques, Sareyo has been able to build a cement house for his
family.
</P>
<P>
   There's the Hyseni family, who resettled from Kosovo to Milton,
with the help of the International Institute of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   And there's also Ren Je of China, holding in his arms a rabbit
from his family's farm; relatives Sunita and Sunanya Gurung of
Nepal, who received a small loan to expand their farm; and Quratul
Ain Bakhteari of Pakistan, who with the help of US charities
doubled girls' enrollments in regional schools.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this all-star push in a city that hasn't had a professional
baseball team since the Washington Senators last played in 1971
isn't expected to win immediate dividends, Houston acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often they (members of Congress) get these things and they
just toss it,'' he said. ``They won't toss this . . . and they may
find a few positive stories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
