<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAYS OF FIGS AND HONEY ARE HERE, BORNE ON A BED OF ICE CREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By THOMAS KELLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)This is the last of eight columns by Thomas Keller, the
chef and owner of the French Laundry in Yountville, Calif. His
collaborator has been Michael Ruhlman. Next week: Waldy Malouf, the
chef of and a partner in Beacon in Manhattan.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is just one of those great recipes, because it's so easy
and so satisfying. Hot figs and cold ice cream with honey _ that's
virtually all there is to it. You don't even have to make the ice
cream: buy some, let it sit until it's pliable and fold in the
honey.
</P>
<P>
   To make it even simpler, drizzle the honey on top of the ice
cream, or add it to the pan when you cook the figs. However you
want to incorporate the honey is fine.
</P>
<P>
   But it's important to use a honey of good quality. Taste a
variety and find one that you like. In the Napa Valley, there are a
lot of wildflowers and many people who gather honey, so wildflower
is the kind I like to use.
</P>
<P>
   The summertime here also brings an overabundance of figs on the
order of what most people have with tomatoes. So I serve figs in
salad, with lobster, for dessert or in a sauce.
</P>
<P>
   They arrive in two stages, the first crop in late spring, the
second in July. The later crop is high in sugar, perfect for this
dish. I usually use Mission and Brown Turkey varieties, but any fig
will work, as long as it's ripe and wonderful to eat just as it is.
The baking essentially turns the fig into a sauce within its own
skin.
</P>
<P>
   The vanilla bean, cooked and served with the fig, provides
additional flavor and visual components. Typically, vanilla bean is
incorporated into a preparation, like sauce anglaise. Here it's a
separate element, and it's fun to scrape the seeds out of the pod
and eat them with the ice cream and warm buttery sauce.
</P>
<P>
   I love the hot and cold combination in this dessert. It reminds
me of banana splits and hot fudge sundaes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VANILLA ROASTED FIGS WITH WILDFLOWER HONEY ICE CREAM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes plus chilling and freezing for the ice cream;
20 minutes for the figs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the ice cream:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   { cup wildflower honey
</P>
<P>
   12 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sugar &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the figs:
</P>
<P>
   18 ripe figs (Black Mission, Brown Turkey, Adriatic Green or a
combination), washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   4 vanilla beans, split lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons sugar. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare the ice cream: in a large saucepan, combine the milk,
cream and honey. Place over medium heat, and stir. When honey is
completely dissolved, remove pan from heat and allow to cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. With an electric mixer, or by hand in a metal bowl, whisk egg
yolks and sugar until they have thickened and lightened in color.
Gradually whisk in the warm milk mixture. Return mixture to
saucepan and place over medium-low heat. Stir until mixture coats
the back of a wooden spoon and reaches 175 degrees; do not
overheat. Immediately remove from heat and transfer to a mixing
bowl. Chill bowl by placing it in ice water, and allow mixture to
cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   3. Strain mixture into a container. Cover, and refrigerate for
at least 5 hours, or overnight. Freeze in an ice cream maker
according to manufacturer's instructions; then, transfer to a
covered container. Freeze for several hours, or until hardened.
</P>
<P>
   4. Prepare figs: slice off and discard tops of figs. Cut split
vanilla beans into 2-inch pieces. Make a small slit in top of each
fig, and insert a section of vanilla bean.
</P>
<P>
   5. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In an ovenproof pan large enough
to hold all the figs standing upright, melt butter over medium
heat. Add sugar, and stir to dissolve. Stand figs in the butter,
and add any remaining vanilla bean pieces to pan. Place pan in oven
until figs are thoroughly heated, about 10 minutes. Serve figs warm
or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve, place a scoop of ice cream into each of six bowls.
Arrange three of the figs (with vanilla bean) around each scoop.
Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
