A8419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      07-13 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOY SAUCE AND FISH: MATCH MATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cooking food in soy sauce is a tantalizing idea, but it can be
tricky. In large quantities the flavor is overpowering, and in
lesser amounts the sauce often burns, giving off a sharp,
unappealing aroma.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder soy sauce is most often used as a condiment. But it
actually makes a fine poaching liquid for fish, as long as you thin
it with water to prevent the burning and cut the saltiness (a
little sugar helps, too).
</P>
<P>
   The basic liquid can be enhanced with many different
combinations of seasonings, like minced ginger and garlic; the
juice of a lime and a tablespoon or so of sesame oil, or a little
wasabi paste and a garnish of shredded daikon. But it can be even
simpler _ often I just add a handful of chopped scallions and a
dried chili or two, or two or three spring onions or one yellow
onion, peeled and sliced.
</P>
<P>
   Bring the soy mixture to a boil, add the fish fillet or fish
steak, and poach, turning a few times. You'll be rewarded with
mahogany-colored, intensely flavored fish. The dish can be
garnished with the cooked scallions, and the poaching liquid _
slightly reduced, but now enhanced by the flavor of the fish _
makes a fine sauce for rice.
</P>
<P>
   Besides choosing good soy sauce _ find a brand you like, and
stick with it _ the one basic consideration is how much water to
add. If your soy sauce is mild, almost sweet (the kind you would
happily use as a plain dip for sushi), you can dilute it with an
equal part of water. But if it is strong and highly salty, use two
parts water to one part soy.
</P>
<P>
   The other decision is what kind of fish to poach. Striped bass,
now at the peak of its season, is a good suggestion. Supplies are
plentiful because this meaty, flavorful fish has, in recent years,
made a great comeback from overfishing and contamination.
</P>
<P>
   I've used this same preparation for halibut, monkfish and
salmon. If you use cod, undercook it slightly so it doesn't fall
apart. Red snapper, sea bass, swordfish and even sea scallops also
work, but they should be cooked for only three or four minutes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STRIPED BASS POACHED IN SPICY SOY SAUCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One-third to { cup good soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   { to two-thirds cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   About 15 scallions, trimmed and cut into 2-inch lengths, or 2 or
3 spring onions or 1 large onion, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 dried or fresh chili, optional
</P>
<P>
   About 1{ pounds striped bass fillet, about 1 inch thick. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine the soy sauce, water, sugar, scallions and chili in a
skillet just large enough to hold the fish. Turn the heat to
medium-high, and bring to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add the fish and adjust the heat so the mixture bubbles, but
not furiously. Cook 8 to 10 minutes, turning once or twice, until
the fish is coated with a brown glaze and cooked through. Serve
with white rice, spooning the sauce over all and garnishing with
the scallions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
