<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Candido Salice Salentino Riserva 1994, Apulia, Italy. About $7.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who doubts that Italy offers the world's best wine
bargains has only to try a bottle of this little gem. Salice
Salentino is one of eight wine districts in Apulia, in the extreme
southeast of Italy on the Adriatic coast.
</P>
<P>
   This is an estate-grown and produced wine, which means all the
grapes come from the Candido vineyards. The blend is 85 percent
negroamaro grapes and 15 percent malvasia nera. Although virtually
unknown in this country, negroamaro is an important grape in Italy.
Some 75,000 acres of it are planted south and east of Naples.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, negroamaro produces a wine very similar to a good
Chateauneuf-du-Pape. This is no Chateauneuf, but it is a solid,
full-flavored red wine with plenty of character. And the price for
a bottle is less than what most New York restaurants charge for a
glass of their cheap stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
