<HEADER>
A8424 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIKE-SPORTSBRA-COX     07-13 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIKE-SPORTSBRA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soccer's bra-haha a boost for Nike
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So Brandi Chastain whipped off her jersey after the winning goal
in the Women's World Cup, exposing a downright chaste-looking
undergarment. What's the big deal?
</P>
<P>
   Her bra was designed as outerwear in the first place, Nike says.
</P>
<P>
   The company is so thrilled about Saturday evening's ``exposure''
_ ``momentary insanity,'' Chastain called it _ that it's giving its
post-World Cup ad campaign another look, a Nike spokesman says.
</P>
<P>
   Which means you might see that now-famous bra moment many, many,
many more times.
</P>
<P>
   The bra seen by millions is part of a new line Nike is launching
at the end of the month. And Chastain and four of her teammates
have apparel deals with Nike.
</P>
<P>
   Which has people wondering: While no one could have known the
game would end up on penalty kicks, much less that Chastain would
take the final one, was the bra-baring a setup? USA Today called it
``a conveniently revealing moment for Nike.''
</P>
<P>
   The company says it was a complete surprise. Will Chastain get
anything extra anyway? ``A huge thank-you,'' says Nike spokesman
Kathryn Reith. ``We haven't talked about anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain is one of several woman athletes (teammates Tiffeny
Milbrett and Tisha Venturini included) who talked to Nike last year
about what a good sports bra needs.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to their gripes (too-tight bras, chafing,
breast-squishing, not enough support, sweat traps) and advice, Nike
developed a line of six sports bras called Inner Active. Chastain
wore one during Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   The bras should reach stores in early August, and already are on
the Nike Web site under women's fitness apparel, Reith says. Price:
$40.
</P>
<P>
   Reith says Nike fitted the women's soccer team in April and
offered the bras to whoever wanted them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Reith says, ``I'm still trying to figure out who wore
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally, she says, Nike planned on making just one
``ultimate'' bra. But the athletes (tennis' Mary Pierce and Lindsey
Davenport among them) had various needs depending on breast size.
</P>
<P>
   ``The D-cup women want support, support, support,'' says Reith,
who reports that some women, frustrated, would wear two or three
bras at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smaller-busted women, like Brandi, didn't want to be
squished flat,'' Reith says. So Nike made six styles _ two for
smaller women, two for regular and two for large. Some are
racerback, like Chastain's, and others have the more traditional
adjustable back and straps.
</P>
<P>
   What does a sports bra need, anyway? Examples:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``When you run in a bra, the breasts move in kind of a flat
figure-eight pattern, not just up and down,'' Reith says. So Nike
added side panels for stability.
</P>
<P>
   -- Seams that don't chafe. Instead of putting seams on the tops
of the shoulders, the company moved them to the upper back.
</P>
<P>
   -- Wicking, to draw sweat away from the skin.
</P>
<P>
   A sports bra, Reith says, is ``an incredible piece of
equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   And on Saturday, it seems, Nike got incredibly lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was screaming,'' Reith says, ``and when I saw what bra it
was, I screamed even louder.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
