<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ALIBABA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALI BABA AND THE 40 THIEVES': ENJOYABLE, BUT FALLS SHORT OF
ENCHANTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story of ``Ali Baba and the 40 Thieves'' didn't make much of
an impression on me as a child. The idea of a magic password was
fun: two secret words (``Open, sesame'') that would make solid
mountain rocks move, allowing entrance into a secret cave. But when
Ali found all that stolen treasure inside, I lost interest. Maybe
children today have a greater appreciation of how much a huge cache
of jewels and gold coins could change their lives.
</P>
<P>
   HBO's ``Happily Ever After: Fairy Tales for Every Child,'' a
monthly series of familiar tales retold with particular attention
to sexual equality, takes on ``Ali Baba'' Wednesday night, and this
time the title character is a girl. (Ally McBeal, Ali MacGraw, Ali
Baba, what's the difference?) The resulting half-hour of animation
_ written by Gerard Brown, based on an adaptation by Anna Quindlen,
the novelist and former columnist for The New York Times, falls
short of enchanting. But it should make for enjoyable enough
viewing for children.
</P>
<P>
   If only a lot of it didn't look like a rehash of ``The Little
Mermaid,'' ``Beauty and the Beast'' and several other Disney
animated films. Sure enough, Ali (with the voice of Jurnee
Smollett), who is headed out into the desert on her daily errands,
has a couple of cute animal sidekicks (in this case, a personable
camel and a pet snake). Sure enough, there are a couple of perky
musical numbers. Sure enough, there's a big, muscular guy with an
IQ of about 12 (Ali's brother, Cassim, who seems to spend his time
being fanned and fed by adoring girls who aren't as self-actualized
as Ali).
</P>
<P>
   In this version of the story Cassim (Tommy Davidson) manages to
get into the cave and becomes very excited about the vast wealth
inside, but then he can't remember the password to get out. ``Open
seven days'' is one of his many wrong guesses. It's a long story,
but he ends up covered in molten gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali Baba'' never really resolves the moral issue of profiting
from crime. In the end Ali takes only as much of the treasure as
she and her grandmother (Marla Gibbs) really need. But that still
leaves a message that taking stolen goods is sometimes OK.
</P>
<P>
   As HBO continues this series, it also might be nice to see a
script without someone saying, in one way or the other, ``You're
just a girl,'' then putting the heroine in the position of proving
her worth. Next time, let's just see a girl have an adventure and
behave bravely and confidently just because girls do, not because
someone insulted her.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HAPPILY EVER AFTER: FAIRY TALES FOR EVERY CHILD'
</P>
<P>
   Ali Baba and the 40 Thieves
</P>
<P>
   7:30 p.m. ET Wednesday on HBO
</P>
<P>
   Donna Brown Guillaume, Meryl Marshall, Willard Carroll and
Thomas L. Wilhite, executive producers; Libby Simon, producer;
directed by Anthony Bell; story by Anna Quindlen; teleplay by
Gerard Brown; narrated by Robert Guillaume; Spencer Proffer, music
director. A Two Oceans Entertainment Group/Confetti Entertainment
Company/Hyperion Studio Entertainment production.
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of: Jurnee Smollett (Ali Baba), Marla Gibbs
(Grandmother) and Tommy Davidson (Cassim).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1655EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
