<HEADER>
A8436 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAL-MAN'S-COOKBOOK-N     07-13 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-MAN'S-COOKBOOK-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN, START YOUR OVENS.  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DIANE PETERSON   Santa Rosa (Calif.)   The Press Democrat,    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Now there's a no-nonsense, ``Real Man's
Cookbook'' for guys who don't eat quiche, but do want to bake their
own bread, brew their own ale and basically ``steak out'' their own
territory in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   With his tongue planted firmly in cheek, David Bowers wrote
``Bake It Like a Man'' (William Morrow, 1999, $16) as a
quasi-humorous guide for men who want to take back the knife _ the
cleaver, the garlic press and the wire whisk _ to prove their
status as ``high priests of self-sufficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite healthy servings of humor _ and help from his wife,
Sharon, a food-writer, the book is dead serious about men's right
to do it their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kitchen is the last frontier for modern man; and no, no,
he doesn't need any help, thanks,'' Bowers states in the
introduction. ``Real men aren't looking to rush things. We want to
do things a certain way, and we want that way to be the man's
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Some specific rules: a real man doesn't work with leftovers;
ingredients must be pristine, of the highest quality, organic if at
all possible. Also, real men are not daunted by big, imposing
projects and treat their kitchens like a domestic laboratory. (If
you doubt any of the above, check out Jeffrey Steingarten's
imposing tome, ``The Man Who Ate Everything.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Bake It Like a Man'' gets cooking with a chapter on tools
entitled ``Men and Hardware.'' The joy of hand-to-hand combat with
dough is detailed in a chapter on baking bread and pizza, followed
by a juicy discussion of ``Men and Meat'' and ``Men and Flame'' _
``the smoke, the fire, the raw meat in our tongs, the wind in our
hair ... it's an elemental experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The age-old taunt _ my pot is bigger than yours _ is replayed in
the chapter on ``Men and Big Food.'' We're talkin' turkey here,
plus crowd-pleasing recipes for paella, jambalaya and Big Fat
Italian Lasagna. The gut-bustin' fun continues with ``Men and
Fat,'' which offers recipes for Cadillac Mac and Cheese and Classic
Fettuccine Alfredo, among other rich favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men and Hot Foods,'' ``Men and Fermentation,'' and ``Pommmes
des Hommes,'' round out the book, along with a final ``Brass
Tacks'' guide to the basics, from making Marinara Sauce to the
Perfect Caesar Salad.
</P>
<P>
   My husband, who wooed me by making a mustard-shrimp dish from
``The Silver Palate Cookbook'' then retreated from the kitchen for
the next 12 years, is definitely getting a copy of ``Bake it Like a
Man'' as a gift.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be duct-taped to the blowtorch he'll use to finish
off the Creme Brulee recipe on page 131 _ and to clean up after
he's done.
</P>
<P>
   David Bowers writes: I am a long time connoisseur of huevos
rancheros, and the recipe below is the result of years of
tinkering. The basic dish is heated tortillas with fried eggs,
grated cheese and a hefty dose of Salsa Cruda. Over time, I've
gradually made little adjustments to the topping that have improved
it dramatically. The hint of cinnamon and beef stock make a more
full-bodied salsa, the touch of chipolte adds a smoky richness,
while the dish remains simple.
</P>
<P>
   HUEVOS RANCHEROS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 hefty serving
</P>
<P>
   3 corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup salsa
</P>
<P>
   1/4 beef bouillon cube (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 canned chipolte pepper en adobo finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated melting cheese (such as mozzarella, Jack, or
Havarti)
</P>
<P>
   Chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Heat a dry cast iron or other unlined skillet over high heat and
put a tortilla in each for 10 seconds per side, until they start to
color. Remove to a plate, overlapping in a cloverleaf pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a tablespoon or two of olive oil in a skillet and fry the
eggs in whatever style you like. I like yolks soft for this dish.
</P>
<P>
   While the eggs are frying, heat the salsa in a small saucepan
over medium heat with the beef bouillon cube, cinnamon, and
chipolte. Stir the salsa well and heat through.
</P>
<P>
   Spread a few spoons of the sauce over the tortillas. Lay the
eggs on the sauce-spread tortillas. Pour the remaining sauce over
the top of the eggs. Sprinkle generously with the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Place the plate under the broiler for 3 to 5 minutes, until the
cheese melts completely. Garnish with cilantro, if desired. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
