<SLUG> BC-LAST-CODE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEGRAPH STATION TAPS ITS LAST CODE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALF MOON BAY, Calif. _ In the age of satellites and dot.coms,
the last distinctive dots and dashes of commercial telegraph
transmission faded into history Monday night at four telegraph
stations in North America.
</P>
<P>
   At just before 5 p.m. Pacific time, Globe Wireless sent out its
last transmission. The company signed off the air using the same
line Samuel F.B. Morse, inventor of the telegraph, used in the
first message he sent in 1844 from Washington, D.C., to his
assistant in Baltimore: ``What hath God wrought?''
</P>
<P>
   Among those on hand was Dalton Bergstedt, 92, who 27 years ago
managed this small marine communications station, surrounded by
cows and radio towers, which beamed messages by Morse code to ships
across the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being home again,'' who needed a cane to steady
himself as he sat in a swivel chair before the radio telegraph
machine.
</P>
<P>
   The Half Moon Bay station and three others were the last in
North America to broadcast ship-to-shore messages by Morse code.
</P>
<P>
   Globe Wireless, based in Foster City, confirmed what many in the
shipping business have long said: The telegraph is as obsolete as
the horse and buggy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three decades, ships have been shifting to other
technologies: satellite communications, high-frequency radios and
most recently electronic mail, which allows ships to send vast
amounts of information at speeds much faster than any telegraph
operator can type.
</P>
<P>
   But for operators like Bergstedt, the change is bittersweet.
Though ships may benefit from the new technology, it also means the
end of the line for radio telegraph operators _ known
affectionately as ``sparks'' for the electric sparks originally
generated by the friction of the early telegraph transmitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad event for me, but I know it's for the best,''
Bergstedt said. ``It will improve maritime communications (to be)
much better than they ever were.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipping lines were among the last companies to give up the
telegraph. While land-based businesses long ago moved to using
phones, fax machines and other communications technology, seamen
appreciated the dependability of the radio telegraph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very solid, reliable form of communication for all
these years,'' said Tim Gorman, director of operations for the Half
Moon Bay station for Globe Wireless. ``But nowadays it's just too
slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Speed has been the Achilles heel of the radio telegraph. The
pace of the Morse code messages is limited by typing speed. To earn
a first- class license, operators have to type at least 25 words a
minute, retired operator John Brundage, 72, said. For a
second-class license, the minimum speed is 18 words a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Some also complain that radio telegraph systems are limited in
the amount and kinds of data they can transport.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you send a drawing via Morse code? How do you send a
picture via Morse code?'' said Peter Kierans, a vice president for
corporate development of Globe Wireless, which is intent on selling
ships e-mail systems.
</P>
<P>
   Kierans said today's shipping lines are trying to run their
ships with minimal crews and see hiring a radio operator as too
costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of having a skilled radio person on each ship
doesn't fit into today's method of operation,'' he said. ``It's an
extra expense.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tasks that radio operators on ships used to perform
have now been automated as well, making the radio operator less
relevant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the International Marine Organization, a United Nations
agency, established the Global Maritime Distress and Safety System.
Instead of having operators relay ``SOS'' in writing, anyone on the
ship can simply push a specific button that indicates a certain
problem _ sinking, capsizing, dead in the water. A signal then is
automatically sent out to the nearest vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Bart Lee, a radio telegraph history buff who will be teaching a
course on the history of telecommunications at Golden Gate
University next fall, says Morse code won't become a dead language.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be hobbyist uses,'' Lee said. ``The
amateur radio operators still operate Morse code. You can hear it
any night on any band.''
</P>
<P>
   Some countries, like China and Russia, have been slow to make
the transition away from radio telegraph and may not change for
years, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   To some veteran telegraph operators, the move away from Morse
code is risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Satellites go down,'' said Denice Stoops, who says she was the
first female radio operator in the United States when she began in
1979, but lost her job when Globe Wireless bought and closed the
Point Reyes marine radio station in 1997. ``I think this will still
remain as the most reliable and probably the cheapest and most
dependable in an emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bergstedt recalls when he took a distress call from a passenger
liner that struck a reef off Mexico's coast in 1931 and was sinking
fast. The freighter he was on was just 40 miles away, and was able
to respond fast enough to save the passengers and crew.
</P>
<P>
   But the incident more often recalled came after the Titanic
struck an iceberg and the ship's telegrapher dispatched an urgent
call for help. Some 1,500 Titanic passengers and crew died.
</P>
<P>
   Another ship, the Californian, was nearby, but its radio
operator had gone off duty and never heard the messages.
</P>
<P>
   Brundage said people should realize that radio operators did far
more than just give and take dictation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of technical stuff,'' he said. ``Being on a
freighter or tanker, if something breaks down, you're it. You've
got to fix it. So you're a technician as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
