<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8471 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREEN-SUVS14-COX     07-13 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEN-SUVS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'GREEN' SUV DESIGNED BY SCIENISTS' GROUP
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Drivers who prefer roomy sports utility vehicles
don't have to sacrifice clean air and fuel efficiency, the Union of
Concerned Scientists said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, the group described how its engineers used
existing technology to design ``the UCS Exemplar,'' a modified Ford
Explorer with 50 percent better gas mileage and 75 percent less
pollution that the original production model.
</P>
<P>
   ``Higher efficiency and lower pollution don't have to come in a
small car package,'' said Jason Mark, senior transportation
analyst. ``We redesigned the SUV with the environment in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 2004, the Environmental Protection Agency's car
exhaust standards will require reduced emissions from light trucks,
which include minivans and SUVs. The UCS Exemplar gets 28.4 miles
per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The redesigned car is more expensive to buy, but officials said
that cost would be offset by lower fuel bills over the life of the
vehicle. Mark said owners of the new vehicle could save $1,600 over
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to tell the American public, `Thou shalt not
drive sports utility vehicles,''' said Howard Ris, executive
director of UCS. ``Just if you do drive one, you're entitled to a
cleaner one and a more efficient one.''
</P>
<P>
   UCS says that among the improvements they made to the car are a
higher-efficiency engine, low-resistance tires, improved
aerodynamics, and weight reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ford Motor Co. supports making cleaner vehicles,
``environment hasn't been a driving force'' in the SUV market, Mark
said. ``The priority hasn't been on fuel economy in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The average light truck emits 47 percent more smog-forming
pollutants and 43 percent more global warming pollutants than the
average car, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Ris agreed saying that consumers have tended to focus on the
style and size of the vehicles _ ``the number of coffee cup
containers in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark said the market success of vehicles designed according to
the Exemplar's standards is contingent on consumer demand and
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
