<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WITCH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     07-13 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITCH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLAIR WITCH PROJECT': VANISHED IN THE WOODS, PANIC MEETS
IMAGINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a cabin built entirely out of soda cans, ``The Blair Witch
Project'' is a nifty example of how to make something out of
nothing. Nothing but imagination, and a game plan so enterprising
it should elevate its creators to pinup status at film schools
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Shot in only eight days with no real script, this little movie
is a locomotive pulling a Web site, a mythology, a special on the
Sci-Fi Channel and assorted tie-ins in its wake. And all of it,
including the film's cult status, has been skillfully spun out of
thin air.
</P>
<P>
   The horror genre is ideal for the bare-bones (pardon the
expression) nature of this undertaking. And it enabled the
filmmakers to turn a near-total absence of resources into a
creative advantage. Five friends who had come out of the University
of Central Florida's film program realized that the best way to
make a movie without sets, costumes, music or special effects would
be to incorporate that spareness into the story. With no easy
formulas to fall back on, Daniel Myrick and Eduardo Sanchez (who
are jointly credited with writing, directing and editing) give
their audiences no easy idea /f what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blair Witch Project'' begins by announcing the
disappearance of three documentary filmmakers in the woods of
Maryland in 1994 and presents itself as the scenes they left
behind. That way, its scrappy home-movie style is completely, even
ingeniously, appropriate to its story. It so knowingly summons the
atmosphere of a no-budget indie shoot that we even see the
filmmakers filming themselves buying marshmallows for their trip,
and zooming in to a tight close-up of the plastic bag.
</P>
<P>
   It also amusingly differentiates between the solemn,
self-important documentary being made (with a narrator sitting in a
cemetery talking of stories ``etched in stone'') and the
behind-the-scenes slacking and carousing of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   The on-camera filmmakers, Heather, Mike and Josh, are played by
Heather Donahue, Michael Williams and Joshua Leonard with a
warts-and-all improvised verisimilitude, no doubt heightened by the
conditions under which they worked. As documentarians exploring the
legend of the title witch, on a mission that eventually leads them
into the woods under increasingly scary circumstances, the actors
were put through a comparable wringer during shooting.
</P>
<P>
   They actually wielded the film's cameras, and they were left
cold, hungry, lost and increasingly angry, just like the characters
they play. One byproduct of this approach is an acute sensitivity
to things that go bump in the night. Another is the gratingly
limited vocabulary, full of virtually nonstop bleepables, which
makes the film somewhat hard on the ears.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities for horrific special effects are under every rock
here. More interestingly, the filmmakers confine themselves to
using the rocks themselves as alarming effects, not to mention the
twig figures that, when found hanging from the trees in the
morning, cause a considerable stir. In a textbook illustration of
how a literal image counts for less than its implicit horror, the
``Blair Witch'' crew creates a string of spooky occurrences in the
forest. It would seem that someone is following the filmmakers,
making strange noises outside their tent, leaving creepy souvenirs
for them and so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blair Witch Project,'' a most inventive departure from
standard horror fare, is frightening only insofar as its
characters' panic seems real. Everything else is left to the
imagination. And the imagination works overtime watching the acuity
of these talented filmmakers, and wondering what bright idea
they'll have next.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE BLAIR WITCH PROJECT'
</P>
<P>
   Written, directed and edited by Daniel Myrick and Eduardo
Sanchez; director of photography, Neal Fredericks; music by Tony
Cora; production designer, Ben Rock; produced by Gregg Hale and
Robin Cowie; released by Artisan Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 87 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``The Blair Witch Project'' is rated R (Under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes
endless profanities, one mysterious gory artifact and much implicit
menace.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Heather Donahue (Heather), Michael Williams (Mike) and
Joshua Leonard (Josh).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1708EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-CEMETERY-ART-NY     07-13 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-CEMETERY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART VANDALISM DERAILS SHOW IN ROME CEMETERY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036. 
(yn) 
 By ELISABETTA POVOLEDO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Sometimes art does not survive death, at least in the
case of some contemporary art in Rome. Four days after it opened,
an exhibition titled ``Life Beyond: The Vision of Death in
Contemporary Art'' closed Tuesday amid recriminations and smashed
artworks.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, offering 24 works on the theme of death by some
of Italy's most promising contemporary artists, was being held in
the famous non-Catholic cemetery in Rome where John Keats and Percy
Bysshe Shelley are buried. On most days, the cemetery is a haven of
tranquility whose silence is only sporadically disturbed by the
sotto voce murmurings of Keats devotees in particular, who stand
respectfully by his violet-covered grave raptly declaiming his
melancholy odes.
</P>
<P>
   Since the exhibition opened last week, however, the cemetery has
been abuzz with bitter words and controversy. First, an
opening-night cocktail party was canceled after prominent members
of the local English-speaking community objected to its being held
on hallowed ground. Then the opening itself _ which was to include
poetry readings, a contemporary dance piece and classical music _
was canceled altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, only two days after the exhibition opened, organizers
were urgently called to the cemetery because three of the artworks
had been smashed to pieces. On Tuesday the artists voted to close
the show rather than risk destruction of the remaining works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very sorry that this happened,'' said Carmine Sorrentino,
one of the show's curators. ``The exhibition was meant to be a
reflection on death and contemporary art, and we didn't mean to
offend anyone or do anything that would be upsetting. But we cannot
continue after this. The artists have decided to pull out because
they found this manifestation of violence to be offensive to them
and to all contemporary art.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has been charged in connection with the works'
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble began when the editors of Wanted in Rome, a biweekly
publication that is staple reading for English-speaking residents,
heard about the exhibition and organized an angry letter-writing
and press campaign against it. The editors said the exhibition, and
especially the opening night cocktail party, manifested a lack of
sensitivity toward the relatives of those buried in the
still-active cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a disaster,'' said Claire Hammond, owner of
an English-language bookstore in Rome. ``All those people and
cigarette butts everywhere among the tombs. The bottom line is that
this was a lack of respect for the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why Wanted in Rome, which deals more in classified
ads than in controversy, had taken up the cause, the publication's
editor, Mary Wilsey, said, ``We received dozens of phone calls from
outraged private citizens who felt that this was not the way to
treat a cemetery.'' She said their criticisms had been directed not
at the organizers of the exhibition, who she conceded had received
permission to use the cemetery, but at the cemetery's director and
the committee of 12 ambassadors that oversees its administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we are taking the Italians to task,'' she said.
``They have done nothing wrong. What we are worried about is a
cemetery that has been badly administered.''
</P>
<P>
   That was small consolation for the curators of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Sorrentino lamented that the destruction of the artworks had
been virtually ignored in the Italian news media and in cultural
circles and suggested that there was not much sympathy for
contemporary art in Italy. ``When they knock a few noses off the
statues in Villa Borghese, you get pandemonium in the press,'' he
said. ``In this case we were put in the back pages.''
</P>
<P>
   In Italian the cemetery's proper name is Cimitero Acattolico
(Non-Catholic cemetery). In English, it is often wrongly referred
to as the Protestant or English cemetery, though it has always been
open to other denominations. (Many Orthodox Jews are buried there,
as well as other Jews and some Catholics in graves belonging to
non-Catholic members of the same family.) Since 1953 the
regulations have specified that those buried there should be
``non-Catholic citizens,'' though there are exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The cemetery has existed since the middle of the 18th century,
though not in its present form, and in the early part of its
history it was no stranger to controversy. Before the papacy lost
its temporal powers in 1870, non-Catholics were often forced to
bury their dead at night, and crosses and inscriptions that
suggested the possibility of attaining eternal bliss were not
allowed to appear on their tombstones.
</P>
<P>
   Though still open for burials, the cemetery is mostly visited
nowadays by tourists: 10,000 to 15,000 a year are drawn to the
site's history and beauty.
</P>
<P>
   The art exhibition, consisting mostly of sculptures and
installations, had been set up in the old part of the cemetery,
where the more historic graves are. The placement of the artworks
ranged from the whimsical _ in the case of Felice Levini's
conceptual offering, an electric blue urn and an upended black
table, with ``Only one day without an end'' written across the top,
facing the tomb of the the 18th-century Neo-Classical painter Asmus
Jacob Carstens _ to the poetic, in the case of Luigi Ontani's
brightly colored Egyptian sarcophagus, probably the ultimate symbol
of death, set against the imposing mass of the pyramid of Caius
Cestius.
</P>
<P>
   A work that consisted of three terra cotta sculptures by
Benedetto Pietromarchi was placed upon a wall in the shadow of the
Caius Cestius pyramid, which dates from the first century B.C.
Sometime on Sunday morning, those three figures were thrown over
the side and smashed to smithereens.
</P>
<P>
   Two other artworks were destroyed, both of them installations:
``Alien Next to Hollywood. Roswell, New Mexico 1947,'' a
cryptically titled work by Adrian Tranquilli consisting of a white
plaster sculpture of the supposed Roswell alien, and a piece by
Marina Paris in which three bodyless elementary school uniforms
seemed to grow like bright black and blue flowers from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Pietromarchi was dismayed by the destruction, especially because
two of the sculptures had recently been sold to different buyers.
He said he had not yet told the works' owners about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily I was insured,'' he said, gazing down upon his broken
statues, ``but that's small consolation. It doesn't make up for
this at all.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
