<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   VALUJET-INDICT _ MIAMI _ A federal grand jury today is expected
to indict the air maintenance company that packed more than 140
flammable oxygen-generating canisters later placed on ValuJet
Airlines Flight 592, which slammed into the Everglades moments
after takeoff in 1996, killing all 110 aboard. Critics have charged
that, three years later, many dramatic changes promised in the wake
of the crash have died aborning. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post). 40.
</P>
<P>
   w/VALUJET-BOX _ MIAMI _ Highlights of the indictment.
(Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   VALUJET-TIME _ MIAMI _ VlauJet crash/investigation chronology.
(Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   MASSACRE-FOLO _ATLANTA _ Follow on Monday's seven-person
shooting in southwest Atlanta. Update police investigation; look at
history of police calls to the house at 3783 Adamsville Drive; try
to learn more about what the 11-year-old survivor saw and how he
escaped into a closet; funeral planning for seven; more community
react; why did the police wait three hours to get into the house
when someone could have been alive inside? (Longa, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RAIL-KILLER _ Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, the train-riding fugitive
suspected of killing eight people who lived near railroad tracks,
surrendered at a border checkpoint in El Paso, Texas today in a
deal brokered by his sister.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: American-Statesman reporters will be filing from Austin,
Houston and El Paso for this story.
</P>
<P>
   SKOLSHOOT-HEARING _ ATLANTA _ Anthony ``T.J.'' Solomon, accused
in the shooting last May at Heritage High School in Rockdale
County, Ga., has a hearing Tuesday on whether he should be tried as
an adult. (Stafford, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA (DEVELOPING) _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's summer and time
for the annual exodus from Cuba, as immigrants take advantage of
calm seas to reach the U.S. shores. Rafters seem more desperate to
reach the ground, we find out why. (Douthat, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ MIAMI _ President Clinton is visiting Miami to attend
a political fundraiser. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MANAGED-CARE _ WASHINGTON _ As the Senate moved toward its first
votes Tuesday on competing versions of legislation to regulate
HMOs, President Clinton and Democratic leaders accused Republicans
of sacrificing the public in favor of wealthy special interests.
(Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   F22-FUNDING _ WASHINGTON _ Reaction from Sen. Max Cleland and
Lockheed officials to the news that a House subcommittee voted to
withhold the $1.8 billion that had been budgeted to buy six F-22s,
proposing to use the money instead to expand the fleet of older
F-15s and F-16s. This follows bad news for the C130. The committee
told the Air Force to rethink or reject the $70 billion program,
which is behind schedule and $1 billion over budget. (Montgomery
and Thurston/Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Scott Montgomery (F22) and Scott Thurston (F22-FUNDING) are
filing separate stories.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-ENGLISH _ WASHINGTON _ Wowser. Dinkum. Bazodee. They may
sound like foreign words, but they're English as spoken in other
Anglophone nations. The new Encarta Dictionary of Foreign English
is a whole world of exotic words. (Dart, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   With FOREIGN-LIST.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN-SUVS _ WASHINGTON _ The Union of Concerned Scientists
holds a news conference to release a new report on designing sport
utility vehicles that are ``cleaner, more efficient, better
performing, and cheaper.'' (Dart, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-ECONOMY _ WASHINGTON _ High-tech jobs are transforming
local economies, according to a study released Tuedsay by the
Milken Institute. Study includes data on localities. (Geewax, Cox
News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   w/ATLANTA-ECONOMY _ WASHINGTON _ Atlanta's concentration of
high-tech businesses will give its economy a running start into the
new century, according to a study released Tuesday by the
non-profit Milken Institute. (Geewax, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Atlanta editors.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN-ECONOMY _ WASHINGTON _ Austin has the reputation as
Texas's high-tech heaven, but Dallas has the mojo. A new study
measuring the impact of new technologies on regional economies
shows that metro Dallas is second only to the Silicon Valley for
being a tech mega-center. Austin-San Marcos turns up as No. 21 on a
list of 315 cities studied. But an economist who helped prepare the
study, Perry Wong, says Austin's place among the Top 25 tech
centers may be more precarious that city boosters may believe, and
that Dallas is more firmly entrenched. That's because Dallas has a
very complex technology base, with seven different high-tech
industries represented. Austin, in contrast, has a lot of high-tech
jobs, but they are highly concentrated in the business of making
computers. (Geewax, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Austineditors.
</P>
<P>
   E-PRIVACY _ WASHINGTON _ The House Commerce subcommittee on
telecommunications holds a hearing on ``Electronic Commerce:
Current Status of Privacy Protections for Online Consumers.''
(Geewax, Cox News Service). 118.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   GLICKMAN _ WASHINGTON _ Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman
addresses a National Press Club luncheon on the future of
Biotechnology. (Hall, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
