<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I charged onto the subway train, found it too crowded and
decided to wait for the next one. My right leg touched the platform
just as the doors closed on my left leg. ``Open the doors,'' I
yelped, and although the doors often open and close several times
before the train takes off, they didn't this time. I decided the
only way out was to pull _ my leg slid free with more ease than I
expected, but my left shoe was lost inside the car as I fought my
way free.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the car, an attractive, well-dressed man picked up the
shoe and held it near the window for me to see. The train headed
out of the station as I screamed, ``Leave it at the next station!''
I didn't know whether he heard me, but I thought he gave me two
thumbs up. There I was at the 50th Street station, to all intents
and purposes shoeless. Going home to get another pair was
logistically out of the question; buying another pair was a
possibility but too time consuming.
</P>
<P>
   I boarded the next train at the exact spot my loafer had left
me. My hope, wishful thinking, was that the Samaritan would be
waiting at the comparable spot at Times Square. When we arrived
there, I leapt off the train and ran up and down the platform. No
shoe. I accepted my fate and got back on the train. As I stood
inside the door looking out, I saw my shoe, delicately placed by
the garbage can right in front of me. I leapt out, grabbed it and
made it back on board. The other passengers were gaping.
</P>
<P>
   -KRISTIN HARDING
</P>
<P>
   Walking on the west side of Broadway near 87th Street, Stella
Chess found her way barred by an elderly man. She looked around and
saw that in fact, a cordon of people was sealing off an area of the
pavement. A little girl of about 6, and a number of men, women and
youngsters were diligently searching the sidewalk. The child's
father was urging her to give up, but several people told him to
hush.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the girl's tooth had come loose, and as she wiggled
it to show her father, it came out in her hand and she dropped it.
She began searching, and as she became increasingly upset, more and
more passers-by joined her search. The group informally assigned
itself to different areas and finally, the tooth was found. Within
seconds, the Samaritans once again became hurried and harried New
Yorkers. They were off even before the father could thank them.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Power was walking along Lexington Avenue recently when
he noticed a postal worker hunkered down by an open mailbox,
shoveling letters into his bag. Mr. Power's attention was riveted
when the man pulled two bagels out of the mailbox, placed them on
top and continued loading his bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does this happen very often?'' Mr. Power asked. The man, still
loading his bag, and without looking up, responded, ``It's the
first time I've seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Power assumed the bagels were the work of vandals or
litterbugs. ``What are you going to do with them?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mail them, of course. They have stamps and addresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Power peeked. The bagels seemed to be quite stale and hard,
but sure enough, they had addresses written right on them and
stamps affixed. How, why, he's still wondering.
</P>
<P>
   A Metropolitan Opera park concert on Staten Island in late June
was a particularly memorable occasion _ it was the first time I can
recall an opera grinding to a halt because of an attack by a swarm
of kamikaze June bugs.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun descended and the stage lights came on, thousands
of the bugs rose from the grass and assaulted the stage,
divebombing the singers and musicians, of which I was one. They
crashed into our heads, flew into the singers' mouths and spattered
onto the stage. As they watched the distracted singers and
musicians trying to bat the insects away while performing, a scene
worthy of a Marx Brothers movie, the spectators reacted with
appropriate howls. About halfway through Act I, we all fled the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   After about 15 minutes of unscheduled intermission, we crept
tentatively back, crunching over hundreds of tiny corpses, and took
up the opera from where we left off.
</P>
<P>
   The onslaught continued, but the intensity gradually abated. The
poor young woman making her debut as Lucia di Lammermoor looked
suitably beside herself as she sang the famous final scene while
frantically slapping and flicking incoming bugs away from her
shoulders and wrenching them out of her hair. A Mad Scene indeed!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -MICHAEL PARLOFF &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A friend was driving along Park Avenue in the 70's when he
spotted a prosperous-looking older couple cruising along in not
only a Bentley but also a Bentley that he thought was probably a
custom color _ a shade he described as a black-cherry red. The
license plate reflected a sense of humor. ``PRE HMO,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Dizozza is a lawyer, poet, playwright, composer and
arranger who moonlights as an entertainer at clubs and cabarets.
Recently he was performing at the Sidewalk Bar on Avenue A, and at
2 A.M. there were only four people left in the audience. How could
he resist?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an attorney, poet, composer, playwright, arranger, pianist
and singer,'' he announced. ``How come there are so many of me and
so few of you?''
</P>
