<P>
   OTHER BASEBALL NEWS . . .
</P>
<P>
   BBO-MCCOY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The assignment is difficult _
the old compare apples to oranges cliche, except in this case it is
comparing giants, like watermelons to cantaloupes. Question: Are
the 1999 Cleveland Indians comparable to the 1976 Cincinnati Reds,
The Big Red Machine? Answer: Gulp. It is an assignment designed to
make people angry, but also to get people talking and, no, the
results won't be biased. (McCoy, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BROPEN-WATSON _ CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ It's hard to forget
the 1975 British Open battle at Carnoustie. Tom Watson and Jack
Newton, an Australian, fought it out in a playoff round until
Watson emerged as the winner. Then their paths split. Watson
continued to become one of the world's best golfers; Newton lost
his arm after walking into the propeller of an airplane and will be
serving as a commentator for Australian television this week.
(Sheeley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BROPEN-NOTES _ CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ British Open notebook.
(Sheeley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 16.
</P>
<P>
   TRACK AND FIELD
</P>
<P>
   RUN-TRIPLEJUMP _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Many athletes are looking
forward to 2000, the year of the Summer Olympics in Sydney. But for
triple jumper Desmond Hunt, next year will be doubly significant.
That's also when he's scheduled to complete his doctoral work in
kinesiology at the University of Texas. ``I've never seen a guy do
what he's doing,'' said Dan Pfaff, assistant track coach at the
University of Texas. ``He's in the top 10 in his event and he's
getting a doctorate in a top 10 program.'' (Maher, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BASKETBALL _ SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ Advancing Pre Olympic
Basketball tournament, a qualifier for Sydney. The NBA-heavy U.S.
team includes Steve Smith, the subject of trade talks (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 16.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Jamal Anderson will get the money
he wants, or most of it. He'll get his new contract soon enough,
probably after training camp begins but before the second
exhibition game. And he'll be happy, and he'll have another big
season, and probably the Atlanta Falcons will, too. Question is,
what happens when this extended contract hits Year 4, Year 5, Year
6? (Bradley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
