<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEWS BUSINESS LOSES A HERO 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ John Lynch was one of ours, one of Sonoma's and
one of a kind. One day last week, at the age of 46, John died.
</P>
<P>
   He was found at home, fully dressed for the morning shift at the
San Francisco Examiner. We all have searched for explanations for
his death, and found nothing but reasons for him to live.
</P>
<P>
   We must admit our selfishness. In part, we want him to be alive
for us. We want to share his humor, which like all great humor was
entirely serious. We need him as the cool professional he was, too.
</P>
<P>
   John was a part of this column you never saw, an editor fighting
creeping ungrammaticality and leaping illogic. You'd have to see
John to really appreciate him, too. He was as handsome as any lead
singer, with the tan of a surfer and the elegant suits of a
Hollywood producer.
</P>
<P>
   The phone would ring at my home and he'd be all business, but
the business was the rock 'n' roll of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morse, Lynch here,'' he'd say. ``Now maybe I'm not intelligent
enough to be part of your readership, but there's a sentence here I
don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Or else he'd say, ``I know you don't care about prepositions at
the end of sentences, but here's a way we could reword it to keep
English teachers from sending you letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Or else he'd say, ``Here's a way I think we can make this
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a way I think we can make this better.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the last words of his I remember, the words of the
consummate editor, words we all should try to apply in life. He was
a self-deprecating man, so he always added ``I think'' when he
knew.
</P>
<P>
   John was a fourth-generation newspaperman, one of the family
that founded and still publishes the Sonoma Index-Tribune. A
memorial service for John was held on Sunday at Sonoma's Trinity
Episcopal Church, and the church overflowed with hundreds of
journalists and residents of Sonoma, including members of the
Sebastiani family and the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, family, reporters, cops and firemen wept for John in
the small country church.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is quite a tribute to John and this town,'' said my
friend Michael Coats, who has lived in Sonoma since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``John was the first person I met when I moved here,'' Coats
said. ``I was a new PR guy in town and he was managing editor of
the Index-Tribune, so I called him up. He answered his own phone,
and we went out for drinks. We talked about the Rolling Stones.''
</P>
<P>
   One of John's expressions about newspapering was ``Remember,
it's only rock 'n' roll.''
</P>
<P>
   He cared deeply about both newspapering and rock 'n' roll. It
was just like John to use that expression to soften his
seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   At the memorial service, John's brother Bill told the mourners
to remember John as the good friend and selfless colleague that he
was. He told us to write down our thoughts, so John's teen-age
kids, Max and Lily, can have them forever.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I write this, and also to admit to readers that
sometimes newspaper people can't deal with issues of mortality,
even though that's the business we're in.
</P>
<P>
   John once edited a story written by my wife. ``It was just about
Christmas tree lots, but he treated it as seriously as any
front-page story,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper is the sum of its parts, as a great editor once told
me. I've come to know what that means. It means stories about
Christmas tree lots are as important, in their way, as stories
about plane crashes and political scandals.
</P>
<P>
   It means an editor looking for spelling errors and logical
lapses is as important as someone with a picture over a column.
</P>
<P>
   We're all equal in putting out a newspaper, just as we're all
equal in the eyes of the Lord. But I wish John could have seen his
own funeral to know how special he was.
</P>
<P>
   My wife said he was still there, that people don't depart until
bidden farewell. I say they don't depart because they live in
people's hearts. Editors live in writers' copy.
</P>
<P>
   We all knew John was going through hard times and he'd lost an
awful lot of weight. His brother Bill told the mourners that he
could come up with no reason for John's death.
</P>
<P>
   John came to work every day when called. He always was on time.
He always had a smile. He took dictation on deadline like the pro
he was. He made the tough calls on stories. A small-town
newspaperman at heart, he was unfailingly polite to angry readers
who called the city desk.
</P>
<P>
   The day John died, a bunch of us took a very long lunch at the
local bar and told newspaper stories, stories about John and ones
he would have appreciated. ``He was a hero,'' one grizzled
newspaperman said.
</P>
<P>
   The way John worked and joked was an inspiration to all of us.
</P>
<P>
   All I can say is that if this column reads poorly, it's because
he isn't here to edit it.
</P>
<P>
   As I drove away from the memorial service on Sunday, I popped in
a Rolling Stones CD. Leaving Sonoma, I drove through the square,
past vineyards and the firemen's barbecue, and mouthed the words to
``Not Fade Away.''
</P>
<P>
   I know it's only rock 'n' roll, but I liked him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
