A8601 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS &LR;      07-13 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAN SHRUGS OFF ADVERSITY TO WIN A THIRD TOUR STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SESTRIERES, Italy _ Nothing fazed Lance Armstrong Tuesday _ not
the rain mixed with occasional hail, not the summits he attacked in
the Alps, not the 173 racers who attacked him.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong seemed immune to it all as he wore the Tour de France
leader's yellow jersey. The 27-year-old from Austin, Texas, won the
134-mile stage in 5 hours, 57 minutes, 11 seconds. That was 30
seconds ahead of his nearest pursuer, Switzerland's Alex Zulle, and
it gave Armstrong an overall lead of more than six minutes almost
halfway through the event.
</P>
<P>
   The win was Armstrong's second in a row and third stage win so
far.
</P>
<P>
   So is it presumptuous to envision him as just the second
American to win the 86-year-old Tour de France? Armstrong believes
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still nervous, and I still don't think that the race is
over,'' he said. ``The others will be back and they'll be better,
and I can have bad days and my condition can run out.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not how it looked Tuesday, when you could almost hear
the Tour organizers say, ``Gentlemen, start your engines,'' as the
racers rolled out of the streets of Le Grand Bornand, a French ski
resort in the Alps near the Italy and Switzerland borders. The race
would start with a descent and then cover four summits to finish on
top of another.
</P>
<P>
   So while the riders had no motors to rely on, they instead had
to summon all the manpower they could for the first mountain stage
after a week in the relatively flat regions of northern France.
</P>
<P>
   Every view of the snow-covered Alps was mere foreshadowing to
the riders of what was in store. With much of the course filled
with fans who had hiked or biked up, one could only wonder what
went through Signor Agnelli's mind when he designed the stage in
1952.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong, aided by teammates Tyler Hamilton and Kevin
Livingston in the first part of the race, seemed to relish it.
Armstrong was 12th to arrive at the summit 120 miles into the race
and the fifth to ride to the top of summit less than 15 miles
later.
</P>
<P>
   And the rain didn't seem to bother him any more than the
ascents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good day for me because of the conditions,'' he said.
``I always ride good in these cold, wet conditions, and on a day
like this you automatically eliminate 50 percent of the opposition
because of bad morale or accidents, so I've always looked on that
as an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   And he capitalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel super, but I realized the others looked like
they were suffering,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong approached the final climb with six other riders but
pulled away from them less than 4 miles from the summit. He
grimaced as he steadily rode to the top on roads lined with
cheering and umbrella-holding fans, and he lifted his hands to tug
on his jersey before raising them high as he crossed the finish
line.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who missed all of the 1997 season and sat out last
year's Tour after surgery for testicular cancer, said Tuesday's win
also showed that he and his team can battle the Alps as well as any
seasoned European racer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think before today there were some questions, and people
weren't sure of my team's or my ability in the mountains,'' he
said. ``So I think there was some importance to showing that we
were stronger. It was good for our whole team.''
</P>
<P>
   And he steadfastedly refused to predict a victory in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I built the whole season around this race, but I also had good
form in June, and the form could run out in the next four or five
days, and then I'm in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, things are looking just fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
