<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLICKMAN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRUST A BARRIER TO WIDER BIOTECH USE ON THE FARM, GLICKMAN SAYS
 &HT;    By JONATHAN HALL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Biotechnology has enormous potential to help combat
hunger, reduce pesticide use and increase crop yields, but first
there must be a greater level of trust between scientists, the
public and regulators, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the National Press Club, Glickman said the European
Union's refusal to allow the sale of genetically modified food from
U.S. producers is ``scientifically unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   European fears of these products stem from the fact that ``they
have no independent regulatory agencies'' like the Food and Drug
Administration, U.S. Department of Agriculture or Environmental
Protection Agency, Glickman said. As a result, ``they've had many
food scares in recent years,'' such as outbreaks of ``mad cow
disease'' and chicken tainted with dioxin.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are many benefits from genetic modification of
foods, he said, noting that nearly half of the soybeans in the
United States are a variety altered to increase resistance to
certain pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary, who has declined to propose labeling of
genetically altered foods in the United States, said the USDA, FDA
and EPA must stay at ``arm's length'' in regulating biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary said he would seek an independent scientific
review of USDA's biotechnology approval process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of this review will be to ensure that, as we are
faced with increasingly complex issues surrounding biotechnology,
our scientists have the best information and tools to ensure our
regulatory capabilities continue to evolve along with advances in
new technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said the USDA would seek funding for regional centers
to evaluate biotech products for long periods of time and supply
information to growers, consumers, researchers and regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Once biotech products hit the market and the benefits are known,
consumer acceptance will be high, according to Glickman. ``There
clearly needs to be a strong public education effort to show
consumers the benefits of these products and why they are safe,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said he was concerned with how biotechnology would
affect farmers, who are suffering from very low commodity prices.
``We need to ensure that biotechnology becomes a tool that results
in greater _ not fewer _ options for farmers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To determine if the biotech approach is helping or hurting
family farmers, Glickman said the government needs to integrate
issues of privatization of genetic resources and patent-holders'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
