<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTTLE-RECYCLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTLE DEPOSIT SPURS RECYCLING IN NEW YORK STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DINA CAPPIELLO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ While New Yorkers are recycling a hefty 42
percent of all trash, the rate is nearly double for bottles and
cans sold with nickel deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, well over a billion beverage containers _ one out of four
sold _ are never cashed in and the money stays with the
distributors. The 1982 Returnable Container Law that placed a
nickel deposit on the sale of carbonated soft drinks, beer and some
wine is widely credited with achieving its initial purpose _ to
decrease litter. It has also spurred recycling.
</P>
<P>
   Until the late 1980s, when curbside programs began, returnable
containers were the single largest contributor to the state's
recycling efforts. Today, they account for 2.3 percent of the 12.5
million tons of paper, bottles, cans, tires and other materials the
state recycles.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gov. George Pataki announced with pride that New
York's 42 percent solid waste recycling rate met goals set a dozen
years ago. Other states don't do as well. Pennsylvania recycles 26
percent, Massachusetts 34 percent and Texas 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $255.9 million paid out in deposits in 1997, New Yorkers
redeemed $194.7 million _ $7.1 million more than the previous year.
The billion-plus nickels not redeemed by consumers _ or some other
enterprising individuals _ stay with the beverage distributors. And
that's no small change. The total was $61 million dollars in 1997,
the most recent statistic available.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Conservation tracks how
many deposit bottles and cans are brought back in nine regions. The
redemption rates vary widely. Statewide, 76 percent of glass and
plastic bottles and aluminum cans are returned, usually at
supermarket machines that count the cans and bottles and identify
their brands before they are crushed.
</P>
<P>
   In Central New York, where redemption centers handle much of the
nickel-payback business, the deposit is redeemed 93 percent of the
time. New York City's rate of 68 percent is the lowest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the highest redemption rate in New York state,'' said
George Gianquitti, whose redemption center near Syracuse collects
8.25 million containers per year. ``It's not because we're better
environmentalists than anyone else in the state. We've just made it
easier to redeem cans.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to machines, the process is quicker and cleaner.
Beverage distributors reimburse the five-cent deposits and pay the
handler _ be it a redemption center or supermarket _ an additional
two cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our phone book you see 15 redemption centers listed,'' said
Gianquitti, who operates R.G. Nickel Back Redemption Center in
Mattydale and helped found the New York State Bottle and Can
Redemption Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The creation of redemption centers would have a lot to do with
increasing the redemption rate,'' said Donna Stewart, an
environmental program specialist at the DEC's Bureau of Waste
Reduction and Recycling.
</P>
<P>
   If the law were stretched to include today's popular
non-carbonated drinks, the number of containers returned would grow
by 20 percent, cutting litter and boosting recycling, according to
Pat Franklin, executive director of the Container Recycling
Institute near Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, bills to amend the container law are introduced in
the state Legislature to include additional beverages. The beverage
industry has successfully fought off attempts to get the unredeemed
nickels into the state treasury. In Massachusetts the left-over
deposit goes to the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
