A8626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BROPEN-NOTES14-CO     07-13 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-NOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Course pretty unforgiving, no matter the weather
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ At most major championship venues, each
practice day brings some progress. At a place like the Carnoustie
Golf Links, where the conditions went from sunny and mild to cool
and rainy over lunch Tuesday, it's a struggle even without keeping
score.
</P>
<P>
   Add Carnoustie's tight fairways, which have knee-high rough
lurking near, and the 128th British Open takes on an appearance of
a bogeyfest. On the par-5 sixth hole, the fairway is only 11 yards
wide at the layup point.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the 3-iron or the 1-iron, you lay up into an area that is
only 10 or 11 yards wide, with a ditch on the right and the rough
on the left,'' American Jim Furyk said. ``It's a bit over the top,
I think. . . . It's very tough, the hardest course I've ever
played.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Carnoustie is living up to everything that has been discussed
about it,'' Phil Mickelson said. ``A fair test? Off the tee, it's
arguable. I've never seen fairways this penalizing for a major
championship. You might as well stick red hazard posts down the
fairways.''
</P>
<P>
   Per-Ulrik Johansson of Sweden called the 10- to 15-yard landing
area at the 479-yard 12th hole ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience doesn't mean a thing if you can't hit it
straight,'' said Nick Faldo, a three-time champion. ``And it's long
as well. You've got to hit the driver. And it's narrow. It's pretty
serious out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather forecast for Thursday is dry and sunny, with
temperatures in the high 60s and winds at 10-15 mph, gusting to 20.
</P>
<P>
   What are the odds?
</P>
<P>
   Most bookmakers list Tiger Woods at 5-1 or 6-1 as the favorite.
Colin Montgomerie is about 11-1, down from 16-1, followed by David
Duval at 12-1, Ernie Els at 16-1, Vijay Singh at 18-1 and Sergio
Garcia at 20-1.
</P>
<P>
   England's Justin Rose, the sensation of last year's Open with a
third-place finish as an amateur, is a 500-1 shot _ no wonder,
after it took him 22 European Tour events to make a pro cut. Zane
Scotland of England, the 16-year-old amateur qualifier, is a
2,000-1 shot.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III is 33-1, along with Justin Leonard, Tom Lehman,
Mickelson and U.S. Open champion Payne Stewart. Defending champion
Mark O'Meara is 40-1, along with Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Duval's practice start on Monday was less than stellar. Hitting
with a group off the first tee that included Greg Norman and Nick
Price, Duval popped up his first drive maybe 225 yards to the right
and quickly reloaded. . . .You might want to avoid Lee Janzen in
your office pool. ``I'd say on a 1-to-10 scale, my game is about a
negative 4 right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
