<HEADER>
A8627 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BROPEN-WATSON-COX     07-13 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-WATSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tale of two destinies
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ In golf history, never have two
combatants in a major championship left the course, left the
country and then taken such different paths. For one, the high road
led to five British Open titles. For the other, the low road ended
his career _ and nearly his life.
</P>
<P>
   American Tom Watson beat Australian Jack Newton by one shot in
an 18-hole playoff the Monday after regulation play of the 1975
British Open, at the same Carnoustie Golf Links that will be the
site of the 128th championship this week. Watson would evolve into
one of golf's greatest champions, winning four more times across
the pond. Newton, eight years later, on July 24, 1983, would walk
into an airplane propeller on a rainy night in Newcastle,
Australia, and lose his right arm, his right eye and half of his
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are here this week, of course, with their roles still
as contrasting. Watson returns to the scene of his first British
Open win _ on his first try at age 25. Newton annually works the
tournament for Australian television. The two men are on the
grounds for the first time since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's thoughts at Carnoustie are mostly wonderful, until he
remembers that the man who lost the 90-hole battle by one shot,
then lost almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping he was going to survive, first of all,'' Watson
said when asked to recall the emotions he felt when he heard about
Newton's accident. ``He was in intensive care and close to death
for many weeks after that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Newton was able to recover from the tragedy and rework his
life. Although Newton's professional career became just memories
and press clippings, he started playing golf again with one arm,
reduced his handicap from 36 to 15 and breaks 80 occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Newton is chairman of the PGA Tour of Australasia and head
of the Jack Newton Junior Golf Foundation. He has been a fixture at
every major championship in recent years, dapper always in his bow
tie and blue blazer. The right sleeve is pinned at the shoulder,
but Newton's mood and mannerisms do not give away the horrors he
has felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I looked at it,'' Newton said as he awaited British
Open week and Carnoustie, ``I had two choices _ go sit in the
corner and sulk for the rest of my life, or get on with it. It was
no choice, really.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Watson, he turns 50 on Sept 4 and will hit the Senior PGA
Tour full-time. If he makes the cut this week, it will be an upset,
especially if the weather gets rainy and windy by Thursday.
Laughing at himself, Watson established one goal of parring the
16th hole, the often brutal 250-yard par-3. In 1975, Watson never
managed it in five rounds, including the playoff, or a practice
round. He hit the green one time and 3-putted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not playing particularly well right now,'' he said. ``I
am putting well, though. . . . Something here brings out the best
in me, though. I hope this time it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Watson was a young man from Kansas City who had not yet
developed a fondness for links golf. He wore a plaid Hogan-type
cap, purchased in Carnoustie, with longish hair sticking out from
under it. This week at 49, Watson sat at the interview room table
wearing a Duke baseball cap, blue with a white D, for the school
that daughter Meg attends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played American target golf _ hit the ball high,'' Watson
said. ``I truly didn't really like the game over here until maybe
1979 at Royal Lytham. . . . I honestly didn't like St. Andrews in
1978 when I played. I liked to get the ball up in the air and stop
it quickly, and it was going against my nature at the time. But I
decided I better change my nature. . . . So I pretended I was a
little kid again, in the sense that you had to run the ball on the
greens _ you know, when you couldn't hit the ball very far. You had
to try and find the openings and run the ball on to the greens. And
that free association, I guess, really worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnoustie was a gentler giant in July of 1975, with little
rough and not much wind. Newton, in fact, moved into Sunday's final
pairing with a 65 _ the Carnoustie course record until Colin
Montgomerie and Alan Tait shot 64s in the 1995 Scottish Open. The
course won't yield such numbers this week. The nearly unnegotiable
rough is at many places no more than 10 yards from the fairway, and
the fairways are barely wider than some of the nearby roads.
</P>
<P>
   Telling a story to illustrate Carnoustie's difficulty, Watson
remembered a conversation with Jack Nicklaus about a ``Big Three
Golf'' match he played at the course with Arnold Palmer and Gary
Player in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack said, `We went out and played in about 40-mph winds, and
the course was completely baked out,' '' Watson said. ``Jack said,
`I shot 77, Gary shot 78, and Arnold shot 79.' Then they counted up
the greens in regulation. Jack led with four, he said Gary hit two
and Arnold hit one.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, if you add rough and length and wind to it,'' Watson said,
``now what's going to happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
