A8628 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCCER-HUMBUG-NYTSF &LR;      07-13 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-HUMBUG-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU TAKE SOCCER ... I'LL WATCH THE FISH CHANNEL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Hail the World Cup champions!
</P>
<P>
   That Mia Hamm sure is a telegenic babe, isn't she? Really cute,
in an athlete-next-door kind of way. If she weren't married to that
military dude, I'm sure she'd be flooded with all kinds of romantic
offers.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi Chastain has her own special brand of sex appeal as well.
That move she did Saturday when she ripped off her jersey in front
of the crowd, revealing just a black sports bra, was practically
Rodman-esque _ though Dennis never wore a bra under his jersey, as
far as we know.
</P>
<P>
   But I think I prefer the pose Chastain struck earlier this year
for Gear magazine, with only a strategically placed soccer ball for
cover. That was even better than the group picture the team did for
David Letterman, in which they appear to be wearing nothing but
``Late Night'' T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute, though. How can we have a discussion of the U.S.
women's team without mentioning Brianna Scurry's pledge to run
naked through her hometown should the squad win the Cup? She's
pulled that move before, you know.
</P>
<P>
   It's also worth noting that the players have called themselves
``booters with hooters''; that they paint each other's toenails
red, white and blue; and that they have endorsed the benefits of
conjugal relations before big games.
</P>
<P>
   These truly are women of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   What's your complaint? That I'm a third of the way through the
column and it's been all about sex appeal and superficialities?
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can't get mad at me about the sexy stuff. That's the
image the team itself has been projecting all along: wholesome,
down-to-earth attractiveness, spiced with more than a little of the
assertive jock persona.
</P>
<P>
   As for their soccer skills, I guess they're darn good _ but then
again, I watched only about 20 minutes of game action. Everybody
looked great in their ponytails chasing after the ball, but nothing
really happened, so I went back to the Aquarium Channel. (All
fishies all the time; you should check it out.)
</P>
<P>
   Not that I'm unaware of this girls' soccer craze. Over the last
few weeks, I I've read tons of newspaper and magazine stories and I
I've watched several TV features about the World Cup team. I saw
the commercials starring Mia Hamm, and I noticed the Soccer Barbies
in the toy stores. One night in late June, I was nearly overrun by
packs of 12-year-old girls who were all talking at once as they
stampeded to the World Cup action at Soldier Field.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I'd really be into this thing, if it weren't for the
soccer part.
</P>
<P>
   Try as I have over the years to appreciate the global pastime,
all I see is the Myth of Sisyphus without the mountain: a bunch of
people kicking a ball and chasing after it, kicking a ball and
chasing after it, with somebody scoring a goal every hour or so.
It's like looking at one of those ``Magic Eye'' optical illusions
and never seeing the spaceship emerge from the squiggly lines.
</P>
<P>
   Nor am I convinced this is anything more than a temporary
explosion. In the wake of the incredible media blitz about the
World Cup team, a little perspective is in order.
</P>
<P>
   True, there were record crowds for the games. Whether busloads
of girls' teams were given tickets for free or people were plunking
down their hard-earned money, attendance figures of 75,000 and
90,000-plus are impressive.
</P>
<P>
   But the TV ratings provide a more enlightening picture.
</P>
<P>
   Although Saturday's final was the most-watched soccer game ever
on U.S. network television, according to overnight ratings, the
first two weeks of World Cup games on ESPN averaged 1 percent of
U.S. cable households _ and let's remember that almost half the
country still isn't wired for cable. Last week in USA Today,
Michael Hiestand pointed out that only 32 percent of that tiny
viewership is female _ meaning that in terms of percentage of
female viewers, the World Cup lagged behind ``fringe'' sports such
as skiing, NASCAR, horse racing, rodeo and bowling. Bowling!
</P>
<P>
   You can market and hype soccer to the sky, but those 12-year-old
girls who love to play the game and watch it in person will never
become adult couch potatoes, soaking up match after match and
absorbing commercial after commercial.
</P>
<P>
   When they're not working, the vast majority of women in this
country are busy giving birth and running marathons and organizing
car pools and changing the oil in their cars and playing softball
and sweeping out the gutters; they won't waste entire days and
nights watching sports on TV. They're not stupid, like us men.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was fueled by more than a touch of jingoism and
marketing, the World Cup was a nice story _ but it doesn't mean
women's soccer is now a big-time sport for the masses. If you want
to argue with me, I'll ask you this:
</P>
<P>
   Can you name one player on any team outside the USA?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a
radio host and a commentator for Fox News in Chicago _ and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
