<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, July 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and patchy rain will occur Wednesday from the southern
Appalachians to the Carolina coast as weak disturbances travel
along a wavering front near the Atlantic Seaboard. However, most of
the rain will be light, converging winds near a low pressure center
will cause some heavier rain over southeastern Virginia and eastern
North Carolina. Afternoon temperatures will continue to average 8
to 12 degrees below the seasonal average.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Northeast will become warmer and more humid.
Sunshine will be plentiful near the Canadian border where
temperatures will surge several degrees above seasonal levels.
Meanwhile, light onshore breezes will keep most coastal areas cool
for the middle of July.
</P>
<P>
   Hot and humid conditions will spread from the Plains over most
of the Middle West and interior Southeast. A few showers and
thunderstorms will form near the leading edge of the sultry air
from the northern Mississippi Valley to the northern Great Lakes.
Afternoon thunderstorms will also form near the Gulf of Mexico
coast where sea breezes undercut and lift sultry air.
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled conditions will linger from the western slopes of the
Rockies to the deserts of the Southwest. The day will begin with
ample sunshine in most areas, but numerous thundershowers will form
during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Northwest will turn breezy and cooler with some
mountain showers as a cold front moves south through Oregon and
Idaho. Another surge of unusually chilly air will reach northern
parts of Montana late Wednesday night and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Daytime Chill
</P>
<P>
   In Raleigh, N.C., temperatures were near 100 on Sunday, but the
following day was the coldest July day since records began there in
1887. A damp, chill blew in from the Atlantic Ocean on Monday and
the mercury reached only 67 degrees, setting a record low maximum
temperature. While record high temperatures and extreme nighttime
cold are routinely reported, unusual daytime chill is a more
obscure quantity. Nevertheless, a low maximum is good indicator of
how cold a day is, since it measures chill in the afternoon, a time
when most people experience the weather. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
