<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8648 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-MELONS-ART-3TA     07-13 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-MELONS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COOLEST SLICE OF SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Melons are the aristocrats of summer fruit, their
cool elegance and exotic lushness perfuming dishes with the
fragrances of a flower garden. The charming palette of summer
colors spans the spectrum, from the creamy white flesh of the
honeydew to the brassy firecracker red of the watermelon. In
sorbets and chilled soups, in cocktails and salads, or simply eaten
out of hand, melons are wonderful restoratives for the long, hot
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Melons have been admired for just these qualities through the
centuries, the admiration reaching something of a frenzy in
16th-century France, when they appeared at every meal and moved the
poet Marc-Antoine de Gerard Sieur de Saint-Amant to verse:
</P>
<P>
   ``O precious food! Delight of the mouth! Oh, much better than
gold masterpiece of Apollo! O flower of all the fruits! O ravishing
melon!''
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary abundance and variety of melons available
today would send the poet into a new frenzy. Within the next two
weeks, we will enter the height of the season, when melons from
California and local farms are at their juiciest and sweetest.
There will be dozens of varieties like the golden Juan Canary and
satiny honeydew from the West, and from nearby farms the meltingly
sweet flesh of ambrosia and even the East Coast version of the much
admired French Charentais. The little Cavaillon, which is a version
of the Charentais and is still imported from France, is already
turning up in produce sections where price is no object. Chefs
treasure them for their lovely striated green skins, salmon pink
flesh and creamy sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these melons will keep coming into September, and some
even longer, depending on the weather.
</P>
<P>
   What makes them so appealing is their high water content. When
that water chills the smooth flesh of the melons, they taste cooler
and more refreshing than any of the other equally luscious fruits
of summer. In the recent hot weeks, restaurants that have had melon
dishes as specials have made them a permanent part of their
seasonal repertoire because of their popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the way the musky earthiness of the melon marries well
with savory foods,'' said Rocco DiSpirito, the chef at Union
Pacific. ``If you handle it the right way, it can take spice, salt
and sweet unlike other fruits.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSpirito's salad of calamari, watermelon and avocado
beautifully balances all these things. A salad at the Berkeley Bar
and Grill is a lesson in how easily melon can be transformed into a
refreshing, attractive summer dish: a lovely construction of red
and yellow watermelon balls, goat cheese and basil.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet melons fall into two broad classes: muskmelon and
watermelon. Muskmelons further divide into two principal varieties:
those with netted skins, like cantaloupe, Persian, Santa Claus,
Sharlyn and Galia, and those with smooth skins, like Juan Canary,
casaba, Crenshaw, Cavaillon and honeydew.
</P>
<P>
   This profusion can seem difficult to sort out at the market, and
it turns out it is.
</P>
<P>
   Muskmelons hybridize eagerly with one another, producing colors
that bear little relationship to what we have come to expect, like
orange honeydews. Alan Davidson, the author of ``Fruit'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, 1991), says French gardeners in the 19th century were
careful to cultivate melons far removed from other gourds to avoid
``incestuous intercourse'' with cucumbers. In fact, some melons,
like casaba, have heavy overtones of a cucumber flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Timothy Ng, a professor of natural resource sciences at the
University of Maryland and a melon breeder, said that because of
cross-breeding, ``at some point it's arbitrary whether the melon is
a cantaloupe, a muskmelon or a honeydew.'' He added, ``There's a
rich amount of variation.'' And confusion. Experts don't agree on
what each variety tastes like _ something that partly depends on
where the melon was grown. But there are, of course, distinctions.
</P>
<P>
   Among the netted Western melons, the cantaloupe is highly
perfumed with firm flesh and a sweet, musky flavor. Crenshaw, a
cross between a Persian and a casaba, has a high sugar content and
is very sweet, with a rich aroma and either a strong spicy flavor
or a mild sweet one. The Persian and Galia have a dense texture
like a cantaloupe's, with delicate flavor and good fragrance. The
Santa Claus has a fairly firm flesh, and is crisp, juicy and mildly
sweet. The Sharlyn (or Sharlyne or Sharlin) has a high sugar
content, with flesh that melts in your mouth but not much aroma.
</P>
<P>
   Among the smooth melons, the honeydew has a more delicate aroma
and subtler taste than a cantaloupe. The casaba has a low sugar
content, is fairly firm but juicy and offers hints of cucumber. The
Juan Canary is sweet but has little flavor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The flesh of Eastern melons is not as firm as that of Western
melons, and they tend to taste muskier. One of the best is the
ambrosia. The Saticoy is firmer and is sometimes sweeter than
ambrosia, sometimes not. Gold Star is juicy but not as flavorful.
</P>
<P>
   The finest local melon, by most accounts, seldom makes its way
to markets in New York City. Hand melons from Greenwich, N.Y.,
named for the family that has grown them since 1925, should be
available in a few weeks in the Greenwich area (they are a
breakfast tradition at Saratoga Race Track). Because of careful
harvesting or because the microclimate in which they grow is
particularly salubrious, they are succulently sweet.
</P>
<P>
   The finest from California come from ``the west side,'' says
Harold Seybert, an owner of Fairway. The reference is to the west
side of the fertile San Joaquin Valley, where the days are hot and
the nights are warm, perfect growing conditions for melons to ripen
evenly. Markets often advertise the melons as ``west side'' because
they are so good.
</P>
<P>
   During the rest of the year, melons are harvested in places
where the temperature often spikes, so the fruit does not ripen or
color evenly. And of course, the farther the melons have to travel,
the firmer they must be when harvested. No wonder melons out of
season are usually a terrible disappointment _ rock hard and
practically tasteless.
</P>
<P>
   Local melons are expected to be superb this year because of the
hot weather, but they may not be plentiful because there has been
so little rain. California has also had a good season. At the
Greenmarkets in New York City, 1.5-pound local melons are expected
to sell for about $3 each, the same price as last year. California
melons are selling for $3 to $7 each, depending on where they are
purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Melons have been around for millenniums. Watermelons alone have
been traced to prehistoric times, when they were introduced to
India from their native soil of southern Africa. Egyptians were
eating them around 4,000 B.C. They reached the New World in 1493,
when Columbus took melon seeds to Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   The origin of muskmelons is a little more obscure. They come
from either Africa or India, and just to confuse matters more, what
we call cantaloupes are actually muskmelons. Cantaloupes are found
in Europe: the name comes from Cantalupo, a former papal garden
near Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Melons have long been treated as culinary treasures, and not
just in Renaissance France. This was true even before anyone cared
that they are very low in calories and have no fat, or that
orange-fleshed melons have lots of vitamins A and C.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have been trying various culinary experiments with
melons for decades. Before Prohibition, watermelons were filled
with alcohol and left to marinate overnight, a tradition still
observed at many beach parties. There were several recipes in the
1940s and '50s for filling a melon with flavored gelatin. And of
course, there have always been watermelon pickles.
</P>
<P>
   But the recipes that chefs in the '90s have created with melons
are considerably more imaginative and appealing. There are
delightful soups at Bouley Bakery, Cello, Montrachet, the Cub Room,
Daniel, Aureole and Chianti, as well as a particularly refreshing
sorbet at March and another at the River Cafe. And then there is
the traditional melon-and-prosciutto combination that has been
enhanced with figs at Le Cirque 2000.
</P>
<P>
   How do you choose a good melon? There are some rules, starting
with the fact that all melons should feel heavy. A good sign of
ripeness for most melons is a clean break between the melon and
stem rather than a cut in the stem itself, because when most melons
are perfectly ripe, they separate naturally from the plant.
</P>
<P>
   As with other fruits and vegetables, the moment of harvest is
crucial, because melons do not ripen further once they are picked,
although they continue to soften. Some melons, like Persians,
cantaloupes and casabas, have a little softness at the blossom end
when ripe, while others do not.
</P>
<P>
   The skin of a honeydew and other smooth melons should feel
velvety. Honeydews also have a creamy-golden tinge; avoid those
with a greenish hue. Melons that have netted skins should have a
yellowish, not green, color under the netting.
</P>
<P>
   Watermelons should sound hollow when thumped. The bottom side
should be yellowish, not white. With cut watermelon, look for the
thinnest skin and the brightest flesh, be it red, yellow or, new
this year, orange.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid melons that are too firm or too soft or that have sunken
spots on the skin.
</P>
<P>
   A ripe melon can be stored in the refrigerator for a couple of
days, but it is better to eat it before it has been refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   And there are better things to do with the juice of a watermelon
than to let it dribble down your chin. Puree seeded chunks of
melon, strain the juice, and shake it over ice with lemon-flavored
vodka. You'll never know what hit you.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MELON AND GOAT CHEESE SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Berkeley Bar and Grill
</P>
<P>
   Time: 12 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   36 balls ripe yellow watermelon
</P>
<P>
   16 balls ripe red watermelon
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons soft fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   8 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   8 large basil leaves, julienned
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place 9 yellow watermelon balls in center of each of four
plates, and top with 4 red watermelon balls. Sprinkle bits of goat
cheese around plate.
</P>
<P>
   2. Whisk oil and vinegar, and spoon over melon and cheese. Strew
basil leaves around, and season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CHILLED MELON AND YELLOW TOMATO SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Chianti
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 large ripe yellow tomatoes, about 1 pound
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe cantaloupe, 2{ to 2} pounds
</P>
<P>
   12 fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   \ cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Cook onions over very low heat in olive oil until soft, about
5 minutes. Coarsely chop 2 tomatoes, and add to onion to warm
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove skin from cantaloupe, seed and coarsely dice,
reserving \ cup of dice. Place tomato mixture and some of the diced
cantaloupe in blender, and puree, adding more melon until mixture
has the consistency of pureed soup, adding water if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add 4 mint leaves, Worcestershire sauce, lemon juice and lime
juice, and puree until smooth. Season with salt and pepper, and
chill well.
</P>
<P>
   4. Finely chop reserved cantaloupe. Finely chop remaining tomato
to yield { cup. Julienne remaining mint. Garnish each bowl of soup,
placing chopped cantaloupe and chopped tomato in center and
strewing with mint.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CALAMARI, WATERMELON AND AVOCADO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Union Pacific
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 cups fresh cilantro, plus { cup for garnish
</P>
<P>
   \ cup rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grape-seed oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces cleaned squid, cut into rings, including tentacles
</P>
<P>
   1 egg white, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1} tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons finely chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fines herbes (mixed chervil, tarragon,
chives and parsley)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces baby salad greens, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   16 thin slices of watermelon, rind and seeds removed, cut into
1-inch squares
</P>
<P>
   8 \-inch-thick slices of avocado. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare cilantro vinaigrette: Fill saucepan half full of
water, and bring to boil. Set aside a bowl of ice water. Place 4
cups cilantro in boiling water, and immediately lift out with
slotted spoon and transfer to ice water. Squeeze cilantro dry. In a
blender, combine cilantro, rice wine vinegar and grape-seed oil.
Puree until smooth. Transfer to a bowl, and season with salt and
pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare calamari: In medium bowl, combine squid, egg white
and ground coriander; mix well. In large saute pan over medium-high
heat, heat 1 tablespoon olive oil until it is smoking. Add squid
mixture, and saute until it is translucent, about 2 minutes. Add
butter, and stir until melted. Add 1 tablespoon shallots, stir, and
remove pan from heat. Add fines herbes and salt and pepper to
taste. Toss to mix well.
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare lemon vinaigrette: In small bowl, combine lemon
juice, remaining olive oil, and salt and pepper to taste. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Grate zest from lemon and reserve. Remove white pith and
seeds, and cut lemon into segments. In mixing bowl, combine lemon
zest, lemon segments, salad greens, remaining shallots, calamari
and lemon vinaigrette. Toss quickly to blend well.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, spread calamari mixture in center of large serving
platter. Arrange watermelon and avocado decoratively on top. Pour
ring of cilantro vinaigrette over salad, and drizzle vinaigrette
decoratively around edge of plate. Garnish with cilantro leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   MELON AND ORGANIC STRAWBERRY SOUP WITH FRUIT SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Bouley Bakery
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus 1 hour for chilling  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 small melon (Cavaillon, cantaloupe or honeydew), skin and
seeds removed, cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon acacia or other good-quality honey
</P>
<P>
   [ teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flat mineral water
</P>
<P>
   1 pint organic strawberries, washed and hulled
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberry sorbet
</P>
<P>
   { pint raspberries
</P>
<P>
   { cup skinned and seeded fresh litchis, or { cup canned litchis
(available in Asian markets and specialty food stores).
</P>
<P>
   1. In blender, combine melon, honey, salt and mineral water.
Blend until smooth and creamy, and then transfer mixture to a bowl.
Rinse container of blender.
</P>
<P>
   2. Puree strawberries until smooth. Strain through fine sieve to
remove seeds, and then transfer mixture to a bowl. Cover both bowls
of pureed fruit, and refrigerate until chilled, at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   3. To serve, pour 3 tablespoons of melon puree into each of six
chilled soup bowls. Pour 3 tablespoons of strawberry puree into
center of each bowl, to make concentric circles of fruit puree.
Place a scoop of sorbet into center of each bowl, and garnish with
raspberries and litchis. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 small servings.
</P>
<P>
   With the simplest embellishment, a melon can be transformed into
a light dessert or refreshing first course. Here are a few
suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cut a small melon like a Cavaillon in half, remove the seeds
and make a few slashes in the flesh. Fill the cavity with port wine
or moscato d'Asti, and refrigerate for eight hours or more. Or do
what Le Cirque 2000 does: serve a glass of port on the side, or
pour it in.
</P>
<P>
   _ For James Beard's Drunken Melon, cut a 2-inch-square plug in a
watermelon deep enough to go into the cavity. Deeply prick the
flesh with an ice pick, and fill to near the top with light rum,
Cognac, Champagne or gin. Replace the plug, and seal with heavy
tape. Refrigerate the melon for 24 hours, turning it over four or
five times. Serve sliced.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sprinkle slices or chunks with lime juice and dash of cayenne.
</P>
<P>
   _ Serve thin slices with prosciutto and figs, or with capocollo
or Smithfield ham and freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Drizzle wedges with hazelnut or orange liqueur, or sprinkle
with powdered ginger or finely cut candied ginger.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gently toss watermelon cubes in a mixture of lime juice,
tequila, hot pepper sauce and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that room-temperature melons have the best flavor
but that in the heat of summer, the well-chilled melon is most
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
