<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE CONSIDER SANCTIONS AGAINST CREDIT SUISSE GROUP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Switzerland, Japan)   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japanese regulators met Tuesday to consider possible
sanctions against Credit Suisse Group for obstructing a six-month
investigation into its financial activities in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse, based in Switzerland and one of the world's
biggest investment banks, could lose at least one of its licenses
to do business in Japan, according to a government official who
asked not to be identified by name, and it might face criminal
prosecution as well.
</P>
<P>
   If the Japanese authorities were to revoke the license of Credit
Suisse's Financial Products, which handles the firm's derivatives
products business, it would cut off a large source of profit. Such
a punishment also would turn into a huge embarrassment for Credit
Suisse, which has acknowledged some problems in its derivatives
business in Japan but says it took action to correct them.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators who met Tuesday are officials of the Financial
Supervisory Agency, Japan's financial watchdog. The agency also
handed over the findings of its investigation to Credit Suisse's
Tokyo office Tuesday. Results of the investigation were not
immediately released.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working to try to persuade the FSA to levy fair
penalties on Credit Suisse Group in Japan in light of our
acknowledged shortcomings,'' said Robert Baker, a Credit Suisse
spokesman in London.``This should be balanced by the clear legality
of our past transaction activity and by our discovery, reporting
and prompt disciplinary action in relation to the conduct of a
small number of our employees in Tokyo.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of Credit Suisse has received close scrutiny
from foreign investment banks here as an indicator of how Japan
will deal with them as it cleans up the country's debt-ridden
banking system and eases financial market regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The firm engaged in so-called window dressing, using a variety
of financial trading tools to help Japanese banks and companies
obscure their losses. Oddly, Credit Suisse is not likely to be
punished heavily for that activity. The legality of that business
does not seem to be in question, although the Financial Supervisory
Agency has begun investigating similar operations of Lehman
Brothers here.
</P>
<P>
   What outraged the regulators were efforts by Michael Winning,
the executive in charge of handling legal matters at Credit Suisse
in Tokyo, and other executives based here to hide the firm's
activities by shredding some documents and shipping others out of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Those activities, which Credit Suisse has acknowledged, give
officials here grounds to refer the case to the public prosecutor's
office for a criminal trial, which could result in financial
penalties and even jail terms.
</P>
<P>
   The case has been compared to the scandal that hurt Daiwa Bank
in the United States several years ago when it tried to cover up
more than $1 billion in trading losses at its New York branch.
After U.S. regulators began their investigation at Daiwa, a Daiwa
employee broke the seal on a box of evidence, which, among other
things, led to a record fine of $340 million when Daiwa pleaded
guilty in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo, Credit Suisse suspended Winning and others who
participated in the attempted cover-up and withheld the bonuses of
other employees. But it has contended that its employees were
engaged in an effort to hide evidence of violations of the
``firewall,'' the strict regulatory barrier aimed at keeping its
banking operations separate from its securities operations, not to
thwart the agency's investigators and cover up evidence related to
window dressing.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities here began to scrutinize Credit Suisse's window
dressing when Long Term Credit Bank of Japan and Nippon Credit Bank
were nationalized by the government last year. Both banks were
Credit Suisse clients, and their employees helped investigators
understand how the banks had hidden their losses using Credit
Suisse products and services.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
