<SLUG> BC-SWISS-MONEYLAUNDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWITZERLAND CITES SHARP RISE IN REPORTS OF MONEY LAUNDERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Reports of suspected money laundering have more than
quintupled since a law requiring expanded reporting went into
effect last year as part of Switzerland's effort to clean up its
international banking image, authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Office for Police Matters said it has received 210
tips involving assets worth $270 million, a ``substantial
increase'' in reporting, since the stricter accountability measure
went into effect on April 1, 1998. It released a report Tuesday
about the impact of the new law.
</P>
<P>
   One report involved a $32 million bank account, but most
involved smaller accounts, worth an average of $2 million, said
Daniel Thelesklaf, director of the Money Laundering Reporting
Office, which is mart of the Police Matters office.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of the money involved in reported cases came
from foreigners, he said. It included an attempt by an unnamed
Persian Gulf region country to deposit millions of dollars in
counterfeit money in a Swiss account, he said. The fake money was
not included in the accounting total, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Of the tips, more than 100 are being followed up by local and
federal prosecutors. Most of the suspected money laundering
transactions took place in the Swiss cantons of Geneva, Zurich and
Ticino, according to the 55-page report.
</P>
<P>
   Thelesklaf said it was too early for indictments, particularly
since a majority of the cases require Switzerland to seek
assistance from authorities in other countries, which takes time.
However, the reports have resulted in accounts being blocked by law
enforcement officials in cases that prosecutors decide to pursue,
he noted in a telephone interview from Bern, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 law broadened the obligation to report suspicious
transactions beyond banks to asset managers, lawyers, insurance
firms, credit card companies and foreign exchange bureaus. Prior to
that, between 30 and 40 reports had been filed yearly.
</P>
<P>
   Banks were responsible for 80 percent of the tips, Thelesklaf
said, an indication that they are increasing their monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   While he said he was satisfied with the number of reports in the
first year, the report noted that the number ``is still low, given
Switzerland's importance as a financial center.''
</P>
<P>
   It said measures would be taken to encourage reporting,
including ``increasing awareness among players in Swiss financial
circles, especially in the non-banking sector.'' For decades,
handling and managing money in Switzerland has been shrouded in
total secrecy, a tradition that the money laundering office is
seeking to end.
</P>
<P>
   The office plans to report yearly on the number of reports, and
the overall amounts involved.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
