<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-MILKEN-BOS &LR;      07-13 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MILKEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP GIVES BOSTON A FOURTH AS A TECHNOLOGY HOTSPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- So much for Greater Boston's self-image as Silicon
Valley East. According to a new economic ranking of America's top
high-technology regions, we're not playing second fiddle to
Northern California's high-tech economy. We're not even playing
third fiddle.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, we're number four. And look who's ahead of
us: Dallas and Los Angeles. At least that's the view from the Los
Angeles-based Milken Institute, a think tank created by Michael
Milken, the former junk-bond financier.
</P>
<P>
   Junk indeed, say some Boston technology mavens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just unbelievable to me,'' griped Leslie Smith, director
of the Massachusetts Interactive Media Council.
</P>
<P>
   But economist Ross DeVol, who prepared the study, minces no
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that Boston and its traditional manufacturing
industries have waned in importance,'' he said. ``It's entirely
possible that Boston may get back up to the number two point in the
next couple of years, but it's not there yet, based on the way we
conducted the study.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston suffers partly because the study looks at a broad variety
of technology businesses, not just the computer and biotech
sectors, in which Boston is so strong.
</P>
<P>
   But look on the bright side: DeVol sees Boston as a very strong
number four, because of a rich diversity of tech businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston has a truly diverse high-tech economy,'' he said.
``It's not just high-tech manufacturing, it's a lot of high-tech
services as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The institute drew up a list of 14 key high-tech industries,
ranging from computers to aircraft parts. Next, the study
determined how much each of these industries contributes to the
nation's industrial output. Then the researchers examined 300
metropolitan areas to see how much output was generated in these
regions for each of the 14 industries. The top high-tech regions
are places with above-average levels of output in several of the
industries.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that the study found the San Jose, Calif., area
by far the nation's leading center for high-technology business.
But who'd have expected to see Dallas come in second? Forget
stereotypes about oil and cattle. Dallas now hosts six of the
nation's 20 largest telecommunications services firms, including
the headquarters of giant GTE Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In third place comes Los Angeles, which lost a lot of tech jobs
after the end of the Cold War, but has made it up through a boom in
computerization of the entertainment business.
Special-effects-laden movies such as ``The Phantom Menace''
couldn't be produced without vast amounts of computing power and
state-of-the-art software. Remove the Hollywood factor, and LA
would slip all the way to seventh place.
</P>
<P>
   Boston finally appears in fourth place. Considering such local
disasters as the demise of Digital Equipment Corp., it could have
been worse. But we were saved by the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the joint impact of defense downsizing and heavy
dependence on the lagging mainframe computer industry has been
sizable,'' the study says, ``Boston is enjoying renewed vigor due
to its Internet-related prowess.''
</P>
<P>
   The Milken report cites numerous Net-related start-ups in the
region, with special mention of Waltham-based Lycos Inc., one of
the top Internet portals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Milken Institute's conclusions didn't sit well with
MIMC's Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard Dallas or LA be put in front of
Massachusetts,'' said Smith. ``There is an extraordinary amount
going on here. ... I think we're definitely growing much quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Plotkin, executive director of the Massachusetts Software
Council, questioned the assumptions of the Milken Institute report.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you back out the aerospace, defense, and entertainment
industries included in this report,'' Plotkin said, ``then Dallas
and LA drop from the radar screen, and Silicon Valley and Boston
remain the two leading high-tech centers.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Plotkin noted, the report cites research centers and
institutions as key factors in tech-industry growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clear leadership in the brainpower (and) idea-generation
area and our diversity of technology industries indicate that
Boston is extremely well-positioned for success in the new
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Foley, president of the Massachusetts High Technology
Council, said he wasn't much concerned about the report, or exactly
where Boston ranked among high-tech towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all in the eye of the beholder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Foley noted his organization's members _ top executives
of local tech companies _ said in a recent survey they were quite
pleased with the business climate in Greater Boston. But Foley
warned that last month's Massachusetts Senate vote to restore
capital gains taxes on assets held longer than four years will
damage the state's high-tech business climate.
</P>
<P>
   Said Foley: ``People are going to hear it and say, `To hell with
Massachusetts.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
