<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8664 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-F22-FUNDING-COX     07-13 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-F22-FUNDING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockheed F-22 funding in jeopardy
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston and Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A move in Congress to cut initial production funding
for the F-22 fighter raises new questions about the future of the
warplane to be assembled at Lockheed Martin Corp.'s plant in
Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The House Defense appropriations subcommittee unanimously
chopped $1.8 billion of the $3 billion in F-22 funding included in
the fiscal 2000 budget submitted by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The money is slated to fund initial production of the
next-generation fighter, pending a major Pentagon review this fall.
Under the House panel's proposal Monday, the remaining $1.2 billion
would still be spent on further development work.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerry Lewis (R-Calif.), the subcommittee chairman, said
F-22 production should be delayed while money is diverted to
``desperately needed'' programs to retain military pilots and
upgrade existing weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one beneficiary of the panel's plan is the Lockheed
Martin C-130J, the Marietta plant's primary product. The
subcommittee included money for eight Marine Corps refueling tanker
versions of the planes. The administration budget didn't include
any C-130Js.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon, Lockheed Martin and members of Georgia's
congressional delegation vowed to fight the F-22 cut, which Sen.
Max Cleland (D-Ga.) said could be fatal to the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House subcommittee erred on the F-22 by, in effect, voting
to kill it,'' Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has already passed a defense bill that includes the
full $3 billion for the F-22 but only two C-130Js.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Lockheed Martin and its political allies in the
tricky position of supporting the Senate version of the defense
bill in regard to the F-22 and the House version as it relates to
the C-130J.
</P>
<P>
   The House subcommittee plan faces another vote by the full House
Appropriations Committee, then would go to a conference committee
of the two chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be very fortunate if you came out with eight C-130Js and
$1.8 billion being restored for the F-22,'' said Rep. Saxby
Chambliss (R-Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin badly wants the C-130J orders to sustain
production of the plane until the Air Force begins a major
replacement program of older models. But the F-22 program is at a
more critical juncture, since a delay in initial production could
foster support for cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Burbage, president of Marietta-based Lockheed Martin
Aeronautical Systems, said he was ``surprised'' by the House
subcommittee's action. ``The aircraft are performing marvelously in
flight testing, and the overall program is on track and within
budget,'' Burbage said. ``We do not understand the subcommittee's
rationale.''
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 people work on the F-22 program at the Marietta
plant, where an assembly line and test facilities have been readied
for the start of production. So far, five test versions of the
plane have been built.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall Congress and the Pentagon approved two ``production
test vehicles'' to be built this year, along with pre-production
funding for an initial batch of six production F-22s. The $1.8
billion at issue in next year's budget would provide the full
funding for those planes.
</P>
<P>
   They would be the first of 339 F-22s the Air Force plans to buy.
Congress in 1997 capped F-22 costs at $18.9 billion for development
and $43.4 billion for production. Since then, concerns have been
raised that the program will exceed the caps, although Lockheed
Martin promises to stay within them.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a moderate conservative, said he's concerned the Pentagon
cannot afford to buy the F-22 and two other new planes, the Joint
Strike Fighter and the updated F-18 E/F, without diverting too much
money from other military needs.
</P>
<P>
   All three planes could cost more than $300 billion over the next
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said those plans are ``based on assessments made during
the Cold War.'' He added the Air Force should ``pause in its
pursuit of the F-22 and reassess if world events have warranted a
change in course. Delaying procurement of the first six fighters
will provide that pause.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said it ``remains convinced that the F-22 is the
revolutionary advance in fighter design that is needed to maintain
air superiority in the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we've got an airplane on the cutting edge of technology
in every respect,'' he said. ``If we ever let that slip, we run the
risk of not being able to do what we just did in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss also said he has had lengthy discussions with Lewis
and believes the subcommittee chairman wants to keep the Air Force
focused on controlling F-22 costs without killing the program.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston and Mark Sherman write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
