<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8665 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KASICH-2000-HNS &LR;      07-13 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASICH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GOP CONTENDERS WITHDRAWING FROM PRESIDENTIAL RACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Note budget change to include withdrawal of Sen. Bob Smith
of New Hampshire.) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The ranks of Republican presidential contenders are
thinning, with one departing prospect attacking league-leader
George W. Bush and another preparing to back the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire, a conservative firebrand,
huffed out of the Republican Party with a Senate speech Tuesday
that lambasted Bush and the GOP ``establishment'' as too pragmatic
and accommodating. He is looking to transfer his frail presidential
candidacy, perhaps to the U.S. Taxpayers Party.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, the Ohio Republican and chairman of the House
Budget Committee, was preparing to shut down his presidential
exploratory bid and endorse Bush on Wednesday as the governor
campaigns _ and raises more political contributions _ in the
Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   The developments come a month before a major test of popular
support and organizational ability, an Aug. 14 straw poll in Iowa,
an early caucus state where Smith and Kasich had spent a lot of
time campaigning, but with little apparent effect. Since the 1997
presidential inauguration, Smith had spent 50 days in Iowa and
Kasich 34, according to Hugh Winebrenner of Drake University in Des
Moines.
</P>
<P>
   Both contenders have shown negligible support in national polls
as well as those in Iowa and New Hampshire, an especially
embarrassing note for Granite Stater Smith. None of New Hampshire's
three other members of Congress, all Republicans, had endorsed the
maverick hard-liner.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who has two years remaining on his second Senate term,
said his move was a matter of conscience, but New Hampshire
Republican chairman Steve Duprey dismissed Smith as ``a sore
loser.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns of Smith and Kasich also had been plagued by
lackluster fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, in an emotional speech announcing his decision to change
his voter registration from Republican to independent, declared the
conservative platform drafted at the party's 1996 national
convention ``not worth the paper it's written on.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on NBC-TV's ``Today,'' Smith said the party was in the
thrall of ``pollsters and consultants'' who valued winning more
than hewing to conservative principles.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that no matter which party he took his candidacy to,
his platform would remain dedicated to anti-abortion and pro-gun
rights principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pro-life, it's pro-Second Amendment, it's pro-military,
it's pro-sovereignty, it's pro-character and integrity,'' Smith
said. ``Many who want to lead our party _ specifically candidate
Bush _ won't take a position on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other candidates who trail Bush in polls and fund
raising aligned themselves with Smith's sentiments but said they
would stick with the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I share the frustration but not the conclusion that leaving
the party is the right course of action,'' said former Vice
President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Steve Forbes, making his second run for the White
House, said Smith's decision was a ``wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that Bob Smith is abandoning the Republican Party,
it's that the Republican establishment is in the process of
abandoning grass-roots conservatives,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich, in the House since 1983, is not expected to seek
re-election from his central Ohio district next year. His move to
Bush could position him for a key federal post if the Texan wins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
