<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, July 14, Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Warnken (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-PROTESTS (Tehran, Iran) _ Developing. The worst unrest in
the Islamic Republic's history is countered in Tehran's clogged
streets by tens of thousands of uniformed and plain-clothes
security police, army troops, anti-riot police, Revolutionary
Guards, intelligence operatives, semi-official and free-lance
vigilantes, and ordinary street thugs. In scenes eerily reminiscent
of Iran's revolution two decades ago, police fired tear gas at
countless thousands of demonstrators and fired pistols and
submachine guns in the air as street battles raged through huge
swathes of the capital. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   VALUJET-INDICTMENT (Miami) _ SabreTech Inc., the airline
maintenance company that packed up the oxygen canisters blamed for
the 1996 ValuJet crash that killed 110 people is charged with
murder and manslaughter by a Florida grand jury; a federal grand
jury piled on charges of illegal transportation of hazardous
wastes, namely the oxygen cannisters that caused the fire that
brought the plane down. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   RAILWAY-KILLER (Houston) _ Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, the
rail-riding fugitive suspected of killing eight people who lived
near railroad tracks, surrenders at a border checkpoint Tuesday in
a deal brokered by his sister. Ramirez's sister, who lives in
Albuquerque, N.M., called a Texas ranger Sunday and said she had
been in touch with her brother through an intermediary, said a
state Department of Public Safety spokesman. The ranger, an FBI
agent and a deputy U.S. marshal met with the sister to negotiate
the surrender on a burglary warrant related to one of the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ In an interview on the eve of his
departure for a visit to Washington, Ehud Barak talks about his new
role as prime minister, saying that he is working hard to convince
the region's players that because he is a different kind of leader
with a different outlook than his predecessor, he can be trusted to
take a different path to peace. By Deborah Sontag. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SPRAWL (Salt Lake City) _ Salt Lake City and Milwaukee, two
cities with roughly equal metropolitan populations, each having
declared war on sprawl, are examples of how federal transportation
subsidies are still one of the biggest forces shaping urban areas.
For all the debate over the quality of life in America's gangly new
suburbs, highways direct growth, often with little debate. These
two urban areas are using federal highway money to go in opposite
directions, Salt Lake to speed people into and out of the city,
Milwaukee to restore a neighborhood and revive city life. By
Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   Special Report, 3,000 words; an abridged version will also be
sent.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ENVIRON (Pancevo, Yugoslavia) _ A look at one war-torn
town, its residents and its ruined factories. Here, in a sprawling
industrial park that held an oil refinery, a petro-chemical plant
and a fertilizer factory, lie the twisted pipes, scorched storage
tanks and jagged detritus left by bombs. Yet it is not these ruined
factories that are the worst scourges of war, many people here
believe, but the tons of toxic material that poured out of the
facilities. By Chris Hedges. 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   REEFERS:
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CANDIDATES-NO-MORE (Washington) _ Two Republican
presidential candidates are dropping out of the race, seven months
before the first vote is cast, because of Texas Gov. George W.
Bush's dominance. One, Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire, announced
he would leave the GOP and run for president as an independent. But
the other, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, faced with the reality that
his campaign has not taken off, will endorse Bush, aides said. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-HOMOSEXUALITY (Undated) _ The Vatican orders an American
priest and a nun to end a ministry to gay men and lesbians, saying
that the pair's work since the 1970s has strayed from church
teaching that homosexual activity is morally wrong. By Gustav
Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   TOURDEFRANCE (Sestrieres, Italy) _ Lance Armstrong takes a huge
step toward victory in the Tour de France by surging ahead of his
rivals on the tough first mountain stage and keeping a firm hold on
first place. By Samuel Abt.
</P>
