<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8688 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOPP-EDUCATION-2500(3     07-13 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOPP-EDUCATION-2500(3TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCIDENTAL REVOLUTIONARY IS CHANGING FACE OF EDUCATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wendy Kopp allows the standing ovation to fill the auditorium
for 10 seconds before she cuts in with a modest ``Hello.'' The
applause continues, and she leans toward the microphone again:
``Hello.'' Not ``Thanks very much.'' Not ``Wow, this is great.''
Her gratitude shows itself in a restrained smile.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp isn't here to bask in the adoration of the crowd. She
hasn't come to Houston to toot her horn or gush about what an
amazing 10 years it has been for Teach for America, the ``Peace
Corps for teachers'' she created when she was fresh out of
Princeton University. She's ready to get down to business.
</P>
<P>
   Her speech lasts 14 minutes. No jokes. No cute remarks. The
audience of 790 recent college graduates, which moments before was
whooping and laughing at the other presentations during this
opening ceremony, is entranced by Kopp's practiced oratory. She may
lack the magnetism of some natural-born motivators, but what she's
saying has them thoroughly mesmerized.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not joining Teach for America to become part of a
system where low achievement rates are viewed as unavoidable,''
Kopp stresses from behind the lectern. ``You are joining Teach for
America to be part of an effort to reach the day when all children
in this nation truly have the opportunity to attain an excellent
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we know that, as of now, we are shockingly far from
reaching that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Kopp needs her words to convey urgency as much as inspiration.
In less than two months, these new TFA corps members will be left
to their own devices in some of the toughest classrooms in the
United States: Houston, the Rio Grande Valley, the Bronx, Los
Angeles, the Mississippi Delta and eight other sites.
</P>
<P>
   They have no prior teacher training. They are very, very young.
Most have little or no experience working in low-income
communities, where they have committed to spend the next two years
of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Kopp is concerned, they are the perfect candidates for
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The notion is radical and controversial, but Kopp believes that
academically gifted young adults with the passion to help can be
great teachers without undergoing lengthy, rigorous training.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 corps members have graduated from the country's top
colleges _ Harvard, Stanford, Cornell, Spelman, Duke and the
University of Chicago, among others _ with degrees in science,
math, history and literature. Had they chosen differently, they
could have earned far more than a starting teacher's salary.
</P>
<P>
   They will have five weeks at this Houston-based training
institute to soak up a fraction of what most teacher-education
students study over several years. If they don't use this time
well, Kopp emphasizes tonight, they will surely fail.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp has built her adult life around the belief that public
education is shortchanging poor children _ and around the
conviction that she can do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   At 21, this Highland Park High School graduate created Teach for
America as a step toward strengthening neglected urban and rural
schools. At 22, she was camped in Ross Perot Sr.'s office
persuading him to write a check for a half-million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   By 23, Kopp and her brainchild had been featured in The New York
Times and the Los Angeles Times and on a PBS documentary called
``Who Will Teach for America?'' Glamour magazine named her one of
its 1990 Women of the Year, picturing Kopp alongside Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, Wendy Kopp, now 32, still possesses the same
mind-boggling confidence in her mission. And because of that, Teach
for America still has thousands of top college graduates vying for
the chance to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp would have moved on long ago if she wasn't positive they
were doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   A SIMPLE IDEA
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan's garment district is as unlikely a location as any
for Teach for America's national headquarters. On 36th Street
between Eighth and Ninth avenues trucks line the curb like circus
elephants, trunk to tail, and workers weave through foot traffic
dragging racks of fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Six stories up, above neighboring businesses' lightly graffitied
corridors, TFA stitches together its solution for educational
equity.
</P>
<P>
   The office is starkly unadorned: cement floor, exposed pipes,
cubicles separated by glorified particle board, and wire mesh
baskets stacked one atop another for mailboxes. The place looks
like the headquarters of a campus student group, and the fact that
everyone appears to be well under 30 only adds to the illusion.
</P>
<P>
   It also belies the reality that many of them, like Kopp, work
15-hour days and run one of the most well-known education
initiatives in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp oils the TFA machinery from a semi-enclosed office with
little more than a desk and a laptop computer. She keeps few
mementos on her shelves: the framed Woodrow Wilson Award from
Princeton, bestowed upon an outstanding undergraduate alumnus (Kopp
was the youngest person and the first woman ever to receive it);
and the group-shot photograph with Bill Clinton, taken during a
recent dinner at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   There's also a photograph from her wedding in February 1998 to
former TFA staff member Richard Barth. Barth now works for The
Edison Project, an education-reform enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Kopp seems an unlikely leader for such an
idealistic endeavor. Today she's wearing a flax-colored linen suit
and her long, naturally brown hair is pulled back off her face, but
in old pictures she's blond and perpetually tan. At Princeton she
never was the Birkenstock-wearing activist out protesting
apartheid, but spent her time as editor and publisher of a business
journal, selling advertising in the summers.
</P>
<P>
   A media magnet since founding TFA, Kopp nonetheless dislikes
that part of her job the most _ hates being in front of a camera
and prefers to keep the focus of any article off herself and on the
organization. She's not too fond of schmoozing either: Her friends
say she's much more comfortable talking one-on-one than working a
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   They also call Kopp, a former marathon runner who's always out
of bed by 6 a.m., super human. And they are awed by her ability to
juggle the responsibilities of a $6.5 million operation, to weather
the critics and to remain completely sane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still trying to figure it out 10 years later,'' says
Kopp's friend Daniel Oscar, the first person Kopp hired at TFA. ``I
really do think it comes back to this personal sense of
extraordinary confidence and this personal sense of conviction and
passion for what she believes in.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea to establish a national teacher corps evolved slowly,
between Kopp's freshman and senior years at Princeton. Educational
inequity hadn't exactly been foremost on her mind growing up in a
wealthy Dallas enclave, though according to friends she was far
from the stereotypical Highland Park teen.
</P>
<P>
   People who know her frequently apply the word ``overachiever''
to Kopp, and even she describes herself as ``driven'' in high
school: valedictorian of her senior class, editor of the school
newspaper, an actor in theater productions, a standout on the
debate team.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp made her spare change working for the family publishing
business and part time at a craft store. She even sewed her own
dresses. For fun, she and her friends would take long walks and
have ``very intense, very engaging conversations about big,
abstract issues like `Does God exist?' '' says Neeta Vallab, Kopp's
high-school debate partner and good friend. ``I think we probably
thought of ourselves as the cooler smart kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In college, the education issue confronted Kopp, a public policy
major, on more than an academic level. Her freshman-year roommate
had gone to public school in the Bronx, and though Kopp found her
college studies ``easier than my senior year in high school,'' her
roommate struggled to keep up _ ``despite the fact that she was
absolutely brilliant,'' Kopp says. ``That really got me thinking
about the disparities that exist in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Her senior year, Kopp chose sociology department chairman Marvin
Bressler as her thesis adviser. She took her proposal to him _ an
examination of volunteerism and a plan for launching a national
teachers corps _ in the fall of 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp's idea was simple: Recruit 500 recent college graduates
from the best universities in the country and place them, for
two-year stints, in under-resourced schools across the country.
</P>
<P>
   To do it, she proposed setting up an eight-week training
institute run by education professionals; raising $2.5 million from
corporate donors; negotiating with school districts around the
country; and generating a buzz on the program that would woo media
and applicants alike.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the new teachers lacked in preparation, Kopp
calculated, they would make up for in sheer intelligence and
enthusiasm. Just as important, TFA alumni would bring to their
respective fields _ law, business, technology _ a rare commitment
to improving public education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to her, as any supportive faculty member would say,
`Ms. Kopp, you are quite clearly deranged,' '' Bressler recalls.
But Kopp refused to bite off any less, and the professor finally
gave in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot tell you how much I admire her,'' says Bressler, a
professor emeritus who still keeps in touch with Kopp. ``She's
remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   ALL FOR ONE
</P>
<P>
   Kopp has told the story of how TFA came together hundreds of
times: how she sent letters to random CEOs asking for money; how
Mobil Corp. was the first to offer a $26,000 seed grant in June
1989, the month she graduated from Princeton; how Union Carbide and
then Morgan Stanley donated Manhattan office space to the fledgling
group.
</P>
<P>
   The staff worked around the clock; part time was defined as
about 60 hours a week; people took turns catching Z's on a
community cot. When Vallab first visited the New York offices, she
saw a sign-in board with everyone's name and categories like
``Taking a nap'' and ``Gone home to shower.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of looked enviously at other folks in their early 20s
who went out to restaurants and did normal things,'' Oscar says.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1990, when Ross Perot Sr. called the TFA
offices asking for Kopp, she thought it was a prank. Kopp had
written Perot 11 letters asking for support and had heard nothing,
but now the voice on the phone was unmistakable. She made an
appointment to meet him the next week in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally sat on his couch for two hours while he tried to
tell me that he wasn't the answer, that Sam Walton was the
answer,'' Kopp says. When she left Perot's office that day, she had
a commitment of $500,000 _ as long as TFA could match it threefold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a certain naivete about her that enables her
to do things like that,'' says Vallab, who worked at TFA from 1990
to 1995. ``She almost doesn't consider all the things that would
make someone else nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   By February 1990, 2,500 college seniors and graduates had
applied to be among the first TFA corps. Staff members in donated
rental cars were driving from campus to campus interviewing them,
and Kopp was making preparations for the first training institute,
to be held on the campus of the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Everything would come together exactly as she envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if I believe in something,'' Kopp says, ``I'm just
convinced that I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BACKLASH
</P>
<P>
   As lauded as TFA was during its first few years, the
organization drew vocal critics, too. The education establishment,
especially, decried the corps members' lack of training.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest blow came in 1994, when Linda Darling-Hammond, then
a respected professor of education at Columbia University's
Teachers College, wrote a 13,000-word article condemning TFA as
ineffective and potentially harmful to the children it served.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of first-time public-school teachers enter a
classroom with a year or more of education course work under their
belts (much more for those going into elementary education). States
continue to raise the bar on teacher qualifications, and teacher
educators are pushing hard for longer and more rigorous degree
programs.
</P>
<P>
   But TFA has thrown out decades worth of research into how to
best train teachers. Its program values on-the-job experience and
thorough subject knowledge _ of science, math, English, etc. _ over
teaching theory.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp dismisses the criticisms now as she did then. She points to
corps members' concrete successes and the impressive results of
annual surveys asking principals, parents and students to rate
their TFA teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Darling-Hammond article hurt. Kopp was
vacationing in Ocean City, N.J., when a staff member called to
deliver the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing was awful,'' she says. ``The fact is, we were so
weak organizationally that this was the last thing I had time to
deal with. We had no money, the staff was unhappy ...''
</P>
<P>
   By its fourth year, the TFA budget had burgeoned to $8 million.
Kopp was overseeing 75 full-time employees in 10 offices nationwide
and acting as the primary fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   But donors had started holding back. Not only did arguments like
Darling-Hammond's concern them, but most corporations had committed
only seed money to TFA. Now that the organization was up and
running, they were less inclined to give.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp dug in her heels, calling every number in her Rolodex for
help. ``I've never been so miserable,'' she says. ``Every two weeks
I would look in the bank accounts and there was no money, and we
had to get $200,000 in the bank to make the next payroll.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kopp was more anxious than ever, no one could tell. Vallab
says she never saw an ``external manifestation of stress'' in
Kopp's manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very strong person from an emotional standpoint,''
says her brother, David, 30. ``And I think you have to be to do
something like that. She becomes the person that everyone in her
organization looks to for emotional strength.''
</P>
<P>
   TFA weathered the crisis and rebuilt. Today, the organization
has collected $3 million toward a $10 million endowment, and Kopp
hopes to expand from 13 to 18 sites. The program continues to spark
controversy in education circles, but interest from college
students remains high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Wendy has any enemies,'' says Bressler. ``I
think she has people who disagree with her, but it's impossible to
disregard her good will.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she had the least bit of malice in her at all, she'd be a
menace to organized society.''
</P>
<P>
   MAKING THE GRADE
</P>
<P>
   The speech Kopp gives at the University of Houston student
center on opening night goes over big. The new recruits head back
to the campus dorms, where they will live for the next five weeks,
chewing over her words. Some of them may have known her as merely
``Wendy someone'' earlier, but by the next morning the TFA founder
is an icon among them.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp says she could walk away from TFA tomorrow and feel
confident that the organization would thrive. ``It's far beyond
me,'' she says. ``The only reason I'm not doing it is because I've
realized this is the issue I'm most passionate about.''
</P>
<P>
   She spends weekends these days working on a book, an overview of
what she's learned ``about education ... about everything.'' She
admits to wanting a saner life in the future, including a family,
but she's not fretting about how it will all work out. It just
will.
</P>
<P>
   The day after her speech, Kopp sits observing an institute
classroom, where new corps members are studying education theory.
During a break in the discussion, a lanky recruit in shirt and tie
walks by Kopp's desk and bends slightly toward her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to say thank you,'' he offers shyly.
</P>
<P>
   This time Kopp smiles broadly.
</P>
<P>
   This time she says ``Thank you'' back.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
