<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8695 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      07-13 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON COURTS NEW YORK SUBURBAN VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``a'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALHALLA, N.Y. _ In an appeal to New York's suburban voters,
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton said Tuesday she supports making
college tuition tax deductible, a more dramatic solution to rising
college costs than the modest tuition tax breaks favored by her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   She said the 1997 enactment of President Clinton's proposals for
a $1,500 tuition tax credit and boosts in federal grant programs
has helped make college more affordable for many students. However,
she said the high cost of college tuition remains a concern for
families.
</P>
<P>
   Her solution: ``I think that college tuition should be tax
deductible,'' Clinton told a student who asked her about more
federal aid for college education.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't spell out what she wanted but said that she has
spoken with Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., about his bill that would
allow individuals earning $100,000 or less and couples earning
$140,000 or less to fully deduct the cost of their children's
college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with a select group of about 50 business leaders,
educators, students and former welfare recipients at Westchester
Community College in affluent Westchester County outside New York
City. Her audience was picked by the college with input from local
political officials.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton indicated that the 1997 package of federal tax breaks
wasn't enough to deal with high college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as though we move one step forward, then we get
overwhelmed by costs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's college visit marked the start of the second
week of her ``listening tour'' of New York as she gears up to run
for the U.S. Senate seat being vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y. Last week Clinton created an exploratory committee
that allows her to raise money while she considers whether to
formally announce her decision to run.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-hour session, Clinton listened intently, took
notes and posed questions to a panel of educators, business leaders
and a former welfare recipient who discussed education and welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Hodges, who recently completed a one-year job-training
program affiliated with the community college, told Clinton that
she would like to complete her two-year degree but has been unable
to because she is working full-time and unable to find child-care
in the evenings to attend classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very successful, overall,'' Clinton said of the
federal welfare reform law enacted in 1996. ``But I am concerned
about the child-care piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the audience were generally very friendly in their
questioning of the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton side-stepped a question from Sarah Stern, 40, a
self-described Republican, who asked whether Clinton favored ending
tenure for teachers as a way to more easily eliminate ineffective
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't we make them have five year contracts?'' said Stern, who
serves on a Westchester school board nominating committee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is counting on the political support of New York's
teachers' unions, turned to a school principal on the panel and
asked her to describe the steps that can be taken to remove a
poorly performing teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Stern later said she found Clinton to be ``very bright,'' but
said she was unlikely to vote for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't trust her,'' she said, citing concerns about
Clinton's role in Whitewater and other scandals.
</P>
<P>
   But Vincent Beni, a Westchester educator, said he was ``very
impressed'' with Clinton and will consider voting for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't vote for people who aren't running,'' Beni said
referring to the exploratory status of Clinton and New York Mayor
Rudolph Guilani, who is expected to seek the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton travelled to Jones Beach, L.I., where she shook hands
with beach-goers for about 10 minutes before meeting with William
Cunningham, her exploratory campaign committee treasurer, over
lunch of crab cakes and ice tea.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also shook hands some of the 200 people sitting in the
Boardwalk Restaurant located above the beach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS - STORY MAY END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters that she is still looking for housing in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking any suggestions, ideas and recommendations,'' she
said before group of about 20 reporters and a few dozen tourists
who had come off of the beach to see what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody have any neighbors who are moving shortly?,'' Clinton
asked the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a lot more complicated than I thought it would be
because I have to worry about security and other matters that I
wouldn't have to worry about under other circumstances,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she and her friends will continue looking for a
home to enable her to establish residency in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who was wearing a black pant suit and a light-blue
t-shirt, briefly strolled to the edge of the board walk to look at
the ocean before heading inside for her hour-long lunch at the
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady will continue her tour of Long Island Wednesday
when she visits a middle school in Rockville Center and a health
care center in Great Neck.
</P>
<P>
   She will then attend a private fundraiser on Thursday at a
Manhattan law firm. About 100 people are expected to attend the
$1,000-per-person event.
</P>
<P>
   Among those expected to attend the event are Wall Street
financier Roger Altman, who was deputy treasury secretary during
President Clinton's first term, and millionaire businessman Erskine
Bowles, a former White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign is expected to cost $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, her press secretary, refused to say how much
money Clinton and her supporters have raised, except to say ``It's
going very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaigns in New York are expensive,'' he said. ``The last
campaign cost about $40 million and I don't have any reason to
expect this to be different,'' referring to last year's Senate race
between Schumer and incumbent Alfonse D'Amato, a Republican.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
