<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON COURTS NEW YORK SUBURBAN VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``a'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALHALLA, N.Y. _ In an appeal to New York's suburban voters,
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton said Tuesday she supports making
college tuition tax deductible, a more dramatic solution to rising
college costs than the modest tuition tax breaks favored by her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   She said the 1997 enactment of President Clinton's proposals for
a $1,500 tuition tax credit and boosts in federal grant programs
has helped make college more affordable for many students. However,
she said the high cost of college tuition remains a concern for
families.
</P>
<P>
   Her solution: ``I think that college tuition should be tax
deductible,'' Clinton told a student who asked her about more
federal aid for college education.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't spell out what she wanted but said that she has
spoken with Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., about his bill that would
allow individuals earning $100,000 or less and couples earning
$140,000 or less to fully deduct the cost of their children's
college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with a select group of about 50 business leaders,
educators, students and former welfare recipients at Westchester
Community College in affluent Westchester County outside New York
City. Her audience was picked by the college with input from local
political officials.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton indicated that the 1997 package of federal tax breaks
wasn't enough to deal with high college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as though we move one step forward, then we get
overwhelmed by costs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's college visit marked the start of the second
week of her ``listening tour'' of New York as she gears up to run
for the U.S. Senate seat being vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y. Last week Clinton created an exploratory committee
that allows her to raise money while she considers whether to
formally announce her decision to run.
</P>
