<SLUG> BC-U.S.-KOSOVO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISE  -HNS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 U.S. COMMANDER SAYS ATTACKS ON TROOPS ON THE (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Army Brig. Gen. John Craddock, the commander of
U.S. forces in Kosovo, said Tuesday that peacekeeping troops have
come under renewed attack over the last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a period of about eight or nine days at the
beginning of July where we had no instances of U.S. soldiers coming
under fire,'' Craddock told reporters here in a telephone interview
from the U.S.-controlled sector of Kosovo. ``Recently, that's
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The attacks have increased As U.S. forces have fanned out across
the southeastern portion of Kosovo to enforce the peace agreement
formalized June 20 between NATO, Yugoslav forces and separatist
ethnic Albanian guerrillas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, American troops were fired on several times near the
town of Gnjilane. Sunday night U.S. forces were shot at outside the
town of Vitina, and Monday night American peacekeepers were
attacked in Urosevac.
</P>
<P>
   Craddock said the attacks, which did not result in any U.S.
casualties, were not part of a coordinated campaign. Rather, he
said, it's likely that ``rogue'' or ``splinter'' Yugoslav army
troops and possibly ethnic Albanians are to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's incident was a case of mistaken identity, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Several Army troops were patrolling when they were fired on.
``They looked to see what was going on. They found a Serb, an
elderly Serb man, 65 years old, standing in his doorway with a
rifle. So they went up and disarmed him,'' Craddock said. The Serb
said he had mistaken the Americans for Yugoslav troops, whom he did
not support.
</P>
<P>
   American forces first arrived June 14 _ four days after the
78-day NATO air assault was suspended _ to patrol the southeastern
portion of Kosovo, a Serb province about the size of Connecticut.
Serbia is the dominant republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   On June 23, U.S. Marines killed two attackers who had fired on
them. The night before, members of the U.S. Army's 82nd Airborne
Division were fired on. No one was killed, and three men were
detained for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Craddock said, lawlessness has dropped since the U.S.
forces took control of the sector, one of five that NATO has
established in the province. The others are controlled by British,
French, German and Italian forces.
</P>
<P>
   But the commander said that the crime level ``is still not to
the point where we want it.'' He added, ``There are still far too
many instances of houses being burned _ vacant houses throughout
the entire area _ and incidents of random shootings.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO eventually will deploy 50,000 troops across the province,
including 7,000 U.S. troops in the American sector. Craddock said
about 6,500 U.S. troops are now in the region.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
