<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, July 14 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Susan Leh at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   MURDER-SOLVED (Los Angeles) _ Fifteen years after Los Angeles
County Sheriff's Sgt. George Arthur was shot to death while driving
in Boyle Heights, police say DNA matches prove a fellow deputy was
the killer. A nationwide manhunt is underway for Ted Eugene Kirby,
a retired sheriff's deputy whom police say was driving with Arthur
and then shot him to death, causing them to crash. By Lisa Van
Proyen. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news
files.)
</P>
<P>
   SECEDE-FUNDS (Los Angeles) _ The Los Angeles County Board of
Supervisors voted unanimously Tuesday to provide funds for a study
of San Fernando Valley secession, provided the city of Los Angeles
does the same. By Douglas Haberman. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HEAT-WAVE (Los Angeles) _ Triple-digit temperatures and East
Coast-like humidity return, creating freakish weather and giving
air conditioning repairmen and tow truck drivers plenty of work. By
Jesse Hiestand. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a''
national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   PRINCIPALS-REPORT (Los Angeles) _ The Los Angeles Educational
Alliance for Restructuring Now called Tuesday for an ``overhaul of
the way principals are recruited, trained, paid and disciplined in
the Los Angeles Unified School District.'' The LEARN report
recommends retraining all principals _ old and new. By David Baker.
(Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT (Los Angeles) _ Help from the entertainment industry
pulled the Los Angeles metropolitan area into the top tier of
high-tech regions in the country last year, according to an
economic report released Tuesday. By Jason Takenouchi. (Will move
in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AMGEN-GAIN (Los Angeles) _ Amgen Inc., the world's largest
biotechnology company, gained 9 percent after second-quarter profit
rose a better-than-expected 24 percent. Amgen also surprised
investors by unveiling plans to seek U.S. approval to market a new
arthritis treatment by year-end. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the
``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
