<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEFEATS MEASURE ON WOMENS' HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republicans on Tuesday defeated a Democratic
measure that would have given women greater choices in choosing a
doctor and longer hospital stays after a mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening vote on patients' rights legislation, Republican
senators said they would offer competing legislation Wednesday that
addresses the same issues.
</P>
<P>
   But the 52-48 defeat drew harsh criticism from the supporters.
The defeated measure would have let women choose an
obstetrician-gynecologists as a primary-care doctor under managed
care programs, and let them remain in a hospital after a
breast-removal surgery if a doctor advises it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got on this floor, they gave us the back of their hand,
they lied to us and women will suffer,'' said Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif. She said the lives of women are at stake if they can't go
directly to a gynecologist after discovering a lump in a breast.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., said ``women shouldn't have to go
through a maze of doctors to be treated, but that's what this
Senate has told us. ... I am amazed and appalled.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Republicans _ John W. Warner of Virginia, Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania and and John H. Chafee of Rhode Island _ deserted
their party on the vote and joined in supporting one of the
provisions of the Democratic version of the Patients' Bill of
Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is considering this week different proposals to give
people more power in dealing with managed care providers, which are
generally credited with helping to control health care costs by
using a network of member doctors and requiring patients to first
see a primary care physician before seeing specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders blunted criticism that they were insensitive
to the needs of women.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are ridiculous charges by the Democrats, that politicize
the issue,'' said Brook Simmons, a spokesman for Sen. Don Nickles,
R-Okla., the assistant minority leaders who is handling the managed
care legislation for Republicans. ``We do not use patients as
political props.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, President Clinton accused the Republican
leadership of catering to health insurance companies and supporting
a rights bill that would do little to help patients who have
coverage through managed care companies, or health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about political power in Washington trying to shut off
something that is manifestly in the best interest of the average
citizen of this country _ and not just the average citizen _ every
single person covered by an HMO,'' Clinton said at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans seek a much narrower version of the Democratic
patients' rights bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, for example, say patients need a bigger legal
stick to prevent managed care organizations from denying coverage.
They want to change the law to allow a patient to sue managed care
providers in state courts for pain and suffering and punitive
damages _ whatever is allowable under the state's law _ if a
patient was harmed because a treatment was wrongfully denied.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law now limits such lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republican leaders argue that expanding a patient's right
to sue would lead to litigation that would jack up the cost of
health care, making it too costly for smaller businesses to provide
insurance for their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Republicans support a scaled-down approach to help
patients fight back if they think they've been wrongfully denied
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats want to extend new consumer protections to 161
million people, including increased access to specialists. The
Republican's narrower protections would apply to 48 million people
in group health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats held simultaneous dueling press
conferences on Capitol Hill Tuesday with each side jockeying for
political advantage as they eye the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said the Republican proposals
lacked substance. ``We're finding out how inadequate, how empty
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are empty provisions, they basically are riddled with
loopholes and they are completely a sham,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Minority Leader Thomas A. Daschle said the Republican bill was
nothing but ``a shell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is preposterous that they would call this a bill of rights,
this is a bill of goods,'' said Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles called on the Senate to reject the Democrats' bill,
which he said contains far too much regulation of the managed care
industry and amounts to ``Washington D.C. knows best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
