<SLUG> BC-SOC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ISN'T ABOUT THE BOYS CLUB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of a moment in time that should endure well into the
next century, several naysayers wearing the uniform of your typical
American male, macho sports fan went on a rant after the Women's
World Cup final.
</P>
<P>
   They beat their chest and said soccer still sucks. They said the
large crowds and TV ratings for the U.S. team were flukes. They
said no one would ever pay to watch a woman's pro soccer league.
And their enjoyment of Saturday's win over China was limited to
Brandi Chastain taking off her jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I have a news flash for fellows in this clique: This
wasn't about you.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup wasn't about seizing the attention of
anyone in the Boys Club. It wasn't designed to change anyone's view
of soccer or the rest of the sports world.
</P>
<P>
   If the World Cup turns out to be a success, it will have little
to do with the sports talk hosts who do remote broadcasts from
Hooters, or any other media types having difficulties or
inadequacies accepting the image of the female athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Based on some of the post-Cup chit chat, that's an issue. A
whole lot of air time and ink have been wasted over Chastain's
decision to rip her jersey off in celebration, revealing ...
ohmygawd, a SPORTS BRA!
</P>
<P>
   To hear some guys talk about it, you'd think Chastain had just
given every guy in the Rose Bowl a lap dance. Geez, get over
yourself. Visit a gym, or take in a track meet or marathon. You'll
see dozens of women wearing sports bras.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup was about women athletes defining
themselves on their own terms in front of a new audience. Of the
90,185 who attended Saturday's game, I'd reckon less than 10
percent of them are likely to attend a college football game this
fall. Or, for that matter, a Galaxy game.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd's common profile was that of a family of four-to-six,
with at least one daughter who plays youth soccer. These were
soccer moms bringing their daughter to a big game, just as there
are baseball dads who take their sons to Dodgers games.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. team member Tisha Venturini summarized it best after the
game: ``I think everybody in the stadium had a sister, daughter or
niece who played soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the consumers who will determine if a pro league can
survive and thrive, not the Bud Lite crowd. But if anyone wants to
stay on the bandwagon, they're welcome. ``We all consider it an
honor that people who don't know our sport came out to look,'' said
Venturini.
</P>
<P>
   Every time a sport outside of the usual rotation has a big
event, talk of a professional league fills the air. Anyone remember
World Team Tennis, or the first professional soccer league, the
NASL? In the '90s, we've seen pro leagues for lacrosse, roller
hockey and women's softball pop up, with modest success.
</P>
<P>
   Women's soccer has a chance to prosper for several reasons. For
starters, there is plenty of talent available and a foundation of
youth programs that will keep producing talent. There are 246
Division I soccer programs in the NCAA, and the U.S. under-21 and
under-18 national team programs are having the same kind of success
as the World Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, a U.S. league could be arranged around national team
demands, and those demands aren't nearly as pressing as they are in
men's soccer. Many of the top Major League Soccer (MLS) players
have to leave their teams to compete in national tournaments and
Cup qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   And while we may call the MLS a major league, the soccer world
does not. The MLS would be a B Division league if it operated in
Europe. A women's pro league here could quickly become the
equivalent of an A league, in part because there are fewer
opportunities for women soccer players overseas.
</P>
<P>
   And as the crowds for the World Cup indicate, there appears to
be an audience out there. Organizers just need to be cognizant that
great moments and good intentions aren't fail safe.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of two pro leagues, the Women's NBA and American
Basketball League (ABL), after the '96 Olympics wasn't the smartest
way to launch women's pro basketball. The ABL died, and some WNBA
cities are struggling at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a benefactor in television will be important, but a
league can't let TV dictate too much. Pro volleyball leagues let TV
talk them into fundamental changes in the game. Not only did it
hurt the sport, but network TV bailed out.
</P>
<P>
   Television and marketing executives will say a women's league
needs to have franchises in major markets. But I'm no longer sure
that's a necessity. It's not like NFL ratings have nose-dived since
L.A. lost two franchises. The presence of the Knicks in the NBA
finals didn't keep NBC's Nielsen ratings from falling to
pre-Magic/Bird levels.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask a women's soccer league team to play in a 50,000-seat
stadium and compete with more traditional sports, it will be
difficult to prosper. Small markets can offer something big cities
can't, exclusive attention for the product.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest franchise success stories in the MLS, for example,
have been in Columbus and Washington, D.C. Cities like Portland,
San Jose, San Antonio and Charlotte are large enough to provide a
fan base and hunger for teams to call their own.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, the best place to plant a women's team would be Cal
State Fullerton. The soccer stadium there now seats 10,000, but the
original blueprint included expansion plans up to 30,000. It
wouldn't take long to build it up to a 20,000-seat stadium. Plus,
there are more youth leagues per square mile in Orange County than
anywhere else in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much has happened here to deny the energy of this team and
how it captured America,'' U.S. World Cup coach Tony DiCicco said
after the win. ``It will be interesting to see where we go with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people will stay on what goalkeeper Briana Scurry called
``an incredible, unbelievable, awesome ride.'' Others won't. You'll
know them when you see them. They'll be at Hooters watching women
in sports bras.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
