</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISESHIP-ASSAULTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE LINE REPORTS 62 ALLEGED SEXUAL ASSAULTS OVER 5 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (mk) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In a rare look at crime aboard the nation's growing
cruise fleet, Carnival Cruise Lines reported in court papers filed
Tuesday that its crew members were accused of sexually assaulting
passengers and fellow workers aboard its ships 62 times in a
five-year period that ended last August, a rate of nearly once a
month.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics represent the first public disclosure by a cruise
line about the number of alleged rapes and other sexual assaults
that occur on cruises. Industry officials have said cruises are
safe, but there have been no figures because big cruise ships are
registered in foreign countries and are not required to report all
incidents to U.S. authorities.
</P>
<P>
   There has been growing criticism by crime victims and others
that the industry covers up crime on its cruises. Officials of the
FBI said last year that they had investigated fewer than two
accusations of rape a month in the Port of Miami, the nation's
busiest cruise passenger center.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival Cruise Lines, a subsidiary of the Miami-based Carnival
Corp., said in court papers that it investigated the 62 incidents
but did not disclose the results or say whether any arrests were
made. The figures did not include accusations involving only
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival produced its numbers in connection with a lawsuit in
Miami against the company by a former crew member who says she was
raped and sodomized by an officer aboard Carnival's Imagination
last Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival is the world's largest cruise company, carrying about a
third of the nearly 6 million passengers who travel out of U.S.
ports every year. Tim Gallagher, a company spokesman, said he was
unaware of the assault figures and referred questions to a lawyer
for Carnival, Curtis Mase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any allegation would be taken seriously, but do these
statistics suggest that Carnival ships are unsafe?'' Mase said.
``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   The company provided only sketchy information about the
incidents, which Mase said covered a broad range of sexual
misconduct, including molestation and rape. A chart compiled by
Carnival listed the date of each reported incident, the date the
company learned of it, the name of the ship where it occurred and
the job title of the accused attacker.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents were scattered among the company's ships, and
involved employees ranging from cabin steward and assistant cook to
supervisors, engineers and a chief security officer. The statistics
are limited to accusations involving attacks by crew members and do
not include any incidents that may have occurred between
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the company said that it investigated the alleged
incident and reported it to the appropriate authorities if
requested to do so by the purported victim. Cruise ships are not
required to report crimes to U.S. authorities when they occur in
international waters.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, some members of Congress have complained that
the fast-growing cruise industry is permitted to operate beyond the
reach of the nation's criminal and environmental laws. They also
have raised questions about the industry's ability to avoid paying
corporate income taxes to the United States by incorporating in
foreign countries and flying foreign flags on their vessels.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, rape victims and their lawyers complained that
Carnival and other cruise lines were not helpful in investigating
reports of assaults on cruise ships and that ship personnel were
sometimes untrained in gathering evidence in rape cases. They also
contended that in some instances victims were discouraged from
reporting the crimes to the FBI or other law-enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The suit that led to Carnival's disclosure of the assault
statistics involved an incident last August aboard the Imagination.
A 26-year-old woman, identified as Jane Doe in court papers, said
that she was raped and sodomized by Yurij Senes, a ship's engineer,
after she invited him to her cabin. At the time of the alleged
incident the woman had worked for Carnival for three years, and
Senes had joined the company two months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   According to her suit and her lawyers, the woman immediately
reported the attack to ship security and identified her attacker,
but she was persuaded not to file a report. A day later, when the
ship docked in Miami, the woman reported the incident to the FBI.
When agents tried to question Senes they learned that he had been
fired and escorted to the airport by Carnival employees for a
flight to his home in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Carnival said earlier that the woman initially did
not want to report the incident to the authorities and that Senes'
departure occurred before the company realized the FBI wanted him
for questioning. He has since been indicted by a federal grand jury
on charges of aggravated sexual assault, but he remains in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   When the woman's lawyer, Gary Fox, sought to obtain information
from Carnival on the frequency of sexual assaults on its ships, the
company objected. The statistics were turned over only after the
trial judge in Dade County and a Florida appellate court twice
rejected efforts by Carnival to block their release.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the most obnoxious, stalling, stonewalling
institutional litigant I've ever seen,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   From the first hearing in the case, Carnival has maintained that
the sex between the woman and Senes was consensual, something she
has repeatedly denied. Mase, the company's lawyer, also asked
numerous questions about the woman's sexual history and attitudes
in her deposition. At one point, he asked if she considered herself
sexually liberal or conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with colleagues on the ship, she said, she considered
herself a nun.
</P>
<P>
   Mase said the personal questions about the woman's sexual
experiences were important to the company's defense. He said that
evidence would show that people could differ on whether the sexual
contact was consensual, though he declined to specify the nature of
the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   As often happens in civil suits, cruise lines usually settle
rape cases with agreements that neither side disclose the terms or
talk further about the incident. But Fox said his client was
determined to pursue her case and would demand that rape-detection
kits be carried on every Carnival ship as a condition of any
settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
