<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT WING REELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The extraordinary chaos this summer in the
political right wing is welcome news for the Republican Party, the
Democratic Party and in fact the entire country.
</P>
<P>
   The ultraconservative ideological purists are in the early
stages of self-destructing. They sense they are losing their
following, their causes and their clout _ and in their frustration
they are blindly speeding up the process.
</P>
<P>
   Goody.
</P>
<P>
   Their internal angst weakens their ability to push the
mainstream GOP to the far right, put Democrats on the defensive,
push narrow-minded wedge issues and distract political centrists
from seeking substantive compromises to solve substantive problems.
</P>
<P>
   It all comes down to the 2000 race for the White House, where
the next occupant will dominate the national agenda for the next
half-decade. The right wing is whining because it is in danger of
being isolated, robbed of the disproportionate power over the
political process that it has exercised since Ronald Reagan's 1980
election.
</P>
<P>
   The Tuesday defection from his party of GOP presidential hopeful
Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., abruptly moved the right-wing diaspora from
political gossip to reality.
</P>
<P>
   His political change of heart has less to do with fundamental
principles than with his candidacy's feeble 3 percent support in
his own state and 1 percent backing in the national polls. But
Smith's plan to flee to a third party focuses our minds wonderfully
on the sorry state of that cluster of far-right candidates once
confident of controlling the Republican Party next year.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody took Smith's candidacy seriously beyond a hard core of
noisy conservative activists who want to take the country in a
direction that a majority of voters do not want to go _ opposing
all gun control, banning all abortion, promoting home schooling,
cutting federal domestic spending, peddling isolationism. That
won't change if some obscure fringe party adopts him.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith's lack of national identity was compounded by the fact
that too many other ultraconservatives also crowded into the
Republican race, all singing to the same small choir from the same
hymn book.
</P>
<P>
   The odd notion that Manhattan real estate developer and supreme
egoist Donald Trump may join them reinforces the silliness of it
all. Trump for president? Give me a break.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the legendary political machine of the religious
right exhibits serious signs of exhaustion. Even Christian
Coalition founder Pat Robertson concedes that Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, parading moderate credentials, seems to have sewed up the GOP
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Buchanan, making his third White House bid, hints that
he might desert the Republicans for the Reform Party if it would
have him, which seems unlikely. Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura,
forcefully moving as the party's only elected official to seize
power from Ross Perot, dislikes Buchanan's cultural intolerance and
isolationist views. No matter what, Buchanan is stale goods.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, whose whole campaign was based on the assumption
that he could ride anti-abortion fervor to the White House, cheered
Smith on and blustered about party philosophical failings. When the
GOP establishment downplayed the inflammatory abortion issue,
however, Bauer became the dangling participle of Republican
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle is also courting the far right
with similar views, contrasting his lofty government exposure with
Buchanan's and Bauer's more humble experience. But Quayle can't
overcome his image as a national joke or rally the troops either.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes is going his own way as before, echoing most of the
positions of the right-wingers, but he doesn't need their money.
They may support him in the end, but he will never be the puppet
they lust after, and their hearts will not be in it.
</P>
<P>
   It is mostly Bush's phenomenal early lead for the Republican
presidential nomination that has sent the right wing into a panic.
The flood of money and his high poll ratings demonstrate the
party's yearning for a sensible candidate who can win with broad
support, an unmistakable turn away from the zealots who demand
fidelity to far-out positions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush needn't feel as pressured to bow to the right wing as did
his father, who was dependent on the good will of the hard-edged
rightists around Ronald Reagan. This could be the remaking of the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   There will always be a philosophical right wing. But the more it
dwindles into the feeble, irrelevant condition of the left wing,
the better off the country will be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
