<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE SURGES IN WAKE OF TAIWAN'S `ONE CHINA' DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Why would Taiwan risk a military confrontation with
China and test the allegiance of its allies by virtually declaring
independence?
</P>
<P>
   Taipei's bold declaration Monday that it has abandoned the
notion of ``One China'' _ the underpinning of a delicate peace
between China and Taiwan for decades _ is the most dramatic move
yet towards Taiwanese statehood. It comes at an odd time; just
three months before high-level talks with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's startling policy shift enraged China, which stepped up
a barrage of threats Tuesday, saying the move would ``bring
monumental disaster to the people of Taiwan'' and reiterating
Beijing's vow to use force to block independence for the island of
21 million people.
</P>
<P>
   A top Taiwan policymaker, meanwhile, insisted the policy change
was intended to promote improved ties by forcing both sides to
accept the reality of two sovereign governments.
</P>
<P>
   Observers across the volatile Taiwan Straits speculate that
Taipei chose this moment for a number of reasons, ranging from a
desire to win votes to a ploy to tilt the balance in cross-straits
negotiations. It could also exploit faltering US-Chinese ties by
securing protection for Taiwan under the US-Japan security
umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   But the move could backfire. Beijing could repeat menacing
military exercises in the Taiwan Straits that in 1996 forced the
United States to send 16 battleships to defend Taiwan, and nearly
escalated into war. A replay of that scenario would put Washington
in a pickle. On the one hand, the Clinton Administration supports
Beijing as the only China; on the other, the United States is bound
by law to defend Taiwan from attack by Beijing, and Congress is
staunchly pro-Taiwan _ even more so after recent Chinese espionage
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our one-China policy has not changed. The Taiwan Relations
Act,'' which binds Washington to defend Taipei, ``has not changed
either,'' said Susan Stahl, spokeswoman for the American Institute
in Taiwan, the unofficial mission in Taipei. Whether the United
States would send warships again, ``would be decided when and if
that moment happens. The US national interest is peace and
stability in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's gambit could also have the surprise effect of sending
Beijing into America's arms in an effort to ensure US support on
the Taiwan question.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Taiwan President Lee Teng-hui's declaration earned
criticism from several newspapers, but apparent support from the
leading opposition party and the public, the majority of whom
support the status quo _ de facto autonomy. Taiwan resents that
China has isolated it diplomatically, forcing nations to recognize
one or the other. One hundred sixty-five nations _ including the
United States _ recognize only Beijing, while a mere 29 have formal
ties with Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   In constrast, 110 nations recognized both East and West Germany
when the two nations were divided.
</P>
<P>
   The local stock market fell more than 3 percent Tuesday,
apparently on fears that Beijing might take military action.
</P>
<P>
   The current impasse has existed since 1949, when Chinese
communists won a civil war and the losing Nationalist Party fled
the mainland to the island of Taiwan. Both sides declared
themselves the legitimate rulers of China, but by 1979, the United
States and most countries had recognized Beijing, rather than
Taipei. Beijing considers Taiwan part of China. Taiwan's government
also considered China a single nation, though it has always said it
would only rejoin the mainland after China becomes a wealthy
democracy like itself.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan ``is trying to make the whole atmosphere worse rather
than better,'' complained Ding Kuisong, a research professor at the
China Institute of Contemporary International Relations, a
government think tank in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Ding asserted the main reason is domestic politics; Taiwan's
presidential elections are set for next March, and the ruling party
candidate, Vice President Lien Chan, is lagging in the polls.
President Lee may be trying to co-opt the agenda of the leading
opposition party, which favors independence, and win support for
his party by standing firm in the face of Beijing _ a strategy that
won votes during the Taiwan missile crisis in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ding said Lee was also likely trying to force concessions from
Wang Daohan, China's top negotiator for Taiwan, who is due to visit
in October. Ding said he would advise a ``wait and see'' attitude
rather than swift action by Beijing, but cautioned that if Lee
insists on ``state to state'' relations, ``it could be unavoidable
to have some sort of military response.''
</P>
<P>
   Few analysts believe there will be immediate military action,
however, though March elections could present a flashpoint. China
has so far stopped short of threatening to invade, and Beijing
could fudge its vow to do so if Taiwan breaks away by saying Taipei
has not declared independence.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan policymakers insist their underlying position is
unchanged; they still support eventual reunification. But Taipei
has been forced to abandon the fiction of a unified China because
Beijing ``has verbally disparaged and militarily intimidated us,''
said the Mainland Affairs Council, Taiwan's top China policy body.
</P>
<P>
   Lin Chong-PinCQ, vice-chairman of the council, said from Taipei
that the new policy was intended to bolster, not damage
cross-straits relations. ``With equal footing, both sides can talk
about anything. . . . This will make the forthcoming visit of Mr.
Wang more productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the risk that Wang could cancel his trip or Beijing
could attack, Lin replied, ``We hope Beijing will behave sensibly
and responsibly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
