<HEADLINE>
BURTON DREBEN; HARVARD PROFESSOR WAS FACULTY'S `CONSCIENCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Burton Spencer Dreben of Brookline, Mass., a longtime professor
of philosophy at Harvard University who has been described as the
``conscience of the Harvard faculty from the 1960s through the
1980s,'' died of lymphoma Sunday in Massachusetts General Hospital.
He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   During the height of student unrest at Harvard during the 1960s,
Mr. Dreben pressed for open, public debate between faculty and
students about such controversial issues as student draft
deferments and a student strike at the school in 1969. He was dean
of the Harvard Graduate School of Arts and Sciences from 1973 to
1975 and, as chairman of the Society of Fellows at the school,
oversaw the committees that selected candidates for post-doctoral
fellowships at the school from 1976 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   As a special assistant to the dean of faculty, he oversaw the ad
hoc committees used by the president of Harvard to assess the
qualifications of candidates for tenure.
</P>
<P>
   He served as parliamentarian of the Harvard faculty for many
years and was one described in the Harvard Crimson as a `Socratic
gadfly'' for both students and faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Rosovsky, former dean of the Harvard faculty, once
described Mr. Dreben as a ``man of remarkable erudition and
fairness'' who was ``the conscience of the Harvard faculty from the
1960s through the 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   A mathematicial logician who published widely, Mr. Dreben taught
at Harvard from 1956 to 1990 and at Boston University since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Dreben was born in Boston. He graduated from Harvard in 1949
and earned a master's degree at the school in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Juliet Floyd; his former wife, Raya Spiegel
Dreben of Belmont, Mass., and their children, Jon Dreben of
Cambridge, Mass. and Elizabeth Dreben of University Heights, Ohio;
and two grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
