</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-DANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN DANCES FROM MERENGUE TO MAMBO CREATING RHYTHM REVOLUCION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As they dance across the floor, sweat trickles down their
cheeks. It's a summery weekend night at Club Babalu in Dallas, and
it doesn't feel any cooler in here than it does outside. But
Yolanda and Jose Guevara seem oblivious as they merengue, moving
with the precise grace of professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Less-experienced onlookers applaud, then try the moves
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's cool,'' Jose says of the newcomers, with a slight chip
on his shoulder. ``But we've been doing this a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the world, it looks like, is slowly catching up.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to interest drummed up by the recent Ry Cooder movie
Buena Vista Social Club, the crossover successes of Ricky Martin
and Jennifer Lopez, and a burgeoning interest in all things Latin,
Cuban dance music is escalating in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Observe: Local nightclubs are now hosting Latin music nights.
Latin-influenced local bands are finding it's a lot easier to find
gigs. And lessons in Cuban dance, and its many offshoots and
hybrids, are rising in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quickly becoming a big deal,'' says Joe Cripps, Cuban
music guru and a onetime Brave Combo percussionist who cut loose to
play in a Latin-jazz band called Norte de Havana. Throughout July,
the group _ which also features members of several other
Latin-influenced bands _ has a Monday-night gig at Dan's Bar in
Denton north of Dallas-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the No. 1 reason why it hasn't been this popular before is
because of (Cuba's) government,'' Cripps says. ``We just haven't
been able to get the records over here. But now that Cuba is
beginning to open up, we've started importing more and more of its
music. And compared to anything that's on the radio, I think it's
the most exciting thing going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Agustin Guzman, who teaches lessons in mambo and salsa with
partner Marilyn Ramos, says Cuban dance music's growing popularity
boils down to two words: perfect timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, being Latino is sorta cool,'' Guzman says. ``It's OK
to express your Latino-ness.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not only Latinos taking dance lessons and filling the
clubs. Guzman's and Ramos' classes are a mishmash of races and
ages. At a recent class, taught at the Japanese Karate Academy in
Arlington, Texas, an elderly Caucasian couple danced side-by-side
with young, giggly Latino girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of families, too,'' Ramos says. ``No one's
excluded. This is music that crosses boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban dance music is grounded in the roots of Cuban slaves and
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, the dances expressed a lot of working-class and
political issues,'' Guzman says. ``There's a part in the plena
dance where the ladies pick up their dresses and show their slips
as a form of mockery. That was our way of saying we were being
oppressed _ and our way of saying it publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban dance's first taste of popularity came in the late '40s
and '50s via the mambo, a form of salsa that originated in Cuba.
New York _ where many Cubans were finding new homes _ is where the
mambo caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was doing it,'' says Guzman, who grew up in New York
during the dance's heyday. ``It became a mainstream thing, and
eventually it went international.''
</P>
<P>
   The mambo craze influenced musicians to start sound-alike bands.
``Meanwhile,'' Cripps says, ``more and more Puerto Ricans were
moving into New York and adding their own styles to it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Cuban dance music has dramatically evolved,
splintering into several genres and sub-genres, such as cumbia,
ranchera and salsa. Like trying to explain what is truly country or
rock, it becomes increasingly difficult to establish what is
authentic Cuban dance music.
</P>
<P>
   Cripps takes a stab at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, real Cuban dance music is from Cuba or people
playing Cuban style,'' he says. ``What we think of as salsa, which
can have a lot of ingredients, was born out of `son,' a popular
style of Cuban music that's built around a rhythmic bed. And Cuban
music has `clave,' a distinct rhythmic pattern. It gets confusing
because Cuban music has influenced a lot of other Latin music, as
well as African and Mexican music.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dances share a common trait, though: They're
sensual. Especially the guaguanco. ``That's all about seduction,''
Cripps says. ``You see that one once, you won't forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Salsa is one of the most popular forms of Cuban dance. Second
most popular: merengue, which has roots in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merengue is a little bit faster than salsa,'' says Fabio
Gutwaks, who teaches both at El Paraiso Latin Club in Euless, a
suburb of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Latin version of disco,'' he says. ``It has a
lot of twists and turns. Salsa is more emotional. It reaches
people's hearts. But the moves are more difficult. People enjoy
listening to the words of salsa songs, but I think they enjoy
dancing more to merengue.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cuban dance music is the next big thing, it could also wind
up being a fad. Same thing happened to swing music two years ago.
But even if it does catch on with mainstream audiences, then
quickly dies, the music, Cripps says, will remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it does have in common with swing, whether it's a fad or
not, is the music is good and it remains that way,'' he says.
``Whether fashion decides to lock onto something is kinda unrelated
to the strength of the music itself.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
