<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-BARAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADMINISTRATION HAS QUESTIONS ABOUT BARAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak arrives Wednesday
night for a heralded weeklong stay in America that will include
hours of private discussions with President Clinton aimed at
reawakening peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   But even as some see Barak's recent election as part of a
historical opportunity for peace in the Middle East, many inside
the Clinton administration are tempering their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   They see many long-intractable issues remaining in the
Arab-Israeli conflict, with plenty of chances for extremists to try
to derail talks. They also are finding it difficult to penetrate
the aura of mystery that surrounds Israel's new leader.
</P>
<P>
   In his first week in office, Barak met with three Arab leaders,
a signal to the world that peace is his priority. But on the eve of
his visit to Washington, no one in the Clinton administration
claims to know how he intends to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   US diplomats have written long cables with more questions than
answers about the intentions of Barak, Israel's most highly
decorated military officer who entered politics only three years
ago. The diplomats say that Barak will unveil his strategic vision
when he meets with Clinton and no sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kept everyone at arm's length,'' said one State
Department official, speaking on the condition of anonymity. ``He
wants to talk turkey with the president, man to man, head of state
to head of state. His attitude seems to be that everyone else can
just wait.''
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking administration official said that Barak
``cultivates so much mystery that it's been hard to prepare the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to see Barak an extraordinary four times,
starting with a 2 1/2-hour private meeting Thursday and then
continuing with a dinner at the White House with a table set for
four: Clinton, first lady Hillary Rodman Clinton, Barak, and his
wife, Nava.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Barak also meet on Monday, and then the White House
hosts a state dinner that night with an extensive guest list. In
addition, Barak meets twice with Vice President Al Gore, twice with
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, and once with Defense
Secretary William S. Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the trip is intended first and
foremost as a chance to probe Barak's vision and, they hope, as a
clarification of the US role in future negotiations with Syria and
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spent nearly 80 hours last fall in negotiations at
the Wye Plantation in Maryland that led to an interim
peace-for-security arrangement between Israel and the Palestinians,
will want to get into the ``nitty-gritty'' of Barak's plans, said
the high-ranking official.
</P>
<P>
   The president and his Mideast experts want to know how Barak
envisions a peace deal with Syria and the Palestinians and his
thoughts about how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, administration officials hope to re-energize
multilateral activities on arms control, water, the environment,
refugees, and economic cooperation in the Mideast. Specifically,
the administration wants to restart the annual Middle East economic
summit, canceled the past two years because of tense Israeli-Arab
relations.
</P>
<P>
   American mediators ``are looking for a balance between
overmanaging and under-involvement in the peace process,'' said
Tara Sonenshine, a senior adviser at the United States Institute of
Peace in Washington and a former top aide to National Security
Adviser Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's only public declaration of his intentions toward peace
was a campaign pledge to pull Israeli troops out of southern
Lebanon within a year. He has given indications to Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat, to Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, to
Jordan's King Abdullah, and to reporters that he would probably
fulfill the next step in the Wye accords but then wants to move to
what is called the final-status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Those negotiations include the tough issues of the future of
Jerusalem, water rights, the return of 3 million Palestinian
refugees, and Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak is committed to Wye, but he believes that Wye was in
many ways a Band-Aid,'' an Israeli government official, speaking on
the condition of anonymity, said in Washington Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Before Barak could pull troops from Lebanon, he needs to
stabilize his relationship with his northern neighbors of Lebanon
and Syria. Talks with Syria broke off in 1996 when Syria refused to
condemn a series of terrorist attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Syrian President Hafez Assad is strongly indicating he
wants the talks to resume. Barak needs American liaisons to restart
those talks. Albright is expected to travel to Damascus early next
month in hopes of reopening that track.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say there has not been a moment of such hope for Middle
East peace since the Oslo peace process was signed on the White
House lawn in September 1993. Every political leader in place has
strong reasons to secure a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But US diplomats still caution that it will probably not happen
fast, and it might happen in pieces. There is some concern about
what the Israeli public can accept.
</P>
<P>
   The occupied territories comprise one-third of the land Israel
controls. If Barak gives back a substantial part of that, ``can
they do all that in one year?'' asked the State Department
official. ``I doubt it. Barak has got to be careful about what
Israelis will accept all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe researcher Wanda Joseph-Rollins contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8744 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ENVIRON-ART-2N     07-13 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ENVIRON-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PANCEVO: into consideration.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``When targeting is done we take into account all possible
collateral damage,'' she said, ``be it environmental, human or to
the civilian infrastructure. Pancevo was considered to me a very,
very important refinery and strategic target, as important as
tactical targets inside Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, anxious families are coping with illnesses
no one seems able to explain. Mothers, clutching the hands of small
children, along with people whose bodies are covered in rashes,
clog the small waiting rooms of local doctors hoping for
explanations and treatment. There is little, the doctors say, they
can do, but wait to see if the exposure leads to cancer, blood
contamination and serious respiratory ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical exposure can produce immediate and longer-term effects,
causing different kinds of damage to the body, experts say. Some
may be clear to the eye and painful; other effects could be silent
and only show up years later. It is difficult to pinpoint the cause
of the symptoms people in Pancevo report without scientific tests.
Neither Polic, nor UNEP officials, said they were ready to
speculate on the possible health risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can we tell people?'' said Dr. Dobrosav Pavlovic, a
gynecologist. ``We have not advised expectant mothers to have
abortions, but we are seeing more and more miscarriages. I can't
say how much the bombing has contributed to this increase. I can't
say what the results of the bombing will be over the long term. It
will be over a year, when we can begin to look for birth defects
and can detect serious illnesses, that we will start to understand
what has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The bombing left most of the 8,761 people who worked in the
plants, 10 miles northwest of Belgrade, out of work. The
government, which was months late with salaries before the bombing,
has reduced incomes from $100 to $15 a month until the factories
are repaired, something workers say will never happen without
foreign investment. The damage is estimated in the hundreds of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Three U.S. companies and a German firm built the petrochemical
plant, used to make plastics, in 1978. Two U.S. corporations and a
French concern constructed the oil refinery in 1969. The fertilizer
plant, which began operation in 1958, was a joint venture by
companies from the United States, Spain and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of income in the town has made it difficult for those
whom would like to move or take precautions against the pollutants.
There is now 70 percent unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son and I have constant headaches,'' said Radmila Vukelic,
52.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel dizzy, as if we were going to faint. No one has told
us anything. We have no information about what has happened or what
we should do. I do not eat the fish from the river. I am afraid. We
would like to eat frozen or canned vegetables, but we do not have
this kind of money. We must eat what is in the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Pancevo Mayor Srdjan Mikovic, 38, said he is bewildered by the
extent of the airstrikes, especially since his town of 130,000,
with a mix of ethnic Hungarians and ethnic Croats, has long been
one of the centers of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the few places in Serbia where the radio and
television stations are free from party control, either by
Milosevic's ruling Socialists, or the parties that oppose him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard nothing from the government,'' the mayor said.
``We have never supported the regime and for this reason I fear we
will be sacrificed. NATO had to understand what they were doing to
us because these factories were built by American and European
firms. They could not have been ignorant of the environmental
damage. I have given up. I eat the fish. How much more can I be
poisoned after living in clouds of this stuff?''
</P>
<P>
   Pancevo was once a frontier town, manned by Hungarian, Serbian
and Austrian soldiers in the Austro-Hungarian empire. The pink
facade of the former imperial army barracks lies in the center of
Pancevo. It was from here that the European troops faced the
Ottoman Turks across the river from 1716, when Vienna captured
Pancevo, until the end of World War I. The buildings, although in
bad repair, look as if they were lifted from Austria, with stuccoed
block exteriors, onion domed towers, arched windows and delicate,
wrought iron staircases.
</P>
<P>
   On the front of the old town hall, built by German-speaking
settlers in 1833 and now a museum, is a Latin inscription reading:
``Justice is the Basis for Any State.'' Outside is a thick iron
cylinder with a hollowed bore in the center. It was once lit with
an explosive charge to announce the arrival of riverboats. The
ethnic Germans, who left behind their churches, tombstones and
architecture, were driven out at the end of World War II after the
communist state was established in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But this part of Serbia has never embraced Milosevic's
nationalist movement.
</P>
<P>
   Pancevo hosted a woman's water polo tournament last year, and
the American swimmers won. The spectators cheered the athletes as
the American anthem was played during the awards ceremony. ``The
bombing has changed how we feel about the outside world,'' said
Mikovic. ``People have lost their desire to fight, to reach out.
They only want to survive. The Americans can come back, but they
will not have any applause from us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
