<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8746 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-AMBROSE-SAINTS-CO     07-13 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AMBROSE-SAINTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ambrose to return to Saints
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, OHIO _ Ashley Ambrose's three-year reign as the Bengals
starting left cornerback ended Tuesday when he agreed to go back
home and play for the New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Reached via telephone at his offseason residence in Houston,
Ambrose told the Dayton Daily News he was taking a 5 p.m. flight to
New Orleans and signing a two-year contract that will be worth $7
million if certain individual and team incentives are reached.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose, who spurned Cincinnati's $2.1 million offer for 1999,
said he tried to call Bengals officials earlier in the day, but
failed. The team's telephone system at Spinney Field remained
disabled from a lightning strike Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to call and just tell them: Thanks for the
opportunity,'' Ambrose said. ``I'm sorry it had to end like this. I
was hoping we could come to an agrement on something.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to the point where I'm taking a little less money during
the year, but I can go beyond what I was going to make in
Cincinnati because I will have a lot of opportunity off the field,
which will really benefit me. That's what I'm looking at _ and the
opportunity to play in front of my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose, who graduated from Alcee Fortier High School in New
Orleans and earned a bachelor's degree in industrial technology
from Mississippi Valley State University, gets a $1 million signing
bonus and $700,000 base salary. A series of incentives worth
$800,000 have also been written into the deal.
</P>
<P>
   He said agent Kennard McGuire and Saints general manager Bill
Kuharich have agreed to work on a contract extension at midseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their whole thing was getting a chance in the middle of the
year to sign me to an extension,'' Ambrose said. ``Basically, I
told them it's going to be tough for me in the beginning because
they've got guys out there who know what they're doing and I have
to go in and learn everything. But I don't think they'll be
disappointed. I plan on going out and having a great year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose, who is entering his eighth NFL season, earned Pro Bowl
honors his first year with the Bengals in 1996 when he recorded
eight interceptions. He had three INTs in 1997 and two in '98.
</P>
<P>
   He spent his first four seasons with the Indianapolis Colts, who
picked him in the second round (29th overall) of the 1992 NFL
draft.
</P>
<P>
   As an unrestricted free agent, Ambrose faced a 4 p.m. Thursday
deadline of signing with another club or having Cincinnati retain
negotiating rights to him. His departure solidifies Corey Sawyer as
the Bengals' starting left corner with rookie second-round pick
Charles Fisher as the backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing to do was just wait it out and see,'' Ambrose
said. ``Atlanta called back, but I just decided to go home. (Saints
owner) Tom Benson is happy I'm coming because he knows I'm from New
Orleans. Everybody is just ready for me to come home.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose plans to keep his house in Houston, but will take his
wife, Monica, and their eight-month-old daughter, Aisha, to New
Orleans, where they'll join his parents, aunts and uncles.
</P>
<P>
   He's eager to play with rookie tailback Ricky Williams, the
Heisman Trophy winner from Texas, and for fiery head coach Mike
Ditka. He'll compete with Tyronne Drakeford and Alex Molden for a
starting cornerback job.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just want somebody to come in and be competitive,'' he
said. ``That's what I'm going to present. I feel I've got a good
five years left in me. Why pass up the opportunity when you get a
chance to play at home?''
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
