<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8747 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-STUDENTS-BOS &LR;      07-13 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-STUDENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT UNREST IN IRAN SEEN AS HAVING LONG EFFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The long-simmering fight for greater freedom in
Iran has burst into the open in the now-daily clashes on Tehran's
streets.
</P>
<P>
   As Iranian students battled with security forces and the
black-clad Hezbollahi vigilantes for the sixth day Tuesday, and
with another face-off expected Wednesday morning, Western analysts
and Middle East diplomats believe the outcome could shape the
Islamic Republic for years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things calm down, we can presume the moderates will come
out stronger,'' said a Washington-based diplomat from a Middle
Eastern country. ``But if it keeps going, there will be either a
conservative backlash or the regime will be shaken very seriously.
There are a lot of open questions.''
</P>
<P>
   While no one is predicting the fall of the Islamic Republic, the
battles could have a major impact on Iran's relationship with the
West. If the moderates gain strength, ties with the West could
accelerate. But if Islamic revolutionaries sharply put down the
unrest, such relationships could be frozen.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting began on Thursday with the latest closing of a
newspaper, the left-leaning Salam, which means peace, spawning
student protests and security crackdowns. That night, security
forces stormed dormitories at Tehran University and threw students
out of second- and third-story windows. Iranian media report five
to eight students died, sparking the street battles that show no
sign yet of abating.
</P>
<P>
   Since the surprise landslide election two years ago of moderate
President Mohammed Khatami, young people in Iran have steadily
tested the controls on freedom of expression imposed by the strict
Islamic revolutionaries, who came to power in 1979 with the
overthrow of the US-backed shah _ before many of the students were
born.
</P>
<P>
   In Iran's system of governance, which has three centers of
power, Khatami controls the weakest branch and has not shown the
ability or perhaps the inclination to open Iran's society to
Western-style democracy or market economies. With each successive
crackdown on freedom, the students have protested with more
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing had come close to the clashes of the last week, and
now Iran-watchers are having difficulty predicting where it's
headed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials, who have carefully attempted
to re-establish dialogue with Khatami with no great success beyond
cultural exchanges, reacted Tuesday with extreme caution to the
clashes. Government spokesmen sent e-mail messages to their
departments telling officials to stay quiet for now.
</P>
<P>
   From the State Department podium, spokesman James P. Rubin said:
``Clearly, these are significant demonstrations that represent the
desire for political change on the part of the younger generation
seeking the rule of law and freedom of expression, and that is
significant and serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin reiterated the administration's concern for the students'
safety and of the use of violence ``to put down demonstrations by
Iranians students in support of freedom of expression and
democratic values.''
</P>
<P>
   A diplomatic cable from an Iran expert in a Middle Eastern
country, which was read to the Globe, showed the uncertainties of
what lies ahead:
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things are going in the power struggle between the
moderates and extremists, it appears the important power centers
are in the hands of the extremists, not the reformers. The Security
Services and the Ministry of Interior are leading this crackdown.
Khatami himself is trying to keep a low profile and not lead a
radical change.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable continues: Khatami ``wants to make sure that things
don't get out of hand, but the students are saying maybe he is not
relevent. The students are not taking orders from him. There is a
fear that things could get out of control, and there's a part of
the students who want to overthrow the whole Islamic regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Metrinko, one the US hostages held for 444 days at the
US Embassy in Tehran two decades ago and now retired from the State
Department, said Tuesday the student protesters have nothing
invested in the Islamic revolution and want to know how the
government can now improve their lives.
</P>
<P>
   With some figures putting unemployment in Iran at 25 percent,
``the government is no longer meeting their needs. They are holding
out very little for their futures. These students are intelligent,
they are capable, educated, competent, they have energy. And there
is nowhere for them to go, and so they are demanding answers,''
said Metrinko, who keeps in touch with many Iranians via e-mail
messages and chat groups.
</P>
<P>
   Metrinko said he didn't believe the students were turning
against Khatami, ``but they are realizing he is not going to be as
effective as they would have liked. The honeymoon has gotten stale.
And Iranians, like everyone else, lose patience after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   William R. Royce, former head of the Voice of America-Farsi
service and a longtime Iran watcher, said Iran's young ``don't want
to be cut off from the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Royce, speaking as a private citizen and not on behalf of the US
government, compared the recent protests to the rallies against the
shah in the summer and fall of 1978. ``The difference was that the
shah was willing to go.'' Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, ``has no place to go. He's got to fight to the bitter
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's protests came despite a ban on all rallies and marches
by the government and calls by Khatami and Khamenei for calm.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Khamenei delivered a highly charged speech condemning
the dormitory attack, saying the ``bitter incident has broken my
heart.'' He blamed ``enemies,'' including the United States and
Israel, for the deaths. A crowd of several thousand responded by
chanting, ``Death to America.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said the charges that
America and Israel fomented the attacks were ``utter nonsense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
