<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8749 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGA-MINORITIES-COX     07-13 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-MINORITIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA will study admission changes
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ University of Georgia officials said Tuesday they
will assemble a team of experts to determine what changes, if any,
will be made in admissions standards for high school students
applying for the freshman Class of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge B. Avant Edenfield of Savannah has said that
UGA's admissions policies _ which consider race along with
geography, extracurricular activities and other factors in
evaluating about 15 percent of applicants _ represent reverse
discrimination and stigmatize minority students.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the judge's comments, the lawyer who represents the
students who challenged the policies said the Board of Regents and
UGA administrators could be held personally liable for monetary
damages in subsequent reverse discrimination lawsuits. Atlanta
lawyer Lee Parks urged the Regents and UGA to change their
admissions policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the implications of the opinion have to be factored into
the development of the admissions criteria for the class of 2000,''
said UGA Communications Director Tom Jackson. ``The team helping
with those criteria include lawyers on this campus and in the
attorney general's office, the chancellor and the Board of Regents,
President (Michael F.) Adams and his top administrators and the
faculty admissions committee. They all will have input.''
</P>
<P>
   With a minority population of 13 percent and a black population
of 6 percent, the state's flagship institution lags behind other
schools in the University System for diversity _ but not for lack
of effort. Admissions officials identify every African-American
student with high standardized test scores and good grades ``from
Texas to Maryland,'' Jackson said, and bombard them with
information about the university.
</P>
<P>
   UGA participates in recruitment fairs, works through black
churches, visits high schools and telephones prospects, ``but it's
not a big pool of people to work with,'' Jackson said. ``There are
only about 700 black public high school students in Georgia who
meet our academic standards, and they're in great demand across the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The university stumbles in getting African-American students who
are accepted to enroll, Jackson admitted. ``We're having trouble
with show rates. What do we need to get the black applicant to
enroll here rather than somewhere else?''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Dawn Bennett-Alexander, who teaches employment law in
the Terry College of Business, acknowledged that UGA has an
aggressive recruitment program. ``But I don't know how much is done
to make sure students are comfortable, that they can stay once they
come here, and that attention is paid to them,'' Bennett-Alexander
said.
</P>
<P>
   While white students socialize and relax in downtown Athens,
there are no clubs in town that cater to black clientele. Many
black students withdraw or transfer from UGA, or never come in the
first place, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be useful to do exit interviews with people to see
why they're leaving,'' Bennett-Alexander said. ``And to talk to
black students about what they want. . . . I don't think the
intricacies of the situation have been explored.''
</P>
<P>
   Renita Ward, a UGA graduate who'll start on her master's next
month, said that after the first year of college, ``I had no
intention of staying, because it wasn't a welcoming community. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   But ``I found professors who helped me do what I could do and
should do,'' she said. ``People who come here from Atlanta look
around a class, and out of 300, they're the only black person. A
lot of people get discouraged and feel outnumbered because they
don't have a community base.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca McCarthy writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
