<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8750 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-HOUSE-BOS &LR;      07-13 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AIDES DENY CANDIDATE KNEW OF `WHITES ONLY' COVENANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Governor George W. Bush purchased a house in
1988 that had a restrictive covenant saying the property was for
``white persons only,'' according to real estate records. But
Bush's presidential campaign spokesman said Tuesday that such
restrictions had already been declared invalid and Bush was never
told about the covenant.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of racial restrictions on land purchases has come up
regularly in political campaigns, but the matter usually does not
become a focal point unless the purchaser knew about a restriction.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Mindy Tucker said the governor was not
aware of the restriction, and she stressed the covenant written in
1939 was not valid at the time of Bush's purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no deed restriction because it is null and void under
Texas law and has been since 1984,'' Tucker said. ``No individual
can remove it.''
</P>
<P>
   The land records were made available Tuesday to selected news
organizations by a source who insisted upon anonymity but who has
connections to a political opponent of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   According to the documents, Bush, whose father had just been
elected president, purchased the Dallas house on Nov. 15, 1988, for
$320,000. The deed, like those for many houses in the neighborhood,
included a restriction stating: ``Said premises shall be used for
private dwelling purposes only and by white persons only, not
excluding bona fide servants of any race.''
</P>
<P>
   Broker Steve Collins told the Associated Press that the language
was not included in the deed that Bush received when he bought the
house, but it was in the platting documents that most homeowners
never see. Bush sold the house in 1995, shortly after he was
elected governor.
</P>
<P>
   If it turned out that Bush knew about such a blatantly racist
restriction, it could be damaging to his presidential campaign. As
a result, the Bush campaign Tuesday went to lengths to try to
prevent publication of the matter, asserting it was not a story
since Bush did not know about the restriction.
</P>
<P>
   The documents originally were reported Monday night on the
on-line Drudge Report and also were described Tuesday on CNN's
``Inside Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The documents emerged amid efforts by a variety of Bush's
political opponents to uncover damaging information about the
Republican front-runner. Bush, who has called for an emphasis on
morality, has said he was once ``young and irresponsible,'' but he
has declined to be specific aside from describing a time when he
was a heavy drinker. Bush also has faced questions about whether he
avoided combat by joining the Texas Air National Guard, but he has
denied receiving preferential treatment in becoming a pilot at the
unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
