<HEADER>
A8752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALESTAX-COX     07-13 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALESTAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Linder urges sales, not income, tax
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.) hates the federal income
tax code with a passion. Today, he intends to try to do something
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Linder will introduce a bill to abolish the income tax, along
with capital gains, estate and payroll taxes. In their place, he is
proposing a 23 percent national retail sales tax, which Linder says
would amount to a tax break for most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're only going to pay tax on what you spend, and you're not
going to pay tax on what you don't spend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The single rate would apply to everyone, regardless of income.
But poorer Americans would be protected through a rebate on taxes
paid on buying necessities, Linder said.
</P>
<P>
   All deductions, including those for home mortgage interest and
charitable contributions, also would disappear.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is likely to have powerful opponents, including what
Linder called the majority of Washington lobbyists whose work
concerns provisions in the tax code. He said it is unlikely that
the bill will come to a vote before next year.
</P>
<P>
   Linder and co-sponsor Rep. Collin Peterson (D-Minn.) drew much
of their plan from Americans for Fair Taxation, a Texas-based
nonpartisan group that has bought newspaper and television ads in
support of the sales tax strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of replacing the income tax with a sales or flat tax
has circulated among Republicans for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidate Steve Forbes used his flat tax proposal
to catapult him to national prominence four years ago. He is
pushing a flat tax again in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Linder's bill also has competition from other lawmakers who have
introduced similar measures, including one that would impose a 15
percent sales tax and would retain a payroll tax, also about 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Linder called his proposal a model of fairness and consistency,
because it would treat all purchases the same, and he said it would
produce the same amount of revenue as the current tax system.
</P>
<P>
   But a critic of the sales tax said its proponents are ``cooking
the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first place, the claim of a 23 percent rate ``just
doesn't come close to adding up,'' said Robert McIntyre, director
of the nonpartisan Citizens for Tax Justice in Washington. McIntyre
said he used Americans for Fair Taxation's own figures _ $1.36
trillion in federal taxes divided by $4.6 trillion in taxable
spending, based on 1995 numbers _ to determine that it would take a
30 percent tax rate to make the change in revenue neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Another weakness, he said, is that the plan would depend on the
federal government taxing its own purchases, which McIntyre said is
akin to taking from one hand and giving to the other.
</P>
<P>
   Linder acknowledged that government purchases would be taxed,
but he said the government would pay so much less in payroll taxes
on government personnel that there would be ample money to pay the
sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that, under his proposal, people who have saved
instead of spent money already taxed under the current system would
still have to pay the sales tax when they spent it. ``Those,
unfortunately, are the people who would be hurt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
