<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLST-DUQUETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUQUETTE BASKS IN ALL-STAR GLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The drama of Roger Clemens and Mo Vaughn returning to
Fenway Park for an All-Star Game probably would have been worth a
$2,000 scalped ticket, especially to watch an encounter between Dan
Duquette and two stars who bashed the general manager on their way
out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, however, was selected to Joe Torre's American League
team, ruining any chance for a dirty look, a blank stare, an
awkward moment, or angry words.
</P>
<P>
   It also ruined any chance for Red Sox fans to see two of the
greatest players to ever wear a Red Sox uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Given the opportunity to possibly gloat about his former stars
not being good enough in '99 to be named to the team, while the
three players he's brought into the organization were named
All-Stars, Duquette elected to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he was busy bringing his son Daniel down to the field to
shag during the Home Run Derby, and electing to dwell on his
shortstop, Nomar Garciaparra, playing in the game, even though he's
missed the last nine games with a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke while walking from his suite on the fifth floor to the
field, where several fans passed him. The common message was
``Great job, Dan'' for the once-maligned GM who has earned the
respect of most Red Sox fans, given the team's performance last
year and especially this season, without Vaughn's big bat in the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans here are very supportive,'' said Duquette. ``You hear
comments like that all the time. People are appreciative of what
we've tried to accomplish here and the great job our players,
manager, and coaches have done to put the kind of team on the field
we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette feels there will be enough reason for Red Sox fans to
cheer with Pedro Martinez and Garciaparra starting and Jose
Offerman selected as a reserve, despite his tumbling numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy we have three reps on the team,'' said Duquette.
``I like what Joe Torre did giving the edge to Offerman on the
ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to allow Garciaparra to play despite missing time
at his real job has been questioned. The feeling is Duquette wanted
Garciaparra, a marquee player, to play in a game in Boston, while
others in the organization questioned it privately because he
wasn't ready to help the Red Sox, who have lost five of their last
six.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's feeling well enough to get out there and perform,'' said
Duquette. ``As the days go by he feels better and he should be
ready to go. He hopes to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he didn't think there would be any restrictions on
Garciaparra, but definitely thought it was up to the player to tell
Torre if he needed out. Of course, Torre would like his own player,
Derek Jeter, to get significant time.
</P>
<P>
   All three All-Stars became Red Sox players either through
Duquette's trades or through the farm system. Garciaparra was
Duquette's first No. 1 pick in the draft after taking over for Lou
Gorman prior to the 1994 season. Martinez was acquired in a major
deal with the Expos a year after Clemens signed with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette was able to trade the depth he had built at the minor
league level (Carl Pavano, Ryan McGuire, and Tony Armas Jr.) in
exchange for Martinez. He then wasted little time in signing
Martinez to a six-year, $75 million deal. After losing Vaughn in a
bitter contract squabble, Duquette signed Offerman to a four-year,
$26 million deal, far more than any other team was willing to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clemens and Vaughn, Duquette will say little about either
player. He did mention Vaughn not making it because, ``It would
have been difficult to take him based on the fact he's missed time
because of injuries. The injuries have really held him back.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette lauded the efforts of the Red Sox and Major League
Baseball in bringing together great stars of the past and former
Red Sox players such as Ted Williams, who threw out the first ball.
Carlton Fisk also made an appearance Monday, and there have been
many others around the FanFest events over the weekend, though one
ex-Red Sox who was not involved was eight-time All-Star Frank
Malzone, a scout for the team who was nowhere to be found. Also
conspicuous by his absence was former Red Sox general manager Lou
Gorman, who still works for the team as an assistant to Sox CEO
John Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   So many have come and gone since Duquette took the reigns, but
his successes were on the field in an All-Star Game at Fenway,
while his failures watched on TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
