<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8756 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVSERIES-MINORITIES14     07-13 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSERIES-MINORITIES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As blacks gravitate toward `niche' channels, big networks grow
more white
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the NAACP on Monday decried the lack of minorities on
upcoming network TV shows, it only pointed out what's been obvious
to many minority viewers for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I notice it to the point where I don't notice it anymore, it's
so expected,'' says Jimmy Stroud, 32, an African-American Web page
designer from Atlanta, of the major networks' shortage of prominent
minority characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problem has been the omission of realistic situations
within the black community _ all we get is stereotypical slapstick
comedy-type programs and nothing of substance,'' adds Reggie
Mitchell, director of broadcast training at Clark Atlanta
University. ``If you came down from Mars and only got your
information about black people from TV, we'd look like idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 26 shows premiering this fall on ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox,
none features an African-American, Latino or Asian-American in a
starring or prominent role, said Kweisi Mfume, president of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, at the
civil rights organization's 90th annual convention in New York.
Mfume called the situation a ``virtual whitewash in network
programming.''
</P>
<P>
   While the networks quibbled with the numbers _ ABC, for
instance, noted that David E. Kelley's latest, ``Snoops,'' features
minority actresses Paula Jai Parker and Majandra Delfino as part of
its ensemble cast _ they didn't duck Mfume's basic point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all agree that those of us in the entertainment
industry need to make sure the characters on our screen reflect the
diversity of the population as a whole,'' said Leslie Moonves,
president of CBS Television.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers point to the expanding TV universe to explain the
dwindling number of prominent minority characters on ABC, CBS, NBC
and Fox. Minority-oriented programming has increasingly been driven
toward niche networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a few small services, like UPN, the WB and BET,
trying to cater to urban black audiences,'' says TV historian Alex
McNeil. ``I don't know if it's cause or effect, but therefore you
also seem to have more shows (on the networks) that have all-white
casts, like `Friends.'''
</P>
<P>
   One result has been the fragmenting of TV audiences along racial
lines. Only six of last season's shows ranked in the Top 20 among
both black households and total households _ the highest number of
crossovers since the 1990-91 season. The top-rated show in black
households, ``The Steve Harvey Show,'' ranked No. 154 in white
households.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too hard to figure out,'' said Doug Alligood, senior
vice president for special markets at BBDO, a New York ad agency
that annually breaks down viewing habits between blacks and whites.
``If you put yourself overseas in a foreign country, say you're
looking at French TV, and you turn it on and there's a show set in
New York City, you're going to watch it. You're not going to
analyze the quality of it, you're going to be so glad to see it.
That's where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Kisha Dennis, 25, a producer for the communications
department of the city of Atlanta, says, ``The reason I watch `Ally
McBeal' is there's a sister (Lisa Nicole Carson) on that. When I
see a familiar face, one that looks like me, has mannerisms like
me, someone I have a lot in common with, I'm drawn toward that.''
</P>
<P>
   McNeil refers to the 1974-75 network season as the ``high-water
mark'' in the popularity of race-conscious shows: ``Sanford and
Son'' (No. 2), ``Chico and the Man'' (3), ``The Jeffersons'' (4)
and ``Good Times'' (8) were all monority-based programs that
finished in the Neilsen Top 10. And in the year's top-rated show,
``All in the Family,'' race was a prominent theme.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, last season's Top 5 entertainment shows _ ``ER,''
``Friends,'' ``Frasier,'' ``Veronica's Closet'' and ``Jesse'' _
were principally white-cast shows with a sprinkling of prominent
minority characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious there is a downturn in black representation in
prime time,'' says Alligood. ``What is not obvious is why. Is it an
oversight? Somebody's decision there's not enough talent? I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Fontana, producer of such critically acclaimed and racially
diverse shows as NBC's ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' and HBO's
``Oz,'' says the networks' current lemming-like embrace of young,
white audiences is mostly a commercial decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the guilt lies more in the networks grabbing for a
very specific audience next season _ the teenaged white audience _
than in creative people saying, `I'm going to be exclusive and not
write for other ethnic groups,''' Fontana says. ``The demand from
the networks is give us white high school students, and people give
them what they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arbitrary nature of what they're looking for changes from
season to season,'' Fontana adds. ``This season they've all decided
they're going for the teen audience. Next year, everybody might
want Latino characters. It's the nature of selling: who's buying
and who they're trying to sell to determines the color of faces on
TV.''
</P>
<P>
   That situation is no comfort to minority viewers, who until the
mid-1960s were virtually excluded from TV programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's why the (black) community feels panicky and frustrated,''
says Alligood. ``It was enjoying the direction things were going
in, and then all of a sudden it was gone and people are asking,
`Are you ignoring us again? Are we going back to the days when we
didn't exist other than as maids and butlers?'
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is not to go back. It's to go forward creatively.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
