<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8758 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-MANAGEMENT-BOS &LR;      07-13 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-MANAGEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITY WOMEN SAY THEY'VE HIT BARRIER TO CORPORATE ADVANCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minority women who have achieved management jobs in US
corporations paint a picture of extreme isolation in their jobs and
say they often hit a ``concrete ceiling'' in which there is no
clear path to advancement, according to an in-depth study by a New
York research organization.
</P>
<P>
   Catalyst, which specializes in issues facing women in the
workplace, said that almost half of the 1,735 minority female
executives surveyed say they lack a formal relationship with a
mentor and 40 percent report they do not have even the informal
network that may be helpful to advancing within their companies.
</P>
<P>
   These black, Hispanic, and Asian-American women also said that
even though their employers are strongly committed to recruiting
minority women through diversity programs, they often are
ineffective in helping them with further career development once
they are in the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mentor gives you the politics of an organization, the
culture of an organization, clues you into what's going on, helps
you avoid pitfalls, pushes your career forward,'' said Sheila
Wellington, Catalyst's president.
</P>
<P>
   Because many minority women often lack mentors of a network of
supporters, they ``frequently feel at sea'' in their jobs,
Wellington said.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the findings were not surprising, the report is
among the most comprehensive looks at the specific issues facing
minority women as their numbers in the work force are on the rise
in a trend that is expected to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Catalyst sent surveys to more than 6,500 minority women in
management positions who were within seven reporting levels of the
chief executive; the 1,735 respondents resulted in a 27 percent
response rate, which is considered adequate for a reliable survey.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year study by Catalyst also involved 59 focus groups
with minority women executives and research conducted inside 15
companies, most of them in the Fortune 1,000 list of firms,
Catalyst said.
</P>
<P>
   Catalyst said minority women must remain in a job 3.6 years on
average _ a year more than white women _ before winning promotions.
Also, minority women are often in lower levels of management, which
helps explain their inability to get past the ``concrete ceiling''
through experience gained as they move up the corporate ladder, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Freada Klein, a Cambridge, Mass. diversity consultant whose
clients include Fortune 1,000 companies, said Catalyst's report
reinforces her own findings. In particular, she noted that women of
color face the double-barreled problems of race and gender and
often feel ``ostracized by all groups,'' including white women.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a comfort level by the senior people with the
junior people for them to be willing to mentor them, invest the
time and resources,'' Klein said. ``If the company is run by
Caucasian men, then it's one big step to let in either men of color
or Caucasian women. It may be perceived as two steps to let in
women of color.''
</P>
<P>
   Minority women who responded to Catalyst's survey said the
support from their supervisors varied. Asian-American women said
female managers are more receptive to helping them with problems,
while black women said their minority supervisors were more
receptive than white managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a myth that being a woman of color is a double plus,''
Wellington said. ``In fact, when you analyze the data and look at
the survey, women of color report that it's a double minus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
