<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8769 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-SUIT-COX     07-13 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key issue in Coca-Cola suit airs Thursday
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The gloves come off Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That's when lawyers for Coca-Cola and the four plaintiffs suing
the company for alleged racial discrimination will argue over a key
part of the case _ whether to eliminate the chance of it ever
becoming a class action.
</P>
<P>
   If U.S. District Judge Richard Story eventually grants
class-action status, the plaintiffs could potentially represent
about 1,500 black, salaried Coke employees in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Coca-Cola has asked the judge to throw out the class-action
discrimination claims now. The company argues there are too many
individual facts and circumstances among existing and prospective
plaintiffs for the case to be handled as one lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs, however, vigorously disagree, saying the common
issues about racial discrimination outweigh any individual
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Story has said he will either rule at the hearing Thursday or a
day or two afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's dismissal motion comes early in this legal contest
since the information gathering period, called ``discovery,'' has
just begun. The class-action suit was filed April 22.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the company loses in its dismissal motion now, the
plaintiffs must still convince the judge at a later date that the
suit should be granted class-action status. That will not be an
easy hurdle for the plaintiffs to overcome, but it would occur
after months of information gathering that has not yet taken place.
</P>
<P>
   The company just recently handed over about 15,000 documents
plus a computerized employment database to the plaintiffs, who must
analyze the information before trying to gain class-action status.
</P>
<P>
   But if the class-action claims in the lawsuit are thrown out
this week, the case would be confined to just the four plaintiffs.
They allege a companywide practice of discrimination against
African-American employees in pay, promotions and performance
evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola denies the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs are seeking monetary damages and a court order
forbidding further alleged discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   To buttress their arguments, each side has submitted two legal
briefs to the judge. Essentially, the company argues that ``every
named plaintiff and every prospective class member has different
claims and different facts.'' As a result, the
information-gathering process will only reinforce the need for a
series of mini-trials for each prospective class member.
</P>
<P>
   But the whole point of a class-action suit is to avoid 1,500
mini-trials and consolidate the issues in one trial. Since that
will be impossible, the company argues, the class-action claims
should be dismissed. The four plaintiffs could still proceed with
their individual cases against the company.
</P>
<P>
   The company also argues that despite the ``broad brush strokes
and general references to discriminatory practices, the named
plaintiffs' and prospective class members' claims have no
commonality, other than the race of their proponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, say the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is the company wrong about the law, but even if the
company's position had any arguable merit, this case is in far too
preliminary a stage for the court to take any action ... without
committing clear reversible error,'' the plaintiffs argued.
</P>
<P>
   They go on to say that dismissing the class-action claims would
be both premature and inefficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, without knowing the facts of the case and the universe
of the issues that plaintiffs will ultimately seek to try in a
class action, the court cannot make a reasoned determination,''
they argued.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, they said, if the court were to dismiss claims
before any factual record was developed through the discovery
process, and that decision was reversed on appeal, then the case
would likely have to be retried.
</P>
<P>
   But if the court makes a decision on the class-action matter
after the information gathering process is completed, then an
appeal ``is far less likely to result in reversal.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides also disagree about whether the plaintiffs in a
class-action suit can simultaneously ask for substantial monetary
damages and for a court order requiring Coca-Cola to change its
employment practices.
</P>
<P>
   The company argues that in a class-action case the plaintiffs
can't seek both remedies at the same time. As a result, the company
said the judge should also dismiss the class-action portion of the
suit on that ground.
</P>
<P>
   But the plaintiffs say they can seek both remedies.
</P>
<P>
   The four plaintiffs in the case are administrative assistant
Motisola Malikha Abdallah, security officer Gregory Allen Clark,
information specialist Linda Ingram and former director Kimberly
Gray Orton.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
