A8779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBERTSHAW-HALL-COX     07-13 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERTSHAW-HALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Foundation offers millions for new hall, wants Shaw's name on it
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta and Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Arthur M. Blank Family Foundation will give as
much as $15 million for a new Atlanta Symphony Orchestra hall on
the site of the old First Baptist Church in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   The Blank family is also leading a challenge campaign to name
the building after legendary ASO conductor Robert Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, part of the gift will honor ASO music director
Yoel Levi, whose contract is not being renewed beyond next season,
a move that has caused controversy among his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I now believe the impossible can be done. I believe we will
get a new symphony hall,'' said A.D. Frazier, chairman of the
symphony board and president and CEO of Invesco Inc. ``This is
truly a giant step towards a new symphony hall.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blank gift, announced Tuesday, is the first major
contribution pledged for a proposed $113 million symphony hall. The
ASO needs at least $45 million in pledges by Aug. 10 in order to
proceed with the project. Atlanta's corporate community and arts
supporters will be asked to come up with the rest of the initial
funding over the next month.
</P>
<P>
   The hall would be part of BellSouth Corp.'s new office
development at the corner of Peachtree and Fifth streets. BellSouth
has given the ASO until Aug. 10 to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just thought this was a unique chance in the life of the
symphony,'' said Arthur M. Blank, president, CEO and co-founder of
Home Depot. He is making the gift along with his wife, Stephanie,
and his son, Kenny.
</P>
<P>
   The Blank Family Foundation actually is making two gifts _ $10
million outright and another $5 million challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 million gift will include naming the hall's grand lobby
after the Blank family. In the lobby, the Blanks also would like to
honor Arthur Blank's mother, Molly Blank, now a Los Angeles
resident who introduced her son to classical music when he was a
teenager.
</P>
<P>
   The man who would help build a home supply giant recalls that he
and his mother would take a bus, then the subway and then another
bus, to go to Carnegie Hall in New York City on Saturday mornings
to attend Leonard Bernstein concerts. Blank also wants to find a
way to honor Yoel Levi in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The Blank family has proposed naming the hall after the late
Robert Shaw, the ASO's music director for 21 years, and would award
the additional $5 million challenge grant if three other $5 million
donations can be raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of momentum here,'' said ASO President Allison
Vulgamore, who has been meeting with the Blanks for months. ``This
is a gift of $15 million that could become $30 million. We need a
team to join the Blanks to complete the naming of the concert hall
after Robert Shaw.''
</P>
<P>
   At his death in January, at 82, Shaw was universally
acknowledged as the world's greatest choral music figure. As music
director of the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra and Chorus from
1967-1988, he elevated the ASO into a professional ensemble of
international fame. Under his direction, the ASO toured the world
and performed at the inauguration of President Jimmy Carter in
1977. He won a total of 17 Grammys and was awarded the Kennedy
Center Honors in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Shaw family's response was euphoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's lovely,'' said Alex Hitz, Shaw's stepson, answering
the phone at the Shaw home in Atlanta. ``We as a family are
absolutely thrilled by this great honor and very grateful that
Robert is being remembered in such a lasting way.'' He said that he
had been trying to reach his younger brother, Thomas Shaw, who was
traveling in Spain, to tell him the news.
</P>
<P>
   Hitz said he was optimistic that the challenge money could be
raised. ``I think the money will come,'' he said. ``I'm going to
try to help them raise it.''
</P>
<P>
   Musicworld observers said it was appropriate that the honor go
to Shaw. ``He had such a huge impact on the city, on that orchestra
and on the music of America and the world,'' said New York
Philharmonic artistic administrator Welz Kauffman, who held that
position at the ASO from 1992-94. ``It's absolutely the right thing
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blank gift also sends a message of healing to Atlanta's
music lovers who have been divided over the imminent departure of
Levi. One of Levi's backers is Bernard Marcus, who co-founded the
Home Depot with Blank.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a signal from our family that the community
needs to move past the personalities in this and move towards the
love of music,'' Blank said. ``It has been a very painful
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoel Levi declined comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stunning is what it is,'' said horn player Bruce Kenney,
president of the ASO Players Association. ``I think we are seeing
that a new chapter in the history of the Atlanta Symphony is being
written.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the ASO leadership was celebrating the Blank gift
Tuesday, it still faces the difficult task of raising at least $30
million more by Aug. 10 in order to use the First Baptist Church
site. Blank said he'll help recruit other donors. ``There are a lot
of people in Atlanta, some I'm closer to than others, who have the
capacity to contribute,'' Blank said. ``It is our hope and our
prayer that this will get folks to support the arts at a much
higher level in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Saporta and Wendell Brock write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
