<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ASKED TO EXPLAIN RACIALLY RESTRICTIVE CLAUSE IN DEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The racist clause is legally meaningless, but
George W. Bush found himself explaining Tuesday why he sold his
Dallas home five years ago with a deed provision restricting
ownership to whites.
</P>
<P>
   The racially restrictive covenant was part of the paperwork when
the just-elected Texas governor sold his North Dallas home in 1995
to move into the Governor's Mansion in Austin. The deed restriction
declared the property could be occupied ``by white persons only,''
with an exception for ``servants of any race.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said Bush was not aware of the
covenant, which had covered the property since 1939. The
restriction was legally meaningless because the Supreme Court
outlawed racially exclusive covenants in 1948. Texas banned them in
1984, four years before Bush bought the Dallas home.
</P>
<P>
   But the legal repudiation of segregation did not erase the
offensive language from existing deeds. Racial restrictions were
once commonplace in communities throughout the country. Some
neighborhoods used similar provisions to exclude Jewish homeowners.
Deeds in California often prohibited sales to Chinese residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``That deed is a matter of record. There would be no way to
erase the record,'' said Dallas housing lawyer Norman ``Happy''
Nelson. ``If it was there when he got the property, there was no
way he could do anything about it. It's a non-issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, racially restrictive covenants, ghosts of the nation's
segregationist past, have a way of haunting politicians. In a new
twist, Bush's old deed came to light via the Internet. Cyber snoop
Matt Drudge, probably best known for his role in publicizing the
White House sex scandal, trumpeted his news tidbit as an
``exclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't news to Alphonso Jackson, an African-American who
lives in Bush's old Dallas neighborhood. Jackson, former president
of the Dallas Housing Authority, said his home in the upscale area
also came with a deed restricting ownership to whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I laughed about it. We thought it was funny. We
still think it's funny,'' Jackson said. ``I'm just glad I moved in
before the houses got so expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said Bush and his wife, Laura, welcomed him to the
Preston Hollow neighborhood with a party when he bought his house
in 1990. He said the governor has ``no racist bone'' in his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``George is the fairest human being _ with everyone _ that I've
ever come across,'' Jackson said. ``Laura and the governor are
first rate. They respect and love people of all races and colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is the latest in the long line of public officials who have
had to explain racially restrictive covenants.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist came under fire from
Democrats at his 1986 confirmation hearings for the top court post
because of deed restrictions on his home in Phoenix, Ariz., and at
a summer home in Vermont. The Vermont deed prohibited sale or lease
of the property to ``any member of the Hebrew race.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., attacked Republican Michael
Huffington in their 1994 Senate race for restrictive covenants on
his previous homes in Texas. Huffington retaliated two days later
by revealing similar restrictions on the deed to Feinstein's
turn-of-the-century San Francisco home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's there, it's there,'' said Nelson, the housing lawyer.
``Nobody can take it out.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
