<SLUG> BC-NH-PRIMARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. ECONOMY GAINS $175M EXTRA IN PRIMARY YEAR, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ New Hampshire's first-in-the-nation presidential
primary is worth about $175 million to the state's economy in the
year leading up to and immediately following the event, according
to an interim report released Tuesday by the Library and Archives
of New Hampshire's Political Tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The report estimates that over a four-year election cycle, the
primary is worth $210 million to the Granite State.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of what the primary brings in have ranged over the
years from $30 million to $238 million. New Hampshire Secretary of
State William M. Gardner said this study marks the first time an
attempt has been made to truly quantify the dollar value.
</P>
<P>
   The report was commissioned by the Library and Archives, the
state's political library, and conducted by economists from New
Hampshire's Business and Industry Association, professors from the
University of New Hampshire and Salem State College, and a media
research firm. They analyzed spending from the 1996 primary _
including travel tourism, tax data and Federal Election Commission
filings _ conducted polls and estimated the value of media
coverage. The full report is due out after the 2000 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Total direct, indirect and induced spending during the peak
season of the 1996 primary was calculated at just under $150
million. Researchers estimated the state gained an additional $25
million from media exposure.
</P>
<P>
   And primary season never seems to end here: The researchers
estimated an additional $30 million was spent on primary-related
visits between the end of the 1992 primary and March of 1995. And
prior to March of 1995, the report says, the state gained an
additional $5 million from media exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big numbers in terms of dollars,'' said Brian Gottlob of
the New Hampshire Business and Industry Association, ``But in the
context of an over 30 billion dollar economy, it's relatively
small. It's not driving economic events. It has a role, it
certainly has an impact, but it's not something that changes the
fortunes of New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates, campaign staff and media who descended on the
state to cover the last primary spent $55 million between March
1995 and February 1996. Of that, $24 million was spent on hotels,
restaurants and recreation.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said that the $55 million in direct spending
resulted in another $24 million in indirect expenditures by
businesses with the money they received from direct spending; and
another $70 million of induced spending _ purchases made by
households that received income from the direct and indirect sales.
</P>
<P>
   That spending, researchers said, results in over 1,500 full-time
jobs, almost half of which come in the lodging and restaurant
industries.
</P>
<P>
   The economic gain from media coverage is harder to quantify.
Based on a series of suppositions, researchers estimated the state
gained $25 million as a result of media coverage in the six months
leading up to the primary. They said $5 million of that was from
tourists visiting New Hampshire after reading about the state in
the press.
</P>
<P>
   The other $20 million, they estimated, came in value to the
state as a result of new businesses being created or moving here.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of that can be attributed directly to stories about the
primary, but the primary is the single-biggest occasion for New
Hampshire being mentioned in the media.
</P>
<P>
   Media research indicated that nearly 20,000 stories about the
primary appeared in the print and broadcast media in six months in
1996. Of those stories, 11 percent showed New Hampshire in a
favorable light and 85 percent were neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlob said New Hampshire has the opportunity to increase the
percentage of favorability.
</P>
<P>
   Ask reporters, said Gottlob, if they realize New Hampshire has
``the highest percentage of high-tech workers of any state in the
nation. I guarantee they will not know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also attempted to quantify the political and social
benefits of the primary. In a survey of 500 New Hampshire
households in February, 18 percent of respondents said they had met
or shaken hands with a presidential candidate, 27 percent had
attended a campaign event, 43 percent said they volunteered on a
campaign and 70 percent said they voted in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it that New Hampshire is always first and always
right?'' asked former New Hampshire Governor Hugh Gregg, chairman
of the Library and Archives. ``Twenty percent of people in New
Hampshire have shaken hands with a candidate. I think that's our
answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
