<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8785 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMITH-GOP-BOS &LR;      07-13 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-GOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH BREAKS WITH GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As dawn broke Tuesday on his last morning in the
Republican Party, Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire followed the
script of his celluloid hero, Jimmy Stewart, in ``Mr. Smith Goes to
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final scene before he became the first Republican senator
in nearly a half-century to walk away from his party, Bob Smith
strode through the mist to the Lincoln and Jefferson memorials.
</P>
<P>
   The former schoolteacher moved on to the Vietnam memorial and
his parents' graves in Arlington National Cemetery, as he
contemplated his pending act of defiance _ a move that even his
supporters portrayed as political suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the footsteps of his movie hero, Smith ventured to the
Senate desk once occupied by Daniel Webster and declared he was
turning his back on the Republican Party because he believes the
party has turned its back on its conservative principles in the
name of political expedience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's a party in the sense of wearing hats and blowing
whistles, but it's not a party that means anything,'' Smith said in
a dramatic 55-minute speech.
</P>
<P>
   It was an extraordinary moment in the annals of New Hampshire
politics: a powerful GOP incumbent kicking aside the party
machinery that helped elevate him from small-town obscurity to the
alabaster halls of Congress, and choosing to seek the presidency as
a newly minted independent.
</P>
<P>
   In that instant, the prospect of Smith's political saga ending
as triumphantly as Stewart's on the silver screen appeared to fade
to black, or bleak at best.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 58, said in a news conference that he is strongly
considering seeking the nomination of the tiny US Taxpayer Party,
which has no significant history as a vehicle for a presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving open a possible bid for the Reform Party nomination,
Smith said he also hopes to pay a courtesy visit this weekend to
Minnesota Governor Jesse Ventura, who is vying for control of the
party with its founder, Ross Perot. The party's annual convention
is scheduled for July 23 to 25 in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, whose plan to bolt the GOP leaked last week to the news
media, acknowledged in his Senate speech that many of his friends
and colleagues ``have said that what I am doing is foolish.''
</P>
<P>
   Abandoning the Republican Party could cost Smith his Senate seat
should he seek reelection in 2002. He also could be stripped of his
Senate seniority and chairmanship of the ethics committee, although
the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, said there is no timetable
for Smith's 54 Republican colleagues to resolve those matters.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the historical odds of Smith winning the presidency on
a small, third-party ticket are extremely remote.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he is prepared to face the consequences. In an
address peppered with blistering criticism of the ``Republican
establishment,'' he credited a long cast of individuals _ from Mark
Twain to Patrick Henry to Jimmy Stewart's film character _ with
inspiring his risky endeavor and buoying him for the lonely journey
he faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remember them for what they were and what they said, not
for the party they were,'' Smith said of several American heroes.
``It inspired me today.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he tried his best to stop Smith from turning
independent. Smith became the first GOP senator to repudiate his
party registration since Wayne Morse of Oregon turned indpendent in
1953.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he is doing this out of conviction, but I am
disappointed,'' Lott said after Smith's speech. ``I don't think
it's necessary to do this, but he's made up his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of other Republican senators expressed disdain for
Smith's move, which they considered a bad precedent even if it does
not shift the balance of power in the Senate. As one of the most
conservative senators, Smith made clear that Democrats can expect
no support from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate and regrettable that he has chosen this
path,'' said Senator Olympia J. Snowe, a Maine Republican. ``We all
have disagreements with our party, but we don't walk away because
of them. Certainly, it would be a lot more constructive to work
within the party.''
</P>
<P>
   With about 20 senators in the Senate chamber, including Lott and
his leadership team, Smith renewed attacks he had leveled earlier
against GOP leaders in Washington and New Hampshire. The party
leaders had harshly criticized his defection.
</P>
<P>
   Depicting the party establishment as hostages of pollsters and
consultants who consider winning elections more important than
defending the party's principles, Smith said, ``We need to get out
the fumigation equipment. We need to clean out the pollsters and
consultants and the spin doctors and the bloated staffs who tell us
what to say, how to say it, when to say it, and how long to say it.
The American people elected us. Isn't it time we started thinking
for ourselves?''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a lifelong Republican who said President Reagan inspired
him to pursue a political career, expressed lingering resentment at
GOP leaders who asked him to withdraw from a race for a New
Hampshire House seat in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Smith refused to pull out and won the primary, though he lost
the general election. Two years later, he won the House seat, an
unpolished newcomer who quickly drew comparisons to Stewart's movie
character.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has served in Congress ever since, though he said he has
yet to decide whether he will seek reelection in 2002, without the
benefit of Republican Party support.
</P>
<P>
   More pressing, he said, is his presidential campaign. Though the
campaign is flagging badly, Smith clings to his trademark tenacity.
``Sure, right now, if you want to look at the polls, it doesn't
look all that great,'' he said. ``But things change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
