<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8786 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-PATIENT-RIGHTS     07-13 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-PATIENT-RIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEFEATS PROVISION GIVING WOMEN DIRECT ACCESS TO
OBSTETRICIANS, GYNECOLOGISTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
and GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate efforts to address consumer worries about
managed care plans remained mired in partisanship Tuesday as
Republicans defeated a Democratic provision that would give women
greater freedom in choosing which doctors they see.
</P>
<P>
   Voting closely along party lines, the Senate rejected by a
margin of 52-48 an amendment that would have given women direct
access to obstetricians and gynecologists without having to go
through a health plan gatekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   The provision also would have allowed physicians and patients,
not health plans, to determine how long a woman should stay in a
hospital following a mastectomy. Only three Republicans joined all
the Democrats in supporting the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was also expected to approve a Republican-sponsored
amendment that permits the self employed to deduct 100 percent of
their health care premiums on their tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   The votes marked the first skirmish in the health care debate
now raging in the Senate as lawmakers consider GOP and Democrat
attempts to regulate managed care plans. It was also a clear signal
that Republicans have the votes to defeat numerous Democratic
amendments and push through their own health care measure.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton administration officials have indicated the
president would likely veto the Republican plan as it is presently
constituted.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the arguments of business and insurance interests,
Republicans charged that the Democratic provisions would raise the
cost of health insurance so high that women would no longer be able
to afford treatment for breast cancer or other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats expressed astonishment that the Republicans would
reject a provision that would allow women to bypass health plan
bureaucrats in search of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we found out what compassionate conservatism is to be.
It is not compassionate. But it is conservative,'' said Sen.
Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., referring to the `` the compassionate
conservative'' slogan used repeatedly by GOP presidential
frontrunner Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush vetoed a managed care bill approved by the Texas
Legislature in 1995, two years later he signed an HMO bill that,
among other things, gives women direct access to obstetricians and
gynecologists. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``On the governors watch we've gotten the most comprehensive
patients rights laws in the country,'' said Kim Ross, a lobbyist
with the Texas Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Bush even allowed to become law a provision that gives Texans
the right to sue their HMO, a measure embraced by congressional
Democrats but opposed by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the different approach taken by Bush and
congressional Republicans over regulating HMOs, Ross said, ``that's
why they are in trouble and he's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans promised to offer an alternative provision
concerning women's health, but did not divulge what it would do.
</P>
<P>
   Even if their patients' rights bill is defeated, as expected,
Democrats still believe the issue will resonate in the 2000
elections.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, President Clinton also weighed in on what he called
the ``watered-down'' patients rights bill offered by the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nowhere near what the American people deserve or need.
Not only does it offer merely toothless and halfhearted
protections, it fails to protect all Americans in managed care,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic bill, authored primarily by Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., seeks to provide basic consumer protections for
patients by making access easier to specialists and emergency
services, allowing lawsuits against health maintenance
organizations and giving physicians instead of insurers the final
authority in determining whether treatments are medically
necessary. It would cover all 161 million Americans with private
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican measure, on the other hand, would strengthen the
appeals process for denials of coverage or other complaints, but it
would not repeal the current federal ban on patients suing HMOs.
Like the Democratic bill, it would also expand access to services
now denied by some plans. But most of its provisions would cover
only some 48 million Americans whose coverage is provided through
large, self-funded employer programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton accused the GOP of trying to kill the Democratic
proposal because of pressure from the health insurance industry and
managed care providers, which are spending millions of dollars on
television and other media advertising campaigns in an all-out
effort to defeat the Democrats' bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about ... whether the people of this country come
first in the votes of the Congress of the United States,'' Clinton
said. ``The people deserve a bill that protects them, not the
insurance companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans responded by accusing Clinton and the Democrats
of trying to ``nationalize'' the nation's health care system by
imposing universal standards that states would be required to
enforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always had the idea that the federal government knows
best,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., who, along with Texas Sen.
Phil Gramm, has taken the lead in mounting the GOP opposition to
the Democratic proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reject that philosophy, that Washington knows best on health
care.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to alter the Democratic proposal, the Republicans
are pushing an amendment offered by Gramm, Nickles and other
Republicans that would expand the medical savings account program
Congress authorized a few years ago on a limited basis. It would
allow people who can afford it to opt out of their current health
care systems and put aside tax-free savings to be used for medical
expenses. Any funds not used at the end of a year for
health-related expense, can then be used for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   These accounts, known as MSA's and backed by high-deductible
insurance policies designed to provide catastrophic coverage, are
now limited to small businesses with 50 or fewer employees and are
used primarily by younger or healthy individuals without families.
</P>
<P>
   But Gramm insisted that under the Republican proposal, MSA's
would eventually become the health insurance program of choice for
most Americans because they give patients's greater freedom to
choose their own doctors and other health care services. He said
that the savings could be used for investments and other purposes
also provides people with ``enough incentive to be cost
conscience'' about the kind of care they choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fix the system not with lawsuits and heavy-handed
regulations...but by giving people more freedom,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
