<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-ARTISTS-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FINE ART OF BITING INTO JAPANESE CUTENESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Edward M. Gomez writes regularly about Japanese art and design.  
 By EDWARD M. GOMEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNANDALE-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. _ Since the late 1980s, a number of
younger Japanese artists have emerged on the international scene to
challenge the old notion that all modern art from Japan is merely a
pale imitation of modern art from the West.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are Yasumasa Morimura, Tatsuo Miyajima, Mariko Mori
and Takashi Murakami, whose goofy, glossy work has found an avid
audience outside Japan. Rooted in Japanese popular culture,
Murakami's art communicates across borders in a media-driven era of
global pop to which fashion, animation, music and electronic
gadgetry from Japan have all contributed.
</P>
<P>
   It is now the focus of ``The Meaning of the Nonsense of the
Meaning,'' a mini-retrospective on view here at the Center for
Curatorial Studies Museum at Bard College through Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, art people and intellectuals get what my art is
about, but for the Japanese it's still threatening,'' Murakami said
recently while installing his show. At 37, his boyish looks are
accentuated by his hip-hop uniform: baggy shorts, a T-shirt, a
baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   Murakami, who grew up in Tokyo, is a member of what his
countrymen call the shinjinrui (new human species), the postwar
generations whose easy access to leisure, travel and consumer goods
was unknown to the millions who struggled to rebuild the nation
after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Murakami's art has been called neo-pop or critical pop. ``In
Japan, communication is about appearances and surfaces,'' he said.
``We use cuteness and formality to disguise what we really want to
say. My work looks at the other side of that cuteness.''
</P>
<P>
   That calculated cheerfulness is visible in the cartoon-character
corporate logotypes seen all across Japan for everything from
fast-food outlets to banks, and in an endless outpouring of anime
(animated films), manga (comic books) and video games that often
share heroes and story lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our traditional arts, whose rules are strict, but in a
contemporary context there is no fine art anymore,'' said Murakami.
``Pop-culture imagery has become the dominant language, so through
it I try to create a fine art for our times.''
</P>
<P>
   These may be surprising words from someone who, in 1993, earned
the first doctorate degree in nihonga ever awarded by the
prestigious Tokyo National University of Fine Arts and Music.
Nihonga is a Japanese genre that mixes local, traditional subject
matter with 19th-century European-derived painting techniques.
Murakami also taught drawing before setting out on an art career in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In his earlier conceptual-action works, Murakami recruited four
art students to pose simultaneously as the same Japanese television
star who had lost the right to use his stage name in a dispute with
his manager, and in another work, he appropriated a well-known
comic strip satirizing Japanese middle-class life. Meticulously
assembled, his more recent art is inspired by Japan's otaku, or
``geek,'' subculture. Otaku are obsessive fans of sexy manga, anime
and computer games.
</P>
<P>
   By 1994, Murakami had devised his own edgy cartoon-character
alter ego. Known as Mr. DOB, it vaguely resembles a certain famous
mouse but also recalls an inflatable pygmy doll that the artist
once spotted in a toy shop. Mr. DOB has turned up in lusciously
textured paintings, on T-shirts, as a plush toy and in large
balloon sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murakami sees no distinction between his fine art and his
merchandise; his goal is to speak to and about current Japanese
society by creating and distributing works that are understood by
all,'' said Amada Cruz, the director of Bard's Center for
Curatorial Studies Museum and a curator, with Dana Friis-Hansen, of
the artist's show.
</P>
<P>
   In his newest works at Bard, Murakami metamorphoses Mr. DOB into
DNA helixes, ectoplasmic webs and three-dimensional toadstools that
look like fixtures from a psychedelic amusement park. Mr. DOB's
smile often reveals spiky, monstrous teeth; many pieces on view
exude a sinister charm.
</P>
<P>
   Murakami, who now regularly uses skilled assistants, maintains
studios in Tokyo and New York and has galleries in those cities as
well as in Los Angeles. He admits to being much more ambitious than
his casual demeanor suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Critiquing pop culture's daunting effluence even as he adds to
it, Murakami said slyly: ``Eventually, if my characters go in the
direction of kitsch, that's O.K. If I see them on coffee mugs in
airport souvenir shops everywhere, that's fine with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
