<SLUG> BC-ALA-SCHOOLPRAYER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court overturns school prayer ruling
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A federal appeals court panel Tuesday said a judge's
ruling on school prayer in Alabama went too far and restricted the
right of students to lead a prayer or express religious feelings in
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in a 3-0 decision said
U.S. District Judge Ira DeMent wrongly restricted students'
religious expression in his 1997 ruling. DeMent's ruling stemmed
from a lawsuit brought against Alabama's DeKalb County schools by
Michael Chandler on behalf of his son, Jessie, a pupil there.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 years of legal precedent had gone against
school-sanctioned prayers. The appellate decision also runs counter
to a three-judge panel's ruling in a similar Florida case, but that
ruling has been set aside and the case will be heard by all 11
members of the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   DeMent's order covered a range of school religion issues. The
appeals court's decision focused on sections that had been
challenged by Alabama Attorney General Bill Pryor.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor described the decision Tuesday as a victory for all
Alabamians, particularly schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was looking forward to returning to DeMent's
courtroom to have the rules redrawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court held that schoolchildren are not `state actors' and,
following that reasoning, they can seize the intercom and pray,
which a school employee cannot do. But what this now allows
teachers to do is choose a kid to pray over the intercom, or at
graduation or assemblies,'' said Pamela Sumners, the Chandler
family's attorney in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Gita M. Smith writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
