r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-13 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI'S FLEXIBLE POINT OF VIEW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York Mayor  &UR; Rudy Giuliani &LR; , a potential rival, &LR;  hasn't been
gentle to possible New York senatorial candidate  &UR; Hillary &LR; 
 &UR; Rodham Clinton &LR; , a carpetbagger &LR; , &LR;  in his estimation.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani didn't always view the out-of-state candidate with
disdain. Thesmokinggun.com reprints a story Giuliani wrote in a
student newspaper in October 1964, when he was a student at
Manhattan College and  &UR; Robert F. Kennedy  &LR; was running against
incumbent Sen.  &UR; Kenneth Keating &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Wrote Giuliani in the Quadrangle: ``The political climate in New
York is alive and for the first time since 1954 New York has a
two-party race for a major state-wide office. ... Senator Keating
claims he is running on his record; but his only real issue has
been that Robert Kennedy is an intruder in New York State
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The carpetbagger issue ``is a truly ridiculous reason for not
voting for a man in the year 1964. Without doubt, the Kennedy
candidacy in New York is perfectly in accord with the
Constitutional stipulation that a Senator must be a resident of the
state he represents on the day he is elected. ... The main question
is whether or not we in New York are going to make our decision on
a candidate by the standards of parochialism. ... Let us hope that
cosmopolitan New Yorkers can rise above the ridiculous, time-worn
provincial attitude that has so dis-unified our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AFTERLIFE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ If heaven exists, Madison magazine asked  &UR; Peter Falk &LR; , what
would you like to hear God say when you arrive? ``What did you pay
for those shoes?'' Falk answered.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bob Treuhaft &LR; , husband of the late  &UR; Jessica Mitford &LR; , says
he's of two minds about the Pacific Interment Service ad that
specifies _ without prior permission _ that it was ``chosen by
Jessica Mitford, author of `The American Way of Death,' for her own
cremation.''
</P>
<P>
   He's probably entitled to a licensing fee, says Treuhaft, but
``they're a good outfit,'' and he doesn't want to press it. ``It's
a good ad for the book.''
</P>
<P>
   _ WhiteLight, a Dallas coffinmaker, is offering discerning
buyers ``Art Caskets,'' which feature the results of ``a state of
the art process'' that applies ``a laminated photo mural to a steel
casket's exterior.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the stock designs, which cost $2,500, are Fairway to
Heaven for golfers, the Awareness Ribbon or the Cathedral Stained
Glass model. The company also can create custom-designed caskets,
says Details magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Bob Lilley &LR; , who used to be half of ``The Blazy and Bob
Morning Show'' on KOME-FM in San Jose, has quit radio and turned to
history, in particular the study of the cultural effects of the
assassination of JFK in 1963. Lilley is looking for recollections
of what people were doing the day  &UR; John F. Kennedy &LR;  was shot, and
how it affected them. He's at IR112263 &LR; aol.com, or I Remember, PMB
133, 708 Blossom Hill Road, Los Gatos, CA 95032.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sinead O'Connor &LR; , who said a few months ago when she was
ordained a priest in a Catholic splinter group that she was
considering celibacy, apparently decided heck, no. The Mirror of
London reports that she is expecting her third child early next
year. The father is Irish Mirror journalist  &UR; Neil Michael &LR; , who met
her in May when he interviewed her.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Garth Brooks &LR;  has sold more albums than  &UR; Elvis Presley &LR;  and
 &UR; Nirvana &LR;  combined, says Jump magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ardent Television Production Co., which is the company of
 &UR; Prince Edward &LR;  (who is supposed to be the Earl of Wessex, but you
might as well call him 3-Com), is selling tours to Windsor that
include overnight stays in a hotel, a visit to the castle and four
lectures by the prince. ``Prince Edward should not be cashing in
like this,'' said constitutional historian  &UR; David &LR; 
 &UR; Starkey &LR; . ``This is as much an insider job as a politician milking
his position for private profit.''
</P>
