<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-JONES-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW JONES EARNINGS EXCEED EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strong gains in advertising and low newsprint prices combined to
propel Dow Jones &AMP; Co.'s second-quarter earnings above analyst
expectations. The company reported Tuesday that its net income for
the quarter reached $57.2 million, or 62 cents a diluted share, a
penny above the consensus estimate reported by the First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive quarter in which earnings exceeded
expectations, and the strongest improvements came in the company's
print publishing operations. Ad lineage at The Wall Street Journal
increased 6.9 percent in the second quarter over the comparable
period in 1998. But the improvement accelerated sharply in June,
when advertising lineage was up 19 percent over June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising revenue at all Dow Jones United States publications
grew 10 percent, pushing print publishing revenue up 6 percent, to
$327 million. Over all, revenues rose 4.9 percent over the 1998
period, to $510.6 million. Operating income was $104.8 million, up
6.9 percent from the pro forma figure for the second quarter of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   At the company's Ottaway community newspapers division,
operating income rose 47 percent to $23.6 million, despite slight
advertising losses, because of economies that pushed up that
division's cash-flow margins to 33.1 percent, up from 25.1 percent
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an investor's point of view, it is sensational The
Journal is doing as well as it is,'' said Lauren Rich Fine, an
analyst with Merrill Lynch. ``It is carrying the whole company.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was more guarded about the prospects for the company's
electronic publishing division, where operating income dropped 44.6
percent, to $10.2 million, despite a 1.4 percent rise in revenue,
as the sales force was expanded to sell the Dow Jones news wires
product overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons investors are interested in Dow Jones is
the emerging electronic segment, and there are a lot of caveats,''
Ms. Fine said.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued Tuesday, she pointed out that The Wall Street
Journal's interactive edition continued to grow, with 306,000
subscribers to date, up from 223,000 a year ago; it brought in $7.9
million, up 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the far larger news wire business, Ms. Fine wrote, ``is
relatively stagnant.'' The company reported total electronic
revenue of $98.9 million for the quarter, up 1 percent from a year
ago; revenue from the news wires were $51.1 million, basically
unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
