A8801 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILGRIM-SALE-BOS &LR;      07-13 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILGRIM-SALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON EDISTON COMPLETES SALE OF 27-YEAR-OLD N-PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the right price, anything _ even a 27-year-old nuclear power
plant that someday could cost $600 million to clean up _ can be a
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving what some US energy analysts once thought was
impossible, Boston Edison's parent company Tuesday completed its
$81 million sale of the Pilgrim nuclear power plant in Plymouth,
Mass. to a unit of New Orleans energy giant Entergy Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilgrim deal, one of a handful that have been in the works,
was the first successfully completed nuclear plant sale in US
history. It may herald a new era for many of the nation's 103
nuclear power plants, which not long ago were widely considered
doomed albatrosses.
</P>
<P>
   As industry restructuring pushes utilities to unload their
generating assets to competitive power producers, a handful of
national energy giants such as Entergy and Amergen are lining up.
On their shopping lists: such nuclear plants as Pilgrim, Seabrook,
Vermont Yankee, and the Millstone complex in Connecticut, once seen
as hopelessly uneconomical.
</P>
<P>
   Amergen is looking over Vermont Yankee and is close to a final
deal on the Three Mile Island 1 plant in Pennsylvania, the
undamaged sister of the now-closed plant involved in the 1979
disaster that chilled nuclear power development nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   While buyers are accepting potentially enormous risks, a huge
enticement is that utilities are offering below-fire-sale prices
for nuclear plants. Pilgrim is selling for barely 11 cents on the
book-value dollar, or perhaps six months' gross revenues.
</P>
<P>
   And state regulators in Massachusetts and elsewhere are allowing
utilities to pass along huge cleanup costs to ratepayers. Edison
will charge customers $271 million in coming years to fund a
federally required decommissioning account for the time when
Pilgrim is permanently shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrim can produce up to 670 megawatts of electricity, about 3
percent of New England's peak power needs. Under Tuesday's deal,
Edison will buy 100 percent of Pilgrim's output through the end of
2002, after which Entergy will begin converting Pilgrim to a
``merchant plant'' competing with gas, oil, coal, and other units
to sell to the New England grid.
</P>
<P>
   As long as current regulatory and market conditions last,
``Nuclear power is going to get a second look,'' said analyst Ethan
Cohen of the Yankee Group in Boston. ``Once you've covered the
installed cost base, it is exceptionally cheap energy to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Maloney, president of Devonrue Ltd., a Hingham consulting
firm active in energy deregulation issues, said of the Pilgrim
sale: ``It's like buying a car for the price of the gas in the
tank. It's basically a giveaway.''
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference in Plymouth, Entergy president Don Hintz
said: ``I believe this sale is the first of many. Entergy believes
that well-run nuclear plants, at least of a certain size and in a
good area, can be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is to acquire as many of the big nuclear plants
in good power regions as we can,'' Hintz said, including New
England. Entergy, which beat out 10 bidders for Pilgrim, owns five
Deep South nuclear units. It predicted Pilgrim will add 5 cents a
share to this year's net profits.
</P>
<P>
   Under deregulation deals being discussed with New Hampshire and
Connecticut regulators, by December 2003 Northeast Utilities is
proposing to sell its stakes in the Seabrook and Millstone plants,
although it may have a subsidiary bid on Millstone.
</P>
<P>
   Hintz also said that although Pilgrim's operating license
expires in 2012, ``I would be surprised if we didn't make the
decision to'' ask federal regulators to extend the license.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy Nuclear already has contracts to decommission the Maine
Yankee and Millstone 1 Connecticut unit. ``I'd sooner operate
nuclear plants than decommission them,'' Hintz said.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrim employs more than 600 people and pays one-quarter of the
town's property taxes. After a rocky safety record in the
mid-1980s, Pilgrim this month completed 500 days of uninterrupted
operation, Edison chairman Thomas May said.
</P>
<P>
   The $81 million purchase price includes $67 million for
radioactive fuel on site and just $14 million for the plant itself,
which cost $231 million to build in 1972 and has a net book value
of $700 million, counting capital improvements since.
</P>
<P>
   Edison is transferring about $200 million in the decommissioning
fund to Entergy and will add the $271 million that will be billed
to its 650,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy officials are confident the $471 million, plus future
investment returns, will cover ultimate shutdown costs. Edison
spokesman David Tarantino said Edison customers will save more than
$100 million in future decommissioning charges they would have had
to pay if Edison continued to own Pilgrim through 2012. Edison also
expects to get $31 million in insurance rebates if Pilgrim operates
without incident through 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilgrim site also includes 1,600 acres of land abutting Cape
Cod Bay, some of which could be prime development land. Also, if
the nuclear generator is ever shut down, the site could well be
used as a platform for a new gas-powered plant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8805 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAILWAY-KILLER-2TAKES     07-13 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILWAY-KILLER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE SUSPECTED OF COMMITTING AT LEAST EIGHT MURDERS IS
ARRESTED
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After eluding an international manhunt for months, a
Mexican fugitive suspected of jumping freight cars to commit at
least eight brutal murders in Texas, Illinois and Kentucky
surrendered on Tuesday morning after his family negotiated his
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, walked across a bridge
from Juarez, Mexico, to the Usleta border checkpoint in El Pasoat 9
a.m. and extended his hand to a Texas Ranger who greeted him with a
handshake and handcuffs. Resendez-Ramirez, 39, a slight man who
wore a striped shirt and wire-rimmed aviator glasses, was described
as calm and ``very pleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, after thousands of law-enforcement officers in the
United States and Mexico followed thousands of tips in vain, the
case broke because a sister of the suspect called the Texas Ranger
who later made the arrest on the bridge. The ranger, Andrew Carter,
had traded calls with the sister, who lives in Albuquerque, for two
weeks before she reached him Sunday on his cellular telephone as he
fished off the Texas coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramirez's sister called him on his cell phone and said, `We
need to talk,'''said Mike Cox, a spokesman for the Texas Department
of Public Safety. ``She thought her brother was ready to
surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an unexpected break in a case that had looked hopeless as
recently as last week when the authorities and the suspect's
common-law wife in Mexico had issued a public plea for
Resendez-Ramirez to surrender. With each of the eight killings
occurring near railroad tracks, guns sales in many railroad
communities in Texas rose sharply as law-enforcement officials
warned that the ``railroad killer'' could strike again.
</P>
<P>
   For months, grainy photographs of the suspect had been plastered
in post offices across the country as Resendez-Ramirez was named to
the FBI's Ten Most Wanted List on June 21. A federal, state and
local law enforcement task force in Houston had followed thousands
of tips, most of them false leads. The last credible sighting came
on June 18 when he was spotted at a homeless shelter in Louisville,
Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez appeared on Tuesday morning before a state
magistrate in El Paso on a pending burglary charge from the Houston
area. He was then flown to Houston, accompanied by Carter, and
placed in the Harris County Jail in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Harris County District Attorney's Office is expected to
charge him with murder. He has been linked to five slayings in
Texas since last December. He faces two murder charges in Illinois
for the June 15 shotgun slayings of an elderly man and his
daughter. Another murder charge is pending in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Resendez-Ramirez faces the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission accomplished, for the moment,'' said Don K. Clark, the
FBI special agent in charge in Houston, speaking at a news
conference on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by a phalanx of investigators, Clark paused to make a
statement to the families of the victims. ``We cannot bring your
loved ones back,'' he said, ``but we did pledge to work endlessly
to work for justice, and we did just that.''
</P>
<P>
   But until Tuesday's arrest, the investigation had met with
criticism, particularly after it was discovered that Border Patrol
agents had picked up the suspect on June 2 and released him into
Mexico even though the FBI was searching for him and the Houston
police had told the Immigration and Naturalization Service that
Resendez-Ramirez was wanted for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the suspect was released, a 73-year-old woman,
Josephine Konvicka, was found beaten to death in her home in
Fayette County west of Houston. On the next day, June 5, a Houston
school teacher, Noemie Dominguez, 26, was found clubbed to death in
her home. Ms. Dominguez's car was later found in the border town of
Del Rio, reportedly with fingerprints of the suspect inside.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the investigation, Resendez-Ramirez had remained a
mysterious figure. Even his true identity was uncertain since
investigators say he has used more than 30 aliases. Born in the
Mexican city of Puebla, he first entered the United States
illegally in 1976, when he was arrested in Brownsville by
Immigration and Naturalization Service agents.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 23 years ago, Resendez-Ramirez led the life of a
transient, illegally jumping freight cars from Mexico into the
United States. His adventures carried him from Vermont to
California, and he bounced in and out of federal prisons and local
jails on a long string of immigration violations and other minor
non-violent offenses.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his non-violent history, investigators have linked
him through physical evidence, including fingerprints in some of
the cases, to the five Texas killings as well as the slayings in
Illinois and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The first murder occurred on Aug. 29, 1997, when Christopher
Maier was killed along the railroad tracks in Lexington. Maier's
girlfriend was raped and beaten but survived the attack.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Maier case remained unsolved, and Resendez-Ramirez had
apparently not yet emerged as a suspect in 1998. He was stopped by
border agents and deported six times that year, the last time in
April. Eight months later, the first of the five related Texas
murders occurred when Dr. Claudia Benton, 39, was raped and stabbed
to death inside her home in West University Place on Dec. 17, 1998.
Then, last April 30, the Rev. Norman Sirnic and his wife, Karen,
were bludgeoned with a sledgehammer inside their home in Weimar,
Texas. Fingerprints and other evidence linked Resendez-Ramirez to
the crime, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   But the big break came on Sunday. Cox, the spokesman for the
Texas Department of Public Safety, said that Carter had first
visited the suspect's sister about two or three weeks ago at her
home in Albuquerque and had remained in regular telephone contact
with her. At the same time, the sister apparently had contacted
another brother in Mexico who knew the whereabouts of the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of receiving the cellular call on his fishing trip,
Carter flew to Albuquerque with an FBI agent and a U.S. marshal to
meet with the sister. By Monday, an agreement had been drafted by
the Harris County District Attorney's Office in Houston that
offered the suspect and his family three things: a pledge of safety
in the Harris County jail, the promise of regular visits from his
family and a full psychological examination.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said that winning the trust of Resendez-Ramirez' sister was
essential in breaking the case. He said that Carter, 32, ``was able
to build up some rapport and trust with them'' and ultimately his
siblings and a family minister convinced the suspect to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Though Clark was noncommittal when asked if the sister would
receive the $125,000 reward offered in the case, other officials
said it appeared that she would. Officials would not say if the
prospect of the reward prompted the sister to turn her brother in.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said that Mr. Resendez-Ramirez could be charged in
additional murder cases as the investigation progresses. He said
that 50 or 60 law enforcement agencies from throughout the country
had contacted the task force with possible related cases.
</P>
<P>
   In the summers of 1996 and 1998, Resendez-Ramirez labored as a
migrant worker at a tobacco farm in Russell County, Ky. Official
say they are investigating him for several murders that occurred
near railroad tracks in the area during those same summers.
Investigators also suspect that Mr. Resendez-Ramirez may be
connected to the Oct. 2, 1998, slaying of an elderly man in the
northeast Texas town of Hughes Springs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
