<HEADLINE>
COLLEAGUES CREDIT TEXAS RANGER WITH MAKING SURRENDER HAPPEN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Rangers Sgt. Andrew F. ``Drew'' Carter Jr.
was fishing on the Gulf Coast near Houston on Sunday when his
cellular phone rang, with probably the biggest phone call in his
short career as a Texas Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   The call was from Albuquerque, N.M., the home of the sister of
suspected serial killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez. Manuela Maturino
said her brother might be willing to give up if certain concerns
were addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suspect's sister had said that he would only surrender to
a Texas Ranger, not a federal officer or any other officer,'' said
Mike Cox, spokesman for the Department of Public Safety, the agency
that oversees the Rangers. He attributed the surrender in large
part to ``the rapport they (Carter and Maturino) had built up.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a Houston-based Ranger who had gained the woman's
confidence during the weeks-long international manhunt for her
brother, immediately returned to Houston. He conferred with Harris
County prosecutors about how to entice Resendez-Ramirez out of
hiding in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   They drew up a document that assured the suspect he would be
safe while in jail, that he would be allowed family visitors and
that he would get psychological help, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 48 hours later, Resendez-Ramirez _ insistent on
surrendering to a Texas Ranger _ walked across the Mexican border
near El Paso, shook hands with Carter and then allowed Carter to
end his freedom by slipping a pair of handcuffs on him.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt for the man who had cracked the FBI's Ten Most Wanted
list was over _ and several colleagues credit Carter with making it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who turned 32 Tuesday, joined the legendary and elite
Texas Rangers only last year, after a career with the Texas
Department of Public Safety that began in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was initially assigned as a highway patrolman in
Huntsville before stints in Brenham, Tyler and Houston. During his
11 years in state law enforcement he has gained 14 commendations.
He rose to lieutenant with the DPS. But, because officers must
enter the Rangers as a sergeant, he accepted a pay cut to join.
</P>
<P>
   Described as ``quiet and easygoing,'' Carter had little to say
after Resendez-Ramirez was in custody. In brief comments in El
Paso, he credited other law officers and the cooperation of the
family of Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been involved in this case since early on,'' Cox said,
noting that Carter originally worked on the Texas murders of the
Rev. Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic and his wife, Karen, in May in Weimar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
