<SLUG> BC-TOURDEFRANCE-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG'S TOUR DE FRANCE TOUR DE FORCE ROLLS ON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (jw) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SESTRIERE, Italy _ Lance Armstrong opened the defense of his
yellow jersey in the best possible way Tuesday as he demolished the
field in the Tour de France and won the first stage in the Alps,
put even more time between him and his rivals and showed that he
was the man to beat _ if anybody can _ in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think before today there were some questions about my
abilities in the mountains, so I think it was important to show
that the team and I are strong in the mountains,'' Armstrong said
Tuesday after his easy victory over five climbs and 213.5
kilometers (132.65 miles) from Le Grand Bornand, France, to
Sestriere, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The American leader of the U.S. Postal Service said he had
surprised even himself with his show of strength. Not an
overwhelming climber in earlier years, Armstrong has worked at his
power and lost a few pounds to help get over the peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Armstrong _ an outspoken opponent of the use of
performance-enhancing drugs in the sport _ given this Tour a
resoundingly positive image, he has also provided a inspirational,
feel-good story. A 27-year-old Texan, Armstrong was the world
road-race champion at 21 and was fighting testicular cancer at 25.
After surgery and three months of chemotherapy late in 1996, he
skipped the 1997 season to recover and returned to racing seriously
barely a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after three victories in the 1999 Tour, he has emphatically
embraced his position as a role model for anyone who has confronted
serious illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this can be a fantastic example for all cancer
patients, all survivors,'' Armstrong said after his victory in the
Tour's opening prologue in Le Puy du Fou on July 3. ``Hopefully, I
can prove it's possible to return to a normal professional life,
and maybe I can prove it's possible for you to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   If Armstrong wins the Tour, he would be only the second American
to win a race that began in 1903 and the first American to win it
since Greg LeMond did it for the third and last time in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Is the race over with nearly two weeks to go before the finish
in Paris on July 25? ``No, no,'' he said. ``I'm still nervous. We
don't think we have the race won at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``My rivals still have three or four days in the mountains and
they're going to be even tougher now. They're all fighters,
scrappers, whatever you want to call them.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, Armstrong finished first by 31 seconds over Alex
Zuelle, a Swiss with Banesto whom he rates as his most dangerous
rival. Fernando Escartin, a Spaniard with Kelme, was third, 1
minute 26 seconds behind, the same time as Ivan Gotti, an Italian
with Polti, in fourth place. Two other major rivals were far back _
Abraham Olano, a Spaniard with ONCE, lost 3:10, and Laurent Dufaux,
a Swiss with Saeco, lost 3:30.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, from Texas, widened his overall lead over the
second-place Olano to 6:03, with Christophe Moreau, a Frenchman
with Festina, third, 7:44 behind. Zuelle, who lost more than six
minutes after a mass crash on the second stage, is fourth, 7:47
behind, and Dufaux is fifth, 8:07 behind.
</P>
<P>
   Those are all big numbers this early in the 86th Tour, or any
other Tour. Especially interesting, Armstrong said earlier that of
the two days in the Alps, he rated his chances much higher on the
second day, the race to Alpe d'Huez on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alpe d'Huez suits me better because it's harder and more
selective,'' he said before Tuesday's race, speaking like the
master climber he was.
</P>
<P>
   With a sly grin, Armstrong admitted after this ninth of 20 daily
stages that he had also said beforehand that he planned to be
conservative in at least the first of two days in the Alps. Then he
was one of the first over the major climb of the day, the Galibier
pass, found himself without a teammate in the lead group but rode
at the front and attacked successfully with about six kilometers
(3.7 miles) to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did say that about being conservative,'' he said. ``But
sometimes the tactics dictate otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he said to the field: ``Here I am, come and get
me if you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong noted that, although he was without a teammate in the
lead pack and surrounded by three riders _ one from Banesto
(Zuelle), and two from Polti (Gotti and Richard Virenque, the star
French climber), ``I was concentrating on putting time between me
and Olano,'' he said. And he rode along securely.
</P>
<P>
   He even had a good word for the occasionally drizzly and cold
weather high in the Alps, which turned into a downpour just before
he crossed the line with his arms upraised. ``This kind of weather
makes half the field give up early,'' he said. ``I don't like it
myself, but it does make the job easier.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The stage began in the Alpine resort of Le Grand Bornand under
overcast skies as an immense crowd of vacationers cheered the
riders. The crowd thinned notably atop the Galibier, a climb of 18
kilometers (11.2 miles) with a grade of 6.9 percent. It is rated
beyond category, on a scale mounting from 4 to 1 in difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the other climbs were only hills but the final one to
the Italian resort of Sestriere was tough, 11 kilometers (6.8
miles) at a grade of 5.8 percent. The ramp to the finish was awash
in tifosi, the Italian bicycle fans, who plastered every rock and
fence with signs for their heroes, many of them unknown outside
their own kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   Among the eight riders who dropped out Tuesday were such names
as Mario Cipollini, the champion Italian sprinter for Saeco, who
showed up for the start in a Julius Caesar costume, and Jaan
Kirsipuu, an Estonian with Casino, who wore the yellow jersey most
of last week until he yielded it to Armstrong after the time trial
in Metz on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to keep the yellow jersey as long as possible,''
Armstrong said. ``If that means a day, a week, into Paris _ I have
no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, barring illness or injury, he is alone in that
uncertainty. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
