<HEADLINE>
HOME WITH KIN BEING SOUGHT FOR HONDURAN RUNAWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (mk) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About two dozen people have made inquiries about
giving a home to the 13-year-old Honduran runaway who captivated
New Yorkers with a fictional tale of a 3,200-mile odyssey, but city
officials said Tuesday that they remained hopeful that the boy
would find a home with his kin.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Edwin Daniel Sabillon, had told an elaborate tale of
traveling solo from Honduras to New York to find his father, who
was later revealed to have died last year. Employees with the city
Administration for Children's Services are currently talking with
the boy's grandmother, Paula Vasquez Hernandez, who raised him at
her home in San Buenventura in Honduras, about taking him in, said
Leonora Wiener, a spokeswoman for the agency. They also plan to
contact Edwin's mother in Choloma, a town in northern Honduras, and
an aunt in Hialeah, Fla., Ms. Wiener said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking to all the relatives and to the Honduran
consulate to try and find the best permanent home for him,'' said
Ms. Wiener.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin's mother, Angela Enamorado, said in an interview on
Honduran television Sunday that she would not let her son live with
her because he was too troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Edwin told police officers and the Dominican taxi
driver who spotted him standing on a Bronx highway and put him up
for the night that his mother had been killed in Hurricane Mitch
and he had traveled to New York to try and find a father he had
never seen. In fact, his relatives later said, it is the boy's
father, Grevis Sabillon, who is dead.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview shortly after Edwin's hoax was uncovered, Mrs.
Hernandez said that she wanted Edwin to return to Honduras, but
that she did not want him back in her home: ``I'll put him in
reform school until he straightens out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora Rodriguez, Edwin's aunt in Hialeah, Fla., where he stayed
for two months after running away from his grandmother's home in
the spring and before coming to New York, has said publicly that
she also does not want him back. But Ms. Wiener said the
Administration for Children's Services was still hopeful that Edwin
would find a suitable home with relatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
