u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MR-PEANUT-AD-COLUMN-N     07-13 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MR-PEANUT-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. PEANUT, PARTY ANIMAL AND PITCHMAN, BACK IN THE LIMELIGHT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:   Va., N.J, Pa.)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the commercial for Almond Joy and Mounds candies that
declared, ``Sometimes you feel like a nut; sometimes you don't?''
Well, an advertising character that feels like a nut all the time _
because he is one _ is helping to increase sales for a venerable
brand.
</P>
<P>
   The character is Mr. Peanut, created in 1916 by a Virginia
school boy, Anthony Gentile, who won $5 in a contest for his
drawing of a ``little peanut person.'' After a commercial artist
added the elements that made Mr. Peanut a dapper society legume,
like his top hat, monocle and cane, the character has served as the
symbol of the Planters brand.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Mr. Peanut played a prominent part in advertising
and promotional efforts for Planters. For instance, consumers could
save package wrappers that could be redeemed for merchandise like
cups, banks, mechanical pencils, even a ``fascinating and
beautiful'' Mr. Peanut rag doll. But more recently the
spindly-legged character had been relegated to a supporting role in
keeping with a general trend to play down longtime brand icons that
were perceived as outdated or irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Mr. Peanut is reassuming a central place in the
Planters marketing pantheon. His comeback echoes those of
characters like Mr. Whipple, for Charmin bathroom tissue; Buddy
Lee, for Lee jeans, and Charlie the tuna, for Star-Kist. The goal
is to capitalize on nostalgia among older shoppers as well as the
trend for ``retro-chic'' styles among the young.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Planters and its agency, Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding in
New York, say it is no coincidence that the Mr. Peanut revival has
been accompanied by a surge in sales for Planters nuts and snacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make nuts more appealing as an everyday snack
rather than for a special occasion,'' said David Yale, vice
president and general manager of the Planters Co. in Parsippany,
N.J., part of the Nabisco Inc. unit of Nabisco Group Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research shows Mr. Peanut to be seen as a regular guy,
everyman,'' he added, ``with qualities that appeal across a wide
range of demographic and socioeconomic groups.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mr. Peanut is considered ``a party animal, but
dignified,'' Yale said. ``And people, especially younger people,
realize that his appearance is meant to be tongue-in-cheek, with a
fun edge.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he added, the character has become ``a leverage
point to talk about the quality, taste and fun that separate us
from other nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Information Resources Inc., a market research
company, sales of Planters packaged nuts in food and drug stores
and mass-merchandise outlets for the 52 weeks ending June 6 totaled
$610.4 million, up 13.3 percent from sales in the period a year
earlier. That outpaced the total category's growth rate of 9.2
percent, to sales of $1.4 billion. The Planters share of market was
42.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at sales for only 1999, the momentum seemed to
accelerate. Planters sales through June 6 rose to $270.4 million,
up 16.6 percent from figures in the period a year earlier, again
outpacing the total category's growth rate, which was a 13.5
percent increase, to $623.3 million. The Planters share of market
rose, too, to 43.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though Mr. Peanut has always been identified with the brand,
over the years he has been dialed up or down to different
degrees,'' said Bill McDonough, executive vice president and
worldwide account director for Nabisco at Foote, Cone New York, a
unit of True North Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Mr. Peanut conjures up Planters,'' he added. ``So we've
dialed Mr. Peanut up.''
</P>
<P>
   Foote, Cone, which has handled the Planters account since 1995,
introduced the current theme, ``Relax. Go nuts'' in 1997. Then,
beginning last year, Mr. Peanut stepped back into the limelight
with initiatives like a colorful oversized billboard in Times
Square, appearances on Max Racks postcard ads distributed in bars
and restaurants, a star turn on the Planters Web site
(www.planters.com), a cross-country tour of ``Mr. Peanut's Hot
Rod'' to publicize the Planters sponsorship of NASCAR races and a
``Find Mr. Peanut'' promotion on packages.
</P>
<P>
   The Planters ad budget was increased significantly, too,
according to Competitive Media Reporting, a unit of VNU NV that
tracks ad spending, to $9.5 million in 1998 from $2.7 million in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Another big step for the character was a television commercial
last year by Foote, Cone New York that took an unusual twist to
demonstrate devotion to Mr. Peanut _ and by extension the Planters
brand.
</P>
<P>
   The spot showed three men walking in the woods who feed a nut to
a beaver. In gratitude, the animal carves a likeness of Mr. Peanut
from the trunk of a tree. ``Think that'll fit in the van?'' one man
asks another admiringly. That commercial has since been followed by
two more, featuring a woodpecker and a dog that also pay homage to
Mr. Peanut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sought to understand Mr. Peanut and what liberties we
should and should not take with him,'' McDonough said. ``There is a
certain integrity to him, as amusing as that sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mr. Peanut never speaks, nor is he made to behave in a
faddish manner. There is no Ms. Peanut nor a rapping Master Peanutz
dressed in baggy jeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Peanut is a wonderful, powerful tool,'' said Ted
Littleford, executive vice president and executive creative
director at Foote, Cone New York. ``We're using him now as a true
icon, as the physical manifestation of the need for peanuts, as if
this subconscious desire for peanuts is exposed through his
appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Littleford said, laughing, ``Mr. Peanut's attire is
coming back,'' citing the sartorial style of the actor Rupert
Everett in the film ``An Ideal Husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Peanut's renewal is being welcomed ardently by members of a
national group of his aficionados known as Peanut Pals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a warm fuzzy in a world of guns and bombings,'' said
Joyce Spontak, a member who is the co-author of two books on
``Planters Peanut Collectibles'' (Schiffer Publishing Ltd., 1995)
and has thousands of items in a ``museum room'' in her home in
Bridgeville, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oddly enough, I have a father-in-law who you can't even give a
cap with a company name on it,'' Mrs. Spontak said. ``He says: `I'm
not getting any money. Why should I be a billboard?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think of Mr. Peanut as promoting the company.''
she continued. ``It's my link to the past, to my grandmother, who
would send away wrappers for anything for her grandchildren. And
it's my link to the future because I'm getting my grandchildren
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   As Mr. Peanut gets ready to enter the 21st century, the Times
Square billboard will come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be there, celebrating the millennium,'' McDonough said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
