<HEADLINE>
34 CHEFS IN FRANCE CONVICTED OF CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
 (yn) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The inmates of Sante Prison in Paris probably don't know
how close they came to culinary heaven Tuesday when 34 chefs,
including some of the best in Paris, were convicted of corruption
in the kitchen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the cooks escaped with fines instead of jail terms and will
not be pursuing their profession behind bars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Martinez, now chef of the Relais Louis XIII with one star
(``a very good table in its category'') in the prestigious Michelin
Guide, said he would probably appeal the $10,000 fine he were
ordered to pay for having accepted what he called ``tips'' from a
fish supplier when he was cooking at the Tour d'Argent in the early
1990s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody got rich,'' Martinez said dismissively from his kitchen
Tuesday night. ``We spread it around among the staff. It was a kind
of tradition in the business to create good will. It's not as if it
was public money and these were kickbacks.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christian Constant, who has two-star recognition (``excellent
table, worth a detour'') from Michelin in this year's guide for
dishes like salad of scallops with truffles and Parmesan cheese at
his Violon d'Ingres, was fined $12,250 for taking envelopes from
the business that supplied fish to the prestigious Les Ambassadeurs
in the Hotel Crillon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Constant could not be reached for comment. Other chefs fined
included Philippe Renard of Lutetia on the Left Bank and Guy Legay,
the chef at the Ritz Hotel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale fishmongers Patrick and Claudine Perrin, whose
company was called Scotfish when culinary corruption came under
scrutiny by Judge Eric Halphen, one of the investigating
magistrates who have turned French business practices upside-down
over the last 10 years, got suspended six-month jail terms and
$15,400 fines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guy Nicolas, their lawyer, said the verdict by a criminal court
in suburban Creteil that found his clients guilty of active
corruption and their customers answerable for the passive version
of the same crime, was ``neither fish nor fowl.''
</P>
</TEXT>
