<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8825 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-TAXES-HNS &LR;      07-13 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TAXES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHER UNVEILS $864 BILLION TAX-CUTTING PLAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer
presented his much-anticipated, $864 billion tax-cutting package to
Congress on Tuesday, with a plan to raise the standard deduction
for married couples as a way to deal with the so-called ``marriage
penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton repeated his call for Republicans to pare
down their tax package, while House Democrats scoffed at Archer's
plan as an unrealistic political manifesto with no chance of
becoming law.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, the chief tax writer in the House, unveiled a bill that
would lower taxes for corporations, abolish the alternative minimum
tax and allow employees to shelter more income in 401(k) plans.
</P>
<P>
   Loaded with these and other tax changes popular with
Republicans, the Texas Republican's bill is expected to sail
unscathed through committee this week and then go to the House
floor for a vote, sometime by end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats plan to launch a counteroffensive in the House,
they are not expected to muster enough votes to block its passage.
</P>
<P>
   Over in the Senate, Finance Committee Chairman William Roth,
R-Del., has drafted a substantially different bill, which would
slash taxes by about $792 billion. That measure has attracted at
least some Democratic support.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House, which favors a far more modest tax cut on
the order of $250 billion, has threatened to veto any tax-cutting
plan the size of the Republican bills.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking Tuesday at a Communication Workers of America
convention in Miami, argued lawmakers should shore up Social
Security, put Medicare on a more sound financial footing and pay
off the national debt within the next 15 years before undertaking
such a huge tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``If America is on a path to becoming debt-free, interest rates
will be lower,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats, emboldened by hopes of recapturing the House in
the next election and cognizant of Archer's intention to retire at
the end of next year, dismissed his tax package as a political bone
to Republican loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tax bill is not going to be signed into law,'' said Rep.
Benjamin Cardin, D-Md. ``It's not real.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, called the proposal ``Republican
fiscal irresponsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer, arguing for the need to reduce taxes as a way to curb
the power of the federal government, pointed to figures that
suggest the average American household stands to pay $5,300 more in
federal taxes than the government will need to pay its bills over
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not right,'' Archer said. ``Americans shouldn't be
working for Washington. Washington should be working for them.''
</P>
<P>
   While many details of his tax bill have trickled out over the
last week Archer revealed plans Tuesday to eliminate the highly
unpopular marriage penalty, the aspect of the tax code that forces
many dual-income couples to pay more in taxes than they would if
they were filing as singles.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's proposal would increase the standard deduction for
married couples filing jointly from the current $7,200 a year to
$8,600. The standard deduction for married couples would then be
twice the deduction allowed for single filers.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would benefit about 21 million couples, saving the
average family about $243 a year in taxes, Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   That provision, however, would not just help those couples hit
by the marriage penalty _ typically those in which both partners
contribute at least 40 percent of the family income _ but any
couple taking the standard deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's office estimates 6 million families that currently
itemize would be able to simplify their tax reporting requirements
by taking the standard deduction instead.
</P>
<P>
   Roth has offered a different strategy to get rid of the marriage
penalty. His proposal would allow married taxpayers to file joint
returns as if they were single filers to dodge the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's tax package also would reduce over 10 years the capital
gains tax rate corporations pay on investments, from the current 35
percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Archer proposed reducing the top capital gains rate
individuals pay from 20 percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   His bill also would eliminate the alternative minimum tax _ the
tax wealthier individuals and corporations with a large number of
deductions are forced to pay to ensure they send Washington at
least some cash.
</P>
<P>
   His bill also would allow employees who are currently able to
shelter up to $10,000 a year in a 401(k) savings plan to increase
that contribution to $15,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
