<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-CANDIDATES-NO-MOR     07-13 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CANDIDATES-NO-MORE-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 CANDIDATES BOW OUT OF GOP PRESIDENTIAL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, N.H., Texas, Ariz., Kan., Ind. Utah, Md., Miss.,
Ore.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seven months before the first votes are cast, two
Republican presidential candidates are dropping out because of Gov.
George W. Bush's dominance of the race.
</P>
<P>
   One, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, faced with the reality that his
campaign had not taken off, seems ready and willing to embrace
Bush's success. The nine-term lawmaker will formally withdraw on
Wednesday and endorse Bush, Republican officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the other, Sen. Robert Smith of N.H., excoriated the
Republicans, saying they had become too willing to compromise their
principles in pursuit of victory. He announced that he was leaving
the Republican Party and would run for president as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   Both are staunch conservatives and both are getting more
attention by pulling out of the race and going their separate ways
than they ever did while in it. The contrasting decisions, from two
long-shot candidates who had been struggling in single digits in
the polls, go to the heart of the turmoil within the G.O.P. to
regain control of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The development leaves 10 Republicans vying for their party's
nomination: Bush, the governor of Texas; Sen. John McCain of
Arizona; Elizabeth Dole, the former head of the Red Cross; former
Vice President Dan Quayle; Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah; Lamar
Alexander, a former education secretary; Steve Forbes, a
multimillionaire publisher; Alan Keyes, a former diplomat; Gary
Bauer, the former head of the Family Research Council; and Patrick
Buchanan, the conservative commentator.
</P>
<P>
   Bush solidified his claim as the front-runner in the race nearly
two weeks ago with record fund-raising of more than $36 million for
the first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich, chairman of the House Budget Committee for the past five
years, has wielded enormous influence over the spending cuts
championed by Republicans, as well as their plan to balance the
budget. He had hoped to run a populist campaign built on a
foundation of fiscal responsibility, but could not keep pace
financially with Bush, Republican officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich has clashed with fellow Republicans before, notably over
how to balance tax cuts and reductions in the federal deficit. But
as his own presidential dream faded, he became a loyal foot soldier
and took up Bush's banner, Republican aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman and his campaign aides declined to comment
Tuesday, waiting until Kasich's formal announcement on Wednesday,
first in Columbus, Ohio, and then in Washington, the second
occurring with Bush at his side.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith's bolt from the Republican Party, most likely to seek
the nomination of the U.S. Taxpayers Party, underscores how
third-party candidacies have gained momentum in recent weeks among
conservatives who accuse Bush and party officials of failing to be
sufficiently conservative on issues like gun control, abortion and
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to clean out the pollsters and the consultants and the
spin doctors and the bloated staffs who tell us what to say, how to
say it, when to say it and how long to say it,'' Smith said in a
nearly hour-long speech on the Senate floor. His comments drew only
about a dozen Republican senators and a smattering of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who has also been considering a third-party run, said,
``When a man as conservative and principled as Bob Smith walks away
from the Republican Party, perhaps the problem is not with Senator
Smith but with the Republican establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the Republican Party's national chairman, and
other top party officials fear that third-party candidates, even
those attracting only negligible support, could still siphon off
precious votes from the Republican nominee in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Nicholson criticized Smith's plans and urged him to
stay, saying in a letter that his decision was shortsighted and
would only help Vice President Al Gore, ``the most extreme liberal
in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Smith's chairmanship of the Senate Ethics
Committee and his seniority in the Senate Republican hierarchy
seemed imperiled. ``It'd be very hard to be running with another
party label and chairing a committee at the same time,'' said
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Smith told reporters Tuesday afternoon: ``I'm prepared for
whatever judgment is handed to me. I'm not a Republican any
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   But by late Tuesday, the momentum was shifting his way. Angered
by Nicholson's biting remarks and worried that stripping Smith's
chairmanship would seem vindictive and divide the party further,
Senate Republicans supported Smith's political perks even as they
assailed his political decision.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We're not the party of punishment,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas. Moments later, Lott backed off his earlier remarks, joking
how difficult it was to get senators to join the Ethics Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, few Senate Republicans who back Bush saw Smith as a
serious threat _ regardless of his party label. ``George Bush is
conservative enough for 99 percent of our party,'' said Sen. Gordon
Smith of Oregon. ``For every vote you chase at that end of our
spectrum, you'll lose two at the center.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
