<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8834 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-MUSIC-2TAKES-$     07-13 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MP3 REVOLUTION: GETTING WITH IT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just a year ago, writing an article about MP3 meant going into
elaborate detail in defining the technology.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the term _ shorthand for the 1992 formula used to
compress audio into manageable, easy-to-share computer files _ had
been mentioned in only four articles in this newspaper; since then,
it has been mentioned in more than 85, becoming a part of the
entertainment vocabulary almost as quickly as the name Lewinsky
became part of the political one.
</P>
<P>
   But in the many media reports about the record industry's
crackdown on the proliferation of illicit MP3s, the more
copyright-friendly alternatives being developed behind closed doors
and the many trumpeted agreements between recording labels,
technology companies and Internet start-ups, what has been
consistently overlooked _ even in the new MP3 issue of Wired
magazine _ is the message of the medium.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the future, but now: most of the recent controversy about
on-line music has been over how it is going to change the
experience of selling and purchasing music, but much more
interesting is the question of how it is changing our experience of
listening to and handling the music.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to music on the Internet is not simply a novel
alternative to CD players or a way to use the computer as a
separate but equal stereo system. Nor is it an opportunity to level
the playing field _ as utopians like to dream _ and allow all
musicians, great and small, access to all listeners mainstream and
marginal.
</P>
<P>
   It is a key to unlocking the restrictions that all audio storage
media before them have posed to musicians and fans. The CD was a
medium similar enough to a record that one could still call it an
album without being corrected. But with the Internet, the idea of
the album is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the CD did wreak its own changes, and not just in
the acoustic differences between analog and digital sound. Making
an album no longer meant coming up with 45 minutes of music,
conceptualized into two sets of five or so songs, each side
self-sufficient enough to stand on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it meant coming up with 60 to 70-something minutes of
songs, arranging them in a long ebb and flow and then maybe
throwing on a few leftover scraps as bonuses at the end. Creating
memorable artwork was no longer done in the painterly
two-dimensional space of an album cover or a gatefold sleeve, but
in the sculptural three-dimensional package and the choice of
materials used.
</P>
<P>
   And listening was a completely new experience: no longer were we
beholden to the flipping of sides every 22 minutes, but we could
put five or a hundred CDs into a player and shuffle and rearrange
the track order _ or just hit random and let the technology decide.
</P>
<P>
   As a musical format, the Internet is a much cooler medium. It
enables users to have multiple sound systems, to watch visual
displays synchronized to the music, to talk to other people
listening to the same Internet radio station, to make compilations
of favorite songs with a few mouse clicks, to e-mail a song to a
disk jockey to play, and to put a CD into a computer and, with the
click of a button, access digital liner notes.
</P>
<P>
   The list could go on and on, and this is only the beginning of
the medium's evolution. With those who originally created much of
these capabilities falling prey to new industry regulations,
lawsuits and takeovers, it may also be the medium's creative summit
as well.
</P>
<P>
   With faster and better-sounding alternatives already available
or in development, there is little doubt that MP3 _ developed by a
multinational committee as an open standard free to anyone _ is a
transitional format. But it is MP3 that has the versatility and
added functions that make it more forward-looking than its more
proprietary corporate rivals developed by Real Networks, Liquid
Audio, Microsoft, AT&AMP;T and Lucent.
</P>
<P>
   Bypassing the financial implications, the biggest change on-line
music distribution brings to those who make music is that it frees
them from the constraints of a platter, disk or cassette that holds
limited information and costs money and time to manufacture and
ship. A new studio recording could be a 3-minute song or a 24-hour
music cycle intended to accompany the listener throughout an entire
day.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions made by bands in the on-line world no longer
involve sequencing 70 minutes of songs, but determining at what
rate new music should be released to fans and in what amount.
</P>
<P>
   This scenario is slightly futuristic, because the medium of the
Internet won't change the message of the music until it becomes the
dominant form of distributing music (or at least a new market on
par with record stores). For now we will concentrate on the
present, on the hunter-gatherer experience of using the Internet
and computer as record store, record album and stereo.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, it's best to walk you through the process. So, if
you are reading this and you own a PC with a halfway decent
Internet connection, follow the instructions below and within an
hour or two you will have a completely free state-of-the-art
Internet stereo system that might explain what an MP3 player's got
that a CD player doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, you need software to play MP3s on your PC. I'd
suggest downloading two software players, Winamp (www.winamp.com)
and Sonique (www.sonique.com). The Winamp is the most commonly used
MP3 player, and many of the most interesting free MP3 programs on
the Internet are only compatible with Winamp; Sonique is more
self-contained, easier to operate and beautifully designed in
adjustable sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to a stereo, in addition to playing songs, both offer a
wide-band graphic equalizer, the shuffle capabilities of a CD
player, VU meters and spectrum analyzers, volume and balance
controls, and, in the case of Sonique, pitch control so that you
can change the speed of the song being played.
</P>
<P>
   Next, you'll want to download what are called skins and
plug-ins, most of them created not by entrepreneurs but by random
computer users as young as 11 years old. Skins are faceplates that
cover your MP3 player like masks, creating a visual appearance of
your choice.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds to choose from, and you can switch between
them as often as you want: you can have a Star Wars MP3 player, a
Britney Spears one, a wooden-looking stereo, a high-tech interface,
or you can scan your favorite image, design a skin yourself and
e-mail it to Winamp or Sonique for other MP3 users to download.
</P>
<P>
   Plug-ins are more exciting supplemental programs, ways to
personalize and soup up your MP3 player. The best of these allow
you to operate your Winamp with a remote control, add effects like
reverb to the music, search for and display song lyrics as you
listen, or match the beats on two different MP3 files and mix them
together like a D.J.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the visual plug-ins, the Internet equivalent of
cover art. These are programs in which waves, fractals, wallpaper
patterns, animated characters and all kinds of images dance and
morph on your computer screen in response to the rhythm, amplitude
and frequencies of a song as it's being played.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have a fully loaded MP3 player brimming with skins and
plug-ins, you'll need music. A number of search engines capable of
scouring the Web for MP3 files have been built.
</P>
<P>
   These include mp3.lycos.com, www.audiofind.com,
www.audioseek.com or the mega-search engine www.palavista.com,
which tend not to differentiate between legitimate sites and
fly-by-night pirates and thus often lead to dead ends.
</P>
<P>
   For beginners, it's better to start at www.scour.net or the
newer www.listen.com, both of which have limited but very reliable
archives of legal music. If you can't find what you're looking for
at any of these sites, you can always go to the newsgroup
alt.binaries.sounds.mp3.requests and post a message naming the
album or song you're looking for and chances are someone will post
it for you within a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Often an easier alternative to downloading music is streaming
music, or listening to music live in real time. This is the
province of Internet radio stations, which, in a medium as
democratic as the Web, are about as numerous as Internet radio
listeners. (All you have to do to start broadcasting is download a
special Winamp plug-in from www.shoutcast.com). There are a number
of good sites housing hundreds of radio stations, chief among them
www.shoutcast.com and icecast.linuxpower.org.
</P>
<P>
   But to better appreciate the advantage Internet radio has over
college radio stations, go to www.mp3spy.com and download the
program MP3spy. Once loaded, MP3spy will arrange Internet radio
stations by genre and let you know what song is playing, how many
people are listening and the quality of the transmission. While
listening, not only can you talk with other listeners and the D.J.,
but you can also send the disk jockey songs to play.
</P>
<P>
   To send your favorite songs to a D.J., you'll need the next
component of your Internet stereo system: the ``record'' button,
also known as the CD ripper, which enables you to turn CDs (or
records or cassettes or random noise recorded into a microphone)
into MP3 files. The best of these also serve as CD players and
jukeboxes, searching the Web as soon as you insert a CD and letting
you know the track sequence and recording notes.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are many of these programs, one favorite is
Musicmatch 4.0 (at www.musicmatch.com). Most users prefer to make
MP3 files from Real Audio's very quick, versatile and efficient
Real Jukebox. But one problem with Real Audio software is that it
is a bully, always trying to kick all other music software off your
desktop and then pop up at the ready whenever your computer starts
to do anything vaguely musical.
</P>
<P>
   So, with your MP3 player, your skins and plug-ins, your CD
ripper and your Internet radio connections, what have you learned?
Beside the fact that integrating the pieces of your MP3 software
and developing a system for downloading music and maintaining a
playlist can be a nuisance akin to finding the jewel boxes for the
disks in a 100-CD changer, you've learned that there is a whole
universe that already exists on line built around the MP3.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a world of pirated music, as the record industry would
have you believe, but one in which you can choose and design the
look and feel of your music player, the lengths and types of
compilations you want to make for yourself, and the interactive
visuals that accompany the sound.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the main difference between the MP3 and the CD is not
that the music is on line instead of in stores, it's that the MP3
is not packaged, perfected and made easy to use by an industry
before being given to consumers. The technology is open-ended and
evolving, which means that the message is that the medium is putty
and, for now, as a listener you can mold it in any way you want.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
