<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGED-CARE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP PREVAILS ON 'PATIENTS' BILL OF RIGHTS' AMENDMENTS
 &HT;    630&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans prevailed on largely party-line votes
Tuesday as the Senate began voting on amendments to legislation
regulating health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The votes, which seemed to indicate that a GOP version of the
``patients' bill of rights'' legislation would be approved later
this week, prompted Democrats to charge that the bill would only
protect insurance companies and managed care organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Voting on more amendments is scheduled to continue Wednesday and
be completed late Thursday, when Republicans will have an
opportunity to offer their own substitute bill for a final vote.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., told
reporters Tuesday that the final substitute could differ from a
Republican-sponsored version approved on a party-line committee
vote in March. The spokesman did not indicate what changes might be
made to the GOP version.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, President Clinton joined Senate Democratic
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., and a group of health organization
leaders in attacking the Republican bill at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the GOP bill ``is watered down, it is nowhere near
what the American people deserve or need. Not only does it offer
merely toothless and half-hearted protections, it fails to protect
all Americans in managed care.''
</P>
<P>
   Disagreements Tuesday focused on whether health care decisions
would ultimately be controlled by doctors or insurers and on how
much tighter regulation would increase insurance costs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the Democrats claimed that a recent Congressional
Budget Office study indicated their version would raise insurance
premiums by less than $2 a month, but Republicans argued that the
same study predicted premiums would jump more than 6 percent and
cause more than 1.8 million people to lose or be denied health
insurance when the bill was fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Offering an amendment that would block the Democratic bill,
Senate Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla., proposed that if
premiums increased by more than 1 percent or the number of
uninsured people increased by more than 100,000 when the bill was
fully implemented, its provisions would be suspended. That
amendment was adopted 52-48 with three GOP senators _ John Chafee,
R-R.I., Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill, and Arlen Specter, R-Pa., _
joining the unanimous Democrats in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter partisan debate was highlighted on the first
amendment offered. The Senate rejected, 48-52, a Democratic
proposal to allow women to designate their
obstetrician-gynecologist as their primary care doctor and allow
women to remain in the hospital as long as their doctor recommended
after a mastectomy. Chafee, Specter and Sen. John Warner, R-Va.,
joined the unanimous Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Several female Democratic senators angrily denounced the vote as
an affront to women and a display of insensitivity to their special
health needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we saw what compassionate conservatism pretends to be.
It's not compassionate, but it is conservative,'' said Sen. Barbara
Mikulski, D-Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a woman, I'm angered and appalled,'' said Sen. Patty
Murray, D-Wash. Sen. Mary Landrieu, D-La., said virtually every
woman over the age of puberty ``knows that an ob/gyn is their
primary care physician.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also rejected, 47-53, an amendment by Sen. Bob
Graham, D-Fla., that would have require insurers and HMOs to cover
patients who sought care in an emergency room if they had a
reasonable belief that their life was in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., said the amendment was flawed
because it would have required insurers to cover post-stabilization
care not related to the cause of emergency treatment. Chafee and
Specter joined the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Senate adopted two Republican amendments over unanimous
Democratic objections.
</P>
<P>
   On a 52-48 vote the Senate approved a GOP plan for creating
external and internal panels to consider appeals from patients if
an HMO denied coverage or treatment. Democrats argued that the
amendment did not go far enough because it would base appeals on
HMO definitions of what treatments were medically necessary.
Chafee, Fitzgerald and Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., joined the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   On a 53-47 vote, the Senate approved an amendment to provide
full tax deductibility of insurance premiums by the self-employed.
Democrats argued that they already had supported a similar
amendment but noted that the GOP proposal would reduce the number
of Americans covered by the Patient's Bill of Rights. They argued
that most HMO patients would not be covered by the bill under the
GOP amendment. Chafee and Specter joined the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
