<SLUG> BC-CONDUCTORS-MUSIC-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REHEARING SZELL: INTENSITY WITHOUT PONDEROUSNESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID SCHIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a time when so many orchestras and conductors are changing
partners, it is good to be reminded of the artistic benefits of
retaining a long-term maestro. One such reminder comes in the form
of a Sony Classical reissue of two classic recordings by the
Cleveland Orchestra under the direction of George Szell:
Prokofiev's Fifth Symphony, recorded in 1959, and Bartok's Concerto
for Orchestra, recorded in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   These performances may not induce discophiles to part with their
version of the Prokofiev by Herbert von Karajan or of the Bartok by
Fritz Reiner, but both offer orchestral playing of breathtaking
refinement while challenging the notion that Szell was a dour
taskmaster and an interpretive literalist.
</P>
<P>
   Composed during World War II, the Prokofiev and Bartok works
have remained popular for more than 50 years because of their
powerful expression, each in its own way, of wartime anxiety,
despair, humor and hope, although routine performances often reduce
both to generic applause generators.
</P>
<P>
   Szell treated both pieces with the interpretive respect he more
famously gave to Mozart. Not that his respect kept him from a bit
of creative tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   The two performances (Masterworks Heritage MHK 63124; CD)
display the Cleveland hallmark: a level of ensemble usually found
only in the greatest string quartets. The flawless but never
soulless execution of phrasing and dynamics is perhaps most obvious
in the Bartok, which spotlights one section of the orchestra after
another.
</P>
<P>
   But the thickly scored Prokofiev symphony occasions an even more
impressive exercise of orchestral ESP. Throughout the symphony,
Prokofiev scores melodic lines for players in different, often
physically distant instrumental families.
</P>
<P>
   These organlike mixed colors are essential to the dark, brooding
character of the first movement as well as to the triumphant close
of the last, but they can be destroyed by the slightest degree of
a-synchrony. Here the instrumental colors fuse perfectly, as the
musicians show the utmost care in intonation, balance and the
shaping of phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Prokofiev's Fifth abounds in notational ambiguities and, for all
its epic scope, often feels like an improvisation. The opening
movement is marked Andante, but the metronome mark of 48 suggests
adagio, or slower. The contrasting theme of this movement feels as
though it wants to go faster than the opening, but how much?
Prokofiev says only ``poco piu mosso'': a little faster.
</P>
<P>
   Karajan (on Deutsche Grammophon) begins very slowly, lending the
opening a portentous gravity that exerts its pull even as the tempo
quickens. Szell's faster, lighter opening gives little indication
of the drama to come; instead, it serves to start the musical line
in motion, setting up a momentum that becomes ever more propulsive
as the movement unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   When the tightly controlled rhythmic tension is finally
released, at the end of the second and fourth movements, the
performance achieves a heart-pounding state of exhilaration.
</P>
<P>
   Szell is often termed a Classicist, but that does not mean that
he was a miniaturist. His control of the musical line, which made
him an eminent Mozartean, also produced some of the greatest
performances of late Romantic repertory, like the Cleveland
Orchestra's renditions of Strauss' ``Death and Transfiguration''
and Mahler's Sixth Symphony (both available in inexpensive reissues
from Sony Classical). This Prokofiev Fifth is no less impressive as
a model of intensity without ponderousness, the Szell-Cleveland
style.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bartok, Szell's approach is again idiosyncratic and, at
one crucial point, seemingly perverse. As its name implies, the
Concerto for Orchestra is full of solos for nearly every
instrument, and Szell, functioning like an opera conductor, often
sets a tempo slower than expected, allowing the players to shape
their solos; listen to the wistful tenderness of the flute solo at
the opening, played by Maurice Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Szell holds back the tempo for the big brass fanfare in this
movement, a passage that often sounds like background music for an
army recruitment movie, so that you can hear each player's
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Even more divergent from other performances is the fugato of the
finale, which Szell takes much slower than normal, bringing out the
peasant humor of its hen-scratch repeated notes. Then he indulges
his interpretive license with a cut that may sour this performance
for some listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Bartok's finale seems to end several times, and indeed, the
score offers two alternative conclusions. Szell evidently felt that
the problem was not the ending itself but a penultimate passage,
which he skips. His excision is shocking the first time you hear
it, but it has a harmonic logic that becomes convincing; the
fourfold repeat of a phrase before the cut, on the other hand, is
clumsy and un-Bartokian. Even Homer nods, and so did even George
Szell.
</P>
<P>
   The album notes relate a story that at once confirms and
challenges the standard picture of Szell's forbidding personality.
Cloyd Duff, the Cleveland Orchestra's legendary timpanist, recounts
that before recording the Bartok, Szell called him up and said,
``Cloyd, I want you to play that snare-drum part.''
</P>
<P>
   A snare-drum solo opens and closes the second movement. Duff
pointed out to Szell that he would be stepping on the toes of the
other percussionists, but Szell insisted that only Duff had the
technique to make the diminuendo called for in the score.
</P>
<P>
   The story illustrates Szell's fanatical concern for musical
detail, if not for human feelings, but it is also the first account
I have heard in which Szell called an orchestral player by his
first name. Perhaps he wasn't quite the monster he was made out to
be. With performances like these, listeners may not care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
