<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESENDEZ-RAMIREZ WENT FROM `MINOR CRIMINAL ... TO WHERE HE IS
TODAY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ From an unremarkable beginning, Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez evolved into an international fugitive whose
suspected crimes near rail lines changed the way people went to bed
at night.
</P>
<P>
   Born Angel Leoncio Reyes-Resendiz on Aug. 1, 1959, in the
Mexican state of Puebla, Resendez-Ramirez was raised by an uncle
whose name he is now known by. It is one of 30 aliases he has used
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to the Mexican state of Durango when his mother married
a soldier in the Mexican army. He was his mother's favorite child,
her ``beautiful little baby.'' Friends and family, including his
common-law wife, said after he became a suspect that they could not
believe he was capable of murder.
</P>
<P>
   But from an early age, Resendez-Ramirez spent most of his life
as a petty criminal. He frequently crossed the U.S.-Mexico border
illegally beginning on Aug. 31, 1976, when he was arrested by U.S.
border agents in Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   The last reported arrest came June 1, when he was arrested by
the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service in Santa Teresa,
N.M. By then, he had already been linked to three slayings, but
unaware U.S. officials deported him to Ciudad Juarez, across the
border from El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, police say, Resendez-Ramirez would return to
the United States and claim his fifth victim. Hours later, he would
take his sixth. Before the month ended, he would be included on the
FBI's Ten Most Wanted list and be the subject of an intense
manhunt. Thus far, Resendez-Ramirez has been linked to at least
eight slayings in three states.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not linked Resendez-Ramirez to any killings
prior to 1997. And what has remained puzzling about the once
elusive serial killer is why, after 20 years in and out of jail for
nonviolent crimes, Resendez-Ramirez would begin to kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the impression that he was a minor criminal, and I don't
know when he made the transition to where he is today,'' said
Georges Scott, spokesman for the New Mexico Department of
Corrections, where Resendez served six months for a March 1992
burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez has traveled coast-to-coast, from Seattle to
Miami and San Bernardino, Calif., to South Burlington, Vt. He
mainly traveled by freight trains like a hobo.
</P>
<P>
   He told his wife, the mother of their 3-month-old daughter, that
he picked oranges in Florida, asparagus in Washington and tobacco
in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez is known as Angel Maturino Recendez in Rodeo,
Durango, where he moved with his family in the 1990s. Those who
know him in Rodeo describe him as quiet and introverted. They say
he likes dogs, that he often shows up driving late-model cars that
he gives to relatives or sells.
</P>
<P>
   But as Resendez-Ramirez, authorities say, the serial killer
wasn't commonly known until the Dec. 17 slaying of Dr. Claudia
Benton of West University Place, an affluent enclave of Houston. He
was linked to the slaying by a fingerprint found on a steering
column broken off the victim's Jeep Cherokee and lying on the
garage floor.
</P>
<P>
   He subsequently was linked to four more deaths in Texas, two in
Illinois and another in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez was arrested in Miami in 1979 for breaking into
a house and beating the homeowner while attempting to steal his car
keys. He was tried for burglary, aggravated battery and grand
theft, and received a 20-year sentence. He was released in 1985
from a facility in Glades, Fla., after serving sentences in a
series of Florida prisons.
</P>
<P>
   His criminal career continued.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his release from the Western New Mexico Correctional
Facility in Grants, N.M., on April 30, 1993, Resendez-Ramirez would
be arrested twice more: five weeks later in Carson County, not far
from Amarillo, by a Texas Department of Public Safety trooper; and
on Aug. 19, 1995, in San Bernardino, Calif., by Santa Fe Railroad
police for trespassing and carrying a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   After he was supposedly spotted a month ago in a Louisville,
Ky., homeless shelter, Resendez-Ramirez disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
