<HEADLINE>
SERB OPPOSITION LEADER NOW PLANS PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ A powerful opposition politician
announced Tuesday that he would call his supporters into the
streets in an effort to topple President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the opposition leader, Vuk Draskovic, to
mobilize members of his Serbian Renewal Movement Party was made
after weeks of abstaining from street protests. Demonstrations
associated with another opposition group have recently been held in
towns in southern and northern Serbia to protest Milosevic's
government.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic is one of the most unpredictable and mercurial
political leaders here. He has swung in the last 10 years from an
embrace of Serbian nationalism, even leading Serbian militias in
Bosnia, to calls for a Western-style democracy. He was thrown out
of Milosevic's government during the NATO bombing campaign after
public denunciations of Milosevic's leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
