<SLUG> BC-DRUG-TRIALS-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH OFFICIALS EXAMINING CLINICAL TRIALS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Calif.)   (jw) 
 By KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal health investigators have begun two separate inquiries
to determine whether the rapidly changing system for clinical
trials, particularly in industry-sponsored research, properly
protects the interests of patients and other potential test
subjects, according to government officials and documents.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiries, conducted by June Gibbs Brown, inspector general
of the Department of Health and Human Services, are focusing on two
areas: the recruitment practices in research sponsored by the drug
industry and the system of oversight used to detect possible fraud
by clinical investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The examinations follow drastic changes in the clinical trials
system, which in just the last decade was largely based in academic
medical institutions and conducted by professional researchers. But
it has now become a multibillion-dollar industry, with hundreds of
testing and drug companies working with thousands of private
doctors who mine their patient lists for test subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry into recruitment will focus on just that change,
government officials said. The inspector general's office plans to
examine the use of private doctors in research and whether that
creates any conflicts between the doctor's obligations to the
patient and responsibilities to the drug company sponsoring the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the inspector general's office will examine the
use of financial incentives to encourage doctors to speed up
patient recruitment, including payments made for each patient
signed up as a test subject and bonuses used to encourage the
recruitment of a particular number of patients.
</P>
<P>
   By conducting this inquiry, government officials said, federal
health investigators hope to identify recruiting practices that
appear questionable, to determine what guidelines exist on
recruitment and what difficulties the industry faces in recruiting
patients in a timely manner.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish these goals, the inspector general's office plans
to gather information several ways. Those include conducting
in-depth visits at investigative sites in three large cities,
accompanying inspectors with the Food and Drug Administration on
required reviews of both investigators and ethics boards that must
approve all human experimentation and surveying a random sample of
those boards about their concerns and experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The second inquiry is intended to determine whether there is
adequate oversight of clinical investigators who are subject to
regulation by the FDA. In particular, that study is examining
whether the FDA's authority to disqualify investigators who are
either dishonest or who fail to follow procedure is being used in a
way that properly protects participants in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these areas were examined in a series of articles that
appeared in The New York Times beginning in May.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Those articles, the result of a 10-month investigation into the
modern system of drug research, described a system that is fueling
a pharmaceutical renaissance but is fraught with conflicts of
interest that patients know nothing about; that places a premium on
speed and meeting quotas; that relies on government and private
monitoring that can be easily fooled and that some researchers say
is inadequate, and that secretly offers a share of the cash to
other health professionals who may influence patients to join a
study.
</P>
<P>
   The articles also examined the case of a California doctor,
Robert Fiddes, whose research center engaged in a multiyear
research fraud that went undetected by monitors until an employee
at the center disclosed his actions. Government officials said
Fiddes was not disqualified by the FDA as a researcher until after
he was sent to prison for fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after those articles appeared, the House Commerce
Committee sought a briefing from the FDA about the Fiddes case and
whether the agency made any missteps that allowed the fraud to
continue for so long, according to a May 17 letter to the FDA from
Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., the committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that briefing, the congressional committee has
also surveyed other government health agencies to determine any
reviews or activities being conducted in the area of clinical
research. On July 13, the committee sent a letter to Ms. Brown
regarding the two separate inquiries she is conducting. In the
letter, the committee asked that the inspector general's findings
be shared with Congress when the inquiries are completed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
