<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTTISH GREENS MAKING GOLFERS SEE RED  
 JANZEN DOESN'T FEEL IT  
 STEWART EYES A RETURN IN STYLE
</HEADLINE>
   (yn) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ The narrowness of Carnoustie's fairways
has drawn numerous complaints from players preparing for this
week's British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen fairways as penalizing as that for a major
championship,'' said Phil Mickelson after Tuesday's practice round.
``You might as well stick red hazard posts down the fairways. But
everybody has to play the course the way it is. You cannot argue
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernhard Langer, a two-time Masters champion from Germany, has
played courses worldwide, but he had never seen anything quite like
Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very tough, the hardest course I've ever played, I
would say,'' Langer said. ``If the wind blows? It's hard enough
without the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Per-Ulrik Johansson of Sweden, who made the field by finishing
first at a Monday qualifying tournament, was particularly critical
of the par 4, 479-yard No. 12. ``I think it's OK at some of the
shorter holes when you have the fairways 15 to 20 yards wide, but
at the 12th hole, it's ridiculous,'' Johansson said. ``I don't know
how wide that landing area is, but it looked to me like 10-15
yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Furyk left the par 5, 578-yard No. 6 shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the toughest par 5 I've ever played,'' Furyk said.
``There's no right way to play it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the narrow fairways, length off the tee may not be
that much of an advantage. Vijay Singh, one of the game's longest
hitters, only used his driver on three holes Tuesday, opting for
accuracy over length.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say the driver could be taken out of a lot of players'
hands,'' Singh said. ``You can always get up and down if you miss
the greens. But where are you going to hit a driver?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Janzen Doesn't Feel It
</P>
<P>
   Unless Lee Janzen was intentionally playing down his chances,
don't look for him to be holding the claret jug Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say on a scale of 1 to 10, my game is about a negative 4
right now,'' said Janzen, a two-time U.S. Open champion. ``I'm not
doing anything very well. I think the winner will be a guy who is
playing extremely well, and I think that's great. That's what
everybody wants to see: a worthy champion.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Eyes a Return in Style
</P>
<P>
   The British Open will be Payne Stewart's first tournament since
winning last month's U.S. Open. ``I needed the three weeks off,''
Stewart said. ``I'm very excited about playing again. But what I
accomplished three weeks ago is something I will never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the deep rough at Carnoustie, knee-high in some
spots, Stewart said: ``It's thick, it's nasty and it's not very far
off the fairway, if you call those fairways. Those are kind of like
walking paths we have in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Count Stewart among those who would gladly take an even-par
score to the clubhouse Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what the weather is going to do, but if it blows
30 mph, you can see an astronomical score win,'' Stewart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
