<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8865 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALUJET-INDICTMENT-NY     07-13 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALUJET-INDICTMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY CHARGED WITH MURDER IN VALUJET CRASH; EMPLOYEES ALSO
INDICTED
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The aviation maintenance company that delivered
oxygen canisters believed to be responsible for the 1996 Valujet
crash was charged with murder and manslaughter Tuesday, and the
company, a vice president and two mechanics were charged with
carelessly handling deadly materials. Aviation experts say the
charges were the first criminal charges brought in an airliner
accident in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Federal safety investigators said the maintenance company,
Sabretech, improperly packed and labeled old airplane parts called
oxygen generators from two other Valujet planes and then delivered
them to the flight, causing a fire in a cargo hold that may have
broken out even before takeoff. All 110 people aboard were killed
when the DC-9 went down in the Everglades on May 11, 1996, shortly
after takeoff from Miami on a flight to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crash was completely preventable,'' said Katherine
Fernandez Rundle, state attorney for Miami-Dade County. ``This was
not an accident. It was a crime. It was a homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   The 110 counts of murder against the company were filed by Ms.
Rundle's office; a federal grand jury in Florida handed up the
indictments on improper handling of materials.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted on the federal charges, the three men could be
sentenced to up to five years in jail and a fine of $250,000, and
the company could face a fine of almost $6 million. The company
would also face a fine under the state charge, although prosecutors
did not say how large.
</P>
<P>
   But because Sabretech has ceased operations and sold its assets,
meaningful punishment is unlikely unless the company sought to
resume operations, said Donald R. Ungurait, a spokesman for Ms.
Rundle.
</P>
<P>
   Sabretech's assets were sold to Aviation Management Systems Inc.
of Orlando, Fla. Valujet renamed itself Airtran Airways.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer representing Sabretech, Kenneth P. Quinn, said the
charges against the company were ``utterly preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are attempting to criminalize a series of mistakes by
many parties, not just Sabretech or some of its former mechanics,''
he said, pointing out that the National Transportation Safety Board
had found fault not only with Sabretech but also with Valujet, for
failing to oversee its contractor, and the Federal Aviation
Administration, which did not require smoke detectors in DC-9 cargo
holds, among other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said the company and the three men would plead not guilty.
He said the men would negotiate surrendering to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The federal indictment named Eugene Florence, 37, and Mauro
Valenzuela, 30, both mechanics employed by sub-contractors to
Sabretech, and Daniel Gonzalez, who is in his mid-50s, then
Sabretech's vice president for operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not criminals; they are honest, well intentioned
mechanics who were trying to do the best they could with inadequate
information that had been given them, by the airline, and the
federal government,'' he said. After the accident, the FAA
suspended their licenses for a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, a corporation is considered the same as a person
and can be charged with many of the same crimes that a person can
be charged with. On conviction, a corporation can be fined and put
on probation, like a person, and its activities limited or
supervised by a judge or court-appointed official. Most charges
against corporations fall short of murder, however; more
frequently, they are charged with violations of pollution laws or
financial regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Some safety officials said that bringing murder charges against
Sabretech might make it difficult in future crashes to win the
cooperation of the various parties involved in investigations,
including the airline, the aircraft manufacturer, manufacturer of
engines and other parts and the unions representing the crew.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the House Aviation subcommittee, Rep. John J.
Duncan, R-Tenn., a former criminal court judge, said Tuesday he
doubted the wisdom of the decision to indict and that if the case
did not succeed, he would favor a congressional inquiry about why
it was brought.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The indictments largely echoed the findings of the Safety Board,
that technicians had removed the oxygen generators, small chemical
reactors that provide oxygen in case of emergency, from the
overhead panels of another airplane because their shelf life had
expired, but had failed to install plastic caps that prevent the
generators from starting up.
</P>
<P>
   Sabretech, located across a runway from the Valujet ramp at
Miami International Airport, conducted a hurried clean-up of its
hangar because another prospective airline client, Continental, was
taking a tour, and technicians packed the canisters loosely into
cardboard cartons, with bubble rap; then someone delivered them to
a Valujet plane that was being loaded with baggage for a flight to
Atlanta. Sabretech said it was returning the canisters to Valujet
because the airline owned them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rundle said, ``We were not able to prove that any single
individual was responsible for the homicides,'' but that
``cumulative acts'' made the airline culpable.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Lewis, an assistant U.S. attorney, said ``critical
maintenance steps were left out,'' and that company personnel
falsely indicated that the safety caps had been installed.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis did not say why the investigation took three years, but
said it was an ``intense, painstaking, careful'' process.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation experts differed on what precedent the indictments
would set. Vernon E. Grose, a member of the Safety Board in 1983
and 1984, said the threat of prosecution would make aviation
companies ``reticent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I think I had equipment that looks like it's going to be
raised as causative, then I'm going to be very, very cautious'' in
cooperating in an investigation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Eliot Brenner, the chief spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration, said the threat of indictment is always present,
and that many companies and individuals had been indicted, and
convicted, in cases that did not involve crashes, for crimes like
selling counterfeit parts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
