u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLST-LATINOS-BOS     07-13 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLST-LATINOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATINOS FUEL MLB GROWTH, GAME SPOKESMAN SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BEARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The rise of Pedro Martinez, Sammy Sosa, Ivan
Rodriguez, and Juan Gonzalez has placed a spotlight on a sport
where nearly four in 10 professional players, and one in four major
leaguers, are Latino, said a special assistant to the Major League
Baseball Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing presence of Latinos is a primary reason why Major
League Baseball has been able to expand to 30 teams, said Tony
Bernazard and other baseball executives speaking at a symposium on
``Latinos in Beisbol,'' sponsored by Northeastern University's
Center for the Study of Sport in Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would not be an Arizona Diamondbacks'' without the flow
of players from Puerto Rico, the Dominican Republic, Venezuela, and
Mexico, said Roland Hemond, assistant general manager of the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Bernazard, a big league second baseman from 1979-91, said the
influx prompted Major League Baseball to begin issuing all legal
documents to Latino players in both English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Often slighted by English-speaking sportswriters because of
language differences, Bernazard said the dramatic rise in Latino
participation will make it impossible to minimize the Latino role
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't hide it anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that based on midseason statistics, Latinos were
not well represented at the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Many major league teams have not made the sustained commitment
to integrate Latino players into society through English-language
programs, said another panelist, Northeastern University
sociologist Alan Klein, author of ``Baseball On the Border,'' a
study of Mexican baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Klein, in interviews with Red Sox fans over the past two
seasons, has found more disturbing news: while Fenway fans
overwhelmingly admire and respect Pedro Martinez as a player and
person, a plurality of fans have negative reactions to the
increasing number of Latinos who attend games when Martinez
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Klein harkened back to the words of Celtics great Bill Russell
in observing that many fans see no contradiction between worshiping
a person of color on the court or playing field _ and not wanting
to sit next to a person of color in the seats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
