u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALESTINIANS-U.S.-NYT     07-13 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIANS-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS MOVE TO AVOID FRICTION WITH ISRAEL AT U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ To avert friction with Israel's new government,
Palestinian leaders will seek the speedy adjournment of a U.N.
meeting that was to have considered possible sanctions against
Israel for human rights violations and settlement activity in Gaza
and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, in Geneva on Thursday, should end after just ``an
hour or two'' of formal remarks and resolutions to hold a future
conference on the issue, a senior Palestinian official said
Tuesday. The conference had been intended as an open-ended
examination of Israeli control of the West Bank and Gaza, sponsored
by the General Assembly and led by Switzerland, in its role as
custodian of the Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a compromise,'' said Nabil Shaath, the Palestinian
Authority's minister for planning and international cooperation, in
a telephone interview from Geneva. ``The idea is to make the
message clear, but not confrontational.''
</P>
<P>
   In public statements and in meetings with Western diplomats
here, the newly appointed foreign minister, David Levy, has said
the conference could be a divisive distraction from the planned
resumption of peace talks. Though Palestinian officials say Prime
Minister Ehud Barak did not raise the conference in his 75-minute
meeting Sunday with the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, Barak
stressed the importance of beginning comprehensive negotiations in
an atmosphere of mutual trust, without recriminations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really giving Barak an opportunity to set up his
program of action,'' Shaath said.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli diplomats criticized the Palestinian plan to
reconvene the conference in November, or next January. ``We see
this entire exercise as an attempt to single out Israel, and we
firmly reject it,'' Dore Gold, Israel's representative at the
United Nations, said Tuesday in a telephone interview from New
York.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Israeli diplomats are urging European members of a
steering commission for the gathering to oppose setting a new date
for the conference, which could in theory attempt to impose
economic sanctions or other penalties on Israel. The threat of such
a conference would be ``a sword of Damocles hanging over the peace
process,'' one Israeli official said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the U.N. General Assembly almost unanimously
adopted a resolution calling for a conference of all Geneva
Convention signers on July 15 to examine violations of the
convention by Israel in the occupied territories of the West Bank
and the Gaza Strip. Israel and the United States cast the only
dissenting votes.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Israeli diplomats have tried without success to
scuttle the conference, contending that there was no precedent for
a new Geneva Conference focusing on a single regional conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signatories of the Convention have never been convened for
any purpose since 1949 _ not when the Soviets invaded
Czechoslovakia or Afghanistan, or when the Iraqis invaded Kuwait,''
Gold said. Israeli diplomats say they have sought to convince other
U.N. members with histories of border wars that there could be
similar intervention in their own territorial disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva meeting is being boycotted by the United States, as
well as by Israel, which says that Australia and several other U.N.
members have also decided to avoid the session.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials who originally pushed for the conference
acknowledged that their motivation was to bypass the standard
diplomatic mechanisms of the United Nations, where anti-Israel
resolutions are passed overwhelmingly by the General Assembly only
to be quashed by U.S. vetoes in the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Shaath, one of the architects of the conference, suggested a few
months ago that the tenets of the original convention would permit
imposing penalties against Israel for its treatment of the occupied
territories.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, he struck a more conciliatory note, while emphasizing
the continuing Palestinian concern about Israeli settlers and a
commitment to meet eventually on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
