A8870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      07-13 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS DEFEAT DEMOCRATIC PROPOSALS ON MANAGED CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the first tests of strength on managed care
legislation, Republicans in the Senate on Tuesday beat back
Democratic amendments on such emotional issues as emergency room
access and special medical protections for women. The Republicans
also went on to pass measures of their own that in large part
dismantled the Democrats' managed care bill.
</P>
<P>
   The five votes on amendments to rival bills were a strong signal
that the Republicans would stick together and pass their own bill
at the end of a four-day debate over how to regulate health
maintenance companies in the new era of managed care. Every vote
ran largely along party lines, with at most four Republicans
breaking with their party.
</P>
<P>
   At day's end, Sen. Don Nickles, the majority whip from Oklahoma,
was virtually declaring victory. ``We've made some good progress to
hopefully passing our bill and defeating a bill that would impose
costs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though two more days of maneuvering are scheduled and the final
shape of the legislation that will emerge from the Senate is not
yet clear, the developments were a sign that the debate over
managed care could well end in a stalemate and a political issue
for the 2000 election. Aides to President Clinton said that if the
Republican version of the bill prevails, they would recommend that
he veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in an appearance on Tuesday with Democrats on the South
Lawn of the White House, accused Senate Republicans of supporting
``a watered down'' bill to regulate managed care companies that
contains ``toothless and half hearted protections.''
</P>
<P>
   The president charged that the Republicans had submitted to
pressure from health insurance companies, which helped scuttle his
own attempt to win universal health care coverage in 1994. ``This
is about political power in Washington trying to shut off something
that is manifestly in the best interest of the average citizen of
this country _ and not just the average citizen _ every single
person covered by an HMO,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans replied by rejecting the idea that federal
regulation is the answer to consumer concerns over managed care
coverage. ``He's always had this idea that the federal government
knows best,'' said Nickles. ``I reject that philosophy that
Washington, D.C., knows best on health care.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's debate marked the first time since the new era of
managed care that the Senate has considered how to protect the
rights of patients and regulate the companies that provide health
insurance to most Americans. Republicans and Democrats have offered
rival bills reflecting different philosophies over how much federal
regulation is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The measures differ on issues such as how many consumers would
be covered by the legislation and what kinds of requirements would
be imposed upon the managed care companies. The Republicans would
offer a number of their consumer protections to the 48 million
Americans in health plans offered by large employers, which are
regulated exclusively by the federal government. The Democrats'
bill would cover all 161 million Americans with private health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   With health care issues expected to be potent in next year's
elections, the two sides were going to great lengths to seize the
advantage in the debate and force votes on amendments that they
hope to turn to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Although Democrats had held out hope that they might prevail on
some amendments, the day's first 52-48 vote defeating an amendment
sponsored by Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., quickly made such a turn of
events look highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the amendments the Democrats planned to offer across four
days of debate, they considered this to be the one most likely to
draw cross-over Republican votes.
</P>
<P>
   Touching on an emotional health issue for a sought-after
political constituency, the measure would have stipulated that
women could choose obstetrician-gynecologists as their primary care
doctors and ensured that a woman could stay overnight in a hospital
after a mastectomy if her doctor recommended it. It also included a
tax credit favored by Republicans that would allow people who are
self-employed to deduct 100 percent of the cost of purchasing
health care coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats cited instances where insurance companies required a
mastectomy to be treated as out-patient surgery. ``Make no mistake,
a mastectomy is an amputation and it has all the horrible, horrific
consequences as an amputation,'' said Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md..
Even so, she said that in some cases, after a woman has had such
surgery, ''she's told to call a cab and go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they would offer their own amendment Thursday
addressing some of the same issues, but they objected to the
designation of a obstetrician-gynecologist as a primary care
physician. Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., said such doctors want to be
considered specialists. He said that in the Republican bill, a
woman would be allowed to choose to see an obstretician-gyneclogist
without a referral from another physician. ``That's what women tell
me they want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, only three Republicans _ Sens. John Chafee of Rhode
Island, John Warner of Virginia and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania _
crossed party lines to join the Democrats on that vote.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats immediately made clear how they would portray the vote
next year. ``All but three Republicans turned their backs on the
women of America,'' said Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In rapid secession after that the Republicans won vote after
vote on Tuesday night. By a vote of 52-48, they stripped from the
Democrats' bill provisions that would grant doctors the right to
decide what procedures are medically necessary. They replaced that
with a Republican provision that would leave that decision up to a
doctor in the insurance company and then set up an external appeals
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 52-48, the Senate passed a measure that would keep
the Democrats bill from taking effect if it causes an increase in
insurance premiums of more than 1 percent. The Congressional Budget
Office has said that the latest version of the Democrats bill would
increase premiums by 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate defeated, 53-47, a Democratic effort to give all
Americans with private health insurance assured access to an
emergency room even if it is outside a managed care network.
</P>
<P>
   And by 53-47, Republicans passed their own amendment that would
give a 100 percent deduction for health care coverage to all
self-employed individuals, instead of the current 40 percent
deduction. The amendment, which amounts to a $3 billion tax
reduction, also contained language blocking a Democratic effort to
make the Republican managed care bill cover all 161 Americans with
private health insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
