<HEADLINE>
EARLY VOTES IN MEDICAL CARE DEBATE GO TO GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate cast its opening votes Tuesday in the
battle over patient's rights, striking down a Democratic measure
that would require insurance companies to pay for any treatments
that doctors say are medically necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also defeated a Democratic amendment that would have
expanded medical care options for women. Both proposals were
defeated on a near party-line vote of 52-48.
</P>
<P>
   The votes came after a day of heated debate, as Democrats
pressed the most extensive plan to overhaul the nation's health
care system since President Clinton's failed effort in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic measure would have required health insurance
companies to pay for care that fits under the generally accepted
principles of medical practice.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans argued that ``one size fits all'' was not
practical and replaced the Democratic medical necessity language
with a measure that would allow patients to appeal if an insurance
company denies coverage for a medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to make sure that every person has the right to
the best medical care available,'' said Senator James Jeffords, a
Vermont Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The women's health care amendment would have allowed women
longer hospital stays after mastectomies and would have given women
the option of choosing their obstetrician-gynecologists as their
primary-care physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shameful vote,'' said Senator Edward M. Kennedy
afterward. ``I'm shocked at the Republican Party's insensitivity to
the needs of American women.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are expected to offer their own version of the bill
later this week that would provide similar benefits for women. But
the competing GOP measure would apply to about 50 million fewer
women than the Democrat proposal.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the president would veto the GOP bill
if it reaches his desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pretends to guarantee direct access to obstetricians and
gynecologists, but it is so narrowly crafted that it will bring
few, if any, benefits to the women eligible for its apparent
protection,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also rejected, 47-53, a Democratic measure that would
prevent HMOs from charging patients more if they sought emergency
care from hospitals not covered under their medical plan.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans offered an amendment, which passed 52-48, that
focuses on how the Democratic bill would drive up insurance costs.
The Democrats' measure would boost premiums by 4.8 percent,
according to congressional experts. Under the Republican amendment,
the bill's provisions would be canceled if the cost is increased by
more than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected Wednesday to vote how many people the
legislation should cover, access to emergency room care and the
cost of the bill. Final passage is expected Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans and Democrats have proposed dueling measures
to protect patients in health-maintenence organizations or other
health care plans. The bills address such issues as patients'
access to specialists, emergency care coverage and grievance
procedures if treatment is denied.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic plan is more far-reaching, covering about 161
million Americans and establishing a more comprehensive framework
for federal regulation of health insurance. But Republicans want to
minimize new federal regulations, covering only the 48 million
Americans in health plans exempt from state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also want to allow patients to sue HMOs and collect
damages when HMOs withhold treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to empower the patients and the doctors making the
decisions, not empower the HMOs,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said excessive litigation would drive up costs
and would prompt employers to drop health care coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You simply cannot sue your way to better health,'' Jeffords
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's debate began, President Clinton, at a morning
rally with Senate Democrats at the White House, accused Republicans
of caving in to pressures from health insurance companies and
backing a ``watered-down'' plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is nowhere near what the American people deserve or need.
Not only does it offer merely toothless and half-hearted
protections, it fails to protect all Americans in managed care,''
Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
