<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-REPUBLICANPARTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smith defects from GOP; Could take Bush votes
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (w) WASHINGTON and (p) NATIONAL POLITICAL
categories.)
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith, whose bid for the
Republican presidential nomination never even achieved favorite-son
status in his home state, quit the party Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Though the move did little to increase his longer-than-long shot
at becoming president, officials in both parties said it could
increase Smith's chances of effecting the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, complaining that the GOP had abandoned its conservative
principles, plans to run a third-party presidential campaign that
could drain votes from the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, polls indicate that will be Gov. George W. Bush,
whose moderate positions came in for specific criticism Tuesday
from Smith. The two-term New Hampshire senator said the GOP
platform is ``not worth the paper it's printed on.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he remains true to his platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pro-life, it's pro-Second Amendment, it's pro-military,
it's pro-sovereignty, it's pro-character and integrity,'' he said.
``Many who want to lead our party _ specifically candidate Bush _
won't take a position on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the governor ``hates to see
(Smith) leave the party.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said Smith, as a third-party candidate, should not take
many votes from the GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who is looking for the party that represents
conservative principles will support the conservative Republican
nominee,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bush will make a stop in Washington to pick up an
endorsement from Ohio Rep. John Kasich, who is giving up his bid
for the presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's comment about Bush came prior to a Senate floor speech
in which he announced his decision to bolt from the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson was among
those downplaying the significance of the move by Smith, who barely
showed up in national polls and never topped 3 percent in his home
state.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Smith, Nicholson said the move would have ``only
a marginal political impact.''
</P>
<P>
   But New Hampshire GOP Chairman Steve Duprey said any impact
Smith does have will come at the expense of the Republican
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the irony here,'' said Duprey. ``Bob Smith leaving our
party might have the effect of helping Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   As a third-party candidate, Smith _ already unknown to most
voters _ would be underfunded and unable to mount a serious
challenge. He could, however, find support from social
conservatives who have targeted Bush as too moderate. Bush has
declined to guarantee he would pick a running mate and judges who,
like him, oppose abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   That puts Bush off limits to people like Bobbie Gobel,
chairwoman of the Iowa Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a large percentage will leave their party and follow
him,'' Gobel said of Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Of Bush, she said, ``If he could pick and choose somebody that
could straddle the fence and not honor God's word that is out of
the Holy Bible then I believe he is not the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Results from the 1996 presidential election, a popular and
electoral vote landslide that kept Democrat Bill Clinton in office,
shows how shifting a relatively few votes can change who gets a
state's electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton got California's 54 electoral votes but garnered only 51
percent of the state's popular votes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also got Florida's 25 electoral votes, though he
outpolled Republican Bob Dole by only 300,000 votes out of 5.3
million. Ross Perot got 484,000 votes, enough to change the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Though debate remains on who Perot took votes from, most
Republicans believe he hurt their candidate, especially
then-President George Bush in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   There's little doubt that any campaign coming from the right of
the GOP nominee would hurt the Republican contender next year.
That's why national Democrats were enjoying Smith's performance on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he can clearly have an effect on the race'' as a
third-party or independent candidate, said Joe Andrew, general
chairman of the Democratic National Committee. ``When you have
extreme positions, as Bob Smith has, and he takes those votes with
him, 100 percent of them are coming from whoever the Republican
nominee is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
