<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-RELIEF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT'S ARREST BRINGS RELIEF TO AREAS WHERE KILLINGS OCCURRED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Tilde needed over n in Zuniga) 
 
By RAD SALLEE 
and JO ANN ZUNIGA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Living in what felt like a secure neighborhood in West
University Place, attorney Karen Chisolm learned wariness after
another woman there fell victim to a serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 17, Rafael Resendez-Ramirez allegedly emerged from the
railroad tracks that run half a block from Chisolm's home in West
University, an affluent enclave of Houston, and bludgeoned Dr.
Claudia Benton to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a lot more careful about keeping my alarm on since
then,'' Chisolm said, ``even when I'm at home and awake.''
</P>
<P>
   News that the suspect had surrendered Tuesday in El Paso was
welcome, but it failed to make her feel completely safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the attention, the uncertainty, the fear, stay with
you even after the immediate threat is gone,'' Chisolm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The security was somewhat illusory.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Kissinger, a caterer and commercial artist, has lived with
her back to the same old Southern Pacific tracks for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The house where the slaying occurred is just across the street,
and Kissinger says she would pick up the mail when Benton was out
of town.
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger's husband was working late and she was home alone the
night their neighbor was slain. Kissinger says the killer probably
walked right past her window.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grow all my vegetables in the back,'' she explained, ``and
ever since, I haven't felt comfortable being out there without my
husband.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrest also brought relief to a neighborhood a few miles
away, in southeast Houston near the Texas Medical Center, where
Noemi Dominguez, a 26-year-old teacher, was beaten to death June 5.
</P>
<P>
   The fenced backyard of the two-story fourplex where she lived is
separated from grocery warehouses by a Houston Belt and Terminal
Railway track.
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez, a Rice University graduate who was on sabbatical from
teaching to finish her master's degree, was bludgeoned in her
bedroom and found by her brother. Evidence links Resendez-Ramirez
to the killing, investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   One of her neighbors, whose door opens onto the tracks a few
feet away, has burglar bars, a security system and a barking dog.
</P>
<P>
   She was relieved but said she must remain cautious, since her
young granddaughters live with her.
</P>
<P>
   A worker in the nearby U.S. Post Office said he comes to work at
4 a.m. and has made a point of watching the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have Hispanic workers here,'' he said, ``and they were
saying that it's not right for people to think that all Hispanics
are immigrants _ and most definitely not all are criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   At Methodist Hospital in Houston, two workers having lunch
gasped when told that the suspect had surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a single woman living alone and this really affected my
life,'' said Irene Minor. ``I would have family members call to
check on me and make sure my doors and windows were locked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was happening in all areas of the city and country,'' Minor
said. ``It was terrifying that one man could have such an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez is also suspected in the 1997 murder of
Christopher Maier, 21, in Lexington, Ky., and the rape of his
girlfriend. That bludgeoning also occurred as the couple walked
along a rail track.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's mother said her daughter is taking a summer class
in England. Although they had not spoken since the arrest, she felt
confident her daughter had heard the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the world has e-mailed her,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fear and relief were felt well beyond the communities where
Resendez-Ramirez is said to have found his victims.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Bell, who has a sheep ranch near Kerrville in the Texas
Hill Country, was in Houston on business Tuesday and lunching at
Cleburne Cafeteria near Benton's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd read in our weekly paper that they'd had five or six
sightings a week,'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody would have seen him in the supermarket, having a cup
of coffee. And the police would come and check it out, but either
the person they saw would be gone or it wouldn't be him.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no killings in the Kerrville area have been linked to
Resendez-Ramirez, he was blamed for two slayings in Weimar and
another about three miles away in Fayette County.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to Houston, the sound of trains near her house in
Magnolia used to give Helen Mateos a soothing sense of peace. Now
they are a disturbing reminder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day I was putting on my makeup when I heard the
train,'' Mateos said. ``I stopped and thought, I just don't like to
hear it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Evans, director of social psychology at the
University of Houston, said such effects can be expected to fade
with time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning,'' he said, ``there's an overreaction among
people who live alone or in secluded areas, even though the chance
of being a victim is very small.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take steps to take care of themselves, but the fear
element begins to diminish very rapidly. Once he's captured, the
excitement of the chase is gone,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since Resendez-Ramirez is not a celebrity like O.J. Simpson,
Evans said, there probably will not even be much news interest in
seeing how his personality unfolds in his trial.
</P>
<P>
   And because his alleged crimes are spread out over the country,
Evans said, there will be nothing like the series of funerals and
community grief that helped sustain interest in the Columbine High
School shootings in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excitement and fantasy of someone on the loose in railroad
cars will be gone,'' Evans predicted. ``That's what gave the story
legs to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, the interest was very much alive. Liz Galvan, a
Spanish teacher who lives across the street from Benton's home, got
three phone calls during a 5-minute interview.
</P>
<P>
   The phone started ringing as soon as the surrender was announced
on television, she said, and hadn't stopped.
</P>
<P>
   It was also ringing for Gary Brye, the West University Place
police chief. He said he had not known the arrest was imminent and
had not taken a break since it was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the calls, he said patiently, were from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Brye said his investigators had contacted Benton's husband,
George, with the news of Resendez-Ramirez's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said the house has been sold, and George Benton has
moved out of state with the couple's twin daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information I have,'' Brye said, ``is that, as one could
expect, the grief was still there, but they were very happy that
the suspect is in custody.''
</P>
<P>
   That feeling is shared by all 21 members of the West University
Place police force, he said, each of whom has worked on the case at
one time or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased he's in custody and is off the streets,''
Brye said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an extremely brutal individual.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle staff writers Lisa Davis and Eric Berger contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
