<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUCCESSOR-SUCCESSOR_S     07-13 1822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUCCESSOR-SUCCESSOR </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Keeping It in the Family  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
A lot of entrepreneurs successfully build businesses, but many balk
at handing over the reins and the assets during their lifetime to
the next generation. That can be a terrible oversight because the
heirs would be hit with a 55 percent tax on estate assets exceeding
$3 million in value.
<P>
   In the United States, family businesses account for an estimated
90 percent of the 15 million total enterprises. But only about 30
percent make it to the second generation, and just 8 percent
survive for the grandchildren. Some companies go public or are sold
at a profit. A great number of potential successors simply lack the
acumen to continue the business; many others are forced to sell the
business to pay the hefty tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   While death is inevitable, an entrepreneur can reduce the tax
burden considerably by taking action early and intelligently. A
number of techniques are available to transfer wealth, including
the use of one-time exclusions from estate taxes, tax-free annual
gifts and discount valuations allowed for assets of privately owned
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Robert Pecota, 60, and his brother Joseph, 69. Both
took aggressive measures to pass their wealth to the next
generation and help ensure that their separate businesses stay in
the family.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pecota started his own wine venture in 1978 after
learning the wine and vineyard trade at Beringer and its former
parent company, Nestle USA, in Napa Valley. Today, Robert Pecota
Winery produces about 15,000 cases of ultra-premium wine with
revenues topping $2 million and a fair-market value approaching $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a San Francisco dry cleaner, and one of 11 children,
Robert Pecota displayed his business know-how early on. After
working his way through the University of San Francisco and getting
an MBA on a scholarship at the University of California at
Berkeley, Pecota, then in his mid-20s, bought the cheapest home in
the most expensive Greenbrae neighborhood with all-borrowed funds.
Three years later, he sold it for a $50,000 profit.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he bought 40 acres three miles north of Calistoga at
the upper end of the Napa Valley, Pecota had purchased and sold two
vineyards for even quicker profits and had built a nest egg of
$200,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; By continuously taking out new loans on his appreciating
vineyard land, refinancing the property as interest rates fell and
using cash flow from sales, Pecota has been able to pour more than
$3 million into capital equipment and an equal amount into
inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Vineyard land in choice parts of the Napa Valley now goes for
well over $100,000 per acre, and Pecota's 40 acres is worth more
than 20 times the $4,500 to $5,000 an acre he paid for it more than
20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the values continued to grow, I realized we would be eaten
alive by the estate taxes that encourage the destruction of family
businesses,'' Pecota said in an interview as he gazed across his
bright green Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   ``To many people, money is a way to control the kids, to get
them to come and visit. My view is to get the money in their hands
as soon as possible and they will make sure you are well taken care
of. In a family business, your kids are your 401(k) plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pecota got some pointers from his older brother, Joseph,
who gave away his entire Tri-Phase Inc. circuit-board assembly
company in Sunnyvale to his three children a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, the younger Pecota attended an estate-planning
seminar and then talked with his accountants and Napa lawyer Robert
Fanucci about an estate and transition plan.
</P>
<P>
   Most crucial to the continued success of a family run and owned
business, Pecota maintains, is a clear understanding of the
strengths, weaknesses and interests of the next generation. Two of
Pecota's three children, 33-year-old Kara and 25-year-old Andrea,
work at the winery while son Steven, 27, is a baker in Reno.
</P>
<P>
   After plotting management strategy, Pecota's next step was using
corporate and tax laws to shift assets out of his estate as quickly
and efficiently as possible. For starters, he set up a revocable
living trust to avoid probate and reduce the chance of delays and
disputes after he dies.
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned his attention to establishing a fair-market value
of his company. In this case, giving away shares in a privately
held company is different from giving away cash or publicly traded
stocks because there is no standard market value. That can be a
major benefit to family businesses because they often can get
discounts of 30 to 50 percent off the fair-market value of their
assets because the transferred shares are minority interests and
stock in the company cannot be easily bought or sold.
</P>
<P>
   Pecota hired Hal Forcey of Pacific Coast Appraisal, a specialist
in winery and vineyard valuation, to come up with a reasonable
discount on the fair-market value for his winery. Then using the
so-called applicable exclusion from estate taxes, which this year
rises from $600,000 to $650,000 for an individual, Pecota gave away
45 percent of his winery over five years _ 15 percent to each of
his children.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Pecota, who is divorced, is making $10,000 annual
tax-free gifts to each of his children. These are used to pay the
premiums on a $1.5 million variable annuity insurance policy on his
life so that when he dies, the proceeds will be outside of his
estate and can be used to pay estate taxes or for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   To lower the tax bite and reduce potential liability problems,
Pecota also formed a family limited partnership for the vineyards
and converted from a sole proprietorship to a limited liability
company for the winery. ``No one should enter this process without
a good accountant and estate attorney,'' Pecota warns. And be
prepared to spend some bucks to save more bucks. Pecota figures he
has paid about $50,000 on legal, accounting and appraisal bills.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Robert Pecota would like to match his older
brother's feat of transferring the entire business in his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   After working for Hewlett-Packard and several electronics sales
representatives, Joseph Pecota started his own electronics company
in 1965 in Sunnyvale. Called Tri-Phase Inc., it grew and prospered,
and two of Pecota's three children joined the company.
</P>
<P>
   Then a decade ago, Joseph Pecota decided it was time to give his
business away to avoid onerous taxes in the future.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife gave away the entire company in three equal
pieces to their three children, using up about $1 million of their
lifetime exclusion from estate taxes. At the same time, son Andrew,
now 42, became CEO and president and Joseph Pecota willingly became
a paid consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the sole owner, the top banana,'' Joseph Pecota recalled
from his home at Clear Lake. ``But it was time for a change. It
made sense to give away an appreciating asset when the tax base was
low. It was the right time, and luckily I had children who were
interested, able and responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   While Andrew Pecota runs the company, which has more than
doubled in size over the past decade, daughter Elizabeth, 31, is
treasurer. Son William, 39, a former major-league baseball player,
is not involved with Tri-Phase.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to giving the company to his children, Pecota and
his wife have used the annual $10,000 tax-free gift allowance to
transfer ownership of a separate 8,000-square-foot industrial
building in Silicon Valley to their children.
</P>
<P>
   There is no single right way to transfer assets to the next
generation. Rather, there are multiple approaches and philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   Many business owners prefer to give equal shares in the business
to all their children, regardless of whether they are involved in
the family business. Some issue nonvoting shares to those who are
not working in the company to avoid unnecessary interference with
management.
</P>
<P>
   But some successful entrepreneurs oppose this approach. They
argue that if family members don't have the same interests or share
the same vision, giving them common stakes is a recipe for
infighting and disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our love of our children and desire to be fair often sets the
stage for conflict,'' said Marshall Paisner, author of the new book
``Sustaining the Family Business: An Insider's Guide to Managing
Across Generations'' (Perseus Books, $26).
</P>
<P>
   ``Give stock only to those in the business,'' advises Paisner,
who at 69 has transferred 100 percent of his ScrubaDub car-wash
chain in Massachusetts to his two sons who work in the business. He
has used an insurance policy on his life and that of his wife to
provide equal financial benefits to a third child who is not
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great equalizer in America is insurance,'' Paisner and
some others argue.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is easy to overlook estate and retirement planning,
Paisner said it is essential to think about it early and execute a
plan. Because you can give a family business away at a discount,
why wait until death, when you have to pay taxes on the full market
value.
</P>
<P>
   Paisner, for example, divided ScrubaDub shares into two classes,
voting and nonvoting. He initially kept the 10 percent that had
voting power for himself to maintain control, and he and his wife
gave away the 90 percent that didn't have voting rights to their
two sons in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Since these nonvoting shares lacked management control and could
not be sold easily because the company is privately owned,
ScrubaDub's appraiser gave Paisner a 50 percent discount on the
valuation of the transfers. That effectively doubled the value of
the annual $20,000 tax-free gifts that Paisner and his wife gave
each child working in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at retirement age, Paisner sold his 10 percent voting
stock back to his children and set up a life insurance policy to
eventually pay off the bank loans used by the company to buy back
these shares.
</P>
<P>
   Paisner and other experts also strongly recommend setting up
formal conflict-resolution procedures rather than leaving it to
chance. Family conflicts can range from differences over business
strategy to which siblings or cousins get which jobs, to arguments
over dividend policy.
</P>
<P>
   Have an outside board of directors or advisers, the experts say.
Set up regular family council meetings to discuss potential
problems and iron out difficulties. Consider putting 2 percent of
the stock in the family business into a deadlock trust where a
mutually agreed upon trustee has the clout to hammer out compromise
and break ties.
</P>
<P>
   Have formal stock redemption agreements such as acceptance of a
lower-than-market price for stock passed between family members.
The mere existence of such agreements might help keep conflicts in
check.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
