<SLUG> BC-FILM-MUPPETS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MUPPETS FROM SPACE' LACKS ENERGY AND ZING, IS ERRATICALLY PACED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1996 film, ``Muppet Treasure Island,'' showed the clever and
canny Muppets could survive the death of their creator, Jim Henson.
But ``Muppets From Space'' raises questions about their movie
future. It's neither very witty nor a particularly original
animatronic puppet adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's a turgid rehash of several good (and bad) sci-fi
movies, including ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind.''
</P>
<P>
   In this spoof of UFO flicks, Gonzo is in the midst of an
identity crisis. All the other Muppets know who and what they are
and where they come from. But poor Gonzo feels lost and alone.
Where is his real home?
</P>
<P>
   When he starts receiving cryptic messages from outer space, he
realizes his roots are somewhere in the stars. Even a sandwich
mysteriously begins to transmit information to him and, when Miss
Piggy broadcasts a report on Gonzo's behavior on the local TV
station, a paranoid government agency catches wind of it. Soon
Gonzo, who is thought to be an alien, along with his roommate and
pal, Rizzo the Rat, are enduring more than a mere rectal exam at
the hands of a mad doctor obsessed with his scary scientific
research.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to the Muppets to rescue their friends and rush Gonzo to
his appointed date with destiny: to meet his real family.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the message remains that Gonzo will learn family is
where your heart is, not necessarily blood _ or alien _ ties.
</P>
<P>
   Though Rizzo has several funny ``small'' moments, the film lacks
energy and zing. It's erratically paced and quite often predictably
dull storywise and even smaller children may not find its jokes and
situations very compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the film is packed with ``human'' guest actors, they
all appear to be slumming. Ray Liotta, Andie MacDowell, F. Murray
Abraham, Jeffrey Tambor and Josh Charles receive such negligible
screen time and so little to do that they seem sheepish at having
agreed to co-star with such upstaging Muppet stars.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, this not-so-big adventure has little of the goofy
intelligence of ``The Muppet Show.'' It's as if, without Henson's
off-kilter sense of humor, the puppets have lapsed into rather
pedestrian situations and schemes. The element of surprise that was
such a delight in the TV series _ and in the last film _ is lost.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the problem may be that they're working with a
first-time feature director but my sense tells me it's more of a
script issue and the challenge to keep the Muppets on top of the
fast-changing, more sophisticated realm of kids' movies. Let's hope
they retain their individuality rather than try to keep up with
competition that is trendy and fashionable but mediocre in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Muppets From Space. Directed by Tim Hill. Cast: F. Murray
Abraham, Jeffrey Tambor, Andie MacDowell, Ray Liotta, David
Arquette. Columbia Pictures.80 minutes. Rated G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
