<HEADER>
A8880 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROWABUSINES-GROWABUS     07-13 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWABUSINES-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 A BUSINESS _ SF CHRON   Transferring Assets to Your Kids 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; Q: I have a family business and am starting to think about
estate planning even though I have no intention of retiring soon.
What are some of the things to consider?
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Experts say the time to start worrying about the next
generation of owners and operators is as soon as the family
business becomes successful.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you feel your children or other relatives should make it
on their own, you might want to start planning and transferring
assets early. Death can be expense. Without proper planning, when
the owner dies, the heirs often have no choice but to sell the
business to pay federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a brief list of some of the things to consider and tools
to use to transfer the business:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Tax-free gifts. The annual allowance to give $10,000 tax-free to
almost anyone is a favorite way to transfer family assets. If you
have a family business, ``you have a dual motive,'' said Ronald
Linder, a San Francisco CPA and attorney. ``You can shift future
appreciation of the assets and you can often claim a 30 to 50
percent discount on their value because it's a minority interest in
a nonmarketable security.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
The applicable credit. Formerly called the unified credit or the
lifetime exclusion from federal estate taxes, the amount rises this
year to $650,000 from $600,000 for individuals and to $1.3 million
from $1.2 million for married couples. By 2006, it will rise to $1
million for individuals and $2 million for couples, and can be used
during one's lifetime to transfer assets while they are still
appreciating.
</P>
<P>
   Many business owners with multimillion-dollar estates also take
advantage of the $1 million exemption ($2 million for couples) from
generation-skipping transfer taxes. Setting up a
generation-skipping trust reduces estate tax on the children's
estates by allowing assets to pass directly to their children.
</P>
<P>
   If you are giving shares in the family business, you will need a
fair-market appraisal from an experienced and qualified appraiser.
Because shares are minority interests, often without voting rights,
in a private business, you should be able to get a nice discount
from the fair-market value.
</P>
<P>
   Appraisals often are called for every time one makes a transfer.
But in practice, an appraisal often can last for a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Because valuations are ``somewhere between an art and a
science,'' Napa Valley appraiser Hal Forcey recommends finding an
experienced, ethical appraiser with an excellent reputation in your
particular industry. Otherwise you could be on weak footing if
challenged by the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The family-owned business deduction. Started in 1997, IRS Code
Section 2057 allows deductions of up to $675,000 for family-owned
businesses that meet certain qualifications. When the founder dies,
the heirs must continue to run the business for at least 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Special Use Valuation. This IRS Code Section 2032A gives family
businesses as much as a $760,000 additional break this year on the
standard fair-market valuation of their real estate. For example,
if the highest and best use for a piece of property is residential
but it is being used for agriculture, the heirs can take the lower
valuation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Business structure. How your company is organized is as important
to preserving your family business assets as tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Regular corporations, or C corporations, pay taxes on corporate
income and shareholders pay taxes on dividends. Partnerships,
limited liability companies and S corporations generally are not
subject to double taxation at the corporate and individual levels,
and income flows directly to the owners.
</P>
<P>
   Some types of business organizations also shield owners more
effectively from legal liability and taxes. For example, property
put into family limited partnerships garner low valuations for tax
purposes because of lack of voting rights and the difficulty
selling partial interests in a private business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Irrevocable life insurance trusts. These can be useful for creating
an ``alternative estate'' for family members who are not involved
in the business. Or they can be used to pay off estate taxes or for
other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Several other types of trusts can be used to shift assets to the
next generation while guaranteeing income for the founder,
according to Mark Watson, a partner with KPMG's National Tax
Practice in Washington, D.C. They include:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Granter trusts. Business-owner parents can sell stock in their
private company to a granter trust in exchange for a promissory
note with annual interest payments and a balloon payment of
principle at the end. This is a nontaxable event, and the advantage
is that any appreciation of the company and its assets above the
roughly 6 percent interest rate is shifted to the next generation
or other beneficiaries tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Granter retained annuity trusts. These are a variation on the same
theme. The granter transfers stock to the trust as a gift but
retains the right to receive an annual payment, or annuity, from
the trust. To the extent that the stock goes up in value more than
the interest rate, the excess appreciation similarly flows to the
beneficiaries of the trust tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from financial planning, you need to focus on who is going
to run the business after you are gone. If your relatives have the
interest and capability, great. If not, it might make sense to
bring in professionals to manage the business for them or sell it
and give your heirs the proceeds. It also is essential to establish
ways to resolve conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When family businesses work well, they are full of trust,
passion and fun,'' said Jack Cakebread of Cakebread Cellars in
Oakville, who has successfully transferred about 36 percent of his
Napa Valley winery to his family. ``But when they don't, they're
hell on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Estate planning is complicated and takes a lot of time. Most
likely, you will need to consult professionals though you might
want to start by doing some reading on your own.
</P>
<P>
   Nolo Press and IDG's Books for Dummies have some relevant books
on the topic. You also might check out ``The Family Business: Power
Tools for Survival, Success and Succession,'' ``Generation to
Generation: Life Cycles of the Family Business,'' ``The Survival
Guide for Business Families'' and ``Sustaining the Family Business:
An Insider's Guide to Managing Across Generations.
</P>
<P>
   Several online sites, including the Family Business Center
(www.fambiz.com), also have useful information.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
