<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOUBLECLICK-DOUBLECLICK </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   DoubleClick to Buy NetGravity for $530 Million 
 &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Internet advertising firm DoubleClick Inc. boosted its standing as
a one-stop shop for clients by acquiring San Mateo's NetGravity
Inc. yesterday in an all-stock deal valued at about $530 million.
<P>
   The deal gives DoubleClick, which sells advertising space on a
network of 1,500 Web sites, the technical know-how to offer
customers the software they need to manage online ads.
</P>
<P>
   NetGravity will also provide DoubleClick with a solid customer
base including the likes of IBM, Time Inc. and E-Trade Group. And
the company boasts an established presence in Asia and Latin
America, where DoubleClick had yet to forge significant inroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say it's a match made in heaven, but it's
pretty close,'' said Jeff Goverman, research director at Pacific
Crest Securities in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   The NetGravity deal follows DoubleClick's $1 billion purchase
last month of Abacus Direct Corp., which provides
consumer-purchasing data to direct marketers like catalog
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you combine the three pieces, it will be very hard to
duplicate this company,'' Goverman said. ``They can bring the right
ad to the right people at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   While that might be an exaggeration, it's not far off. The
NetGravity and Abacus acquisitions position DoubleClick as the
premier supplier of advertising resources in an e-commerce-hungry
world.
</P>
<P>
   Online advertising is expected to reach $3 billion this year,
according to market researcher Jupiter Communications. This would
be up more than $1 billion from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Spivey, NetGravity's president and CEO, said he had been
approached by DoubleClick's chief executive, Kevin O'Connor,
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Spivey had only been on the job since April, having replaced
co-founder John Danner with a mandate to hasten NetGravity's
growth.
</P>
<P>
   He and DoubleClick's top brass met at a hotel in Burlingame last
Wednesday, and spent the ensuing days fleshing out terms of a
possible merger with investment bankers. The secret talks, Spivey
said, were code named ``Project Ice Cream Scoop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even like ice cream,'' he noted. ``Someone on the
investment banking side liked ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, DoubleClick will issue 0.28 shares of
its common stock for each share of NetGravity stock. Based on
Monday's closing prices, this represents a 26-percent premium over
NetGravity's 30-day average price.
</P>
<P>
   NetGravity closed yesterday down $2 at $25.50, while DoubleClick
rose $2.50 to $96.50. Neither company has yet to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A combined offering is going to be very powerful, and no one
else will be able to offer the breadth and depth of what we have,''
Spivey said. ``We're going to be a very important company in this
space.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Spivey won't be on hand long to enjoy it. When the deal
is completed, probably in October, he has agreed to exit the stage.
``I'll have to get a new CEO job,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both companies have relationships with most major Web
publishers and advertisers domestically and internationally,''
DoubleClick's O'Connor said in a statement. ``NetGravity's
strengths combined with DoubleClick's technology infrastructure and
Abacus Direct's data will create a company uniquely positioned to
be the overall leader in targeted advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry was definitely due for some consolidation,'' said
Rob Martin, an analyst with Friedman, Billings, Ramsey in
Arlington, Va. ``This is making it happen.''
</P>
<P>
