<HEADER>
A8883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-CUTS-NYT &LR;      07-13 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DANGERS OF TAX CUTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the recent talk of cutting taxes, Congress rarely cuts
them when the economy is growing robustly, as it is now, and
unemployment is low. The worry among economists is that the extra
money in people's pockets may make an already strong economy too
strong, finally stoking inflation after a long period of relatively
stable prices.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that danger is hardly mentioned in the rising public debate
over the Republican and Democratic proposals for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? In part, it is because the advocates of the tax cuts,
as well as many of the opponents, agree that any reductions will
probably be small, at least in the initial years. Few analysts
expect any final tax cut to come close to the $864 billion over the
next decade that has been proposed by House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the tax cut proposals are phased in gradually over a
number of years,'' said Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., the chairman of
Congress' Joint Economic Committee and the author of a proposal to
cut taxes by $137 billion over 10 years, most of it toward the end
of the period. ``I think the immediate economic stimulus will be
small,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve, however, is concerned. ``If taxes were cut
while the nation's resources are highly employed, that would put
more pressure on monetary policy,'' Edward Gramlich, a Fed
governor, said. He suggested, in effect, that the Fed might have to
raise interest rates to prevent the extra spending that would
overstimulate the economy. Others worry that the higher rates might
reduce investment or bring down inflated stock prices, damaging the
economy through these avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices should already be reacting to the prospect of a tax
cut, some people say, but they have not so far because too many
people on Wall Street express doubt that tax cut legislation will
be enacted before next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bunch of friends on Wall Street have asked me why the
markets are so quiet about the tax cut proposals,'' said James E.
Glassman, a senior economist at Chase Manhattan Bank. ``Wall Street
is unusually quiet because it realizes that there will just be
gridlock on this issue near-term _ a lot of proposals and no real
action.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gramlich's concern reflects a view widely shared among
economists _ that broad tax cuts, covering most Americans, tend to
stimulate spending and therefore should be reserved for recessions
or periods of slow growth. In the early 1960s, President Kennedy
proposed a tax cut in this spirit, and President Reagan's tax cuts,
which started during a recession, contributed to the long expansion
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, President Johnson's 10 percent income tax cut,
carrying through on the original Kennedy proposal, came when the
economy had turned from the weak Kennedy years to the much more
robust mid-1960s. The Fed responded by raising rates.
</P>
<P>
   The altered mix was damaging, says Alan S. Blinder, a Princeton
University economist who served as Fed vice chairman from 1994 to
1996. The new mix _ higher interest rates to offset more fiscal
stimulus from the tax cut and from stepped-up spending for Vietnam
and for Johnson's social programs _ shifted the economy toward
consumption and away from investment. Inflation also got a
foothold.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists argue that fiscal policy has lost its punch
since the 1960s while monetary policy has evolved to the point that
the Fed can regulate the economy through interest rate adjustments,
offsetting tax cuts without damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monetary policy administered by the Fed is far more important
as far as economic stabilization is concerned and regulating
aggregate demand,'' said James Gwertney, the Republican-appointed
chief economist for the Joint Economic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Blinder disagrees. Monetary policy has its limits, he said. A
tax cut offset by higher interest rates ``would reverse the policy
mix that we have followed in the 1990s with such splendid effect:
low interest rates and high corporate investment,'' Blinder said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Kaufman, a Wall Street economist and consultant, adds a
related reason for not using the budget surplus to finance tax
cuts, as both parties now propose. ``With the surplus, we could
have some timely fiscal action when the economy goes inevitably
into recession,'' he said. ``We would not for once have to worry
about deficit financing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials argue that their more modest
tax cut proposal gets around the problem of encouraging too much
consumption. By offering incentives, particularly to the poor, to
invest the tax cuts in retirement accounts, they say, private
savings will rise, and the savings will then be available for
corporations to borrow and invest in productive equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But many economists argue that such tax rebates would not go
dollar for dollar into retirement accounts. Upper-income people in
particular have the wherewithal to shift savings from one account
to another to qualify for a tax refund, which would then be spent
on consumer goods, according to this view. That has been the
experience with individual retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the supply-side view. For supply-siders, tax cuts _
particularly a Republican proposal to reduce the capital gains tax
on the profit made from the sale of stocks and other assets _
encourage investment by reducing its risk. While supply-siders are
a distinct minority among economists, they are a vocal one in the
incipient debate about a tax cut's impact on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In their view, suppliers, not consumers, are the chief economic
actors. And suppliers respond to tax cuts by investing their
capital in new supply. Far from stimulating demand beyond an
economy's capacity, the supply-siders argue, a tax cut increases
the supply of goods and services, which are then consumed.
</P>
<P>
   No one pushes this view harder than Jude Wanniski, an economics
consultant and adviser to Steve Forbes and various other
Republicans involved in tax cutting proposals. ``The government, by
cutting tax rates, is simply removing the barrier to investment,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
