<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-PBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSY ERUPTS ON EVE OF PBS FUNDING DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What had promised to be a triumph for public
broadcasting erupted into a bitter dispute Tuesday, as House
Republicans discovered that a Boston television station had
divulged its donor list to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be a new era for the Corporation for Public
Broadcasting. Newt Gingrich, the former House speaker who once
threatened to ``zero out'' funding for the public network, was
gone. Political support from both parties was at an all-time high.
House members were to work on a bill Wednesday that would give an
unprecedented $525 million in new funds to public broadcasters
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But after learning Tuesday that Boston's WGBH-TV handed its
donor list to the Democratic Party earlier this year, several
Republicans on the House Commerce Committee shifted their stance,
demanding a reexamination of public broadcasting as a whole. Now,
instead of preparing to debate a funding increase, House members
are poised to again fight the so-called Battle of Big Bird over
whether to fund a system Republicans accuse of pandering to the
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been besieged with calls this afternoon from
Republicans wanting everything from reducing funding for public
broadcasting to providing criminal penalties. There are some
members who would like to sanction the station,'' said Ken Johnson,
a spokesman for Representative W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin, a Louisiana
Republican who is chairman of the telecommunications subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing is, it undermines our effort to foster
bipartisan support for public broadcasting,'' Johnson added.
Johnson said Tauzin and Representative Edward J. Markey of
Massachusetts, the top Democrat on the subcommittee, had ``worked
very hard in recent years to dispel the myth that public
broadcasting is a left-leaning, liberal organization.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Johnson added, ``this type of activity by WGBH feeds all
the old stereotypes.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at WGBH first admitted cooperating with the Democratic
Party more than two months ago. In May, a spokeswoman said some
recent hires at the station had initiated an informal swap with
Democrats, handing over the names of several thousand public
broadcasting donors in exchange for a comparable list of political
contributors. When the incident came to light, WGBH officials
apologized, saying it was in clear violation of station rules.
</P>
<P>
   But the congressional fallout did not come until Tuesday, when a
copy of a May 8 Boston Globe article about the incident was
circulated by Republican staff members at a meeting of the House
Commerce subcommittee that oversees the funding. Immediately
afterward, several Republican members, who had remained quiet on
the issue, began lining up amendments _ a procedural maneuver that
could effectively put the authorization on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe funding for public broadcasting is going to
suffer,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Markey sounded more optimistic. Though describing what WGBH did
as ``wrong, and a mistake,'' he said it ``shouldn't interfere with
our ability to authorize funding for public broadcasting for the
entire United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The reauthorization bill would provide $400 million over five
years for public broadcasters to switch to a digital transmitting
system, which they are required by law to do by 2003. It would also
add approximately $175 million to the $350 million appropriation
that public broadcasting received last year. The money would go to
the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, the umbrella organization
of the nation's public broadcasting stations, including the Public
Broadcasting Service and National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   The political explosion caught many public broadcasters by
surprise. Just last week, it appeared the funding for public
broadcasting would face far less opposition than ever before.
Democrats, Republicans, and media analysts said the climate in
Washington had noticeably changed since 1994, when Gingrich called
the national network of public radio and TV stations a ``little
sandbox for the rich.''
</P>
<P>
   A massive public outcry followed earlier Republican threats to
kill the Public Broadcasting Service. WGBH says its donations
doubled in 1995 and 1996, with more than $1 million in new
contributions those years as opposed to the $500,000 in new
donations in years past. At the same time, public broadcasters
started to notice less resistance from Republicans, who many
believed discovered a suburban constituency that watched PBS and
listened to National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as Monday, Jeanne M. Hopkins, vice president for
communications at WGBH, described the prospects for public
broadcasting as ``much more positive than we ever expected.''
Tuesday night, she sounded far less upbeat as she learned of the
political tornado gathering speed on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were completely out front the minute it happened. It was a
mistake,'' Hopkins said. ``It doesn't seem all of public
broadcasting should be affected by one mistake at one station. This
was not a partisan act. It was an individual, human error.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
