<HEADER>
A8891 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLER-VICTIMS     07-13 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-VICTIMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEVED TOWNSFOLK WELCOME NEWS OF SUSPECT'S ARREST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TERRY KLIEWER 
and JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEIMAR, Texas _ The freight trains still rumble through town day
and night, but for the first time in weeks folks here don't have to
worry that one of them is carrying accused serial killer Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mexican fugitive's surrender to authorities Tuesday
morning in El Paso, this farm town of 2,300 residents in west
Colorado County can reclaim a semblance of its peaceful former
self.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where two of the eight victims thus far attributed to
Resendez-Ramirez were killed. The bodies of the Rev. Norman
``Skip'' Sirnic, 46, and his wife, Karen, 47, were found May 2 in
their home near the railroad tracks that bisect the town. They had
been bludgeoned to death.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a month later and only a few miles west of here in Fayette
County, 73-year-old Josephine Konvicka was murdered, presumably by
the same killer.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities mounted a nationwide manhunt, but the fear in this
town was that the elusive killer might return in the dead of night
to kill again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of families have been sleeping altogether in one room,
with the lights on and the doors double-locked, since this began,''
said Mayor Bennie Kosler. ``This (surrender) is a great thing to be
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon Tuesday, Kosler was just about talked out,
having been collared by almost every one of the dozen or more
out-of-town reporters prowling the town for reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was, in a word, relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought he'd give himself up,'' said Kosler, 67.
``Some of these guys can hide forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Crelier, a 66-year-old resident of nearby Columbus who
pastures cattle near Weimar, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure didn't think he'd ever surrender,'' Crelier said. ``A
lot of us figured he'd come back here a third time just to prove he
could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barney Kasper, owner of the local meat market, said he had kept
six guns _ a couple of pistols, three rifles and a shotgun, all
loaded _ at the ready in his house outside town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed everyone in my family where the guns were, just in
case they needed them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Leticia's Mexican Restaurant, waitresses Raquel Guerrero and
Ema Cedillo, whose homes are within a few blocks of the tracks,
were looking forward to being able to actually sleep through the
night hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night I heard a noise at the window. My husband said it
was probably a cat, but I couldn't close my eyes the rest of the
night,'' Guerrero said. ``We're so glad this is over.''
</P>
<P>
   For Police Chief Bill Livingston, Tuesday was marked by
long-awaited phone calls to Lubbock and College Station in Texas,
then to Colorado and California to tell relatives of the Sirnics
that Resendez-Ramirez had been taken into custody. Later, the chief
drove to Houston for a news conference related to the suspect's
arrival and booking at the Harris County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by phone from Santa Maria, Calif., Norman N. Sirnic,
the minister's 70-year-old father, said he had figured Tuesday
would be ``terrible'' because it had been the scheduled date for
his son and daughter-in-law to arrive there for a long-planned
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really feeling down today,'' he confessed. ``(But) it
turned out it's rather satisfying now that we have him in custody.
It bothered me this guy was still running loose and could kill
somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Sirnic's son was the pastor at Weimar United Church of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   From Lubbock, Anna Belle Mohr, the minister's mother, said she
was ``very pleased'' at news of the fugitive's surrender. But she
said her grief would linger: ``I would never wish this kind of pain
on anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she wasn't sure what punishment Resendez-Ramirez
deserves if he is convicted of murder, she said his alleged crimes,
in her view, ``just prove he's an animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in Weimar privately share that view, agreeing in so many
words with the opinion of Keith Foltermann, Karen Siric's brother
and a College Station-area game warden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think society as a whole tends to look for excuses for
everybody,'' he said by phone. ``But some people are just bad.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the sorts of conflicting emotions people here expect
to be sorting through and trying to resolve for weeks to come. To
help in the process, city officials planned a community memorial
service for 7:30 p.m. Wednesday at the high school athletic
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling of celebration, I guess,'' Mayor Kosler
said. ``But before we celebrate I believe we should thank God this
was brought to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
