Unaffected by a night of dining and dancing, members of the World
Cup-winning team welcomed a few hundred fans on Tuesday in midtown
by thanking them for their support. (Librado Romero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) JERUSALEM -- July 13, 1999 -- ISRAEL-BARAK, 07-13 --
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak earlier this week. In an
interview with the New York Times on Tuesday, Barak, a former
general, said he is weary of doing battle and wants to forge a
regional peace agreement that ``works for everyone.'' (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- July 13, 1999 -- GENETIC-ALTERING-FOOD,
07-13 -- Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman talks with Patricia
Klintberg, left, Washington editor of the Farm Journal, as Gene
Grabowski, vice president of Communications for the Grocery
Manufacturers of America looks on at center on Monday at the
National Press Club. Glickman announced that his department will
request voluntary labeling of genetically altered products. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- July 13, 1999 -- TEN-DAVIS-LONGWOOD-BOS-B&AMP;W,
07-13 -- Rod Laver plays a match at Longwood Cricket Club in 1971.
Though tennis has been played here since 1911, the longevity of the
club's name is perhaps a tribute to Boston's devotion to changing
nothing. (John Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- July 13, 1999 -- BBO-ALLST-WOMEN-BOS, 07-13 --
Major League Baseball officials from left, Leslie Sullivan, vice
president of broadcasting and new media; Kathy Francis, vice
president of marketing; Marla Miller, vice president of special
events and Colette Phillips, head of Colette Phillips Public
Relations of FanFest. On the field and in the dugouts at Fenway
Park it will be all men in uniform, the stars of the game. But
anyone spending any time behind the scenes around Boston this week
knows that the All-Star Game clearly is not just another ``guy
thing.'' Women are playing key roles. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- July 13, 1999 -- BBO-ALLST-GRIFFEY-BOS, 07-13
-- Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs, left, jokes with Ken Griffey Jr.
of the Seattle Mariners before Monday's home run contest in Fenway
Park. Griffey's popularity with fans surprises even him. For a
variety of reasons, Griffey, Seattle's center fielder, has emerged
not only as the top vote-getter for the 70th All-Star Game at
Fenway Park (for the fourth consecutive season), but also as one of
the most marketable athletes in pro sports. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands -- July 13, 1999 --
VIRGIN-SYNAGOGUE-2-COX, 07-09 -- The sand-covered floor at the
Blessing and Peace and Loving Deeds synagogue will not be touched
during the synagogue's $350,000 renovation. The floor's meaning can
be traced to the Sephardic Jews of Spain who used sand to muffle
the sounds of their movements during prayer so as not to be
discovered and killed during the Inquisition. The synagogue, which
dates from 1833, is the oldest continuously used synagogue under
the American flag. (Shelley Emling/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands -- July 13, 1999 --
VIRGIN-SYNAGOGUE-COX, 07-09 -- The Blessing and Peace and Loving
Deeds synagogue on St. Thomas in the U.S. Virgin Islands, which
dates from 1833, is the oldest continuously used synagogue under
the American flag. A $350,000 project to restore the synagogue's
original beauty is underway and is expected to be completed by
December. (Shelley Emling/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
