<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8897 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAILKILLINGS-1000(2TA     07-13 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILKILLINGS-1000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-RAILKILLINGS-SURRENDER, BC-RAILKILLINGS-TIMELINE) 
SUSPECT IN RAILWAY KILLINGS SURRENDERS TO TEXAS RANGER
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by BC-RAILKILLINGS-VICTIMS,(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By R.A. DYER and DIANE SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A 39-year-old Mexican drifter suspected of killing
eight people and striking fear in people who live along railroad
tracks throughout the south, surrendered peacefully Tuesday in El
Paso in an arrangement brokered by his sister and a rookie Texas
Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, referred to by the FBI as Rafael Resendez-Ramirez _
one of 30 aliases he has been known to use _ was whisked to Houston
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He was being held on a burglary charge until authorities conduct
DNA tests that they say could link him to five slayings in Texas.
He already faces murder charges in two deaths in Illinois and one
in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Devon Anderson, the assistant Harris County district attorney,
said Resendez-Ramirez will be arraigned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest ended a six-week, nationwide manhunt for the man
authorities believe is the so-called railway serial killer, who on
June 21 was placed on the FBI's 10 Most Wanted list.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez, whose real name is believed to be Angel
Leoncio Reyes Resendiz, was accompanied by his brother as he rode
part way across an international bridge linking Juarez, Mexico, and
southeast El Paso. A second vehicle carried other relatives, and a
sister in the Immigration and Naturalization Service at the bridge
communicated with him by cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 feet from the U.S. border, the pickup carrying
Resendez-Ramirez stopped and he walked to the border and
surrendered to Texas Ranger Sgt. Drew Carter.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect was quickly handcuffed and led away to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carter told me that he extended his hand, they shook hands,
and he handcuffed him. He was very pleasant, not aggressive,'' said
Bruce Casteel, Department of Public Safety senior captain and
commander of the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of law-enforcement officials took part in the search
for Resendez-Ramirez, and authorities throughout Texas received
reports of possible sightings of the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   But police acknowledged Tuesday that they were never certain of
his whereabouts until his dramatic arrival at the U.S. border
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the course of the past few days, a special agent for
the FBI, a deputy United States Marshal and a Texas Ranger have
been negotiating for Ramirez's surrender,'' said FBI Special Agent
Don Clark of Houston. ``Mission accomplished, for the moment. ...
Law enforcement has done this country a great service by getting
this guy off the street.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton issued a statement thanking law enforcement
agencies for their work on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Americans can rest easier knowing that law enforcement
authorities will bring the full force of the law to bear in this
case,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   DPS spokesman Mike Cox said the break in the case came during
the weekend when Carter received a call from Resendez-Ramirez's
sister while on a fishing trip to the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The sister, who lives in Albuquerque, N.M., said she had been in
touch with Resendez-Ramirez through an intermediary, apparently
their brother.
</P>
<P>
   Carter and federal investigators met with the sister Sunday
night and Monday to discuss a surrender on a burglary warrant
related to the slaying of a doctor in the Houston suburb of West
University Place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sister told Carter that he would only surrender to a Texas
Ranger, not any other officer,'' Cox said. ``This again really adds
to the Texas Ranger mythology.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who turned 32 Tuesday and has been a Ranger for less
than a year, had established a rapport with the sister, Cox said.
He had appeared for three consecutive weeks on the television show
``America's Most Wanted'' to discuss the search for
Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   The surrender agreement included assurances that
Resendez-Ramirez will get a psychological evaluation, will be safe
in jail, and can be visited by his family, Casteel said.
</P>
<P>
   But it does not shield Resendez-Ramirez from the death penalty
if he is charged with capital murder in Texas, Casteel said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Resendez-Ramirez would surrender to face the death
penalty, Casteel said, ``I've been in this business a very long
time, and I'm struggling to answer that myself right now.''
</P>
<P>
   At a brief court appearance in El Paso, Resendez-Ramirez was
handcuffed and chained around the waist. He was asked by Magistrate
James Carter if he had any questions about the burglary charge
against him and whether he had any other questions. Twice
Resendez-Ramirez responded softly, ``No, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   He was then put on a small plane with Carter, another Ranger, an
FBI agent and a U.S. Marshal for the flight to Houston, and slept
for much of the flight, a DPS spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, he emerged from the plane wearing jeans, a striped
long-sleeved shirt and gold-rimmed glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Although Resendez-Ramirez is charged with two murders in
Illinois and one in Kentucky, he apparently will be tried first in
Texas, Casteel said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Resendez-Ramirez could be charged with ``probably at
least five'' Texas slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Word of Resendez-Ramirez's arrest spread quickly in Weimar, a
community between Houston and San Antonio where he is suspected of
killing three people.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we didn't believe it, it was too good to be true,''
said Larry Wick, one of the owners of M-G Farm Service Center in
Weimar.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Since May 2 when Weimar minister Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic, 47, and
his wife, Karen, 47, were found dead in their home near the
railroad tracks, the community of about 2,000 has been jolted out
of its tranquil routine.
</P>
<P>
   The second blow came June 4 when Josephine Konvicka, 73, was
found slain in her Fayette County home about three miles from the
Sirnics'.
</P>
<P>
   Wick said his store normally sells four to six guns a month, but
sold 61 in June because people were afraid that the killer would
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has not been a typical summer,'' Wick said. ``Normally,
late in the evening, you would see people out walking at night,
kids out playing in the yard. You haven't seen any of that. Doors
have been locked, people have been sleeping in one room. When you
have three murders in a town of 2,000, people get pretty worried.
Maybe now we can start relaxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Konvicka's 17-year-old grandson, Allen Konvicka of Schulenberg,
said he had borrowed a lawnmower from his grandmother about six
hours before authorities say she was killed.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his family were angered when reports surfaced
that Resendez-Ramirez had been in custody of the INS on June 2 _
before his grandmother was killed _ and then deported.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made me mad, very mad,'' he said. ``They could have
locked him up and that would have been the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wick said the INS' release of Resendez-Ramirez ``basically cost
four more lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe an agency could do that, though we
understand the fact that they process a million-and-a-half coming
across the border,'' he said. ``We still couldn't understand how
they would let him slip through. I guess you could say the system
let us down.''
</P>
<P>
   INS Commissioner Doris Meissner said the Justice Department is
looking into why Resendez-Ramirez ``was not detained and whether
INS knew about Resendez-Ramirez's criminal activities after being
contacted by local law enforcement earlier this year.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Bill Hanna contributed to this report, which
includes material from The Associated Press.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
