agricultural land to the growing suburbs. (Tom Smart/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SALT LAKE CITY -- July 13, 1999 -- SPRAWL-2, 07-13 --
Traffic makes its way past construction on Interstate I-15. Two
thousand workers are pouring concrete around the clock, turning six
lanes of Interstate 15 into 12 lanes through Salt Lake City and its
loping suburbs. Salt Lake City and Milwaukee, two cities with
roughly equal metropolitan populations (about 1.5 million), each
having declared war on urban sprawl, are examples of how federal
transportation subsidies are still one of the biggest forces
shaping urban areas .(Tom Smart/New York Times Photo)
</P>
