<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8902 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HISPANI     07-13 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON HISPANICS BELIEVE RACIAL TENSIONS MAY ENDURE DESPITE
SUSPECT'S ARREST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Tilde needed over n in Trevino) 
 
By EDWARD HEGSTROM 
and MARIA LUISA PEREZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Tuesday's arrest of Rafael Resendez-Ramirez came as a
particular relief to many Hispanics in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one Latino does something wrong, then people blame everyone
with dark skin,'' said Pablo Trevino, a restaurant worker from
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally!'' said Alberto, a painter who recently moved to
Houston from Honduras. ``He has made it more difficult to find
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the manhunt began, local immigrant-rights advocates say
police have begun stopping more Hispanics, some of whom said they
were mistaken for him.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Jimenez, local director of the American Friends Service
Committee, said racial tensions have increased because of
Resendez-Ramirez and the ensuing search for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our office has been getting some terrible calls from people,
sounding mostly elderly, about Mexicans looking alike, saying they
were `small, dirty and ugly,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Resendez-Ramirez is now behind bars, Jimenez said the
tensions may endure, because it exacerbates two of the worst
stereotypes of immigrants: That they are violent criminals and
drifters who cross the border illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people will say all Latinos are bad,'' said Santiago
Gaspar Bareno, a Guatemalan who works at a Mexican restaurant.
``The truth is, most of us are here because we want to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Mexicans also expressed concern that Resendez-Ramirez may
be put to death if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they don't kill him,'' said Jose Luis Garanza, a native
of Mexico, which does not have the death penalty. ``They can give
him life in prison, but he's a human being, and he shouldn't be
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   A ranking official in the office of the Mexican president,
contacted in Mexico City, said the government would likely make a
diplomatic plea if Resendez-Ramirez is condemned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult case,'' said the official, who asked to
remain anonymous. ``But if he gets the death penalty we will almost
certainly ask that it be commuted to life in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodulfo Figueroa, Mexico's consul general in Houston, said
Resendez must be considered innocent until he has been tried and
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts in the United States still have to prove that he is
guilty,'' Figueroa said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the consulate is prepared to provide him legal
assistance, but no special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do with him the same as with any other Mexican who is
in trouble,'' Figueroa said. ``We will contact him and help him in
his defense because he is for sure going to need legal help.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
