<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-STUDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITY WOMEN ARE NOT GETTING TO THE TOP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the efforts of companies to diversify their top
management, many minority women say there are few cracks in the
``concrete ceiling,'' the social barriers that they say prevent
them from reaching the top of Corporate America. They are lagging
behind both white women and minority men in the kind of jobs they
hold and the pay they receive, according to government statistics.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey, the largest of its kind, of minority women
managers and professionals found that many of these women view
their company's diversity programs as largely ineffective and say
opportunities have not improved over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have known intuitively, and this report validates
it, that women of color have not progressed at the same rate,''
said J.T. Childs Jr., the vice president for global work force
diversity at International Business Machines in Armonk, N.Y., who
was on the advisory board for the study.
</P>
<P>
   While companies have sought to employ and promote more women and
minorities, many have neglected the specific issues that concern
minority women, said Sheila W. Wellington, the president of
Catalyst, the New York not-for-profit group that conducted the
three-year study. Catalyst, which focuses on issues concerning
women managers and professionals, surveyed 1,735 black,
Asian-American and Hispanic women at 30 large U.S. companies and
conducted dozens of focus groups and individual interviews. The
study, which did not provide comparative data for minority men, was
financed by the Ford Foundation and 18 companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau of Labor statistics, although they do not specifically
address Asian-American women, indicate that minority women managers
and professionals are earning less than their white and male
counterparts. Black and Hispanic women have seen the gap widen over
the last five years. In 1998, for example, Hispanic women made
roughly 60 percent of what white male managers did, while they made
nearly 70 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are engaged in talking to women of color at your
corporation, this is the kind of thing you hear. You may not like
to hear it,'' said Paul A. Allaire, the chairman of Xerox and a
Catalyst board member, who said the company modified its programs
once it realized that programs focusing on women and minorities
were not addressing the specific needs of minority women.
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly competitive and diverse labor market, and
faced with the changing profile of its customers, more and more
businesses are struggling with the need to hire minorities,
including women, and to make sure they stay. ``Our customer base
includes a strong representation of minority women,'' said Stephen
W. Sanger, the chief executive of General Mills Inc. ``Our talent
pool is that same group of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The study's most dramatic findings center on the usefulness of
diversity programs. While three-quarters of the 500 largest U.S.
companies have some sort of policy or program in place to encourage
diversity, according to Catalyst, they are not viewed as an
effective force of change. Slightly more than half of the minority
women surveyed thought that the diversity programs failed to
address subtle racism or sexism in the workplace, compared with a
third that agreed that diversity programs at their company created
a supportive environment. Only 26 percent said they thought career
development was an important aspect of diversity programs.
</P>
<P>
   While Catalyst has long studied the advancement of women, the
study and the experiences of some of the companies make clear that
minority women do not necessarily benefit from general initiatives
to foster diversity. At Motorola Inc., for example, the push to
advance women in the early  &UR; ' &LR; 90s did little to help minority
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were moving women, but we were basically moving white
women,'' said Roberta Gutman, the vice president and director for
global diversity at Motorola, one of the three executives invited
by Catalyst to talk about the findings at a news conference
Tuesday. By 1995, only two or three of the 25 women vice presidents
were minorities, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Only after Motorola began to focus on the issue of making sure
minority women were promoted and included in its executive ranks
did the company make progress: it now now has 11 vice presidents
who are minority women out of its 54 women vice presidents, Ms.
Gutman said.
</P>
<P>
   Catalyst also found striking differences among white women and
minority women in their perceptions of the progress that has been
made. In similar surveys, 60 percent of white women thought that
there had been improvements in their opportunities over the last
five years, while only 47 percent of minority women agreed.
</P>
<P>
   What many minority women say hinders them from advancing,
according to Catalyst, is the lack of a mentor or the chance to
network informally with colleagues. Even joining in a simple game
of golf can be challenging, as one of the panelists, Karen Fukuma,
the chief financial officer the Lotus Development Corp., which is
owned by IBM, recounted. ``I never have been given an opportunity
to play with the men since I have been at IBM for 20 years,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The message for companies, Ms. Wellington said, is that managers
must step in to help minority women navigate organizational
politics and plan their careers. ``Managers of women of color must
receive training and support from managers and corporate leaders so
they can be both mentor and manager,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The other concern voiced by minority women is that their
companies are paying little more than lip service to the issue.
Less than 20 percent of the minority women surveyed said that their
managers were held accountable for or rewarded for their efforts to
advance minority women.
</P>
<P>
   The study also highlighted significant differences among
different minority groups. ``Most corporate programs approach women
of color as a monolithic group,'' Ms. Wellington said. While the
majority of African-American women surveyed felt as if they were
stereotyped, for example, Asian-American women are least likely
among minority women to be supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a national issue. The monochromatic, monolithic
company will not survive into the future,'' she said. ``It will not
be ready for the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
