<HEADER>
A8905 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAILWAY-KILLER-ART-1S     07-13 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILWAY-KILLER-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE SUSPECTED OF KILLING 8 PEOPLE IS ARRESTED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for inserts, rewriting throughout; adds art note)   (ART ADV: photo and map are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Mexican fugitive suspected of killing eight people
in three states, avoiding capture by hopping freight trains,
surrendered peacefully on Tuesday in El Paso, after members of his
family negotiated his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the suspect, Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, a 39-year-old
drifter from Mexico, walked across a bridge from Ciudad Juarez,
Mexico, to turn himself in, he had become the most-wanted fugitive
in two countries, a man the authorities here say could be
responsible for many more murders than those for which he has been
sought.
</P>
<P>
   The search for him involved thousands of investigators around
the country and in Mexico, who despite an endless supply of tips,
were often thrown off the trail by an elusive suspect.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it was a simple telephone call from his sister
who lives in Albuquerque, N.M., to a Texas ranger, Andrew Carter,
who told the ranger, ``We need to talk,'' according to Mike Cox, a
spokesman for the Texas Department of Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought her brother was ready to surrender,'' said Cox,
who would not reveal the sister's name.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Resendez-Ramirez would surrender even though he faces
the death penalty if convicted, Bruce Casteel, commander of the
Texas Rangers, said, ``I've been in this business a very long time,
and I'm struggling to answer that myself right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Local prosecutors, however, agreed to allow Resendez-Ramirez to
have family members visit him in jail and to have a psychological
examination.
</P>
<P>
   For months leading to the surrender, news of Resendez-Ramirez's
alleged exploits terrified people living and working near railroad
tracks, especially in Texas, where five of the eight victims were
found over the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   When he struck, said the authorities who knew him as ``the
railroad killer,'' the anonymity of freight yards and rails
provided a safe backdrop. Federal and state investigators, who have
collaborated on one of the biggest manhunts in recent years, say
the proximity to railyards of the five deaths in Texas, plus one
other, two years ago in Kentucky, has been one of the most obvious
similarities in building cases against Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   But other evidence also convinced investigators that the murders
were committed by the same person, including the means by which the
victims were killed _ savage beating with blunt objects _ and
fingerprints and other evidence that the authorities say tie the
killings to Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   And the authorities say he could be responsible for many other
deaths. Don Clark, an agent with the FBI in Houston, told reporters
on Tuesday afternoon that since Resendez-Ramirez's surrender ``50
to 60 other police departments have requested information to see if
he is connected to unsolved murders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We used every tool possible to make this come about,'' Clark
added of the capture of Resendez-Ramirez, who was added to the
FBI's 10 Most Wanted List on June 21. ``But we're not finished in
this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The big break in the case came through the telephone call on
Sunday night to the Texas Rangers, which is the state police, from
Resendez-Ramirez's sister, said Tela Mange, a spokeswoman for the
Houston Department of Public Safety. ``She said he wanted to come
in.''
</P>
<P>
   That conversation led to others between Ranger Carter and the
sister as well as with other relatives of Resendez-Ramirez's in the
United States. Ms. Mange said that a written agreement was drafted
that outlined terms of a surrender, and the family accepted late
Monday night or early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities stressed on Tuesday that they made no promises
to Resendez-Ramirez that he would avoid execution by surrendering.
Since the death penalty was declared constitutional in 1976, Texas
has put more inmates to death, 180, than any other state.
</P>
<P>
   With the agreement in place, Resendez-Ramirez walked across the
bridge into El Paso early on Tuesday morning to give himself up.
Later, the authorities flew him here, where he was placed in the
Harris County jail in downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Handcuffed when taken into custody, Resendez-Ramirez looked
tired and wan as he appeared before a state magistrate in El Paso
on a pending burglary charge from the Houston area. He wore a
wrinkled blue-stripped shirt, tattered blue jeans and aviator-style
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   He looked no different, although perhaps a little more tired, as
he emerged from a twin-engine state plane that flew him into
Houston. The authorities said he slept for part of the flight.
</P>
<P>
   He was questioned by law-enforcement officials at the Houston
police department on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he is expected to face murder charges, stemming from the
five killings in Texas that investigators say he is linked to.
</P>
<P>
   He is currently facing two murder charges in Illinois in
connection with the June 15 shotgun slayings of an elderly man and
his daughter. Another murder charge is pending in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy was to put as much pressure as we could on this
individual so that he would have no place to hide,'' Clark said.
``The investigation left no place to turn.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, the search for Resendez-Ramirez exasperated
federal authorities in the United States _ even though Border
Patrol agents picked him up on June 2 and released him into Mexico.
They apparently did not know that the FBI was searching for him and
that the Houston police had told the Immigration and Naturalization
Service that Resendez-Ramirez was wanted for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after he was released, a 73-year-old woman from Fayette
County, Texas, Josephine Konvicka, was found beaten to death in her
home. And a day later, Noemie Dominguez, 26, a Houston
schoolteacher, was found beaten to death in her home.
</P>
<P>
   Her car was found in Del Rio, a Texas border town, with
fingerprints that the authorities say could be Resendez-Ramirez's.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the investigation, Resendez-Ramirez had remained a
mysterious figure. Even his true identity was uncertain since
investigators say he has used more than 30 aliases. Born in the
Mexican city of Puebla, he first entered the United States
illegally in 1976, when he was arrested in Brownsville by INS
agents.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 23 years, Resendez-Ramirez led the life of a
transient, illegally jumping freight cars from Mexico into the
United States. His adventures carried him from Vermont to
California, and he bounced in and out of federal prisons and local
jails on a long string of immigration violations and other minor
non-violent offenses.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his non-violent history, investigators say they have
linked him through physical evidence, including fingerprints in
some of the cases, to the five Texas killings as well as the
slayings in Illinois and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The first murder occurred on Aug. 29, 1997, when Christopher
Maier was killed along the railroad tracks in Lexington. Maier's
girlfriend was raped and beaten but survived the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Maier case remained unsolved and Resendez-Ramirez had
apparently not yet emerged as a suspect in 1998. He was stopped by
border agents and deported six times that year, the last in April.
Eight months later, the first of the five related Texas murders
occurred when Dr. Claudia Benton, 39, was raped and stabbed to
death inside her home in West University Place on Dec. 17, 1998.
Then, on April 30, the Rev. Norman Sirnic and his wife, Karen, were
bludgeoned with a sledgehammer inside their home in Weimar, Texas.
Fingerprints and other evidence linked Resendez-Ramirez to the
crime, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   But the big break came Sunday. Cox, the spokesman for the Texas
Department of Public Safety, said that Ranger Carter had first
visited the suspect's sister about two or three weeks ago at her
home in Albuquerque and had remained in regular telephone contact
with her. At the same time, the sister apparently had contacted
another brother in Mexico who knew the whereabouts of the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of receiving the cellular call on his fishing trip,
Carter flew to Albuquerque with an FBI agent and a U.S. Marshal to
meet with the sister. By Monday, an agreement had been drafted by
the Harris County District Attorney's Office in Houston that
offered the suspect and his family three things: a pledge of safety
in the Harris County jail, the promise of regular visits from his
family and a full psychological examination.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said that winning the trust of Resendez-Ramirez's sister was
essential in breaking the case. He said that Carter, 32, ``was able
to build up some rapport and trust with them'' and ultimately his
siblings and a family minister convinced the suspect to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Though Clark was noncommital when asked if the sister would
receive the $125,000 reward offered in the case, other officials
said it appeared that she would.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
