<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8908 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-INTEL_SFCHRON//     07-13 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-INTEL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRECTS HEADLINE, CORRECTS HEADLINE  
   
  
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON//CORRECTS HEADLINE   Intel's Earnings Miss Mark 
 &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Intel reported quarterly sales and earnings yesterday that were
slightly below expectations, in part because the company succeeded
so well in its efforts to sell more cheap chips for low-cost PCs.
<P>
   The Santa Clara chip giant announced revenues of $6.7 billion
for its second quarter, which ended June 26. That is a 14-percent
increase from $5.9 billion in the same quarter a year ago, but 5
percent below first-quarter 1999 revenues of $7.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Intel had forecast months ago that revenues would be flat or
down slightly compared to the first quarter, but the final figure
was, in the words of Chief Financial Officer Andy Bryant, ``at the
lower end of this guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnings for the second quarter were $1.7 billion, a 49-percent
jump from $1.2 billion the same period last year, when Intel and
the PC industry were beset by excess inventory. But earnings were
down 13 percent from this year's first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings were 51 cents per share, falling short of the 53 cents
analysts were expecting, according to First Call Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call for analysts, Intel Executive Vice
President Paul Otellini described the company's last two quarters
as ``a perfectly normal first half.'' He also said Intel looks
forward to ``a pretty good second half.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Revenues were below expectations, and it looks like it was
caused by average selling price coming down,'' said analyst Steve
Salopek of Stein Roe &AMP; Farnham in Chicago. ``They (Intel) went
after market share at the low end, and cut prices more than people
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   According to analyst Mark Edelstone of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter in San Francisco, the average selling price for Intel chips
in recent years has been between $205 and $215. ``In the second
quarter,'' he said, ``we believe it dropped to $207.''
</P>
<P>
   The price decline reflected increased sales of Intel's
entry-level chip, the Celeron. The company has priced the chip
aggressively in an effort to stop the market-share growth of its
principal competitor, Advanced Micro Devices of Sunnyvale. In
recent quarters, AMD had been gaining ground by marketing its K6
chips to a growing roster of companies making low-end PCs for home
and small-business users.
</P>
<P>
   Intel officials said they had succeeded in regaining market
share in this ``value segment,'' or low end. But they confirmed
that price cuts had reduced the average selling price for their
chips. Unit volumes were also down slightly compared to the first
quarter, a normal seasonal pattern.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of declining prices, Intel managed to hold its gross
margins steady last quarter at 59 percent, and officials predicted
that for the full year the figure would rise to around 60 percent.
They credited across-the-board cost reductions, including a switch
to new packaging that makes the Celeron cheaper to produce.
</P>
<P>
   Otellini also cited strong increases in sales of the company's
current flagship product, the Pentium III. During the current
quarter, he predicted, unit sales of the chip will pass those of
its predecessor, the Pentium II.
</P>
<P>
   He said Intel expects sales of the Xeon, a series of
Pentium-derived chips designed for powerful server computers, to
``lift a bit'' in the coming quarter. After a delay of more than
four months, the company will soon release a new set of related
chips that will allow PC-makers to combine eight Xeons in one
top-of-the-line system.
</P>
<P>
   If Intel's aggressive campaign to bolster its market share
weakened the company's bottom line, it did even more damage to AMD.
The Sunnyvale company will not report its results for the last
quarter until later today, but last month it warned investors to
expect losses of around $200 million because of lower shipments and
average prices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
