<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLST-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAVER SOUR ON PITCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It is an endless debate but you hear it a lot these
days. Today's pitchers just don't have it when compared to the
heros of the 60s and 70s. And when Tom Seaver says so, you listen.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Seaver is living in past glory. He is a
broadcaster for the New York Mets, and his views are as respected
today as they were during his 20-year career, which ended in Boston
in 1986. Seaver is a fan of Pedro Martinez, whom he declared a
``throwback'' to the breed of pitchers once common in the major
leagues . . . talented and smart.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not so sure about the rest of the class of 1999, which
includes some of the highest-paid pitchers in baseball history.
They are giving up runs and base hits at almost a disgraceful rate.
Why? Most of them just don't understand what pitching is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are the hitters so successful?'' said Seaver, who was in
town with several other Hall of Famers who were named to the
All-Century team that was honored in Boston Tuesday as part of the
70th All-Star celebration. ``I think it's bad pitching. Pitchers
don't get enough innings in the minor league. They're afraid to
throw inside. It's the intimidation factor. Pitchers are doing a
lot of basic things wrong. I see more 2-0, 3-0, 3-1 counts. They're
giving hitters more chances to hit the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a person who loves his trade, it's embarrassing for me.
It's bad for the pitching fraternity. If you give Mark McGwire a
2-0, 3-1 count in the same at bat, you're going to get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a theme heard often Tuesday from Hall of Fame players
assembled by Major League Baseball. Seaver, who posted a 311-205
record and appeared in 10 All-Star Games, Bob Gibson, and Warren
Spahn were just three pitchers who beat teams the old-fashioned
way. They challenged you.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't jam people anymore,'' said Spahn, baseball's
all-time winningest lefthander. ``I've seen McGwire play and I
admired him because he was strong. I know what I would have done.
If his bat was over the plate, I worked inside. But today you just
don't see inside pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think ownership has encouraged this. They lowered the mound
and made the ball livelier. The turf has hurt pitching and it's
tough on defensive people. It goes back to the days of Babe Ruth.
Yankee Stadium was constructed the way it was because owners
believed that people wanted to see home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Robinson, another Hall of Famer, agreed that the delicate
balance between hitters and pitchers has changed the past two
decades, and baseball has suffered because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing,'' said Robinson. ``Today's pitchers would
have a hard time measuring up to Seaver. He was a professional
pitcher. There's a difference between pitching and throwing. You
saw more pitching in those days. Today you see more throwing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw more throwing inside. But when I played, pitchers had
the right to throw inside. That was part of the game. Today, the
hitters don't think that pitchers have the right to even throw
inside. They want the ball over the plate. If you throw inside on
the plate, hitters get upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson added that rules that allow hitters to wear ``armor''
to the plate doesn't help.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day you'll see a World Series decided by a ball thrown
into the padding,'' said Robinson. ``It'll be two out, bottom of
the ninth, and the bases loaded. The hitter will just stick out his
padded arm. The game will be over and everybody will be yelling
foul.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver said there might be more professional pitchers if today's
crop could spend more time in the minors. But don't count on it
happening soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they babied? Yes. And there is no single reason,'' said
Seaver. ``I think that organizations want to protect their players
without understanding what a higher degree of excellence they can
get if you put more demands on them. They need to understand there
are mechanical things you can do. But the limitations today are so
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver believes Martinez is one of those pitchers who has done
his apprenticeship.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Red Sox came to New York recently, I was with the
Mets as an announcer and needed to get someone for an interview,''
he said. ``I looked over and Pedro was standing about 10 feet away
talking to somebody in the runway. I knew everybody was after him
but I called out, `Pedro.' He stopped and came over and took my
hand and shook it. I knew then he understands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best pitcher around and yet he knows you can see
there is more than him starting an All-Star Game. He realizes that
he is a part of history and there are people before you and people
coming after you. He was already a good pitcher when he came here.
In Boston, he's shown he has some personality and smarts. That's
what's made him an outstanding pitcher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
