r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAILKILLINGS-VICTIMS-     07-13 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILKILLINGS-VICTIMS-1STLD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-RAILKILLINGS) 
SLAYINGS IN WHICH RAFAEL RESENDEZ-RAMIREZ IS A SUSPECT
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: CORRECTS age of Sirnic in 3rd graf; accompanies(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Maier, 21, of North Canton, Ohio. The University of
Kentucky student and his girlfriend left a party on Aug. 29, 1997,
and walked along Norfolk Southern railroad tracks about a mile from
the Lexington campus. A man jumped from the darkness and demanded
money from Maier and his girlfriend, whose name has been withheld.
Maier was bludgeoned to death while the 20-year-old woman was
raped, beaten and left for dead but survived. DNA evidence linked
Resendez-Ramirez to the attack, authorities said. The woman has
recovered from her injuries, including a broken jaw and a crushed
eye socket, and is considering returning to school.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Claudia Gabriella Benton, 39, of Houston. Her husband and
twin daughters were traveling out of state, leaving Benton alone in
her home, near railroad tracks, in the wealthy Houston enclave of
West University Place on Dec. 17, 1998. A Baylor College of
Medicine physician, Benton was undergoing training in genetics. She
was found sexually assaulted, stabbed and beaten to death, a
butcher knife beside her body. Her Jeep Cherokee was later found
abandoned in San Antonio. Resendez-Ramirez's fingerprint was on the
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic, 47, and his wife Karen, 47, of
Weimar near Houston. The bodies of the popular Church of Christ
minister and his wife, the church secretary, were discovered May 2
in their Weimar home. They had been fatally beaten with a
sledgehammer as they slept. Authorities found their stolen 1998
Mazda pickup in nearby San Antonio. Forensic evidence reportedly
links the suspect to their murder.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Josephine Konvicka, 73, a widow, who lived between Weimar and
Schulenburg. Her only company was an old dog that was nearly deaf
and couldn't bark. The mother of a Houston policeman, she died from
a single blow to the head while in her bed June 4. Her house is
about three miles from the Sirnics' home. The suspect tried but
failed to steal Konvicka's Dodge Spirit. He apparently couldn't
find the keys and was unable to hotwire it. His fingerprint
reportedly was found in Konvicka's home. Dogs tracked the suspect's
scent to nearby railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Noemi Dominguez, 26, of Houston. The bilingual teacher from the
South Texas town of La Feria was found dead on June 5 from a fatal
blow to her head. Railroad tracks run behind her house.
Resendez-Ramirez's fingerprint was found in her 1993 Honda Civic,
which was abandoned near a border crossing in Del Rio. Traces of
Dominguez's blood were found in Konvicka's home, indicating that
Dominguez's slaying might have occurred first.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   George Morber, 79, and his daughter, Carolyn Frederick, 51, of
Gorham, Ill. After 30 years as a prison guard, Morber retired to a
house on the Mississippi about 100 yards from a railroad track in
Gorham in southern Illinois. On June 14, he took his ailing wife to
the hospital. The next day, Morber was mortally wounded in the head
with a shotgun and his daughter, Carolyn Frederick, 51, was beaten
to death. Morber's truck was recovered June 16 in Cairo, Ill.,
about 60 miles away. While investigating the double slaying, the
local sheriff noticed a train passing nearby and recalled that the
serial killer had slain several people along railroad tracks. He
requested fingerprint records from Texas and ``one of the prints
matched'' Resendez-Ramirez, said Jackson County Sheriff William
Kilquist.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
