<SLUG> BC-RAILKILLINGS-TIMELINE-1STLD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-RAILKILLINGS) 
KEY DATES IN RAILROAD KILLINGS CASE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: CORRECTS age of Sirnic in 14th graf; accompanies(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Key dates in the case of the man officials identify as Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez, who is suspected of being a serial killer
responsible for eight deaths in Texas, Kentucky and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   May 23, 1980: Resendez-Ramirez, under the name Jose A. Reyes, is
convicted of burglary in Miami and sentenced to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   May 31, 1984: A prison disciplinary report cites him for
disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   August 1985: He is paroled from prison, and two weeks later the
Immigration and Naturalization Service in Brownsville, Texas,
deports him to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   June 1986: Using the name Jose Reyes-Resendez, he is picked up
by immigration authorities in San Antonio. He is sentenced to 18
months in prison for falsely representing himself as a U.S.
citizen.
</P>
<P>
   October 1987: He is again deported to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   November 1988: Resendez-Ramirez slips into the United States and
is caught in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   March 1991: He is again deported to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   August 1991: Resendez-Ramirez, under the name of Antonio
Martinez, is arrested on a burglary charge in Las Cruces, N.M. He
tells authorities that he works in Juarez, across from El Paso, on
the docks of a trucking company. He pleads guilty and receives a
three-year term.
</P>
<P>
   April 1993: He is again deported. When he returns to the United
States, fingerprint evidence shows that he was jailed in the
Panhandle in Texas, near Amarillo, for evading arrest _ this time
under the name of Carlos Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   August 1995: Pedro Angel Jaramillo is arrested by a Santa Fe
Railway officer in August 1995 in San Bernardino, Calif., on
charges of trespassing and carrying a loaded pistol. Fingerprints
show that the man is Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 29, 1997: Christopher Maier, 21, a junior at the University
of Kentucky, is killed as he and his girlfriend take a shortcut
from one party to another. The two were walking along railroad
tracks when they were assaulted. Resendez-Ramirez has been charged
with murder in Maier's death.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 17, 1998: Houston-area physician Claudia Benton is found
sexually assaulted, stabbed and beaten to death inside her home
near railroad tracks. Her vehicle is discovered abandoned in San
Antonio. Resendez-Ramirez's fingerprint is found in the car.
</P>
<P>
   May 2: Minister Norman Sirnic, 47, and his wife, Karen Sirnic,
47, are found dead in their home near railroad tracks in Weimar,
outside Houston. Their stolen pickup is found in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   June 2: Resendez-Ramirez is picked up by Border Patrol agents
for illegal entry into the United States and sent back to Mexico.
Agents say they were unaware that he was wanted by police and the
FBI.
</P>
<P>
   June 4: Josephine Konvicka, 73, is found slain in her Fayette
County home, about three miles from the Sirnics' home. Railroad
tracks run nearby, but not as close as they were to the homes of
other victims.
</P>
<P>
   June 5: Noemi Dominguez, 26, a Houston schoolteacher, is found
beaten to death in her home. Dominguez, like the other victims,
lived and died near a railroad line.
</P>
<P>
   June 15: The bodies of George Morber, 79, and his daughter,
Carolyn Frederick, 51, are discovered slain at their home in
Gorham, Ill. The house is 100 yards from a railroad track.
Resendez-Ramirez is charged with murder in their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   June 21: FBI places Resendez-Ramirez on its 10 Most Wanted List.
</P>
<P>
   July 13: Resendez-Ramirez surrenders to authorities near El
Paso.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
