<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8915 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLITUDE-THEATER-ART-     07-13 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLITUDE-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUNDING A DRUMBEAT: WE'RE ALL ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18)  
 (af)  
 Matt Wolf is the London theater critic for Variety and a regular
writer on the arts from London.  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ ``Fair enough then. So we're alone.''
</P>
<P>
   When Dame Judi Dench, playing a grieving veteran theater
actress, speaks the final line of ``Amy's View'' Sunday on Broadway
during the last performance at the Ethel Barrymore Theater of David
Hare's play, the remark may make theatergoers sit up with a start.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the frisson comes from the elegant visualization of
those closing moments, in which cascading sheets of silk prompt a
far more real emotive response than any musical's mechanized
scenery ever could. For that, credit Richard Eyre, the director,
and Bob Crowley, the designer, alongside that rare performer, Dame
Judi, who is never more moving than when she is being most
matter-of-fact.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the simplicity of a scene that works simultaneously
as baptism and requiem, is the stark, declarative nature of the
concluding remarks of Dame Judi's character, Esme Allen. In just
those six unsentimental words, Esme gives voice to a condition that
has been dramatized of late with varying degrees of urgency and
pathos on New York and London stages.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 1987 Stephen Sondheim-James Lapine musical ``Into
the Woods'' went to great lengths to reassure us and the show's
battered fairy tale folk that ``no one is alone,'' a number of
provocative recent plays have decided the opposite: in the worlds
of ``Amy's View,'' ``Closer'' and ``The Weir,'' among others,
solitude would appear to be the natural human state.
</P>
<P>
   So prevalent has this sentiment been that one began to encounter
it seemingly everywhere. At the Off Broadway cabaret performance
``Street of Dreams'' last spring, for instance, it was mildly
startling to hear that most engaging performer James Naughton
suddenly sounding as if he had become Esme: ``We go out into the
dark naked and alone,'' Naughton told his listeners, referring to
the lot of the actor.
</P>
<P>
   But he could just as well have been about to describe a primal
attraction of the theater, which is its ability _ however brief _
to make human beings feel less alone when subsumed within that
collective known as an audience.
</P>
<P>
   After all, why else would one of Britain's leading touring
troupes call itself Shared Experience? (That company's ``Anna
Karenina'' traveled to the Brooklyn Academy of Music last fall.)
For good or ill, we're all in this thing called life together. Or
maybe we're not, if some contemporary drama is to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for instance, ``Wit,'' the Off Broadway hit now at the
Union Square Theater that presents self-isolation as something
willed. In Margaret Edson's play, a distinguished academic dying of
cancer is happier in the centuries-old literary company of the
Metaphysical poet John Donne than she is with the humankind from
whom she has quite deliberately removed herself.
</P>
<P>
   For Dr. Vivian Bearing (being played through Aug. 8 by Kathleen
Chalfant), it is as if other people allow into one's life far too
much of that very sentimentality that, Vivian argues, Donne's own
rigor keeps at bay _ starting with his punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   Both Vivian and Hare's Esme find what succor life affords in the
esthetic realm. To that end, they are not substantially different
from the various musicians (and the women in their lives) who
populate Warren Leight's ``Side Man.'' The play, at the Golden
Theater, speaks mournfully about the discordant music made by human
beings as against the transporting sounds of, say, the saxophone.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Broadway's recent visitors from Britain and Ireland
that have thrown this sorrowful condition into the sharpest relief.
In ``Closer,'' the London play now at the Music Box Theater,
Patrick Marber takes a scalpel to the ways of modern-day death and
desire, contrasting in the process a Victorian-era park
memorializing do-gooders with the slick London of a century later,
where good deeds result in both parties getting bruised.
</P>
<P>
   Among the multiple ironies of the play is the fact that _
Marber's title notwithstanding _ its lustful quartet could not be
farther apart. Indeed, one could argue that the closest connection
made in the play is also the most deceitful and isolating: the
erotic exchange in cyberspace between a male obituary writer named
Dan (played by Rupert Graves), relishing his e-mail persona as a
female, and an apparently civilized dermatologist, Larry (Ciaran
Hinds), who is (another irony) a self-described ``caveman'' of the
sort to leave the likes of Rob Becker in the dust.
</P>
<P>
   What do you have to do to get a bit of intimacy around here?
bellows Larry, and the request itself couldn't be more at odds with
the tenor of the remark. Is there any chance, Marber's play asks
shrewdly, of getting close to someone in a world founded on
surfaces and lies?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that Anna (Polly Draper, replacing Natasha
Richardson), the older of the play's two women, is a photographer
whose livelihood _ by definition _ depends on the image of the
thing and not the thing itself. The younger woman, Alice (Anna
Friel) _ who, like Anna, moves between both men over the course of
four years _ would seem to be the play's most direct, uncomplicated
character, until one discovers that her entire life has been built
on subterfuge.
</P>
<P>
   As the full extent of Alice's self-invention is laid bare, Dan
dryly tosses off the line that locates this play squarely within
what one might call ``Esme's view.'' Describing an (unseen) former
lover, Ruth, who went on to marry a Spanish poet, Dan can't resist
naming the title of the collection of poems that apparently
clinched the romance. ``You know what they were called?'' he asks
Anna. ``Solitude.'' The two laugh.
</P>
<P>
   For all the Irish banter that characterizes ``The Weir,'' Conor
McPherson's drama is another play that keeps the prospect of people
at their most essentially solitary just beneath its surface. That
may seem surprising, given the volume of words that fill the
bartender Brendan's pub one blustery night as four men and one
woman gather in a desolate region of northwest Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't simply literary ancestors like Samuel Beckett or
Brian Friel who remind us of the rich Irish tradition of language
serving as a stopgap, however mellifluous, between birth and death.
``We give birth astride a grave'' is Beckett's pithy summation of
existence in ``Waiting for Godot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Weir'' is a ghost story of sorts, to be sure, but only as
the play nears its end at the Walter Kerr Theater do we discover
the specific nature of the haunting _ and the theme of aloneness.
That moment comes in the second of two monologues delivered by the
aging and unmarried Jim (played by Jim Norton), as he relates the
missed romantic opportunity that has shadowed him most of his life,
much as the chill of death itself shadows the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my condition,'' he says tersely, referring to a solitude
leavened only by evenings at the pub and the memory of a brief
instance of compassion. ``Well. That wasn't a ghostly story.
Anyway, at least, ha?'' Jim says, concluding his poignant tale,
although we know as surely as he does the admission encoded in his
statement: in a play rife with talk of otherworldly specters, Jim
is a living, breathing ghost.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``The Weir'' does hold out the option of companionship as
an antidote to life alone. Again, one thinks of Beckett, whose
tramps have one another, even if Godot never arrives.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ``Amy's View,'' over four scenes covering 16 years,
strips Esme of a beloved mother-in-law, a lover, a daughter and an
income. By play's end, she has returned to that vocation _ the
theater _ vilified by the younger generation but bred deep in her
bones, to find a sanctification in art that has been denied her in
life.
</P>
<P>
   Is Esme, then, truly alone? By any objective standard, yes. But
what makes the ending of ``Amy's View'' finally so stirring, more
than justifying the blind alleys (the title included) that the play
travels en route to its finish, is what it suggests _ that Esme in
her very solitariness is never more at one with those of us out
there in the dark who are lifted up by the power of empathy into
the light.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
