</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-BENJAMIN-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YOUNG COMPOSER REMADE?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some artists bloom young; others do not find themselves until
they are a decade or two into adult life. George Benjamin, 39, the
English composer who is in residence at the Tanglewood Music Center
Festival of Contemporary Music, which begins on Thursday in Lenox,
Mass., and will feature his music, has followed both patterns.
</P>
<P>
   In his late teens and early 20s Benjamin produced a quick
succession of bold and beautiful works, full of energy and color,
and remarkable also for their technical finish. Then the flow
almost stopped until, as he entered his 30s in 1990, he emerged
again as an even stronger creative presence, with the same keen ear
but a weightier mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Tanglewood programs include pieces from both the youthful
flourishing and later. Benjamin himself conducts his ``At First
Light,'' of 1982, and Peter Serkin plays ``Meditation on the Name
of Haydn,'' from the same year.
</P>
<P>
   There are also two works from the present decade: ``Sometime
Voices'' _ an aria for Shakespeare's Caliban, here a baritone _ and
``Viola, Viola,'' a viola duo that is Benjamin's most recent piece.
The composer will show another of his talents when he improvises a
piano accompaniment to F.W. Murnau's silent film ``Faust.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin's jump-start around 1980 was helped by the time he
spent as a pupil of Olivier Messiaen at the Paris Conservatory. He
went to Paris when he was only 16, having heard that Messiaen was
due to retire, and he obviously appealed to the senior composer,
across an age gap of more than half a century.
</P>
<P>
   He was young. He was eager, enthusiastic and charming (all
youthful qualities he retains). He was immensely gifted. And he was
quick to learn. He could have been made for the role of Messiaen's
last star pupil, which was how Messiaen came to see him.
</P>
<P>
   The affection between them was mutual and lasting, and Benjamin
has remained on close terms with Messiaen's widow, Yvonne Loriod,
whom he assisted in the completion of Messiaen's last, unfinished
work, the ``Concert a Quatre.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he left Paris, after two years, he was beginning to
make a reputation, which was confirmed by the music he wrote while
studying with Alexander Goehr at Cambridge, England. His first
orchestral score, ``Ringed by the Flat Horizon'' (1980), had a
string of prestige performances, as did ``At First Light,'' for 14
players, which has been conducted by Sir Simon Rattle, Pierre
Boulez and Esa-Pekka Salonen.
</P>
<P>
   ``At First Light'' shows what was so exciting about Benjamin's
early music. There is a feeling for sound, for the substance of
sound, which has to do with finding instrumental combinations that
work well together, with orchestrating chords so that even the
grossest dissonance is good to hear, and with using special effects
so that they sound right and not just special.
</P>
<P>
   But the sounds of ``At First Light'' are not just well chosen:
they are also well placed. One thing leads to another, whether by
simple repetition, by having one instrument or group mimic the
sound of another, or _ most important _ by insuring a strong
harmonic progress in music where simple major or minor chords and
complex combinations are part of the same resonant world. The
feeling for the substance of sound is also a feeling for the
substance of time.
</P>
<P>
   There are, inevitably, echoes of other composers in ``At First
Light'': of Edgard Varese, in the way the piece is initiated by a
repeated signal on a high trumpet; of Gyorgy Ligeti, in some of the
fine tuning; of Elliott Carter, in the strong character of the solo
melodies, and of Messiaen, in the occasional harmonic detail, like
the superb sea swell in A major, Messiaen's blue key.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin, who was 22 at the time, greets these predecessors as
colleagues and equals, not mentors. And in handling an ensemble
with a tricky preponderance of winds over strings, he had nothing
to fear from any comparison.
</P>
<P>
   In expressive terms, though, the piece is unashamedly and
wonderfully juvenile. It communicates a young man's affirmation,
celebration and looking forward, and Benjamin soon came to want
more of himself.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
