<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURIER, MARTIN SET TO LEAD US EFFORT, COACH SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUPEN FOFARIA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The US Davis Cup singles team is Jim Courier
and Todd Martin _ not Pete Sampras, captain Tom Gullikson said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That's the bait. But hardly anyone is biting.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what the boys are saying, it's a team decision,''
Australian captain John Newcombe said. ``So if you're the team, and
you want to win the match _ I think Jim said in the papers this
morning that their objective is to beat Australia, so to win three
matches before we do _ well, why would you have Pete sitting on the
bench?
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I'm not trying to force him to play. I'd rather him
stay on the bench for three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Sampras, the No. 3 singles player in the world,
joined the US team June 9, it has been widely debated whether he
will compete in singles.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson maintains a final decision will not be made until the
day of the tie, which begins Friday at Longwood Cricket Club. But
Martin, whose spot Sampras would take in singles, seems to have his
mind made up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Gulli to feel like he would be able to put the best
team out on the court and not feel bad about it,'' Martin said.
``Pete's swallowed enough pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hypothetically speaking, if Jim and I play and we lose, what
good does that do anyone here? If Pete plays and carries the team,
well then I'm going to be the first one patting him on the back and
telling him, `Good job.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And while Courier and final team member Alex O'Brien have not
spoken publicly, like Martin, both have said their goal is to win _
a sentiment echoed by their captain.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson offered a slight contradiction, conceding that a team
with Sampras playing singles would be the team with the best chance
to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the most logical choice,'' Gullikson said. ``(But you
have to consider) the feelings of Todd, and the feelings of Jim,
and the feelings of Alex, and the feelings of Pete.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, intending not to detract from the first-round success
Courier and Martin had against Great Britain in April _ a success
many critics had all but ruled out before the tie began _ said he
would play only doubles.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin, saying Sampras was a better player, volunteered to
relinquish his singles spot.
</P>
<P>
   When the scenario was posed to the No. 2 singles player in the
world, he said the solution was a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' Australian Patrick Rafter said when asked
whether he believed Sampras would just compete in doubles. ``I
don't think he's come all this way to sit on the sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   With the US team members either boosting Sampras or stating that
they want to win, while agreeing that Sampras gives them the best
opportunity to do that, should there be any doubt who will be the
No. 1 singles player?
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, fans and media watched as Sampras and O'Brien practiced
doubles at Longwood. Many are ready to second-guess Gullikson, but
witnessing the proposed doubles combo at work, no one is quite
ready to call it a bluff.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras and O'Brien beat practice partners James Blake and Chris
Woodruff in a set that went to a 7-5 tie-breaker. Although the set
was close, Gullikson was happy with what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might have some potential as a doubles player,'' Gullikson
said of Sampras. ``I'm sure if he concentrated on it more, he'd
have a lot of success.''
</P>
<P>
   Question is _ will that success be at Longwood this weekend?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll find out on Friday,'' Gullikson replied. ``Right now,
it's Courier and Martin.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the bait. But hardly anyone is biting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
