<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8920 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGE-BENJAMIN-MUSIC     07-13 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-BENJAMIN-MUSIC-2NDTAKE-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: of himself.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1983, the year after ``At First Light,'' he began an
orchestral work, which stalled. He thought he might find a way to
progress by expanding his harmonic resources to include microtones,
and he returned to Paris to work at Boulez's research institute on
what emerged in 1987 as ``Antara,'' for a small orchestra with two
electronic keyboards sampling panpipe sounds. But this piece,
beautiful as it is, did not open a way forward, and for another
three years Benjamin completed nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly his silence was more than a personal problem of having
high expectations of himself and being unwilling to settle for
less. It would have been hard, in the middle and late 80s, to go on
communicating the thrust and optimism that had characterized his
earlier music.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the AIDS epidemic emerging, but Britain was under
the assertively philistine and materialist government of Margaret
Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   However that may be, Benjamin's works of the 90s are darker and
more complex, and show their experience also in a richer range of
musical reference. Of the first of them _ ``Upon Silence,'' a
setting of the Yeats poem ``Long-Legged Fly'' for soprano and viols
_ he has suggested a connection with Indian music, but one might
also hear in it the gagaku of Japan, or European chant or folksong.
</P>
<P>
   What one emphatically does not hear, despite the antique medium,
is any kind of pastiche. ``Upon Silence'' is as new and searching
as anything in Benjamin's earlier output, and his gifts of precise
imagination and technique had not deserted him.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have they since. ``Upon Silence'' was a prelude to the
orchestral piece ``Sudden Time,'' completed in 1993, which begins
with one of the most fascinating essays in musical clockwork since
the opening of ``L'Heure Espagnole'' by Ravel, a composer Benjamin
often recalls in his supreme accomplishment and his simultaneous
expression of pleasure and pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sudden Time'' also manages to be at once exuberant and
uncertain, and it does this partly by having two or three different
tempos happening at once _ and powerfully _ for much of the time.
The ending of the first section is music to cleave the brain as it
forces one to hear time proceeding at contradictory speeds. And the
work achieves another welding of dissimilarities on the poetic
level, bringing into an airy Ravel-Debussy world a Mahlerian sense
of the composer's emotional self.
</P>
<P>
   But if ``Sudden Time'' was a release, Benjamin has remained a
painstaking artist, completing just three works in the subsequent
six years: the two that will be played at Tanglewood and the Three
Inventions for Chamber Orchestra, which veer from frenzy (in a
jazz-expressionist clarinet solo) to grippingly expressed
obsessiveness and dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   This piece, together with ``Sudden Time,'' ``Upon Silence'' and
the student-period Octet, has been recorded on a Nimbus CD, and
most of Benjamin's earlier works are also available from Nimbus.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, a new orchestral score is promised for
Boulez's 75th-birthday tour next year, and farther ahead must
surely lie the opera of which ``Upon Silence'' and ``Sometime
Voices'' provide such tantalizing pre-echoes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
