u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-13 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL REVENUES AND EARNINGS FALL SHORT OF ESTIMATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Intel Corp. reported second-quarter revenues
and earnings that fell slightly short of analysts' estimates, which
the company attributed to a normal seasonal slowdown. Intel said it
expected a strong second half.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported its results after the close of the market.
Its shares closed at $65.375, down 6.25 cents, in Nasdaq trading
Tuesday. In after-hours trading, shares initially slipped $2.25, to
$63.125, but rebounded to $65.125.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the earnings disappointment, though small, was
likely to take the high-flying Nasdaq down a bit on Wednesday.
Intel shares had dropped last month after the company warned that a
new chip would be delayed by two months, prompting some analysts to
reduce estimates for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The delay will affect one version of Intel's Pentium III
processor, to be produced using a new process that reduces the
width of each electronic circuit to .18 micron, from the current
.25 microns. The smaller circuits will enable the chip to run
faster and produce less heat.
</P>
<P>
   Although the delay did not have an impact on the second quarter,
analysts are watching it closely because Intel needs these faster
chips, which command higher prices, to offset declining profit
margins on the bulk of its product line, especially at the low end.
Should the delay be prolonged, Intel's chances for a strong second
half could be diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we're through the period of seasonal weakness for the PC
market, Intel should clearly benefit when the usual seasonal uptick
takes place,'' said Mark Edelstone, an analyst with Morgan Stanley.
``The big question in the second half,'' he said, is, ``will they
be able to get .18 micron Pentium III's ramped up on schedule so
they can continue to refresh the high end of their product line.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel has been locked in a bloody price war with Advanced Micro
Devices Inc., particularly at the low end of its product lines.
Although Intel can offset this price cutting to some extent by
charging premium prices at the high end, its power to do so has
lessened in an increasingly cost-sensitive market.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended June 26, Intel reported earnings of $1.75
billion, or 51 cents a diluted share, up 49 percent from $1.17
billion, or 33 cents a share, in the comparable period a year ago.
Revenues rose 14 percent to $6.75 billion from $5.93 billion in the
second quarter of fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Intel to earn 53 cents a share, according
to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we announced first quarter earnings in April, we
projected second quarter revenue would be flat to slightly down,''
Andy Bryant, Intel's chief financial officer, said in a telephone
conference call. ``Revenues for the second quarter were at the
lower end of this guidance,'' representing a 5 percent decline from
the first quarter, he said. Bryant said price declines were offset
by reductions in costs and improved manufacturing efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said average selling prices of microprocessors were down
in the second quarter as the company moved to regain market share
in the low-priced PC segment. Market research had shown Intel
losing share in that market to Advanced Micro and to a lesser
extent to the National Semiconductor Corp..
</P>
<P>
   Still, the major sufferers of the price wars have been Intel's
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro, which has had trouble shipping faster chips,
last month said it would report a second quarter loss of about $200
million. The actual results will be reported on Wednesday. National
Semiconductor announced in May that it was exiting the PC
microprocessor business and was seeking a buyer for its Cyrix
subsidiary because price competition had made the business
unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said that it now expected gross profit margins for the
full year to be 60 percent, plus or minus a few points, up from
prior guidance of 57 percent, plus or minus a few points. Intel
said the change reflected the positive impact of the company's
continuing focus on cost improvements and manufacturing
efficiencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
