<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PERU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PERU'S INTERNATIONAL DEFIANCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, July 14:
</P>
<P>
   In the international equivalent of taking your marbles and going
home, Peru has announced it will no longer abide by the decisions
of the Inter-American Court of Human Rights. Peru long ago accepted
the court's jurisdiction, but a recent ruling against it angered
the government of Alberto Fujimori. The court and its related human
rights commission, which are part of the Organization of American
States, have become important defenders of rights and the rule of
law in a hemisphere where judicial systems are often too
politicized or weak to protect their citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The Inter-American Court was established in 1979, but has been
issuing real decisions only since 1988. The court's first decisions
held Honduras responsible for the forced disappearance of two men.
Honduras paid their families compensation. Virtually all the
court's decisions have been honored, if at times slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The first crack in the system came in 1998. Trinidad and Tobago,
fearful it would have to delay scheduled hangings, denounced the
human rights convention it had signed that accepted the court's
jurisdiction. The OAS responded with the gentlest possible
criticism of Trinidad and Tobago, which probably encouraged Peru's
decision _ which has so far been met with OAS silence.
</P>
<P>
   The court's current ruling criticizes Peru's use of unfair
military tribunals to try civilians for terrorism. Fujimori is
probably also worried about the outcome of two upcoming court
cases. One involves his having stripped the Israeli-born Baruch
Ivcher of his television station and Peruvian citizenship when
Ivcher began broadcasting reports of government corruption and
murder. The other centers on three judges of Peru's constitutional
tribunal who blocked Fujimori's maneuverings to become eligible for
a third term. He had them sacked.
</P>
<P>
   There are other countries, such as Guatemala, where the military
resents the court. Peru's decision may now encourage these
opponents to press their governments to withdraw. The OAS, and the
Inter-American Development Bank, should be vigorous in defense of
this organization, which for some nations offers the only justice
the armed forces or unscrupulous presidents do not control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
