<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES GOP TO SHRINK TAX-CUT PLAN TO AID MEDICARE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (jw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORAL GABLES, Fla. _ Before a round of golf and a million-dollar
fund-raising dinner, President Clinton appealed Tuesday to
Republican leaders in Washington to scale back their tax-cut plan
to allow the government to shore up Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am asking Republican leaders, in the interest of saving
Medicare, to reconsider the size of their tax-cut plan,'' he said
in a speech to a friendly audience of the Communications Workers of
America in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   With the federal government expecting a surplus of perhaps $2.9
trillion over the next 10 years, the Republicans have proposed
cutting taxes by $864 billion. The president prefers more modest
tax breaks amounting to $250 billion. He refrained Tuesday from
some of the harsh criticism leveled by other administration
officials against the Republican plan, but he still portrayed it as
devastating to education, research and defense.
</P>
<P>
   To extend the life of Medicare without devoting some of the
surplus to saving it, he said, would cut the quality and quantity
of health care available to the elderly. ``That will not happen on
my watch,'' Clinton declared to a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   After his 35-minute address, the president ventured out into the
steamy afternoon to the Indian Creek Country Club, where he played
golf with his brothers-in-law, Hugh and Tony Rodham, and friends.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the evening raising money for the state Democratic
Party, mostly for the highly competitive race for the Senate seat
being vacated by Connie Mack, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner, attended by about 60 people who paid up to $100,000
each, raised from $500,000 to $1 million. Its host was Alfonso
Fanjul, a member of a family of rich Cuban exiles who have become
influential Florida sugar growers and have donated millions of
dollars to both the Republican and Democratic parties.
</P>
<P>
   Fanjul's access to Clinton became apparent inadvertently during
the Monica Lewinsky scandal, when Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr
reported that Fanjul had telephoned Clinton in the Oval Office on
Presidents Day, Feb. 19, 1996, or Dump Day, as Ms. Lewinsky called
it. Fanjul was urging the president, unsuccessfully, to oppose a
proposed tax on sugar farmers to pay for a cleanup of the
Everglades National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Fanjuls control about half of Florida's sugar-cane
production and receive about $60 million a year in federal
subsidies, according to a General Accounting Office report.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sent to Congress this month a $7.8 billion plan to
restore the Everglades. It is endorsed by the sugar growers, and
the cost is to be divided between Florida and the federal
government. Environmental groups say it should set aside more land
from sugar companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
