<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATINAMERICA-MARKETPL     07-13 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINAMERICA-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINA RATTLES A BIT, AND LATIN INVESTORS SHAKE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Worries about Latin America have spooked investors again. And
when worried, they jump for the relative safety of the U.S. bond
market.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a nice rally in bonds, despite the looming
possibility of another interest rate increase by Federal Reserve
policy makers in August.
</P>
<P>
   The latest market tremors come from Argentina, now facing a
tough recession, a growing budget deficit and a presidential
election in October. All that adds up to building uncertainty about
the country's economic restructuring _ something not helped by a
presidential candidate's comment last weekend that he would ask the
pope to support debt relief.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the prices of Argentine bonds fell sharply, pushing
interest rates higher, and the country's main stock index dropped
8.7 percent. The sell-off spread quickly to markets in Brazil,
Mexico and the rest of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Argentina had a small rebound and the demand for U.S.
Treasury securities eased. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond,
which dropped to 5.9 percent on Monday from 6 percent on Friday,
was unchanged. Several emerging-market analysts said that the Latin
American sell-off had been overdone and that fears of an Argentine
bond default or currency devaluation were overblown.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the markets went too far, the outlook for Latin
markets for the next several months is no longer rosy.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts expect continued pressure on Argentina's markets.
And such concerns could spill over to the rest of the region,
especially if the Fed decides to raise rates further next month.
Higher U.S. rates would make it harder for Latin nations to attract
foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``What worries me is all the noise you can have between here and
the election,'' said Jose Luis Daza, managing director of emerging
markets at J.P. Morgan Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin Cottani, chief economist for Latin America at Lehman
Brothers, said that Argentina would continue to be a ``target of
instability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that the government will be able to do,'' he
said, ``is try to convince investors that this has been an
overreaction, that things are likely to improve.'' Still, he noted,
``Nobody expects, even in the government, that the situation will
be too good for the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Argentina's economic future cannot be cleared up
easily. The election will produce a new administration, with
unknown policies, and until then the candidates may try to attract
domestic votes with comments that unsettle international investors.
</P>
<P>
   The sell-off on Monday was a case in point. Gov. Eduardo Duhalde
of Buenos Aires, a presidential candidate, said he wanted to ask
Pope John Paul II to support a debt moratorium for Argentina and
other struggling countries.
</P>
<P>
   For the market, that was not a good move. Investors grow uneasy
over suggestions that a country may not keep paying its debt, even
though a candidate's priorities may shift when elected. Venezuela's
new president, Hugo Chavez, spoke of restructuring that nation's
debt during his campaign, but since taking office has tried to
reassure investors.
</P>
<P>
   In Argentina, until the election is resolved, there is little
the outgoing government of Carlos Saul Menem can do to rebuild
investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina is expected to be able to meet its borrowing needs for
the rest of the year, which diminishes any immediate threat of
default. But there is a much greater likelihood of corporate
defaults, Cottani said.
</P>
<P>
   Also by the first quarter of next year, the outlook on a
government default could be more uncertain. And it will fall to a
new administration to determine how large the financing gap will be
and how to bridge it. ``We will have time to see whether the risks
remain entering the first quarter of next year,'' Cottani said.
</P>
<P>
   Daza said that Latin American interest rates did not indicate
investor fears about an Argentine debt default. Short-term rates
would be higher than longer-term rates if the markets were worried,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the widening spreads between the rates on Latin debt and
those for comparable U.S. Treasury debt show that many investors
are indeed concerned about their ability to sell Latin bonds
quickly, and without big losses, if the Argentine situation _ or
the overall outlook _ takes a sudden turn for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   According to J.P. Morgan, the spread for Argentina shrank
Tuesday by 35 basis points _ or hundredths of a percentage point _
after widening 98 points Monday, to 9.72 percent. At the same time,
the spread between Brazil's debt and comparable American bonds
narrowed by just 1 basis point after widening by 70 points Monday.
And the spread with Mexico grew by 10 basis points after widening
by 56 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the markets seem to have overreacted Monday to Argentina's
situation. But its problems continue to concern investors about
countries that have been considered safer bets.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the market climate for Latin America is much
better than last summer and fall, when first Russia defaulted on
its debt and devalued its currency and then Long Term Capital
Management, the giant hedge fund, teetered near collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Daza said, the Argentine government and the nation's
presidential candidates ``need to work more to calm the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the sensitivity of investors, that is no small task. ``The
guy who got mauled last year is saying `I have to lighten up,' ''
said Barbara Kenworthy, portfolio manager at Prudential Mutual
Funds. ``People are antsy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8937 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-13 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSES, AND WORKERS, MAY NOT LIKE TOO MANY CHANGES IN MEDICAL
BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Congress goes too far with its health-care regulatory bid,
the eventual outcome could be radical changes in how businesses
provide employee medical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate began debate on the Patients Bill of Rights Act
this week, the cost of some proposed reforms was a significant
concern. Some small-business advocates voiced concern about
increased benefit costs because employee health-care coverage was
already barely affordable at small firms.
</P>
<P>
   For larger companies, of course, dropping health-care coverage
isn't an option, because failing to offer this benefit would make
it too difficult to recruit high-quality talent.
</P>
<P>
   Just because a company underwrites health-care coverage,
however, doesn't mean it must be responsible for administering the
benefit, too. Companies, after all, don't feel the need to
underwrite and administer auto or homeowner insurance for
employees. If political leaders insist on health-care reform
without regard for costs, business may be forced to reassess its
approach to providing health-care benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans covered by medical insurance, it's safe to say,
get their coverage at the office. Thus, legislation affecting
health-care providers or insurance companies is usually between
businesses and government rather than individuals and their
government. The cost may be passed on to employees in the form of
wage restraint or increased paycheck deductions for the employee
share of the cost, but this is up to the company.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always like this, though. Just before World War II,
only 10 percent of U.S. workers were covered by employer-provided
coverage. Most Americans bought health insurance on their own,
generally to protect them from the extraordinary expense of serious
disease or injury.
</P>
<P>
   When wartime legislation limited wage increases, the law
provided for employer-paid medical insurance in lieu of wage
increases. It would be another decade, though, before major medical
coverage made its debut. By 1979, nearly all employees in medium to
large companies had major medical coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that companies often get nothing but headaches for
their trouble. Except for the most generous plans offered by the
richest companies, health-care coverage is often a source of
employee-employer contention. The contentious potential of the
arrangement can only intensify as health-care costs continue to
rise.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the spectacular growth of the managed-care concept so
many Americans love to hate was spurred by companies trying to
control the soaring cost of health-care benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than companies continuing to squeeze benefit outlays on
their own at the risk of exacerbating employee alienation,
executives may want to seriously consider a return to the old days.
Instead of providing and administering medical coverage, companies
might be better served to give employees the money instead and let
individuals cut their own deals with insurers.
</P>
<P>
   This approach would allow workers to choose plans that best fit
their individual medical and economic needs. Meanwhile, whenever
lawmakers mulled costly reforms, it would be between themselves and
the voters, without corporate health-care intermediaries insulating
them from the political consequences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
