<HEADLINE>
STANDARDS ARE SET FOR TECHNOLOGY TO THWART MUSIC PIRATES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With few surprises, the music and electronics industries
released the specifications Tuesday for technology that will
prevent portable digital devices from playing pirated music. Now
comes the next hurdle: choosing which technology best translates
the new specifications into reality.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever company is chosen to create the screening technology
could suddenly become a major _ and probably wealthy _ force in the
distribution of digital music, since anyone that uses the
technology, from record labels to Web sites and makers of consumer
electronics devices, may have to pay the company a licensing fee.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of August, the 110 participants in the industry
consortium, called the Secure Digital Music Initiative, or SDMI,
plan to have selected the technology that will determine whether a
given piece of music loaded onto a device in the next generation of
portable music players was acquired legally.
</P>
<P>
   It will fall to the developers of the new technology to clear up
questions left unanswered by the document released Tuesday, which
only vaguely described security measures to be included in
SDMI-compliant players.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lacy, head of the portable device working group for the
SDMI, said 11 companies had submitted proposals for screening
technology, but he declined to identify them. Several other people
involved in the negotiations said that of the 11, five or six were
under serious consideration, with bids coming from a range of small
and large companies. Some candidates are general technology
concerns while others are focused on the digital music industry,
these people said.
</P>
<P>
   The technologies are currently under review to test how well
they detect illegal music, how susceptible they are to hacking and
whether they diminish the music's sound quality, SDMI officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lacy said the technology chosen could be either a single kind of
operation from one company or a hybrid of several.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one were chosen, that would be a major coup for the person
chosen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Moore, general counsel for Diamond Multimedia Systems &UR; ,  &LR; the
San Jose, Calif.-based maker of the Diamond Rio player for MP3
files, said that by letting a third party determine which
technology works best, SDMI was ensuring that no one was playing
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no arm-twisting,'' he said, adding that the record
companies would only embrace the most effective technology. ``If
they don't come up with the best solution, they won't be able to
sell it to their artists.''
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary SDMI standards were released late last month,
and the new ``final specifications'' offer few revelations. The
document is technical but very general, which its authors say will
let it be adopted to various business models.
</P>
<P>
   One requirement is that SDMI-compliant software will prevent
anyone from making more than four copies of a song at a given time.
This means that someone who copies songs from a compact disk onto a
computer's hard drive would then be able to copy it from the
computer to a portable player only four times. The individual could
eventually make more copies of the song, but not before going back
to the original CD and again copying it as an audio file.
</P>
<P>
   That specification appears inconsistent with earlier
pronouncements that portable digital devices would be able to play
``legacy'' content, that is, music recorded onto commercial compact
discs before the advent of the SDMI. But Lacy said the rule was
merely designed to ``put a throttle'' on music piracy by making the
copying cumbersome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
