<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-HOMOSEXUALITY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN ORDERS PRIEST AND NUN TO END MINISTRY TO GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert ``in Maryland'' and ``national'' in lede graf and
to add clarifying information in 12th graf, beginning: Controversy
within ...)  (mk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Vatican on Tuesday ordered an American priest and a nun in
Maryland to end a national ministry to gay men and lesbians, saying
that the pair's work since the 1970s had strayed from church
teaching that homosexual activity is immoral.
</P>
<P>
   The action was unusual in its severity and in that it fell on
people who lack the academic stature of some theologians who have
run afoul of the Vatican in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith,
the body charged with safeguarding church teaching, declared that
the Rev. Robert Nugent and Sister Jeannine Gramick had allowed
``ambiguities and errors'' to color their public discussions about
church teaching on homosexuality and had sown confusion among Roman
Catholic lay people.
</P>
<P>
   Although it stopped short of citing detailed examples, the
congregation said Nugent and Sister Gramick had not sufficiently
emphasized the teaching that homosexual acts are ``intrinsically
disordered'' and ``evil.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision, officially called a ``notification,'' comes after
a lengthy investigation, lasting well over a decade, by American
Catholic authorities and by the Vatican, into Sister Gramick's and
Nugent's work, which they began in the 1970s, putting them in the
forefront of church figures who reached out to gay and lesbian
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   The decision's severity came as a surprise to some.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Gramick and Nugent are permanently prohibited from
conducting the workshops, discussions and retreats (some with the
parents of gay Catholics) that have been the focus of their
ministry for two decades. In addition, they are forbidden
indefinitely from holding office within the religious orders to
which they belong.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, some prominent theologians whose writings the
Vatican has judged unacceptable have been ordered silenced for a
specific period. The Brazilian Leonardo Boff, an exponent of
liberation theology, a controversial system of thought that argues
that the church side with the poor and oppressed, was ordered to
cease his writing for a year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after he arrived in the United States from Rome
on Tuesday, Nugent said he was surprised by the decision. ``It
puzzles me, because I have never questioned any dogma of the
church,'' he said. He added that he and Sister Gramick had
occasionally come under criticism from gay and lesbian groups ``for
being defenders of the church.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nugent said he would accept the decision. ``There are all
kind of ministries,'' he said, ``and I need time to discern what
kind of pastoral work I'd like to do, now that I'm shifting away
from this type of ministry. I just hope the work I've been involved
in bears fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Gramick declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy within the church has dogged the two since 1977 when
they founded New Ways Ministry in Mount Rainier, Md., to reach out
to gay and lesbian Catholics. Situated within the boundaries of the
Archdiocese of Washington, D.C., the organization came under
criticism from Cardinal James Hickey, Washington's archbishop,
prompting Sister Gramick and Nugent to resign as leaders of the
organization in 1984. While they live in Maryland, they had
continued to hold workshops and retreats on homosexuality and the
church across the country.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, the Vatican said it had ``received numerous
complaints and urgent requests for clarification'' from American
bishops and others about what Nugent and Sister Gramick were saying
even after they left New Ways.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the Vatican created a commission under Cardinal Adam
Maida, archbishop of Detroit, to determine whether Nugent and
Sister Gramick had moved outside church teachings on homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   After the two published a book on their work, the commission met
with them in 1994, then forwarded its findings to the Vatican,
which continued the investigation through correspondence with
Nugent and Sister Gramick.
</P>
<P>
   These exchanges continued from February 1996 through January
1999, the Vatican's statement said, but they did not dispel church
authorities' concern that Nugent's and Sister Gramick's views were
``doctrinally unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Catechism describes homosexual acts as
``intrinsically disordered'' and contrary to natural law because
they do not lead to procreation. But it also states that gays
should be treated with ``respect, compassion and sensitivity.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the Vatican said Nugent and Sister Gramick were
presenting only half the message. And in so doing, it said, they
did not allow people ``struggling with homosexuality'' to hear
``the true teaching of the church from those who minister to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Reactions to the decision ran from supportive to critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are surprised at how severely they came down,'' said Sister
Rosemary Howarth, superior at the School Sisters of Notre Dame,
Sister Gramick's order. ``Yes, we are saddened and disappointed at
how hard it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Bruce Williams, a Dominican priest and moral theologian
who had been an adviser to Sister Gramick and Nugent when they
appeared before Maida's commission, said the two ``went to heroic
lengths to cooperate very thoroughly with Vatican authorities.'' He
called the decision dismaying.
</P>
<P>
   But Bishop William Lori, auxiliary bishop of Washington, said
that Cardinal Hickey considered the decision ``doctrinally and
pastorally correct.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far back as 1981, Cardinal Hickey observed that the
approach of Sister Jeannine and Father Nugent to the question of
the immorality of homosexual activity was very ambiguous,'' Lori
said. ``The phrase he always used was `studied ambiguity,' such
that the authentic teaching of the church was undermined.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, errors with regard to the faith come from a certain
selectivity, and I think this is a classic instance of selecting
some of the teaching and distorting the other part,'' Lori said.
</P>
<P>
   In separate statements, Maida and Bishop Joseph Fiorenza,
president of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops, said they
hoped Sister Gramick and Nugent would accept the Vatican's
decision. Fiorenza also quoted from a 1986 Vatican statement
endorsing the ``pastoral care'' of gays and lesbians and said such
work should continue within church teaching.
</P>
<P>
   But Francis DeBernardo, executive director of New Ways Ministry,
called the Vatican's decision misguided and unjust. Speaking of
Nugent and Sister Gramick, he said, ``They have consistently
presented the compassionate face of the church to gay and lesbian
people, and they have done so faithfully to church teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Although DeBernardo said the decision would be ``particularly
hurtful'' to gay and lesbian Catholics, he said the discussion
about homosexuality and the church would continue.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Thomas Reese, editor of the Jesuit magazine America,
offered a view different from some others, saying the decision, in
coming after so many years, showed a careful deliberation, yet
appeared to lack important details. ``On the positive side, it's
clear that the Vatican took a long time before it made its
decision,'' he said. ``On the negative side, there's very little
specificity in the report from the Vatican about what they were
doing that was contrary to church teaching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
