<SLUG> BC-INDUSTRIAL-GAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOC, BRITISH SUPPLIER OF GASES, TO BE BOUGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain's BOC Group PLC, the world's second largest
supplier of industrial gases, will be taken over and divided up by
Air Liquide SA of France and Air Products and Chemicals Inc. of the
United States under an $11.2 billion cash deal announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which will give the two buyers roughly half the
world market for gases such as nitrogen and oxygen, was announced
three weeks after BOC had rejected a takeover overture from the
same suitors.
</P>
<P>
   The 113-year-old British company is valued at 1,460 pence a
share, or $22.63, under terms of the deal, a 42 percent premium
over the price before takeover talk began to drive up BOC stock in
early May. Air Liquide is the world's leading industrial gases
supplier and Air Products is the industry's fourth biggest. BOC had
been under pressure to avoid a drawn-out takeover campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, BOC said a proposal from the two rivals was
unsatisfactory. But Christopher Marsay, head of investor relations
at BOC, said the bidders had strengthened their commitment to
overcoming regulatory hurdles and had improved the financing,
lowering the risk to BOC shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   A BOC statement said the deal provided for Air Liquide to
acquire all of BOC's gases operations in Britain and Ireland. Air
Products is to take over BOC operations in Australia and New
Zealand. The two buyers will split BOC's United States businesses
between them.
</P>
<P>
   Air Liquide is already the market leader in the United States,
with a 19.8 percent share in 1998, and the division of BOC's U.S.
assets is apparently designed to counter antitrust concerns,
analysts said. Remaining businesses, such as those in South Africa,
will be divided up on a ``country by country or region by region
basis,'' a BOC statement said. BOC shares fell by 15 pence to 1,372
pence or about $21.23 _ below the bid price _ reflecting a
perceived risk that the deal still might unravel during regulatory
hearings in Europe, the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The deal has been driven by slow growth in the $28.5 billion
gases market. The market has been hit by Asia's slump and reduced
demand from American steelmakers, analysts said. The prospect that
BOC will be dismantled raised worries among British labor unions
representing BOC's 11,000 employees in Britain. Roger Lyons, of the
Manufacturing, Science and Finance Union, called the deal ``a
disaster for British jobs and for the British chemical industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
