<SLUG> BC-BOOT-SHUTDOWN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIC BOOT COMPANY IN IS STOPPING PRODUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Olathe Boot Co., which according to legend
supplied footwear to Wild Bill Hickok and Annie Oakley, is shutting
down production and looking for a new owner.
</P>
<P>
   Boot production will cease at the end of the week, although the
company's Olathe, Kan., and Denver showrooms will remain open. In
the meantime, talks are being held with potential buyers of the
business, said Chris D'Adamo, the owner of Olathe Boot.
</P>
<P>
   The change comes amid a soft market for boots. In June,
financing to run the business fell through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `To heck with it,' '' D'Adamo said.
</P>
<P>
   D'Adamo, who has owned the company for 12 years, said the boot
business was hot in the early 1990s thanks to the popularity of
line dancing. Production increased, but sales have since fallen
sharply for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Olathe Boot had 80 employees as recently as last year but now
has 20. Some will lose their jobs when production ceases this week.
</P>
<P>
   D'Adamo said Olathe Boot's sales to rodeo stars and ranch
workers had remained strong. But the general retail business at its
Olathe and Denver showrooms had suffered since 1994. Those sales
were off about 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   D'Adamo said he was optimistic that a sale could be worked out
and that boot production could resume. Three of those interested
are from the Kansas City area and one is from out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Olathe Boot goes back to 1875 and evolved from the Hyer Boot Co.
of Olathe. It was founded by C.H. Hyer and developed a reputation
for producing top-quality handcrafted boots. Orscheln Industries
purchased the company's assets in the 1970s. It was sold to D'Adamo
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   As talks continue, the showrooms will stay open and the
inventory of boots will be sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plenty of boots _ that's part of the problem,''
D'Adamo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
