<HEADER>
A8943 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BRITISH-STEWART-H     07-13 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-STEWART-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ It's a different country. A different
world, really. The accents certainly don't sound like they did in
Pinehurst, N.C. Scottish lilt has replaced southern drawl. Though
they are technically the same language, they can be equally
incomprehensible at times.
</P>
<P>
   But in spite of the stark differences, Payne Stewart has arrived
at Carnoustie for his first golf tournament since winning the U.S.
Open, and one important thing hasn't changed a bit.
</P>
<P>
   He's in his element.
</P>
<P>
   Another beastly golf course is laid out before him in the
British Open. More predictions of high scores are being made. And
Stewart again is smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to make us look foolish if the wind blows real
hard,'' Stewart said Tuesday. ``If it blows 30 mph, you could see
an astronomical score win this golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``But why not? They're going to hand somebody the Claret Jug on
Sunday no matter what the score is. And I'd love for it to be me.''
</P>
<P>
   Par on any hole this week is going to be like a small victory,
which is why people aren't ruling out the possibility that Stewart
could become the first player since Tom Watson in '82 to win Opens
on both sides of the Atlantic. Lee Trevino did it before that in
'71.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has a flair for success on courses where birdies are
rare. He won the U.S. Open at 1 under par for the 72 holes. He has
patience and persistence to survive grueling conditions, which this
week most assuredly will present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I come in with confidence,'' he said. ``I don't want
to come here and play poorly and then say, `Well, I won the U.S.
Open, so that's OK.' I won't accept that. I want to come in and
perform the way that Payne Stewart is capable of playing. I hate to
play in a golf tournament that I don't feel I have a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I really didn't have a grip on my golf game like I
do this year. I'm swinging at the ball better. I'm hitting the ball
more solid. So I've got more confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   And a place like Carnoustie could be a hand-in-glove fit for
Stewart, although it's hard to imagine anybody feeling comfortable
on the long, bunkered and narrowed fairways of this old course.
</P>
<P>
   But for Stewart, winning the British Open would be another
feather that he has been reaching for throughout his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought I had a really good chance to win an Open
Championship,'' he said. ``I think I can play a bunch of different
golf shots. I can work the ball in both directions. I'm a good
chipper. And I putt the ball well. And there's not severe breakage
in these greens. They are relatively flat and not too speedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this is the home of golf. There's so much history here in
Scotland. It's a tournament I've always wanted to do well in.''
</P>
<P>
   And one that Stewart believes he can win, especially in the meat
grinder that is expected to be Carnoustie this week. Its ribbonlike
fairways slice through knee-high weeds and brush. The bunkers have
been made more severe than normal, and the greens well, the greens
actually will be like 18 little sanctuaries. They are mostly flat,
and although they are big, they should allow for two putts from
just about anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall severity of the course plays into Stewart's
strength, which is maintaining his poise and his scorecard on
courses where par is a good score.
</P>
<P>
   And even though he didn't pick up a golf club for a couple of
weeks while he basked in the U.S. Open win, Stewart knows he is
capable of picking up right where he left off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have a confidence about you,'' he said. ``That
confidence frees everything up. It frees up your swing and your
mind, and you just ride the wave. It's like getting on top of the
wave, and you ride it as long as you can stay up there on top of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Stewart said he did enjoy getting away for the
three-plus weeks since winning at Pinehurst No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of weeks, all I did was answer the phone and
open up mail,'' Stewart said. ``I got a letter from Bill Clinton,
which I thought was pretty neat. He said he and Hillary were
excited for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed the three weeks off. The last Open I won in
Hazeltine, I went right into the Irish Open and never really had a
chance to sit back and reflect and enjoy what I had accomplished. I
had a chance to do that this time. It's been special. It's
something I will never forget in my life. And I'm very excited
about playing again.''
</P>
<P>
   The rough has Stewart and everybody else concerned about what
kind of score will win this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's thick, it's nasty, and it's not very far off the fairway
_ if you call those fairways,'' Stewart said. ``Those are kind of
like walking paths we have in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to make a lot of money when they cut and bale
the hay out there. The cows are going to eat good this year, very
good.''
</P>
<P>
   But what of the thoroughbreds who will be tromping around
Carnoustie's hayfield starting Thursday morning?
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, for one, is ready to romp. It's not surprising
considering he feels like he's on a familiar track.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
