<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-NOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rose, `Shoeless' on Century list
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _Major League Baseball unveiled the ballot for its All
Century Team on Tuesday afternoon, and the 100 players appearing on
the form posed an interesting philosophical question for
commissioner Bud Selig.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Rose and ``Shoeless'' Joe Jackson, both suspended from the
game for life and banned from the Hall of Fame, were included. That
was promptly brought to Selig's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't in any way affect (their) status with Major League
Baseball,'' Selig said. ``However, they are two players that have
made an impact on the field and they're entitled to be on the
ballot. But it does not in any way alter the circumstances both of
them are under right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The ballot includes four Braves _ outfielder Hank Aaron,
pitchers Warren Spahn and Greg Maddux, third baseman Eddie Mathews
_ and seven other active players other than Maddux _ Mark McGwire,
Cal Ripken Jr., Barry Bonds, Ken Griffey Jr., Tony Gwynn, Rickey
Henderson and Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two candidates were on hand for the announcement,
including Spahn.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a tough team to vote for,'' Aaron said.
``There are so many great players to chose from.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballots will be available at major-league parks, Kmarts and in
selected magazines as well as over the Internet. Voting will
conclude Sept. 15, with the team announced during the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity fever
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' Kevin Millwood found himself suffering through the
same experience as many first-time All-Stars: the fame factor.
Millwood was signing souvenirs in a room off the clubhouse Tuesday
when he turned around to see San Diego's Tony Gwynn, a 15-time
All-Star. Though nearly strangers, the two soon were in
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just started talking about stuff,'' Millwood said. ``Kinda
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood handled the situation better than Texas rookie reliever
Jeff Zimmerman, who rode an elevator with Ripken on Monday.
Zimmerman wanted to introduce himself but was too nervous and rode
to his floor in silence.
</P>
<P>
   Save Fenway
</P>
<P>
   Boston is awash in sentimentality about Fenway Park, which the
Red Sox are planning to replace, whenever they can find the money.
But that hasn't stopped the public cries for preserving the
87-year-old stadium.
</P>
<P>
   New York manager Joe Torre wants to retain as much of its
history as possible: ``I'm going to cherish this night.'' Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa's first career home run came in Boston on June 21,
1989, when he was with the Chicago White Sox facing Roger Clemens.
``From that day on,'' said Sosa, ``I say I know how to play this
game.'' . . . Seattle will host the 2001 All-Star Game at new
Safeco Field. Though no official determination has been made for
2002, Milwaukee is jockeying for that game at Miller Park, which
opens next season. . . . Trevor Hoffman needed no formal
introduction to Fenway. When the San Diego reliever was still in
high school, he was allowed to take part in Red Sox pre-game drills
when his older brother, Glenn, played for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
