<SLUG> BC-PAINE-WEBBER-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINE WEBBER POSTS 26 PERCENT GAIN IN 2ND QUARTER EARNINGS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SHOLNN FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In another record quarter, Paine Webber Group Inc.
posted a 26 percent gain in second-quarter earnings Tuesday,
beating analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The brokerage company reported a profit of $163.5 million, or
$1.02 a diluted share, compared with $129.5 million, or 82 cents a
share, in the comparable period a year earlier. Analysts had
expected a profit of 94 cents a share, according to the First Call
Corp., which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Paine Webber, traded on the New York Stock Exchange,
fell 37.5 cents Tuesday, to $45.125.
</P>
<P>
   Paine Webber generated $488.9 million in income from brokers'
commissions, up 22 percent from $402 million in the quarter a year
earlier. Income from managing assets grew 23 percent, to $224.5
million from $182 million.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the industry, Paine Webber benefited from the
booming stock market. Its strength came in the face of concerns
about profitability from investors and analysts who see the threat
of online trading cutting into commissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They quite handily beat the Street, but the one real negative
is the effect of the Internet,'' said Derek Statkevicus, an analyst
at Keefe Bruyette &AMP; Woods Inc. ``Paine Webber will always be able
to compete. But is the pricing pressure going to be detrimental to
earnings in the future?''
</P>
<P>
   Paine Webber's client assets grew 17 percent, from $329.3
billion to $384.2 billion in the period a year earlier. Donald B.
Marron, the company's chief executive, said the firm's strategy was
to focus on picking up accounts from wealthy clients who will
continue to demand the advice of brokers. With household assets
growing 8 percent a year in the United States, he said, Paine
Webber will continue to thrive off the affluent.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from trading stocks and bonds rose to $279.8 million, an
increase of 15 percent from $244.1 million in the quarter a year
earlier. Investment banking revenue dropped 9 percent, from $176.7
billion to $160.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company is different,'' said Amy Butte, a brokerage
industry analyst at Bear, Stearns. ``Its revenues will continue to
be based on advice and centered on the high net worth individuals.
And people are starting to recognize the difference in the Paine
Webber model.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, Paine Webber announced a plan to offer online trading
later this year, joining other Wall Street firms in the growing but
fiercely competitive Internet market. Two days earlier, Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. said it would start offering online trading in July.
Online brokerage firms like Charles Schwab and ETrade have thrived
on the explosion in online trading.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, Paine Webber has provided updated account and other
market information to clients with accounts of at least $50,000
through its Paine Webber EDGE service. The system now includes
102,500 households, up 31,000 from the beginning of the year. The
firm has 7,118 financial advisers in 303 sales offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
