<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLST-WALKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKER WEDDED TO ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The chances of the Red Sox prying Larry Walker from
the Colorado Rockies is miniscule, particularly after Rockies
management has deemed Walker ``untouchable'' in trade proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, widely considered one of the best all-around players in
the National League, would look ideal in the outfield at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get our own team straightened out,'' said
Walker, hitting a major league-leading .382 with 25 homers and 77
RBIs at the break. ``There will always be people talking about
trades and people denying them. I don't spend much time thinking
about it. I'm very happy where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, under highly regarded manager Jim Leyland, have
been an enigma. Walker doesn't understand why a talented team has
had so much trouble sustaining a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to start playing together as a unit and we haven't
done that for a few years,'' Walker said. ``We played well for
three games vs. Texas recently and then we started to go the other
way again. I've tried to figure it out the past few years and I
have no idea what the solution is.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker may be untouchable, but he is frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in his fourth All-Star Game Tuesday night, he's been
hitting over .350 since May 3. He's also scored 50 percent of the
time he's reached base (69 for 138) and is hitting .405 with
runners on base. Over his last 162 games, Walker is batting .391.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was asked whether the Rockies have what it takes to turn
their fortunes around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I say no I'm ripping my teammates,'' said Walker. ``I
believe my teammates can get the job done. If there are a couple of
moves that need to be made that would help certain areas of our
team, then that would probably be beneficial to us. We might be a
team that needs to make some moves, but I'm just a player, not a GM
who might be able to speak more openly about those moves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies have been a big-name team the past few years, but
haven't lived up to expectations. Walker fondly remembers the 1994
Montreal Expos, who were leading the National League East when the
strike hit in mid-August, ending the Expos' chances of winning with
a younger, ``no-name'' team that at the time included Walker and
Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bring it up again, I always do. I always bring up '94.
Nobody thought we were doing anything. We weren't big names at the
time, though a few of us have become big names as the years have
turned. It doesn't matter what numbers you put up individually, but
if you can't get it done as a team they don't mean much. In '94 we
got it done as a team. It was fun because we were all young players
trying to establish ourselves and we did it together.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spring training this year we were all so optimistic. You
always hope to be over .500 at the break and we haven't even done
that, so it's been disappointing. After making the playoffs in '95
as the wild card, it's been downhill since. There's been no
answers. We've tried everything from the ridiculous to the sensible
stuff and it hasn't worked. I just think we need to be more
consistent. There's still some time to make a difference in this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker played on an Expos team that was run by Dan Duquette, and
there's always been the feeling that Duquette would eventually make
a run at him for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockies aren't willing to dismantle the whole operation
and start over again just yet. Too bad for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad for Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great ballpark for a hitter, whether you're
lefthanded or righthanded,'' said Walker. ``It's an honor to play
here and I know the guys who get to play here feel they're playing
someplace special.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker did make an All-Star prediction for Martinez: ``Knowing
Pedro and the adrenaline is flowing it wouldn't surprise me if it
was three up and three down. He's an awesome pitcher. Anyone who
has ever faced him knows how overpowering he can be.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what happened in the first inning. Three
batters, three strikeouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
