<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONY AND TIME WARNER MAKE MUSIC DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joining the growing ranks of media companies with
quasi-independent Internet units, Time Warner and Sony said Tuesday
that they would merge Columbia House, the music club they jointly
own, with CDnow, the struggling online music store.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting company will focus on selling compact disks and
video tapes from all labels and studios, although the emphasis will
be on promoting Sony and Time Warner products. And by the end of
the year, it will offer music that can be downloaded directly from
the Internet, a market that many in the music industry have long
feared but are now moving quickly to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first business that will benefit the most from the
Internet will be the revolution in music,'' Gerald Levin, the
chairman of Time Warner, said.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, not yet named, will be publicly traded so that
it can give employees stock options and use its shares as currency
in acquisitions. CDnow's existing shareholders will have 26 percent
of the new company. Time Warner and Sony get 37 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   Other big media companies are also rushing to create publicly
traded Internet operations. On Monday, Walt Disney &UR;  &LR; Co. said it had
agreed to buy the 58 percent of the Infoseek Corp. it did not
already own and would create a new class of stock tied to its
online operations. And the NBC unit of the General Electric Co. is
creating a similar venture by merging its stake in Snap, &UR;  &LR; a search
service, with Xoom, a publicly traded online merchant.
</P>
<P>
   As in other industries, record labels are moving to sell
directly to their customers on line at the risk of alienating their
traditional retailers. In April, Bertelsmann and Universal Music, a
unit of Seagram Co., agreed to form their own Internet music store
called Getmusic.com.
</P>
<P>
   CDnow has been struggling to increase sales and move toward
profitability. Selling compact disks is a business with low profit
margins, and CDnow has spent tens of millions of dollars on
promotion _ as much as $70 to bring in each new customer.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, within months after opening its own music store
last year, Amazon.com surged past CDnow in sales by doing little
more than promoting compact discs to its book buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Tuesday, CDnow officials told analysts that revenue in
the second quarter would be about $35 million, less than expected
and less even than the company's sales in the first quarter, a rare
decline for an Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   Even a recent merger with its chief rival, N2K, has failed to
reverse CDnow's fortunes. As a result, its share price has declined
slightly over the last year as shares in other Internet companies
have skyrocketed. Tuesday, the market reaction was no better.
CDnow's shares fell $1.9375, to $20.625.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts questioned whether the business formed from CDnow and
Columbia House would be as attractive as an Internet company.
Columbia House has revenue of $1.3 billion, but its sales have been
declining because baby boomers have stopped buying compact discs to
replace vinyl records. The combined companies will also have about
$250 million in Internet sales this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why CDnow wants to align with big record
companies,'' said Derek Brown, an analyst with Volpe Brown Whelan &AMP;
Co. ``But I'm not sure what Columbia House record club brings to
the party.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger with Columbia House has been in the works for nearly
a year. It was initially proposed by Nancy Peretsman, an investment
banker with Allen &AMP; Co., in a discussion with Richard J. Bressler,
then the chief financial officer of Time Warner. The companies
agreed in principle to the deal early this year, but negotiations
were protracted _ in part because CDnow was occupied with its own
merger and with disputes among its executives, people close to the
transaction said. Moreover, there were differences to work out
between Time Warner and Sony.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, other companies, including BMG-Universal and
Deutsche Telekom, &UR;  &LR; expressed interest in CDnow, executives close to
the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal announced Tuesday is a complex web of commitments. Sony
and Time Warner will guarantee $200 million in existing CDnow debt
and another $150 million in new debt. And they will promote CDnow
on their existing Internet sites as well as on their album covers
and broadcast networks and even through inserts in boxes of Sony
electronics products. Some of this promotion will simply be given
to CDnow. In other cases, the company will have the right to buy
advertising at a discounted rate.
</P>
<P>
   The new company is expected to hire a chief executive from
outside the company. Richard Wolter, the chairman of Columbia
House, will run the record club. Jason Olim, the chief executive of
CDnow, will run the online record store. And Jonathan V. Diamond,
the chairman of CDnow, will leave the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
