<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTEL PROFIT INCREASES 49 PERCENT BUT FALLS SHORT OF FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Intel reported second-quarter profit that was up 49 percent but
fell slightly short of analysts' estimates. The company attributed
the results to a normal seasonal slowdown and said it expected a
strong second half.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the earnings disappointment, which was announced
after the close of markets, was likely to take the NASDAQ down a
bit Wednesday. After closing at $65.375, the company's shares
slipped to $63.125 in after-hours trading but rebounded to $65.125.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA HOUSE TO LINK WITH CDNOW
</P>
<P>
   Joining the growing ranks of media companies with
quasi-independent Internet units, Time Warner and Sony said they
would merge Columbia House, the music club they jointly own, with
CDnow, the online music store.
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY WOMEN SEE FEW GAINS
</P>
<P>
   Despite efforts to diversify the top management of companies,
many minority women say there are few cracks in the ``concrete
ceiling,'' the social barriers that they say prevent them from
reaching the top of corporate America, according to a recent survey
of minority women managers and professionals.
</P>
<P>
   MCI JOINS FORCES WITH EARTHLINK
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom moved into the consumer market for high-speed
Internet access by forming a partnership with Earthlink Network to
sell retail services by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE BEGINS ON BUDGET SURPLUS
</P>
<P>
   The House Ways and Means Committee took the first step toward a
partisan showdown over how to allocate the projected federal budget
surplus, opening debate on a Republican proposal to send $864
billion back to taxpayers over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR STOCK MARKET GAUGES DECLINE
</P>
<P>
   Stocks declined on concern about volatility in Latin American
markets. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 25.96 points, to
11,175.02. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index dropped 5.54
points, to 1,393.56, and the NASDAQ composite index declined 12.21
points, to 2,778.23.
</P>
<P>
   SALES FALL FOR ANOTHER COKE BOTTLER
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's major bottler in Central and Eastern Europe reported
an unexpectedly steep drop in first-half volume sales.
</P>
<P>
   MR. PEANUT MAKES A COMEBACK
</P>
<P>
   The venerable Mr. Peanut, who had been relegated to a supporting
role for Planters nuts, is reassuming a central place in the
company's marketing pantheon. ``Our research shows Mr. Peanut to be
seen as a regular guy, Everyman,'' one Planters executive said,
``with qualities that appeal across a wide range of demographic and
socioeconomic groups.'' The company says it is no coincidence that
the Mr. Peanut revival has been accompanied by a surge in sales.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT RISES 26 PERCENT AT PAINE WEBBER
</P>
<P>
   Posting another record quarter, Paine Webber Group reported a 26
percent gain in earnings, beating analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   DISCLOSURE ON PENSIONS PROPOSED
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration proposed that companies that change
from traditional defined-benefits pension plans to so-called
cash-balance plans disclose to workers how they would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH GAS SUPPLIER TO BE SOLD
</P>
<P>
   BOC Group of Britain, the world's second-largest supplier of
industrial gases, will be taken over and divided up by Air Liquide
of France and Air Products and Chemicals of the United States in an
$11.2 billion cash deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
