<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8957 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-MEET-NYT &LR;      07-13 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-MEET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTEL CHAINS IMPROVED THEIR HIRING, NAACP SAYS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., N.Y., Wash., Fla., D.C.)  (Eds., also filed in `f' code)  
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The nation's largest hotel chains improved in hiring
minority workers and reaching out to minority businesses and
consumers last year, according to an annual survey conducted by the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   Kweisi Mfume, president of the association, unveiled a ``report
card'' for hotels and a separate one for telecommunications
companies Tuesday afternoon at the group's annual convention at the
New York Hilton and Towers in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe, quite frankly, that unless communities of color
become disciplined consumers, we run the risk of still sitting like
beggars on bags of gold, looking at the lack of reciprocity in our
communities, and continuing to see trade as a one-way street,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both surveys were based on information provided by the companies
in five areas: hiring of minority workers, promotion of minority
employees, relationships with businesses owned by members of
minorities, advertising in black media outlets and philanthropy in
minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott topped the list of 14 companies in the hotel survey,
getting a B+ (and a numerical grade of 3.7), followed by the
economy-chain Cendant (B+ and 3.56), whose properties include Days
Inn, Howard Johnson and Super 8 Motels. The Hilton chain ranked
third with a B.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're No. 1 and we intend to stay there,'' said Dave Sampson,
vice president for diversity projects at Marriott International.
The company was handing out announcements saying Marriott was the
``highest-rated hotel company'' in the survey. Last year, Marriott
was given a C+.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson oversees a department that was created 18 months ago to
recruit small service providing businesses owned by women and by
members of minorities. So far, his department has contacted about
200 such companies and signed about 20 to contracts.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the two earlier hotel surveys, none of the
companies received a failing grade this year. But four _
Bass/Holiday (which includes Holiday Inn) Wyndham, Starwood
(Westin, ITT Sheraton) and Omni _ came in at the bottom with a
grade of C.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Rogers, 57, a delegate from Racine, Wash., said she took
the report cards seriously and would avoid hotels that had low
grades. ``If you walk into a hotel that's all white, you're not
going to feel as welcome and accepted, and you will be neglected,''
she said. ``So to us, this is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   In the telecommunications survey, Bell South received the
highest grade of B+ (numerical grade 3.55), followed by Bell
Atlantic, the largest phone service provider in New York, with a B+
and 3.5 The only failing grade went to Alltel, because it did not
respond to requests for information, said Linda Haithcox, national
manager of economic development for the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   This was only the second year for the telecommunications survey,
and Mfume said that it was too soon to see any improvements. But he
urged the delegates not to patronize companies that had a D or a
failing grade.
</P>
<P>
   Like report cards from school, the highest grade is an A, but
Ms. Haithcox said that no company had yet received it. ``If they
deserve an A, they will get it,'' she said without explaining
further about those qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   Several representatives of companies ranked in the NAACP report
cards attended Tuesday's presentation and most emphasized that
their companies had made long-term commitments to diversity that
would not change because of the report cards.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bonavia, a director of corporate communications for Sprint,
said his company had made many improvements even though it received
a C grade for the second year. For instance, he said, Sprint has
made a point of recruiting at historically black colleges like
Howard University in Washington and Florida A &AMP;M University in
Tallahassee. Last year, about 20 percent of the company's 12,000
new employees were black.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bonavia said, Sprint spent $8.14 million in 1998
for advertising in magazines, newspapers and television stations
that cater to blacks, but $1.45 million the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the fact that we made colossal progress year to year
on paper and in practice, you really can't step up your diversity
efforts on multiple fronts because you want to improve your
grade,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0439 </DOCNO>
