<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-GUERILLAS-AR     07-13 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-GUERILLAS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL PUSH IN COLOMBIA ADDS URGENCY TO WASHINGTON TALKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ With sporadic clashes between government
troops and left-wing guerrillas still being reported after last
weekend's fierce rebel offensive, Colombia's defense minister and
armed forces chief were set to arrive in Washington on Wednesday
for consultations with U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement signed last November calls for such contacts
regularly. But the military and political crisis that has erupted
here just days before the formal start of peace negotiations
between the government and leaders of the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia, scheduled for July 20, has given added urgency
to the visit by Luis Fernando Ramirez and Gen. Fernando Tapias.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of raids that began last Thursday, the FARC, as the
main rebel group is known, attacked more than 20 towns, including
one barely 25 miles from the capital, and blew up bridges and power
stations. Over the weekend, in an effort to weaken the group's
supply and reinforcement network, the government decreed a partial
curfew in nearly a third of the country and ordered the military
into a state of heightened alert.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Colombian nor U.S. officials contacted here and in
Washington Tuesday would specify what issues are to be discussed at
the talks. But military cooperation between the two governments has
been growing steadily since President Andres Pastrana took office
in August, replacing an administration that Washington regarded as
corrupt and beholden to drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Congress approved $289 million for Colombia to
help fight drugs, tripling the previous amount and making Colombia
the largest recipient of U.S. security aid after Israel and Egypt.
More recently, in a move that has alarmed human rights groups, the
Clinton administration has quietly begun sharing intelligence on
guerrilla activities with the Pastrana government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything clearly points to a buildup in the relationship,
but our concern is the resistance within the Colombian military to
addressing human rights concerns,'' said Winifred Tate, a Colombia
specialist at the Washington Office on Latin America, an advocacy
and research group. ``There is no guarantee that this information
is going to be used for counternarcotics operations'' and not
shared with paramilitary death squads or otherwise abused.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded intelligence-sharing arrangement was authorized in
March, according to a General Accounting Office report published
last month titled ``Narcotics Threat From Colombia Continues to
Grow.''
</P>
<P>
   The information is intended to be used only to fight drug
trafficking, but a Colombian official said that ``since the
guerrillas operate in drug-producing areas and are part of the
trafficking network, some information about them'' is now also
being supplied.
</P>
<P>
   A series of electronic surveillance and radar stations, built
and staffed by U.S. technicians, are maintained around Colombia as
part of the enhanced cooperation strategy. It is not clear,
however, whether the United States made information obtained from
those listening posts available over the weekend to the Colombian
military.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Washington, Tapias asserted that the army had
achieved ``complete victory'' over the rebels, saying more than 300
insurgents had been killed since Thursday. In the past, however,
the United States has been critical of the performance of the
Colombian military, regarding it as inept and corrupt, and has
preferred to cultivate a close relationship with the national
police, which is a separate entity.
</P>
<P>
   As the United States sees it, the drug war here is going badly
in large part because of the military's inability to stem the rebel
tide. Official U.S. estimates, based on satellite and aerial
surveillance, indicate that the amount of land devoted to
cultivation of drug crops rose by more than a quarter last year,
despite an American-supported drug eradication effort in producing
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cultivation is way down in the Guaviare region, but way up in
the Putumayo and Caqueta areas, which are under guerrilla control
and therefore much more difficult to get in there to eradicate,''
said one U.S. official with long experience here. ``These are
industrial-sized fields, not a couple of hectares for peasants, and
it will take a much more coordinated effort within Colombia to get
a handle on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, all U.S. assistance, including the recent purchase
of helicopters and the training of a new air-mobile battalion, is
directed toward antinarcotics efforts. But the guerrillas, who earn
hundreds of millions of dollars a year from their involvement, see
the effort as aimed at them, and have repeatedly threatened
Washington with retaliation if it continues to step up its support
and involvement here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Yugoslavia,'' Jorge Briceno Suarez, the second in
command of the FARC, said in an interview with an Argentine
newspaper this month. ``If the United States intervenes, it will
see blood flow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
