</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-ANALYSIS (Hong Kong) _ The timing of Taiwan's surprise
move to abandon the one-China policy may have more to with domestic
politics than anything else. While the development puts the United
States in a tough spot, some analysts think it might actually help
Washington and Beijing get past their current tensions. By Indira
A.R. Lakshmanan. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-STUDENTS (Washington) _ Analysts here and in the Mideast
see anti-traditionalist demonstrations ending with a crackdown by
the conservative Muslim regime. Others think the students will be
hard to suppress. By John Donnelly. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   US-BARAK (Washington) _ US officials anxiously await the
weeklong visit of Israel's prime minister, believing this is a
historic opportunity to move ahead with two parts of the Middle
East peace process. They're also concerned whether the former
general can pull it off. By John Donnelly. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-HMOS (Washington) _ Democrats lose the opening vote on a
move to expand a GOP patients' rights bill as the Senate rejects an
effort to allow women more options in choosing doctors and
hospitals. By Eun Lee Koh and Bob Hohler. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-PBS (Washington) _ What had promised to be a triumphant
year for PBS erupts into a bitter dispute as House Republicans
discover a Boston television station had divulged its donor list to
Democrats. By Anne E. Kornblut. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   SMITH-GOP (Washington) -- US Sen. Bob Smith, as promised,
defects from the GOP. GOP policy luncheon will discuss whether to
strip the presidential hopeful of his seniority and committee
chairmanships. By Bob Hohler. 1000 words.
</P>
