<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-ARREST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WE WERE SURPRISED HE WAS SUCH A SLIGHT MAN AND QUIET MAN,' SAYS
BORDER AGENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK SMITH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ Those who saw him surrender were struck most by
the small stature and almost meek demeanor of the man portrayed for
weeks as a brutal, rail-riding serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of the most wanted man in the nation, you would
think he would not be so quiet, so docile,'' said Anne Estrada,
deputy district director of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service office in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   As described by Estrada and others present, the surrender of
accused serial killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez was a remarkably
low-key ending to a frantic international hunt for the suspect in
at least eight slayings in Illinois, Kentucky and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised he was such a slight man and quiet man,''
said Luis Garcia, INS district director in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   INS agents processed Resendez-Ramirez for admission to the
United States after he surrendered to law officers on the bridge
linking Zaragoza, Mexico, and the rural Ysleta community southeast
of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   The officers alerted the INS early Tuesday that Resendez-Ramirez
was in Mexico and had agreed to turn himself in at the
international bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bridge is the most lightly traveled of three that
cross the Rio Grande in the El Paso area, it saw nearly 8 million
of the area's 55 million bridge crossings last year.
</P>
<P>
   About 8:30 a.m. CDT, the suspect's sister, Manuela Maturino of
Albuquerque, N.M., arrived at the INS checkpoint in Ysleta, said
Arthur Gonzales, INS supervisor in charge of inspections at the
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino, described by authorities as a key intermediary in
negotiating Resendez-Ramirez' surrender, was accompanied by an
Albuquerque pastor.
</P>
<P>
   She was talking by cellular phone to the suspect and two other
brothers on the Mexican side of the border.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 a.m., Resendez-Ramirez arrived in a white pickup driven by
his brother, Florentino Maturino Recendis, identified by Estrada as
a church pastor in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Several other family members followed in a blue van, she said.
</P>
<P>
   They pulled into the right lane and stopped about 100 feet from
the checkpoint on the U.S. side of the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez, described as about 5-feet-6-inches tall with a
slight build, stepped out of the pickup and hugged Manuela
Maturino, Gonzales said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gonzales and Texas Ranger Andrew F. ``Drew'' Carter Jr.
approached the suspect, who identified himself and was handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmen did not have guns drawn because they expected no
resistance, and there was none, Gonzales said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in law enforcement 30 years, and people know when it
is time to give up,'' Gonzales said.
</P>
<P>
   The group then went to an INS interview room and processing
center.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, who has used numerous aliases, gave his full name
as Angel Leoncio Reyes Recendis. Authorities said recently that is
his true name, but continued to call him Resendez-Ramirez during
the manhunt because the name had become familiar to the public and
law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   No lawyer was present, Estrada said, and Resendez-Ramirez
apparently said nothing about the charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't ask him any questions about any alleged crimes he
had committed in the United States,'' Garcia said. ``We didn't want
to violate his civil rights. We just asked required, related
immigration questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The process took about an hour, during which time the suspect
had a chance to speak with family members, but he was unable to
return their hugs because of his handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Manuela Maturino and another sister wept. ``I couldn't tell if
it was relief, or sadness, or both,'' Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
   After INS agents confirmed the suspect's identity through
fingerprints, they turned him over to Texas Rangers, part of a task
force that also included FBI agents, U.S. marshals and various
other state and local police.
</P>
<P>
   Family members followed as Resendez-Ramirez was driven to an El
Paso court for arraignment. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
