<HEADER>
A8962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-SALES-EASTERN-EU     07-13 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SALES-EASTERN-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCA-COLA SALES AND STOCK DROP SHARPLY IN EASTERN AND CENTRAL
EUROPE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Poland, France, Belgium, Britain, Greece, Russia, Britain)   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Coca-Cola Co.'s major bottler in Central and Eastern Europe
reported on Tuesday an unexpectedly steep drop in first-half volume
sales, and its stock fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The bottler, Coca-Cola Beverages, attributed the 5 percent
decline in volume, measured in cases sold, to severe economic
problems in Russia, the Kosovo conflict, the company's recent
bottled-water recalls in Poland and bad publicity from Coca-Cola
beverage recalls in Belgium and France, which were handled by a
different bottler.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Coca-Cola Beverages, traded on the London Stock
Exchange, fell 6 pence, or 4.4 percent, to 131 pence ($2.04). The
stock has fallen nearly 20 percent since it was first sold a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The news was the latest headache for Coca-Cola Beverages, which
was spun off from another bottler, Coca-Cola Amatil, in late 1997.
The Coca-Cola Co. owns 50.1 percent of the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Although falling sales in Russia were not a surprise, the impact
of the recalls was greater than expected on the dozen or so other
countries where the bottler does business. The results revealed
that demand for Coca-Cola products in Europe suffered broadly from
consumer fear of contaminated soda, even in areas not included in
the recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the negative publicity that has been associated with
it,'' said Chelsea Allen, a spokeswoman for the bottler. ``It
affected the whole of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottler recalled 170,000 cases of its products in Poland on
July 1 after mold was found inside glass bottles used for Coke,
Fanta and other drinks. Another recall, of 180,000 half-liter
bottles, was ordered around the same time after Polish government
scientists detected coliform bacteria in Bonaqua Plus, a purified
water sold by Coke. The bottler said the bacteria resulted from
poor maintenance at a plant in Poland, which is scheduled to reopen
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The first-half results were announced as merger talks continue
between Coca-Cola Beverages and Hellenic Bottling, an Athens-based
independent Coke bottler. The deal is expected to be completed by
year-end.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Allen said the results would not affect the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone messages left for Hellenic's executive director, Lucas
D. Komis, were not returned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hellenic has offered to pay 150 to 180 pence, or $2.34 to $2.81,
for all of Coca-Cola Beverages stock, either in a stock swap or
cash. The merger would create the second-largest bottler in the
Coca-Cola system, stretching from Ireland to Italy and Nigeria to
Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   Securities analysts who follow the beverage industry have been
puzzled by the planned merger since it was announced. They have
questioned why management at Hellenic, a family-controlled,
profitable, publicly traded company in which Coke has never held an
equity stake, would suddenly decide it wanted to be in business
with the sprawling, money-losing Coca-Cola Beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hellenic is technically the buyer, under the terms of
the deal a management team from Coca-Cola Beverages would control
the newly formed company. The Levantis family, which currently owns
84.5 percent of Hellenic, would see their ownership shrink to 47
percent. The new company is likely to follow the strategy of Coke's
other major bottlers _ big capital expenses for things like
cold-drink equipment at the cost of profits for several years at
least, in contrast to the more judicious spending demonstrated by
Hellenic in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The price for the deal is also considered astonishing, made more
so by Coca-Cola Beverages' share price decline Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extreme price,'' said Adam Spielman, an analyst who
covers both companies for Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the merger could be that Coca-Cola has a plan for
its bottlers _ in short, the bigger and more in step with
Coca-Cola's plans, the better, to strengthen sales of Coca-Cola
concentrate _ and bottlers have little choice. In Europe, they do
not have permanent franchise rights, as they do in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point is that the Coke system has got to
consolidate, and Hellenic is going to consolidate with it,'' said
David Lang, a director at Investec Henderson Crosthwaite, a London
investment bank. ``If Hellenic didn't invest going forward and
didn't manage its business in a way that satisfied Coca-Cola, then
there would be changes anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts say that Coca-Cola Beverages desperately needs to
improve, and merging with a better-performing bottler might work.
Andrew J. Conway, a beverage analyst at Morgan Stanley, noted that
the bottler's return on invested capital is just 1.3 percent _ the
lowest of the major Coke and Pepsi bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is unclear why the Levantis family and Hellenic
management have embraced the deal. Hellenic's share price has been
growing much faster than the Athens Stock Exchange for the last
four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very curious deal, this,'' Spielman said. ``Hellenic
was very happy where it was. Coke wasn't happy.'' He added:
``Clearly, Hellenic management felt the deal was advantageous to
them in the long term. Or, to put it another way, not doing the
deal would be disadvantageous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
