u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDGE-NOMINATION-SPI &LR;      07-13 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-NOMINATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL ENDORSES SEATTLE JUDGE'S SELECTION TO 9TH CIRCUIT
COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ King County Superior Court Judge Marsha Pechman's
nomination to become a federal judge was endorsed Tuesday by Senate
Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the process of filling vacancies on the federal
bench has slowed for a variety of political reasons, Pechman was
one of five relatively non-controversial nominees allowed to move
forward with a hearing before Hatch's committee. Hatch said he
would support approving each of the nominees.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing provided a forum for Republicans and Democrats to
air complaints about the judicial selection process. Hatch, R-Utah,
who is running for president, blasted the 9th Circuit Court of
Appeals, for the alleged judicial activism of its judges. Hatch and
Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., also lectured the nominees about the
need to make decisions more rapidly in death penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., criticized Hatch for the Senate's
slow pace of considering judicial nominees this year.
</P>
<P>
   The consideration process has stalled in part because
Republicans hope to win the presidential election next year, and
with it the right to choose federal judges. Additionally, Hatch is
unhappy that President Clinton has not yet nominated to the bench a
Utah attorney disliked by environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Pechman's nomination, although trapped in the difficult and
intensely political Senate confirmation approval process, was
praised by Sens. Patty Murray, D-Wash., and Slade Gorton, R-Wash.,
who have an unusual agreement to jointly screen candidates for
judicial nominations. No opposition has emerged to Pechman's
nomination, and none of the senators questioning her raised any
obstacle to her approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``She comes to you out of a relatively large court, with a large
number of judges, with a noted enough career so that she appears to
both our search committee and to the two senators of the state as
someone highly qualified, not only by experience and education, but
by temperament, for a position on the United States District
Court,'' Gorton said. (Pechman worked for three months in 1975 as a
law clerk in the state attorney general's office when Gorton was
the attorney general.)
</P>
<P>
   Murray called attention to Pechman's status as a survivor of
breast cancer and a peer mentor for other women suffering from the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Pechman, through her commitment to her family, her
excellence in her work, and her involvement in her community, has
been a shining example for many breast cancer victims,'' Murray
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pechman, 48, is a Seattle resident who has served on the King
County bench since 1988. She had worked as a prosecutor, as a
plaintiff's attorney and as a law professor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton nominated Pechman to a lifetime appointment on the U.S.
District Court for the Western District of Washington on March 24.
She would replace District Court Judge William Dwyer, who wants to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions, Pechman pledged to work to expedite
the handling of large and complex cases, said she is willing to
reduce judgments that she thinks are excessive, and said ``it is
not the business of a district court judge to legislate, but it is
the business of a district court judge to interpret legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Pechman said she would have no problem enforcing the death
penalty, and agreed that lengthy delays in the imposition of the
death penalty can be problematic.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch encouraged the judicial nominees to keep their promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``This committee is having a whale of a difficult time with the
9th Circuit Court of Appeals ... because there are number of people
on that circuit court of appeals who disregard the law. ... They
just substitute their own ideas for what the law ought to be ...
and in the process they have really hurt liberal judges all across
the country,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
