<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PERU: FUJIMORI LEADS DRIVE ON REBELS
</P>
<P>
   With President Alberto Fujimori personally leading the
operation, Peruvian Army troops surrounded a Shining Path guerrilla
jungle position hoping to capture Oscar Ramirez, the group's top
leader still at large. The Maoist group has been in a steep decline
since the 1992 capture of its commander, Abimael Guzman, but the
rebels have attempted to stage a comeback with a series of
hit-and-run attacks since June.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: SUIT OVER CAMPUS STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's top two constitutional lawyers said they would file a
criminal complaint against students who have occupied the National
Automous University of Mexico campus for 12 weeks. The complaint
could lead to federal charges against the strikers for seizing the
offices of the two jurists, who are on the law school faculty, and
other professors, possibly paving the way for police action to end
the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: CALMING THE MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to calm investors, Gov. Eduardo Duhalde of Buenos
Aires, the presidential candidate of the governing party, said
Argentina would not ask creditors to forgive its foreign debt.
Recent comments by Duhalde blaming the burden of servicing the $130
billion debt for Argentina's economic problems were seen as one
reason for a fall in the main stock index of more than 8 percent on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: FALKLAND STALEMATE
</P>
<P>
   A third round of talks between Britain, Argentina and the
Falkland Islands on resuming air links to the South Atlantic
archipelago and allowing Argentine passport holders to land there
reached a stalemate in London. There have been no scheduled flights
between Buenos Aires and the Falklands since Argentina invaded the
islands in 1982 and were then repelled by British troops. The
islands' isolation grew in March when Chile canceled flights there
in protest at Britain's detention of Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: JEWISH LEADER STABBED
</P>
<P>
   The director of Moscow's Jewish Cultural Center was in ``very
serious'' condition after being stabbed with a large hunting knife
by a young man who invaded his synagogue office. The director,
Leopold Kaimovsky, was attacked after morning prayer services by a
man whose shirt, the police said, concealed a large black swastika
drawn in ink on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: MILITANTS' DEADLY ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   Islamic militants burst into the residential compound of Indian
security forces north of Srinagar, in the Indian state of Kashmir,
killed a woman and three men, including a high-ranking officer in
the Border Security Force, and took hostages. The attack stirred
concern in India that guerrillas, upset about Pakistan's insistence
that they withdraw from the Kargil sector of Kashmir, may step up a
campaign of violence in other parts of the Indian state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
