<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL POSTS 23 PERCENT INCREASE IN EARNINGS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the nation's largest brokerage
firm, posted robust second quarter earnings Tuesday, even as the
financial powerhouse struggles with infighting and tension in its
upper ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by a stock market that continued to produce
gravity-defying gains last quarter, Merrill reported earnings of
$673 million, or $1.57 a share, up 23 percent from the $549
million, or $1.31 a share, it earned in the corresponding period
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's earnings easily topped analysts' expectations of $1.46
a share, according to consensus estimates compiled by the First
Call Corp.. In trading Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange,
shares of Merrill rose $1.375, or about 1.8 percent, to $79.25.
</P>
<P>
   But Merrill's shares still trade well below their 52-week high
of $109.125, and should the stock market slow or the economy enter
a recession, Merrill's earnings could suffer. Merrill may be
vulnerable to a takeover later this year or next if its stock price
weakens or if it is unable to successfully execute its plans to
bolster its sales presence on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Merrill is very well positioned for the global trends
driving the industry today _ investment banking trends in Europe,
strong trends in the U.S. that continue and Asia's longer-term
prospects,'' said Richard Strauss, a securities industry analyst
with Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.. ``But investors are also going to be
keeping a close eye on its Internet strategy, and in the near term
I think that expectation is just as important.''
</P>
<P>
   The sharp reversal in Merrill's fortunes in the last year has
produced a startling shift in how the once seemingly impregnable
firm is perceived by many of its competitors and Wall Street. The
firm's finances were hammered by last year's economic chaos
overseas, and it was slower than firms like the Charles Schwab
Corp. to embrace the enthusiasm for trading that is sweeping the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Merrill announced that Herbert M. Allison Jr., its
president, resigned after being told he would not run the firm one
day. Allison, a cool, detached figure who seemed oddly out of sync
in Merrill's gregarious, hard-driving culture, had been at odds
with Merrill's chief executive, David H. Komansky, for some time.
Differences within the firm about how to respond to the growth of
the Internet also added to managerial tensions.
</P>
<P>
   While the stock market seemed to react mildly to Allison's
departure, there is still concern about the lack of a clear
successor to Komansky and how quickly the company will put its
house in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense around the Street that Merrill is adrift,''
said a senior executive at a rival firm. ``I still marvel at where
this company was two years ago and where they are today.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill counters that it is focused on achieving its financial
goals and has managers in place who are up to the task of running
the firm in an era of brutal competition and rapid change in the
financial services industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very fortunate to have many talented executives in
senior management and great bench strength,'' said Paul W.
Critchlow, a Merrill spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some analysts Tuesday questioned how deep Merrill's
managerial bench truly is. Leading candidates to succeed Komansky
include John L. Steffens, a vice chairman who heads online efforts
and supervises the firm's army of retail brokers, and Jeffrey M.
Peek, who oversees asset management. Beyond that, some say, the
candidates are slim.
</P>
<P>
   Although attention has focused on Allison's shortcomings since
his resignation was announced, Komansky has presided over a string
of high-profile blunders or miscues in recent years. Those include
the aggressive marketing of complex financial products known as
derivatives to Orange County, Calif., which helped send the county
into bankruptcy; a big expansion into emerging markets, which
created financial headaches last year, and an unusually deep
involvement in the near collapse of the Long-Term Capital
Management hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   Although Merrill also has had difficulties with its $5 billion
acquisition of the British firm, Mercury Asset Management, which it
acquired last year, Merrill said Mercury's funds were performing
better and that it was ``absolutely happy'' with its returns on
that investment.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's earnings announcement Tuesday disclosed smart gains in
its overall asset-management business. Revenue from the business
was up a record 7 percent from last year, to $1.16 billion, while
total assets under management grew 5 percent, to $516 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were generally pleased with the results from asset
management and other key units as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trading was a bit lighter than I expected and investment
banking a bit better,'' said Joan S. Solotar, an analyst at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``Over all, it was a solid quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   In the period, Merrill's net revenue, which includes interest
income less interest expense, rose 12 percent, to a record $5.4
billion. Commissions rose 8.8 percent, to $1.59 billion, and
trading revenue jumped 7.6 percent, to $1.06 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Investment banking revenue totaled $908 million in the second
quarter, up 1.1 percent from last year's booming quarter. Merrill
said equity underwriting revenue was sharply higher from that of
last year's second quarter, and nearly double the levels recorded
in the first quarter of 1999. But underwriting fees in most debt
categories declined in the second quarter, reflecting concerns
about interest rates, the firm said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they expected Merrill to post solid results for
the third quarter. But uncertainty about the firm will probably
emerge starting in December, when Merrill is scheduled to introduce
new Internet-related products and trading accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are worried about the fourth quarter, when online
trading and the retail products that come along with it will be
rolled out,'' said Sallie Krawcheck, an analyst at Sanford C.
Bernstein &AMP; Co..
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts shared Ms. Krawcheck's interest in how Merrill's
Internet strategy will be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an inherent conflict with their brokers, which may be
compounded by the fact that Launny Steffens will be running both
the retail and Internet sides of the business,'' Ms. Solotar said.
``I am hopeful management realizes it needs a cohesive Internet
strategy and has a window of five months to put it together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
