<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S SOCCER CHAMPIONS SAVOR THE MOMENT THEY'VE SEIZED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You'll have to forgive the 1999 Women's World Cup
soccer champions. They're still pretty new at this celebrity thing.
</P>
<P>
   It was just a few months ago _ nay, a few weeks ago _ that these
20 smiling athletes could walk unrecognized on the street. They
haven't quite polished their canned answers to those cliched
questions yet. They're still having an awfully good time, and need
a pinch every once in a while to remind themselves it's real.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi Chastain _ she who posed nude but for a soccer ball and
cleats, she who whipped off her game jersey and knelt before the
world in a sports bra after knocking in the game-winning penalty
kick in the finals on Saturday _ had dutifully sat through a
half-hour of those ``how do you feel'' queries Tuesday afternoon
after a victory rally outside the Niketown store in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But then some guy with a microphone wondered what it was like to
see a little girl wearing a jersey with your name on the back, and
all of a sudden the fullback who has been nicknamed ``Hollywood''
was crying. Real tears.
</P>
<P>
   Another star might have hidden her face, got up, walked away.
Ms. Chastain sniffed a bit, wiped her eyes and stuck around for 15
more minutes of questions about how she feels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too emotional a person to be sitting here,'' she said,
green eyes sparkling in the freshest of fresh faces. ``It's just
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people showed up at noon Tuesday to celebrate with the
new World Cup champions. Nike organizers said there were 3,500
people. It wasn't just cute little suburban girls with faces
painted red, white and blue. There were gray-haired grandmothers
and men in business suits. There was a 12-year-old boy wearing a
Tiffeny Milbrett No. 16 jersey. Even Donald J. Trump was there
(sure, he owns the building that houses Niketown, but he didn't
have to come outside).
</P>
<P>
   They clapped for all the backup players few people have ever
heard of, and when the women started firing dozens of souvenir
soccer balls into the crowd, they all had their hands up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd watch the Women's World Cup over the Super Bowl any day,''
said Patrick Greene, 26, a systems consultant for a midtown
company. ``I want to marry every single one of them. I'm trying to
find out who's single.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his height advantage over most of the teen-age soccer
fanatics, Greene, at 5 feet 10 inches, did not take home a soccer
ball. A Fox television reporter did, though. It was that kind of
moment, when even supposedly hardened New York journalists could
not keep the fan in them from coming out.
</P>
<P>
   What that meant, of course, was that the old fans, the die-hard
fans, could not get any face time. Meghan and Caitlyn Moroni of
Congers, N.Y., were just a little bit wistful for the old days _
all of maybe a year ago _ when they were the only ones to recognize
Kristine Lilly at a local sneaker store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost felt bad for her. She was just sitting there; nobody
was coming up to her,'' recalled Meghan, 15, who plays center
halfback on a premier club team in Rockland County. ``Now if that
happened, there'd be crowds there. We got to talk to her for like
15 minutes, alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Caitlyn, 17, who plays the same position as her younger sister,
but on a team for older girls, added: ``It wasn't really a big deal
then. Now I wish I could talk to her again.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Shookhoff, 14, came to the rally on crutches and had to
watch from inside Niketown as autographed soccer balls bounced
against the picture-window panes, out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Alex, who lives in Manhattan, tore ligaments in her knee during
a game in Westchester County on May 22. Just like Michelle Akers of
the U.S. team, who has had so many knee surgeries that she has
actually lost track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up five-nothing,'' Alex explained. ``There was like
three minutes left until the end of the game. I was running for a
ball. I hit this girl. I heard a crack.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she will be playing again in six months.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The question, though, is what will happen to this World Cup team
in six months, or six years. Does this herald a revolution for
soccer, for women's sports, or is it just an elongated 15 minutes
of fame?
</P>
<P>
   At the rally Tuesday, the managing editor of Sports Illustrated,
William Colson, presented Ms. Chastain with a framed blowup of the
current issue's cover, which he called ``the greatest picture of a
sports bra in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm took home a framed cover of Time magazine, featuring
herself. Throughout the crowd could be seen copies of the latest
Newsweek, headlined ``Girls Rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in case, though, Julie Foudy, a co-captain, had her own
video camera, capturing the cheering masses, recording her
teammates' glowing smiles, documenting their day in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was my duty and obligation to record the moment,''
she explained later. ``We've obviously got a lot of cameras pointed
at us. It's nice to have one pointed the other way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
