<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WTO DEBATE ON NATION'S ACTIONS GOES BEYOND SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States and Canada will slap $125 million per year in
taxes on European goods. This is to compensate for the European
Union's exclusion of U.S. and Canadian beef.
</P>
<P>
   What's notable is that the action is not unilateral. It has been
given an OK by the Geneva-based World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Under the most recent WTO agreement, all countries agreed to
base human-health restrictions on assessments of scientific risk.
The United States and Canada, whose ranchers treat cattle with
government-approved growth hormones, charged that Europe's ban on
their beef had never been scientifically assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Europe replied that it was following the precautionary
principle, which can be summed up as ``better safe than sorry.''
The United States replied that it's OK to take a precautionary
approach, but to elevate it to a principle ``cannot create a risk
assessment when there is none.''
</P>
<P>
   The WTO appellate panel agreed. Its ruling still allows European
governments to set any standard of risk they want _ one in a
thousand, one in a million, one in ten million.
</P>
<P>
   But they have to consider whether the evidence meets the
standard. They can block a new product while they assess it. But to
ban it permanently they have to assess it, and base their
assessment on science.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a tough standard. ``It is not the same as scientific
certainty,'' said Keith Rockwell, the WTO's director of
information. The WTO decision (available at www.wto.org) does not
call for majority science. If some evidence exists that a given
hormone poses a risk _ and evidence apparently does exist on one of
them _ the Europeans can make the assessment and ban that hormone.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to ban all hormones on the ``better safe than
sorry'' principle.
</P>
<P>
   Twice I've sat through public panels discussing this case, and
twice Seattle trade consultant Bill Bryant of Bryant Christie Inc.
has asked WTO critics: If you throw out the requirement for
science, how can you tell which ``health'' measures are real?
</P>
<P>
   This question simply goes past some. It doesn't matter to
critics that Europe's ban might be a measure to protect European
beef packers. To them, a government's rules are that government's
business (and theirs, when they go to to lobby for new rules).
</P>
<P>
   When Bryant asked critics at Seattle University on May 26 how
they could define a health measure without science, one opponent
called out, ``Forget science!''
</P>
<P>
   When Bryant put his question to the Washington Council on
International Trade's panel last Friday, Lori Wallach of Ralph
Nader's group Public Citizen said there were other reasons than
science. There are religious reasons not to use certain products,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   That Ralph Nader's advocate offered religion as an alternative
to science was a fascinating opening, but the moderator let it go.
Religion is a private matter in the United States. Left unsaid was
that it also cannot be used to ban products.
</P>
<P>
   This argument is about more than science. It is about whether
governments should be bound by any rules, and how they should be
enforced. It is about the idea of the WTO itself, which in the
words of David Hartridge, acting director, is ``a trading system
based on rules, open markets and the acceptance by governments of
freely negotiated limitations on their power.''
</P>
<P>
   At a speech in Geneva on July 5, Hartridge remarked on the
change between the 1980s and the 1990s. In the 1980s, much of the
world rejected the WTO. Now, he said, ``There is no dispute about
the commitment to negotiate, or about the value of open markets and
rules-based trade.''
</P>
<P>
   No dispute from governments. The WTO now has 135 member
governments, and even Russia and China are knocking on the door to
get in.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Hartridge noted, the WTO ``has been subject for the
first time to outspoken and even violent hostility'' from citizens.
``We are told to expect larger demonstrations of skepticism and
hostility at Seattle,'' he said, of the WTO's meeting here in late
November.
</P>
<P>
   Of course. To get other people to give up their special
protections, you have to give up yours. As Washington Secretary of
State Ralph Munro noted a few weeks ago, ``We always wanted all our
ferry boats built in Washington. But if we're going to be a player
in world trade, we can't do that any more.''
</P>
<P>
   In the century now unfolding, Washington ferries might be built
in Mexico. Instead of corn syrup from Iowa, Coca-Cola might contain
cane sugar from the Philippines _ or Cuba. But Washington apples
will be offered in Kyoto, and beef fat from Kansas will eventually
line the arteries of Frenchmen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
