<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-GOLF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER WOODS ON TIMING AND THE BRITISH OPEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Tiger Woods arrived at Carnoustie by
helicopter Tuesday morning, and perhaps it was fitting.
</P>
<P>
   With three titles in his last four starts, Woods is the world's
No. 1-ranked golfer, the hottest player and the favorite at the
British Open, which begins Thursday. Shouldering great expectations
is nothing new for Woods. Playing terrific golf is nothing new for
him, either. But he has not won a major championship since the 1997
Masters, his first and only Grand Slam title, and Woods faces a
severe test at Carnoustie, a course with great history that is
recognized as one of the world's toughest.
</P>
<P>
   Woods builds his schedule around winning majors. So while he has
enjoyed his recent run, this week matters most to Woods because of
the course and the tournament, and because he is playing well
enough to win another major.
</P>
<P>
   It is a chance that he does not want to waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the championship everybody wants to win, because I
think it has the best field in the world,'' Woods said. ``I like it
best out of all the other majors, because the conditions change so
much. Last year, I remember hitting a driver in a practice round on
the first tee at Royal Birkdale, then hitting a 4-iron off the same
tee in the tournament. That's two completely different winds, and
that's the beauty of it. I like having to adapt my game to the
conditions, and they can change pretty rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods has always loved the characteristics of links courses _
treeless and bunker-laden, with thick rough, natural terrain and
unpredictable winds that encourage lower ball flight and a wide
range of shots.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the course has the potential to result in
one of the most difficult majors because Carnoustie has been
lengthened and the fairways have been narrowed for the world's best
players. Predictions for the winning score have ranged from even
par to 10 over par.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, after finishing third at last year's British Open and
improving his short-iron play over the last year, Woods believes he
is ready to win. He has been in Europe for more than a week,
spending last week in Ireland, fishing and golfing with Mark
O'Meara, Payne Stewart, David Duval, Stuart Appleby and Lee Janzen.
He has adjusted to the time change, and he has played in harsh
Scotland weather before.
</P>
<P>
   But this weekend, Woods will find out whether he peaked a few
weeks too soon, or at a perfect time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key to having your game peak at the right time is
scheduling,'' Woods said. ``Scheduling enough rest, enough practice
time, enough time to get away from the game. I never had to deal
with four major championships in one year at junior golf, amateur
golf. As a professional, you have to peak at four different times.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is difficult to do. The purses are getting higher, so you
can get caught up in playing too much. But when you get to a major
championship, you need to have a lot of energy. I believe what I've
done over the last couple of year has been successfully, and my
record is starting to show that.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods has three top 10 finishes in his last four majors,
including a third-place finish at last month's U.S. Open. Perhaps
the only thing that separated Woods and Stewart on the last day at
the U.S. Open was putting. Stewart made crucial putts on the final
few holes, while Woods did not. But instead of dwelling on that
disappointment, Woods said he had focused on giving himself another
chance to win a major _ quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I getting impatient?'' Woods asked. `No. You can't force
the situation. This year, it was Payne's turn to win the U.S. Open
by making those great putts. It all boils down to a little bit of
luck, too. You need a few good breaks at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what Woods does this week, people will watch. At
today's news conference, the room was filled with reporters.
European golf fans, who do not often get to see Woods in person,
are eager to watch him attack Carnoustie. He has become a crowd
favorite in Europe, and he appreciates the fans' knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the most intelligent fans of the game,'' Woods said.
``They know when a shot to 30 feet is a great shot. In the States,
if you hit a ball to 30 feet, you don't get anything. If you hit a
ball to 10 feet, you don't get anything. Sometimes in the States
they just want to see backspin. You may suck it back into the
water, but they're going crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods hopes to give them more to appreciate this week. He has
won four times this season _ at the Buick Invitational, the
Memorial, the Deutsche Bank Open and the Motorola Western Open. But
winning this weekend would be far more special, and Woods is
clearly confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing solid,'' Woods said. ``I'm very happy. I'm getting
my game back to where I like it.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
