<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPOTLIGHT SHIFTS TO THE WNBA AND ITS STARS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JERRY BREWER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wide-eyed and giggling, Chamique Holdsclaw and
Shannon Johnson rummaged through packages of basketball cards after
an autograph session at the NBA Store Tuesday, hoping to find their
card in the stack. Holdsclaw found hers and looked over at Johnson,
who was still opening packages.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson opened three packages and did not see her card in any of
them. The two Women's National Basketball Association All-Stars
laughed, and Holdsclaw, the rookie from the Washington Mystics, had
joke material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not upset about it,'' said Johnson, the Orlando Miracle
guard and a reserve for the Eastern Conference All-Stars. ``I'm one
of those sleepers, I guess you can call me. I'm one of those `down
low' players. I don't get into the spotlight.''
</P>
<P>
   But for about two hours Wednesday night, Johnson will be one of
22 players in the spotlight when the WNBA holds its first All-Star
Game at Madison Square Garden. All 18,645 seats have been sold. A
host of stars are expected, including members of the World Cup
champion U.S. soccer team. Whitney Houston will sing the national
anthem.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball players will streak down the court at the Garden,
the best in the world playing at a blurring pace. Wednesday night
won't merely be an affirmation of the talent of Holdsclaw or Sheryl
Swoopes, some of the most well-known players in this league. It is
also for the Shannon Johnsons. Each player has her own story, her
own tale of how she ascended to stardom. Their talents are as
diverse as their lives have been. They are single mothers, former
world-class volleyball players and aspiring singers. They have
worked at a car repossession business, the Internal Revenue Service
and J.C. Penney. They make the league minimum, the league maximum
and the league average. They go by Spoon, Yo, and Grandmama _ or
Yum Yum now that Jennifer Gillom has lost 20 pounds. These are the
WNBA All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want the kids excited,'' said Liberty point guard
Teresa Weatherspoon, a starter for the East. ``If I want to run up
in the stands and pick one up to get her excited, I'll do it. It's
time to let the kid in me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night is for fun, although both squads say they will
do what it takes to win. The Western Conference is favored to win
because of its star-studded roster, which includes Swoopes, Cynthia
Cooper and Lisa Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we'll see,'' said Vicky Bullett of the Charlotte Sting.
``We'll just have to see.''
</P>
<P>
   To the players, the All-Star Game is a stamp on their careers.
For the Sacramento guard Ruthie Bolton-Holifield, being here
validates her return from a torn anterior cruciate ligament
suffered early last season. Bolton-Holifield, 32, was the first
star of the WNBA to suffer a serious injury, and she heard the
whispers that her career was over. When she returned this season,
Bolton-Holifield was coming off the bench, getting only 18 minutes
a game. Then, about two weeks into the season, her long-range
jumper started falling. She was inserted back into the starting
lineup and is now averaging 14.6 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means more to me than making the WNBA's first team in the
league's first year,'' she said. ``After being injured, people
started counting me out, saying, `It's over,' and `We'll see,' and
`Maybe you should accept that you won't be the player once were.' I
told myself that I'm not going to let man tell me what to do and
accept being 80 percent of what I once was. I was going to work
hard and see what God had in store for me. Look where I am now.''
</P>
<P>
   Look at where her West teammate Natalie Williams is now.
Williams, in her first season with the Utah Starzz, came to the
league from the defunct American Basketball League, where she was
the 1998 most valuable player. Williams played college basketball
and volleyball at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   As a volleyball player, Williams won two national championships
and recognition as player of the year. She was also a Kodak
all-American in basketball in 1993-94. She was later named the
Pac-10 Conference athlete of the decade. When she heard of the
ABL's start-up in 1996, she left the U.S. volleyball team, on which
she was vying for an Olympic spot, and picked the basketball up
again. She averaged 20 points and 11.7 rebounds a game before the
ABL folded last December.
</P>
<P>
   Before the league folded, her Portland Power team was looking
like a championship contender. Now Williams, who is averaging 19.8
points and 10 rebounds, is a relatively unknown star in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, a lot of people haven't seen what I can do,'' Williams
said. ``But they've heard. It's sad. A lot of people see me as a
rookie, but I was the ABL mvp.''
</P>
<P>
   Taj Williams, an Eastern Conference reserve forward from the
Orlando Miracle, may have to guard the bulky Williams when the
teams to go their benches Wednesday night. For the slender
Williams, guarding Williams won't be a hard job. Williams, a single
mother, knows all about jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked at the IRS, did part-time counseling, secretary,
market research, J.C. Penney customer service, TCBY yogurt and
assistant basketball coach,'' she said, explaining how she
supported her daughter Michele, 10, while in college and during the
summers after the professional basketball season in Europe was
over. ``The IRS was the most enjoyable because it was a new
challenge. I was testing new computer programs to see how this
computer was going to work when it tried to audit people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like challenges,'' Williams added. ``I don't like to do the
same thing every day. Of course I play basketball, obviously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
