<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ROSE STIRS ALL-CENTURY THORNS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Nobody can vote for Pete Rose for the Baseball Hall of
Fame, but if you get an All-Century Team ballot, you can vote for
the career hits leader who has been suspended for betting on
baseball. You can also vote for Shoeless Joe Jackson, the Black Sox
outfielder who acknowledged accepting $5,000 to dump the 1919 World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the debate about their indiscretions, both deserve
to be on the All-Century ballot.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the 100 players from 100 years on the Mastercard
Major League Baseball All-Century ballot, Commissioner Bud Selig
explained that Rose and Jackson were included as ``great players;
it doesn't in any way alter their status,'' meaning Rose's
suspension by Commissioner Bart Giamatti and Jackson's lifetime ban
from Commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis.
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. For this 25-man All-Century Team that will be
announced at the World Series, fans should not be asked to judge
Rose and Jackson on integrity, only on their baseball ability.
Which each had in abundance. Rose had a record 4,256 hits in a
record 3,562 games. Jackson's career batting average in the
dead-ball era was .356, third to Ty Cobb's .366 and Rogers
Hornsby's .358.
</P>
<P>
   But why wasn't Rose invited to join the 24 other candidates who
attended the All-Century Team announcement before Tuesday night's
All-Star Game at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``As part of his suspension ban that he voluntarily signed with
Bartlett Giamatti in 1989,'' Selig said, ``attendance at any
function like that was forbidden.''
</P>
<P>
   It's always been the belief here that Rose deserved a suspension
of one to three years, but not an indefinite suspension that keeps
him off the Hall of Fame ballot. His betting on baseball did not
equate with Jackson's involvement in dumping the 1919 World Series.
Therefore, Rose's punishment should not be the same.
</P>
<P>
   In making the distinction between enshrinement and endorsement,
Major League Baseball has the right to keep Rose and Jackson out of
Cooperstown, but not off its 100-year all-star ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who also played first base, second base and third base,
and Shoeless Joe are among the 34 outfielders on the ballot, but
you can vote for only nine, along with six pitchers, two catchers
and two at each of the infield positions. There's space for one
write-in selection. And for what it's worth, here are my 25
choices:
</P>
<P>
   -- First base, Lou Gehrig, Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   -- Second base, Rogers Hornsby, Jackie Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   -- Shortstop, Honus Wagner, Cal Ripken Jr.
</P>
<P>
   -- Third base, Mike Schmidt, Brooks Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   -- Catchers, Johnny Bench, Josh Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   -- Outfielders, Babe Ruth, Hank Aaron, Ty Cobb, Joe DiMaggio,
Ted Williams, Willie Mays, Mickey Mantle, Stan Musial, Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   -- Pitchers, Cy Young, Sandy Koufax, Christy Mathewson, Walter
Johnson, Bob Feller, Grover Cleveland Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   According to Selig, if it's necessary to correct obvious
oversights by the fans, a special panel will be authorized to add
up to five players to the team. With that in mind, my five would be
outfielder Ken Griffey Jr. and four pitchers _ Tom Seaver, Bob
Gibson, Satchel Paige and Bob ``Lefty'' Grove.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest to omit were Jimmie Foxx, Joe Morgan, Ernie Banks,
Eddie Mathews, Yogi Berra, Roy Campanella, Roberto Clemente, Frank
Robinson, Carl Hubbell, Juan Marichal and Warren Spahn.
</P>
<P>
   Ballots are available at major league ball parks, at
participating Kmart stores, on line through MLB's Web site
(www.majorleaguebaseball.com) and in special Mastercard advertising
inserts in Sports Illustrated and TV Guide. They must be in by
Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 names on the ballot were whittled down by a panel of
experts from a list of 128 compiled from the ``top 100'' players
selected by The Sporting News, ``Total Baseball'' and Ken Shouler's
``The Real 100 Best Baseball Players of All Time ... and Why?''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to McGwire, Ripken and Griffey, four other active
players are on the ballot _ Barry Bonds, Tony Gwynn, Rickey
Henderson and Roger Clemens _ but Sammy Sosa is not.
</P>
<P>
   Like the All-Star selections, the All-Century voting is expected
to turn into a popularity contest dominated by the most recent, if
not the current, players, but two names will make the fans stop and
think about the past and their past _ Pete Rose and Shoeless Joe
Jackson.
</P>
</TEXT>
