<HEADLINE>
THIEF TELLS JUDGE HE STOLE PARROT `OUT OF LOVE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When he was arrested in January and accused of
stealing a rare parrot from the Central Park Zoo, John Bryant
Davilla stuck his tongue out at reporters as he was led away by the
police and boasted, ``I wanted to make stew out of that bird!''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in State Supreme Court in Manhattan, a far more subdued
Davilla quietly pleaded guilty to third-degree criminal possession
of stolen property and offered his first public explanation for the
bizarre caper. Davilla, a 25-year-old film actor from South
Brooklyn, told a judge that he had stolen the nameless parrot ``out
of love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought truly loving people who were handicapped could care
for this animal,'' he said, ``and give it more love than people
gawking at it in a zoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Davilla's guilty plea brought to a curious close one of the
oddest thefts of 1998 in Manhattan. In halting tones Tuesday
morning, he admitted breaking into the Central Park Zoo at 1 a.m.
on Dec. 17 and snatching the 6-year-old female thick-billed parrot
_ an endangered species _ from her cage.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by Acting Justice Carol Berkman why he had chosen to
steal that specific parrot, Davilla replied, ``It was a very
friendly bird.'' But prosecutors argued that the rare bird had been
chosen for her worth, an estimated $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Davilla denied prosecutors' accusations that he had offered to
sell the bird to a pet store for $1,000 and, later, to a friend for
$500. Davilla said that he had gone to the pet store simply to find
out what kind of bird he had. He later offered to sell the parrot
to a friend, Edwin Juppi, when he realized that he ``couldn't give
it enough love'' himself, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Juppi, a bird owner who uses a wheelchair, recognized how rare
the bird was and called the police, prosecutors have said. The
parrot had been receiving antibiotics for a respiratory infection
when she was stolen. After she was returned to the zoo on Jan. 27,
veterinarians found that the bird had lost weight and was having
difficulty breathing.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 31, the parrot was taken to the Bronx Zoo's Wildlife
Center for emergency surgery, but she died on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Berkman said she would probably sentence Davilla, who
had faced up to seven years in prison, to five years' probation at
his sentencing, scheduled for Sept. 8. But she scoffed at his
explanation for the theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're telling me you did it for love,'' she said. ``But you
didn't know how much that could harm the animal. I guess you're not
that interested in animals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
