<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTED KILLER IN EIGHT SLAYINGS SURRENDERS IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo and graphic available on NYT database) 
(Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
(Attn: Ill. and Ky.) 
 
By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
and ERIC BERGER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Mexican fugitive suspected as a railway-riding
serial killer surrendered to a Texas Ranger on a remote bridge
along the El Paso border Tuesday, ending a fear-driven manhunt and
starting a lengthy legal drama in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, 39, gave himself up in a peaceful,
anti-climactic episode arranged by his relatives, who conceivably
may collect up to $125,000 in reward money, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He realized there was no place to go, that it was just a
matter of time before he was going to be captured by American
authorities or Mexican authorities,'' Texas Department of Public
Safety spokesman Tom Vinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez slept on a DPS turbo-prop airplane Tuesday as
he was flown to Houston, where he faces a burglary charge in
connection with the Dec. 17 slaying of physician Claudia Benton at
her house in West University Place, an affluent enclave of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities suspect Resendez-Ramirez in at least eight gruesome,
seemingly random killings in Illinois, Kentucky and Texas. Each
took place near railroad tracks, which the suspect is suspected of
using to travel across the nation and to his native Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Murder charges have been filed against him in Kentucky and
Illinois, but not in Texas _ yet. Police took a sample of his blood
Tuesday evening, under court order, to see if his DNA matches
homicide evidence in the Benton case and others.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez _ a name the FBI said was an alias for his true
identity, Angel Leoncio Reyes Recendis _ first became a suspect in
a series of slayings when his fingerprints were discovered on a
steering column broken from Benton's stolen Jeep Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   The DNA evidence could lead to the suspect's being charged with
capital murder in Harris County, which sends more criminals to
death row than any state other than Texas. Harris County, which
includes most of Houston, has 3.1 million people and is the largest
county in Texas. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Texas Ranger Andrew F. ``Drew'' Carter Jr., who took the
suspect into custody after negotiating for his surrender, joined
Houston police detectives in questioning Resendez-Ramirez for more
than two hours at the downtown Houston police headquarters Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Carter declined to offer specifics afterward, but another Ranger
said he believed that Resendez-Ramirez had made no confessions
during those interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect was to be transferred Tuesday night to the Harris
County Jail in preparation for a 9 a.m. preliminary court hearing
Wednesday, before state District Judge Bill Harmon, on the burglary
charge. Prosecutors said they will ask the judge to deny bond,
forcing the suspect to remain in custody pending further charges.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the intense manhunt, which included
Resendez-Ramirez's placement on the FBI's Ten Most Wanted list,
afforded a sigh of relief to law enforcement authorities and
relatives of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission accomplished, for the moment,'' said Don K. Clark,
special agent in charge of the FBI office in Houston, where a
special task force processed tips about the suspect's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said authorities had not known Resendez-Ramirez's
whereabouts since a June 18 sighting in Kentucky. With the suspect
at large, many people living near railroad tracks in Houston and
across the country were on a terrified alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered me this guy was still running loose and could kill
somebody else, because he didn't pick any victims, he just stumbled
onto somebody and murdered them. I was afraid he would go on and
on,'' said Norman N. Sirnic of Santa Maria, Calif., the 70-year-old
father of slain Weimar, Texas, minister Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic.
</P>
<P>
   In a case linked to Resendez-Ramirez, the minister and his wife,
Karen Sirnic, were found dead May 2 inside their home near railroad
tracks. Their pickup was found in San Antonio, as was Benton's Jeep
Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   Fayette County resident Josephine Konvica was found slain June 4
at her home about three miles from the Sirnics'. A day later,
southeast Houston school teacher Noemi Dominguez was found in her
home near some tracks. She had been beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases were added to the string of killings blamed on the
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez, who has served U.S. jail sentences and was
deported to Mexico several times since 1976, avoided capture
despite the FBI-led manhunt.
</P>
<P>
   In a towering embarrassment, the suspect was released into
Mexico early on June 2 after Border Patrol agents took him into
custody for illegally entering the United States. It was just
before Konvica and Dominguez were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the Border Patrol lacked information that
Resendez-Ramirez was being sought, and treated him as a routine
illegal immigrant. The U.S. Justice Department is investigating
those actions.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of the Mexican national's surrender were planted
several weeks ago when Carter and a fellow Texas Ranger, Sgt. Brian
Taylor, visited Resendez-Ramirez's sister, Manuela Maturino, in
Albuquerque, N.M., officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino grew to trust the Rangers and worked toward the
suspect's surrender in consultation with her pastor and a second
brother, Florentino Maturino Recendis, in Mexico, according to
Rangers Senior Capt. Bruce Casteel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say that there were very personal, one-on-one
discussions with family members and myself with one goal in mind
... his surrender,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Maturino called Carter _ he was on a fishing trip
along the Texas Gulf coast _ and said a surrender could be arranged
if authorities would promise in writing that Resendez-Ramirez would
be kept safe in jail, that his relatives could visit him and that
he would get a psychological evaluation, Casteel said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials agreed to those terms as routine for such a case, and
made no agreements involving leniency or exemption from the death
penalty, Casteel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government opposes the death penalty and has refused
in past cases to extradite suspects to the United States to face
capital-punishment prosecution. Mexican police were not involved
with the surrender, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After Carter and Maturino drove to El Paso, Resendez-Ramirez
followed through by crossing the Zaragosa Bridge with his brother
at 10 a.m. CDT, Casteel said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, accompanied by agents from the FBI and other agencies,
shook the suspect's hand, handcuffed him and drove him through the
Ysleta del Sur area, dominated by cotton fields and garment
factories on the El Paso outskirts.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was Carter's 32nd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez _ slight and emotionless and wearing
metal-rimmed eye glasses, a striped shirt, dirty jeans and leather
work boots _ was taken before a judge in El Paso and warned of his
rights, which include consultation with officials of the Mexican
government.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect's family may be eligible to receive the $125,000 in
reward money offered for information leading to his capture, DPS
spokesman Mike Cox said, ``and they've indicated that if they did,
they would use it for his defense.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI chief Clark said experts who compiled a psychological
profile of the suspect had concluded that a public plea for
surrender and the involvement of his family might lead to his
capture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was based on what profilers were telling us and it
worked,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the family's motivation in part, was to bring some
type of normalcy back to their lives,'' he added. ``We were not
going to stop looking until this person was in custody, so their
lives would have been turned upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said the fugitive's photograph was on thousands of fliers,
in newspapers and on television, making it very difficult for him
to move about without being recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really intent that there would not be a place in this
country where this person could freely move around. I would like to
believe that this pressure led to his decision,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark made his comments in the lobby of FBI headquarters in
northwest Houston where dozens of reporters and photographers were
jammed shoulder to shoulder. After Clark finished answering
questions, FBI employees perched on a walkway above the lobby gave
him a round of applause.
</P>
<P>
   With the murder charges pending in Illinois and Kentucky,
Resendez-Ramirez will be prosecuted in Texas first because he was
captured in the state, Rangers Capt. Earl Pearson said. He was
brought to Houston because the only Texas warrant for his arrest is
in Harris County.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County prosecutors said the suspect's blood sample will
be rushed for DNA processing and will be available in three to four
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney John B. Holmes Jr. could not be reached for
comment about whether prosecutors would seek the death penalty if
Resendez-Ramirez is charged with capital murder here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot imagine that we would not (seek the death penalty),
but we haven't made that decision yet,'' said Assistant District
Attorney Devon Anderson, who is assigned to the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Benton case is the first for which the suspect would face a
Harris County murder charge.
</P>
<P>
   If enough evidence is found in that case to link Ramirez to it,
he could be charged with capital murder in Dominguez's killing as
well, Anderson said. But there is more evidence in the Benton
investigation that leads directly to Ramirez, so that case appears
stronger at this point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than likely, facts gathered during the Dominguez
investigation would be introduced in the punishment phase of a
capital murder trial for Benton's death, assuming Ramirez is
convicted. Evidence from cases in other states could also be used
by Harris County prosecutors to convince a jury that the suspect
deserves the death penalty because he would otherwise pose a
continuing threat to society.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon was expected to establish in Wednesday's hearing whether
Ramirez has enough money to hire a lawyer. If he does not,
officials say, the judge already has two court-appointed attorneys
waiting in the wings _ Allen Tanner and Rudy Duarte.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner, a former prosecutor, would be the lead counsel, court
personnel said.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner told the Houston Chronicle Tuesday that he had no comment
on the case and that he had not spoken to law-enforcement officials
or Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon's court personnel said Tuesday that the judge has
indicated that he would allow cameras in the courtroom today for
Ramirez's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was moved from Harmon's court to a larger one on the
same floor that is occupied by state District Judge Elsa Alcala.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the northeast Texas community of Hughes Springs, police were
awaiting word on a palm print comparison that investigators hope
will link Resendez-Ramirez to a ninth slaying _ the October's
killing of 89-year-old Leafie Mason.
</P>
<P>
   Mason was found beaten to death with an antique iron in her
home. Police obtained no fingerprints at the scene, but recovered
the palm print and a strand of hair, thought to be that of the
killer.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Randy Kennedy said the palm print was to be
compared in Houston with the suspect's palm print Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it matches and he's talking, I hope to talk to him the
following week,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle staff writers Eric Hanson, Steve Brewer and Armando
Villafranca in Houston, John W. Gonzalez in Austin and Evan Moore
in Fort Worth contributed to this report. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
