</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MO.-CHRISTIAN-FISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY ORDERED TO REMOVE FISH SYMBOL FROM OFFICIAL SEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in Missouri has ordered the City of Republic to
remove a fish symbol, known as an ichthus, from its seal because
the symbol unconstitutionally depicts Christianity as the city's
official religion.
</P>
<P>
   Republic was given 30 days to remove the ichthus from the seal,
which was designed eight years ago and adorns the city's trucks,
flags, street signs, stationery and business cards. The
eight-member board of aldermen has scheduled a meeting next week to
decide whether to appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The case, brought by the American Civil Liberties Union, never
went to trial. In a summary judgment on July 9, Senior Judge
Russell Clark of U.S. District Court for the Western District of
Missouri wrote that depicting the ``Christian fish'' in an official
city logo violated the establishment clause of the First Amendment,
which governs the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Clark wrote, ``The portrayal of the fish
impermissibly excludes other religious beliefs or nonbeliefs and _
intended or not _ depicts Christianity as the religion recognized
and endorsed by the residents of Republic. The Republic city seal
pervasively invades the daily lives of non-Christians and sends a
message that they are outsiders. The Constitution forbids such a
result.''
</P>
<P>
   The little fish became a big cause celebre in Republic, a town
of about 6,000 people in southwestern Missouri, just west of
Springfield. A committee raised $35,000 to finance the legal battle
to support the fish, and ichthus signs sprang up on sidewalks,
churches and roadsides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we stood up for it and fought for it,'' said Paula
Howell, co-chairman of the Support Republic Committee, which raised
the money, ``was because the logo was designed to show community
values and community morals, and it was never intended to promote
religion.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clark found that the fish symbol ``is exhibited extensively
throughout southwest Missouri to denote Christian-owned
businesses,'' and that ``even Republic's own citizens do not deny
that the fish on the city seal is a Christian symbol.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of the board of aldermen, the judge noted, two
residents said they moved to Republic because, as Christians, they
were attracted by the fish on the city seal. The seal is an oval
with quadrants that contain a map of Missouri, a family of four in
silhouette, an outstretched hand and the ichthus, formed by two
intersecting arcs.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU's plaintiff in the case, Jean Webb, is a practitioner
of Wicca, or witchcraft. After writing an editorial in the local
newspaper opposing the city seal, Mrs. Webb said she received hate
mail and angry phone calls. She moved and has not spoken to the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Republic was represented pro bono by the National Legal
Foundation, which calls itself a ``Christian public interest law
firm'' with headquarters in Virginia Beach, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Fitschen, president of the foundation, said his group took
the case because ``what the framers of the Constitution intended to
prohibit was the establishment of religion, but they clearly
intended to allow encouragement, accommodation and acknowledgment
of religion, and we think that's what this is.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clark noted precedents in two other cities where courts held
that city seals that included crosses also violated the
establishment clause of the First Amendment. He also said that only
in Austin, Texas, where ``the city insignia was based upon `the
family coat of arms of Stephen F. Austin, the father of Texas and
the person after whom the city is named,''' did courts approve a
city seal that includes a cross.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
