<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0461 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8984 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAIL-KILLER-COX     07-13 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIL-KILLER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Railroad suspect in custody
 &HT;    By Rebecca Thatcher and Mike Kelley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A national manhunt ended unexpectedly Tuesday
morning in El Paso when Rafael Resendez-Ramirez _ who has spent 23
days on the FBI's most wanted list _ walked across an international
bridge near El Paso and shook the hand of a Texas Ranger waiting to
arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, Resendez-Ramirez, suspected in killings in three
states, had been flown to Houston and was in jail on a burglary
charge related to one of the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The fugitive's decision to turn himself in stunned and puzzled
law enforcement officers, who have spent recent weeks searching for
Resendez-Ramirez in communities and rail yards across the country.
He has been charged in three slayings and has been linked to five
others. Three of those five are in Fayette County, just 70 miles
southeast of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this business a very, very long time,'' Texas
Ranger Senior Capt. Bruce Casteel said when asked why
Resendez-Ramirez had returned voluntarily from his Mexico safe
haven and surrendered. ``And I'm struggling to answer that
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the surrender, Texas Ranger Drew Carter spent two days
discussing terms and other issues with Resendez-Ramirez's sister.
Resendez-Ramirez met Carter on the Ysleta Bridge over the Rio
Grande at 10 a.m. CDT, Casteel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carter told me that he extended his hand, they shook hands,
and he handcuffed him. He (Resendez-Ramirez) was very pleasant, not
aggressive,'' Casteel said.
</P>
<P>
   The climax to an intense, nationwide hunt for Resendez-Ramirez
began when Carter, who was on a family fishing trip to the Gulf
Coast, received a call Sunday on his cell phone from the
fugitive'-- sister in Albuquerque, N.M. The sister, whose name
authorities have not released, told the ranger she needed to talk
to him, Casteel said. Carter took his family back to Houston and,
in company with an FBI agent and deputy U.S. marshal, headed for
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Casteel said, Resendez-Ramirez was somewhere in
Mexico, believed to be staying with his brother.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving in New Mexico and over the next 36 hours, the law
officers discussed surrender terms with the sister, who was either
in direct contact with Resendez-Ramirez or communicating with him
through their brother.
</P>
<P>
   The only charge pending against Resendez-Ramirez in Texas is one
of burglary, related to the killing of a doctor in the Houston
suburb of West University Place, in Harris County. Monday night,
officials said, Harris County District Attorney Johnny Holmes sent
a fax to Albuquerque, giving assurance that Resendez-Ramirez would
be safe in that county's jail, that family members would be able to
visit him and that he would receive a psychological evaluation.
Asked if there were any guarantee that prosecutors would not pursue
the death penalty, Casteel said, ``None whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Department of Public Safety spokesman Mike Cox said that
the guarantee from Holmes ``had a 72-hour life to it.'' That was
communicated to the fugitive in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said that the original timetable called for a somewhat later
meeting on the bridge. A DPS plane was already en route Tuesday
morning from Houston to Albuquerque to pick up the law officers and
sister there and then fly to El Paso, Cox said, ``when for some
reason, Resendez-Ramirez got antsy.'' To speed things up, the
sister and officers drove to El Paso and the plane diverted to the
border city.
</P>
<P>
   Casteel, the Ranger commander, said that Rangers Carter and
Brian Taylor had gone to Albuquerque several weeks ago to talk to
the sister and that ``this initial contact resulted in the
development of good rapport between Carter and the sister. That
rapport, based on trust, has been very crucial in bringing about
the Ramirez surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said that ``the crucial thing here is that she trusted
Ranger Carter. Ramirez supposedly said that he would not surrender
to anyone but a Texas Ranger, and we're very proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Resendez-Ramirez has been charged with murder in Kentucky
and Illinois, he has not yet been charged in any of the Texas
cases. Cox said one reason for that is that Mexican authorities in
the past have been reluctant to extradite to the United States
people charged with capital crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico does not have the death penalty. Kentucky, Illinois and
Texas do. Casteel said now that the man is in custody in this
country, he will likely will face ``probably five, possibly six''
murder charges in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Casteel said he did not know how long Resendez-Ramirez had been
in Mexico. Cox said that though authorities in that country had
been cooperative in the early stages of the search for the
fugitive, they were not involved in the surrender. In Mexico City,
a spokesman for the Attorney General's office had no comment on the
case, other than to say that Resendez-Ramirez has not been accused
of any crimes in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said there is ``a possibility'' that Resendez-Ramirez family
members will receive $125,000 reward money for helping to bring him
in. If they do, he said, his understanding was that they would use
it for his legal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez, 39, has a long criminal history in the United
States, beginning when he was first arrested for car theft in
Florida in 1979. He has used many different names and social
security numbers over the years and served short prison sentences
for burglary, carrying a weapon and trespassing on railroad
property, and claiming U.S. citizenship. The FBI said his birth
certificate gives his real name as Angel Leoncio Reyes Recendis.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt for Resendez-Ramirez had become such a part of the
lives of the residents of Weimar, in Fayette County, that Most
Wanted flyers with his many mug shots still were taped to office
walls and store windows late Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But residents said Resendez-Ramirez's surrender means they may
be able to emerge from the shadow of death that he _ and someone
else _ left behind after moving through like a vicious cyclone,
upturning lives and shattering Weimar's small-town sense of
security.
</P>
<P>
   Three people _ two from Weimar and another who lived west of the
city _ are believed to have been among his eight victims. The Rev.
Norman Sirnic and his wife, Karen, were found May 2 bludgeoned with
a sledgehammer in the parsonage behind Weimar United Church of
Christ. And June 4, Josephine Konvicka, 73, was found, also
bludgeoned to death. Officials have said they found fingerprints
belonging to Resendez-Ramirez in her home.
</P>
<P>
   Weimar Police Chief Bill Davidson said his officers want to
interview Resendez-Ramirez and get more physical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot to do as far as the case is concerned,''
Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   After the slayings, police began checking every one of the 40
trains that moved through town, questioning anyone found on the
freight trains. Families put alarms and floodlights in their homes,
began locking doors and avoiding the railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the slayings changed the city's image from that of
a quaint community to a place to be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our big town celebration the second weekend in June and
we had our parade, and I had three other Chambers of Commerce call
and say they decided not to come this year,'' said Denise Delgado,
38, a secretary at the Weimar Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The chambers told her they feared for the safety of the children
who would ride the floats in the daytime parade. Only five of 300
T-shirts were sold at the celebration called ``Gedenke,'' meaning
``to remember'' in German. The event made $114, far below proceeds
of previous years, Delgado said. A church group of 37 people due to
tour the city in late June canceled, also citing fear for safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to be known for great sausage. Now we are known for
this,'' she said. ``It's not fair to our town, all this stuff that
is going on. It's not our fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the negative image, Weimar collectively exhaled Tuesday
as news of the surrender filtered through the air waves and the
neighborhood grapevine. The stranglehold of fear visibly loosened.
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall, a young boy stopped Police Chief Livingston and
gave him a congratulatory handshake. ``We got him,'' Livingston
replied, shooting a wide grin while cradling a large binder with
Resendez-Ramirez's photo pasted on the front.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said the violent deaths of their three friends will
keep the city of 2,052 from returning to normal. But this weekend
Los Tiburones del Norte will perform at Weimar Hall. In a few
weeks, the city will host the 1999 Babe Ruth Southwest Regional
baseball tournament _ no one has canceled _ and on Aug. 8, a fried
chicken and stew dinner will be served at the Harvest Feast.
</P>
<P>
   It's a start, Delgado said, but recovery ``is going to take a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Thatcher and Mike Kelley write for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas. Suzanne Gamboa and The
Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
