<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8985 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-BRISCOE-SPI &LR;      07-13 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BRISCOE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNIE BRISCOE HOPES BOOK WILL OPEN UP PEOPLE'S UNDERSTANDING OF
SLAVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SARAH SKIDMORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For two to three years, Connie Briscoe created the
ultimate family heirloom.
</P>
<P>
   It's her latest novel, ``A Long Way From Home,'' the story of
three generations of women: her ancestors and slaves in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blacks don't have as many family heirlooms, but we have
stories to pass on,'' the writer said recently during an interview
in Seattle on a book promotion tour.
</P>
<P>
   Although she is an accomplished writer, one of a handful of
black women to make the New York Times best-seller list, her task
was difficult. Constructing the story of her ancestors' lives was
some of the most challenging and rewarding work of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really rejuvenating for me,'' Briscoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Her ancestors were children of a black slave and a white master,
they worked in the house rather than the field, several could read
and many of them operated with greater levels of freedom than most
slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not the typical stories about slaves most people
see,'' she said. ``People have certain images of slavery they want
you to remember and think is true.''
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, Briscoe hopes she can open up people's
understanding of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a story that hasn't been told or talked about that
much,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Briscoe has frequently addressed the issues of black women in
such novels as ``Big Girls Don't Cry'' and ``Sisters &AMP; Lovers.''
This novel, however, is a departure as it is set in an earlier time
and is the first to include her family.
</P>
<P>
   Her skills as a writer helped her craft the narrative from the
point of view of her ancestors, slaves on President James Madison's
Montpelier estate in Virginia. The story covers their lives from
one generation at the end of Madison's life through the Civil War.
Through her work, she was able to discover which white master her
relatives were most likely to be descended from, dispelling the
family belief they were descendents of Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Briscoe herself lives in Virginia, the state where her relatives
lived as slaves and later fought for their freedom.
</P>
<P>
   She is a stunningly attractive woman, who uses an American Sign
Language interpreter during the interview because of a hearing
impairment. Her cool composure seems far removed from the heat and
pain of slavery in her novel. However, she asserted, the story of
her ancesters is an issue of today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't go back and address these old wounds, we will
never get past our racial differences today,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During her research, the modern-day currency of Civil War-era
racial issues became abundantly clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asking questions on a general level about slavery is
fine,''she said. ``But when you try to find a white father of a
slave, you start running into `I don't know,' `We can't help you'.
And you just have to be a little more pushy.''
</P>
<P>
   After two to three years of pushing, Briscoe wrote the book in
about six months. It was the longest period of time she has ever
spent on a novel. Her primary tools were family members, interviews
with researchers and historical documents.
</P>
<P>
   She believes that the non-traditional nature of her ancestors'
stories and the personal elements of her novel may interest readers
and ultimately broaden the vision some people have of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   She said the impact of her work on her life has taken an
unforeseen twist.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family has responded really well,'' she said. ``But now my
father's family is begging me to do a project for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
