<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'LL PLAY IN GAMES BY RIDING WITH DALLAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The local suitors to the Olympic flame
divvied up the booty the other day, and great news _ we got table
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   We also may get dressage, modern pentathlon and the ever-popular
rhythmic gymnastics, which is just like real, Kerri Strug-type
gymnastics, except it involves, I think, hula hoops, beach balls
and Russian piano music.
</P>
<P>
   If that didn't stoke Olympic fever in you, nothing will,
comrade.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive my cattiness. My only hope here is to defuse any whiffs
of provincialism that might be emanating from your flared nostrils.
</P>
<P>
   It's much too early. The name of the bid group is Dallas 2012,
not Dallas 2001. The dream goes on.
</P>
<P>
   And all cattiness aside, there seems to be a place in it for
Fort Worth and Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   When the board of directors of the Dallas 2012 Olympic bid
committee convenes next week, the site will be the UT-Arlington
Robotics and Automation Research Institute in East Fort Worth. They
didn't accidentally consult the wrong Mapsco. Committee chairman
Tom Luce planned it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're proving to everybody that we're walking the
walk,'' Luce said yesterday. ``You just can't host an Olympic Games
and not get everybody involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Luce stressed that that was merely a ``preliminary draft'' of
possible Olympic venues that his group unveiled two weeks ago. Like
most drafts, it is subject to major revisions between now and the
deadline for submitting formal bids _ Dec. 15, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   No contracts have been signed. No ground has been broken. No one
has even exchanged winks or handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it's a good starting point. And it's reason to squelch any
grandiose notions that Tarrant County residents may have had about
Dream Teams and future Michael Johnsons walking our streets.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly and humbly, we don't have the facilities that our
neighbor to the east will have. By 2012, Dallas will have the
American Airlines Center (maybe), Texas Stadium (or something
bigger), an expanded Dallas Convention Center, a spiffed-up Cotton
Bowl and the city's underestimated jewel, Fair Park.
</P>
<P>
   Other than facilities for the equestrian events and The Ballpark
in Arlington, for every possible Olympic site that Tarrant County
can offer, the Dallas side probably can do better.
</P>
<P>
   The other notable exception is Texas Motor Speedway, where
general manager Eddie Gossage still wants to get involved. People
on the Dallas 2012 board have casually mentioned the possibility of
leveling the speedway's garage area and turning the infield into a
giant soccer field.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a bad Jenny Jones makeover.
</P>
<P>
   But the point is, we're being neither overwhelmed nor ignored as
the Dallas 2012 people charge intrepidly up Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally agree,'' said Donna Parker, executive vice president
of the Fort Worth Chamber of Commerce. ``And I've got to give a lot
of credit to Tom Luce, whose dedication to the regional aspect of
this bid has been tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee, formally titled the Dallas 2012 Preliminary
Group, includes among its Tarrant County representatives Mayor
Kenneth Barr; former Mayor Bob Bolen; local philanthropist Ed Bass;
Don Carty of American Airlines; John Roach, formerly of Tandy;
former U.S. Congressman Pete Geren; Marvin Girouard of Pier One;
Gossage; Terry Stinson of Bell Helicopter TEXTRON; and Vernell
Sturns of Harris Methodist Health Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Those aren't exactly the Ten Dwarfs. Parker is convinced that
the group is committed to extending the Games beyond the confines
of downtown Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done everything I can to show that we fully intend to
make this a regional effort,'' chairman Luce said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, it would have taken a naive soul to imagine
mayors Barr, Elzie Odom of Arlington and Ron Kirk of Dallas
together on the same stage, all wearing T-shirts with the D-word on
them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, they did, and now here they are, attending meetings in Fort
Worth together. Behind the visibility of the Dallas 2012 group, the
area was able to secure the U.S. Olympic Trials in wrestling and
triathlon for next year. A contingent from the national canoe and
kayak association toured and declared Lake Arlington an ideal place
for its whitewater trials.
</P>
<P>
   The name, no doubt, still makes some Fort Worth people cringe,
but the reality is that the Olympic bid needed a Dallas branding to
go anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   As the Chamber's Parker said, ``That's OK _ it gets our foot in
the door.''
</P>
<P>
   And in this crazy dream, the door _ even the modern pentathlon
door _ is going to still feel Olympian.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
