<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAM'S POLITICAL STAND IS MIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last week, in their ``Wish List'' feature, editors
at Sports Illustrated expressed the hope ``that no one drags global
politics into Saturday's U.S.-China Women's World Cup final.''
</P>
<P>
   As with almost every American wish attached to the tournament,
this one came true _ and then some.
</P>
<P>
   That's nice. But is it good?
</P>
<P>
   The final game went off without a political hitch, without
public acknowledgment from the players that the U.S. and Chinese
governments are at odds, with scant press attention to that angle
beyond the obligatory wisecracks about the possibility Chinese
spies had stolen the U.S. game plan.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, within minutes of Brandi Chastain's winning penalty
kick, the opposing players were literally arm-in-arm at midfield,
creating a long line of alternately white and red shirts, and were
spinning the entire human olive branch until it had faced every
corner of the packed Rose Bowl stands in a more or less spontaneous
gesture of gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   Fans shouted their approval. Weren't any of them offended?
</P>
<P>
   I'm asking because, unless a drastic shift in international
politics went unreported amid the weekend's sports-bra mania, the
People's Republic of China is the closest thing the United States
has to a major enemy in the post-Soviet world.
</P>
<P>
   I'm as soft on Communism as the next Democrat, but come on.
China has been a repressive, murderous regime. China steals our
military secrets. China slips cash to our politicians. (If there
are politicians to be bought off, we'll take care of it ourselves,
thank you very much.)
</P>
<P>
   Not to be redundant, but China is a human-rights violator from
way back, its offenses including treatment of women that most of us
in the western world find appalling.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here were our new sports heroes dancing shoulder to shoulder
with representatives of official China in a show of _ what?
</P>
<P>
   Was it good sportsmanship? Or a display of ignorance or apathy
by the 20- to 33-year-olds who make up the U.S. team?
</P>
<P>
   Along with the significance we've already wrung out of it, the
1999 Women's World Cup might have marked a generational shift in
the way Americans view international sports.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, victories in the athletic arena were cheered as
triumphs of the American way, not applauded for their role in
fostering understanding among peoples.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Owens became a track legend not merely because he won four
gold medals, but because he did it under the pouting gaze of Adolph
Hitler, who meant to use the 1936 Games in Berlin to prove ``Aryan
superiority.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Louis' fights against German heavyweight Max Schmeling had
extra meaning because they occurred in the buildup to World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. basketball team's last-second defeat in the 1972
Olympic final pained us not simply because it was the result of bad
officiating but because it came against the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, memories of the U.S. hockey team's shocking gold medal
in 1980 are sweetened by the semifinal victory, which came against
the Soviet Union weeks after the Russians' invasion of Afghanistan
raised East-West military tensions. The final victory over friendly
Finland has become a footnote.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, Louis and Jim Craig didn't dance with the enemy, they
just went out and beat him.
</P>
<P>
   But Mia Hamm was 7 years old in 1980. Lorrie Fair was 1. We can
hardly expect them to remember the Miracle on Ice. Do they remember
the Soviet Union?
</P>
<P>
   Olympic boycotts and fan riots are one thing, unpleasant
intrusions of politics into sports. Acknowledging political
differences between competing nations can be something else,
leading to catharsis for fans on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   When England's Manchester United scored a last-minute victory
over Germany's Bayern Munich in the European Champions League final
in May, all of England celebrated, not because everybody loves Man
United, but because it beat (begin ital)Germany(end ital). Again.
</P>
<P>
   Sports didn't create the English bitterness toward the Germans.
Jesse Owens' host did that. Sports were the healthy means for
working off the tension.If the Women's World Cup opened American
eyes to the pleasures of international soccer, a generation that
wouldn't know Nikita Khrushchev from ``La Femme Nikita'' could
discover that political spice is among those pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   Subtly, perhaps without realizing it, they already did last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   When they celebrated the U.S. victory as a result of Title IX,
the 1972 federal mandate for gender equity in education, they
recognized that the championship was the work not just of 20 young
women but of American society as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Bloc countries dominated women's sports by pumping their
girls full of steroids. We're doing it with democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing this was, after all, a victory for the American way
makes it all the more rewarding, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   That's something to dance about. But with China? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
