</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-STAR NOTEBOOK: WILLIAMS AND FENWAY STILL CLICK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As soon as Ted Williams emerged along the center field
warning track as a passenger in a green golf cart Tuesday night,
the fans at Fenway Park rose as one noisy group and saluted perhaps
the finest hitter in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-year-old Williams raised his white cap to the fans as the
cart crept along the periphery of the stadium. Slowly, very slowly,
Williams and the fans blew each other symbolic kisses.
</P>
<P>
   After Williams was delivered to the mound to toss out the
ceremonial first pitch for the final All-Star game at a fabled park
where he was such a hero and which will soon be replaced, an
emotional scene occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The current All-Stars and the players who were assembled on the
field as part of the all-century team converged on the middle of
the diamond to greet the former Red Sox great.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire, Ken Griffey Jr. and Cal Ripken Jr. surrounded
Williams, and then Tony Gwynn, who, like Williams, might be the
best hitter of his era, leaned in to shake Williams' hand.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who vigorously chewed gum and wore a blue shirt and
tan pants, was animated as he spoke with several players.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as Williams continued chatting with current and former
stars for a few minutes, officials from Major League Baseball moved
in on the spontaneous showing so that the game would not be delayed
further.
</P>
<P>
   The public address announcer even asked the players to return to
their dugouts.
</P>
<P>
   Some would not depart. McGwire and Gwynn remained on the field
as Williams readied himself to throw the ceremonial pitch to
Carlton Fisk, another former Red Sox great.
</P>
<P>
   Williams waved at Fisk and then put his hand over his eyes to
peek in at Fisk. He used Gwynn to support his left side and then
lofted the ball from 40 feet away. It floated through the crisp,
black night and landed neatly in Fisk's glove, once again causing
the fans to embrace the player they loved and loathed during his
career with another loud and long ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Still on the Outside
</P>
<P>
   Though his view has never been in doubt, baseball commissioner
Bud Selig indicated publicly for the first time Tuesday that he
would not lift Pete Rose's lifetime ban.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who accepted the ban in 1989 from the commissioner at the
time, A. Bartlett Giamatti, as a result of betting on sports
events, has applied for reinstatement and Selig has taken a long
time to act on his request.
</P>
<P>
   The subject arose Tuesday during a news conference at which
Major League Baseball unveiled plans to have fans select an
all-century Team from a list of 100 players.
</P>
<P>
   Rose and Joe Jackson, who was also banned for life as a result
of the Black Sox scandal in the 1919 World Series, were among the
list of 100, and Selig was asked how Major League Baseball could
justify having them included. Neither is eligible for the Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the fans choose them amongst their 30 players, they're
entitled to that,'' he said. ``That does not, in my judgment,
affect what Landis did or Bart Giamatti did, nor affect my
thinking, to be quite candid about it.''
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, after another question on the subject, Selig
added, ``I don't think there's anything new or if there's anything
new that I would do to change what Bart did.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Is Back in the Fold
</P>
<P>
   Fay Vincent, who resigned as commissioner under pressure from
owners in September 1992, was at the All-Star game in the
commissioner's box next to the American League dugout as his
successor's guest.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig's invitation and Vincent's presence represented the
most visible evidence that the two have reconciled. Selig had been
one of the primary movers behind Vincent's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bygones are bygones,'' Vincent said. ``It was very nice of Bud
to invite me. I appreciate it. I'm happy to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent has attended a few regular-season games since he left
office, but this was the first time he was at an All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   Catch 22 of Sorts
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra was criticized by some reporters for playing
in Tuesday night's All-Star game, even though he did not play in
Boston's last nine games because of a strained left groin.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Tony Gwynn, who was voted a starting outfielder for
the National League, did not play because he was disabled with a
calf injury and felt it would be unfair for him to return in the
All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a big believer in doing things I feel are right,''
said Gwynn, who came to Fenway Park anyway and took batting
practice. ``I'm not worried about what people say. I was out for
three and a half weeks. Coming back in the All-Star game wouldn't
feel right to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Gwynn was asked if he would have felt differently if
the game was being played in San Diego, similar to Garciaparra's
situation, he said, ``Probably, probably.''
</P>
<P>
   First Things First
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn and the Padres will open the second half of the
season at Seattle's new Safeco Field, but Gwynn did not exactly act
as an ambassador for the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of you are going to fly to Seattle from here, I could
care less,'' Gwynn said. ``My biggest concern is going out there
and doing my job, not opening up a ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Raise the Mound, Gibson Says
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gibson, whose 1.12 earned run average in 1968 helped prompt
baseball to lower the pitching mound from 15 inches to 10, said
Tuesday that he supported the idea of raising the mound again to
restore some balance to pitching and offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me whenever there's any legislation in baseball to
improve the game it always makes the pitcher a little less
effective,'' Gibson, the former St. Louis Cardinals star, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see the mound back up. And I can see the
strike zone a little bigger up and down, not sideways.'' Then, he
added for effect, ``And I'd like for them to take the guys and give
them two strikes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
