<SLUG> BC-DAILY-NEWS-DRIVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAILY NEWS DISPUTE ON WAGES AWAITS JUDGE'S RULING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Continuing a struggle with one of its most powerful
unions, The Daily News plans to ask a federal judge to vacate a
labor arbitrator's award of back wages to its drivers, the
newspaper's chief legal officer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported erroneously Tuesday that Chief Judge
Thomas Griesa of U.S. District Court in Manhattan had upheld the
arbitrator's decision on Monday. In fact, the arbitrator had simply
submitted a document reaffirming his earlier decision to increase
the drivers' salaries and award the back wages dating to Jan. 1,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Krall, The News' executive vice president and chief legal
officer, said that the newspaper would ask Griesa this week to
vacate the award. If the judge does not, Krall said, the newspaper
will appeal to a three-judge panel of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   If the award is upheld, it could eventually cost the newspaper
what union officials have estimated would be tens of millions of
dollars. Krall said that because of a ``me too'' clause, most of
the newspaper's other unions would be entitled to the same
increases granted to the drivers, who are represented by the
Newspaper and Mail Deliverers Union.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers have been seeking to increase their wages to bring
them in line with those of drivers at The New York Times. Without
an appeal, Krall said, the newspaper would have to put the new wage
increase into effect immediately. It also would have to begin
paying out portions of the retroactive wages as soon as next month.
</P>
<P>
   Under the award, the base salary of the drivers would
immediately be raised to $911.79 a week. Under the current
contract, the drivers earn $773.57 a week, a union lawyer said
Tuesday. The union represents more than 400 drivers who deliver The
Daily News in the city and suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrator's document reaffirmed the percentage amount of
the retroactive wage increases. The drivers' salaries would be
raised retroactively by 5.9 percent, effective Jan. 1, 1997; there
would be a 5.8 percent raise from Oct. 1, 1997, and a 5.2 percent
raise from Jan. 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the arbitration case, The Daily News had proposed to pay
significantly smaller wage increases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
