<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-MARCHING-BANDS-AR     07-13 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MARCHING-BANDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONTROVERSY PLAYS ON, BUT WILL THE BAND? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(yn) 
 By JOHN SHAW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The organizers of the Sydney Olympics seem
to have devised a new event for the 2000 Summer Games: a U-turn
with back flip.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the organizing committee has provoked protests
from the United States and Japan, and plenty of grumbling locally,
because of stop-go decisions about sites and events at the Games,
which are scheduled to open Sept. 15 next year.
</P>
<P>
   The latest controversy, which is now being negotiated toward a
possible compromise, concerns, of all things, high school marching
bands from the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The organizing committee invited these bands _ 10 from the
United States _ to perform along with Australian students for 10
minutes as part of a three-hour opening ceremony for the Games, an
event that will be attended by 110,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   But this stirred a populist mixture of local pride and
Australian nationalism that led the committee to retreat and ``give
the American kids the boot,'' as a columnist in California put it.
The American and Japanese bands are now being offered lesser roles
away from the Olympic center stage, and their response is expected
shortly.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal was just the latest in a series of actions that
have provided Sydney Games officials with an almost constant
headache.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the choice of sites for the beach volleyball and
road cycling events attracted strong opposition from interests as
diverse as residents of Bondi Beach, a Sydney suburb, and
executives of a movie studio here owned by Rupert Murdoch's Fox
conglomerate. The beach site survives for the moment, in the face
of claims of risks of environmental damage, but the cycling route
has been changed twice.
</P>
<P>
   But here and in parts of the United States, the uproar over the
marching bands is wider and louder than the volleyball and cycling
arguments and has increased criticism of the committee's secretive
style and see-saw decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not since the 1960s Broadway and Hollywood hit ``The
Music Man'' has there been such a fuss about school bands.
</P>
<P>
   Of the young musicians who suddenly find themselves ``Olympic
orphans,'' according to one Sydney headline, 800 are from Southern
California and 500 more are from Georgia. For the last nine months,
they have been practicing music and marches to perform alongside
200 Japanese and 500 Australian students with whom they were to
form a 2,000-strong group to play and parade at the start of the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   News that the young Americans would have a major entertainment
role at the opening ceremony, an event many Australians expected
would be reserved for local talent, was slow to emerge here.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremonies director, Ric Birch, an Australian citizen,
issued invitations last September, after winning committee approval
for an ``international'' ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Birch's American connections go back to 1984, when he helped
stage the Los Angeles Games pageant, which featured scores of grand
pianos. At the Barcelona Games in 1992, Birch was praised for
devising the lighting of the Olympic cauldron with a flaming arrow.
But his closing ceremony segment in Atlanta in 1996, involving
large inflated kangaroo models on bicycles, made many Australians
cringe.
</P>
<P>
   When Victor Grieve, director of the Golden Kangaroos, a Sydney
suburban band, learned last month that Birch's program next year
would highlight American high schoolers and their showy precision
marching, he complained that Birch had ``closed the door'' on
Australian band members, most of whom are older and emphasize music
more than spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Birch did not respond for a month so Grieve and others took
their claims to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Talk-radio hosts and their listeners seized on the story. One
caller declared that if the Americans marched, she would burn her
tickets in protest. Officials of the Musicians Union said he was
``seeking to impose American culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Letters to editors claimed, ``This is the Australian Olympics.''
An Australian sports columnist, Peter Fitzsimmons, said
``warmed-over American schmaltz'' should not be part of Australia's
Olympic message.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Holloway, the chief executive of the organizing committee,
said he was ``mystified'' by ``the depth of feeling'' in the
community over the issue. Michael Knight, the Olympics minister, in
deciding to withdraw the invitation to the bands, said that the
organizing committee had been out of step with public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a mistake,'' he said. ``There was overwhelming
community opposition to foreign musicians.''
</P>
<P>
   The American counterattack was swift, particularly from
Californians who bombarded Sydney newspapers with e-mailed
protests.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange County Register columnist Gordon Dillon, whose
readers include many families connected to the six bands that had
been invited from the area, declared Australians ``a bunch of
low-down, back-stabbing rats'' who had ``cravenly weaseled out'' of
their offer.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Narr, father of a band member in Placentia, Calif., wrote
to The Sydney Morning Herald that ``Australians should be ashamed''
and charged them with ``a mean nationalism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney committee is rated highly by International Olympic
Committee officials for meeting construction and transportation
requirements, but it seems accident-prone in public relations and
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Prime Minister John Howard, who will officially open
the Games, was even drawn into the controversy over the bands on
the eve of his visit to Washington this week.
</P>
<P>
   Already riled by recent U.S. actions to strengthen tariffs and
quotas against imports of Australian lamb, Howard said barring the
American musicians from the opening ceremony was ``the right
decision'' because many young Australians were able to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Six marching band leaders from California, led by Roy Anthony of
San Diego, argued against that decision in Sydney last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Australians offered six minor Olympic appearances for the
American and Japanese bands, such as the opening soccer match to be
played in Canberra, the national capital. Anthony said the offers
are being considered. ``We are still in discussions here. We can't
decide until we contact our schools and students.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, John Moore, a member of the Australian organizing
committee arrived in California on Monday to meet with band members
and their parents and try to sell them on a revised performing
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting was set for Tuesday evening at El Dorado High School
in Placentia, with the hope that somehow, some way there might be
some harmony at the conclusion of this saga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
