<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENSION-PLANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS DISCLOSURE ON PENSION PLAN CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Del., Texas)  (mk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration proposed Tuesday that companies that
change from an old-fashioned pension plan to a much-disputed new
type of plan popular with large employers be required to tell their
workers roughly how much retirement money they stand to lose from
the switch.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal comes in response to harsh criticism of so-called
cash-balance pension plans by many employees and consumer groups.
These plans often save companies millions of dollars a year, but
they can reduce the money older workers receive in retirement by
one-third or more. Moreover, many employees have complained they do
not have enough information to figure out how they will be affected
by the conversions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike traditional defined-benefit pensions, where workers earn
the bulk of their retirement pay late in their careers, with
cash-balance plans employees can accrue retirement benefits evenly
over their careers and can often take plan balances with them if
they switch jobs. While that can be helpful to younger workers, the
conversions can sometimes cost older workers hundreds of thousands
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of companies have converted to cash-balance plans and,
according to Watson Wyatt Worldwide, a human resources consulting
firm in Bethesda, Md., 16 of the nation's 100 largest companies now
have such plans, and six others have a hybrid pension plan; none
had these options a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   It appears likely that Congress will pass legislation requiring
improved disclosure to employees when companies convert to
cash-balance plans. But lobbyists and others involved on both sides
of the issue said it is not clear what form the final legislation
will take. Among the proposals are the administration's plan, and a
``right to know'' bill sponsored by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Finance Committee in the Senate, William
Roth, R-Del., is considering introducing cash-balance disclosure
language as part of a tax bill, and the chairman of the House Ways
and Means Committee, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, has included
language in his tax bill requiring that employees be given
``sufficient information'' to understand the effect of conversions.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's proposal would require employers to provide
specific examples of how the change would affect different groups
of workers, comparing the old and new plans. It would also require
that employees be told if a ``wear-away'' period was included, in
which some employees stop earning pension benefits for a time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
