<HEADLINE>
BLAZE OF GLORY: SOX' MARTINEZ STRIKES OUT 5 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- They formed a scrum around Ted Williams at the center
of the Fenway Park diamond last night, the greatest collection of
baseball stars _ past, present, and future _ ever assembled in a
single setting.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Famers in suits, which included Hammerin' Hank, the
Say Hey Kid, and Yaz, and the All-Stars in full uniform blended
into an emotional tableau of applause, hugs, and tears around the
golf cart transporting Williams, the 80-year-old Red Sox icon who
before our eyes is being transformed from Teddy Ballgame into
Father Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to imagine, in the wake of such a dramatic
prelude, that anyone playing in the 70th All-Star Game could make
this stage his own. But as one fan in the sellout crowd of 34,187
in Fenway Park shouted from the grandstand, ``This is your house,
Pedro,'' Red Sox ace Pedro Martinez once again staked his claim on
Yawkey Way's most precious property.
</P>
<P>
   In a pitching performance that rivaled one of the All-Star
Game's most legendary moments _ Carl Hubbell of the Giants striking
out Hall of Famers Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Jimmie Foxx, Al Simmons,
and Joe Cronin in succession 65 years ago _ Martinez struck out the
side in the first inning, then struck out two more batters in the
second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's victims were Barry Larkin, Larry Walker, and Sammy
Sosa in the first inning, Mark McGwire and Jeff Bagwell in the
second. Sosa is the biggest star in Martinez's native Dominican
Republic, and a close second here to McGwire, whose Home Run Derby
performance Monday night will remain a part of Fenway lore.
</P>
<P>
   But the bats of the game's biggest sluggers were turned to
sawdust by Martinez, who allowed one base-runner to reach, Matt
Williams, who got on board on Robbie Alomar's error, and was erased
when Bagwell whiffed, ending Martinez's stint.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez became the first pitcher in All-Star history to strike
out the game's first three batters, and tied an American League
All-Star record, shared by the Monster, Dick Radatz, and Billy
Pierce of the White Sox, for most strikeouts in a game, five.
</P>
<P>
   The AL led the NL, 4-1, after five innings.
</P>
<P>
   As Dorchester's Donna Summer was finishing her elegant rendition
of the national anthem, four F-14s thundered past, seemingly
skimming across the tops of the Fenway light stanchions.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, a clear, 67-degree midsummer's delight, the
complaints about the noise would be few, although surely there was
some minor grumbling that Martinez only worked the first two
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The National League broke through in the third against
Martinez's replacement, David Cone of the Yankees, but not before
Cone struck out the first batter he faced, Mets catcher Mike
Piazza, the sixth NL strikeout victim of the night.
</P>
<P>
   First-time All-Star Jeromy Burnitz, the Milwaukee Brewers'
slugger, lined a double to right, and after Jay Bell looked at a
third strike for the second out, the Reds' Larkin grounded a single
up the middle, Burnitz scoring to make it 2-1. Walker was retired
on a comebacker to the mound, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   American League manager Joe Torre had said before the game that
he was thinking of sending Garciaparra onto the field for the start
of the third inning, then sending Derek Jeter of the Yankees out to
replace the Red Sox shortstop before play resumed.
</P>
<P>
   That way, Torre said, Garciaparra would receive a final sendoff
from the home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if I do that,'' Torre said, ``my own guy (Jeter) won't get
booed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Torre put off doing so, allowing Garciaparra to lead off the
bottom of the third against the Big Unit, Randy Johnson, the
majors' strikeout leader with 200.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who lined to right against National League starter
Curt Schilling in the first, swung at Johnson's first pitch and
lifted a high fly to shallow center, where the Cubs' Sosa gathered
it in.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on cue, Jeter emerged from the American League dugout and
met Garciaparra just in front of second base. The two shook hands
in front of second base, then embraced, and then with his usual
stiff-legged gait, Garciaparra trotted off the field to sustained
applause.
</P>
<P>
   The AL gave Martinez a 2-0 lead in the bottom of the first, as
three of the four Cleveland Indians in the starting lineup, plus
Iron Cal Ripken, combined to jump-start the AL team.
</P>
<P>
   Leadoff man Kenny Lofton, taking advantage of Schilling's tardy
arrival at first base, beat out an infield hit to McGwire at first
base. Two outs later, Lofton stole second and Manny Ramirez of the
Indians drew a full-count walk. Jim Thome, the Indians' first
baseman, lined a 1-and-0 single to center, scoring Lofton with the
game's first run, and Ripken hit Schilling's next pitch to right
field, scoring Ramirez to make it 2-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
