</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-U.S.-TEAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAM SPRINTING TO SEVILLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES DUNAWAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recent world records in the men's 100 meters by an American, and
marks in the mile and decathlon by foreign athletes, have refocused
attention on the track and field team the United States will send
to next month's 1999 world championships in Seville, Spain. It is
as strong, deep and versatile as any in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the United States is strongest in the sprints, where
Marion Jones, Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene are favored to win
four or five individual gold medals among them.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who will be trying to win five gold medals in next year's
Olympics, will go for four Aug. 20 to 29.
</P>
<P>
   Jones should be a strong favorite in the 100 meters and an
odds-on choice in the 200, and if the coaches select her to run in
the 4-by-400-meter relay, she could pick up another gold medal
there. But in the long jump Jones is only one of a half-dozen or so
women clustered around the 23-foot mark. No one is dominant, and
any of them could win, including Jones' two American teammates,
Dawn Burrell, who beat Jones in the U.S. championships in Eugene,
Ore., last month, and Shana Williams, who finished third.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene's world record of 9.79 in the men's 100 meters,
combined with his taking-care-of-business work ethic, will make him
hard to beat in the men's dashes. His training partner, Ato Boldon
of Trinidad, and the Namibian Frankie Fredericks should offer a
strong challenge in both the 100 and 200.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson, forced to withdraw from the U.S. championships
in the 200 meters because of a slight injury, is eligible only for
the 400 meters in Seville, where he will be the defending world
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Johnson has demonstrated that the injury was minor by
running the 400 in 43.92 seconds, the fastest time in the world
this year. In April, Johnson said he was not interested in trying
the 200-400 double in Seville, although he hoped to repeat his
historic 1996 Olympic double in Sydney, Australia, next year.
</P>
<P>
   Both men's and women's American relay teams will be fast enough
to win. But American relay teams have a history of dropped batons,
passes out of the zone and other mishaps, especially in the
4-by-100, where there is no margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about to come to an end,'' Greene said last week.
</P>
<P>
   American men will also be favored to win the shot-put and the
110-meter hurdles. John Godina won the U.S. title with a put of 72
feet 3 inches, the longest throw since July 1977. He will be going
for his third straight world championship.
</P>
<P>
   Americans will be overmatched, however, in the decathlon and the
men's middle distances, especially after recent world-record
performances by Hicham el-Guerrouj of Morocco in the mile (3:43.13)
and Tomas Dvorak in the decathlon (8,994 points). The American Dan
O'Brien, the previous decathlon record-holder, has withdrawn from
the worlds with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. team also has gold-medal possibilities in several
other events. They include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Men's pole vault, where Jeff Hartwig set an American record of
19-9 in late June at the U.S. championships.
</P>
<P>
   _ Men's high jump, with Charles Austin, 1996 Olympic high-jump
champion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Men's discus, with Godina and the former Syracuse star Anthony
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   _ Men's 400-meter hurdles, where Angelo Taylor and Joey Woody
provide a 1-2 punch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women's 100-meter hurdles, where Gail Devers _ after a year
off to overcome various injuries _ returned to competition with a
strong victory at the U.S. championships. As a two-time Olympic
100-meter champion, she is also a threat in that event if Jones
makes any mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women's pole vault, where the American record-holder Stacy
Dragila could upset the world-record holder Emma George of
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women's high jump, where the U.S. meet winner, Tisha Waller,
and the runnerup, Amy Acuff, could place 1-2 with a good day in
Seville.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women's 1,500 meters, where Regina Jacobs has the year's
fastest time (4:02.41) and will be hard to beat. Jacobs won both
the 1,500 and the 5,000 at the U.S. meet, and she is waiting to
decide which distance she will run in Seville until after she runs
a 5,000-meter race in Stockholm, Sweden, July 30. If she chooses
the 5,000 in Seville her chances don't look as bright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
