<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-COX     07-13 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Cuban exodus may be on Florida's horizon
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Eighteen months ago, Pope John Paul II
stood in a square in the eastern Cuban city of Camaguey and
implored Cubans to stay and fight for change rather than boarding
boats to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1999, with their hopes of change dwindling,
Cubans are once again taking to the sea in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, 1,260 Cubans have made the perilous journey
across the Florida Straits and landed safely in South Florida _
already more than in any year since the dramatic 1994 exodus of
more than 33,000 rafters.
</P>
<P>
   And so far this year, 951 others have been intercepted at sea
and returned to the island.
</P>
<P>
   This current wave has been characterized by an increasing sense
of urgency and desperation, as refugees have waved machetes at
Coast Guardsmen, threatened to set themselves afire at sea and
staged mad dashes through the South Florida surf to claim asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, one woman drowned while attempting to elude capture.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, about 200 protesters lined a street leading to
the Coral Gables home of sugar producer Alfonso Fanjul, who was
hosting a dinner for President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, who stood behind a pink coffin, a reminder of
the death of the Cuban woman who drowned, complained that Clinton
is cooperating too much with Cuban President Fidel Castro and about
how the Coast Guard is treating refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The latest surge of refugees flocking to the United States can
be explained by increased repression and a worsening economic
outlook in Cuba since that promise-filled visit by the pope early
last year, diplomats and Cuba observers said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lull after the pope's visit that gave people some
hope, some breathing room,'' a Western diplomat in Havana said.
``That began to change about September when the Cuban government
began ratcheting up its control.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's visit came as the socialist government _ ruled for 40
years by Castro _ appeared to be allowing more free expression and
permitting Cubans to open small mom and pop businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Then, from September to February, the Castro government took a
series of steps to tighten state control over almost every aspect
of life on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Professionals who moonlighted as taxi drivers to earn precious
U.S. dollars suddenly faced stiff fines for competing with
state-owned taxi companies.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners who rented rooms to tourists or opened small
restaurants found new taxes made the enterprise unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
   Police enforcing new laws against economic crimes began
routinely setting up roadblocks outside major cities to check the
identity and possessions of the occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Police presence in Havana, already heavy, was reinforced with
hundreds of new officers wearing black berets and carrying
walkie-talkies.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar sellers, prostitutes and hustlers who once strolled
Havana's boulevards with impunity were swept from the streets,
taking away what had become part of the city's ambiance as well as
a major source of money for Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic hardships were bad enough, but life was becoming
a lot less fun,'' the diplomat said. ``The average Cuban can't walk
three blocks without getting stopped by the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's prisons swelled by several thousand, mostly young people
arrested for crimes ``often related to the situation of poverty and
unemployment,'' the Cuban Commission for Human Rights and National
Reconciliation reported last week.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which is not recognized by the Cuban government,
cited its own unofficial sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is less tourism, less money in the street,'' said Daniel
Hernandez, 32, a West Palm Beach photographer who returned from
Cuba last week after visiting his family. ``Desperation is growing
block by block.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's occasional moves to allow Cubans to venture
into private enterprise have been inefficient and often
nonsensical, said Mariela Ferretti, a spokeswoman for the
Cuban-American National Foundation in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the job categories were amusing,'' Ferretti said.
``They included doll repair and dog grooming. Who in Cuba can groom
their dog when they can't afford to groom themselves?''
</P>
<P>
   Ferretti said Castro's government won't allow any meaningful
reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message has been made clear to them that they have no hope
for options,'' she said. ``And when people cannot vote, they vote
with their feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The current discontent in Cuba is not unlike the conditions that
helped give rise to previous waves of emigration, but diplomats say
they see no indications that Castro might open his ports and allow
a mass exodus this time around.
</P>
<P>
   The new wave of Cuban refugees follows old and new patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is related to the condition of the seas, which are
more calm and always bring more refugees in the summer months.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike the exodus in 1994, Cubans are no longer coming in
inner-tube rafts. The vessels now arriving are mostly seaworthy,
powered by sails or motors.
</P>
<P>
   The homemade rafts proved useful in 1994 because they could
venture far enough off the Cuban coast to draw the attention of
friendly Coast Guard and Navy ships patrolling the waters between
Florida and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But later in 1994, the United States reached an agreement with
the Cuban government that changed the rules. Cubans intercepted by
U.S. authorities were routinely returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The repatriation led to an increase in smuggling and a change in
tactics by Cubans seeking political asylum in the United States.
Cubans quickly learned the principle nuance of the new U.S. policy
_ that the trip would be wasted unless they set foot on U.S. soil,
where they were permitted to stay while they applied for asylum.
</P>
<P>
   The wet-foot, dry-foot policy explains why Cubans attempt to
evade Coast Guard vessels.
</P>
<P>
   If captured in the water, they are shipped back to Cuba. A dry
foot almost certainly means a life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be sure that not only Hialeah knows about that, but
Havana knows about that as well,'' said Dan Geoghegan, a spokesman
for the Border Patrol in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Douthat writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Brian E. Crowley contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
