<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9121 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALUJET-INDICT-COX     07-13 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALUJET-INDICT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murder charged in ValuJet crash
 &HT;    (EDS: TIMELINE AT BOTTOM OF STORY.)
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ State prosecutors Tuesday charged an air maintenance
company with murder for every one of the 110 people who died when
ValuJet Flight 592 slammed into the Everglades three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities also charged SabreTech, Inc. and three
former employees with criminally mishandling the combustible oxygen
generators that investigators say burst into flames and doomed the
DC-9 minutes after it left Miami International Airport on May 11,
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The federal charges and 220 state counts _ 110 for manslaughter
and 110 for felony murder _ are believed to be the first stemming
from an air crash in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   ``SabreTech is ultimately responsible for these deaths,''
Miami-Dade State Attorney Kathleen Fernandez Rundle said. ``This
crash was completely preventable. It was not an accident, like many
other crashes are. It was a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta lawyer Richard Kessler, who lost his wife, attorney
Kathleen Kessler, in the crash, welcomed the action, but said,
``There's no closure or anything like that. It doesn't happen. It's
a myth.''
</P>
<P>
   Families for all but 10 of the 110 victims have settled their
civil cases, said Aaron Podhurst, a Miami-based attorney for 25
victims.
</P>
<P>
   SabreTech lawyer Kenneth Quinn called the charges ``outrageous''
and said the firm, which lost $37 million after the crash and is
now out of business, was being made the scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``No useful purpose is served by going after a company that has
been driven out of business, or employees who have learned the most
painful lessons of their lives,'' said Quinn, a former Federal
Aviation Administration lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   A felony murder is a death, intentional or otherwise, resulting
from commission of a felony _ in this case the illegal transporting
of hazardous waste, with which the state also charged SabreTech.
Because no individuals are named in the state case, no one can go
to prison, but the company can be fined for as much as $10,000 for
each count it is convicted of, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-count federal indictment charges Maintenance Vice
President Daniel Gonzalez and mechanics Eugene Florence and Mauro
Valenzuela. Acting U.S. Attorney Guy Lewis said lawyers were
arranging Tuesday for the three to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   They are charged with conspiring to place a destructive device
on an airplane; making false statements about the removal of the
generators; improperly training employees; and improperly removing,
loading, packaging and transporting hazardous materials. If
convicted of the federal charges, the company faces up to $6
million in fines and restitution and the employees face up to 55
years in prison, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn criticized the government for not going after ValuJet,
which actually loaded the canisters onto the plane and which
investigators said contributed to the crash by hiring SabreTech
because it was a low-cost firm and then not keeping an eye on it.
He also pointed to the FAA, which investigators said shared the
blame through lax oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not able to prove any individual (at ValuJet) was
responsible for the deaths,'' Fernandez Rundle said. She also said
that at one point ValuJet reminded SabreTech that canisters must be
properly monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Though the ValuJet flight virtually vanished into the swamp
along with 110 lives, there was enough evidence for National
Transportation Safety Board investigators to conclude that
SabreTech workers improperly labeled canisters as empty before
taking them to the ramp where ValuJet workers loaded them on the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical canisters, normally packed in insulation and spaced
in airline cabin ceilings, generate heat of more than 500 degrees.
The five crates were swathed in plastic bubble wrap, stacked atop
rubber tires and stored in a cargo compartment with no smoke
detector.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB said a firing pin on a canister became dislodged during
loading or takeoff and became hot enough, in six minutes, to cause
a tire to explode. The flames them disabled the electrical system
and spread so quickly that the crew was powerless to land the plane
safely. Cockpit tape transcripts showed passengers shouting ``Fire!
Fire! Fire!'' in the flight's last moments and a videotaped test
done later on similar canisters showed them generating heat that
approached 3,000 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB found SabreTech mechanics worked 12-hour shifts, seven
days a week; mechanics with no experience handled oxygen
generators; and workers responsible for signing off on inspections
of DC-9s had not been through DC-9 systems training.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez Rundle on Tuesday alleged what she called a systematic
chain of ``cumulative errors, omissions and sometimes deliberate
acts'' between January and May 1996 that included SabreTech workers
falsely documenting that the canisters had been fitted with safety
caps _ caps that cost only 3 cents apiece, are easily fitted and
could have prevented the fire that brought the plane down.
</P>
<P>
   At one point at Tuesday's news conference, Fernandez Rundle
showed Lee Sawyer of Miami, who lost her parents, the cap and had
her fit it onto one of the canisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should give you some answers,'' Fernandez Rundle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' Sawyer said. ``Someone needs to be
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   ValuJet merged in 1997 with Orlando-based discount carrier
AirWays Corp to form AirTran, which said Tuesday it has cooperated
with investigators since the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fully confident the government will bring to justice
those it believes are responsible,'' AirTran Chairman Joe Leonard
said in a statement. ``We will continue to cooperate with those who
seek the truth in this matter and will not, as have others, use the
media to deflect blame and avoid responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer George Bennett and Lillian Weis and staff
researcher Barbara Gellis Shapiro contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   ValuJet Crash Chronology:
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 26, 1993: Atlanta-based ValuJet begins operation.
</P>
<P>
   February 1996: FAA internal report recommends ValuJet be
grounded because of safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   May 6, 1996: The FAA completes a 3-month investigation that
uncovers at least 100 problems on ValuJet planes and a rate of
accidents four times greater than the major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   May 11, 1996, about 2:15 p.m.: ValuJet Flight 592 crashes into
Everglades six minutes after leaving Miami International Airport
for Atlanta. The five crew members and 105 passengers are all
killed.
</P>
<P>
   June 17, 1996: ValuJet agrees to temporarily shut down after a
federal inspection finds ``several serious deficiencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 29, 1996: The FAA declares ValuJet safe to fly again.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 26, 1996: The U.S. Department of Transportation clears
ValuJet to fly again.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 30, 1996: ValuJet returns to the air.
</P>
<P>
   November 18-22, 1996: NTSB holds five days of wrenching hearings
in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   August 19, 1997: NTSB says the crash could have been avoided and
blames federal regulators, ValuJet and Sabretech for ``failures all
up and down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   September 1997: ValuJet merges into Orlando-based AirTran
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   January 1998: Published reports say FAA inspectors found
falsified documents, improper maintenance, faulty repairs, and lack
of oversight at ValuJet.
</P>
<P>
   April 30, 1998: The FAA fines SabreTech $2.25 million for
improperly handling oxygen canisters that wound up on Flight 592.
Sept. 9, 1998: AirTran ends flights out of Palm Beach International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 16, 1998: AirTran resumes flights out of Miami
International Airport for the first time since the crash of Flight
592.
</P>
<P>
   Fall of 1998: SabreTech shuts down.
</P>
<P>
   May 15, 1999: A monument to the victims of Flight 592 is
dedicated near where the plane went down.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Kleinberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
