<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAILWAY-KILLER-ART-2N     07-13 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILWAY-KILLER-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE SUSPECTED OF KILLING 8 PEOPLE IS ARRESTED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for re-editing and updating throughout, including new
information about suspect's sister.)   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Photo
is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Mexican fugitive suspected of killing eight people
in three states, avoiding capture by hopping freight trains,
surrendered peacefully today in El Paso, after members of his
family negotiated his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the suspect, Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, a 39-year-old
drifter from Mexico, walked across a bridge from Ciudad Juarez,
Mexico, to turn himself in, he had become the most-wanted fugitive
in two countries, a man the authorities here say could be
responsible for many more killings than those for which he has been
sought.
</P>
<P>
   The search for him involved thousands of investigators around
the country and in Mexico, who despite an endless supply of tips,
were often thrown off the trail by an elusive suspect.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it was a simple telephone call from his sister,
Manuela Matorino Karkiewicz, who lives in Albuquerque, N.M., to a
Texas ranger. She told the ranger, Andrew Carter, ``We need to
talk,'' said Mike Cox, a spokesman for the Texas Department of
Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought her brother was ready to surrender,'' said Cox,
who would not reveal the sister's name.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Robinson, pastor of Hope Chapel Foursquare, Mrs.
Karkiewicz's church, said the ranger ``was very protective of the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Resendez-Ramirez would surrender even though he faced
the death penalty if convicted, Bruce Casteel, commander of the
Texas Rangers, said, ``I've been in this business a very long time,
and I'm struggling to answer that myself right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, the pastor, said Mrs. Karkiewicz had initially
contacted him in June. Of Resendez-Ramirez's surrender, he said,
``It was a direct answer to prayer. We prayed for a very peaceful
and calm ending.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local prosecutors, meanwhile, agreed to allow Resendez-Ramirez
to have family members visit him in jail and to have a
psychological examination.
</P>
<P>
   For months leading to the surrender, news of Resendez-Ramirez's
alleged exploits terrified people living and working near railroad
tracks, especially in Texas, where five of the eight victims were
found over the last six months. Gun sales in many railroad
communities in Texas rose sharply as the police warned the suspect
could kill again.
</P>
<P>
   When he struck, said the authorities who knew him as ``the
railroad killer,'' the anonymity of freight yards and rails
provided a safe backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state investigators, who have collaborated on one of
the biggest manhunts in recent years, say the proximity to
railyards of the five deaths in Texas, plus one other, two years
ago in Kentucky, has been one of the most obvious similarities in
building the cases.
</P>
<P>
   But other evidence also convinced investigators that the murders
were committed by the same person, including the means by which the
victims were killed _ savage beating with blunt objects _ and
fingerprints and other evidence that the authorities say tie the
killings to the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   And the authorities say he could be responsible for many other
deaths. Don Clark, an agent with the FBI in Houston, told reporters
on Tuesday afternoon that since Resendez-Ramirez's surrender ``50
to 60 other police departments have requested information to see if
he is connected to unsolved murders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We used every tool possible to make this come about,'' Clark
added of the capture of Resendez-Ramirez, who was added to the
FBI's 10 Most Wanted List on June 21. ``But we're not finished in
this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The big break in the case came through the telephone call on
Sunday night to the Texas Rangers, which is the state police, from
Mrs. Karkiewicz, said Tela Mange, a spokeswoman for the Houston
Department of Public Safety. ``She said he wanted to come in.''
</P>
<P>
   That conversation led to others between Ranger Carter and Mrs.
Karkiewicz as well as with other relatives of Resendez-Ramirez's in
the United States. Ms. Mange said that a written agreement was
drafted that outlined terms of a surrender, and the family accepted
late Monday night or early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities stressed on Tuesday that they made no promises
to Resendez-Ramirez that he would avoid execution by surrendering.
Since the death penalty was declared constitutional in 1976, Texas
has put more inmates to death, 180, than any other state.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know the possibilities,'' Robinson said of the family.
``This is very painful for them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the agreement in place, Resendez-Ramirez walked across the
bridge into El Paso early on Tuesday morning to give himself up.
Later, the authorities flew him here, where he was placed in the
Harris County jail in downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had opportunity to leave last night, and didn't,'' said
Robinson about talks with Resendez-Ramireza on Monday night when he
was apparently with a brother in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez looked tired and wan as he appeared before a
state magistrate in El Paso on a pending burglary charge from the
Houston area. He wore a wrinkled blue-stripped shirt, tattered blue
jeans and aviator-style glasses.
</P>
<P>
   He looked no different, although perhaps a little more tired, as
he emerged from a twin-engine state plane that flew him into
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   He was questioned by law-enforcement officials at the Houston
police department on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he is expected to face murder charges stemming from the
five killings in Texas that investigators say he is linked to.
</P>
<P>
   He is currently facing two murder charges in Illinois in
connection with the June 15 shotgun slayings of an elderly man and
his daughter. Another murder charge is pending in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, the search for Resendez-Ramirez exasperated
federal authorities in the United States. Border Patrol agents
picked him up on June 2 and released him into Mexico. They
apparently did not know that the FBI was searching for him and that
the Houston police had told the Immigration and Naturalization
Service that he was wanted for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after he was released, a 73-year-old woman from Fayette
County, Texas, Josephine Konvicka, was found beaten to death in her
home. A day later, Noemi Dominguez, 26, a Houston teacher, was
found beaten to death in her home.
</P>
<P>
   Her car was found in Del Rio, a Texas border town, with
fingerprints that the authorities say could be Resendez-Ramirez's.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the investigation, Resendez-Ramirez had remained a
mysterious figure. Even his true identity was uncertain since
investigators say he has used more than 30 aliases. Born in the
Mexican city of Puebla, he first entered the United States
illegally in 1976, when he was arrested in Brownsville by INS
agents. For the next 23 years, Resendez-Ramirez led the life of a
transient, illegally jumping freight cars from Mexico into the
United States. He bounced in and out of federal prisons and local
jails on minor non-violent offenses.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his non-violent history, investigators say they have
linked him through physical evidence to the five Texas killings as
well as the slayings in Illinois and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   But the big break came Sunday. Cox, the spokesman for the Texas
Department of Public Safety, said that Carter had first visited
Mrs. Karkiewicz, an aide at a physical rehabilitation center, about
two or three weeks ago at her home in Albuquerque and had remained
in regular telephone contact with her. At the same time, Mrs.
Karkiewicz apparently had contacted another brother in Mexico who
knew the whereabouts of the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of receiving the cellular call on his fishing trip,
Carter flew to Albuquerque with an FBI agent and a U.S. marshal to
meet with Mrs. Karkiewicz. By Monday, an agreement had been drafted
by the Harris County District Attorney's Office in Houston that
offered the suspect and his family three things: a pledge of safety
in the Harris County jail, the promise of regular visits from his
family and a full psychological examination.
</P>
<P>
   Though Clark was noncommital when asked if Mrs. Karkiewicz would
receive the $125,000 reward offered in the case, other officials
said it appeared that she would.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
