<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BALLPARKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST WAVE OF NEW BALLPARKS BLENDS HIGH TECH, RETRO LOOK 
WITH NEW-BALLPARK PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of the big-league ballparks in use today were built in one
of two eras.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, which roughly covered the 1960s and 1970s,
ballparks were mostly multipurpose concrete ovals, often outfitted
with artificial turf and sometimes topped with domes.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, which began with the opening of Baltimore's
Oriole Park at Camden Yards in 1992, the theme was
turn-back-the-clock, as architects tried to give new stadiums the
feel of yesteryear with brick exteriors, irregular field dimensions
and manual scoreboards.
</P>
<P>
   A third era, now being ushered in with the opening of five new
ballparks in less than a year, continues to reject the
aesthetically unpleasant stadium designs of the '60s and '70s,
while improving on the economic and artistic successes of '90s
ballparks built in Baltimore, Cleveland, Denver and Arlington. That
third era begins tomorrow in Seattle when the Mariners face the San
Diego Padres at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   The new stadiums, in Seattle, Milwaukee, San Francisco, Detroit
and Houston will all strive for the historic look, even though
three of the five will have movable roofs.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the new stadiums, the one with the best chance to be
special might be Pacific Bell Park in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ballpark will not be the biggest, not the most expensive,
not the most luxurious,'' Giants owner Peter Magowan said, ``just
the best. Small and cozy. Urban. Brick and steel. \RWith\S a
grass-field \Rand\S a short right-field porch where sluggers like
Barry Bonds can send home runs right into San Francisco Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   While it will carry a corporate name and offer the usual
revenue-producing amenities of the day _ luxury boxes, club seats,
more and more varied concessions _ PacBell might be the most
unusual of the new stadiums, and not just because long balls can
sail into the bay.
</P>
<P>
   The $306 million stadium is being privately financed, the first
major-league park not to use public funds since Dodger Stadium,
which opened in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   The other open-air stadium to make its debut next year is
Comerica Park in Detroit, which will replace one of baseball's
oldest venues, Tiger Stadium. Renderings of the downtown ballpark
depict a facility similar in interior appearance to Camden Yards
and Cleveland's Jacobs Field. Comerica also has an outfield view of
downtown, a sea of green seats, a smallish seating capacity (a
little more than 40,000) and a brick, stone and steel exterior.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities to other ballparks are not surprising since one
of Comerica Park's architects is HOK Sport, which designed several
other 1990s stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   The covered ballparks going up in Houston and in Milwaukee also
borrow from existing stadiums, but improve on domed facilities in
Toronto and St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest improvements is that even when covered,
Miller Park and Enron Field will allow fans a view of the outdoors.
That's the result of having glass-paneled walls above the top row
of upper-level seats, stretching to the point where the roof meets
the seating bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Enron Field will be an improvement over the Astrodome because of
its downtown location, its grass field (which wasn't possible with
a fixed roof), its brick facade and its smaller seating capacity,
which, at 42,000, will allow for greater intimacy than was possible
at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Camden Yards does, Enron Field will make use of existing
historic structures in the surrounding neighborhood: A renovated
Union Station will be part of the new park, along with housing
offices, retail and restaurant space.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Park will be adjacent to County Stadium, away from
downtown in a park-like setting that will encourage the pregame
tailgating that is a tradition in Milwaukee. Like Enron Field,
Miller Park will be an ``airy'' retractable-roof facility, with a
brick exterior reminiscent of The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Park's most unique feature, however, will be its
fan-shaped roof, which is supposed to open or close in about 10
minutes and afford fans a more open stadium feel.
</P>
<P>
   One feature consistent in all the new parks is premium seating,
which guarantees revenue beyond ticket sales. Miller Park, for
example, will have 70 suites and 3,100 club seats, whereas County
Stadium had neither. Comerica Park will have 3,000 club seats and
2,000 suite seats; Tiger Stadium had no modern premium seating.
</P>
<P>
   So, while ballpark designs have changed, the reason for building
new ballparks _ economics _ hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer T.R. Sullivan contributed to this story.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
