<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENRON FIELD WILL BRING BACK TEXAS-SIZE SCOREBOARD 
WITH NEW-BALLPARK PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astrodome made history when it opened in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros intend to keep that history alive when they move into
their new ballpark next year by emulating one of the Astrodome's
most beloved features.
</P>
<P>
   No, not the Dome or the AstroTurf; the Astros are going with a
retractable roof and real grass at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   But Enron Field will have a huge scoreboard, and those who
remember the old Astrodome remember how much a part of tradition
that is in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A series of boards and video displays will stretch from the
right-field foul line to dead center field, 200 feet long and 50
feet high. The main video screen will be 26 feet by 46 feet, one of
the largest in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing our best to keep some tradition alive in the new
ballpark,'' Astros senior vice president Bob McClaren said. ``We
wanted to keep the Astros history of having big scoreboards.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had the biggest around when they moved into the
Astrodome. It also was revolutionary, the first animated scoreboard
ever, costing $2 million and containing 1,220 miles of wiring.
</P>
<P>
   After Jimmy Wynn, Doug Rader or Rusty Staub smacked a home run,
the scoreboard showed the Astrodome top being blown off with a
tremendous explosion. A huge baseball appeared with the words
``HOME RUN'' on it, more explosions, followed by cowboys riding on
the screen with their guns ablazing and then two giant steers
waving the American and Texas flags.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys would round up the steers and then the show would
end with more fireworks exploding in a multicolor display. The
whole production took 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard served other functions as well. When the Astros
were upset with Commissioner Bowie Kuhn, the scoreboard operator
made him the answer to the night's trivia question: Who is the most
unpopular man in the world? The other choices were Frankenstein and
Pete Rozelle.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard was the forerunner of JumboTron, DiamondVision
and all the other high-tech gadgetry that would come later.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Astrodome will be left behind. In all other
respects, Enron Field will be on the cutting edge of technology
with all the usual amenities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a world-class facility befitting Houston and
allowing us to maintain competitiveness in baseball's current
environment,'' Astros owner Drayton McLane said.
</P>
<P>
   The $251 million park is being built on the site of Union
Station, a historic train depot that opened in 1911 and closed in
1974. The station is being restored, and the Astros estimate 60
percent of their fans will enter through there.
</P>
<P>
   The park also is a baseball-only facility, as opposed to the
Astrodome, which was multipurpose. The Houston Oilers played there,
and their owner, Bud Adams, was the one who demanded the animated
scoreboard be torn down in 1988 so he could add 10,000 seats to the
place. Nine years later, he took his team to Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Astros' lease, they have the right to use Enron
Field for all lawful purposes, excluding the operation of sexually
oriented businesses, an industrial site or waste-disposal site.
Provisions also have been made for the place to be used for the
Olympics if they ever come to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the Astros don't have to worry about being forced
on the road for a month while their home-field plays host to the
Republican National Convention, as the Astrodome did in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros still will be able to play in air-conditioned comfort
when the roof is closed, but without the fans losing their view of
downtown Houston. Fifty thousand square feet of glass will stand
between the roof and the left-field wall, allowing for both
aesthetic beauty and air-conditioned comfort.
</P>
<P>
   All that and the giant scoreboard, too.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
