<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-BELL PARK IN SAN FRANCISCO HAS NICE RING, BEFITTING THE CITY'S
STATURE 
WITH NEW-BALLPARK PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ben Grieve walks to the plate, and 41,000 fans
give him a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   That's been a common occurrence at Pac-Bell Park, ever since
Grieve became a free agent after the 2003 season and left the Las
Vegas Athletics to sign with the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   He has owned the city ever since. Now, midway through the 2020
season, history beckons. Knuckleballer Kerry Wood stands on the
mound, and Grieve needs just one more. One more home run and Hank
Aaron is erased from the record book forever.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipation is over the baseball. Some collectors are
offering as much as $10 million _ one-fifth of Grieve's salary _
for the record-breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
   Wood floats a knuckleball, and Grieve whips the bat around. A
loud crack echoes through the ballpark and the ball sails high and
deep to right, high above the 25-foot wall, over the promenade
behind it and _ ker-plunk! _ right into San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Then ...
</P>
<P>
   Then what?
</P>
<P>
   One guy gets the baseball and five others drown in the attempt?
</P>
<P>
   ``Good question,'' said Shana Daum, public-affairs officer for
the San Francisco Giants. ``That's not our jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the first questions that arises when Daum takes
you on a tour of Pac-Bell Park, the Giants' new palace scheduled to
open by April 4, 2000. The 25-foot right-field wall is 307 feet
from home plate. There's a promenade behind it and ``knotholes'' in
the wall where people actually can get a glimpse of the game for
free.
</P>
<P>
   Then _ as advertised _ comes the cold, dark waters of San
Francisco Bay. The Giants' favorite sales pitch about their new
place is really true: There will be home runs hit into the bay.
</P>
<P>
   So you can't help but wonder what happens when souvenir-hungry
fans start diving in after home-run balls. After all, there are
fans who dive into alligator-infested waters in Florida during
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember Father Guido Sarducci, from Saturday Night
Live?'' Daum asked. ``He's a big Giants fan, and he lives in Marin
County \Racross the Golden Gate Bridge\S. He's offered us to train
dogs to jump in the water and retrieve the baseballs.''
</P>
<P>
   She is serious.
</P>
<P>
   It's all a part of why the Giants' new ballpark could easily end
up as the best in baseball. Pac-Bell fits the three most important
factors of any real-estate transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Location. Location. Location.
</P>
<P>
   The brick-and-steel park is built right on the San Francisco
waterfront, a 15-minute walk or two-minute trolley car ride from
downtown. Ferries from all over the Bay Area will dock just beyond
right field. Million-dollar yachts use the marina beyond left
field. The neighborhood _ formerly a warehouse and pier district _
is undergoing massive renovations: condos, restaurants, the works.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-Bell also will have the usual amenities that come with
ballparks these days, including luxury suites, children's play
areas and chic cafes. Plus, the Giants insist windbreaks will keep
it from being cold and miserable, as 3Com Park is.
</P>
<P>
   But the views are like none in any other park.
</P>
<P>
   If you go, don't worry about trying to get a seat on the lower
level. Those seats will be sold out. Just ask for upper deck, down
the right-field line.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have a good view of the field, a spectacular view of the
Bay Bridge, San Francisco Bay and the Oakland hills beyond, and
you'll be able to see Father Guido's dogs taking the plunge below.
</P>
<P>
   The most beautiful city in the country should finally have a
ballpark befitting its grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   The second most beautiful city in the country didn't seem to
fare as well.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt Seattle's Safeco Field will be a fine place to
play and a vast improvement over the Kingdome. Just to watch
baseball in sunshine on a gentle Seattle afternon will make it a
worthwhile facility. For $517 million, it should be.
</P>
<P>
   But ....
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is a spectacular city, located between Puget Sound and
Lake Washington, and surrounded by magnificent vistas of Mount
Ranier, the Cascades and the Olympic Mountains. Evergreen trees
abound, and the city has many superb neighborhoods built on hills
or next to small lakes, bays and canals.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco Field is not. It sits just south of downtown in a valley.
The nearest waterfront is several blocks away, a major shipping
area devoid of entertainment and eating places.
</P>
<P>
   Historic Pioneer Square is close, and billionaire Paul Allen has
renovated the nearby train station. But all of that and any views
will be blocked by the new football stadium/parking garage being
built in place of the Kingdome beyond the left-field fence. The
retractable roof hangs ominously over right field.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that to the University of Washington football stadium,
built on the banks of Lake Washington. The east end is open,
affording a terrific view of the lake and the Cascade Mountains
beyond. The most fashionable way to attend the game is by boat.
It's considered one of the best college football stadiums in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   It is truly Seattle. Safeco Field is not. It's just a really
nice, really expensive ballpark, and Father Guido's dogs can't do
anything about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-99 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
