<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9131 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MILLER-PARK-TEX     07-13 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MILLER-PARK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILWAUKEE'S NEW PARK COMBINES MODERN TECHNOLOGY, OLD-TIME LOOK 
WITH NEW-BALLPARK PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Miller Park is one of four big-league parks
scheduled to debut next season, and only one of three movable-roof
stadiums to open in less than a year, along with those in Houston
and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But Milwaukee Brewers officials say they have the best of the
lot. They say their ballpark meets the needs of Wisconsin sports
fans while blending modern technology with the old-time ballpark
look that has become the vogue design of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think we're the first of the next generation of
covered ballparks,'' said Scott Jenkins, the club's vice president
of stadium operations. ``I hope we're sort of a Camden Yards with a
roof.''
</P>
<P>
   That might seem unrealistic, given that the much-acclaimed
Baltimore Orioles' home field is set downtown, which Miller Park is
not, and isn't burdened with the visual weight of a retractable
roof.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is something to what Jenkins says. Miller Park will
have the only fan-shaped convertible roof in North America, and
that should allow for a more streamlined appearance as well as an
openness that is lacking in older domed ballparks, said Bryan
Trubey, design principal for HKS Architects, the Dallas-based firm
that designed Miller Park.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the outdoor feel of Miller Park is the wall of
glass between the top row of upper-deck seats and the roof. This
will provide fans sitting at the top of the stadium with views to
the outside when the roof is closed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a portion of the exterior outfield wall can be
opened even when it rains, temperature permitting.
</P>
<P>
   In a state where football fans are willing to endure subfreezing
temperatures to watch the Packers at Lambeau Field in Green Bay,
the idea of a covered facility might seem odd. But a sampling of
Brewers fans at a recent game found that most feel baseball
shouldn't be played in the cold or the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think adverse weather in any way helps a baseball
game,'' said Harley Wright, who travels about 130 miles from
Stevens Point, Wis. for Brewers games.
</P>
<P>
   Club officials point out that because Milwaukee is one of the
major leagues' smaller metropolitan areas, the Brewers have to draw
fans from a greater distance to fill a stadium. Fans traveling
farther need the certainty that a game will be played if they
travel, so a dome is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milwaukee's not a community of 3 \Rmillion\S or 4 million
people, so we have to draw from hours away,'' Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Park is being built just beyond the outfield wall of
County Stadium, which will be razed for parking at the end of this
season. The Brewers are taking care to preserve the best of the
County Stadium experience, however.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Brewers have the best tailgating scene in the
major leagues, and that will continue thanks to Miller Park's
``Park within a park'' design, which will take advantage of nearby
amenities such as the Menomonee River.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in-game promotions popular with Milwaukeeans, including
mascot Bernie Brewer's slide into a stein of suds after Brewers
home runs, will continue. So will the between-innings sausage race,
a live variation on the animated dot race popular at stadiums such
as The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Park will also feature about 200 ``Uecker Seats,'' $1
day-of-the-game seats in the upper deck with obstructed views.
</P>
<P>
   That's a nod to Brewers announcer Bob Uecker, who became famous,
in part, for a beer commercial in which he informed an umpire that,
``He missed the tag.'' In the commercial, Uecker's seat was about a
mile from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said that except for the retractable roof, Miller Park
reminds him somewhat of The Ballpark in Arlington, with its brick
exterior and park setting. That's not surprising because Miller
Park architect HKS also had a hand in designing The Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Club officials hope Miller Park will help the Brewers compete
financially against better-funded franchises, and the revenue from
increased ticket sales and premium seating should do just that.
</P>
<P>
   But some fans say the Brewers will have to start winning if they
want people to keep coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll come for the first year to satisfy their curiosity,''
said Cam Lundquist, 39, of Stevens Point. ``But the novelty of the
new park will wear off in a year if they don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
