<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton vows to stop huge GOP tax cut
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH _ Defying Republicans who are determined to use the
nation's extra cash for a huge tax cut, President Clinton vowed to
force the GOP to use most of the money to protect Social Security
and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must put first things first,'' Clinton said repeatedly to
the cheering members of the Communication Workers of America, who
are having their annual convention here. ``We can still have a
good-sized tax cut, but not as large as the one the Republicans
propose.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, speaking to the GOP leadership in Congress, Clinton said,
``I am asking Republican leaders, in the interest of saving
Medicare, to reconsider the size of their tax-cut plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Jockeying for political advantage with the election 16 months
away, Democrats are attempting to portray themselves as the party
most concerned about spending enough money to keep Social Security
and Medicare from going broke.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say they can accomplish the same thing and still
reduce taxes for businesses and families.
</P>
<P>
   With a robust economy, political leaders suddenly find
themselves with a potential $2.9 trillion in budget surpluses over
the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that $1.9 trillion must be kept with Social
Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The squabbling is over the other $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton was threatening to veto any huge tax cuts, House
GOP leaders offered a plan Monday to cut taxes by $864 billion by
approving a 10 percent income tax reduction over 10 years, cutting
capital gains taxes and eliminating estate taxes and the ``marriage
penalty'' on income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are talking about is a defining difference between the
Republicans and Democrats,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, the
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee. ``We believe the
people can spend their money more wisely than the bureaucrats in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   After the president's speech, sugar producer Alfonso Fanjul of
Coral Gables hosted a $25,000-per-couple dinner for Clinton, which
was intended to raise up to $1 million for the cash-starved Florida
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   With Florida expected to be a major player in next year's
presidential campaign and having a tough race for the U.S. Senate
seat being vacated by Republican Connie Mack, the party is hoping
to have $2.5 million in the bank by the end of year to help
Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Brian E. Crowley writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
