A9136 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-TICK2000-     07-13 0238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-TICK2000-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In 2000, tickets won't be so scarce
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Braves officially presented themselves as host of
the 2000 All-Star Game in a Tuesday morning breakfast. What became
clear is that Major League Baseball is looking forward to having a
site where tickets might actually be available.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, the All-Star Game has been held in Colorado and
Cleveland, where season-ticket bases are over 40,000, and then
Fenway Park, so small (33,871) that tickets were never put up for
public sale. After granting first priority to Braves season-ticket
holders (26,000) and 10,000-plus going to Major League Baseball's
disposal, 50,062-seat Turner Field offers a larger share of tickets
to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think with that ticket base, you'd have some kind of
public availability,'' said MLB public relations manager Pat
Courtney.
</P>
<P>
   The experience won't come cheaply. Tickets at Fenway this week
went for $150 for box seats, $100 for reserves and $75 for the
grandstand. Those prices are expected to hold for 2000. Braves
season-ticket holders will receive All-Star ticket information with
next year's order forms, with public sale expected in April.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
