<DOCNO> NYT19990713.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-MAIN-COX     07-13 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American league bests National 4-1
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They played one from the heart Tuesday night. The
American League beat the Nationals again, 4-1 in the 70th All-Star
Game, winning for the third consecutive year and the ninth time in
the past 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   But Fenway Park, Ted Williams, Pedro Martinez and one of the
longest collective baseball memories in any league made the game
more than it set out to be. Cleveland's Jim Thome and Baltimore's
Cal Ripken each scored and drove in runs but 44,187 went home
remembering a night more than a score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to a few (All-Star Games) but what happened with
Boston?'' asked Martinez, who set a record by striking out the side
in the first. ``What's here? Do the people eat baseball and drink
baseball? It's unbelievable. I don't really have the words to
explain how good it feels to just be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The night opened on an emotional edge, starting with a pre-game
ceremony involving 31 members of the select 100 greatest players
walking in from center field and surrounding the infield. Ted
Williams, still the emotional mayor of Boston, road a cart to the
mound, threw out of the first pitch to Red Sox great Carlton Fisk
and no one wanted to leave the field. The game started more than 20
minutes late while players from both sides mobbed Williams at the
mound while the Splendid Splinter dabbhis eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He left the field waving his cap to a heart-felt ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did that,'' said Williams, slowed by the effects of a 1991
stroke. ``Hell, I haven't had a base hit in 30 years and I'm a
better hitter now than I've ever been in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the game after three innings, Colorado right
fielder tore up a piece of turf to bring back to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the grounds crew doesn't get too made, because I tore
this piece of grass out of right field. I'm taking it home and I'm
going to have it forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Kevin Millwood worked a scoreless sixth. After
allowing a single to Baltimore's ageless Harold Baines, he put the
side down in order on a fielder's choice from Brad Ausmus, a
grounder back to the mound by Jose Offerman and a strike out
against Bernie Williams, whiffing on a full-count changeup.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Brian Jordan, entering the game in the fifth as a
center fielder, walked off Texas's Jeff Zimmerman in his first
plate appearance in the seventh but was thrown out by Detroit's
Brad Ausmus attempting to steal second two pitches later.
</P>
<P>
   Down 4-1 after four, twice the National League had excellent
chances early on but left five men on in the fourth and fifth
innings. Milwaukee's Jeromy Burnitz rolled out to first with the
bases loaded to end the fourth and when two men reached scoring
position in the fifth, Baltimore's Mike Mussina struck out Sammy
Sosa and Mark McGwire back-to-back, McGwire going down swinging on
three straight pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Bottenfield, the NL's leading game-winner with 14, made a
mess of the fourth inning, walking Jim Thome and then hitting Cal
Ripken before Rafael Palmeiro's RBI single pumped the lead to 3-1.
The inning might have ended when Roberto Alomar sent a potential
double play-ball to third but Matt Williams failed with a backhand
stab, the error bringing in Ripken for a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Burnitz, an unlikely starter for the injured Tony Gwynn, made
the NL's first offensive impact, looping a soft double over first
base off New York's David Cone in the third. Barry Larkin, with
just one hit in 11 All-Star at-bats covering nine games, singled up
the middle with two outs to bring in Burnitz to close it to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever criticism the Cleveland organization received for
ballot box-stuffing, the Indians immediately began deflecting in
the first inning. Kenny Lofton, the first of four Indian starters,
beat Curt Schilling to first on a grounder to first baseman Mark
McGwire and then stole second three batters later, with teammate
Manny Ramirez at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   When Schilling missed with a 3-2 fastball to walk Ramirez,
Cleveland's Jim Thome sent a two-out single up the middle to bring
around Lofton for a 1-0 lead. Schilling next yielded an RBI single
to Cal Ripken to put the AL up 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Boston starter Pedro Martinez, with the Fenway crowd roaring
with every strike, became the first pitcher in All-Star history to
strike out the side in the first inning. Lead-off hitter Larkin
went down swinging at a fastball, Larry Walker took a called third
strike on a changeup and Sammy Sosa appeared outmatched by
Martinez's fastball in a third swinging strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez followed up with by fanning Mark McGwire to open the
second and, after Matt Williams reached on second baseman Roberto
Alomar's error, Martinez gunned down Jeff Bagwell before Williams
was out attempting to steal in an inning-ending double play. His
five strikeout performance tied the AL All-Star record.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
